:abbeyGrangeDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Abbey Grange" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Abbey Grange" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Inspector Stanley Hopkins summons Holmes and Watson before dawn to Abbey Grange, the Kent estate of Sir Eustace Brackenstall, who has been found dead in the dining room — his head crushed by a heavy poker. Lady Brackenstall, a beautiful Australian woman, tells a vivid account: three burglars — the Randall gang, a father and two sons known to be operating in the area — broke in, tied her to a chair with the bell-rope, struck her across the face when she screamed, and bludgeoned her husband to death when he came downstairs. The intruders then drank from a bottle of wine, using three glasses, before fleeing with the household silver. Lady Brackenstall's devoted maid Theresa Wright corroborates the story, and Hopkins is confident in the Randall theory. Holmes, however, notices inconsistencies: the bell-rope was cut, not torn; the wine glasses don't match the story; and the knot used to bind Lady Brackenstall was a sailor's knot. 
Holmes returns to the scene alone and unravels the truth. The killer was not a burglar but Captain Jack Croker, a handsome young officer of the Adelaide-Southampton line, who was deeply in love with Lady Brackenstall. She had married Sir Eustace, a violent and brutal drunkard who had abused her throughout their marriage — throwing a decanter at her, pouring wine over her, and committing other cruelties confirmed by Theresa. Croker had known Mary — Lady Brackenstall — in Australia before her marriage, and they had reconnected. On the night in question, Croker came to see Mary and was confronted by Sir Eustace, who attacked his wife. Croker struck Sir Eustace with the poker in her defense, killing him. He and Mary then staged the burglary scene, Theresa helping to create the Randall gang fiction. Holmes summons Croker to Baker Street, hears his account, and with Watson acting as a jury of one, renders their own private verdict — acquittal, on the grounds that Sir Eustace was a brutal man who provoked his own death, and that Croker acted to protect a woman being assaulted. Holmes gives Croker a year to prove his worth, pledging to suppress the evidence unless his conscience demands otherwise. Hopkins is left to pursue the Randalls in vain.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/abbe.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:berylCoronetDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Beryl Coronet" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Beryl Coronet" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Alexander Holder, a senior partner in the banking firm of Holder & Stevenson, rushes to Baker Street in a state of near-madness. One of the most important clients in the nation — implied to be royalty — has left the priceless Beryl Coronet, a public treasure of immense value, as security against a fifty-thousand-pound loan. Holder, uneasy about keeping such a treasure at the bank, took it home and locked it in his bureau. That night, he was awakened by a noise and found his dissolute son Arthur holding the coronet in his hands with a corner — bearing three of the thirty-nine beryls — missing. Arthur refuses to explain himself beyond insisting on his innocence, but the circumstantial evidence is overwhelming: he is deeply in debt, keeps company with Sir George Burnwell, a charming but disreputable man of the world, and was caught literally red-handed. Holder has Arthur arrested but is equally tormented by the missing gems, whose loss could trigger a national scandal. 
Holmes investigates and discovers that the true culprit is not Arthur but Mary Holder — Alexander's beautiful and beloved niece, whom he has raised as a daughter. Mary has fallen secretly under the influence of Sir George Burnwell, a practiced seducer, and it was she who took the coronet from the bureau and passed it through the window to Burnwell. Arthur, happening to witness the handoff, struggled to wrest the coronet back from Burnwell and managed to recover the main piece but not before the corner with three beryls snapped off in Burnwell's hands. Arthur refused to speak because he was shielding Mary, whom he loved. Holmes tracks Burnwell down, recovers the three gems by purchasing them from him, and returns them to the ecstatic Holder. But the cost is devastating: Mary has eloped with Burnwell, Arthur's reputation and relationship with his father have been shattered, and Holder realizes he had given his trust and affection to the wrong person all along. Holmes counsels him to make amends with his loyal son, who sacrificed everything to protect the family.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/bery.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:blackPeterDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of Black Peter" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of Black Peter" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Inspector Stanley Hopkins, a young and promising Scotland Yard detective whom Holmes has been mentoring, seeks Holmes's help with the brutal murder of Captain Peter Carey — known as Black Peter — a retired whaling and sealing captain found pinned to the wall of his cabin by a steel harpoon driven clean through his chest. Black Peter was a violent, alcoholic tyrant who terrorized his wife and daughter at their home, Woodman's Lee, near Forest Row in Sussex. His outhouse cabin, fitted out like a ship's berth and lined with logbooks and mementos, was his nightly drinking refuge. Hopkins has arrested a young man named John Hopley Neligan, found near the cabin carrying a notebook containing the initials of various securities, whose father — a failed banker — had disappeared years earlier after allegedly absconding with his clients' securities on the ship Sea Unicorn, which Black Peter had captained. Neligan claims he came to the cabin to search for evidence that might clear his father's name and found the door open and Black Peter already dead. 
Holmes proves Neligan could not be the killer through a practical experiment — he spends a morning at a butcher's shop attempting to drive a harpoon through a pig carcass and demonstrates that no man of Neligan's slight build could have delivered such a blow. Holmes deduces that the killer must be an experienced harpooner and places advertisements in maritime newspapers seeking harpoonists who sailed on the Sea Unicorn. Three men respond, and one — Patrick Cairns, a tough former harpooner from Dundee — is seized by Holmes when he arrives at Baker Street, handcuffs already concealed in Holmes's hands. Cairns confesses: he was aboard the Sea Unicorn when Black Peter murdered Neligan's father at sea and stole the securities, and Cairns had been blackmailing Black Peter with his knowledge of the crime. When Black Peter attacked him with a knife during a drunken confrontation over increased payment, Cairns grabbed the nearest weapon — the harpoon — and killed him in self-defense. Neligan's father was thus an innocent victim, not an absconder, and his son is cleared. Hopkins, initially deflated that his own suspect was wrong, receives Holmes's characteristically dry encouragement.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/blac.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:blanchedSoldierDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Blanched Soldier" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Blanched Soldier" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1926"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """This is one of only two stories narrated by Holmes himself rather than Watson, who is unavailable because he has recently married. James M. Dodd, a bluff, honest ex-soldier, consults Holmes about his close friend and former comrade Godfrey Emsworth, with whom he served in the Boer War. During the war, Dodd witnessed Godfrey being wounded and carried away during a skirmish near Diamond Hill, and after the war ended, Godfrey simply vanished from public life. His letters ceased, and when Dodd wrote to Godfrey's father, Colonel Emsworth, at Tuxbury Old Park in Bedfordshire, he received a cold and evasive reply discouraging any visit. Dodd insisted on coming anyway and found the atmosphere at the estate deeply strange — Colonel Emsworth and his wife were hostile and secretive, Godfrey was said to have gone on a voyage around the world, and a servant named Ralph was oddly protective of an outbuilding called "The Gables." One night, Dodd glimpsed Godfrey's face pressed against his bedroom window — ghastly white and bleached of all colour — before being pulled away. 
Holmes deduces from the evidence — the blanched skin, the isolation in a separate building, the family's desperate secrecy, and the presence of a medical attendant — that Godfrey has contracted what the family fears is leprosy, likely from a field hospital in South Africa where he was billeted alongside a case of the disease. The Emsworths have been hiding Godfrey in The Gables out of terror and shame, keeping him away from all contact. Holmes travels to Tuxbury Old Park and confronts the family, but rather than simply exposing the secret, he has arranged for Sir James Saunders, a leading dermatologist, to accompany him. Saunders examines Godfrey and delivers a joyful diagnosis: the condition is not true leprosy but pseudo-leprosy, known as ichthyosis — a disfiguring but non-contagious skin condition that is treatable and carries no danger to others. The family is overwhelmed with relief, Godfrey can rejoin the world, and Dodd's loyal persistence is vindicated. Holmes notes with characteristic modesty that the case, while dramatic in its human dimensions, was not particularly complex in its deductive requirements.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/blan.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:blueCarbuncleDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Blue Carbuncle" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Blue Carbuncle" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """A few days after Christmas, Holmes's friend Peterson the commissionaire brings him a battered felt hat and a large Christmas goose that were dropped by a stranger during a scuffle on the street. Holmes is amusing himself by deducing the owner's character from the hat when Peterson rushes back with astonishing news: his wife found the Blue Carbuncle — the famous Countess of Morcar's stolen gemstone — inside the crop of the goose. The stone had been stolen from the Countess's room at the Hotel Cosmopolitan, and a plumber named John Horner has been arrested for the theft on the testimony of the hotel's upper-attendant, James Ryder. Holmes traces the hat's owner through a newspaper advertisement to Henry Baker, a down-on-his-luck intellectual, but quickly determines Baker knows nothing of the gem. The trail then leads to the goose — Baker bought it from the Alpha Inn near the British Museum, which sourced its geese from a salesman named Breckinridge in Covent Garden. 
At Breckinridge's stall, Holmes finds the dealer besieged by an anxious, rat-faced little man desperately asking about the same flock of geese. Holmes follows this man and reveals him to be James Ryder himself — the hotel attendant who framed Horner for the theft. Confronted, Ryder breaks down and confesses the whole scheme: he stole the Carbuncle from the Countess's jewel case with the help of a maid named Catherine Cusack, then forced the gem down the throat of a goose belonging to his sister, Mrs. Oakshott, who raised geese in Brixton, intending to retrieve it later. But Ryder picked the wrong bird from his sister's flock, and the goose containing the jewel was sold on to Breckinridge and thence through the Alpha Inn to Henry Baker. Holmes, in a merciful Christmas spirit, lets the terrified Ryder go free — reasoning that prison would only make him a hardened criminal and that without Ryder's testimony the case against the innocent Horner will collapse. Holmes keeps the adventure as a private triumph, content to have saved one man and perhaps reformed another during the season of forgiveness.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/blue.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:boscombeValleyMysteryDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Boscombe Valley Mystery" ;
    dc:title "The Boscombe Valley Mystery" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Lestrade summons Holmes and Watson to Herefordshire, where a young man named James McCarthy has been arrested for the murder of his father, Charles McCarthy, at the Boscombe Pool — a small lake on the estate of John Turner, the wealthiest landowner in the district. The circumstantial evidence is damning: witnesses saw James following his father toward the pool, heard cries of "Cooee" — an Australian call — and found James kneeling beside his father's body with blood on his hands. The dying Charles McCarthy muttered what sounded like "a rat," and James admits to having quarreled violently with his father shortly before the death but refuses to reveal the subject of their argument. Holmes and Watson travel to the Ross area and Holmes examines the crime scene minutely, finding footprints, a jagged stone used as the murder weapon, and traces that point not to James but to a tall, left-handed man with a limp who smoked Indian cigars and carried a grey cloak. 
Holmes deduces that the killer is John Turner himself, the seemingly respectable squire, and confronts him privately. Turner, now elderly and dying of diabetes, confesses the full story: decades earlier in Australia, he was a highwayman known as Black Jack of Ballarat who robbed Charles McCarthy's gold convoy. McCarthy recognized Turner after both settled in England and had been blackmailing him for years, ultimately demanding that Turner's daughter Alice marry James McCarthy to cement the hold. When Turner overheard McCarthy pressing this demand on his reluctant son at the Boscombe Pool, he struck McCarthy down in a fury. The dying man's last word was not "a rat" but "Ballarat" — the Australian city that connected them. Holmes persuades Turner to write a sealed confession to be used only if James is convicted, then works to clear the young man by presenting evidence of the true killer's physical description. James is acquitted at the assizes, and he and Alice Turner eventually marry — never learning that Alice's father killed James's father. Turner dies within a few months, his secret intact.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/bosc.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:brucePartingtonPlansDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Bruce-Partington Plans" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Bruce-Partington Plans" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1908"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Mycroft Holmes takes the extraordinary step of visiting Baker Street in person — something he does only in the gravest emergencies — to enlist Sherlock's help recovering stolen submarine plans. Arthur Cadogan West, a young clerk at the Woolwich Arsenal, has been found dead on the tracks near Aldgate Underground station with seven of the ten pages of the top-secret Bruce-Partington submarine plans in his pockets. Three critical pages are missing. Cadogan West's fiancée Violet Westbury insists he was a devoted patriot incapable of treason, though she admits he rushed away from her abruptly on the foggy Monday evening of his death. Suspicion falls on Sidney Johnson, the senior clerk at Woolwich, and on Sir James Walter, the distinguished guardian of the plans, who dies of shock upon learning of the theft. Holmes notices that the body showed no signs of a train ticket and that the Underground line at the point where the body was found runs through a tunnel with no place to fall onto the tracks from above. 
Holmes deduces that the body was placed on the roof of a train carriage from a point where the tracks pass close to a building, and that it slid off when the train jolted over points near Aldgate. He identifies the critical location — a window overlooking the tracks near Gloucester Road station — and traces it to the home of Hugo Oberstein, one of the three great international espionage agents Holmes had previously identified. Oberstein had conspired with Colonel Valentine Walter, Sir James's younger brother who was deep in debt, to steal the plans. Valentine copied the key to the safe from Sir James's key ring and passed the plans to Oberstein. Cadogan West, spotting the suspicious transaction in the fog, followed the plans to Oberstein's house and was murdered there — his body then placed on the train roof to suggest an accidental death on the Underground. Holmes lures Oberstein back to London by placing a newspaper advertisement posing as Valentine offering the remaining three pages, and Oberstein is arrested. Colonel Valentine Walter confesses and is sentenced to fifteen years. Holmes receives an emerald tie-pin from a certain gracious lady at Windsor — implied to be Queen Victoria — for averting a national catastrophe.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/bruc.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:cardboardBoxDoc a schema:ShortStory ;  
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:storyYear "1888"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Susan Cushing, an elderly and unremarkable spinster living in Cross Street, Croydon, receives a parcel in the post containing two severed human ears packed in coarse salt. Inspector Lestrade initially treats the matter as a grotesque medical student's prank — Susan's younger sister Mary had once lodged medical students in her house — but Holmes immediately recognizes the ears as freshly severed and carefully preserved, one male and one female. Holmes studies Susan's three sisters: Mary Cushing, a widow in Wallington who runs a lodging house; Sarah Cushing, the eldest, a sharp-faced woman now living alone in New Street, Wallington, who had previously lived with Susan in Croydon before being sent away; and the youngest, the absent Jim Browner's wife. Holmes deduces from the knot used to tie the parcel — a sailor's knot — and from a strong physical resemblance he observes between Susan's features and one of the severed ears that the parcel was sent to the wrong sister. It was meant for Sarah, who had lived at Susan's address until recently. 
Holmes traces the package through shipping records to Jim Browner, a steward on the Liverpool-based steamship May Day. Browner, arrested in his cabin, makes a full and anguished confession. He had been a hard-drinking sailor who reformed after marrying Mary Cushing's youngest sister, the lively and beautiful Emmeline. Their marriage was happy until Sarah — a bitter, jealous woman who had never married — came to live with them. Sarah, attracted to Jim herself and rejected by him, poisoned the marriage out of spite by encouraging Emmeline into a social life with a young man named Alec Fairbairn, then manipulated the situation until Emmeline fell into an affair. Jim banned Fairbairn from his house, but Sarah ensured the meetings continued. One day, Jim followed Emmeline and Fairbairn as they went boating together on the New Brighton pleasure grounds, overtook their boat, and in a frenzy of jealous rage killed them both — cutting an ear from each as a grim trophy, which he sent to Sarah as an accusation, only to address the package to the old Croydon address where Susan now lived alone. Holmes reflects somberly on the senseless tragedy, pondering what purpose such suffering could serve.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/card.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:caseOfIdentityDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "A Case of Identity" ;
    dc:title "A Case of Identity" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Mary Sutherland, a plump and plainly dressed young woman with a comfortable income from her late uncle's estate, consults Holmes about the mysterious disappearance of her fiancé, Hosmer Angel. She describes how Angel — a shy, soft-spoken cashier — courted her at a gasfitters' ball and subsequent meetings, always while her stepfather James Windibank was conveniently away on business trips to France. Angel was peculiarly secretive: he would only meet her after dark, spoke in a whisper, kept his face shadowed by tinted glasses and a heavy moustache, and insisted she swear on a Bible that she would remain faithful to him no matter what happened. On their wedding morning, Angel entered a cab ahead of her on the way to the Church of St. Saviour's near King's Cross, and when the cab arrived, it was empty — he had vanished completely. 
Holmes quickly perceives the truth but finds it a problem with no satisfying resolution. By comparing the typewritten letters Angel sent to Mary with a typewritten letter Holmes elicits from James Windibank on a pretext, Holmes confirms that the two were typed on the same machine — Hosmer Angel is in fact Windibank himself in disguise. The stepfather, a younger man only five years older than Mary, invented the fictitious suitor to keep Mary infatuated and living at home, ensuring that her annual income of one hundred pounds continued to supplement the household rather than following her into a marriage with someone else. Holmes confronts Windibank, who smugly points out he has broken no law. Holmes agrees the case falls short of criminal prosecution but warns Windibank that he will come to a bad end, seizing a riding crop and threatening to thrash him as he flees. Holmes decides not to tell Mary the truth, predicting sadly that she would not believe him and would remain faithful to the phantom Hosmer Angel for years to come.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/iden.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:copperBeechesDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Copper Beeches" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Copper Beeches" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Violet Hunter, a young and capable governess, consults Holmes about a suspiciously generous job offer. Jephro Rucastle, a genial, heavyset man, has offered her an extraordinary salary of one hundred and twenty pounds a year to serve as governess to his six-year-old son at the Copper Beeches, a country house near Winchester. The conditions, however, are bizarre: she must cut her luxuriant chestnut hair short, sit where she is told, wear a specific electric-blue dress, and occasionally perform other odd tasks without question. Her agency, run by Miss Stoper, pressured her to accept. Holmes finds the situation sinister but advises her to take the position, promising she may summon him if she feels threatened. Violet accepts and soon writes to Holmes in alarm. At the Copper Beeches, she is periodically instructed by Rucastle and his pale, silent wife to sit with her back to a window while Mr. Rucastle tells her amusing stories, clearly for the benefit of someone watching from the road. She discovers a coil of chestnut hair matching her own shade locked in a drawer, and finds that an entire wing of the house is sealed off. The Rucastles' servant, a hulking, taciturn man named Toller, and his wife are the only others in the household, and a large mastiff is unchained at night to guard the grounds. 
Holmes and Watson rush to Winchester when Violet reports that she glimpsed a prisoner in the locked wing. Holmes deduces that the Rucastles' daughter Alice — from Jephro's first marriage — is being held captive to prevent her from reaching her fiancé or accessing her inheritance. Violet's role was to sit at the window impersonating Alice so that the watching suitor, a Mr. Fowler, would believe Alice was free and content, eventually giving up his suit. When they arrive at the Copper Beeches, they discover that Mrs. Toller, sympathetic to Alice, has helped Fowler rescue her through the back wing while the Rucastles were away. Jephro Rucastle, discovering the escape, rushes to the locked wing and is savaged nearly to death by his own mastiff, which Toller had neglected to feed. Rucastle survives but is left a broken invalid, tended by his subdued wife. Alice and Fowler marry, Mrs. Toller's testimony fills in the final gaps, and Violet Hunter goes on to a successful career as head of a private school — though Holmes, Watson notes with some amusement, never showed the personal interest in her that her intelligence and courage might have warranted.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/copp.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:creepingManDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Creeping Man" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Creeping Man" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1923"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Trevor Bennett, a young assistant and prospective son-in-law to the eminent Professor Presbury of Camford University, consults Holmes about his employer's alarming transformation. Presbury, a distinguished physiologist in his sixties, recently became engaged to Alice Morphy, the young daughter of his colleague Professor Morphy. After a mysterious trip to Prague — from which he returned secretive and irritable — Presbury's behaviour has changed dramatically. He receives letters from a London address and a sealed wooden box that he guards obsessively. More disturbingly, his faithful wolfhound Roy has attacked him twice at the bedroom door — an animal that previously adored him — and Bennett has witnessed the professor moving through the house at night in a strange, crouching, simian manner. His devoted daughter Edith and the household are deeply unsettled. Holmes notes that the bizarre episodes seem to occur at regular nine-day intervals. 
Holmes, Watson, and Bennett stake out the professor's home on the night the next episode is expected. They witness Presbury emerge and climb the ivy-covered wall of the house with ape-like agility, swinging from hand to hand to peer into his daughter's second-floor window — apparently spying on her and Bennett together. Roy the wolfhound breaks free and attacks Presbury savagely, biting his throat before Holmes and Watson pull the dog away. The professor is saved, and Holmes reveals the explanation: Presbury, desperate to restore his youthful vigour to be worthy of his young fiancée, had been corresponding with a shadowy Prague dealer named Lowenstein who supplied him with a serum derived from the langur monkey — a black-faced climbing primate. The injections, taken every nine days, gave Presbury temporary simian physical abilities but also monkey-like behavioural compulsions, including the climbing and creeping. The dog attacked because it sensed something fundamentally altered and alien in its master. Holmes warns darkly that such experiments — the attempt to artificially override the natural process of aging — represent a dangerous frontier of science, and he writes a stern letter to Lowenstein. Presbury eventually recovers, though the episode has shaken everyone close to him.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/cree.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:crookedManDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Crooked Man" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Crooked Man" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes visits Watson late one evening and invites him to investigate the death of Colonel James Barclay, the commanding officer of the Royal Mallows regiment, stationed at Aldershot. Barclay was found dead in his locked sitting room, his wife Nancy lying unconscious nearby, with signs of a violent quarrel between them. The door had to be broken down, yet the key was never found, and a small animal — possibly a weasel or stoat — had left odd tracks across the room and curtains. Servants testified that Nancy had returned from a charity meeting with her friend Miss Morrison in an agitated state, and that a furious argument ensued during which Nancy was heard screaming the word "David" at her husband — a name no one in the household recognized. Colonel Barclay appeared to have died of a stroke or seizure brought on by extreme terror, his face frozen in a look of horror, and a singular wooden-footed instrument was found near the body. 
Holmes, having traced Nancy's movements through Miss Morrison, reveals the astonishing backstory. After her charity meeting, Nancy had encountered Henry Wood — a wretched, crooked old man with a twisted spine who earned pennies performing with a mongoose on the streets. Wood was in fact Nancy's first love from thirty years ago, a young corporal in the same regiment, who had been sent on a dangerous mission to relieve the besieged garrison at Dobjhun during the Indian Mutiny. James Barclay, also in love with Nancy, had betrayed Wood's path to the enemy. Wood was captured, tortured, and spent decades in captivity and wandering Asia, his body broken. Nancy, believing Wood dead, had married Barclay. When she stumbled upon Wood by chance, the shock of learning the truth about her husband's treachery sent her home in a fury. Wood followed her and confronted Barclay through the garden window. Barclay, seeing the living proof of his betrayal after thirty years, collapsed and died of apoplexy — the shock killing him. Nancy fainted, and Wood fled with his mongoose, leaving the mysterious tracks. Nancy's cry of "David" was a biblical reference — David sending Uriah to his death to claim his wife. Holmes tells Watson there will likely be no prosecution, as Barclay died of natural causes triggered by his own guilty conscience, and the coroner's inquest confirms this.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/croo.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;  
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:dancingMenDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Dancing Men" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Dancing Men" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1903"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Hilton Cubitt, a sturdy Norfolk squire from Riding Thorpe Manor, consults Holmes about a series of mysterious drawings that have been terrifying his young American wife Elsie. A year earlier, Cubitt had married Elsie Patrick in London after she extracted a promise that he would never ask about her past, hinting only that she had been involved with disagreeable people in America. Their marriage was blissful until strange chalk drawings of stick figures — little dancing men — began appearing on windowsills, the garden sundial, and in notes slipped under the door. Each appearance sent Elsie into greater terror, though she refused to explain their meaning. Cubitt, deeply in love but troubled by the secrecy, copied the drawings and brought them to Holmes. Over a period of weeks, Holmes receives successive batches and undertakes to decipher them, recognizing the dancing figures as a substitution cipher in which each figure represents a letter of the alphabet, with flags held by certain figures marking the ends of words. 
Holmes cracks the code and discovers the messages are from a man named Abe Slaney, an American writing to Elsie — messages like "Come Elsie" and threatening "Else danger." Holmes sends an urgent warning to Cubitt and also dispatches a message to Slaney using the dancing-men cipher, but he is too late. Before Holmes and Watson can reach Norfolk, they learn that Cubitt has been shot dead and Elsie is critically wounded with a bullet to the brain, found in their sitting room in what initially appears to be a murder-suicide. Holmes examines the scene and determines from the bullet holes, spent cartridges, powder marks, and the smell of gunpowder that a third shot was fired from outside through the open window — meaning there was an intruder. Using his decoded knowledge, Holmes lures Abe Slaney to Riding Thorpe Manor with a note written in the dancing-men cipher purporting to be from Elsie. Slaney arrives and is arrested by Inspector Martin. He confesses that Elsie was the daughter of a Chicago crime boss named Patrick, and Slaney had been her fiancé before she fled America to escape that life. He tracked her to England, tried to persuade her to return, and when Cubitt confronted him at the window, they exchanged shots — Slaney killing Cubitt and Elsie then turning a gun on herself in despair. Slaney is convicted and sentenced to death, later commuted to penal servitude, and Elsie eventually recovers to devote herself to charitable works.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/danc.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:devilsFootDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Devil's Foot" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Devil's Foot" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1910"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes and Watson are on a restorative holiday in Cornwall near Poldhu Bay on the Mounts Bay coast when the local vicar, Mr. Roundhay, and his lodger Mortimer Tregennis bring them a horrifying case. The previous evening, Mortimer had played cards with his sister Brenda and two brothers, George and Owen Tregennis, at their home in Tredannick Wartha. When the household was discovered the next morning, Brenda was dead in her chair and George and Owen were sitting beside her laughing and singing, completely insane — all three frozen in expressions of absolute terror with no sign of physical violence. Mortimer, who had walked home to Roundhay's vicarage after the card game, was apparently the last to see them alive. Holmes examines the scene and finds no clue except that a lamp had been burning and a window was partially open. The local doctor, Leon Sterndale, a famous lion-hunter and African explorer who is deeply connected to the area, abruptly returns from his journey to London upon hearing the news — particularly distressed because he was romantically attached to Brenda Tregennis. 
Days later, Mortimer Tregennis himself is found dead in his room at the vicarage, his face contorted in the same expression of horror, with a lamp burning beside him. Holmes discovers traces of a powdery substance in the lamp and determines that the deaths were caused by Radix pedis diaboli — the Devil's Foot root — a rare and deadly West African poison that when burned produces fumes causing insanity or death in anyone who inhales them. Holmes tests the substance on himself and Watson in a reckless experiment that nearly kills them both. He deduces the sequence of events: Mortimer Tregennis, motivated by greed over a family inheritance dispute, had obtained a sample of the Devil's Foot powder from Sterndale's African collection, burned it in his siblings' room, and murdered his sister while driving his brothers mad. Leon Sterndale, discovering the truth through Holmes's investigation and his own knowledge of the poison, then administered justice himself — burning the same poison in Mortimer's lamp as retribution for Brenda's death, the woman Sterndale had secretly loved for years. Holmes allows Sterndale to walk free, accepting his argument that he has dispensed a rough but fitting justice, and tells Watson the case is closed.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/devi.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Disappearance of Lady Frances Carfax" ;
    dc:title "The Disappearance of Lady Frances Carfax" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1911"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes dispatches Watson to Lausanne, Switzerland, to investigate the disappearance of Lady Frances Carfax — an unmarried, middle-aged noblewoman of the late Earl of Rufton's family, who has been wandering alone across the Continent and has suddenly stopped writing to her correspondents. Watson traces her path through the Hotel National in Lausanne, where she had befriended a former missionary couple, Dr. Shlessinger and his wife, who were travelling to London for the doctor's health. Watson also encounters Philip Green, a rough-mannered South African who has been following Lady Frances — and whom Watson nearly fights before learning Green is a devoted admirer who once courted her. Watson discovers that Lady Frances left Lausanne abruptly, stayed in Baden and then Montpellier, was seen in the company of the Shlessingers in each city, and had been persuaded to visit the doctor's wife at their London lodgings. Alarmingly, she was observed pawning her jewelry — old Spanish silver and other heirlooms — and her trail has gone cold. 
Holmes, dissatisfied with Watson's progress, arrives in person and discovers that "Dr. Shlessinger" is actually Holy Peters, a notorious Australian criminal, and his companion is Annie Fraser, his partner in crime. The pair have been systematically stripping Lady Frances of her valuables, and Holmes fears they mean to murder her. Holmes and Watson trace the couple to a house in Brixton, where they find Peters has ordered a suspiciously long coffin for the supposed funeral of an old woman named Rose Spender who had died in the house. Holmes initially dismisses the coffin lead after finding old Rose's body inside it, but realizes in a flash of insight that Peters has hidden Lady Frances beneath the dead body — chloroformed and sealed in the coffin, to be buried alive. Holmes, Watson, Philip Green, and Inspector Lestrade rush to the undertaker and pry open the coffin just in time, finding Lady Frances drugged but alive beneath the corpse. She is revived by Dr. Watson with ether injections, barely saved from a ghastly death. Peters and Fraser are arrested, though Holmes ruefully admits the case was one where his own initial skepticism about the coffin nearly proved fatal.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/lady.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:dyingDetectiveDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Dying Detective" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Dying Detective" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1913"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Mrs. Hudson summons Watson in a panic, reporting that Holmes has been desperately ill for three days, refusing all food and medical attention, and appears to be dying. Watson rushes to Baker Street and finds Holmes emaciated, delirious, and raving about a deadly tropical disease — Tapanuli fever, or "black Formosa corruption" — that he claims to have contracted while investigating a case among Chinese sailors in Rotherhithe. Holmes violently refuses Watson's medical help, insisting that only one man has the expertise to treat him: Culverton Smith, a planter from Sumatra who is known for his study of such diseases. Holmes sends Watson to fetch Smith, but with specific instructions: Watson must return before Smith and must not tell Smith that Holmes has any suspicion against him. Watson dutifully brings Smith to Baker Street, then is ordered to leave the room — but Holmes had earlier instructed Watson to remain hidden, and Watson watches from behind the bed head. 
Smith arrives and, believing they are alone, reveals his true nature. He gloats over Holmes's suffering, confessing that he murdered his nephew Victor Savage using the same disease — delivered through a poisoned spring-loaded box sent through the mail — and that he sent Holmes an identical infected box, which Holmes opened. Smith refuses to help and waits for Holmes to die. At that moment, Holmes sits up in perfect health — the entire illness was an elaborate performance. Holmes had fasted for three days, applied belladonna to his eyes, rouge and beeswax to his face, and used a coin on his lips to simulate cracked, parched skin, all to deceive both Watson and Smith. The box did arrive, but Holmes handled it with care and was never infected. Watson turns up the gas to signal Inspector Morton, who has been waiting outside, and Smith is arrested for the murder of Victor Savage, with Watson as a witness to Smith's bedside confession. Holmes apologizes to Watson for the deception, explaining that only a genuinely horrified Watson could convince Smith that Holmes was truly dying — Watson's honest nature would have betrayed any conspiracy.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/dyin.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:emptyHouseDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Empty House" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Empty House" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1903"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Three years after his apparent death at the Reichenbach Falls, Holmes makes a dramatic return. Watson, now a widower, has been following the unsolved murder of the Honourable Ronald Adair — a young nobleman shot through the head in his locked second-floor sitting room at 427 Park Lane, with no weapon found and no clue as to how the bullet entered the room. While investigating the scene among the crowd of onlookers, Watson bumps into a deformed elderly bibliophile who later appears at his home — and reveals himself to be Sherlock Holmes in disguise. Holmes explains that he did not die at Reichenbach: he knew Moriarty had a confederate watching from above, so after grappling with Moriarty and sending the professor to his death, Holmes used his knowledge of baritsu, a Japanese martial art, to scramble up the cliff face and escape. He then faked his death and spent three years traveling incognito — visiting Tibet under the name Sigerson, passing through Montpellier to conduct chemical research, and journeying through Persia and southern France — because at least one dangerous member of Moriarty's gang remained at large and believed Holmes dead. 
That remaining agent is Colonel Sebastian Moran, a celebrated big-game hunter and Moriarty's chief lieutenant, whom Holmes identifies as the man who tried to kill him with rocks at Reichenbach and who murdered Ronald Adair. Adair had discovered that Moran was cheating at cards at their clubs — the Bagatelle, the Cavendish, and others — and threatened to expose him, so Moran shot him with a silent air rifle from across the street. Holmes lures Moran into a trap using a wax bust of himself placed in the window of 221B Baker Street, crafted by the French sculptor Oscar Meunier and moved periodically by Mrs. Hudson to simulate lifelike movement. Moran takes the bait, firing at the bust from the empty house across the street, and is seized by Holmes, Watson, and Inspector Lestrade. The air rifle — a remarkable weapon constructed by a blind German mechanic named Von Herder — is recovered. Moran is charged with Adair's murder, and Holmes resumes his residence at Baker Street, his long exile ended and London's criminal underworld once again put on notice.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/empt.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:engineersThumbDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Engineer's Thumb" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Engineer's Thumb" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Watson receives an early morning visit at his consulting room from Victor Hatherley, a young hydraulic engineer whose thumb has been cleanly chopped off during a terrifying nocturnal adventure. Hatherley recounts that he was hired by a Colonel Lysander Stark, a thin, nervous German, to inspect a hydraulic press at his isolated country house near Eyford in Berkshire, ostensibly used for compressing fuller's earth into bricks. Stark offered fifty guineas for secrecy and a single night's work. Arriving late at night, Hatherley was met by Stark and driven to a lonely house, where a frightened woman — Elise — urgently begged him to leave. Hatherley examined the press and quickly realized it was not being used for fuller's earth at all but for a criminal operation. When he noticed metallic deposits revealing that the press was being used to stamp counterfeit coins, Stark trapped him inside the press and began lowering the ceiling to crush him. Elise saved his life by showing him a side panel through which he escaped, but as he clung to the windowsill outside, Stark hacked at him with a cleaver, severing his thumb and sending him falling into the garden, where he lost consciousness. 
Watson brings Hatherley to Holmes, who quickly deduces key details — including that Hatherley was driven in a circle to disguise the fact that the house was very near Eyford station — and they set off with Inspector Bradstreet to investigate. They arrive to find the house already ablaze, likely set when a lamp was crushed during Hatherley's escape through the press. Stark, Elise, and a burly accomplice named Ferguson have fled with their equipment, and despite a thorough investigation, the counterfeiters are never caught. Holmes consoles the dejected Hatherley, who has lost his thumb and his fee and gained nothing from the experience, by suggesting he has at least gained a remarkable story — though Hatherley replies ruefully that he would gladly trade it for his missing thumb.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/engr.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:finalProblemDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Final Problem" ;
    dc:title "The Final Problem" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Watson recounts with heavy heart the events leading to what he believes is the death of Sherlock Holmes. Holmes appears at Watson's consulting room one evening in April 1891, visibly shaken and with scraped knuckles, revealing that he has been locked in a secret war against Professor James Moriarty — the supreme criminal mastermind of London, a former mathematics professor whose intellectual brilliance masks his role as the organizing genius behind half the evil in the city. Holmes has spent months carefully dismantling Moriarty's vast network and has arranged with the police for a mass arrest on the following Monday. But Moriarty himself has visited Holmes at Baker Street, warning him to withdraw or be destroyed. Three attempts on Holmes's life follow in rapid succession — a speeding cab nearly runs him down, a brick falls from a rooftop narrowly missing him, and a ruffian with a bludgeon attacks him on the way to Watson's. Holmes asks Watson to flee with him to the Continent, planning to wait out the weekend until the arrests are made and Moriarty's organization is crushed. 
Holmes and Watson embark on a desperate flight across Europe, escaping from Victoria Station just as Moriarty charters a special train in pursuit. They travel through Brussels and Strasbourg to Switzerland, learning along the way that while most of Moriarty's gang has been captured, Moriarty himself evaded the police. At the village of Meiringen in the Swiss Alps, Holmes is lured away from Watson by a false message, and Watson returns to find Holmes gone. At the Reichenbach Falls — a terrifying cascade plunging into an immense chasm — Watson finds Holmes's silver cigarette case, his alpine-stock, and a farewell letter explaining that he and Moriarty had met at the precipice. Holmes writes that he is content to end his career by ridding the world of Moriarty, and that no better conclusion to his life's work could be imagined. Watson sees evidence that two sets of footprints approach the cliff edge and none return. He concludes that Holmes and Moriarty grappled at the brink and fell together into the abyss. Watson mourns the loss of the best and wisest man he has ever known, while acknowledging that Holmes's sacrifice destroyed the most dangerous criminal organization in Europe.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/fina.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:fiveOrangePipsDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Five Orange Pips" ;
    dc:title "The Five Orange Pips" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """On a stormy autumn night in 1887, a young man named John Openshaw consults Holmes in great distress. His uncle Elias Openshaw, a former planter who had lived for years in the American South and served briefly as a colonel in the Confederate army, returned to England and lived as a recluse at his estate in Horsham, Sussex. In 1883, Elias received an envelope postmarked from Pondicherry, India, containing five dried orange pips and a note reading "K.K.K." with instructions to leave certain papers on the sundial. Elias was terrified, burned papers from a brass box marked "K.K.K.," and was found dead in a garden pool weeks later — the inquest ruling suicide. The estate passed to John's father Joseph, who in 1885 received an identical envelope postmarked Dundee, Scotland, with the same demand. Joseph dismissed it, and within days was found dead at the bottom of a chalk pit near his home, the coroner calling it an accident. Now John himself has received the pips, posted from East London, with the instruction to place the papers on the sundial. 
Holmes recognizes the K.K.K. as the Ku Klux Klan and deduces that Elias Openshaw must have kept documents from his time with the organization that someone is determined to recover. He advises John to place a note on the sundial stating that the papers were burned, and Holmes begins tracing the threat by tracking sailing vessels between the postmark cities. But Holmes acts too slowly — John Openshaw is found drowned near Waterloo Bridge that very night, pushed into the Thames on a dark, rainy walk from Holmes's rooms. Holmes, deeply shaken and blaming himself, traces the source of the envelopes to the bark Lone Star out of Savannah, Georgia, and sends five orange pips of his own to the ship's captain, James Calhoun, along with a letter. However, justice comes by another hand: the Lone Star is lost at sea in the Atlantic storms, and Calhoun and his crew are never heard from again. Holmes counts the case among his rare failures, the murderers having perished before human justice could reach them.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/five.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:gloriaScottDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Gloria Scott" ;
    dc:title "The Gloria Scott" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes recounts to Watson the very first case that set him on the path to becoming a detective. During his university days, Holmes's only friend was a fellow student named Victor Trevor, who invited Holmes to spend a month at his father's estate in Donnithorpe, Norfolk. Old Mr. Trevor, a retired justice of the peace and prosperous country gentleman, was deeply shaken when Holmes casually deduced details about his past from his appearance — particularly the initials "J.A." tattooed on his arm, suggesting a former intimate relationship. Weeks later, a rough, sunburned sailor named Hudson appeared at the estate, claiming to be an old shipmate, and Mr. Trevor received him with a hospitality that seemed driven more by fear than friendship. Hudson gradually became an insolent tyrant in the household, tormenting Mr. Trevor and driving away the gamekeeper before being sent to work for Mr. Trevor's friend, Mr. Beddoes, in Hampshire. Shortly afterward, Mr. Trevor received a seemingly innocuous message about fly-fishing, collapsed upon reading it, and never recovered. Victor summoned Holmes, who discovered that reading every third word of the message revealed a hidden warning: Hudson had betrayed them and a man named Beddoes was informing on them to the authorities. 
Among the dying Mr. Trevor's papers, Holmes found a written confession revealing the old man's true identity. He was originally James Armitage, a young bank embezzler transported to Australia aboard the convict ship Gloria Scott in 1855. During the voyage, Armitage and fellow convicts — including Jack Prendergast, a wealthy and charismatic criminal who had bribed the guards and smuggled weapons aboard — staged a mutiny. The takeover went violently wrong: the ship's chaplain tried to ignite the powder magazine, the explosion destroyed the vessel, and only a handful survived in a small boat. Among the survivors were Armitage, a man named Evans (later Mr. Beddoes), and the sailor Hudson. The survivors were rescued by another ship, assumed false identities, and used Prendergast's hidden wealth to build respectable new lives. Hudson, however, eventually tracked them down and blackmailed them. After Mr. Trevor's death, Beddoes apparently killed Hudson and fled — a letter from Beddoes to Mr. Trevor confirming this was never opened, and Beddoes was never seen again. Holmes tells Watson that this case — the unraveling of a hidden message and a buried past — showed him that his talents for observation and deduction could become a profession.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/glor.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:goldenPinceNezDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Golden Pince-Nez" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Golden Pince-Nez" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Inspector Stanley Hopkins again summons Holmes, this time to Yoxley Old Place in Kent, where Willoughby Smith, a young secretary, has been found stabbed to death in the study of his employer, the reclusive Professor Coram. Smith's dying words to the maid Susan Tarlton were "the professor — it was she," clutching a pair of golden pince-nez in his hand that belonged neither to him nor to anyone known in the household. Professor Coram, an elderly invalid who keeps his bed half the time and is tended by his housekeeper Mrs. Marker, seems genuinely distraught. The corridor leading to the study is a dead end — anyone entering must exit the same way — yet no one was seen leaving, and the grounds show no sign of escape. Holmes examines the pince-nez carefully and deduces from the thick lenses and nose clip that the owner is a woman with a thick nose, close-set eyes, a puckered forehead, rounded shoulders, and very poor eyesight — virtually blind without the glasses. 
Holmes sets a trap by watching for signs that someone is hiding in the house, and his patience is rewarded. Following clues — a scratch on the bureau and subtle changes in the professor's food consumption — Holmes deduces that a second person has been concealed in an inner room. He confronts Professor Coram, who breaks down. The hidden woman emerges: she is Anna, the professor's estranged wife, a Russian revolutionary whom he had betrayed years ago in their homeland. Coram — whose real name is Sergius — had been a nihilist in their circle but turned informer, sending Anna and her compatriots to Siberian imprisonment while he escaped to England under a false identity. Anna, released after years of suffering, tracked him down to retrieve a document that could free another imprisoned comrade named Alexis. She broke into the study to find the document in Coram's cabinet, was surprised by Willoughby Smith, and in the blind struggle — unable to see without her glasses — accidentally stabbed him with a sealing-wax knife. Smith tore the pince-nez from her face as he fell. Anna hid in the professor's secret room with his reluctant help. Having now secured the document, Anna takes poison before she can be arrested, dying defiantly and expressing remorse only for the innocent young man she killed by accident. Holmes ensures the document reaches the Russian Embassy to aid her cause.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/gold.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:greekInterpreterDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Greek Interpreter" ;
    dc:title "The Greek Interpreter" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """This story introduces Mycroft Holmes, Sherlock's elder brother, whom Holmes describes as possessing even greater powers of observation and deduction but lacking the energy or ambition to put them to practical use. Mycroft works as a government auditor and spends his evenings at the Diogenes Club, an eccentric institution for the most unsociable men in London where no member is permitted to speak to another. At the club, Mycroft introduces a distressed acquaintance named Melas, a Greek interpreter, who recounts a harrowing experience. Melas was abducted by a threatening, giggling man named Latimer, driven through darkened streets for hours, and brought to a house where he was forced to interpret between Latimer's associate — a gaunt, cruel man named Harold — and a Greek prisoner whose face was covered in plasters and who was clearly being held against his will. The prisoner, who identified himself as Paul Kratides, was being pressured to sign documents, which he steadfastly refused to do. During the interrogation, Melas managed to covertly exchange information with Kratides, learning that Kratides had been imprisoned for weeks and that a woman named Sophy — his sister — was involved. A woman did appear, screaming in horror at Kratides's condition before being dragged away. Melas was threatened with death if he spoke, then driven home and abandoned. 
Holmes places newspaper advertisements seeking information about both Kratides and a Greek woman named Sophy, but their plans are overtaken when Melas is abducted a second time. Holmes and Watson, together with Mycroft, Inspector Gregson, and a plainclothes officer, trace the address to a house in Beckenham. They arrive to find Melas and Kratides locked in a room filled with burning charcoal — a deliberate attempt to asphyxiate them. Melas is revived but Paul Kratides is dead. The villains' scheme is now clear: Harold Latimer and Wilson Kemp had kidnapped Paul Kratides to force him to sign over property belonging to his sister Sophy, with whom Harold had eloped or whom he had lured from Greece. Sophy was being held captive and used as leverage against her brother. Latimer and Kemp have fled by the time the police arrive, taking Sophy with them. Some months later, a newspaper report from Budapest reveals that two Englishmen travelling with a Greek woman were found murdered — stabbed to death — with the woman believed responsible. Holmes considers it likely that Sophy Kratides avenged her brother's death by killing his captors.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/gree.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:hisLastBowDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "His Last Bow" ;
    dc:title "His Last Bow" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1917"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Set on the eve of the First World War in August 1914, this story is narrated in the third person rather than by Watson. Von Bork, a German spymaster operating under diplomatic cover from his villa on the English coast near Harwich, is preparing to return to Germany with a trove of stolen British military secrets — naval signals, harbour defences, aeronautic plans, and more — collected over four years of espionage. His chief agent, an Irish-American named Altamont who has cultivated a reputation as a bitter Anglophobe, is due to deliver the final and most critical package: the naval signals. Von Bork's colleague Baron Von Herling, the chief secretary of the German legation, departs after a conversation in which both men congratulate themselves on Germany's war preparations and Britain's apparent unreadiness. Altamont arrives in a Ford car with the promised parcel — but when Von Bork opens it, he finds not naval signals but a book titled Practical Handbook of Bee Culture, and Altamont's manner suddenly changes. 
Altamont is revealed to be Sherlock Holmes, who has spent two years deep undercover infiltrating Von Bork's spy network on instructions from the British government, working through the Foreign Minister himself. Holmes has been systematically feeding false intelligence to Von Bork while identifying the entire German spy ring, which has already been rolled up — every agent arrested. Watson, who was driving the car, helps Holmes chloroform and bind the stunned Von Bork, and they prepare to deliver him and his safe full of documents to Scotland Yard. Holmes reveals that his years of supposed retirement — keeping bees on the Sussex Downs — gave him the perfect cover for the assignment, and that his wandering years as Altamont through Chicago, Buffalo, and Ireland built the credible persona. As they drive away with their prisoner, Holmes gazes out at the moonlit sea and speaks presciently of an east wind coming — a terrible storm that will leave a cleaner, better, stronger land in its wake — in what amounts to a farewell from Holmes on the brink of the Great War.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/last.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc a schema:Book ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Hound of the Baskervilles" ;
    dc:title "The Hound of the Baskervilles" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1902"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Dr. James Mortimer visits Holmes and Watson at Baker Street with a chilling problem: his friend and patron Sir Charles Baskerville has been found dead on the grounds of Baskerville Hall on Dartmoor, his face frozen in terror, and nearby were the footprints of a gigantic hound. An old family legend holds that a spectral hound has haunted the Baskervilles since the wicked Hugo Baskerville was killed by such a creature in the 1600s while pursuing a kidnapped maiden across the moor. The heir, Sir Henry Baskerville, arrives in London from Canada and is immediately targeted — a warning letter assembled from newspaper cuttings tells him to stay away from the moor, and one of his new boots is stolen from his hotel. Holmes, too busy with other cases to go himself, dispatches Watson to Dartmoor as Sir Henry's protector, where Watson encounters a cast of suspicious neighbors: the naturalist Stapleton and his beautiful sister Beryl, the Barrymore butler couple who have been secretly signaling to Beryl's escaped-convict brother Selden on the moor, and the reclusive old lawyer Frankland. 
Watson discovers that Holmes has in fact been hiding on the moor all along, secretly investigating from a stone hut among the ancient ruins. Holmes has deduced that Stapleton is actually a Baskerville cousin — the son of Roger Baskerville, the black sheep of the family — who stands to inherit if both Sir Charles and Sir Henry die. Stapleton has been using a real hound, an enormous dog coated in phosphorus to give it a ghostly appearance, to literally frighten the Baskervilles to death; Sir Charles, already in poor cardiac health, died of heart failure upon seeing the beast. Holmes and Watson set a trap using Sir Henry as bait after a dinner at Stapleton's home, Merripit House. The hound is released in a thick fog and nearly kills Sir Henry before Holmes and Watson shoot it dead. Stapleton flees into the great Grimpen Mire, a treacherous bog from which he presumably never emerges. It is further revealed that Beryl is not Stapleton's sister but his abused wife, whom he kept captive to prevent her from warning Sir Henry, with whom Stapleton had encouraged a flirtation as part of his scheme.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/houn.txt" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:illustriousClientDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Illustrious Client" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Illustrious Client" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1924"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """An emissary named Colonel Sir James Damery visits Holmes on behalf of an unnamed but powerful client — implied to be royalty or a figure very close to it — to prevent the marriage of Violet de Merville, a beautiful and strong-willed young woman, to Baron Adelbert Gruner, an Austrian nobleman whom Holmes privately knows to be one of the most dangerous men in Europe. Gruner is a murderer — widely suspected of killing his first wife on the Splügen Pass and making it look like an accident — a collector of fine Chinese pottery, and a systematic seducer who keeps a leather-bound diary recording his conquests in lurid detail. Violet, however, is utterly enthralled by Gruner and has been warned by her father General de Merville and by friends without success. Holmes confronts Gruner directly but is rebuffed with threats, and shortly afterward Holmes is attacked on the street by two thugs hired by Gruner, leaving him badly injured. While Holmes recovers, Watson is sent to enlist the help of Kitty Winter — a former mistress whom Gruner used and discarded — who knows about the diary and burns with desire for revenge. 
Holmes devises a two-pronged attack. He sends Watson to Gruner's house under the pretext of being a fellow collector of Chinese pottery — Holmes having crammed Watson with expertise overnight from a borrowed book — to distract Gruner with a conversation about Ming saucers and other ceramics. Meanwhile, Holmes's agent Kitty Winter burgles Gruner's study and steals the incriminating diary. The plan partly succeeds: Watson engages Gruner, and the diary is recovered, but Kitty Winter, overcome with fury, throws vitriol — sulfuric acid — into Gruner's face, horribly disfiguring him. The diary is shown to Violet de Merville, whose infatuation instantly collapses upon reading the documented evidence of Gruner's treatment of other women. The marriage is called off. Gruner survives but is permanently scarred, and Kitty Winter faces trial for the acid attack, though Holmes hopes for a lenient sentence given the provocation. The illustrious client's identity is never revealed, though Holmes and Watson dine afterward at a famous establishment where the unnamed client's gratitude is personally expressed.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/illu.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:lionsManeDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Lion's Mane" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Lion's Mane" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1926"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """This story is narrated by Holmes himself during his retirement years, living alone on the Sussex Downs near the coast keeping bees. Fitzroy McPherson, a popular young science teacher at Harold Stackhurst's coaching establishment, The Gables, staggers up from the beach one morning in agony, his back covered in angry red welts as if lashed by a whip, gasping the words "the lion's mane" before collapsing dead at Holmes's feet. McPherson had been heading for his regular morning swim in a tidal pool among the chalk cliffs. Suspicion falls on Ian Murdoch, a dour and jealous mathematics colleague who had quarreled with McPherson over McPherson's secret relationship with Maud Bellamy, the beautiful daughter of old Tom Bellamy who runs the local boat business with his son William. Murdoch and McPherson had clashed bitterly, and Murdoch had no alibi. Holmes also discovers that McPherson's dog, a faithful terrier, was found dead on the beach path the following day with identical welts across its body — eliminating any human suspect, since no killer would bother to murder a dog in the same manner. 
Holmes is stumped until he recalls a passage from a book he has read — J.G. Wood's Out of Doors — describing the deadly sting of Cyanea capillata, the lion's mane jellyfish, the most dangerous jellyfish in the world. Holmes rushes to the tidal pool and finds an enormous specimen lurking in the lagoon, its translucent body barely visible and its long trailing tentacles filling the rocky pool like a tangle of deadly threads. McPherson had been stung while entering the water for his swim, and the dog died from contact with the same creature on the path where it had brushed against residual tentacles on the rocks. Holmes, Stackhurst, and the local policeman Inspector Bardle destroy the jellyfish with a large boulder. Murdoch is exonerated — his surly behaviour was driven by private grief, and he and McPherson had in fact recently reconciled. Maud Bellamy is devastated by her lover's death. Holmes reflects that the case was one where nature itself was the culprit, and that the creature's common name — the lion's mane — was McPherson's dying clue, had Holmes only recognized it sooner.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/lion.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:manWithTheTwistedLipDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Man with the Twisted Lip" ;
    dc:title "The Man with the Twisted Lip" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Watson is drawn into a case when his wife sends him to retrieve Isa Whitney, an opium addict, from a low den in Upper Swandam Lane near the London docks. At the den, Watson is startled to find Holmes himself in disguise, working on the disappearance of Neville St. Clair — a respectable gentleman from Lee in Kent whose wife saw him at a second-floor window of the opium den before he seemingly vanished. When police searched the room, they found not St. Clair but a filthy, disfigured beggar named Hugh Boone, well known in the City for his wit and pitiful appearance. St. Clair's coat, weighted with pennies, was found in the Thames mud below the window, and blood was discovered in the room. Boone is arrested on suspicion of murder but protests his innocence, and no body is ever found. Mrs. St. Clair complicates matters by receiving a letter in her husband's handwriting days after his disappearance, enclosing his signet ring. 
Holmes spends a long night smoking his way through the problem at their lodging in Lee, and by morning has the solution. He and Watson rush to the jail with Inspector Bradstreet, where Holmes takes a wet sponge to Hugh Boone's face — washing away paint, grime, and a scar to reveal the healthy features of Neville St. Clair himself. St. Clair, a former journalist, had once disguised himself as a beggar for a newspaper article and discovered he could earn far more money begging in the City than writing. Over the years he secretly maintained this double life, earning a substantial income as Hugh Boone while his family believed he commuted to an office in London. On the day of his disappearance, his wife spotted him unexpectedly at the window of the room above the den where he changed into his disguise; in a panic, he had Lascar — the den's operator — help him hide and was arrested as Boone before he could escape. No crime has been committed beyond a minor charge of begging, and St. Clair swears never to resume the imposture. Holmes and the police agree to keep the secret, provided Boone the beggar is never seen again.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/twis.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:mazarinStoneDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Mazarin Stone" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Mazarin Stone" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1921"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """This is one of the rare Holmes stories narrated in the third person rather than by Watson. Lord Cantlemere, a sceptical and disdainful elderly peer, visits Baker Street on behalf of the government regarding the theft of the Crown diamond — the famous yellow Mazarin Stone, worth a hundred thousand pounds. Holmes has already identified the thieves: Count Negretto Sylvius, a big-game hunter and dangerous aristocratic criminal, and his accomplice Sam Merton, a hulking boxer. Holmes has been shadowing Sylvius through London, surviving at least one attempt on his life — a dropped stone from a building — and has the Count thoroughly rattled. Holmes demonstrates his confidence by showing Lord Cantlemere a wax bust of himself that he uses as a decoy in the window of 221B, turned periodically by Billy the page boy to simulate movement — a trick reminiscent of the Moran affair. Cantlemere departs unconvinced that Holmes can recover the stone. 
Holmes lures both Sylvius and Merton to Baker Street, where he confronts them openly, revealing he knows the stone was stolen by Sylvius while Merton distracted a guard, and that their associate the boxer Ikey Sanders has been arrested. Holmes offers them a choice: return the stone and walk free, or face arrest for the murder of the old woman Mrs. Blumer and be hanged. He then excuses himself, seemingly stepping behind a curtain to play his violin — but the music actually comes from a gramophone, and Holmes has slipped away through a secret door. Sylvius and Merton, believing themselves alone, take out the hidden stone to discuss their situation, and Holmes silently re-enters and palms it from the table. When Lord Cantlemere returns, Holmes directs him to check his own overcoat pocket, where Holmes has surreptitiously planted the recovered Mazarin Stone — a theatrical flourish that leaves the pompous lord speechless. Sylvius and Merton are arrested, the Crown diamond is restored, and Holmes savors the triumph with characteristic flair.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/maza.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:milvertonDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of Charles Augustus Milverton" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of Charles Augustus Milverton" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes declares Charles Augustus Milverton to be the worst man in London — worse than any murderer. Milverton is a master blackmailer who systematically purchases compromising letters from treacherous servants and former lovers, then extorts enormous sums from his victims, ruining those who cannot or will not pay. His latest target is Lady Eva Brackwell, a beautiful debutante whose impending marriage to the Earl of Dovercourt will be destroyed if certain indiscreet letters are made public. Holmes is engaged to negotiate, but Milverton demands seven thousand pounds and will not budge from his price. Holmes resolves to take extraordinary measures: he becomes engaged to Milverton's housemaid Agatha under the alias of a plumber named Escott, courting her to gain intelligence about the layout of Milverton's heavily secured Appledore Towers mansion in Hampstead. Watson is shocked but Holmes insists the stakes justify the deception. 
Holmes and Watson break into Appledore Towers at night to steal and destroy the compromising documents. While hiding behind a curtain in Milverton's study, they witness a dramatic scene: a veiled woman arrives for what Milverton believes is a business transaction, but she reveals herself as one of his former victims — a noblewoman whose husband died of a broken heart after Milverton ruined her. She produces a pistol and shoots Milverton dead, grinding her heel into his face before fleeing. Holmes seizes the opportunity to burn the contents of Milverton's safe — bundles of letters that would have destroyed dozens of lives — while Watson keeps watch. They escape over the garden wall with Milverton's servants in pursuit. The next morning, Inspector Lestrade visits Baker Street seeking Holmes's help in solving Milverton's murder, showing photographs of a suspect. Holmes recognizes the veiled woman but refuses the case outright, and Watson notices Holmes turn a photograph face-down at a shop — revealing the killer to be a famous and titled lady. Both Holmes and Watson tacitly agree that justice has been served and that Milverton's death was a matter of private retribution they have no desire to undo.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/chas.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:missingThreeQuarterDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Missing Three-Quarter" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Missing Three-Quarter" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Dr. Leslie Armstrong, a prominent physician in Cambridge, is at the center of a mystery brought to Holmes by Cyril Overton, the captain of the Cambridge university rugby team. Godfrey Staunton, the brilliant three-quarter whose play is essential to their chances in the upcoming match against Oxford, has vanished from his hotel the night before the game after receiving a cryptic telegram and leaving with a bearded man in a brougham. Overton is desperate — without Staunton, Cambridge will surely lose. Holmes investigates and discovers that Staunton had recently been in correspondence with Dr. Leslie Armstrong, a gruff and formidable man who is openly hostile to Holmes's inquiries and deliberately misleads him. Holmes also learns from a helpful telegraph clerk that Staunton sent an urgent wire to Dr. Armstrong the previous night, and from the manager of his inn that Lord Mount-James — Staunton's notoriously miserly uncle and nearest relative — is unlikely to have provided financial help despite Staunton's evident money troubles. 
Holmes, unable to break through Armstrong's stonewalling, resorts to an ingenious stratagem: he obtains aniseed oil from a local druggist and uses it to track Armstrong's carriage by scent with a draghound borrowed from the area. The hound follows the trail to a remote cottage on the outskirts of Cambridge, where Holmes, Watson, and the distraught Overton find the truth — not a crime but a tragedy. Godfrey Staunton had been secretly married to a young woman who suffered from consumption, keeping the marriage hidden to avoid being disinherited by the wealthy but heartless Lord Mount-James. His wife had taken a fatal turn, and Dr. Armstrong — who had been treating her for free out of compassion — summoned Staunton to her deathside. They arrive to find Staunton weeping over the body of his dead wife, with Armstrong tenderly attending. Holmes quietly withdraws, telling Overton that this is no matter for a detective, and privately expresses deep respect for Dr. Armstrong's character and devotion. The rugby match and the missing three-quarter become trivial in the face of genuine human grief.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/miss.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:musgraveRitualDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Musgrave Ritual" ;
    dc:title "The Musgrave Ritual" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes tells Watson about another early case, from the period before they shared lodgings, involving his university acquaintance Reginald Musgrave. Musgrave, a proud and precise young aristocrat, summoned Holmes to his ancestral estate, Hurlstone Manor in western Sussex, after two servants mysteriously disappeared. Richard Brunton, the intelligent and ambitious butler who had served the family for twenty years, was caught by Musgrave at two in the morning secretly studying the Musgrave Ritual — an ancient family catechism of cryptic questions and answers passed down through generations, whose meaning had long been forgotten. Musgrave dismissed Brunton with a week's notice, but within days the butler vanished entirely. Shortly afterward, Rachel Howells — a Welsh housemaid who had been Brunton's devoted lover before he jilted her for another servant, Janet Tregellis — suffered a hysterical fit and also disappeared, leaving tracks leading to a mere on the grounds where her trail ended. 
Holmes recognized the Ritual's questions as encoded directions — references to an oak tree's shadow, elm height measurements, compass points, and paces — and followed them geometrically across the estate grounds. His calculations led to the old cellar beneath the manor, where he and Musgrave found a heavy flagstone that had been recently disturbed. Beneath it lay a recess containing a battered metal box holding only old, rusted metal discs and pebbles, along with a bright piece of tarnished metal — and beside the box, the body of Richard Brunton, who had suffocated after being trapped beneath the lowered stone. Holmes deduced that Brunton had solved the Ritual's puzzle himself, enlisted Rachel Howells to help him lift the flagstone, then descended to claim what he hoped was treasure. Rachel, full of jealous rage at his betrayal, seized her chance and dropped the stone on him, trapping him to die. She then fled — her tracks to the mere suggest she drowned herself or escaped. Holmes realized the ancient relics were the battered and reduced remains of the crown of Charles I, hidden by a Cavalier ancestor of the Musgraves during the English Civil War, making the Musgrave Ritual a secret treasure map preserved for over two centuries. The twisted metal circlet now sits in Musgrave's manor as a relic of both royalist loyalty and domestic tragedy.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/musg.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:navalTreatyDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Naval Treaty" ;
    dc:title "The Naval Treaty" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Percy Phelps, a former schoolmate of Watson's and a rising clerk at the Foreign Office, writes desperately for Holmes's help. Phelps had been entrusted by his uncle, Lord Holdhurst — a future premier — with copying a highly sensitive naval treaty between England and Italy. Working alone late at night in his Whitehall office, Phelps rang for coffee and stepped away briefly; when he returned, the treaty had vanished from his desk. The commissionaire, a former soldier named Tangey, and his wife were the only people nearby. Phelps collapsed into brain fever that lasted nine weeks, nursed by his devoted fiancée Annie Harrison at her brother Joseph Harrison's home, Briarbrae, in Woking. Despite investigations by Inspector Forbes and Scotland Yard, no trace of the treaty has been found, and Phelps faces professional ruin and a potential diplomatic catastrophe. 
Holmes investigates methodically, visiting the Foreign Office, questioning the Tangey household, and examining Briarbrae. During one night at Briarbrae, Phelps is awakened by a sound and discovers someone trying to enter his sickroom through the French window — he rings a bell and the intruder flees, but a break-in has clearly been attempted. Holmes becomes intensely focused and asks Phelps to stay in London overnight while he returns to Woking. The next morning, Holmes dramatically reveals the treaty hidden under a breakfast dish cover. The thief was Joseph Harrison, Annie's brother, who was heavily in debt from stock market speculation. Harrison had visited the Foreign Office that night on other business, saw Phelps leave the treaty unattended, and impulsively stole it intending to sell it to a foreign embassy. When Phelps unexpectedly came to convalesce at Briarbrae, Harrison was unable to retrieve the treaty from where he had hidden it in Phelps's sickroom without risking discovery. His attempted burglary through the window was a desperate effort to recover it. Holmes spent the night lying in wait in the sickroom and caught Harrison when he made a second attempt. The treaty is restored, Phelps's career is saved, and Harrison faces justice — though Holmes notes the irony that Harrison's own greed and the proximity of his victim nearly made the crime undetectable.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/nava.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:nobleBachelorDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Noble Bachelor" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Noble Bachelor" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Lord Robert St. Simon, the second son of the Duke of Balmoral and one of London's most eligible bachelors, consults Holmes after a scandal at his wedding. He has married Hatty Doran, the beautiful daughter of a wealthy California gold-mining magnate named Aloysius Doran. The ceremony at St. George's Church, Hanover Square, went smoothly enough, though a woman in the front pew caused a brief disturbance by throwing a bouquet at the bride, and Hatty appeared to drop her own bouquet, which was retrieved by a man in the pew. At the wedding breakfast afterward, Hatty complained of feeling unwell, retreated to her room, and vanished — slipping out a side passage while the household thought she was resting. Her wedding dress and veil were later found floating in the Serpentine in Hyde Park, leading Lestrade and the press to suspect foul play, but no body is discovered. Lord St. Simon is humiliated and bewildered, particularly by the discovery of a note in Hatty's dress reading "You will see me when all is ready. Come at once. F.H.M." 
Holmes solves the case quickly by tracing Flora Miller — a former dancer and Lord St. Simon's previous mistress, who was the woman who threw the bouquet and who was briefly arrested as a suspect — and by placing an advertisement. He reveals to Lord St. Simon that Hatty Doran had been secretly married years earlier in the American West to a man named Francis Hay Moulton, a struggling miner who was believed killed in an Apache raid. Moulton had in fact survived and tracked Hatty to London, revealing himself to her by retrieving the dropped bouquet and slipping her a note during the ceremony. Hatty, realizing her marriage to Lord St. Simon was bigamous and that her true husband was alive, fled the wedding breakfast to rejoin Moulton. Holmes has invited the couple to Baker Street, and they explain and apologize. Lord St. Simon departs in cold indignation, refusing to share a meal with them, and Holmes dryly observes that the case has a close parallel in the marriage of the Earl of St. Simon and an American heiress decades earlier — suggesting the aristocracy might learn from historical precedent.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/nobl.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:norwoodBuilderDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Norwood Builder" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Norwood Builder" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1903"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """John Hector McFarlane, a young and agitated solicitor from Blackheath, bursts into Baker Street one step ahead of Inspector Lestrade, who intends to arrest him for the murder of Jonas Oldacre, a retired builder from Lower Norwood. McFarlane explains that Oldacre — a complete stranger to him — had appeared at his office the previous evening, claiming to be an old friend of McFarlane's mother, and asked McFarlane to draw up a will leaving him Oldacre's entire estate, including property, securities, and timber yards. That night, McFarlane visited Oldacre's home in Norwood to finalize the documents and left late in the evening. By morning, Oldacre's timber yard had been set ablaze, charred organic remains were found in the ashes along with trouser buttons and Oldacre's safe was emptied. McFarlane's walking stick was found inside the house, and bloodstains matching a thumb print on the wall pointed directly at him. Lestrade arrests McFarlane, and the case seems hopeless — even Holmes admits it is the strongest circumstantial case he has ever seen built against a suspect. 
Holmes investigates and gradually builds a counter-theory. He discovers that Oldacre's housekeeper, Mrs. Lexington, is fiercely loyal to the builder and uncooperative. Holmes learns that McFarlane's mother had rejected Oldacre's romantic advances years ago and married McFarlane's father instead, giving Oldacre a long-nursed grudge. The elaborate will was designed not as a gift but as a noose — creating the perfect motive for McFarlane to be accused of killing Oldacre for his inheritance. Holmes notices that the incriminating thumbprint on the wall was not there during an earlier police search, proving it was planted after McFarlane's arrest. Holmes then sets a small fire in the hallway and raises a cry of alarm, flushing a pale and terrified Jonas Oldacre from a secret hiding place constructed within the walls of his own house. Oldacre had faked his own death, using animal remains and butcher's offal to simulate a body, planted evidence against McFarlane, and hidden in a concealed room with Mrs. Lexington's assistance — all to frame the son of the woman who had spurned him and to disappear with the proceeds of his secretly liquidated estate. Lestrade arrests Oldacre, McFarlane is freed, and Holmes savors the triumph of having beaten a case that even he initially found daunting.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/norw.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:priorySchoolDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Priory School" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Priory School" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Thorneycroft Huxtable, the pompous and exhausted headmaster of the prestigious Priory School in Mackleton, Derbyshire, collapses at Baker Street after rushing to London with alarming news: ten-year-old Lord Saltire, the only son of the Duke of Holdernesse — one of the wealthiest and most powerful noblemen in England — has vanished from the school in the middle of the night, along with Heidegger, the German master who taught the boy. The Duke and his wife are estranged, the Duchess having left over the Duke's association with a former actress, and Huxtable fears the boy may have run away to his mother. Holmes and Watson travel to Mackleton, where Holmes examines the grounds and nearby moor, discovering the tracks of a bicycle and cow-like hoofprints. Tragically, Heidegger is found dead on the moor, his head crushed — murdered and hidden in a hollow. 
Holmes traces the bicycle tracks and the strange hoofprints — which he deduces were made by horses wearing modified shoes designed to resemble cow tracks — to the Fighting Cock Inn, a remote public house run by the landlord Reuben Hayes. Holmes discovers that Hayes drove a bicycle-riding accomplice and the boy in a carriage to Holdernesse Hall, the Duke's own estate. The stunning revelation is that the conspiracy was orchestrated by James Wilder, the Duke's private secretary — who is in fact the Duke's illegitimate son from his relationship with the former actress. Wilder, jealous of the young legitimate heir and desperate to improve his own position, arranged the kidnapping to pressure the Duke, using Hayes as his confederate. Heidegger was killed by Hayes when the German teacher pursued the kidnappers on a bicycle. The Duke, discovering Wilder's involvement, had shamefully concealed his knowledge to protect his illegitimate son. Holmes confronts the Duke directly and forces a full accounting. Lord Saltire is recovered safely, Hayes is arrested for Heidegger's murder, and the Duke agrees to send Wilder abroad permanently. Holmes accepts a cheque for six thousand pounds from the chastened Duke, and later donates a portion to a school fund — though he bluntly tells the Duke that his silence made him an accessory after the fact.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/prio.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:redCircleDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Red Circle" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Red Circle" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1911"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Mrs. Warren, a lodging-house keeper in Great Orme Street near the British Museum, consults Holmes about her mysterious new tenant. The lodger — who took the rooms ten days earlier and paid generously in advance — has since refused to leave the room, communicating only through printed notes slipped under the door and never showing his or her face. Mrs. Warren's husband, who delivers meals on a tray, has noticed that the lodger consumes the food and prints replies but never speaks. Mrs. Warren is unnerved, especially when her husband was attacked on the street by two men, and she suspects the lodger is hiding something dangerous. Holmes is intrigued and observes the lodging house, noticing that each evening a candle signal is flashed in the window — a pattern he recognizes as a coded message using the alphabet. Holmes deciphers the signals as spelling out "Attenta" and "Pericolo" — Italian words meaning "beware" and "danger" — addressed to someone watching from the street. 
Holmes traces the signal's recipient to a room across the street, where Inspector Gregson is independently investigating the murder of Black Gorgiano — an enormous Italian man found stabbed to death. The two cases converge: the lodger is Emilia Lucca, a beautiful young Italian woman hiding from Gorgiano, who was the leader of the Red Circle, a deadly Neapolitan criminal society. Emilia's husband Gennaro Lucca had been forced to join the Red Circle in New York and was compelled to carry out a murder for the organization. The couple fled to London, but Gorgiano pursued them, intending to claim Emilia for himself and punish Gennaro for attempted defection. Gennaro hid Emilia in Mrs. Warren's lodgings and communicated with her via the candle signals, warning her of danger. When Gorgiano tracked them down, Gennaro confronted and killed him in self-defense with a knife. Inspector Gregson arrests Gennaro, but Holmes and Gregson both acknowledge the killing was clearly defensive. The Italian embassy provides evidence of Gorgiano's criminal record, and it is implied that Gennaro will be treated leniently. Holmes reflects that Mrs. Warren's peculiar lodger turned out to be at the center of a drama far more serious than a landlady's curiosity.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/redc.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:redHeadedLeagueDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Red-Headed League" ;
    dc:title "The Red-Headed League" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Jabez Wilson, a stout, elderly London pawnbroker with a shock of fiery red hair, consults Holmes about a bewildering experience. His young assistant, Vincent Spaulding, had drawn his attention to a newspaper advertisement offering a handsome salary to red-headed men for nominal work through the "Red-Headed League," supposedly endowed by a late American eccentric named Ezekiah Hopkins. Wilson applied and was hired on the spot by a man named Duncan Ross, his duties consisting entirely of copying out the Encyclopaedia Britannica in an office on Pope's Court near Fleet Street for four pounds a week. After eight weeks of this easy employment, Wilson arrived one morning to find the office closed and a terse notice announcing the League had been dissolved. Baffled and indignant, he seeks Holmes's help in making sense of the affair.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/redh.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:reigateSquiresDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Reigate Squires" ;
    dc:title "The Reigate Squires" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes is convalescing at the Surrey estate of his friend Colonel Hayter near Reigate after a gruelling case in France — the Netherland-Sumatra Company affair and the schemes of Baron Maupertuis — that left him in a state of nervous exhaustion. Watson has brought Holmes to the countryside to rest, but their peace is immediately disturbed when the neighborhood is roiled by a burglary at the nearby home of the Actons, a local family engaged in a bitter lawsuit with the neighbouring Cunningham estate over disputed land rights. Nothing of obvious value was taken. Days later, William Kirwan, the coachman of old Mr. Cunningham, is found shot dead early in the morning at the gate of the Cunningham property. Cunningham's son Alec claims he saw a burglar fleeing the scene, and a torn fragment of paper was found clutched in the dead man's hand, bearing a few words that suggest the coachman had been lured out by a note arranging a meeting. 
Holmes, despite his fragile health, becomes intensely focused on the case. He deduces from the handwriting on the torn note that it was written by two people alternating words — and that the two writers are father and son. Holmes concludes that the elder Mr. Cunningham and young Alec Cunningham themselves wrote the note to lure their own coachman to the gate and murdered him. The motive connects back to the Acton burglary: the Cunninghams had broken into the Acton home to steal a document vital to the ongoing lawsuit, and William Kirwan had somehow discovered this, making him a dangerous witness. Holmes provokes the Cunninghams into revealing themselves by insisting on searching for the missing portion of the torn note. When he finds it in Alec's dressing gown, Alec violently attacks Holmes and attempts to throttle him before Watson and the police overpower both Cunninghams. Inspector Forrester arrests father and son for murder, and the full note — now reconstructed — confirms Holmes's deduction. Holmes admits the case provided rather more excitement than was prescribed for his recovery.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/reig.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:residentPatientDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Resident Patient" ;
    dc:title "The Resident Patient" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Dr. Percy Trevelyan, a young and talented physician specializing in nervous diseases, consults Holmes about the strange behavior of his resident patient and benefactor. Years earlier, Trevelyan lacked the capital to establish a practice despite having won a prize for a monograph on obscure nervous lesions. A man calling himself Mr. Blessington appeared and offered to fund the entire venture — furnishing consulting rooms on Brook Street, paying all expenses, and installing himself as a live-in patient in exchange for three-quarters of the earnings. The arrangement worked well for several years until Blessington became suddenly agitated after reading about a burglary in the newspaper. His anxiety worsened when a Russian nobleman and his adult son visited Trevelyan's practice twice — the father feigning cataleptic symptoms while the son waited upstairs, near Blessington's rooms. After their second visit, Blessington accused Trevelyan of letting the men into his chambers, claiming someone had rummaged through his belongings. Holmes visits and finds evidence confirming an intrusion but is sent away when Blessington refuses to reveal what he is truly afraid of. 
The next morning, Blessington is found hanged in his room. Inspector Lanner initially considers suicide, but Holmes demonstrates it was murder — the room shows signs of multiple intruders, cigar ash from at least three men, and scrape marks on the furniture where Blessington stood before being forced off. Holmes deduces the truth: Blessington's real name was Sutton, and he was a member of the Worthington bank robbery gang of 1875, who had turned informer against his confederates, leading to the hanging of two of them and long prison sentences for three others. Having served their time, the surviving gang members — Biddle, Hayward, and Moffat — tracked Sutton down. The fake Russian patients were two of them conducting reconnaissance of the house, and all three returned at night, held a mock trial, and executed Blessington by hanging him from his own bed hook. Holmes identifies the men, but they escape London by ship and are lost when their vessel founders in a storm off the coast of Portugal, cheating human justice as in the Openshaw case.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/resi.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:retiredColourmanDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Retired Colourman" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Retired Colourman" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1926"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Josiah Amberley, a retired manufacturer of artistic colours, consults Holmes about the disappearance of his young wife and a neighbour named Dr. Ray Ernest, along with a substantial sum of money and securities from Amberley's strongbox. Amberley, a miserly and disagreeable old man living at Lewisham, married a woman much younger than himself who apparently eloped with the dashing Dr. Ernest, taking Amberley's savings with them. Holmes, busy with other matters, sends Watson to investigate the Lewisham home. Watson notes that Amberley has recently been painting the interior of the house — an odd activity for a man supposedly distraught — and observes a strong smell of paint throughout. Meanwhile, Holmes discovers that a rival detective, Barker — his professional competitor — has also been hired to investigate the same case, apparently by the Elman family connected to Dr. Ernest. 
Holmes suspects Amberley from the start and sets a trap. He sends Amberley on a wild goose chase to a false address in Essex while Holmes and Inspector MacKinnon search the house. Behind the freshly painted walls of a sealed room, they discover the bodies of Mrs. Amberley and Dr. Ernest, who were not eloped lovers but murder victims — gassed to death with a pipe connected to a gas lamp. Amberley had discovered or suspected their relationship, lured them into the room, sealed the exits, and turned on the gas. He then staged the disappearance as an elopement and painted the room to conceal the sealed doors and mask the smell. A neighbour, Josiah Baker, had seen Amberley loading a large trunk onto a pony trap — presumably intending to dispose of the bodies — and the chess club at the Vicarage provided a shaky alibi. Holmes's rival Barker had independently reached similar conclusions. Amberley is arrested and eventually convicted, with Holmes describing him as one of the most cunning and cruel criminals he has encountered — a man who nearly combined murder with the perfect disguise of victimhood. The case ends with Holmes reflecting grimly on the hidden depths of human wickedness lurking behind the most mundane suburban facades.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/reti.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:scandalInBohemiaDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "A Scandal in Bohemia" ;
    dc:title "A Scandal in Bohemia" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1891"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Watson, now married and living away from Baker Street, pays a visit to Holmes and finds him contemplating a letter from an anonymous but clearly noble client. The visitor proves to be Wilhelm Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein, the hereditary King of Bohemia, who is desperate to recover a compromising photograph of himself with the adventuress Irene Adler before his impending marriage to Clotilde Lothman von Saxe-Meningen, a Scandinavian princess. The King has already tried burglary, theft, and hired agents — all have failed. Adler, a retired opera singer of great beauty and intelligence, has kept the photograph as insurance, threatening to send it to the princess's family if the King proceeds with the marriage. Holmes takes the case and begins by disguising himself to reconnoiter Adler's home on Serpentine Avenue in St. John's Wood, learning in the process that she is being courted by a lawyer named Godfrey Norton, whom she hastily marries that very day at the Church of St. Monica. 
That evening, Holmes stages an elaborate ruse: Watson throws a smoke rocket through Adler's window to simulate a fire, and Holmes, disguised as a clergyman, watches as Adler instinctively rushes to protect her most valued possession — revealing the hiding place of the photograph behind a sliding panel. Holmes plans to retrieve it the next morning, but when he and the King arrive at Adler's house, they find she has fled the country overnight with her new husband. She saw through Holmes's disguise, and a letter she left behind explains that she recognized the supposed clergyman, confirmed her suspicion by bidding Holmes goodnight on the street, and then departed with the photograph. She assures the King she will not use it, as she now has a happier life and no desire for revenge, leaving behind only a photograph of herself as a keepsake. Holmes, bested for once, asks the King for Adler's portrait as his sole payment — and Watson notes that from that point forward, Holmes always refers to her simply as 'the woman.'""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/scan.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:secondStainDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Second Stain" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Second Stain" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """The Prime Minister, Lord Bellinger, and the Secretary for European Affairs, the Right Honourable Trelawney Hope, arrive at Baker Street in grave distress. A letter of extreme sensitivity — written by a provocative foreign potentate and capable of triggering a European war if published — has vanished from Hope's locked dispatch box at his Whitehall home. Only Hope and the Prime Minister knew of the letter's existence, and Hope kept it in a bedroom dispatch box to which only he had the key. Holmes identifies three international agents capable of such a theft — Eduardo Lucas of Godolphin Street, Louis La Rothière, and Oberstein — and focuses on Lucas. That very evening, Lucas is found murdered in his home, stabbed by his secret wife — a Parisian woman driven to a frenzy of jealousy who travelled from Paris and killed him, then returned to France without anyone connecting her to the crime. Inspector Lestrade investigates the murder but finds the connection to the missing letter elusive. 
Holmes deduces the crucial link: Lady Hilda Trelawney Hope, the beautiful and devoted wife of the Secretary, has been behaving suspiciously. Holmes confronts her and extracts the truth. Lady Hilda had received a letter of her own years ago — an indiscreet note written before her marriage — which Lucas used to blackmail her. He demanded the foreign potentate's letter from her husband's dispatch box in exchange for returning her compromising correspondence. Lady Hilda, desperate to protect her marriage, stole the document from her husband's box while he slept and gave it to Lucas. After Lucas was murdered, Lady Hilda boldly returned to his house, found the letter hidden beneath a carpet where a bloodstain showed the rug had been recently turned, and recovered it. Holmes persuades Lady Hilda to give him the document and he secretly replaces it in Hope's dispatch box, allowing Hope to discover it and believe he had simply overlooked it. The international crisis is averted, the Hopes' marriage is preserved, and Holmes accepts the personal thanks of a grateful Premier — though he notes with characteristic understatement that the adventure involved certain political implications that prevent him from ever fully revealing the details.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/seco.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:shoscombeOldPlaceDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of Shoscombe Old Place" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of Shoscombe Old Place" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1927"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """John Mason, the head trainer at Shoscombe Old Place in Berkshire, consults Holmes about the increasingly erratic behaviour of his employer Sir Robert Norberton, a once-dashing but now debt-ridden sportsman whose entire fortune rides on his racehorse Donatello winning an upcoming stakes race. Sir Robert has been acting strangely: he has given away his sister Lady Beatrice Falder's beloved spaniel — which the dog's new owner reports howls outside the old church crypt at night — and Lady Beatrice herself, who holds the estate in her own name and whose death would end Sir Robert's use of it, has suddenly changed her habits. She no longer visits the stables or shows interest in the horse she loved, rides in a closed carriage with pulled blinds, and her devoted maid has been replaced by a new attendant. Mason also discovered Sir Robert secretly visiting the ancient crypt and burning something in the furnace, and found a charred human bone among the ashes. 
Holmes and Watson travel to Shoscombe, where Holmes investigates the crypt and discovers a coffin belonging to a long-dead ancestor that has been opened and now contains the recently deceased body of Lady Beatrice Falder. Holmes confronts Sir Robert, who confesses the full scheme: Lady Beatrice died of natural causes a week earlier, but because her death would immediately end the family's tenancy of the estate and allow creditors to seize everything — including Donatello before the crucial race — Sir Robert concealed her death. He had Lady Beatrice's maid replaced so no one close would see the substitution, dressed an accomplice in Lady Beatrice's clothing for the carriage rides, hid her body in the ancestral coffin, and burned evidence. The spaniel was given away because it recognized that the woman in the carriage was not its mistress. Sir Robert gambled everything on the horse winning the race, which would pay off his debts and save him from ruin. Holmes treats the matter sympathetically — no murder was committed, and Sir Robert is described as a man driven to desperation rather than malice. Inspector Norwood ultimately handles the case leniently, particularly after Donatello wins the race and Sir Robert's financial crisis is resolved. Holmes reflects that Sir Robert's nerve held through an extraordinary deception born of desperation rather than criminality.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/shos.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:signOfTheFourDoc a schema:Book ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Sign of the Four" ;
    dc:title "The Sign of the Four" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1890"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """The novel opens at 221B Baker Street, where Holmes, restless between cases, is injecting himself with cocaine — a habit Watson disapproves of. Their ennui is broken by the arrival of Mary Morstan, a young governess whose father, Captain Arthur Morstan, vanished ten years earlier after returning from service in India. Since his disappearance, she has received an anonymous pearl each year, and now a mysterious letter summons her to a meeting. Holmes and Watson accompany her to the home of Thaddeus Sholto, a nervous, art-loving man who reveals that his late father, Major John Sholto, had shared a secret treasure from India with Captain Morstan, and that Morstan died of a heart attack during a quarrel over it. Thaddeus leads them to his twin brother Bartholomew's estate, Pondicherry Lodge, where they find Bartholomew dead in a locked room — killed by a poisoned thorn — and the Agra treasure stolen. 
Holmes's investigation reveals a trail of two accomplices: a wooden-legged man named Jonathan Small and a diminutive Andaman Islander named Tonga, who fired the fatal dart. A dramatic steamboat chase down the Thames ends with Tonga shot dead and Small captured, but the treasure chest is found empty — Small had scattered the jewels overboard rather than let anyone else have them. In custody, Small recounts the treasure's origin: during the Indian Mutiny of 1857, he and three Sikh confederates — Mahomet Singh, Abdullah Khan, and Dost Akbar, collectively "the Four" of the title — murdered a servant carrying the rajah's treasure and hid it at the Agra fort, swearing a pact. Major Sholto and Captain Morstan, as prison officers, learned the secret and stole the treasure for themselves, betraying the four convicts. Small eventually escaped from the Andaman penal colony with Tonga's help to reclaim what he considered rightfully his. Watson, meanwhile, has fallen in love with Mary Morstan over the course of the adventure, and with the treasure lost, he proposes and she accepts — prompting Holmes to reach once more for his cocaine bottle.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/sign.txt" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:silverBlazeDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "Silver Blaze" ;
    dc:title "Silver Blaze" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes and Watson travel to Dartmoor to investigate the disappearance of Silver Blaze, the celebrated racehorse and favorite for the Wessex Cup, along with the murder of his trainer, John Straker. The horse was kept at King's Pyland stables near Tavistock, under the watch of three stable boys. On the night of the crime, a stranger named Fitzroy Simpson — a London bookmaker — was found lurking near the stables and was caught trying to bribe a stable boy with a curried mutton dish. Straker's body was found on the moor with his skull crushed and a small knife wound on his thigh, and Simpson's cravat was found in Straker's hand. Inspector Gregory has arrested Simpson as the obvious suspect, but Holmes is not satisfied, noting several curious details — including a dog that did nothing in the night, and the discovery of Straker's surgical knife, a wax vesta, and a bill for an expensive dress in the dead man's pockets. 
Holmes deduces the stunning truth: there was no murderer, because Straker himself was the villain. Straker, secretly living beyond his means to support a mistress in London under the alias of William Derbyshire, had drugged the stable boy's supper with opium via the curried dish, led Silver Blaze out onto the moor at night, and planned to subtly lame the horse with the surgical knife so it would lose the race — allowing Straker to profit from betting against his own horse. The horse, sensing the danger, kicked Straker in the head, killing him, and the knife nicked Straker's own thigh as he fell. Silver Blaze then wandered across the moor and was taken in by a neighboring trainer, Silas Brown of Mapleton stables, who recognized the horse's value and disguised it by painting over its distinctive white forehead blaze. Holmes quietly compels Brown to return the horse, and Silver Blaze wins the Wessex Cup under Colonel Ross's colors. The curious incident of the dog in the night-time — the dog did not bark because the intruder was Straker, its master — is among the most famous deductions in the Holmes canon.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/silv.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:sixNapoleonsDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Six Napoleons" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Six Napoleons" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Lestrade brings Holmes a puzzling case: someone has been systematically smashing plaster busts of Napoleon across London. The first was shattered in the shop of Morse Hudson, a dealer in pictures and statues on the Kennington Road. Two more were stolen from the home of Dr. Barnicot, a Napoleon admirer in Kennington — one taken from his consulting room and another from his branch surgery in Lower Brixton. Lestrade suspects a monomaniac with a hatred of Napoleon, but Holmes is intrigued by the methodical pattern. The case turns deadly when a fourth bust is stolen from the home of Horace Harker, a journalist in Kensington, and a man is found murdered on Harker's doorstep — his throat cut. The dead man is identified as Pietro Venucci, a Mafia member from Naples. A photograph found on Venucci's body leads to his associate Beppo, an Italian immigrant and skilled sculptor who had worked at Gelder & Co., the Stepney manufacturer of all six busts, before being arrested for a stabbing. 
Holmes traces the remaining two busts: one sold to Mr. Sandeford in Reading, the other purchased by Josiah Brown of Chiswick. When Brown's bust is smashed after another break-in, Holmes buys the final bust from Sandeford and, in a dramatic reveal before Lestrade at Baker Street, smashes it open to produce the famous Borgia Pearl — a black pearl of immense value that had been stolen from the hotel room of the Prince of Colonna six months earlier. Holmes explains the entire chain: Beppo, who had stolen the pearl, was arrested at Gelder & Co. before he could retrieve it and hid it in the wet plaster of one of six Napoleon busts then being manufactured. After serving his prison sentence, Beppo systematically tracked down all six busts through Gelder's sales records, smashing each to find the pearl. Venucci, connected to the pearl's theft through the Mafia and pursuing Beppo independently, was killed by Beppo when he caught up with him at Harker's house. Holmes captures Beppo at Brown's house and recovers the pearl from the final bust. Lestrade, for once, is moved to genuine admiration, and the assembled Scotland Yard men break into spontaneous applause.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/sixn.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:solitaryCyclistDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Solitary Cyclist" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Solitary Cyclist" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1903"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Violet Smith, a beautiful young music teacher, consults Holmes about a mysterious cyclist who follows her every Saturday along a lonely stretch of road between Charlington Hall and Farnham station in Surrey. Violet had been hired by Bob Carruthers, a wiry, sharp-featured man, to give music lessons to his daughter at Charlington Hall for a generous salary of a hundred pounds a year. Carruthers had appeared with his associate Jack Woodley — a coarse, red-moustached bully whom Violet loathes — claiming they had known her late uncle Ralph Smith in South Africa. Woodley made an aggressive attempt to court Violet during a visit, and Carruthers eventually sent him away after a violent altercation between the two men. Despite this, Violet's weekly rides to the station are now shadowed by an unknown bearded cyclist who keeps his distance and vanishes whenever she tries to confront him. Holmes investigates and discovers that Charlington Hall, which has a separate tenant from Carruthers, is occupied by a disreputable retired clergyman named Williamson. 
Holmes briefly sends Watson to observe but the doctor's reconnaissance yields little beyond confirming the cyclist's persistence and the connection between Woodley and Williamson at the Hall. Holmes, occupied with other cases, delays returning to the matter — a decision he comes to regret. When he and Watson finally rush to Farnham, they arrive just in time to find Violet being forcibly married to Jack Woodley by the defrocked Williamson on the roadside near Charlington Heath, with Woodley having dragged her from a trap. Carruthers gallops up on a bicycle and shoots Woodley, wounding him. The full scheme is revealed: Ralph Smith had died in South Africa leaving a large fortune to Violet as his nearest relative. Carruthers and Woodley, both aware of the inheritance, had conspired to place Violet where one of them could marry her and claim the money. Carruthers, however, genuinely fell in love with Violet and tried to protect her from Woodley — he was the mysterious cyclist, secretly guarding her on her rides. Woodley and Williamson, growing impatient, forced the issue with the roadside abduction and sham marriage. Holmes ensures that the forced marriage is declared invalid, Woodley and Williamson are imprisoned, and Carruthers receives a light sentence given his mitigating conduct. Violet eventually marries her fiancé, Cyril Morton, an electrical engineer in Coventry.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/soli.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:speckledBandDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Speckled Band" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Speckled Band" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1892"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Early one morning, a terrified young woman named Helen Stoner arrives at Baker Street to beg Holmes's help. She lives with her stepfather, Dr. Grimesby Roylott, the last scion of the once-wealthy Roylott family, at the decaying Stoke Moran manor house in Surrey. Roylott is a violent, powerful man who spent years in India as a doctor, was imprisoned for beating his native butler to death, and now keeps exotic animals — a cheetah and a baboon — roaming the grounds. Helen's twin sister Julia died two years earlier under mysterious circumstances: shortly after becoming engaged, Julia began hearing a strange low whistle at night, and one evening she staggered from her locked room screaming "the speckled band!" before collapsing and dying within minutes. No cause of death was determined. Now Helen herself has become engaged, and Roylott has forced her to move into Julia's old bedroom on the pretext of repairs. Helen has begun hearing the same whistle at night and fears for her life. After Helen leaves, Roylott himself bursts into Baker Street and threatens Holmes, bending a steel fire poker to demonstrate his strength — which only confirms Holmes's determination to take the case. 
Holmes and Watson travel to Stoke Moran while Roylott is away and examine the bedrooms. Holmes discovers a series of damning anomalies: a ventilator that connects Julia's room not to the outside but to Roylott's adjacent chamber, a bell-pull that is a dummy fastened to a hook beside the ventilator, and a bed that is clamped to the floor so it cannot be moved away from the ventilator opening. In Roylott's room, Holmes finds a small dog leash fashioned into a loop, a saucer of milk, and an iron safe. That night, Holmes and Watson keep vigil in the dark bedroom. In the dead of night, Holmes sees a venomous snake — an Indian swamp adder — descending through the ventilator along the bell-rope. He strikes at it with his cane, driving it back through the ventilator into Roylott's room, where the enraged snake bites its master. They find Roylott dead in his chair with the speckled band — the snake — coiled around his head. Holmes explains that Roylott had been training the snake to crawl through the ventilator and down the dummy bell-pull onto the clamped bed, using the whistle to call it back and the milk to reward it. The motive was money: under the terms of his late wife's will, each stepdaughter's marriage would have significantly reduced Roylott's income. Holmes remarks that he cannot say the outcome weighs heavily on his conscience.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/spec.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:stockBrokersClerkDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Stock-Broker's Clerk" ;
    dc:title "The Stock-Broker's Clerk" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Hall Pycroft, a young and eager stockbroker's clerk, consults Holmes about a situation that seems too good to be true. After months of unemployment following the collapse of his previous firm, Coxon & Woodhouse, Pycroft secured a position at the prestigious Mawson & Williams brokerage. Before he could start, however, he was approached by a man calling himself Arthur Pinner, who offered him a far more lucrative position as business manager for a new hardware venture, the Franco-Midland Hardware Company, at five hundred pounds a year — an enormous salary. Pinner, a gold-toothed, genial man, asked Pycroft to resign from Mawson & Williams immediately and report to the company's Birmingham office. In Birmingham, Pycroft was met by Arthur's supposed brother Harry Pinner, who bore a striking resemblance to Arthur — including the same gold tooth — and set Pycroft to the pointless task of compiling a directory from trade catalogues in an empty office. Pycroft grew suspicious and sought Holmes's help. 
Holmes, Watson, and Pycroft travel to Birmingham, where Holmes explains his deduction: Arthur and Harry Pinner are the same man, and the entire scheme was designed to keep Pycroft away from Mawson & Williams so that someone else — using Pycroft's references and the fact that no one at Mawson's had met him — could impersonate him at the firm and carry out a robbery from within. When they arrive at the Birmingham office, they find "Harry Pinner" has attempted to hang himself after reading a newspaper report that his accomplice — his brother Beddington — has been arrested at Mawson & Williams while trying to steal securities worth nearly a hundred thousand pounds. Holmes and Watson cut the man down and save his life. The scheme is revealed as the work of the Beddington brothers, notorious forgers, one posing as Pinner in Birmingham to occupy Pycroft while the other took Pycroft's place at Mawson's. Holmes notes with satisfaction that the surviving brother will face justice once he recovers.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/stoc.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:studyInScarletDoc a schema:Book ;
    ex:prefLabel "A Study in Scarlet" ;
    dc:title "A Study in Scarlet" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Dr. John Watson, recently invalided home from the Second Afghan War, finds himself in London with limited means. Through a mutual acquaintance he is introduced to Sherlock Holmes, an eccentric consulting detective, and the two agree to share lodgings at 221B Baker Street. When Scotland Yard detectives Gregson and Lestrade find themselves baffled by the murder of Enoch Drebber — discovered in an empty house off the Brixton Road with no wounds yet the word "RACHE" scrawled in blood on the wall — Holmes takes up the case. Through meticulous observation of cab tracks, footprints, and a wedding ring left at the scene, Holmes traces the crime to Jefferson Hope, a cab driver who also poisoned Drebber's secretary Joseph Stangerson at a Halliday's Private Hotel. Hope is captured in a dramatic arrest at Baker Street. 
The second half of the novel shifts to the American West, revealing the backstory. Years earlier in the Utah Territory, John Ferrier and a young girl named Lucy were rescued from starvation by a Mormon wagon train led by Brigham Young. Ferrier prospered in Salt Lake City but refused to let Lucy marry into the Mormon faith, particularly rejecting the suits of Enoch Drebber and Joseph Stangerson. Jefferson Hope, a young silver prospector who loved Lucy, attempted to spirit Lucy and her father away, but Ferrier was murdered and Lucy was forced into marriage with Drebber, dying within a month. Hope spent decades pursuing the two men across the world, finally cornering them in London, where he forced each to choose between two pills — one poisoned, one harmless — as a form of divine justice. Captured and confessing freely, Hope dies of an aortic aneurysm before he can stand trial, and Holmes is left without public credit as the newspapers attribute the solution to Gregson and Lestrade.""" ;
	rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/stud.txt" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:sussexVampireDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Sussex Vampire" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Sussex Vampire" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1924"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes receives a referral from the old legal firm of Morrison, Morrison, and Dodd regarding Robert Ferguson, a tea broker and former rugby player, who fears that his young Peruvian second wife has been caught in the act of vampirism — sucking blood from the neck of their infant son. Ferguson adores his wife but the evidence seems damning: the nursemaid Dolores, who is devoted to Mrs. Ferguson, found the mother bent over the baby with blood on her lips, and the child had a small wound on its neck. This was not the first disturbing incident — Ferguson's older son Jack, a crippled teenager from his first marriage, had been struck violently by his stepmother for no apparent reason, and the household atmosphere is poisoned with suspicion. Ferguson has been sleeping apart from his wife, who has locked herself in her room in apparent shame and refuses to explain her actions. Holmes travels to Ferguson's home, Cheeseman's, an old house near Lamberley in Sussex, to investigate. 
Holmes observes the household dynamics carefully and solves the case through a small but crucial detail: he notices Jack Ferguson's quiver of darts from a South American collection in the house. Holmes deduces that it is Jack — bitter and jealous over the attention his stepmother and half-brother receive from his father — who has been poisoning the baby. Jack had been using a curare-tipped dart, pricking the infant's neck when left alone with him. Mrs. Ferguson discovered what was happening and had been desperately sucking the poison from the baby's wound to save its life — the apparent vampirism was in fact maternal heroism. Her violent blow to Jack was struck when she caught him in the act. She refused to explain because, despite everything, she could not bring herself to denounce her husband's son. Holmes reveals the truth to the shattered Ferguson, advises that Jack needs compassionate professional help — perhaps a year with a sympathetic tutor like the one in the sea voyage Mr. Baker had suggested — and the family crisis is resolved. Holmes dryly notes that the case, despite its sensational appearance, had a purely natural explanation, as he had predicted from the outset.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/suss.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:TheStrandMagazine a schema:Periodical ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Strand Magazine" ;
    ex:description "The Strand Magazine was a monthly British magazine founded by George Newnes, composed of short fiction and general interest articles. It was published in the United Kingdom from January 1891 to March 1950, running to 711 issues, though the first issue was on sale well before Christmas 1890. Its immediate popularity is evidenced by an initial sale of nearly 300,000." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:thorBridgeDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Problem of Thor Bridge" ;
    dc:title "The Problem of Thor Bridge" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1922"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Neil Gibson, the Gold King — a ruthless American mining magnate of immense wealth and domineering temperament — consults Holmes after his children's governess, Grace Dunbar, is arrested for the murder of his wife Maria Gibson, a Brazilian woman found shot dead on Thor Bridge on the Gibson estate near Winchester. The circumstantial evidence against Grace is overwhelming: a note in Maria's handwriting lured her to the bridge, a revolver with one discharged chamber was found in Grace's wardrobe, and the bullet in Maria's body matches the weapon. Gibson, however, insists Grace is innocent and is passionately determined to save her, which Holmes quickly perceives is because Gibson has fallen in love with the governess — a fact Gibson eventually admits with brutal frankness. Maria Gibson was a woman consumed by jealous rage over her husband's emotional attachment to Grace, and the household had been a miserable environment. Holmes takes the case despite his distaste for Gibson's character, moved by Grace Dunbar's own dignified plea of innocence. 
Holmes examines Thor Bridge and notices a chip in the stone on the underside of the parapet, directly above where Maria's body was found. This observation leads him to reconstruct a brilliant suicide designed to frame Grace Dunbar for murder. Maria Gibson, determined that if she could not have her husband's love then her rival would be destroyed, shot herself at the bridge while holding one end of a cord attached to a heavy stone weight — the revolver was tied to the other end. When she fired, the weight dragged the gun off the bridge and into the water below, chipping the stone as it went over, making it appear she had been shot by someone else. Maria had previously stolen a matching revolver from Grace's room and planted it with one spent cartridge to complete the frame. Holmes demonstrates the mechanism by replicating it with a similar revolver and weight, and the original weapon is recovered from the bottom of the stream by a police dredge. Grace Dunbar is released, the case against her collapses, and Holmes delivers a characteristically measured rebuke to Gibson — acknowledging the man's love for Grace but warning him that his overbearing nature must change if any relationship is to follow.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/thor.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:threeGablesDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Three Gables" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Three Gables" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1926"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Holmes is visited first by Steve Dixie, a hulking prizefighter sent to intimidate him into dropping a case, and then by Mary Maberley, an elderly widow living at the Three Gables in Harrow Weald. Mrs. Maberley has received an extraordinary anonymous offer to purchase her entire house and its contents at a generous price — with the condition that she leave everything behind exactly as it is. Holmes suspects the offer is connected to her recently deceased son Douglas Maberley, a brilliant and handsome young attaché who had been stationed in Rome before returning home ill and dying of pneumonia shortly afterward. Holmes discovers that Douglas had been romantically involved with Isadora Klein, a beautiful and notorious Spanish-born adventuress — the widow of a German sugar magnate and currently engaged to the young Duke of Lomond. Douglas had written a novel closely based on their affair, a manuscript that would scandalize society and destroy Isadora's impending marriage if published. 
Holmes traces the conspiracy: Isadora hired a gang led by Barney Stockdale and his wife Susan — along with Steve Dixie as muscle — to break into the Three Gables and steal the manuscript. The burglary has already occurred by the time Holmes investigates, and the manuscript is gone, taken from Douglas's trunk while Mrs. Maberley was chloroformed. Holmes confronts Isadora Klein at her home in Grosvenor Square and, rather than turning the matter over to the police, negotiates a private settlement. He secures from Isadora a large sum of money — enough to pay for Mrs. Maberley to take a round-the-world cruise — as compensation for the stolen manuscript and the rough treatment. Holmes makes clear that if Isadora does not comply, he will ensure the Duke of Lomond and society at large learn the full truth. Isadora, cornered, agrees. Holmes remarks that while the law cannot adequately punish Isadora, the arrangement serves justice after a fashion — and Mrs. Maberley gets the holiday of a lifetime at her tormentor's expense.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/3gab.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:threeGarridebsDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Three Garridebs" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Three Garridebs" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1924"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Nathan Garrideb, an elderly, reclusive collector of curiosities living in a museum-like flat on Little Ryder Street near the Edge, consults Holmes about an extraordinary proposition. A man calling himself John Garrideb, claiming to be from Kansas, has appeared with a remarkable tale: the late Alexander Hamilton Garrideb of Chicago bequeathed his five-million-dollar estate to be divided equally among three men bearing the uncommon surname Garrideb — provided three such men can be found. John Garrideb claims to be one and has located Nathan as the second, and is now desperately searching for a third Garrideb to complete the set and unlock the fortune. Holmes is immediately suspicious of the American's story and investigates, discovering that John Garrideb's knowledge of Kansas does not match reality — he claims connections to a town and individuals that check out poorly when Holmes cables an American contact. 
Holmes deduces the real scheme: "John Garrideb" is actually James Winter, alias Morecroft, alias Killer Evans — a dangerous American criminal and forger. The flat below Nathan Garrideb's rooms formerly belonged to Rodger Prescott, a Chicago counterfeiter whom Evans killed, and Prescott's printing press and counterfeiting equipment are still hidden in the basement. Evans invented the entire Garrideb inheritance story to lure Nathan out of his flat long enough to access Prescott's hidden workshop. Evans sends Nathan a fake telegram summoning him to Birmingham to meet a fictitious third Garrideb named Howard Garrideb, but Holmes and Watson lie in wait. When Evans breaks through the floor into the basement and uncovers the counterfeiting press, Holmes and Watson confront him. Evans fires his revolver and grazes Watson's thigh — provoking from Holmes an uncharacteristic flash of intense emotion as he fears Watson is seriously hurt. Holmes disarms and subdues Evans with a pistol-whipping, and Watson later reflects that the wound was worth it to witness the depth of Holmes's friendship. Evans is arrested, Nathan Garrideb is devastated to learn the fortune was fiction, and Holmes notes sadly that the old man was never the same afterward.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/3gar.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:threeStudentsDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Three Students" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Three Students" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1904"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Hilton Soames, a tutor and lecturer at a prominent university — which Holmes and Watson are visiting for research purposes — urgently consults Holmes about an academic cheating scandal that could disgrace the college. Soames had left the proofs of a forthcoming Greek examination, the Fortescue Scholarship, on his desk while stepping out briefly. Upon returning, he found that someone had entered his sitting room, examined the proofs, and partially copied them — long rolls of paper and evidence of cutting with a penknife were left behind, along with a fresh pyramidal blob of dark clay, a pencil shaving, and a deep gouge in the desktop. The exams were set for the next day, and Soames had three students living in rooms above his on the same staircase: Gilchrist, a tall and athletic young man who was the son of the ruined Sir Jabez Gilchrist; Daulat Ras, a quiet and studious Indian student; and Miles McLaren, a brilliant but wayward student with a poor character. Soames's servant Bannister behaved nervously during Holmes's initial inspection, and Holmes found a key clue — the clay matched material from a particular jump pit on the athletic grounds. 
Holmes solves the case the next morning. The culprit is Gilchrist, the tall athlete, whose height allowed him to see the examination proofs through Soames's window while passing. Gilchrist used Soames's spare key — which had been inadvertently left in the door by Bannister — to enter the room, and his spiked jumping shoes tracked the distinctive clay onto the desktop where he knelt to copy the proofs. Bannister had discovered Gilchrist in the act but remained silent out of loyalty to the memory of Gilchrist's late father, his former master, instead leaving his own gloves on a chair as a silent signal to Gilchrist that he had been seen. When Holmes confronts Gilchrist, the young man confesses — he had already been overcome with shame and, prompted by a letter from Bannister urging him to do the right thing, had decided not to sit the exam. Gilchrist announces he will leave the university and accept a commission in the Rhodesian Police instead. Holmes, satisfied that justice is served through conscience rather than exposure, keeps the matter confidential. Soames's honour and the college's reputation are preserved.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/3stu.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:valleyOfFearDoc a schema:Book ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Valley of Fear" ;
    dc:title "The Valley of Fear" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1915"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """The novel opens with Holmes receiving a coded warning from a secret informant within Professor Moriarty's criminal network, alerting him that danger threatens a man named "Douglas" at "Birlstone." Before Holmes can act, Inspector MacDonald of Scotland Yard arrives with news that John Douglas has been found dead at his Sussex manor house, Birlstone — an ancient moated home with a drawbridge. The victim's face has been obliterated by a sawed-off shotgun blast at close range, and a cryptic card bearing the initials "V.V. 341" is found nearby. Holmes and Watson travel to Birlstone, where they find puzzling clues: a missing dumbbell, a wedding ring on the dead man's finger though Douglas was known to have removed his ring due to a mark beneath it, and a bicycle belonging to no one in the household. Holmes eventually uncovers the truth — the dead man is not Douglas but Ted Baldwin, an American who came to kill Douglas. Douglas, a resourceful and powerful man, turned the tables on his would-be assassin, killed Baldwin in self-defense, then switched clothes and identifying marks with the corpse and hid in a concealed space beneath the drawbridge, assisted by his wife and his friend Cecil Barker, to make it appear he was the victim and thus end the threat against him permanently. 
The second part of the novel, set twenty years earlier in the coal-mining Vermissa Valley of Pennsylvania, reveals why Douglas was hunted. Under the alias Birdy Edwards, Douglas was a Pinkerton detective who infiltrated the Scowrers, a murderous secret society operating as Lodge 341 of the Freemen — a fraternal order corrupted by its ruthless Bodymaster, Boss McGinty. Edwards gained McGinty's trust, participated in the lodge's conspiracies, and ultimately gathered enough evidence to bring the gang to justice, resulting in convictions and hangings. But the Scowrers' reach was long, and survivors swore vengeance. Edwards fled to England under the name John Douglas, married, and lived quietly for years, but the organization eventually tracked him down — Ted Baldwin being the instrument of their revenge. Though Douglas escapes the immediate trap at Birlstone, Holmes receives word at the novel's close that Douglas was lost overboard from a ship shortly afterward, and Holmes darkly suspects that Professor Moriarty's network, connected to the original warning, has ensured that Douglas did not ultimately survive.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/vall.txt" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:veiledLodgerDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Veiled Lodger" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of the Veiled Lodger" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1927"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:storyYear "1896"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Mrs. Merrilow, a landlady in South Brixton, consults Holmes about her mysterious lodger — a woman named Eugenia Ronder who has lived behind a thick veil for seven years, never leaving the house and paying her rent faithfully. Mrs. Merrilow has heard the lodger weeping and muttering the name "Holmes" in the night, and has finally persuaded her to allow Holmes to visit. Holmes recognizes the name: Eugenia Ronder was connected to the famous Abbas Parva tragedy of 1896, in which her husband Donatello Ronder — the proprietor of a travelling wild beast show — was found horribly mauled to death by a North African lion named Donatello near the village of Abbas Parva in Berkshire. The case was officially closed as a tragic accident, though there were unexplained elements that troubled the police. 
Eugenia, her face hideously disfigured beneath the veil from what were assumed to be the lion's claws, now reveals the full truth to Holmes: she and Leonardo, the show's powerful strongman and her secret lover, conspired to murder her husband. Ronder was a brutal man who abused her, and she and Leonardo planned the killing to look like an animal attack. Leonardo crafted a club weighted with nails set in a lion's claw pattern and used it to batter Ronder to death near the lion's cage, then released the lion to obscure the evidence. But the plan went horribly wrong — the freed lion turned on Eugenia and savaged her face before being driven off. Leonardo, a coward at heart, abandoned her and fled rather than helping. He was later found dead, drowned in a swimming pool on the Continent in what was ruled an accident. Eugenia has lived in solitary torment ever since, disfigured and guilt-ridden, and now wishes only to die, showing Holmes a small bottle of prussic acid she intends to use. Holmes speaks to her gently but firmly, urging her to endure and find purpose, telling her that her life is not hers to take. He later sends her a message: "If God had wished you to die, He would not have placed you in the path of the lion." He receives word that the vial of poison was sent to Holmes at Baker Street, suggesting that Eugenia has chosen to live.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/veil.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:wisteriaLodgeDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of Wisteria Lodge" ;
    dc:title "The Adventure of Wisteria Lodge" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1908"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """John Scott Eccles, a conventional and respectable Englishman, consults Holmes in bewilderment. He had accepted an invitation from a new acquaintance, Aloysius Garcia, to spend a night at Wisteria Lodge near Esher in Surrey. The evening was strange — Garcia's mulatto cook prepared an excellent dinner but the household felt odd, and Garcia disappeared in the middle of the night after receiving a cryptic note reading "Our own colours, green and white. Green open, white shut. Main stair, first corridor, seventh right, green baize. Godspeed. D." Eccles awoke to find the house abandoned, the cook and the staff vanished. Before Holmes can investigate fully, Inspector Baynes of the Surrey Constabulary arrives with news that Garcia has been found murdered on Oxshott Common, his head battered in. Eccles becomes an immediate suspect, as he was the last known person with Garcia and has no witness to his movements after Garcia left the house. Holmes recognizes the note as navigation instructions through a large house. 
Holmes and the capable Inspector Baynes — whom Holmes comes to admire as a shrewd investigator — work in parallel to unravel the mystery. The trail leads to a neighbouring estate, the home of the reclusive Mr. Henderson, a domineering man who lives with his secretary Lucas and two savage-looking servants. Holmes discovers that Henderson is in fact Don Juan Murillo, the deposed dictator of a Central American republic — the "Tiger of San Pedro" — who fled with the national treasury after a career of torture and murder. Garcia, a Spaniard whose daughter was among Murillo's victims, had been planning an assassination with the help of the cook and other conspirators, using the note to navigate Henderson's mansion. The cook, who is revealed to have voodoo practices including a grotesque mummified creature found at the lodge, had prepared the household's departure. Garcia was killed by Henderson's guards — his secretary Lucas and the savage servants — before the plot could be carried out. Baynes cleverly arrests the cook as a decoy to make Henderson feel safe, then moves to apprehend Henderson, but Murillo and Lucas escape England. Justice catches up months later: a Madrid newspaper reports that Murillo and his secretary were both murdered by two unknown women — presumably further victims of his past tyranny — on a train platform in Spain. Holmes praises Baynes generously as an investigator who succeeded through patient cunning.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/wist.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .

:yellowFaceDoc a schema:ShortStory ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Yellow Face" ;
    dc:title "The Yellow Face" ;
    dc:creator "Arthur Conan Doyle" ;
    ex:publicationYear "1893"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:plotSummary """Grant Munro, a hop merchant living in Norbury, consults Holmes about the strange behavior of his wife Effie. Their marriage had been happy and trusting — Effie, an American, told him before their wedding that she had been previously married to a lawyer named John Hebron in Atlanta, who died along with their child during a yellow fever epidemic, and that she had received an inheritance of about four thousand five hundred pounds from Hebron's estate. Recently, Effie asked Grant for a hundred pounds without explanation, and shortly afterward he noticed activity in a neighboring cottage that had stood empty. Peering through the window, Grant saw a livid, unnaturally yellow face staring back at him, and when he forced his way into the cottage, he found it hastily vacated. Effie has been making secret visits to the cottage and begged Grant not to enter, promising to explain everything in three days, but Grant's suspicions are tormenting him. 
Holmes theorizes that Effie's first husband may still be alive and living secretly in the cottage, but he is completely wrong — one of the rare cases Holmes himself later cites as a humbling lesson. When Grant forces the issue by going to the cottage with Holmes and Watson, they find a small child wearing a mask — the livid yellow face Grant saw at the window. The child is Effie's daughter Lucy from her first marriage, who did not die in the epidemic. Effie's first husband John Hebron was Black, and their daughter has dark skin. Effie concealed the child's existence, fearing Grant would not accept a mixed-race child, and used the hundred pounds to bring Lucy and her caretaker from America and install them secretly in the cottage, with Lucy wearing the mask to hide her appearance during the transition. Grant, to his great credit, responds with immediate warmth — he lifts the child, kisses her, and takes her by the hand, telling Effie they will work it out together. Holmes asks Watson afterward to remind him of this case whenever he becomes overconfident, saying simply "Norbury.""" ;
    rdfs:seeAlso "https://sherlock-holm.es/stories/plain-text/yell.txt" ;
    schema:isPartOf :TheStrandMagazine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology .


# ============================================================================
# CLASS DEFINITIONS (Sorted Alphabetically)
# ============================================================================

# PERSON CLASSIFICATION MODEL (two orthogonal axes):
# Persons are classified along two independent axes via multi-class membership:
#   Axis 1 — Ontological status (mutually exclusive / disjoint):
#   Axis 2 — Role or profession (independent of ontological status):
# Both axes are subclasses of ex:Person. Roles are NOT subclasses of
# Every person individual MUST have exactly one of ex:FictionalPerson or ex:RealPerson.


