# as full definitions in this file. All other individuals have stubs here
# with full definitions in the pillar files.
#
# Recurring character list:
#   :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :lestrade, :mrsHudson,
#   :maryMorstan, :professorMoriarty, :wiggins, :bakerStreetIrregulars

:bakerStreetIrregulars a ex:Organization ;
    ex:prefLabel "Baker Street Irregulars" ;
    skos:altLabel "street Arabs" ;
    ex:description "The Baker Street Irregulars are Holmes's street Arab detective corps. Half a dozen dirty ragged street boys led by Wiggins. Used by Holmes to search London for Jefferson Hope's cab. Paid a shilling each. In The Sign of the Four, the Irregulars are deployed to search the Thames for the steam launch Aurora. About a dozen boys, led by Wiggins. Holmes pays them a shilling a day each plus a guinea for the finder." ;
    ex:hasLeader :wiggins ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:johnWatson a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Doctor ;
    ex:firstName "John" ;
    ex:lastName "Watson" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Dr. John H. Watson" ;
    skos:altLabel "Dr. Watson" ;
    skos:altLabel "John H. Watson, M.D." ;
    skos:altLabel "Watson" ;
    ex:description "Dr. John H. Watson is the narrator of A Study in Scarlet. Doctor of Medicine from the University of London (1878). Army surgeon attached first to the Fifth Northumberland Fusiliers as Assistant Surgeon, then transferred to the Berkshires. Wounded at the Battle of Maiwand by a Jezail bullet in the shoulder, which shattered the bone and grazed the subclavian artery. Saved by his orderly Murray. Contracted enteric fever at Peshawar base hospital. Returned to England on troopship Orontes, landing at Portsmouth. Income of eleven shillings and sixpence a day. Stayed at a private hotel in the Strand before sharing rooms with Holmes at 221B Baker Street. Owns a bull pup (mentioned but never seen) and an old service revolver. Keeps a journal. In The Sign of the Four, Watson's wound is described as in the leg from a Jezail bullet (cf. shoulder in A Study in Scarlet). Describes himself as a half-pay surgeon with weak leg and weaker banking account. Elder brother deceased (inherited father's watch, was a drunkard with initials H.W.). Author of A Study in Scarlet brochure. Proposes to Mary Morstan after Agra treasure found empty; she accepts. Accompanied Sir Henry Baskerville to Dartmoor as Holmes's agent. Sent regular reports and letters to Holmes. Carried a revolver. Interviewed Laura Lyons. Discovered Holmes hiding on the moor. Watson narrates the Engineer's Thumb case as one of only two cases he personally introduced to Holmes (the other being Colonel Warburton's madness). He had returned to civil practice after his marriage and lived near Paddington Station, gaining patients from railway officials. He treated Victor Hatherley's severed thumb and brought him to Holmes. Narrates the case of the Noble Bachelor. Still sharing rooms with Holmes in Baker Street, a few weeks before his own marriage. The Jezail bullet in one of his limbs throbbed with dull persistence on a rainy day. Had been reading newspapers diligently and briefed Holmes on the St. Simon-Doran wedding details from press accounts. Watson describes his rough-and-tumble work in Afghanistan giving him a natural Bohemianism, but finds Holmes's untidiness beyond his limits. He narrates the framing story at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:occupation "Doctor of Medicine, Army Surgeon" ;
    ex:middleInitial "H" ;
    ex:nationality "British" ;
    ex:rank "Assistant Surgeon" ;
    ex:title "Dr." ;
