:maryMorstan a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Client, ex:Governess ;
    ex:firstName "Mary" ;
    ex:lastName "Morstan" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mary Morstan" ;
    skos:altLabel "Miss Mary Morstan" ;
    skos:altLabel "Miss Morstan" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mrs. Watson" ;
    ex:description "Mary Morstan is the client of Sherlock Holmes in The Sign of the Four. Blonde young lady, small, dainty, well-gloved and dressed in quiet good taste, with large blue spiritual eyes. Approximately 27 years old. Daughter of Captain Arthur Morstan of the 34th Bombay Infantry, who disappeared December 3, 1878. Mother dead. Sent to boarding school in Edinburgh as a child; remained until age 17. Employed as governess by Mrs Cecil Forrester in Lower Camberwell. Received six large lustrous pearls annually since May 1882 from anonymous sender (Thaddeus Sholto). Received anonymous letter directing her to the Lyceum Theatre. Watson proposes to her after the Agra treasure is found empty; she accepts. In The Final Problem, referred to as 'Mrs. Watson'; was away on a visit when Holmes arrived at Watson's consulting room. Holmes sends greetings to her in his farewell letter." ;
    ex:occupation "governess" ;
    ex:gender "female" ;
    ex:childOf :captainArthurMorstan ;
    ex:employedBy :mrsCecilForrester ;
    ex:engagedTo :johnWatson ;
