:professorMoriarty a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "James" ;
    ex:lastName "Moriarty" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Professor James Moriarty" ;
    skos:altLabel "Moriarty" ;
    skos:altLabel "Professor Moriarty" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Napoleon of crime" ;
    skos:altLabel "ex-Professor Moriarty" ;
    ex:description "The great criminal mastermind. Author of The Dynamics of an Asteroid. Controls Porlock as an agent. In The Valley of Fear, Holmes identifies Moriarty as the master hand behind Douglas's murder at sea, having been hired by the American Scowrers to find and eliminate Douglas. Described by Holmes as having a great brain and huge organization. In The Final Problem, Moriarty is described as extremely tall and thin, clean-shaven, pale, ascetic-looking, with forehead doming out in a white curve and deeply sunken eyes. Shoulders rounded from study, face oscillating in a reptilian fashion. Of good birth and excellent education, with a phenomenal mathematical faculty. Wrote a treatise on the Binomial Theorem at age 21. Called 'the Napoleon of crime' by Holmes. Orchestrated three assassination attempts on Holmes. Pursued Holmes to the Continent. Engaged in final struggle at Reichenbach Falls on May 4, 1891; both fell into the abyss." ;
    ex:occupation "Mathematics professor; criminal consultant" ;
    ex:authorOf :dynamicsOfAnAsteroid ;
    ex:authorOf :binomialTheoremTreatise ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:knows :fredPorlock ;
    ex:leaderOf :moriartyCriminalOrganization ;
    ex:pursues :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:pursuedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:siblingOf :colonelJamesMoriarty ;
    ex:escapedFrom :arrestOfMoriartyGang ;
    ex:commissioned :vonHerderAirGun ;
    ex:employs :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:employs :parkerGarroter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
