:sherlockHolmes a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Detective ;
    ex:firstName "Sherlock" ;
    ex:lastName "Holmes" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sherlock Holmes" ;
    skos:altLabel "Holmes" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Holmes" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Sherlock Holmes" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Altamont of Chicago" ;
    skos:altLabel "Altamont" ;
    skos:altLabel "Sigerson" ;
    skos:altLabel "Escott" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes is a fictional consulting detective, the only one in the world. Resident of 221B Baker Street, London, sharing rooms with Dr. Watson. Over six feet tall, excessively lean, with sharp piercing eyes, a thin hawk-like nose, and a prominent square chin. Hands blotted with ink and stained with chemicals. Expert chemist, anatomist, violinist, singlestick player, boxer, and swordsman. Profound knowledge of chemistry, sensational literature, British law, poisons, cigar ashes, and footsteps. Ignorant of literature, philosophy, astronomy, and politics. Discovered a reagent precipitated by haemoglobin at Bart's chemical laboratory. Author of a magazine article titled 'The Book of Life' on deduction and observation. Plays violin including Mendelssohn's Lieder. Uses magnifying glass and tape measure. Captured Jefferson Hope by luring him to 221B and snapping handcuffs on him. Uses seven-per-cent cocaine solution and morphine injection. Master of disguise (impersonated aged seaman during Sign of Four case). Wrote monographs on tobacco ashes (140 forms), footsteps, and influence of trade on hand form. Consulted by French detective Francois Le Villard. Boxed McMurdo at Alison's rooms. Quotes Goethe and Jean Paul Richter. Recommends Winwood Reade's Martyrdom of Man. Investigated the Baskerville case. Secretly camped on Dartmoor in stone hut while pretending to be in London. Used Cartwright as messenger. Killed the hound with Watson. Identified Stapleton as a Baskerville through Hugo's portrait. In the Engineer's Thumb case, Holmes deduced that the criminals had driven Hatherley in circles to disguise the location, correctly identifying the house as near Eyford Station. He recognized the hydraulic press was used for counterfeiting and connected the case to the disappearance of Jeremiah Hayling. Despite his deductions, the criminals escaped. Investigated the disappearance of Lady St. Simon (Hatty Doran) after her wedding breakfast. Had already solved the case from newspaper reports before Lord St. Simon arrived. Deduced the bride had seen an American in the church pew - likely a prior husband. Traced Francis Hay Moulton via a hotel bill fragment from a select hotel on Northumberland Avenue, found him registered there, letters forwarded to 226 Gordon Square. Persuaded the Moultons to make their position clear. Arranged a cold supper at 221B for all parties. Referenced parallel cases in Aberdeen and Munich. Mentioned the King of Scandinavia as a previous client. Also referenced the recently solved Grosvenor Square furniture van case. Before meeting Watson, Holmes had rooms in Montague Street near the British Museum. The Musgrave Ritual was his third case in this early period. He was a college acquaintance of Reginald Musgrave. Holmes kept cigars in the coal-scuttle, tobacco in a Persian slipper, and unanswered correspondence transfixed by a jack-knife on the mantelpiece. He practiced pistol shooting indoors, creating a patriotic V.R. in bullet-pocks on the wall. In The Final Problem, Holmes had been engaged by the French government and assisted the royal family of Scandinavia. He spent years investigating Moriarty's criminal organization. Moriarty visited Holmes at 221B to threaten him. Holmes survived three assassination attempts in one day. He fled to the Continent disguised as an Italian priest. At Reichenbach Falls on May 4, 1891, he wrote a farewell letter to Watson and engaged Moriarty in a final struggle; both fell into the abyss. Before leaving England, Holmes handed all his property to Mycroft." ;
    ex:occupation "Consulting Detective" ;
    ex:nationality "British" ;
