:holmesRegentStreetAttackers a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Regent Street Attackers" ;
    ex:description """Two unnamed men, respectably dressed, armed with sticks, who attacked Sherlock Holmes in Regent Street outside the Cafe Royal. They beat Holmes about the head and body, causing lacerated scalp wounds and considerable bruises. They escaped by passing through the Cafe Royal and out into Glasshouse Street. Their get-away had been well prepared. They are implied to have been hired by Baron Gruner.""" ;
    ex:perpetratorOf :attackOnHolmesRegentStreet ;
    ex:hiredBy :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:horaceHarker a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Journalist ;
    ex:firstName "Horace" ;
    ex:lastName "Harker" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Horace Harker" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Horace Harker" ;
    ex:description "A journalist of the Central Press Syndicate living at 131 Pitt Street, Kensington. Described as exceedingly unkempt and agitated, elderly. Much of his journalistic work is done at night. Purchased a Napoleon bust from Harding Brothers four months before the events. Found a dead man (Pietro Venucci) on his doorstep after the bust was stolen. Wrote a sensational newspaper account of the incident. Previously missed covering the stand collapse at Doncaster despite being the only journalist present." ;
    ex:occupation "journalist" ;
    ex:livesAt :131PittStreet ;
    ex:employedBy :centralPressSyndicate ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:hughPattins a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Hugh" ;
    ex:lastName "Pattins" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hugh Pattins" ;
    skos:altLabel "Pattins" ;
    ex:description "Second of three men who responded to Holmes's harpooner advertisement. Described as a long, dried-up creature with lank hair and sallow cheeks. Dismissed by Holmes and given half a sovereign." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:hugoOberstein a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Spy, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "Hugo" ;
    ex:lastName "Oberstein" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hugo Oberstein" ;
    skos:altLabel "Oberstein" ;
    ex:description "International agent and spy. Resided at 13 Caulfield Gardens, Kensington, with a single valet who was probably a confederate. Known to be in London on Monday, then left for the Continent. The leading international agent per Mycroft's assessment. Used the alias 'Pierrot' in Daily Telegraph agony column advertisements to correspond with Colonel Walter about the theft. Killed Arthur Cadogan West with a short life-preserver he always carried when West confronted them at his house. Devised the plan to place West's body on a train roof from his back window. Kept the three most essential Bruce-Partington papers, intending to sell them to foreign naval centres. Lured back to England by a forged letter from Colonel Walter, captured at the Charing Cross Hotel. Sentenced to fifteen years in a British prison. The invaluable Bruce-Partington plans were found in his trunk." ;
    ex:prisonSentence "15 years" ;
    ex:livesAt :13CaulfieldGardens ;
    ex:knows :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:killed :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:huret a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:lastName "Huret" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Huret" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Boulevard assassin" ;
    ex:description "Known as the Boulevard assassin. Tracked and arrested by Sherlock Holmes in 1894, an exploit which won Holmes an autograph letter of thanks from the French President and the Order of the Legion of Honour." ;
    ex:occupation "assassin" ;
    ex:participantIn :arrestOfHuret ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
