:slaterStonemason a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Witness ;
    ex:lastName "Slater" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Slater" ;
    skos:altLabel "Slater the stonemason" ;
    ex:description "A stonemason from Forest Row. Walking from Forest Row at about one o'clock in the morning on the Monday before the murder, he stopped at the grounds of Woodman's Lee and observed a square of light from the cabin window. He saw the shadow of a man's head on the blind, turned sideways, with a short beard bristling forward — clearly not Peter Carey. He had been two hours in the public-house and it was some distance from the road to the window." ;
    ex:occupation "stonemason" ;
    ex:livesAt :forestRow ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:soamesFriend a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:prefLabel "Soames's Friend" ;
    ex:description "An unnamed friend of Hilton Soames at the university. Soames left the exam proofs on his desk to take tea in this friend's rooms at about four-thirty, being absent for over an hour." ;
    ex:knows :hiltonSoames ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:stanleyHopkins a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:PoliceInspector ;
    ex:firstName "Stanley" ;
    ex:lastName "Hopkins" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Inspector Stanley Hopkins" ;
    skos:altLabel "Stanley Hopkins" ;
    skos:altLabel "Hopkins" ;
    ex:description "Young police inspector, approximately thirty years of age, dressed in quiet tweed suit with erect bearing of one accustomed to official uniform. Professed admiration for Holmes's scientific methods as a pupil to a master. Investigated the Black Peter case at Woodman's Lee but initially arrested the wrong man (John Hopley Neligan). Also investigated the Yoxley Old Place murder of Willoughby Smith (the Golden Pince-Nez case), bringing the case to Holmes at Baker Street. Resided at 46 Lord Street, Brixton. Called Holmes to the Abbey Grange case at 3:30 AM, initially suspecting the Randall gang of burglars. Described as having a youthful figure and alert, eager face. Hopkins has called Holmes in seven times, each justified. Brought the Yoxley Old Place murder case to Holmes. Traveled from Charing Cross to Kent, investigated the scene, drew a rough chart of the study. Arrested Anna at the conclusion. Slept on Holmes's sofa before morning train. Referred Cyril Overton to Holmes, saying the case was more in Holmes's line than the regular police. Calls Holmes to Abbey Grange case. Described as having a youthful figure and alert, eager face. Initially suspects the Randall gang. Discovers silver in the pond based on Holmes's note. Learns the Randalls were arrested in New York, invalidating his theory. Holmes notes Hopkins has called him in seven times, each justified." ;
    ex:occupation "police inspector" ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson ;
    ex:livesAt :46LordStreetBrixton ;
    ex:investigates :blackPeterInvestigation ;
    ex:clientOf :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:arrests :johnNeligan ;
    ex:investigates :goldenPinceNezInvestigation ;
    ex:investigates :abbeyGrangeInvestigation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc  ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc  ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:staples a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Butler ;
    ex:lastName "Staples" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Staples" ;
    ex:description "Staples is the butler to Culverton Smith at 13 Lower Burke Street. He is described as solemn, appearing framed in the pink radiance of a tinted electrical light. He attempts to turn Watson away per Smith's instructions but Watson pushes past him." ;
    ex:occupation "butler" ;
    ex:worksAt :13LowerBurkeStreet ;
    ex:employs :culvertonSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:stauntonWifeFather a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:prefLabel "Father of Godfrey Staunton's Wife" ;
    skos:altLabel "the bearded messenger" ;
    ex:description "Father of Godfrey Staunton's wife and likely the bearded messenger who delivered the note to Godfrey at Bentley's Hotel. Described as a rough-looking man of about fifty with a grizzled beard, pale face, quietly dressed, and visibly agitated with trembling hands. Dr. Armstrong sent him the truth about his daughter's critical condition, and he 'very injudiciously' communicated this to Godfrey, causing Godfrey to rush back to Cambridge. His name is not given in the text." ;
    ex:knows :godfreyStaunton ;
    ex:knows :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:parentOf :godfreyStauntonWife ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc .

