:henryWood a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Henry" ;
    ex:lastName "Wood" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Henry Wood" ;
    skos:altLabel "Corporal Henry Wood" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Crooked Man" ;
    skos:altLabel "Corporal Wood" ;
    ex:description "The crooked man. Formerly Corporal Henry Wood of the 117th foot (Royal Munsters), described as once the smartest man in the regiment, with a face remarkable for its beauty. During the Siege of Bhurtee in the Indian Mutiny, volunteered to reach General Neill's column to bring relief. Was betrayed by Sergeant Barclay, who had drawn up his route then informed the enemy via a native servant. Captured, stunned, bound. Taken away by retreating rebels. Tortured repeatedly, escaped and recaptured. Some rebels took him to Nepal, then past Darjeeling. Hill-folk murdered his captors and he became their slave. Escaped north among the Afghans where he wandered for years. Eventually reached the Punjab, living among natives and earning a living by conjuring tricks learned during captivity. Returned to England after many years, drawn by longing for home. Settled in lodgings on Hudson Street, Aldershot, performing conjuring at canteens after nightfall. Carries Teddy the mongoose in a box for his performances. Now severely deformed: crooked back like a camel, ribs awry, walks with bent knees and a stick, head carried low. Dark, swarthy, fearsome face, worn but once handsome, gray hair and whiskers, crinkled and puckered skin, yellow-shot bilious eyes. Had been in Aldershot only five days when the incident occurred. Encountered Nancy Barclay on Hudson Street and recognized her. Followed the Barclays home, witnessed the quarrel through the window, rushed in. Colonel Barclay died of shock at the sight of him. Wood took the door key accidentally in his haste and dropped his stick while chasing Teddy. Gave his landlady an Indian rupee mistaken for a bad florin. Landlady heard him groaning and weeping in his bedroom." ;
    ex:occupation "Conjurer and performer" ;
    ex:rank "Corporal" ;
    ex:livesAt :hudsonStreetAldershot ;
    ex:knows :nancyBarclay, :jamesBarclay ;
    ex:formerlyEmployedBy :royalMunsters ;
    ex:owns :teddy ;
    ex:hasParticipatedIn :siegeOfBhurtee, :betrayalOfHenryWood, :encounterHudsonStreet, :deathOfColonelBarclay ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:henryWoodLandlady a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:prefLabel "Henry Wood's Landlady" ;
    ex:description "Unnamed woman who rents lodgings to Henry Wood on Hudson Street in Aldershot. Provided information to Holmes who posed as a registration-agent. Was in considerable trepidation about Wood's strange animal (Teddy the mongoose). Reported that Wood spoke in a strange tongue sometimes, and had been heard groaning and weeping in his bedroom the last two nights. Noted Wood was all right for money but had given her what looked like a bad florin, which was actually an Indian rupee." ;
    ex:occupation "Landlady" ;
    ex:locatedIn :hudsonStreetAldershot ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:holmesGrandmother a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Grandmother" ;
    ex:description "Unnamed grandmother of Sherlock and Mycroft Holmes. She was the sister of Vernet, the French artist. Holmes attributes his and Mycroft's extraordinary powers of observation to heredity through her line." ;
    ex:gender "female" ;
    ex:grandmotherOf :sherlockHolmes , :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:sisterOf :vernet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

