:jamesBarclay a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:MilitaryOfficer, ex:Victim ;
    ex:firstName "James" ;
    ex:lastName "Barclay" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Colonel James Barclay" ;
    skos:altLabel "Colonel Barclay" ;
    skos:altLabel "Sergeant Barclay" ;
    skos:altLabel "James Barclay" ;
    ex:description "Commander of the Royal Munsters (old 117th), an Irish regiment in the British Army, stationed at Aldershot. Started as a full private, was raised to commissioned rank for bravery during the Indian Mutiny. Formerly a sergeant in the same company as Corporal Henry Wood. Married Nancy Devoy, daughter of the color-sergeant. Described as a dashing, jovial old soldier in his usual mood, but capable of considerable violence and vindictiveness. Suffered from singular bouts of depression where the smile would be struck from his mouth. Had a superstitious dislike of being left alone, especially after dark. During the Siege of Bhurtee, drew up Henry Wood's escape route then betrayed him via a native servant to the enemy. Lived at Lachine villa about half a mile from north camp. Died of apoplexy upon seeing Henry Wood enter the morning-room during a quarrel with his wife. His face was contorted in an expression of dreadful fear and horror. Found dead in a pool of blood with a jagged cut on the back of his head from hitting the fender. The inquest concluded death was due to apoplexy." ;
    ex:rank "Colonel" ;
    ex:causeOfDeath "Apoplexy" ;
    ex:livesAt :lachine ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :nancyBarclay ;
    ex:knows :nancyBarclay, :henryWood, :majorMurphy ;
    ex:employedBy :royalMunsters ;
    ex:commanderOf :royalMunsters ;
    ex:hasParticipatedIn :siegeOfBhurtee, :betrayalOfHenryWood ;
    ex:diedAt :lachine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:janeStewart a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Servant ;
    ex:firstName "Jane" ;
    ex:lastName "Stewart" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jane Stewart" ;
    ex:description "Housemaid at Lachine, the Barclay residence in Aldershot. Brought tea to the morning-room as requested by Mrs. Barclay. On approaching the door, heard the voices of master and mistress in furious altercation. Knocked without answer, found the door locked. Ran down to tell the cook. On her first approach alone, heard the voices sunk low; remembered hearing the word 'David' uttered twice by Mrs. Barclay." ;
    ex:occupation "Housemaid" ;
    ex:employedBy :jamesBarclay ;
    ex:worksAt :lachine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

