:brighamYoung a ex:RealPerson, ex:HistoricalFigure ;
    ex:firstName "Brigham" ;
    ex:lastName "Young" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Brigham Young" ;
    skos:altLabel "Young" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Prophet" ;
    ex:description "Brigham Young is the leader of the Mormons / Latter Day Saints. Described as a stout, sandy-haired, middle-aged man with light-coloured eyelashes. Led the great Mormon caravan west to Salt Lake Valley. Gave John Ferrier one month to have Lucy married to either young Stangerson or young Drebber." ;
    ex:leaderOf :latterDaySaints ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:brionyLodgeServant a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Servant ;
    ex:prefLabel "Briony Lodge Elderly Servant" ;
    ex:description "An elderly woman servant at Briony Lodge. Watches Holmes, Watson, and the King with a sardonic eye when they arrive the morning after Irene's departure. Informs them that her mistress left that morning with her husband by the 5:15 train from Charing Cross for the Continent. Name not given in text." ;
    ex:employedBy :ireneAdler ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:brotherMorris a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:lastName "Morris" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Brother Morris" ;
    skos:altLabel "Morris" ;
    ex:description "Elderly, clean-shaved man with kindly face and good brow. Reluctant member of Lodge 341 who runs a dry goods store on Market Square, Vermissa. Joined Freemen in Philadelphia, came to Vermissa with wife and three children including son Fred. Good Catholic but excommunicated for being a Scowrer. Warns McMurdo about the Pinkerton detective Birdy Edwards after receiving a letter from a friend in the telegraph service." ;
    ex:occupation "Dry goods store owner" ;
    ex:knows :johnDouglas, :bossMcGinty ;
    ex:memberOf :eminentOrderOfFreemen, :lodge341 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:burnwellValet a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Servant ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sir George Burnwell's Valet" ;
    ex:description "Unnamed valet in Sir George Burnwell's household. Holmes, disguised as a loafer, befriended him and learned that Burnwell had cut his head the night before. Holmes also purchased a pair of Burnwell's cast-off shoes from him for six shillings. His name is not given in the text." ;
    ex:occupation "valet" ;
    ex:employedBy :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:calhounMates a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:prefLabel "Calhoun's Two Mates" ;
    ex:description "Two unnamed mates aboard the barque Lone Star. Along with Captain James Calhoun, they were the only native-born Americans on the ship (the other crew being Finns and Germans). All three were away from the ship the night John Openshaw was murdered. Holmes identified them as accomplices in the murders and intended to have the Savannah police arrest them." ;
    ex:nationality "American" ;
    ex:accompliceOf :captainJamesCalhoun ;
    ex:memberOf :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:captainArthurMorstan a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:MilitaryOfficer, ex:Victim ;
    ex:firstName "Arthur" ;
    ex:lastName "Morstan" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Captain Arthur Morstan" ;
    skos:altLabel "Captain Morstan" ;
    ex:description "Captain Arthur Morstan is the father of Mary Morstan. Senior captain of the 34th Bombay Infantry. Sent Mary to boarding school in Edinburgh. In command of troops at Andaman Islands with Major Sholto. Made deal with Jonathan Small for Agra treasure. Obtained twelve months leave in 1878, telegraphed Mary from London. Disappeared December 3, 1878. Actually died of heart attack during quarrel with Major Sholto over division of treasure at Pondicherry Lodge. Had weak heart concealed from everyone except Sholto. Body concealed by Sholto and Lal Chowdar. Wife (Mary's mother) was dead." ;
    ex:causeOfDeath "heart attack during quarrel with Major Sholto" ;
    ex:gender "male" ;
    ex:rank "Captain" ;
    ex:knows :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:knows :majorJohnSholto ;
    ex:memberOf :34thBombayInfantry ;
    ex:parentOf :maryMorstan ;
    ex:victimOf :deathOfCaptainMorstan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:captainJamesCalhoun a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "James" ;
    ex:lastName "Calhoun" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Captain James Calhoun" ;
    ex:description "The leader of the gang responsible for the murders of the Openshaw family. Captain of the barque Lone Star, registered at Savannah, Georgia. An American, one of only three native-born Americans aboard the ship (himself and two mates). Holmes traced him through Lloyd's registers by tracking the Lone Star's presence at Pondicherry in January-February 1883 and at Dundee in January 1885. Holmes sent five orange pips to him addressed to 'Captain James Calhoun, Barque Lone Star, Savannah, Georgia' inscribed 'S.H. for J.O.' The Lone Star was lost at sea in the Atlantic during equinoctial gales, and Calhoun presumably perished." ;
    ex:causeOfDeath "Presumably lost at sea when the Lone Star sank in the Atlantic during equinoctial gales" ;
    ex:nationality "American" ;
    ex:rank "Captain" ;
    ex:title "Captain" ;
    ex:commands :loneStar ;
    ex:memberOf :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:captainMarvin a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:PoliceOfficer ;
    ex:lastName "Marvin" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Captain Marvin" ;
    skos:altLabel "Teddy Marvin" ;
    ex:description "Captain of the Mine Police (Mine Constabulary). Formerly an officer in Chicago Central police who knew McMurdo there. Arrested McMurdo for the Stanger beating. Was the one person besides Edwards's employers who knew Edwards's true identity. Led the armed men who arrested the Scowrers at the trap at Widow MacNamara's house." ;
    ex:occupation "Captain of the Mine Police; former Chicago Central police officer" ;
    ex:employedBy :minePolice ;
    ex:knows :johnDouglas, :bossMcGinty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:carter a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:lastName "Carter" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Carter" ;
    ex:description "Treasurer of Lodge 341, Vermissa. Middle-aged man with impassive, rather sulky expression and yellow parchment skin. Capable organizer from whose plotting brain nearly every outrage sprang." ;
    ex:occupation "Treasurer of Lodge 341" ;
    ex:memberOf :eminentOrderOfFreemen, :lodge341 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:cartwright a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Cartwright" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Cartwright" ;
    ex:description "Lad of fourteen with a bright keen face, employed at a district messenger office in London managed by Wilson. Holmes had previously noted his ability during an investigation. Sent by Holmes to search twenty-three hotels near Charing Cross for the cut Times. Later brought to Dartmoor by Holmes to serve as his messenger and supplier, disguised as a country boy. Brought food, bread, and clean linen to Holmes in the stone hut on the moor." ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:catherineCusack a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Maid, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "Catherine" ;
    ex:lastName "Cusack" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Catherine Cusack" ;
    ex:description "Catherine Cusack is the maid to the Countess of Morcar. She told James Ryder about the blue carbuncle and was his confederate in planning the theft and framing of John Horner. She testified at the hearing, deposing to having heard Ryder's cry of dismay on discovering the robbery." ;
    ex:occupation "lady's maid" ;
    ex:confederateOf :jamesRyder ;
    ex:employedBy :countessOfMorcar ;
    ex:framesForCrime :johnHorner ;
    ex:worksAt :hotelCosmopolitan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:cecilBarker a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Cecil" ;
    ex:lastName "Barker" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Cecil James Barker" ;
    skos:altLabel "Barker" ;
    skos:altLabel "Cecil Barker" ;
    ex:description "Close friend of John Douglas. Tall, loose-jointed, broad-chested man about forty-five with clean-shaved prize-fighter face, thick strong black eyebrows and masterful black eyes. Of Hales Lodge, Hampstead. First met Douglas as mining partners at Benito Canyon, California. Was Douglas's best man at his second wedding. Helped conceal Douglas after the killing and retrieved the bundle from the moat. Reports Douglas's death to Holmes in the Epilogue." ;
    ex:friendOf :johnDouglas ;
    ex:knows :johnDouglas, :ivyDouglas, :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:livesAt :halesLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:charlesBaskerville a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim ;
    ex:firstName "Charles" ;
    ex:lastName "Baskerville" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sir Charles Baskerville" ;
    skos:altLabel "Sir Charles" ;
    ex:description "Eldest of three Baskerville brothers. Made large sums of money in South African speculation. Returned to England and resided at Baskerville Hall for approximately two years. Widower, childless. Probable Liberal candidate for Mid-Devon. Known for generosity and charitable donations. Died on May 4th in the Yew Alley of Baskerville Hall, officially of cardiac exhaustion. Dr. Mortimer found gigantic hound footprints near the body. Had been deeply affected by the Baskerville legend and feared a supernatural fate. Was meeting someone at the moor-gate on the night of his death, lured by Laura Lyons's letter dictated by Stapleton. Heart was weak. His will left 500 pounds each to the Barrymores, 1000 pounds to Dr. Mortimer, and the residue of approximately 740,000 pounds to Sir Henry." ;
    ex:knows :elizaBarrymore ;
    ex:knows :frankland ;
    ex:knows :jackStapleton ;
    ex:knows :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:knows :johnBarrymore ;
    ex:livesAt :baskervilleHall ;
    ex:memberOf :baskervilleFamily ;
    ex:siblingOf :henryBaskFather ;
    ex:siblingOf :rodgerBaskerville ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:charlesI a ex:RealPerson, ex:Monarch ;
    ex:firstName "Charles" ;
    ex:title "King" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Charles I" ;
    skos:altLabel "Charles the First" ;
    ex:description "Historical King of England who was executed during the English Civil War. Referenced in the story through coins found in the ancient chest bearing his name, and as 'his who is gone' in the Musgrave Ritual. The crown hidden at Hurlstone dates to his era." ;
    ex:occupation "King of England" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:charlesII a ex:RealPerson, ex:Monarch ;
    ex:firstName "Charles" ;
    ex:title "King" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Charles II" ;
    skos:altLabel "Charles the Second" ;
    ex:description "Historical King of England, son of Charles I. Referenced in the Musgrave Ritual as 'he who will come' — his advent was already foreseen by Cavalier supporters. Sir Ralph Musgrave was described as his right-hand man in his wanderings before the Restoration." ;
    ex:occupation "King of England" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:charlesMcCarthy a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "Charles" ;
    ex:lastName "McCarthy" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Charles McCarthy" ;
    skos:altLabel "McCarthy" , "Mr. McCarthy" ;
    ex:description "An ex-Australian who settled in Herefordshire as tenant of John Turner at Hatherley Farm. Had known Turner in the Australian gold-mining colonies of Victoria. A man of violent temper, somewhat cold and forbidding in manners. Kept two servants. Fond of sport and frequented local race meetings. Blackmailed Turner for twenty years after recognizing him as Black Jack of Ballarat. Was the wagon-driver during the Ballarat gold convoy robbery whom Turner spared. Demanded that Turner consent to a marriage between his son James and Turner's daughter Alice. Murdered by Turner at Boscombe Pool on June 3rd by a blow to the head with a jagged stone. His dying words were an attempt to say 'Ballarat' — his son only caught 'a rat'. Had driven to Ross with his groom John Cobb on the morning of his death." ;
    ex:occupation "farmer, former wagon-driver" ;
    ex:blackmails :johnTurner ;
    ex:employs :johnCobb ;
    ex:isVictimOf :boscombeValleyMurder ;
    ex:knows :johnTurner, :johnCobb ;
    ex:livesAt :hatherleyFarm ;
    ex:murderedBy :johnTurner ;
    ex:parentOf :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:tenantOf :johnTurner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

