:horace a ex:RealPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Horace" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Horace" ;
    ex:description "Horace is a real historical Roman poet. Holmes compares Hafiz to Horace, noting there is as much sense and knowledge of the world in the former as the latter." ;
    ex:occupation "poet" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:hosmerAngel a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Hosmer" ;
    ex:lastName "Angel" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hosmer Angel" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Hosmer Angel", "Hosmer" ;
    ex:description "Hosmer Angel is a fictitious identity created by James Windibank to deceive his stepdaughter Mary Sutherland. Described as about five feet seven inches in height, strongly built, sallow complexion, black hair slightly bald in the centre, with bushy black side-whiskers and moustache, tinted glasses, and a slight infirmity of speech -- a hesitating whispering voice he attributed to quinsy and swollen glands in youth. Claimed to be a cashier in an office in Leadenhall Street who slept on the premises. Wore black frock-coat faced with silk, black waistcoat, gold Albert chain, and grey Harris tweed trousers with brown gaiters over elastic-sided boots. Very shy, preferring to walk in evenings. His letters were typewritten with typewritten signature, addressed from Leadenhall Street Post Office. Quoted Balzac once. Met Mary at the gasfitters' ball, became engaged after the first walk, and made her swear on the Testament to be always true. Arranged wedding at St. Saviour's near King's Cross with breakfast at St. Pancras Hotel. Vanished from a four-wheeler on the wedding morning by stepping in one door and out the other." ;
    ex:occupation "cashier (claimed)" ;
    ex:disguiseOf :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:knows :marySutherland, :mrsWindibank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:hudsonKKK a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:lastName "Hudson" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hudson (KKK Associate)" ;
    ex:description "A person named in Colonel Elias Openshaw's diary entry for March 4, 1869: 'Hudson came. Same old platform.' Associated with the Ku Klux Klan activities recorded in the diary. Not to be confused with Mrs. Hudson, the Baker Street landlady." ;
    ex:memberOf :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:hudsonSailor a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Blackmailer, ex:Sailor ;
    ex:lastName "Hudson" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hudson" ;
    skos:altLabel "the sailor" ;
    skos:altLabel "Head-keeper Hudson" ;
    ex:description "A sailor and blackmailer. A little wizened fellow with a cringing manner and shambling walk, thin brown crafty face with perpetual smile showing irregular yellow teeth, crinkled half-closed hands distinctive of sailors. Wore open jacket with tar on sleeve, red-and-black check shirt, dungaree trousers, and heavy worn boots. As a young seaman, he was the sole survivor pulled from the wreckage of the Gloria Scott after its explosion on Nov 6, 1855, rescued by the dissenting group in their boat. He tracked down the former convicts (Trevor/Armitage and Beddoes) and blackmailed them for over 20 years. Arrived at Donnithorpe claiming to be an old shipmate, was given position as gardener then butler. Became increasingly intrusive and drunken. After Victor Trevor threw him out, he went to Beddoes in Hampshire. Holmes believed Beddoes killed Hudson and fled the country, though police believed Hudson killed Beddoes. Neither was ever heard from again." ;
    ex:occupation "Sailor; gardener; butler (at Trevor estate)" ;
    ex:knows :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:knows :beddoes ;
    ex:livesAt :donnithorpe ;
    ex:survivorOf :gloriaScottExplosion ;
    ex:blackmails :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:blackmails :beddoes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:hugoBaskerville a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "Hugo" ;
    ex:lastName "Baskerville" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hugo Baskerville" ;
    skos:altLabel "Hugo" ;
    skos:altLabel "the wicked Hugo" ;
    ex:description "Baskerville ancestor from the time of the Great Rebellion. Described in the 1742 manuscript as wild, profane, and godless, with a wanton and cruel humour. Kidnapped a yeoman's daughter, who escaped from the Hall. Hugo unleashed his hounds to pursue her, and was himself found dead on the moor with a spectral hound at his throat. Portrait dated 1647 hangs at Baskerville Hall, showing him in black velvet and lace. His face bore a striking resemblance to Stapleton. Father of Rodger, John, and Elizabeth. Originated the Baskerville curse." ;
    ex:memberOf :baskervilleFamily ;
    ex:parentOf :elizabethBaskerville ;
    ex:parentOf :johnBaskerville1742 ;
    ex:parentOf :rodgerBaskerville1742 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:hugosVictim a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hugo's Victim (unnamed maiden)" ;
    skos:altLabel "the maiden" ;
    skos:altLabel "the yeoman's daughter" ;
    ex:description "Daughter of a yeoman who held lands near the Baskerville estate. Kidnapped by Hugo Baskerville and held in an upper chamber at the Hall. Escaped by climbing down the ivy on the south wall and fled across the moor. Died of fear and fatigue before Hugo and his hounds caught her. Her name is not given in the text." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:inspectorBarton a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:PoliceInspector ;
    ex:lastName "Barton" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Inspector Barton" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Barton is the police inspector who had charge of the Neville St. Clair disappearance case at the scene. Made a very careful examination of the premises at the Bar of Gold but found nothing conclusive. Failed to arrest Boone instantly, allowing him time to communicate with the Lascar." ;
    ex:occupation "police inspector" ;
    ex:title "Inspector" ;
    ex:investigates :disappearanceOfNevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:inspectorBradstreet a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:PoliceInspector ;
    ex:lastName "Bradstreet" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Inspector Bradstreet" ;
    skos:altLabel "Bradstreet" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Bradstreet is a Bow Street police inspector. A tall, stout official in a peaked cap and frogged jacket. Twenty-seven years in the force. On duty when Holmes and Watson visit to see Hugh Boone. Allows Holmes to wash Boone face, revealing Neville St. Clair. Agrees to hush up the case if St. Clair swears never to beg again. In the Engineer's Thumb case, Inspector Bradstreet of Scotland Yard accompanied Holmes, Watson, and Hatherley to Eyford. He used an ordnance map to draw a ten-mile radius circle around Eyford to locate the criminals' base. He noted the police had been tracking a counterfeiting gang and had traced them as far as Reading. In the Blue Carbuncle case, Bradstreet of B division gave evidence as to the arrest of John Horner, a plumber falsely accused of stealing the Countess of Morcar's gem." ;
    ex:occupation "police inspector" ;
    ex:title "Inspector" ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:worksAt :bowStreetPoliceStation ;
    ex:employedBy :scotlandYard ;
    ex:yearsOfService 27 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:inspectorGregory a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Detective ;
    ex:firstName "Gregory" ;
    ex:lastName "Gregory" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Inspector Gregory" ;
    skos:altLabel "Gregory" ;
    ex:description "Police inspector to whom the Silver Blaze case was committed. Tall, fair man with lion-like hair and beard and curiously penetrating light blue eyes. An extremely competent officer rapidly making his name in the English detective service. Holmes noted he lacked imagination. Sent a telegram to Holmes on Tuesday evening. Promptly found and arrested Fitzroy Simpson. Examined every stable and out-house in Tavistock within a ten-mile radius. Had examined the ground at the crime scene for a hundred yards in each direction. Kept Straker's personal effects in a tin box. Provided Holmes with a photograph of Straker. Had come to the conclusion Straker wounded himself in his fall." ;
    ex:occupation "police inspector" ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes, :colonelRoss ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:ireneAdler a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Adventuress, ex:Singer ;
    ex:firstName "Irene" ;
    ex:lastName "Adler" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Irene Adler" ;
    skos:altLabel "Irene Norton" ;
    skos:altLabel "Irene Norton, née Adler" ;
    skos:altLabel "Madame" ;
    skos:altLabel "Miss Adler" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Woman" ;
    ex:description "Irene Adler is an adventuress and opera singer known to Sherlock Holmes as 'the woman.' Born in New Jersey in 1858. Contralto voice. Performed at La Scala and as prima donna at the Imperial Opera of Warsaw. Retired from operatic stage and living in London at Briony Lodge, Serpentine Avenue, St. John's Wood. Possessed a compromising photograph of herself with the King of Bohemia. Has a soul of steel, the face of the most beautiful of women, and the mind of the most resolute of men. Lives quietly, sings at concerts, drives out at five daily. Trained as actress; adept at male disguise. Marries Godfrey Norton at Church of St. Monica with Holmes as unwitting witness. Outwits Holmes by recognizing him despite his clergyman disguise, following him home in male costume, then fleeing to the Continent with her husband via the 5:15 train from Charing Cross. Keeps the compromising photograph as a safeguard but promises not to use it. Leaves behind a photograph of herself in evening dress and a letter to Holmes. Described by Watson as 'the late Irene Adler, of dubious and questionable memory.' Referenced in His Last Bow: Holmes brought about the separation between Irene Adler and the late King of Bohemia when Von Bork's cousin Heinrich was Imperial Envoy." ;
    ex:occupation "Opera singer, adventuress" ;
    ex:birthYear "1858"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:nationality "American" ;
    ex:voiceType "Contralto" ;
    ex:birthPlace :newJersey ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :godfreyNorton ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes, :wilhelmVonOrmstein, :godfreyNorton ;
    ex:livesAt :brionyLodge ;
    ex:owns :scandalPhotograph ;
    ex:performsAt :laScala, :imperialOperaOfWarsaw ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:isaWhitney a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Isa" ;
    ex:lastName "Whitney" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Isa Whitney" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Isa Whitney" ;
    ex:description "Isa Whitney is the brother of the late Elias Whitney, D.D. Addicted to opium since college, when he drenched his tobacco with laudanum after reading De Quincey descriptions of opium dreams. For many years a slave to the drug, appearing with yellow, pasty face, drooping lids, and pin-point pupils. Found by Watson in the Bar of Gold opium den in Upper Swandam Lane, pale, haggard, and unkempt, confused about the day of the week. Watson sends him home in a cab." ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :kateWhitney ;
    ex:knows :johnWatson ;
    ex:knows :kateWhitney ;
    ex:siblingOf :eliasWhitney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:ivyDouglas a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim ;
    ex:firstName "Ivy" ;
    ex:lastName "Douglas" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. Ivy Douglas" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mrs. Douglas" ;
    ex:description "Second wife of John Douglas. Beautiful woman of about thirty, tall, dark and slender, about twenty years younger than her husband. English lady who met Douglas in London when he was a widower. Reserved and self-possessed. Helped conceal that Douglas was alive after the killing. Sends cable from Cape Town reporting Douglas lost overboard from the Palmyra." ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :johnDouglas ;
    ex:knows :cecilBarker, :johnDouglas ;
    ex:livesAt :birlstoneManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:jabezWilson a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim, ex:Pawnbroker ;
    ex:firstName "Jabez" ;
    ex:lastName "Wilson" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jabez Wilson" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Jabez Wilson" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Wilson" ;
    ex:description "Jabez Wilson is a stout, florid-faced, elderly pawnbroker with blazing fiery red hair who runs a small pawnbroker's business at Saxe-Coburg Square near the City of London. A widower with no family. Former ship's carpenter. Has been to China (evidenced by fish tattoo on right wrist and Chinese coin on watch-chain). Takes snuff. Is a Freemason (wears arc-and-compass breastpin). Was duped by the Red-headed League scheme, hired to copy the Encyclopaedia Britannica at 7 Pope's Court, Fleet Street, for four pounds a week while John Clay tunneled from his cellar to the City and Suburban Bank vault. Employs Vincent Spaulding (John Clay) as assistant at half wages and a fourteen-year-old servant girl." ;
    ex:occupation "pawnbroker; former ship's carpenter" ;
    ex:hairColor "blazing fiery red" ;
    ex:physicalDescription "Stout, florid-faced, elderly, obese, pompous. Right hand larger than left from manual labour. Fish tattoo above right wrist done in China. Wears baggy grey shepherd's check trousers, black frock-coat, drab waistcoat with brassy Albert chain." ;
    ex:clientOf :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:employs :johnClay ;
    ex:employs :wilsonServantGirl ;
    ex:knows :duncanRoss ;
    ex:knows :johnClay ;
    ex:knows :johnWatson ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:livesAt :saxeCoburgSquare ;
    ex:memberOf :freemasons ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:jackKnox a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Jack" ;
    ex:lastName "Knox" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jack Knox" ;
    skos:altLabel "Knox" ;
    ex:description "Man of Ironhill mentioned by McMurdo as someone he would like to see targeted." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:jackPrendergast a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal, ex:Fraudster, ex:Convict ;
    ex:firstName "Jack" ;
    ex:lastName "Prendergast" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jack Prendergast" ;
    skos:altLabel "Prendergast" ;
    skos:altLabel "Predergast" ;
    ex:description "Leader of the Gloria Scott mutiny. A man of good family and great ability but of incurably vicious habits. Had obtained nearly a quarter of a million pounds through an ingenious system of fraud from leading London merchants — none of the money was recovered. Extraordinarily tall, at least six and a half feet, with a clear hairless face, long thin nose, and nut-cracker jaws. Carried his head jauntily, had a swaggering walk. His case had made an immense sensation before his arrest. On the Gloria Scott, he was Armitage's neighbor in the cells and organized the mutiny with his hidden wealth, buying crew loyalty through his partner Wilson (the sham chaplain). After the mutiny succeeded, Prendergast became murderously violent — bellowed like a bull, threw soldiers overboard alive or dead, personally cut the throat of the surgeon. Insisted on killing all remaining prisoners. Died when the first mate triggered an explosion of the powder barrel that destroyed the ship." ;
    ex:occupation "Fraudster" ;
    ex:height "At least six and a half feet" ;
    ex:causeOfDeath "Killed in explosion of the Gloria Scott" ;
    ex:knows :wilsonChaplain ;
    ex:knows :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:knows :evansConvict ;
    ex:knows :mercer ;
    ex:ledBy :gloriaScottMutiny ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:jackSmith a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Jack" ;
    ex:lastName "Smith" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jack Smith" ;
    ex:description "Jack Smith is the young son of Mordecai Smith, about six years old. Curly-headed lad. Holmes gave him two shillings for information." ;
    ex:gender "male" ;
    ex:childOf :mordecaiSmith ;
    ex:childOf :mrsSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
