:johnStraker a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "John" ;
    ex:lastName "Straker" ;
    ex:prefLabel "John Straker" ;
    skos:altLabel "Straker" ;
    skos:altLabel "William Derbyshire" ;
    skos:altLabel "Derbyshire" ;
    ex:description "Trainer at King's Pyland training stables, employed by Colonel Ross. Retired jockey who rode in Colonel Ross's colors before becoming too heavy. Served five years as jockey and seven as trainer. Married man with no children, lived in a small red-brick villa about two hundred yards from the stables with one maid-servant. Led a double life under the alias William Derbyshire, maintaining an expensive mistress. The milliner's bill from Madame Lesurier showed he was spending lavishly. Drugged the stable-boy Ned Hunter's curried mutton with powdered opium, then took Silver Blaze out onto the moor at night intending to nick the horse's tendon with a cataract knife to fix the Wessex Cup race. Had practiced the tendon-nicking technique on sheep in the paddock, causing three to go lame. Killed when Silver Blaze kicked him in the forehead after he struck a light. His own knife gashed his thigh as he fell. Found dead in a bowl-shaped depression a quarter mile from the stables. A zealous and honest servant in appearance, but secretly in debt from his double life." ;
    ex:occupation "horse trainer, former jockey" ;
    ex:hasAlias "William Derbyshire" ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :mrsStraker ;
    ex:employedBy :colonelRoss ;
    ex:worksAt :kingsPyland ;
    ex:livesAt :strakerVilla ;
    ex:knows :mrsStraker, :colonelRoss, :nedHunter, :edithBaxter, :strakerMistress ;
    ex:owns :cataractKnife, :strakerOvercoat, :strakerWatch ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:johnSwain a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Victim ;
    ex:firstName "John" ;
    ex:lastName "Swain" ;
    ex:prefLabel "John Swain" ;
    ex:description "A person of St. Augustine named in Colonel Elias Openshaw's diary. On March 7, 1869, the pips were 'set on' McCauley, Paramore, and John Swain of St. Augustine. By March 10, John Swain had 'cleared' — meaning he either fled or was killed." ;
    ex:livesAt :stAugustine ;
    ex:targetOf :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:johnTheCoachman a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Servant ;
