:mrsStClair a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Client ;
    ex:lastName "St. Clair" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. St. Clair" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mrs. Neville St. Clair" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. St. Clair is the wife of Neville St. Clair. A little blonde woman. Daughter of a local brewer in Lee. Married Neville St. Clair in 1887; has two children. While walking through Swandam Lane on Monday at 4:35 PM, saw her husband in a second-floor window above the opium den. He appeared terribly agitated, waved his hands, then vanished. She ran into the den but was blocked by the Lascar and the Dane. Met constables and an inspector in Fresno Street. Fainted at the sight of blood on the windowsill. Received a letter from her husband posted from Gravesend, containing his signet ring. Hosted Holmes at The Cedars during the investigation. First name not given in text." ;
    ex:gender "female" ;
    ex:clientOf :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:knows :johnWatson ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:livesAt :theCedars ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:mrsStoner a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:lastName "Stoner" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. Stoner" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mrs. Roylott" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Stoner is the mother of Helen and Julia Stoner. She was the young widow of Major-General Stoner of the Bengal Artillery when Dr. Roylott married her in India. She had a considerable income of not less than 1000 pounds a year, which she bequeathed to Dr. Roylott while the daughters resided with him, with a provision that a certain annual sum should be allowed to each daughter in the event of marriage. She was killed in a railway accident near Crewe eight years before the main events of the story (approximately 1875)." ;
    ex:causeOfDeath "Killed in a railway accident near Crewe" ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :majorGeneralStoner ;
    ex:knows :honoriaWestphail ;
    ex:parentOf :helenStoner ;
    ex:parentOf :juliaStoner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:mrsStraker a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:lastName "Straker" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. Straker" ;
    ex:description "Wife of John Straker, the trainer at King's Pyland. Woke at one in the morning to find her husband dressing; he said he was anxious about the horses. Begged him not to go out in the rain but he left in his mackintosh. Woke at seven to find he had not returned. Dressed hastily, called the maid, and set off for the stables. Told Inspector Gregory that the cataract knife had been on the dressing-table and Straker picked it up as he left. Confirmed that Derbyshire was supposedly a friend of her husband's whose letters were occasionally addressed to their house. Holmes tested her about a dress without her knowing it." ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :johnStraker ;
    ex:livesAt :strakerVilla ;
    ex:knows :johnStraker, :edithBaxter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:mrsTurner a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Servant ;
    ex:lastName "Turner" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. Turner" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Turner is identified as the landlady at Baker Street who brings in the tray for Holmes. (Note: This appears to be a different name from the usual landlady Mrs. Hudson, though they serve the same narrative role.)" ;
    ex:occupation "Landlady" ;
    ex:title "Mrs." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:mrsWindibank a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:lastName "Windibank" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. Windibank" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mary Sutherland's Mother" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Windibank is Mary Sutherland's mother. Her first husband was a plumber in Tottenham Court Road who died. She carried on the plumbing business with foreman Mr. Hardy, then married James Windibank, a man nearly fifteen years younger than herself, soon after her first husband's death. They sold the business for 4700 pounds. She was complicit in the Hosmer Angel deception -- with her connivance and assistance, Windibank disguised himself. She was all in Angel's favour from the first and even fonder of him than Mary. When Mary was jilted, mother was angry and forbade Mary from speaking of the matter again. Her first name is not given in the text." ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:knows :mrHardy, :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:livesAt :31LyonPlace ;
    ex:parentOf :marySutherland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

