:nedHunter a ex:FictionalPerson ;
    ex:firstName "Ned" ;
    ex:lastName "Hunter" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Ned Hunter" ;
    skos:altLabel "Hunter" ;
    ex:description "Stable-lad at King's Pyland who was on guard duty the night of the crime. Was seated at a small table inside the stables when Edith Baxter brought his supper of curried mutton. Confronted by Fitzroy Simpson through the stable window. Rushed out with the hound to chase Simpson away but locked the door first. Was drugged with powdered opium added to his curried mutton. Found the next morning huddled on a chair in a state of absolute stupor. On recovering, was positive about the ownership of Simpson's cravat. Was equally certain Simpson had drugged his food." ;
    ex:occupation "stable-lad" ;
    ex:employedBy :colonelRoss ;
    ex:worksAt :kingsPyland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:nevilleStClair a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Beggar, ex:Reporter, ex:Actor ;
    ex:firstName "Neville" ;
    ex:lastName "St. Clair" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Neville St. Clair" ;
    skos:altLabel "Hugh Boone" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. Neville St. Clair" ;
    skos:altLabel "Mr. St. Clair" ;
    ex:description "Neville St. Clair is a gentleman of Lee, Kent, who secretly lives a double life as the professional beggar Hugh Boone. Thirty-seven years old. Came to Lee in May 1884, appeared wealthy. Married in 1887 to the daughter of a local brewer; has two children. Takes the 5:14 from Cannon Street every evening. His whole debts amount to 88 pounds 10s., with 220 pounds credit at the Capital and Counties Bank. His father was a schoolmaster in Chesterfield, where he received an excellent education. Travelled in youth, took to the stage, then became a reporter on an evening paper in London. Volunteered to write articles on begging, discovered through disguise that begging earned far more than reporting. Famous in the green-room for skill at making up. Created the Hugh Boone persona: fake scar, twisted lip via flesh-coloured plaster, red wig, ragged clothes. Begged on Threadneedle Street daily, ostensibly selling wax vestas. Average takings 700 pounds per year. Used the Lascar opium den in Upper Swandam Lane as a changing room. On Monday, his wife saw him at the window while he was changing out of disguise. He threw his coin-weighted coat into the Thames and was arrested as Hugh Boone for his own murder. Holmes solved the case by washing the disguise off his face with a sponge at Bow Street. Bradstreet agreed to hush up the matter if St. Clair swore never to beg again." ;
    ex:occupation "gentleman, former reporter, former actor, professional beggar" ;
    ex:age 37 ;
    ex:participatedIn :disappearanceOfNevilleStClair ;
    ex:isMarriedTo :mrsStClair ;
    ex:knows :barOfGoldLascar ;
    ex:knows :inspectorBradstreet ;
    ex:knows :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:livesAt :theCedars ;
    ex:lodgerAt :barOfGold ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

