:sirGeorgeBurnwell a ex:FictionalPerson, ex:Criminal ;
    ex:firstName "George" ;
    ex:lastName "Burnwell" ;
    ex:title "Sir" ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sir George Burnwell" ;
    ex:description "A titled man older than Arthur Holder, described as a man of the world, one who had been everywhere and seen everything, a brilliant talker and a man of great personal beauty. Holmes describes him as one of the most dangerous men in England: a ruined gambler, an absolutely desperate villain, a man without heart or conscience, with an evil reputation among women. Befriended Arthur Holder at his club and was a frequent visitor to Fairbank. Secretly seduced Mary Holder. On the night of the theft, waited in the stable lane and received the beryl coronet from Mary through the window. Broke off a corner with three beryls. Was caught by Arthur, struggled, received a cut over the eye. Sold the three beryls to a receiver for £600 each. When confronted by Holmes, threatened him with a life-preserver but was subdued by Holmes's pistol. Gave up the receiver's address. Fled with Mary Holder." ;
    ex:occupation "gentleman (ruined gambler)" ;
    ex:knows :arthurHolder ;
    ex:knows :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:knows :maryHolder ;
    ex:romanticPartnerOf :maryHolder ;
    ex:stolenObject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:livesAt :burnwellHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

