:221bBakerStreet a ex:Residence ;
    ex:prefLabel "221B Baker Street" ;
    ex:description "221B Baker Street is the London residence shared by Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson. A suite with two comfortable bedrooms and one large airy sitting-room, cheerfully furnished, illuminated by two broad windows. Continues as Holmes and Watson's residence during The Sign of the Four case. Setting for opening and closing chapters of the Baskerville case. Holmes examined Mortimer's walking stick here and later explained the full case to Watson here in November. Holmes received Watson and Hatherley at 221B, ordering breakfast and hearing Hatherley's account on the sofa. Holmes's rooms and papers preserved by Mycroft Holmes and the immediate care of Mrs. Hudson during Holmes's three-year absence. Chemical corner, acid-stained deal-topped table, row of scrap-books and reference books, diagrams, violin-case, pipe-rack, and Persian slipper containing tobacco all remained in their places." ;
