:watsonExaminesMrsFerguson a ex:FictionalEvent ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Examines Mrs. Ferguson" ;
    ex:description "Watson is taken to Mrs. Ferguson's room by Dolores to examine the confined wife as a physician. He finds her in high fever with both pulse and temperature high, but judges her condition to be mental and nervous excitement rather than actual seizure. Mrs. Ferguson speaks of a fiend and devil, refuses to see her husband, and asks only for her child. She tells Watson that she loves her husband and sacrificed herself rather than break his heart." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :dolores ;
    ex:occurredAt :mrsFergusonsRoom ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:watsonProposesToMary a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Proposes to Mary Morstan" ;
    ex:description "After discovering the Agra treasure chest was empty at Mrs Cecil Forrester's house, Watson confessed his love to Mary Morstan and proposed marriage. Mary accepted. Watson had been restraining his feelings because the treasure would have made her an heiress, creating what he felt was an impassable barrier. Holmes later expressed dismay at the engagement, fearing it would end their partnership." ;
    ex:involves :johnWatson ;
    ex:involves :maryMorstan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:watsonReconnaissance a ex:Reconnaissance ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's reconnaissance at Charlington Heath" ;
    ex:description "Watson traveled to Farnham Station and concealed himself on Charlington Heath to observe the mysterious cyclist. He saw the cyclist follow Violet, watched her confront him, and later saw the cyclist enter Charlington Hall grounds and adjust what appeared to be his necktie. Watson then inquired about the Hall at local and Pall Mall house agents." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:occurredAt :charlingtonHeath ;
    ex:occurredAt :farnhamStation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:watsonsVisitToSmith a ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Visit to Culverton Smith" ;
    ex:description "Watson visits Culverton Smith at 13 Lower Burke Street to persuade him to come attend Holmes. Smith's butler Staples initially tries to turn Watson away, but Watson pushes past him. Smith is initially hostile but becomes alert at the mention of Holmes's name and agrees to visit." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :culvertonSmith ;
    ex:hasParticipant :staples ;
    ex:occurredAt :13LowerBurkeStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:watsonVisitHaven a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Visit to The Haven" ;
    ex:description "Watson visits Josiah Amberley at The Haven in Lewisham on Holmes's behalf. He observes the neglected house and garden, the pot of green paint, Amberley's artificial limb, and the strong-room. He notes the unused theatre ticket number and the smell of paint. On leaving, he is followed by Mr. Barker from the house to Blackheath Station and London Bridge." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:occurredAt :theHavenLewisham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:watsonVisitVernonLodge a ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Visit to Vernon Lodge" ;
    ex:description """Watson poses as Dr. Hill Barton of 369 Half Moon Street and visits Baron Gruner at Vernon Lodge at half-past eight, bringing the Ming dynasty saucer as a lure. Gruner examines the saucer with interest but becomes suspicious, questioning Watson about Chinese pottery. When Watson cannot answer detailed questions about Emperor Shomu and the Northern Wei dynasty, Gruner realizes the deception and accuses Watson of being Holmes's spy.""" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:occurredAt :vernonLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:williamKirwanMurder a ex:Crime, ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of William Kirwan" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Reigate murder" ;
    ex:description "The murder of William Kirwan, coachman to the Cunninghams, at quarter to twelve at night on the Cunningham estate near Reigate. Kirwan had been blackmailing the Cunninghams after secretly following them during their burglary of Acton's house. The Cunninghams lured him to the east gate with a note (written jointly in alternate words) mentioning Annie Morrison. He was shot through the heart with a revolver from over four yards. Alec Cunningham tore the note from the dead man's hand, though a fragment remained between Kirwan's finger and thumb." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :oldCunningham, :alecCunningham ;
    ex:hasVictim :williamKirwan ;
    ex:occurredAt :cunninghamEastGate ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:adlerNortonWedding a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Wedding of Irene Adler and Godfrey Norton" ;
    ex:description "The marriage of Irene Adler to Godfrey Norton at the Church of St. Monica in the Edgware Road. Norton rushes to Gross & Hankey's and then to the church. Irene follows in her landau. There was some informality about the license; the clergyman absolutely refused to marry them without a witness. Holmes, in his groom disguise, is dragged up to the altar and serves as the unwitting witness. The bride gives Holmes a sovereign. After the ceremony, they separate: Norton drives back to the Temple, Irene to Briony Lodge." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :ireneAdler, :godfreyNorton, :sherlockHolmes, :stMonicaClergyman ;
    ex:hasWitness :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :churchOfStMonica ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:ambushMerripitHouse a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Ambush at Merripit House" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's trap to catch Stapleton. Sir Henry dined alone at Merripit House and walked home across the moor. Holmes, Watson, and Lestrade waited in hiding. Dense fog from the Grimpen Mire nearly ruined the plan. The hound burst from the fog, coated in phosphorescent paste, and attacked Sir Henry. Holmes and Watson shot and killed it. Stapleton fled into the Grimpen Mire. Mrs. Stapleton was found tied up inside the house." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackStapleton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :merripitHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:andoverCase a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Andover Case of '77" ;
    ex:description "A case from Andover in 1877 that Holmes references as a parallel case to the Sutherland/Angel deception. Listed in Holmes's index." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1877"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:occurredAt :andover ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:apacheAttackOnMinersCamp a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Apache Attack on Miners' Camp" ;
    ex:description "A miners' camp was attacked by Apache Indians. A newspaper reported Francis Hay Moulton's name among the killed, but he had actually been taken prisoner. He was held captive by the Apaches for an extended period before escaping." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :apacheIndians ;
    ex:locatedIn :newMexico ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:armitageConviction a ex:Embezzlement ;
    ex:prefLabel "Armitage's Conviction for Embezzlement" ;
    ex:description "James Armitage, working at a London banking house, used money that was not his own to pay a 'debt of honor.' The money he had reckoned upon to replace it never came to hand, and a premature examination of accounts exposed his deficit. Laws being more harshly administered thirty years before the story's events, on his twenty-third birthday he was convicted and sentenced to transportation. He was chained with thirty-seven other convicts aboard the bark Gloria Scott." ;
    ex:occurredAt :londonBankingHouse ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:arnsworthCastleBusiness a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arnsworth Castle Business" ;
    ex:description "A previous case referenced by Holmes in which the fire alarm trick was also of use. No other details given." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:arrestOfBeddington a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Beddington" ;
    ex:description "The arrest of Beddington outside Mawson & Williams. Sergeant Tuson of the City Police observed a gentleman with a carpet bag descending the steps at twenty minutes past one on Saturday and, his suspicions aroused, followed him. With the aid of Constable Pollack, after a most desperate resistance, they arrested him. The carpet bag was found to contain nearly a hundred thousand pounds in stolen securities." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sergeantTuson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :constablePollack ;
    ex:hasParticipant :beddingtonBrother2 ;
    ex:occurredAt :mawsonAndWilliamsBuilding ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:arrestOfFitzroySimpson a ex:Arrest ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Fitzroy Simpson" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Gregory promptly found and arrested Fitzroy Simpson, who inhabited one of the villas near King's Pyland. Simpson was arrested on circumstantial evidence: his large bets against Silver Blaze, the drugging of the stable-boy, his presence in the storm, his heavy stick, and his cravat in the dead man's hand. He was ultimately exonerated by Holmes's investigation." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :inspectorGregory, :fitzroySimpson ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:arrestOfJohnClay a ex:Arrest ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of John Clay" ;
    ex:description "John Clay is captured by Holmes (who seizes him by the collar) and handcuffed by Peter Jones in the vault of the City and Suburban Bank after emerging from the tunnel. Clay demands to be addressed as 'sir' and claims royal blood. His accomplice dives back down the tunnel but three men wait at the front door." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "October 1890" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClay ;
    ex:hasParticipant :peterJones ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:arthurHolderArrest a ex:Arrest ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Arthur Holder" ;
    ex:description "Arthur Holder was arrested at Fairbank by the police inspector and constable after his father Alexander found him holding the damaged beryl coronet. Arthur refused to explain, choosing to protect his cousin Mary's secret. He was taken to a cell. Later vindicated when Holmes uncovered the truth." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :berylCoronetInspector ;
    ex:hasParticipant :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:occurredAt :fairbank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:atkinsonBrothersTragedy a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Atkinson Brothers Tragedy" ;
    ex:description "A singular tragedy involving the Atkinson brothers at Trincomalee, which Holmes cleared up. Referenced only; no details given." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :trincomalee ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:atlantaFire a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Great Fire in Atlanta" ;
    ex:description "A great fire in Atlanta that occurred shortly after John Hebron's death, destroying all of Effie's papers. This necessitated obtaining a duplicate death certificate for Hebron." ;
    ex:occurredAt :atlanta ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:attemptedBankRobbery a ex:AttemptedTheft ;
    ex:prefLabel "Attempted Bank Robbery" ;
    ex:description "John Clay and his accomplice Duncan Ross attempted to rob the City and Suburban Bank's Coburg branch of 30,000 napoleons of French gold by tunneling from Jabez Wilson's cellar into the bank vault. The scheme involved creating the Red-headed League to keep Wilson away. Foiled by Holmes's ambush." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "October 1890" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :duncanRoss ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClay ;
    ex:occurredAt :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:targets :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:ballaratGoldConvoyRobbery a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Ballarat Gold Convoy Robbery" ;
    ex:description "A robbery of a gold convoy traveling from Ballarat to Melbourne in the early 1860s. The Ballarat Gang (six robbers including John Turner as Black Jack) ambushed six troopers escorting the convoy. Four troopers were shot from their saddles in the first volley, and three gang members were killed. Turner held his pistol to the head of the wagon-driver, Charles McCarthy, but spared his life. The gang escaped with the gold and became wealthy. McCarthy's recognition of Turner led to twenty years of blackmail." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnTurner, :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:occurredAt :victoria ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:bankVaultAmbush a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Bank Vault Ambush" ;
    ex:description "Holmes, Watson, Peter Jones, and Mr. Merryweather wait in the darkened vault of the City and Suburban Bank for John Clay and his accomplice to emerge from their tunnel on a Saturday night. After about an hour and a quarter, Clay emerges with his accomplice. Holmes seizes Clay, Jones handcuffs him, the accomplice escapes back down the tunnel." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "Saturday night, October 1890" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :duncanRoss ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClay ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrMerryweather ;
    ex:hasParticipant :peterJones ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:baskervilleInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Baskerville case" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into the death of Sir Charles Baskerville and threats against Sir Henry Baskerville. Commissioned by Dr. Mortimer. Watson served as Holmes's agent on Dartmoor while Holmes secretly operated from Coombe Tracey and a stone hut on the moor. Lestrade brought a warrant from Scotland Yard. The investigation uncovered Stapleton as a Baskerville descendant who used a trained hound coated in phosphorescent paste to frighten Sir Charles to death and attempt to murder Sir Henry. Case resolved with the shooting of the hound and Stapleton's presumed death in the Grimpen Mire." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :baskervilleHall ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:battleOfMaiwand a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Battle of Maiwand" ;
    ex:description "The Battle of Maiwand is the fatal battle during the Second Afghan War where Watson was wounded by a Jezail bullet in the shoulder. Watson's regiment, the Berkshires, was nearly destroyed." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1880" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :murray ;
    ex:occurredAt :afghanistan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:beatingOfStanger a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Beating of James Stanger" ;
    ex:description "Attack on the editor of the Vermissa Herald by Baldwin and others on McGinty's orders. Stanger was beaten with sticks, suffering severe head injuries but surviving." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tedBaldwin, :johnDouglas, :gower, :mansel, :mikeScanlan, :willabyBrothers ;
    ex:hasVictim :jamesStanger ;
    ex:occurredAt :vermissaHeraldOffice ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:becherHouseFire a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Fire at Dr. Becher's House" ;
    ex:description "A fire that destroyed Dr. Becher's house near Eyford. Caused by Hatherley's oil lamp being crushed in the hydraulic press, which set fire to the wooden walls. The fire broke out during the night and worsened, with the whole place in a blaze by the time Holmes, Watson, Bradstreet, and Hatherley arrived. Three fire-engines worked to control the flames. The roof fell in and the entire building was reduced to ruin, destroying the counterfeiting machinery." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:occurredAt :becherHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:berylCoronetInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Beryl Coronet Theft" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's investigation into the theft of three beryls from the beryl coronet. Holmes examined Fairbank (including the hall window sill, the dressing-room bureau, and footprints in the snow), disguised himself to visit Sir George Burnwell's household, purchased Burnwell's cast-off shoes to match tracks, confronted Burnwell, and recovered the gems from a fence. The case was solved within approximately 24 hours." ;
    ex:hasInvestigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :maryHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:occurredAt :fairbank ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :burnwellHouse ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:rewardOffered "£1,000" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:berylCoronetLoan a ex:Loan ;
    ex:prefLabel "Beryl Coronet Loan" ;
    ex:description "A loan of £50,000 made by the banking firm of Holder & Stevenson to an unnamed illustrious client, with the beryl coronet left as security. The client expected to repay the following Monday. This transaction is the inciting event of the case." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :berylCoronetClient ;
    ex:hasParticipant :holderAndStevenson ;
    ex:loanAmountValue "£50,000" ;
    ex:involvedObject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:berylCoronetRecovery a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Recovery of the Beryl Coronet Gems" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's recovery of the three missing beryls. After confronting Sir George Burnwell (who threatened with a life-preserver, subdued by Holmes's pistol), Holmes obtained the address of the receiver who had purchased the gems for £600 each. Holmes bought them back for £1,000 apiece (£3,000 total). Alexander Holder paid £4,000 by cheque (£3,000 for gems plus reward)." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:hasParticipant :berylCoronetReceiver ;
    ex:involvedObject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:berylCoronetTheft a ex:Theft ;
    ex:prefLabel "Theft of the Beryl Coronet" ;
    ex:description "The central crime of the case. Mary Holder, acting under the influence of Sir George Burnwell, took the beryl coronet from her uncle's bureau and passed it through the hall window at Fairbank to Burnwell waiting in the stable lane. Burnwell broke off a corner containing three beryls before being intercepted by Arthur Holder. The theft occurred around 2 AM." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :maryHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurHolder ;
    ex:occurredAt :fairbank ;
    ex:involvedObject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:birlstoneInvestigation a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Birlstone Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Investigation into the apparent murder of John Douglas at Birlstone Manor House. Led by Inspector MacDonald and White Mason with Holmes's assistance. Holmes deduced Douglas was alive and set a trap." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes, :alecMacDonald, :whiteMason ;
    ex:occurredAt :birlstoneManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:blastingOfWilcoxHouse a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Blasting of Wilcox House" ;
    ex:description "McMurdo, Manders, and Reilly blew up Chester Wilcox's isolated house at Iron Dike crossroad with blasting powder. Wilcox and his family had moved the day before." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :manders ;
    ex:occurredAt :ironDike ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:bloodReagentDiscovery a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Blood Reagent Discovery" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes discovers a reagent that is precipitated by haemoglobin and nothing else, a revolutionary chemical test for blood stains. He demonstrates it to Watson and Stamford at the chemical laboratory of St. Bartholomew's Hospital." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :stamford ;
    ex:occurredAt :stBartholomewsHospital ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:blueCarbuncleInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Blue Carbuncle Investigation" ;
    ex:description "The Blue Carbuncle Investigation is Sherlock Holmes's investigation into the theft of the Countess of Morcar's blue carbuncle. It began when Peterson the commissionaire brought a hat and goose to Holmes, and his wife found the gem in the goose's crop. Holmes traced the goose through Henry Baker, the Alpha Inn's Windigate, Breckinridge at Covent Garden Market, and Mrs. Oakshott at 117 Brixton Road, ultimately confronting James Ryder as the true thief. Holmes resolved the case by letting Ryder go free, reasoning it was the season of forgiveness." ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :peterson, :henryBaker, :jamesRyder, :breckinridge, :windigate ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet, :alphaInn, :coventGardenMarket ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:blueCarbuncleTheft a ex:Theft ;
    ex:prefLabel "Theft of the Blue Carbuncle" ;
    skos:altLabel "Hotel Cosmopolitan Jewel Robbery" ;
    ex:description "The theft of the blue carbuncle occurred on December 22nd at the Hotel Cosmopolitan. James Ryder, the upper-attendant, conspired with Catherine Cusack, maid to the Countess of Morcar, to steal the precious gem from the Countess's jewel-case. They arranged for John Horner, a plumber with a previous conviction, to be sent to the Countess's room to solder a loose bar, then framed him for the theft. Ryder rifled the jewel-case after Horner left and raised the alarm." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "December 22" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesRyder, :catherineCusack, :johnHorner, :countessOfMorcar ;
    ex:occurredAt :hotelCosmopolitan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:boscombePoolQuarrel a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Boscombe Pool Quarrel" ;
    ex:description "The violent quarrel between Charles and James McCarthy at Boscombe Pool, witnessed by Patience Moran from the nearby woods. Charles used very strong language and James raised his hand as if to strike his father. The quarrel concerned Charles's insistence that James marry Alice Turner, which James could not do due to his secret marriage. Charles called 'Cooee!' to signal John Turner, not knowing James had returned from Bristol." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :charlesMcCarthy, :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:occurredAt :boscombePool ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:boscombeValleyInquest a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Boscombe Valley Inquest" ;
    ex:description "The coroner's inquest into the death of Charles McCarthy, held on the Tuesday after the murder. James McCarthy gave testimony about the events. William Crowder and Patience Moran provided witness testimony. The surgeon gave a deposition about the injuries. A verdict of 'wilful murder' was returned by the jury." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMcCarthy, :williamCrowder, :patienceMoran, :boscombeValleyCoroner, :boscombeValleySurgeon ;
    ex:occurredAt :ross ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:boscombeValleyInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Boscombe Valley Investigation" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Boscombe Valley case" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's investigation into the murder of Charles McCarthy at Boscombe Pool. Holmes was summoned by telegram and traveled with Watson to Ross, Herefordshire. Lestrade had been retained by Miss Turner's allies but referred the case to Holmes. Holmes examined the crime scene, deduced the true killer's characteristics from footprints and cigar ash, identified John Turner as the murderer, obtained Turner's confession, and arranged for James McCarthy's acquittal at the Assizes." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:hasClient :aliceTurner ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :lestrade ;
    ex:investigates :boscombeValleyMurder ;
    ex:occurredAt :boscombeValley, :ross ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:boscombeValleyMagistrateHearing a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Boscombe Valley Magistrate Hearing" ;
    ex:description "Hearing before the magistrates at Ross on Wednesday (two days after the murder), at which James McCarthy was brought from custody. The magistrates referred the case to the next Assizes." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:occurredAt :ross ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:boscombeValleyMurder a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Boscombe Valley Murder" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Boscombe Valley tragedy" ;
    ex:description "The murder of Charles McCarthy by John Turner at Boscombe Pool on June 3rd (a Monday). McCarthy was struck from behind on the left side of the head with a jagged stone while his back was turned. Turner had been hiding behind a beech tree, smoking a cigar, and struck McCarthy after overhearing him urging his son James to marry Alice Turner. James McCarthy found his father expiring and was subsequently arrested and charged with the murder." ;
    ex:hasDate "June 3rd" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :charlesMcCarthy, :johnTurner ;
    ex:hasVictim :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:occurredAt :boscombePool ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:brionyLodgeFireRuse a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Briony Lodge Fire Ruse" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's scheme to locate the hidden photograph at Briony Lodge. Holmes arranged a crowd of accomplices (shabbily dressed men, a scissors-grinder, guardsmen, loungers) outside Briony Lodge. When Irene's carriage arrived, a staged altercation broke out. Holmes dashed in to protect her, feigned injury with red paint, and was carried inside. He signaled Watson, who threw a smoke-rocket and raised the cry of fire. Irene instinctively rushed to the hiding place (recess behind sliding panel above right bell-pull), revealing the photograph's location. Holmes then claimed it was a false alarm." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :ireneAdler ;
    ex:occurredAt :brionyLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:brixtonRoadInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Brixton Road Investigation" ;
    ex:description "The investigation into the murders of Enoch Drebber and Joseph Stangerson. Holmes is the consulting detective, aided by Watson. Gregson and Lestrade conduct separate parallel investigations for Scotland Yard. Holmes solves the case by identifying Jefferson Hope as the cabman-murderer." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tobiasGregson ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:bruntonCaughtReading a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Brunton Caught Reading the Ritual" ;
    ex:description "On a Thursday night, Reginald Musgrave could not sleep and went to the billiard room. He saw a light in the library and found Richard Brunton sitting fully dressed, studying the Musgrave Ritual document and a chart-like map. Musgrave confronted him and dismissed him with one week's notice. Brunton begged for a fortnight but was refused." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :richardBrunton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneLibrary ;
    ex:hasOutcome "Brunton dismissed with one week's notice" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:bruntonDeath a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Richard Brunton" ;
    ex:description "Richard Brunton was found dead in the hidden cellar chamber at Hurlstone, squatting beside the ancient chest with his forehead sunk upon its edge and arms thrown out on each side. His face was distorted and liver-colored from blood pooling. There was no wound or bruise on his person. Holmes deduced that Brunton had descended into the chamber to retrieve the treasure, and the flagstone was allowed to fall back — trapping and suffocating him — either accidentally or deliberately by Rachel Howells." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :richardBrunton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :rachelHowells ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneCellar ;
    ex:hasOutcome "Death by suffocation/entrapment" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:bruntonDisappearance a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance of Richard Brunton" ;
    ex:description "On the third morning after being caught in the library, Richard Brunton failed to appear for his duties. His bed had not been slept in, he had been seen by no one since retiring the night before, and doors and windows were fastened. His clothes, watch, and money were in his room, but his black suit and slippers were missing. Boots were left behind." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :richardBrunton ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstone ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:burningOfKKKPapers a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Burning of KKK Papers" ;
    ex:description "In March 1883, after receiving the threatening letter with five orange pips, Colonel Elias Openshaw took his brass box from the locked attic and burned the papers it contained. John Openshaw observed a mass of black fluffy ashes in the grate and the brass box standing open and empty beside it. Only a single diary page survived, having apparently fluttered out during the burning." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1883"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:hasParticipant :eliasOpenshaw ;
    ex:occurredAt :openshawEstate ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:cabSurveillance a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Cab surveillance in London" ;
    ex:description "A bearded man in hansom cab number 2704 followed Sir Henry and Dr. Mortimer through London. Holmes and Watson spotted the tail on Regent Street. The spy escaped when Holmes attempted to intercept. Cabman John Clayton reported the fare hired at Trafalgar Square, paid two guineas for a day's work, and gave his name as Sherlock Holmes upon leaving. The spy was actually Stapleton in disguise (the black beard matched Barrymore's)." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackStapleton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClayton ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:camberwellPoisoningCase a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Camberwell Poisoning Case" ;
    ex:description "A case from 1887 mentioned by Watson. Holmes was able, by winding up the dead man's watch, to prove that it had been wound up two hours before, and therefore the deceased had gone to bed within that time. This deduction was of the greatest importance in clearing up the case." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :camberwell ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:captureOfJeffersonHope a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Capture of Jefferson Hope" ;
    ex:description "Holmes lured Jefferson Hope to 221B Baker Street by having Wiggins summon his cab. Holmes snapped handcuffs on him. Hope resisted violently, threw himself through a window, and was subdued by Holmes, Watson, Gregson, and Lestrade." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tobiasGregson ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:captureOfJonathanSmall a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Capture of Jonathan Small" ;
    ex:description "Aurora ran aground on mud bank at Barking Level. Small's wooden leg stuck in mud. Hauled out by rope onto police launch. Small confessed his story at Baker Street." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :athelneyJones ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :thames ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:collapseOfCoxonAndWoodhouse a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Collapse of Coxon & Woodhouse" ;
    ex:description "The financial collapse of Coxon & Woodhouse of Draper's Gardens. They were let in early in the spring through the Venezuelan loan and came a nasty cropper. All twenty-seven clerks were turned adrift. Old Coxon gave Hall Pycroft a good testimonial." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :coxonAndWoodhouse ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hallPycroft ;
    ex:hasParticipant :oldCoxon ;
    ex:occurredAt :drapersGardens ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:cottageDiscovery a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Discovery at the Cottage" ;
    ex:description "The climactic event of the Yellow Face case. Holmes, Watson, and Grant Munro force their way into the cottage at Norbury over Effie's protests. They discover a little girl wearing a livid mask, which Holmes removes to reveal Lucy Hebron. Effie then confesses the full truth about her first marriage and child. Munro responds with nobility, lifting and kissing the child." ;
    ex:occurredAt :cottageAtNorbury ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :grantMunro, :effieMunro, :lucyHebron, :scottishNurse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:crowHillMurders a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Crow Hill Mine Murders" ;
    ex:description "Double murder at Crow Hill mine. Andrews shot manager Dunn and Menzies the engineer was killed when he rushed at the assassins." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lawler, :andrews ;
    ex:hasVictim :josiahDunn, :menzies ;
    ex:occurredAt :crowHillMine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:darlingtonSubstitutionScandal a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Darlington Substitution Scandal" ;
    ex:description "A previous case referenced by Holmes in which the fire alarm trick was of use to him. No other details given." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deathOfCaptainMorstan a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Captain Morstan" ;
    ex:description "Captain Arthur Morstan died of heart attack during quarrel with Major Sholto over division of the Agra treasure at Pondicherry Lodge. December 3, 1878. Body concealed by Sholto and Lal Chowdar." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :captainArthurMorstan ;
    ex:hasParticipant :majorJohnSholto ;
    ex:occurredAt :pondicherryLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deathOfCharlesBaskerville a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Sir Charles Baskerville" ;
    ex:description "Sir Charles Baskerville died on the night of May 4th in the Yew Alley of Baskerville Hall. Official verdict was death by cardiac exhaustion. Found by Barrymore with no signs of violence. Footprints showed he had been walking on tiptoe (running) down the Yew Alley. Dr. Mortimer discovered gigantic hound footprints near the body. In reality, Stapleton had released the hound coated in luminous paste; Sir Charles died of heart failure from fright. He had been lured to the moor-gate by Laura Lyons's letter." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :charlesBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackStapleton ;
    ex:occurredAt :yewAlley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deathOfDouglasAtSea a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Douglas at Sea" ;
    ex:description "John Douglas was lost overboard from the ship Palmyra in a gale off St. Helena. Holmes identifies this as murder orchestrated by Professor Moriarty." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:hasVictim :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deathOfEliasOpenshaw a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Elias Openshaw" ;
    ex:description "Colonel Elias Openshaw was found face-downward in a little green-scummed pool at the foot of the garden at the Openshaw estate on May 2, 1883, seven weeks after receiving five orange pips from Pondicherry. The jury brought in a verdict of suicide, but John Openshaw, who knew how his uncle dreaded death, suspected murder by KKK agents." ;
    ex:occurredOn "1883-05-02" ;
    ex:verdictOfDeath "suicide" ;
    ex:hasVictim :eliasOpenshaw ;
    ex:occurredAt :openshawEstate ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deathOfJeffersonHope a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Jefferson Hope" ;
    ex:description "Jefferson Hope died in his police cell the night after his capture. His aortic aneurism burst. He was found with a placid smile on his face." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:deathOfJosephOpenshaw a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Joseph Openshaw" ;
    ex:description "Joseph Openshaw fell over a deep chalk-pit near Fareham while returning from visiting Major Freebody at the Portsdown Hill fort in January 1885, shortly after receiving five orange pips from Dundee. He suffered a shattered skull and died without recovering consciousness. The jury returned a verdict of death from accidental causes, but John suspected murder by KKK agents." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1885"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:verdictOfDeath "death from accidental causes" ;
    ex:hasVictim :josephOpenshaw ;
    ex:occurredAt :fareham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deathOfLucyFerrier a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Lucy Ferrier" ;
    ex:description "Lucy Ferrier died within a month of her forced marriage to Drebber. Jefferson Hope came to her bier and took the wedding ring from her dead finger." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1860" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lucyFerrier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:deathOfOldTrevor a ex:Apoplexy ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Old Mr. Trevor" ;
    ex:description "Old Mr. Trevor (James Armitage) suffered a fatal apoplectic stroke after reading the coded cipher letter from Beddoes with the Fordingbridge post-mark. He clapped both hands to his head, ran in circles, and collapsed with mouth and eyelids puckered on one side. Dr. Fordham was called. Trevor briefly regained consciousness to tell that the papers were in the back drawer of the Japanese cabinet, then died. Victor Trevor had left to fetch Holmes; Trevor died almost immediately after Victor departed." ;
    ex:occurredAt :trevorEstate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:hasParticipant :drFordham ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorTrevor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deathOfSelden a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Selden" ;
    ex:description "Selden the escaped convict died falling from a cliff on the moor while fleeing the hound. He was wearing Sir Henry's old clothes (given via the Barrymores), which caused the hound to track him by scent. Holmes and Watson found his body and initially mistook it for Sir Henry's." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :selden ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deathOfTonga a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Tonga" ;
    ex:description "Tonga shot by Holmes and Watson during Thames chase after attempting to fire poisoned dart. Fell into river and drowned. Body never recovered." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tonga ;
    ex:occurredAt :thames ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:decodingMusgraveRitual a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Decoding of the Musgrave Ritual" ;
    ex:description "Holmes decoded the Musgrave Ritual's cryptic directions at Hurlstone. He used a six-foot fishing rod to cast a shadow (nine feet), then calculated by proportion that the sixty-four-foot elm would cast a ninety-six-foot shadow when the sun was just above the oak. He measured the distance from the elm stump, finding it led to the old wing's doorway. Following the compass directions (north by ten and ten, east by five and five, south by two and two, west by one and one), he reached the flagstone covering the hidden cellar." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneGrounds ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstone ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:disappearanceOfHattyDoran a ex:Disappearance ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance of Hatty Doran" ;
    ex:description "Hatty Doran disappeared from the wedding breakfast at the Lancaster Gate house. After speaking to her maid Alice about 'jumping a claim,' she sat at the breakfast table for about ten minutes, then rose with muttered apologies and left. She went to her room, put on an ulster and bonnet over her bride's dress, and fled the house. She briefly encountered Flora Millar, then joined Francis Moulton who was waiting across the road. They took a cab to lodgings at 226 Gordon Square." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hattyDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :aliceMaid ;
    ex:occurredAt :lancasterGateHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:disappearanceOfNevilleStClair a ex:Disappearance, ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance and Investigation of Neville St. Clair" ;
    ex:description "The disappearance of Neville St. Clair occurred on a Monday in June 1889. Mrs. St. Clair saw her husband in a second-floor window above the Bar of Gold opium den at 4:35 PM. He appeared agitated, waved his hands, then vanished. Blood was found on the windowsill. His clothes (except his coat) were found behind a curtain. His coin-weighted coat was found in the river mud at low tide. Hugh Boone, a crippled beggar living in the room, was arrested. Holmes investigated from The Cedars, staying up all night smoking. He solved the case by washing Boone face with a sponge at Bow Street, revealing him to be Neville St. Clair in disguise. No crime had been committed. Inspector Bradstreet agreed to hush up the matter." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasClient :mrsStClair ;
    ex:ledBy :inspectorBarton ;
    ex:ledBy :inspectorBradstreet ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :barOfGoldDane ;
    ex:hasParticipant :barOfGoldLascar ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrsStClair ;
    ex:hasParticipant :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :barOfGold ;
    ex:occurredAt :bowStreetPoliceStation ;
    ex:occurredAt :theCedars ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:disappearanceOfSilverBlaze a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance of Silver Blaze" ;
    ex:description "The disappearance of racehorse Silver Blaze from King's Pyland stables on Dartmoor. The horse bolted after killing Straker and wandered to Mapleton stables where Silas Brown found and concealed it. Brown disguised the horse by dyeing its distinctive markings. Holmes tracked the horse to Mapleton and confronted Brown, securing the horse's safe return for the Wessex Cup." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :silverBlaze, :silasBrown ;
    ex:occurredAt :kingsPyland ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:discoveryOfBruntonsBody a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Discovery of Brunton's Body" ;
    ex:description "Holmes and Reginald Musgrave, with the aid of county police constables, raised the flagstone in the cellar and discovered the hidden chamber below. Inside was the ancient chest and the body of Richard Brunton, dead for several days, crouched beside the box." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneCellar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:discoveryOfLinenBag a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Discovery of Linen Bag in Mere" ;
    ex:description "While dragging the mere for Rachel Howells's body, a linen bag was recovered containing a mass of old rusted and discolored metal and several dull-colored pieces of pebble or glass — later identified as the ancient crown of England. No body was found." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneMere ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:discoveryOfStrakersBody a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Discovery of Straker's Body" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Straker awoke at seven to find her husband had not returned. She dressed, called the maid Edith Baxter, and went to the stables where they found Hunter in a stupor and the favorite's stall empty. The two lads from the loft were roused. On ascending a knoll near the house, they saw Straker's overcoat on a furze-bush and found his body in a bowl-shaped depression, head shattered and thigh cut." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrsStraker, :edithBaxter ;
    ex:occurredAt :deathHollow ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:douglasFlight a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Douglas's Flight from America" ;
    ex:description "After breaking up the Scowrers, Edwards/Douglas was chased from Chicago, fled to California where Ettie died, nearly killed again, then fled to England under the name Douglas." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:draggingOfSerpentine a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Dragging of the Serpentine" ;
    ex:description "Lestrade spent the day dragging the Serpentine lake in Hyde Park, searching for the body of Lady St. Simon. The wedding clothes (dress, shoes, wreath, veil, ring) had been found floating near the margin by a park-keeper, leading Lestrade to believe the body would be nearby. Holmes mocked this reasoning." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:occurredAt :serpentine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:druggingOfNedHunter a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Drugging of Ned Hunter" ;
    ex:description "The drugging of stable-lad Ned Hunter with powdered opium added to his curried mutton supper. Carried out by John Straker to remove the stable guard so he could take out Silver Blaze. Hunter was found the next morning in a state of absolute stupor, huddled on a chair. Analysis confirmed appreciable quantity of powdered opium in his food remains. The curry was the key clue: its strong flavor disguised the opium, and only Straker or his wife could have arranged for curry to be served and then added the drug." ;
    ex:hasVictim :nedHunter ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnStraker, :nedHunter ;
    ex:occurredAt :kingsPyland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:dundasSeparationCase a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Dundas Separation Case" ;
    ex:description "A case mentioned in the morning paper under the heading 'A husband's cruelty to his wife.' Watson assumed it was a typical domestic case, but Holmes revealed unusual details: the husband was a teetotaler, there was no other woman, and the complaint was that he had drifted into the habit of taking out his false teeth and hurling them at his wife. Holmes was engaged in clearing up some small points in connection with it." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:effieNocturnalVisit a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Effie's Nocturnal Visit to the Cottage" ;
    ex:description "Effie Munro secretly left her home at three in the morning to visit the cottage at Norbury where her daughter Lucy was staying with the Scottish nurse. She dressed and slipped out, but Grant Munro woke and observed her departure. She returned and made excuses about needing fresh air, but Munro did not believe her." ;
    ex:occurredAt :grantMunroVilla, :cottageAtNorbury ;
    ex:hasParticipant :effieMunro, :grantMunro ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:eliseRescuesHatherley a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Elise Rescues Hatherley" ;
    ex:description "Elise saved Victor Hatherley from being crushed in the hydraulic press by opening a secret panel in the wooden wall of the press chamber. She then guided him along a corridor and down a winding staircase, led him to a bedroom window from which he could escape, and physically tried to restrain Stark from pursuing him. Later, she (with Ferguson's help) carried the unconscious Hatherley from the garden to the roadside near Eyford Station." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elise ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrFerguson ;
    ex:occurredAt :becherHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:engineersThumbInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Adventure of the Engineer's Thumb" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Engineer's Thumb Case" ;
    ex:description "An investigation into the attack on Victor Hatherley, a hydraulic engineer who lost his thumb after being lured to a counterfeiting operation near Eyford, Berkshire. Watson introduced the case to Holmes after treating Hatherley's wound. Holmes deduced the criminals had driven Hatherley in circles to disguise the location and that the hydraulic press was used for counterfeiting. Inspector Bradstreet of Scotland Yard joined the investigation. The criminals' base (Dr. Becher's house) was found destroyed by fire. The criminals — Stark, Elise, and Ferguson — escaped and were never found. Set in the summer of 1889." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:isSolved "true" ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:investigatedBy :inspectorBradstreet ;
    ex:hasClient :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :inspectorBradstreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :eyford ;
    ex:occurredAt :becherHouse ;
    ex:introducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:fiveOrangePipsInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Five Orange Pips Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's investigation into the KKK threats against the Openshaw family in September 1887. John Openshaw, the last surviving male of the family, came to Holmes after receiving five orange pips with 'K.K.K.' and 'Put the papers on the sundial.' Holmes deduced the connection to the Ku Klux Klan from the seaport postmarks and the surviving diary page. He traced the barque Lone Star through Lloyd's registers and identified Captain James Calhoun as the gang leader. However, Holmes was too late to save John Openshaw, who was murdered near Waterloo Bridge the same night. Holmes sent orange pips to Calhoun and informed the Savannah police, but the Lone Star was lost at sea before reaching port. The case was one of Holmes's notable failures — he was deeply shaken by John's death, calling it a blow to his pride and a personal matter." ;
    ex:isSolved "false" ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:hasClient :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :johnOpenshaw, :captainJamesCalhoun ;
    ex:hasVictim :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet, :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:flightFromSaltLakeCity a ex:Journey ;
    ex:prefLabel "Flight from Salt Lake City" ;
    ex:description "Jefferson Hope, John Ferrier, and Lucy Ferrier fled Salt Lake City through Eagle Canyon on horseback and mule. Passed a sentinel using the Danite countersign. Ferrier was captured and killed; Lucy was taken back." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1860" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnFerrier ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lucyFerrier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:floraMillarArrest a ex:Arrest ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Flora Millar" ;
    ex:description "Flora Millar was arrested by police on suspicion of involvement in the disappearance of the bride, based on her earlier disturbance and the fact that Hatty was seen walking with her in Hyde Park." ;
    ex:arrestedPerson :floraMillar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:floraMillarDisturbance a ex:Disturbance ;
    ex:prefLabel "Flora Millar's Disturbance at Lancaster Gate" ;
    ex:description "After the bridal party returned to the Doran house at Lancaster Gate, Flora Millar attempted to force her way into the house, alleging she had some claim upon Lord St. Simon. She uttered abusive expressions towards the bride and even threatened her. She was ejected by the butler and the footman after a painful and prolonged scene. Lord St. Simon had foreseen such a possibility and had two plainclothes police present." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :floraMillar ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:occurredAt :lancasterGateHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:forcedMarriageOfLucy a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Forced Marriage of Lucy Ferrier" ;
    ex:description "Lucy Ferrier was forced to marry young Enoch Drebber after her father's murder by the Avenging Angels. She died within a month of the forced marriage." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1860" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :enochDrebber ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lucyFerrier ;
    ex:occurredAt :saltLakeCity ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:gasfittersBall a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Gasfitters' Ball" ;
    skos:altLabel "the gasfitters' ball" ;
    ex:description "A ball organized by a gasfitters' trade association. Mary Sutherland's father used to receive tickets when alive, and afterwards they were sent to her mother. James Windibank forbade attendance but left for France on business. Mary, her mother, and Mr. Hardy attended. Mary met Hosmer Angel at this ball." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :marySutherland, :mrsWindibank, :mrHardy, :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:gloriaScottExplosion a ex:Explosion ;
    ex:prefLabel "Destruction of the Gloria Scott" ;
    skos:altLabel "Gloria Scott explosion" ;
    ex:description "The catastrophic explosion that destroyed the bark Gloria Scott on November 6, 1855, at approximately N. Lat. 15° 20', W. Long. 25° 14'. After the mutiny, the first mate escaped to the after-hold and sat beside an open powder-barrel (one of a hundred carried on board) with a match-box, threatening to blow up the ship. The explosion occurred — Hudson believed it was caused by a misdirected bullet from a convict rather than the mate's match. A dense black cloud of smoke shot up, followed by a roar like thunder. Only Hudson survived from those aboard, clinging to wreckage until rescued by the dissenting group in their boat." ;
    ex:destructionDate "November 6, 1855" ;
    ex:occurredAt :gloriaScottShip ;
    ex:hasParticipant :gloriaScottFirstMate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackPrendergast ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:gloriaScottInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Gloria Scott Case" ;
    skos:altLabel "Holmes's first case" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's very first investigation. Victor Trevor summoned Holmes back to Donnithorpe by telegram after his father suffered a stroke. Holmes decoded the cipher letter from Beddoes (every third word: 'The game is up. Hudson has told all. Fly for your life.') and read old Trevor's confession about the Gloria Scott voyage. The investigation revealed old Trevor's true identity as James Armitage, a former convict transported for embezzlement who had been blackmailed by Hudson, a seaman who survived the Gloria Scott explosion. Holmes concluded that Beddoes likely killed Hudson and fled the country." ;
    ex:occurredAt :trevorEstate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorTrevor ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hudsonSailor ;
    ex:hasParticipant :beddoes ;
    ex:hasClient :victorTrevor ;
    ex:investigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:gloriaScottMutiny a ex:Mutiny ;
    ex:prefLabel "Gloria Scott Mutiny" ;
    ex:description "A convict uprising aboard the bark Gloria Scott, approximately three weeks after departure from Falmouth (circa late October/early November 1855). Led by Jack Prendergast with the complicity of the sham chaplain Wilson, the crew, two warders, and second mate Mercer. Triggered when the ship's doctor discovered hidden pistols in a convict's bunk. Sentries, a corporal, and soldiers at the state-room were shot. The captain was found dead in his cabin with Wilson holding a smoking pistol. Lieutenant Martin and his soldiers fired through the saloon skylights, killing Wilson and eight others. Prendergast overpowered the remaining soldiers. After the mutiny, Prendergast murdered the remaining prisoners (two warders, third mate, and surgeon). Eight dissenters (five convicts including Armitage and Evans, and three sailors) were given a boat and set adrift." ;
    ex:ledBy :jackPrendergast ;
    ex:occurredAt :gloriaScottShip ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackPrendergast ;
    ex:hasParticipant :wilsonChaplain ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:hasParticipant :evansConvict ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mercer ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lieutenantMartin ;
    ex:hasParticipant :gloriaScottCaptain ;
    ex:hasParticipant :gloriaScottFirstMate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :gloriaScottDoctor ;
    ex:isSolved "false"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:goodgeStreetIncident a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Goodge Street Incident" ;
    ex:description "The Goodge Street incident occurred on Christmas morning around 4am on Tottenham Court Road near the corner of Goodge Street. Henry Baker, walking with a slight stagger and carrying a white goose, was accosted by a group of roughs. One knocked off his hat, and Baker raised his stick to defend himself, accidentally smashing a shop window. Frightened by Peterson's approach in his commissionaire uniform, Baker fled, leaving his hat and goose behind." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "Christmas morning" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaker, :peterson ;
    ex:occurredAt :tottenhamCourtRoad, :goodgeStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:gricePatersonsAdventure a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Singular Adventures of the Grice Patersons" ;
    skos:altLabel "Grice Patersons in the island of Uffa" ;
    ex:description "An unrecorded case mentioned by Watson among his headings for the year 1887. Involved the Grice Patersons in the island of Uffa. No further details are given in the text." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:occurredAt :uffa ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:grosvenorSquareFurnitureVanCase a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Grosvenor Square Furniture Van Case" ;
    ex:description "A previous case mentioned by Holmes as 'the little problem of the Grosvenor Square furniture van,' described as 'quite cleared up now - though, indeed, it was obvious from the first.' No further details given." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :grosvenorSquare ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:hagueCase a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Hague Case" ;
    ex:description "A case from The Hague that occurred last year which Holmes references as similar to the Sutherland/Angel deception." ;
    ex:occurredAt :theHague ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:hatherleyAttack a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Attack on Victor Hatherley" ;
    skos:altLabel "the attempted murder of Hatherley" ;
    ex:description "Colonel Lysander Stark's attempted murder of Victor Hatherley. After Hatherley discovered metallic deposits in the hydraulic press (revealing the fuller's-earth story as false), Stark locked him inside the press chamber and activated it. Hatherley was saved when Elise opened a secret panel in the wooden wall. He escaped through a bedroom window, but Stark pursued him with a butcher's cleaver and severed his thumb as he hung from the window-sill. Hatherley fell into the garden, fainted from blood loss among rose-bushes, and was later carried to the roadside near Eyford Station by Elise and Ferguson." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lysanderStark ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elise ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrFerguson ;
    ex:occurredAt :becherHouse ;
    ex:hasVictim :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :lysanderStark ;
    ex:weaponUsed :starkCleaver ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:hatherleyEyfordVisit a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hatherley's Visit to Eyford" ;
    ex:description "Victor Hatherley's overnight visit to Dr. Becher's house near Eyford, hired by Colonel Lysander Stark for fifty guineas to examine a hydraulic press. He travelled by last train from Paddington to Eyford, was collected by Stark in a carriage with frosted windows, and driven in circles to disguise the location. At the house he examined the press, discovered metallic deposits indicating the fuller's-earth story was false, and was subsequently locked in the press and nearly killed. Set in the summer of 1889." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lysanderStark ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrFerguson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elise ;
    ex:occurredAt :becherHouse ;
    ex:occurredAt :eyfordStation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:hattyFrankSecretMarriage a ex:Marriage ;
    ex:prefLabel "Secret Marriage of Hatty Doran and Francis Moulton" ;
    ex:description "Hatty Doran and Francis Hay Moulton were secretly married in 1884 at McQuire's camp near the Rockies. A clergyman had been arranged in advance by Frank. Hatty pledged not to marry anyone else while Frank lived, and Frank agreed not to claim her as his wife until he had made his fortune. After the ceremony, Frank went to seek his fortune and Hatty returned to her father." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1884" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hattyDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :clergyman1884Marriage ;
    ex:occurredAt :mcQuiresCamp ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:haylingDisappearance a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance of Jeremiah Hayling" ;
    ex:description "The disappearance and presumed murder of Jeremiah Hayling, a 26-year-old hydraulic engineer, about a year before the Engineer's Thumb case. He left his lodgings at ten o'clock at night and was never heard from again. Holmes connected his disappearance to Colonel Lysander Stark, stating it represented 'the last time that the colonel needed to have his machine overhauled.' An advertisement about the disappearance appeared in all the papers." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "approximately 1888" ;
    ex:hasVictim :jeremiahHayling ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :lysanderStark ;
    ex:previousVictim :jeremiahHayling ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:hebronMarriage a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Marriage of John Hebron and Effie" ;
    ex:description "The marriage of John Hebron and Effie in Atlanta. An interracial marriage - Effie stated she 'cut herself off from her race' to wed Hebron, who was of African descent. They had one child, Lucy, who took after her father's people." ;
    ex:occurredAt :atlanta ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnHebron, :effieMunro ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:hollandMission a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holland Mission" ;
    ex:description "A mission accomplished by Holmes delicately and successfully for the reigning family of Holland. Referenced only; no details given." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:holmesBrownConfrontation a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Confrontation with Silas Brown" ;
    ex:description "Holmes confronted Silas Brown at Mapleton stables. After Brown blustered and threatened, Holmes leaned forward and whispered something in his ear, describing exactly what Brown had done on the morning he found Silver Blaze. Brown turned ashy pale, hands shaking, and completely capitulated. He agreed to keep the horse safe and follow Holmes's instructions. Twenty minutes of private conversation in Brown's parlor. Brown was transformed from bullying and overbearing to cringing." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :silasBrown ;
    ex:occurredAt :mapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:holmesDeductionTrevor a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Deduction at Trevor Estate" ;
    ex:description "An event one evening at the Trevor estate where young Victor Trevor prompted his father to test Holmes's deductive abilities. Holmes deduced that old Trevor had gone about in fear of personal attack (from the lead-weighted stick), had boxed in his youth (from his ears), had done digging (callosities), had been to New Zealand and Japan, and had been intimately associated with someone with initials J.A. (from a half-effaced tattoo on his arm). The J.A. deduction caused old Trevor to faint. Upon recovery, Trevor told Holmes that all detectives would be children in his hands — the first external validation that detective work could be Holmes's profession." ;
    ex:occurredAt :trevorEstate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorTrevor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:holmesRevealsMoor a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes reveals himself on the moor" ;
    ex:description "Watson discovered Holmes living secretly in a prehistoric stone hut on the moor near Black Tor. Holmes had been staying there while pretending to be in London, with Cartwright bringing him supplies disguised as a country boy. Holmes revealed his deductions about Stapleton's true identity as a Baskerville and his marriage to Beryl. Interrupted by Selden's scream as the hound attacked him." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:hornerArrest a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of John Horner" ;
    ex:description "The arrest of John Horner took place on the evening of December 22nd. Inspector Bradstreet of B division arrested Horner, who struggled frantically and protested his innocence. At the subsequent hearing, evidence of a previous conviction was given, and the magistrate referred the case to the Assizes. Horner fainted at the conclusion of proceedings and was carried out of court." ;
    ex:narrativeDate "December 22" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnHorner, :inspectorBradstreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:hosmerAngelDisappearance a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hosmer Angel's Disappearance" ;
    ex:description "On the wedding morning (a Friday, the fourteenth), Hosmer Angel put Mary Sutherland and her mother into a hansom cab and stepped into a four-wheeler, the only other cab in the street. When the four-wheeler arrived at St. Saviour's Church near King's Cross, it was empty. The cabman said he had seen Angel get in with his own eyes but could not explain the disappearance. Angel had used the old trick of stepping in at one door and out the other side. The wedding breakfast was to have been at the St. Pancras Hotel." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hosmerAngel, :marySutherland, :mrsWindibank ;
    ex:occurredAt :stSaviours ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:hudsonsArrival a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hudson's Arrival at Donnithorpe" ;
    ex:description "The arrival of Hudson the sailor at the Trevor estate in Donnithorpe. While Holmes, Victor, and old Trevor were sitting on the lawn, a maid announced a visitor who would not give his name. Hudson appeared — a wizened sailor whom old Trevor recognized with visible distress, needing brandy to steady himself. Hudson claimed thirty years had passed since they last met and mentioned knowing where Beddoes lived. Trevor gave Hudson food, drink, and eventually positions as gardener and then butler. Hudson's arrival marked the beginning of his blackmail campaign that would ultimately lead to old Trevor's death." ;
    ex:occurredAt :trevorEstate ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hudsonSailor ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorTrevor ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:hugoBaskLegendEvent a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hugo Baskerville legend event" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Baskerville curse" ;
    ex:description "Historical/legendary event from the time of the Great Rebellion. Hugo Baskerville kidnapped a yeoman's daughter and imprisoned her. She escaped by climbing down the ivy on the south wall. Hugo and companions pursued with hounds across the moor. Both Hugo and the maiden were found dead, with a spectral hound standing over Hugo's body. This legend became the Baskerville family curse recorded in the 1742 manuscript." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hugoBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hugosVictim ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:identityInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "A Case of Identity Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into the disappearance of Hosmer Angel, commissioned by Mary Sutherland who was referred by Mrs. Etherege. Holmes quickly deduced that Angel was Mary's stepfather James Windibank in disguise, motivated by preventing her marriage which would cost the household her 100 pounds per year income. Holmes proved the identity by matching typewriter defects between Angel's four letters and Windibank's typewritten note. The case was not legally actionable. Holmes quotes Hafiz about the danger of snatching a delusion from a woman, deciding not to tell Mary the truth as she would not believe it." ;
    ex:hasClient :marySutherland ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :marySutherland, :jamesWindibank, :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:indianMutiny a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Indian Mutiny (1857)" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Mutiny" ;
    skos:altLabel "the great mutiny" ;
    ex:description "Historical event in 1857. Backdrop to Jonathan Small's story. Abelwhite killed, Dawsons killed. Small fled to Agra Fort. Europeans fortified major cities. Eventually suppressed by British forces." ;
    ex:occurredOn "1857"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:occurredAt :india ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:investigationSignOfFour a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Sign of the Four" ;
    ex:description "Central investigation of The Sign of the Four. Client: Mary Morstan. Investigator: Sherlock Holmes with Watson and later Athelney Jones. Involves Mary's missing father, annual pearls, Agra treasure. Solved: Jonathan Small and Tonga identified as criminals; treasure lost in Thames." ;
    ex:assistedBy :athelneyJones ;
    ex:assistedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasClient :maryMorstan ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:investigationStockBrokersClerk a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Stock-Broker's Clerk" ;
    ex:description "Holmes investigates the suspicious circumstances surrounding Hall Pycroft's recruitment by Arthur Pinner to the Franco-Midland Hardware Company. Pycroft realized he had been duped when he noticed that Arthur Pinner and Harry Pinner were the same person, identifiable by a distinctive gold-stuffed tooth. Holmes deduced that the scheme was to impersonate Pycroft at Mawson & Williams while keeping the real Pycroft occupied in Birmingham. The case culminated in Pinner's suicide attempt upon learning his brother had been arrested for robbery and murder." ;
    ex:hasInvestigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :hallPycroft ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hallPycroft ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:occurredAt :watsonPaddingtonPractice ;
    ex:occurredAt :birmingham ;
    ex:occurredAt :126bCorporationStreet ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:jamesMcCarthyArrest a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "James McCarthy's Arrest" ;
    ex:description "The arrest of James McCarthy at Hatherley Farm after his return from Boscombe Pool. The inspector of constabulary informed him he was a prisoner. James remarked he was not surprised and that it was no more than his deserts — a remark Holmes interpreted as a sign of innocence and self-reproach over his quarrel with his father." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMcCarthy, :boscombeValleyInspector ;
    ex:occurredAt :hatherleyFarm ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:jamesMcCarthyTrial a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "James McCarthy's Trial" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Assizes" ;
    ex:description "The trial of James McCarthy at the Assizes for the murder of his father Charles McCarthy. James was acquitted based on a number of objections drawn out by Holmes and submitted to the defending counsel." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:journeyToBirmingham a ex:Journey ;
    ex:prefLabel "Journey to Birmingham" ;
    ex:description "Holmes, Watson, and Pycroft travel by train from London to Birmingham. The journey takes seventy minutes. During the trip, Pycroft recounts his experience to Watson while Holmes listens." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hallPycroft ;
    ex:hasOrigin :london ;
    ex:hasDestination :birmingham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:juliaDeathEvent a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Julia Stoner" ;
    ex:description "Julia Stoner died approximately two years before April 1883, within a fortnight of her planned wedding, in her locked bedroom at Stoke Moran Manor House. She had heard a low whistle for several nights prior. On the fatal night, she screamed, staggered into the corridor, and collapsed, dying with the words 'the speckled band' while pointing toward Dr. Roylott's room. She was found with a charred match and matchbox. The coroner found no satisfactory cause of death. She was killed by the bite of a swamp adder sent through the ventilator by her stepfather." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:hasParticipant :juliaStoner ;
    ex:hasParticipant :swampAdder ;
    ex:hasVictim :juliaStoner ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :stokeMorenManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:lossOfSophyAnderson a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Loss of the British Barque Sophy Anderson" ;
    ex:description "A case from 1887 mentioned by Watson among his headings. Connected with the loss of the British barque Sophy Anderson. No further details are given in the text." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:marseillesCase a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Marseilles Case" ;
    ex:description "A rather intricate matter referred to Holmes from Marseilles. One of the 10-12 cases Holmes has on hand at the time of the Sutherland case. No further details given." ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :marseilles ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:maryHolderFlight a ex:Flight ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mary Holder's Flight" ;
    ex:description "Mary Holder fled from Fairbank overnight after the theft was discovered, leaving a farewell note on the hall table. Her bed had not been slept in. She fled to join Sir George Burnwell. Holmes concluded she was wherever Burnwell was." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :maryHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:occurredAt :fairbank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:mcmurdoArrest a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of McMurdo" ;
    ex:description "Captain Marvin arrests McMurdo for the Stanger beating. All are discharged at trial due to alibis provided by McGinty." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :captainMarvin, :bossMcGinty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:mcmurdoInitiation a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "McMurdo's Lodge Initiation" ;
    ex:description "McMurdo is formally initiated into Lodge 341 on a Saturday night at the Union House, including being branded with the circle-and-triangle mark." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :bossMcGinty ;
    ex:occurredAt :unionHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:mormonMigration a ex:Journey ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mormon Migration" ;
    ex:description "The great caravan of nearly ten thousand Mormons migrating from Nauvoo, Illinois to Salt Lake Valley, passing across the Great Alkali Plain. Rescued John Ferrier and child Lucy on May 4, 1847." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1847" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :brighamYoung ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnFerrier ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lucyFerrier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:mrsRoylottDeathEvent a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Mrs. Stoner in Railway Accident" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Stoner (Mrs. Roylott) was killed in a railway accident near Crewe, approximately eight years before April 1883 (circa 1875). After her death, Dr. Roylott abandoned his attempts to establish a practice in London and took the girls to Stoke Moran." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrsStoner ;
    ex:hasVictim :mrsStoner ;
    ex:occurredAt :crewe ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:munroDaytimeConfrontation a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Munro's Daytime Confrontation at the Cottage" ;
    ex:description "Grant Munro returned home unexpectedly by the 2.40 train and, seeing the maid running across the field to the cottage, realized his wife was there. He rushed to the cottage and entered without knocking, but found it apparently empty - the nurse and child had escaped through the back door. He found common furniture throughout except for one comfortable elegant room upstairs with Effie's photograph on the mantelpiece." ;
    ex:occurredAt :cottageAtNorbury ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grantMunro, :effieMunro, :munroHouseholdMaid ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:munroMarriage a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Marriage of Grant Munro and Effie" ;
    ex:description "The marriage of Grant Munro and Effie (formerly Mrs. Hebron) after a courtship of a few weeks. They met at Pinner, Middlesex, where Effie had been living with her maiden aunt for six months after returning from America. Effie made over all her property to Munro upon marriage." ;
    ex:occurredAt :pinner ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grantMunro, :effieMunro ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:murderAtBirlstone a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder at Birlstone" ;
    ex:description "On the night of January 6th, Ted Baldwin attempted to assassinate John Douglas at Birlstone Manor House. In the ensuing struggle, Douglas killed Baldwin with Baldwin's own sawed-off shotgun. Douglas and Barker then staged the scene to make it appear Douglas was the victim." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:hasVictim :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:occurredAt :birlstoneManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:murderOfAchmet a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Achmet" ;
    ex:description "Merchant Achmet murdered at Agra Fort during the Indian Mutiny. Tripped by Jonathan Small, stabbed twice by Abdullah Khan. Treasure taken. Body buried in hall under loose bricks." ;
    ex:hasSuspect :abdullahKhan ;
    ex:hasSuspect :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:hasVictim :achmet ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :agraFort ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:murderOfBartholomewSholto a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Bartholomew Sholto" ;
    ex:description "Bartholomew Sholto found dead in his locked chemical laboratory at Pondicherry Lodge, killed by Tonga's poisoned dart shot through ceiling trap door. Treasure stolen. Note with sign of the four left beside body." ;
    ex:hasSuspect :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:hasSuspect :tonga ;
    ex:hasVictim :bartholomewSholto ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :pondicherryLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:murderOfDrebber a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Enoch Drebber" ;
    ex:description "The murder of Enoch Drebber. Drebber was poisoned by Jefferson Hope at 3 Lauriston Gardens, Brixton Road. Forced to choose between two pills, one containing deadly alkaloid. RACHE written in blood on the wall." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:hasVictim :enochDrebber ;
    ex:occurredAt :3LauristonGardens ;
    ex:weaponUsedIn :poisonedPills ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:murderOfHales a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of William Hales" ;
    ex:description "Assassination of mine owner William Hales of Stake Royal in the Gilmerton district. Led by Ted Baldwin with two comrades." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:hasVictim :williamHales ;
    ex:occurredAt :stakeRoyal ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:murderOfJohnFerrier a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of John Ferrier" ;
    ex:description "The murder of John Ferrier by the Avenging Angels during the flight from Salt Lake City on August 4, 1860. He was killed and buried in the mountains with a grave marker." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1860" ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :josephStangerson ;
    ex:hasVictim :johnFerrier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:murderOfJohnOpenshaw a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of John Openshaw" ;
    skos:altLabel "Tragedy Near Waterloo Bridge" ;
    ex:description "John Openshaw was murdered near Waterloo Bridge on the night he visited Sherlock Holmes in September 1887. Police-Constable Cook of the H Division heard a cry for help and a splash in the water. Despite the help of passers-by and the water-police, John's body was recovered from the Thames. The official inquest conjectured that he was hurrying to catch the last train from Waterloo Station and accidentally walked over the edge of a river landing-place. Holmes, however, knew it was murder by Calhoun's gang, who had decoyed him to the Embankment." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:verdictOfDeath "unfortunate accident" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :captainJamesCalhoun, :calhounMates ;
    ex:hasVictim :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:occurredAt :waterlooBridge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:murderOfJohnStraker a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of John Straker" ;
    skos:altLabel "death of John Straker" ;
    ex:description "The death of trainer John Straker on Dartmoor. Straker drugged the stable-boy with opium in curried mutton, took Silver Blaze out to a hollow on the moor intending to nick its tendon with a cataract knife. He struck a light, frightening the horse, which lashed out and struck Straker full on the forehead with its steel shoe, shattering his head. His knife gashed his own thigh as he fell. Initially investigated as a murder by an outsider (Fitzroy Simpson) but Holmes proved the horse killed Straker in self-defence. Occurred on a Monday night." ;
    ex:hasVictim :johnStraker ;
    ex:hasParticipant :silverBlaze, :johnStraker ;
    ex:occurredAt :deathHollow ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:murderOfMawsonsWatchman a ex:Crime, ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Mawson's Watchman" ;
    ex:description "The murder of the armed watchman at Mawson & Williams by Beddington during the robbery. The watchman's skull was shattered by a blow from a poker delivered from behind. His body was doubled up and thrust into the largest of the safes, where it would not have been discovered until Monday morning." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :beddingtonBrother2 ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mawsonsWatchman ;
    ex:occurredAt :mawsonAndWilliamsBuilding ;
    ex:weaponUsedIn :pokerMawsons ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:murderOfStangerson a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Joseph Stangerson" ;
    ex:description "The murder of Joseph Stangerson. Stangerson was stabbed by Jefferson Hope at Halliday's Private Hotel, Little George Street. Hope entered via a ladder through the window. RACHE written in blood above the body. Stangerson attacked Hope first, who stabbed him in self-defence." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1881" ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :jeffersonHope ;
    ex:hasVictim :josephStangerson ;
    ex:occurredAt :hallidaysPrivateHotel ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:murderOfStendals a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of the Stendals" ;
    ex:description "The Stendal family was murdered during the terrible winter of Scowrer violence." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:musgraveRitualInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Musgrave Ritual" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Musgrave Ritual case" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's third case during his early career before meeting Watson, when he was living in Montague Street. Reginald Musgrave, a college acquaintance, sought Holmes's help after his butler Richard Brunton was caught reading the ancient Musgrave Ritual document, then disappeared along with housemaid Rachel Howells. Holmes traveled to Hurlstone in Sussex, decoded the Ritual's cryptic directions using shadow calculations from an oak and the stump of an elm, and located a hidden cellar beneath a flagstone. There he found Brunton's body beside an ancient chest. Holmes deduced that Brunton had enlisted Rachel's help to open the chamber, and she had trapped him inside as revenge for jilting her. The treasure proved to be the ancient crown of the kings of England, hidden by a Cavalier ancestor. Rachel Howells was never found." ;
    ex:hasInvestigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:hasParticipant :richardBrunton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :rachelHowells ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstone ;
    ex:occurredAt :montagueStreet ;
    ex:isSolved "true" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:nightVigilStokeMoran a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Night Vigil at Stoke Moran" ;
    ex:description "Holmes and Watson spent the night in Helen Stoner's room at Stoke Moran Manor House, waiting in complete darkness. They engaged rooms at the Crown Inn, then entered the manor through the window after Helen's signal lamp. They encountered the baboon on the lawn and heard the cheetah's whine. After hours of waiting, they heard a sound from the ventilator, then the hiss of the snake descending the bell-rope. Holmes struck the snake with his cane and lit a match, driving the snake back through the ventilator where it bit Roylott." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :helenStoner ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :stokeMorenManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:nobleBachelorInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Noble Bachelor Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into the disappearance of Hatty Doran (Lady St. Simon) after the wedding breakfast. Holmes deduced from newspaper accounts alone that the bride had seen an American at the ceremony - likely a prior husband. Lord St. Simon's account of the man in the pew, the bouquet drop, the 'jumping a claim' remark, and the maid confirmed his theory. Lestrade's discovery of the F.H.M. note and hotel bill fragment on its reverse allowed Holmes to trace Francis Moulton to a select hotel on Northumberland Avenue and then to lodgings at 226 Gordon Square. Holmes persuaded the Moultons to explain and arranged a supper meeting at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lestrade ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hattyDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:paradolChamberAdventure a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Adventure of the Paradol Chamber" ;
    skos:altLabel "Paradol Chamber" ;
    ex:description "An unrecorded case mentioned by Watson among his headings for the year 1887. No further details are given in the text." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:pinnerSuicideAttempt a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Pinner's Suicide Attempt" ;
    ex:description "Arthur Pinner/Beddington's attempted suicide at 126b Corporation Street, Birmingham. After reading the Evening Standard report of his brother's arrest for robbery and murder at Mawson's, he excused himself to an inner room, removed his coat and waistcoat, and hanged himself from a hook behind the door using his own braces. Holmes, Watson, and Pycroft broke down the locked door upon hearing knocking and gargling sounds. Watson provided emergency medical care, reviving him with cold water." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hallPycroft ;
    ex:occurredAt :126bCorporationStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:pycroftRecruitment a ex:Event, ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Pycroft's Recruitment by Pinner" ;
    ex:description "Arthur Pinner's visit to Hall Pycroft at 17 Potter's Terrace, Hampstead, on the evening after Pycroft had been promised the Mawson & Williams position. Pinner tested Pycroft's stock market knowledge, offered him a position as business manager of the Franco-Midland Hardware Company at five hundred pounds per year, gave him a hundred pound advance, obtained a handwriting specimen via a written declaration, and persuaded him not to resign from Mawson's. All part of the scheme to impersonate Pycroft at Mawson's." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hallPycroft ;
    ex:occurredAt :17PottersTerrace ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:rachelHowellsDisappearance a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Disappearance of Rachel Howells" ;
    ex:description "Three nights after Brunton's disappearance, Rachel Howells escaped through her window while her nurse slept. Her footprints were traced across the lawn to the edge of the mere, where they vanished near the gravel path. No body was found when the mere was dragged. She was never heard from again; Holmes believed she fled England." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :rachelHowells ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstone ;
    ex:occurredAt :hurlstoneMere ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:redHeadedLeagueInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Red-Headed League Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Holmes investigates the case of Jabez Wilson and the dissolved Red-headed League. Wilson reports that the League hired him to copy the Encyclopaedia Britannica, then dissolved without warning. Holmes deduces that the scheme was designed by John Clay to tunnel from Wilson's cellar to the City and Suburban Bank vault. Holmes arranges an ambush in the vault with Watson, Peter Jones, and Mr. Merryweather, resulting in Clay's arrest." ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeDate "1890" ;
    ex:hasClient :jabezWilson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :duncanRoss ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jabezWilson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClay ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrMerryweather ;
    ex:hasParticipant :peterJones ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:occurredAt :saxeCoburgSquare ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:robberyAtMawsons a ex:Crime, ex:Theft ;
    ex:prefLabel "Robbery at Mawson & Williams" ;
    ex:description "A daring robbery at Mawson & Williams on a Saturday afternoon. Beddington, who had been impersonating Hall Pycroft as a clerk, entered the building pretending he had left something behind. He murdered the armed watchman, rifled the large safe, and stole nearly a hundred thousand pounds worth of American railway bonds and scrip in mines and other companies, which he placed in a carpet bag. He was spotted leaving the building at twenty minutes past one by Sergeant Tuson." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :beddingtonBrother2 ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mawsonsWatchman ;
    ex:occurredAt :mawsonAndWilliamsBuilding ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:roylottButlerMurder a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Roylott's Murder of Native Butler" ;
    ex:description "Dr. Grimesby Roylott beat his native butler to death in India in a fit of anger caused by robberies in the house. He narrowly escaped a capital sentence and suffered a long term of imprisonment." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:hasParticipant :roylottButler ;
    ex:hasVictim :roylottButler ;
    ex:occurredAt :india ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:roylottConfrontation a ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Roylott's Confrontation at Baker Street" ;
    ex:description "Dr. Grimesby Roylott burst into 221B Baker Street after tracing Helen Stoner there. He threatened Holmes, called him 'the meddler', 'the busybody', and 'the Scotland Yard Jack-in-office', shook his hunting crop, seized the steel poker and bent it into a curve, then hurled it into the fireplace and strode out. Holmes subsequently straightened the poker and remarked on the incident giving zest to the investigation." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:roylottDeathEvent a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Death of Dr. Grimesby Roylott" ;
    ex:description "Dr. Roylott died in his room at Stoke Moran Manor House when his swamp adder, driven back through the ventilator by Holmes's cane blows, bit him. He was found seated on a wooden chair in his dressing-gown, the snake coiled around his brow—the 'speckled band'. He died within ten seconds of being bitten. The official inquiry concluded he died while 'indiscreetly playing with a dangerous pet.' Holmes acknowledged being 'indirectly responsible' but said it was unlikely to weigh heavily on his conscience." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :swampAdder ;
    ex:hasVictim :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:occurredAt :stokeMorenManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:saloonMassacre a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Saloon Massacre on the Gloria Scott" ;
    ex:description "An event during the Gloria Scott mutiny in which Lieutenant Martin and ten of his soldiers, positioned on the poop deck, fired through the open swing skylights above the saloon table at the celebrating mutineers below. Wilson the sham chaplain and eight others were killed. The survivors, led by Prendergast, rushed out and overpowered the soldiers." ;
    ex:occurredAt :gloriaScottShip ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lieutenantMartin ;
    ex:hasParticipant :wilsonChaplain ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:scandalInBohemiaInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "A Scandal in Bohemia Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's investigation to recover a compromising photograph of the King of Bohemia with Irene Adler. Begins March 20, 1888. Holmes is hired by the King of Bohemia. Holmes uses disguise (groom, then clergyman) and a fire ruse to locate the photograph at Briony Lodge but Irene Adler outwits him, recognizing him and fleeing with the photograph to the Continent. The investigation fails in its primary objective, though Irene promises not to use the photograph against the King. Holmes keeps a photograph of Irene as his only reward." ;
    ex:isSolved "false"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:narrativeDate "March 20, 1888" ;
    ex:hasClient :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :wilhelmVonOrmstein, :ireneAdler ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet, :brionyLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:secondAfghanWar a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Second Afghan War" ;
    ex:description "The Second Afghan War is the war in Afghanistan in which Watson served, leading to his wounding at the Battle of Maiwand and return to England." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:occurredAt :afghanistan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :studyInScarletDoc .

:seldenEscape a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Selden's escape from Princetown" ;
    ex:description "Selden the Notting Hill murderer escaped from Princetown Prison on Dartmoor. Armed soldiers were stationed at railway stations. He hid in stone huts on the moor and was secretly fed by his sister Mrs. Barrymore and brother-in-law Barrymore via candle signals. His escape coincided with the early period of Watson's stay at Baskerville Hall." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :selden ;
    ex:occurredAt :princetownPrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:seldenPursuit a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Pursuit of Selden on the moor" ;
    ex:description "Watson and Sir Henry pursued Selden across the moor at night after discovering Barrymore's candle signaling. They heard the eerie cry of a hound during the chase. Watson glimpsed a second mysterious figure silhouetted on a tor (later revealed as Holmes). Selden escaped." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :selden ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:silverBlazeInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Silver Blaze Case" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into the disappearance of racehorse Silver Blaze and the murder of trainer John Straker at King's Pyland, Dartmoor. Holmes received telegrams from Colonel Ross and Inspector Gregory on Tuesday evening. Traveled to Dartmoor on Thursday with Watson. Deduced the significance of the curried mutton (drugging by an insider), the silence of the dog (familiar visitor), the cataract knife (tendon-nicking intent), the milliner's bill (double life motive), and the lame sheep (practice). Tracked horse to Mapleton and confronted Silas Brown. Returned to London, visited the milliner. Four days later attended Wessex Cup at Winchester where Silver Blaze won. Revealed Straker as the true criminal killed by his own intended victim." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :inspectorGregory, :colonelRoss ;
    ex:occurredAt :kingsPyland, :mapleton, :winchesterRacecourse ;
    ex:investigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :colonelRoss ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:simpsonStableEncounter a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Simpson's Encounter at King's Pyland" ;
    ex:description "Fitzroy Simpson appeared out of the darkness and accosted Edith Baxter near the stables, attempting to bribe her to deliver a paper to the stable-boy. Then spoke to Ned Hunter through the stable window, trying to get racing tips about Silver Blaze and Bayard. Hunter called him a tout and rushed out with the watchdog, but Simpson had fled. Simpson's cravat was later found at the scene. Key event establishing Simpson as a suspect." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :fitzroySimpson, :edithBaxter, :nedHunter ;
    ex:occurredAt :kingsPyland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:sinkingOfLoneStar a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sinking of the Lone Star" ;
    ex:description "The barque Lone Star was lost at sea during the severe equinoctial gales. Somewhere far out in the Atlantic, a shattered stern-post with the letters 'L.S.' carved upon it was seen swinging in the trough of a wave. That is all that was ever known of the fate of the Lone Star and its crew, including Captain James Calhoun and his two mates." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :captainJamesCalhoun, :calhounMates ;
    ex:occurredAt :atlanticOcean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:speckledBandInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Speckled Band" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into the mysterious death of Julia Stoner and the threat to her twin sister Helen Stoner, conducted in April 1883. Helen Stoner consulted Holmes at Baker Street after hearing the same nocturnal whistle that preceded her sister's death. Holmes visited Doctors' Commons to examine the financial motive, inspected the rooms at Stoke Moran Manor House, and conducted a night vigil during which he struck the swamp adder with his cane, driving it back through the ventilator to kill Dr. Roylott. The case was resolved and Helen was taken to her aunt's care." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1883"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ex:hasClient :helenStoner ;
    ex:ledBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:hasParticipant :helenStoner ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :stokeMorenManorHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:stableLaneStruggle a ex:PhysicalStruggle ;
    ex:prefLabel "Struggle in the Stable Lane" ;
    ex:description "A physical confrontation between Arthur Holder and Sir George Burnwell in the stable lane at Fairbank. Arthur, barefoot and in nightclothes, pursued Burnwell after seeing Mary pass the coronet through the window. They struggled over the coronet, with Arthur tugging at one side and Burnwell at the other. Arthur struck Burnwell, cutting him over the eye. The coronet snapped, leaving the corner with three beryls in Burnwell's grasp. Drops of blood in the snow marked the scene." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :arthurHolder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:occurredAt :fairbank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:staphouseExplosion a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Blowing Up of the Staphouse Family" ;
    ex:description "The Staphouse family was blown up during the terrible winter of Scowrer violence." ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:stapletonConfrontsSirHenry a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Stapleton confronts Sir Henry" ;
    ex:description "Stapleton angrily confronted Sir Henry Baskerville for courting Beryl on the moor path. Despite using Beryl as bait to keep Sir Henry visiting Merripit House, Stapleton's jealousy overcame his calculation. He later apologized, claiming his sister was everything in his life. Sir Henry was bewildered by the outburst." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :berylStapleton ;
    ex:hasParticipant :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackStapleton ;
    ex:occurredAt :dartmoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:stapletonFlight a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Stapleton's flight into Grimpen Mire" ;
    ex:description "After the hound was killed and his plot exposed, Stapleton fled from Merripit House into the Grimpen Mire. Despite knowing safe paths through the mire, the dense fog made navigation impossible. His body was never found. Presumed dead, swallowed by the mire." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackStapleton ;
    ex:occurredAt :grimpenMire ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:starkGangEscape a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Escape of Stark's Gang" ;
    ex:description "The escape of Colonel Lysander Stark, Elise, and Mr. Ferguson from Dr. Becher's house before the police arrived. A peasant reported seeing a cart with several people and bulky boxes driving rapidly toward Reading early in the morning. All traces of the fugitives disappeared and Holmes's ingenuity failed to discover their whereabouts. The woman, 'the sinister German,' and 'the morose Englishman' were never heard from again." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lysanderStark ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elise ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mrFerguson ;
    ex:occurredAt :eyford ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:stJamesHallConcert a ex:Concert ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sarasate Concert at St. James's Hall" ;
    ex:description "Musical performance by Sarasate at St. James's Hall on the afternoon of the Red-headed League case. Holmes and Watson attend. The programme includes German music, which Holmes prefers. Holmes sits wrapped in happiness, waving his fingers in time to the music." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasPerformer :sarasate ;
    ex:occurredAt :stJamesHall ;
    ex:performedAt :stJamesHall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:stSimonDoranWedding a ex:Marriage ;
    ex:prefLabel "St. Simon-Doran Wedding" ;
    ex:description "The quiet wedding of Lord Robert St. Simon and Hatty Doran at St. George's Hanover Square. Only half a dozen intimate friends present: the father of the bride (Aloysius Doran), the Duchess of Balmoral, Lord Backwater, Lord Eustace and Lady Clara St. Simon, and Lady Alicia Whittington. Francis Hay Moulton, Hatty's secret first husband, was present among the general public in the front pew. Hatty dropped her bouquet near his pew and received a note. After the ceremony, the party returned to the Doran house at Lancaster Gate for breakfast." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1887" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hattyDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :aloysiusDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :duchessOfBalmoral ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordBackwater ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordEustace ;
    ex:hasParticipant :ladyClaraStSimon ;
    ex:hasParticipant :ladyAliciaWhittington ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:occurredAt :stGeorgesHanoverSquare ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:supperAt221B a ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Supper at 221B Baker Street" ;
    ex:description "An epicurean cold supper arranged by Holmes at 221B Baker Street for five people: Holmes, Watson, Lord St. Simon, and Mr. and Mrs. Francis Hay Moulton. The supper included cold woodcock, pheasant, pâté de foie gras pie, and ancient cobwebby bottles. Lord St. Simon refused to stay and departed with offended dignity. The Moultons remained and were warmly received by Holmes." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hattyDoran ;
    ex:hasParticipant :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:tankervilleClubScandal a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Tankerville Club Scandal" ;
    ex:description "A case in which Sherlock Holmes saved Major Prendergast, who was wrongfully accused of cheating at cards at the Tankerville Club. Prendergast later referred John Openshaw to Holmes." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :majorPrendergast ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :tankervilleClub ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:thamesChase a ex:Pursuit ;
    ex:prefLabel "Thames Chase" ;
    ex:description "Police launch pursued Aurora down Thames from Tower/Jacobson's Yard through Greenwich, Blackwall, past Isle of Dogs to Barking Level. Tonga shot by Holmes and Watson; fell into river. Small captured when Aurora ran aground." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :athelneyJones ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tonga ;
    ex:occurredAt :thames ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:trappingOfScowrers a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trapping of the Scowrers" ;
    ex:description "McMurdo/Birdy Edwards reveals his true identity and Captain Marvin's armed men arrest the seven Scowrer leaders at Widow MacNamara's house." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :captainMarvin, :bossMcGinty, :tedBaldwin, :harraway, :carter, :tigerCormac, :willabyBrothers ;
    ex:occurredAt :widowMacNamaraHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:trepoffMurder a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trepoff Murder Case" ;
    ex:description "A murder case in Odessa for which Holmes was summoned. Referenced only by Watson as one of Holmes's recent activities. No details given." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :odessa ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:trialOfScowrers a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trial of the Scowrers" ;
    ex:description "Trial held far from the valley. McGinty hanged, eight chief followers hanged, fifty-odd imprisoned. Based on Edwards's testimony." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnDouglas, :bossMcGinty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:tunnelDigging a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Tunnel Digging" ;
    ex:description "Over several weeks, John Clay (as Vincent Spaulding) dug a tunnel from the cellar of Jabez Wilson's pawnbroker's shop in Saxe-Coburg Square to the vault of the City and Suburban Bank's Coburg branch. His knees were worn, wrinkled, and stained from burrowing. He used his photography hobby as cover for spending time in the cellar." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :duncanRoss ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnClay ;
    ex:occurredAt :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:occurredAt :saxeCoburgSquare ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:turnerMcCarthyReunion a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Turner-McCarthy Reunion on Regent Street" ;
    ex:description "The chance encounter between John Turner and Charles McCarthy on Regent Street, London, some years after both returned to England from Australia. McCarthy, nearly destitute, recognized Turner and initiated blackmail, demanding that Turner support him and his son or face exposure to the police. This led to McCarthy settling in Boscombe Valley as Turner's tenant." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnTurner, :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:occurredAt :regentStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:visitSaxeCoburgSquare a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Visit to Saxe-Coburg Square" ;
    ex:description "Holmes and Watson travel by Underground to Aldersgate and walk to Saxe-Coburg Square. Holmes examines Wilson's shop, thumps the pavement with his stick to test the cellar, and knocks on the door to see Vincent Spaulding. He then surveys the businesses behind the square, noting the City and Suburban Bank abuts Wilson's premises." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :saxeCoburgSquare ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:watsonBringsHatherley a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Brings Hatherley to Holmes" ;
    ex:description "Watson treated Hatherley's severed thumb at his practice, then brought him by hansom cab to Baker Street to see Holmes. This was one of only two cases Watson personally introduced to Holmes (the other being Colonel Warburton's madness). Watson briefly explained the matter to his wife before departing." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1889" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :victorHatherley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:occurredAt :watsonPractice ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:watsonsEngagement a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Engagement to Mary Morstan" ;
    ex:description "Watson proposes to Mary Morstan after the Agra treasure is found empty. She accepts. The treasure's absence removed the barrier between them. Announced to Holmes at the end of the case." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :maryMorstan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:watsonVisitsLyons a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's visit to Laura Lyons" ;
    ex:description "Watson traveled to Coombe Tracey to interview Laura Lyons about her letter to Sir Charles Baskerville. She admitted writing the letter requesting a meeting but denied keeping the appointment, claiming she received help from another source (implied to be Stapleton). This interview provided a key piece of evidence." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lauraLyons ;
    ex:occurredAt :coombeTracey ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:wessexCupRace a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Wessex Cup Race" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Wessex Cup" ;
    skos:altLabel "the Wessex Plate" ;
    ex:description "Horse race held at Winchester racecourse, officially the Wessex Plate. 50 sovereigns each half forfeit with 1000 sovereigns added, for four and five year olds. Second prize £300, third £200. New course of one mile and five furlongs. Six horses ran: The Negro, Pugilist, Desborough, Silver Blaze, Iris, and Rasper. Silver Blaze won by a good six lengths over Desborough with Iris making a bad third. Silver Blaze ran disguised with dyed markings, having been returned by Silas Brown." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :silverBlaze, :desborough, :theNegro, :pugilist, :iris, :rasper ;
    ex:occurredAt :winchesterRacecourse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:willSigningNorwood a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Signing of Oldacre's Will" ;
    ex:description "Jonas Oldacre visits McFarlane at Graham and McFarlane's offices to have his will signed and sealed. During the sealing, a wax impression of McFarlane's thumb is taken, which Oldacre later uses to plant the fake thumbprint." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:hasParticipant :mcFarlaneClerk ;
    ex:occurredAt :greshamBuildings ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:wilsonArrest a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Wilson the canary-trainer" ;
    ex:description "In 1895, Holmes arrested Wilson, the notorious canary-trainer, removing a plague-spot from the East End of London. Referenced only; no details given." ;
    ex:eventYear "1895" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :wilsonCanaryTrainer ;
    ex:occurredAt :eastEndLondon ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:windigbankConfrontation a ex:Event, ex:Meeting ;
    ex:prefLabel "Windibank Confrontation" ;
    ex:description "Holmes confronts James Windibank at 221B Baker Street at six o'clock. Holmes demonstrates the typewriter match between Hosmer Angel's four letters and Windibank's typewritten note, revealing identical defects. Windibank protests the scheme is not actionable. Holmes agrees but calls it a cruel, selfish, and heartless trick. Holmes locks the door, explains the full chain of events, then threatens Windibank with a hunting crop. Windibank flees down the stairs and out the door at top speed." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes, :johnWatson, :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:wisteriaLodgeInvestigation a ex:Event, ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Wisteria Lodge case" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Oxshott Mystery" ;
    ex:description "Investigation into the murder of Aloysius Garcia and the mystery of Wisteria Lodge. Led independently by both Sherlock Holmes and Inspector Baynes of the Surrey Constabulary. Holmes deduced Garcia intended Scott Eccles as an alibi and traced the conspiracy to High Gable. Baynes shrewdly arrested the mulatto cook as a decoy. The case ultimately revealed Henderson as Don Murillo, the Tiger of San Pedro." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :inspectorBaynes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tobiasGregson ;
    ex:hasClient :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:occurredAt :wisteriaLodge ;
    ex:occurredAt :highGable ;
    ex:occurredAt :esher ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1892" ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:woodleyAssaultOnViolet a ex:Assault ;
    ex:prefLabel "Woodley's assault on Violet at Chiltern Grange" ;
    ex:description "During a week-long visit to Chiltern Grange, Woodley seized Violet in his arms after dinner, swearing he would not let her go until she kissed him. Carruthers intervened and tore him off, whereupon Woodley turned on Carruthers, knocking him down and cutting his face." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jackWoodley ;
    ex:hasParticipant :violetSmith ;
    ex:hasParticipant :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:hasVictim :violetSmith ;
    ex:occurredAt :chilternGrange ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:worthingdonBankRobbery a ex:Theft ;
    ex:prefLabel "Worthingdon bank robbery" ;
    skos:altLabel "the great Worthingdon bank business" ;
    ex:description "A bank robbery in 1875 in which five men (Biddle, Hayward, Moffat, Cartwright, and Sutton/Blessington) robbed the Worthingdon bank, murdering the caretaker Tobin and stealing seven thousand pounds. All five were arrested but the evidence was not conclusive. Sutton turned informer." ;
    ex:narrativeYear "1875" ;
    ex:hasParticipant :biddle ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hayward ;
    ex:hasParticipant :moffat ;
    ex:hasParticipant :cartwrightCriminal ;
    ex:hasParticipant :blessington ;
    ex:hasParticipant :tobin ;
    ex:occurredAt :worthingdonBank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:worthingdonGangTrial a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trial of the Worthingdon bank gang" ;
    ex:description "The trial following the 1875 Worthingdon bank robbery. All five gang members were arrested but evidence was not conclusive. Sutton/Blessington turned informer, leading to Cartwright being hanged and Biddle, Hayward, and Moffat receiving fifteen-year sentences." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :biddle ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hayward ;
    ex:hasParticipant :moffat ;
    ex:hasParticipant :cartwrightCriminal ;
    ex:hasParticipant :blessington ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:wristSeizureLausanne a ex:Assault ;
    ex:prefLabel "Green Seizes Lady Frances's Wrist in Lausanne" ;
    ex:description "Philip Green seized Lady Frances Carfax's wrist with great violence on the public promenade by the lake in Lausanne. This incident was witnessed by Marie Devine and contributed to Lady Frances's fear of Green and her acceptance of the Shlessingers' escort to London." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :philipGreen, :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:occurredAt :lausannePromenade ;
    ex:witnessedBy :marieDevine ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:yellowFaceInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Yellow Face" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Yellow Face Case" ;
    ex:description "Sherlock Holmes's investigation into the mystery surrounding a cottage at Norbury and its connection to Grant Munro's wife Effie. Holmes theorized incorrectly that Effie's first husband was alive and blackmailing her. The truth was that Effie was hiding her mixed-race daughter Lucy from her first marriage to John Hebron, having told Munro that both husband and child had died. One of Holmes's notable failures, leading to his famous request that Watson whisper 'Norbury' whenever Holmes becomes overconfident." ;
    ex:hasInvestigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :grantMunro ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson, :effieMunro, :lucyHebron, :scottishNurse ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet, :norbury, :cottageAtNorbury ;
    ex:isSolved "true" ;
    ex:narrativeYear "uncertain" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:yellowFeverOutbreakAtlanta a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Yellow Fever Outbreak in Atlanta" ;
    ex:description "An outbreak of yellow fever in Atlanta, Georgia that killed John Hebron. Effie Munro told Grant Munro that both her first husband and child died in this outbreak, though in truth only Hebron died and their daughter Lucy survived." ;
    ex:occurredAt :atlanta ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnHebron, :lucyHebron ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :yellowFaceDoc .

:arrestOfAbeSlaney a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Abe Slaney" ;
    ex:description "Holmes lured Abe Slaney to Ridling Thorpe Manor by writing a note in the dancing men cipher saying 'Come here at once,' addressed to Slaney at Elrige's Farm. When Slaney arrived and entered the drawing-room, Holmes clapped a pistol to his head while Inspector Martin slipped handcuffs on his wrists. Slaney confessed to the shooting, claiming self-defence as Cubitt had fired first. He was conveyed to Norwich by cab with two uniformed policemen." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :abeSlaney ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :inspectorMartin ;
    ex:occurredAt :ridlingThorpeDrawingRoom ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:cubittElsieMarriage a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Marriage of Hilton Cubitt and Elsie Patrick" ;
    ex:description "Hilton Cubitt and Elsie Patrick were married quietly at a registry office after meeting at a boarding-house in Russell Square during the Jubilee. Before the wedding, Elsie told Cubitt she had disagreeable associations in her past and asked him to accept her without knowing her history. The marriage took place about a year before the main events of the story." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:occurredAt :london ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:dancingMenInvestigation a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "The Dancing Men Investigation" ;
    skos:altLabel "The Adventure of the Dancing Men case" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's investigation into mysterious dancing men cipher messages appearing at Ridling Thorpe Manor, Norfolk. The case began when Hilton Cubitt consulted Holmes about hieroglyphic stick-figure drawings that were terrorizing his wife Elsie. Holmes decoded the cipher as a substitution cipher using frequency analysis, identifying the sender as Abe Slaney, an American criminal from Chicago. Despite Holmes's efforts, Cubitt was killed and Elsie seriously wounded before he could intervene. Holmes lured Slaney to the Manor using the cipher and he was arrested. The case was solved." ;
    ex:investigatedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasClient :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:hasParticipant :abeSlaney ;
    ex:hasParticipant :inspectorMartin ;
    ex:occurredAt :221bBakerStreet ;
    ex:occurredAt :ridlingThorpeManor ;
    ex:isSolved "true"^^xsd:boolean ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:murderOfHiltonCubitt a ex:Murder ;
    ex:prefLabel "Murder of Hilton Cubitt" ;
    skos:altLabel "Shooting at Ridling Thorpe Manor" ;
    ex:description "At approximately three in the morning, Elsie Cubitt came down to meet Abe Slaney at the study window, bringing money to bribe him to leave. Slaney caught her arm and tried to pull her through the window. Hilton Cubitt rushed in with his revolver and fired at Slaney, missing. Slaney returned fire, hitting Cubitt through the heart, killing him instantly. Elsie then shut and fastened the window and attempted suicide." ;
    ex:hasVictim :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:hasPerpetrator :abeSlaney ;
    ex:hasParticipant :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:hasParticipant :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:hasParticipant :abeSlaney ;
    ex:occurredAt :ridlingThorpeStudy ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:shootingOfElsieCubitt a ex:Crime ;
    ex:prefLabel "Shooting of Elsie Cubitt" ;
    skos:altLabel "Elsie's suicide attempt" ;
    ex:description "After Hilton Cubitt was shot dead by Abe Slaney, Elsie Cubitt shot herself through the front of the brain in an apparent suicide attempt. She was found crouching near the window with her head against the wall, horribly wounded with the side of her face red with blood. She survived and eventually recovered entirely." ;
    ex:hasVictim :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:occurredAt :ridlingThorpeStudy ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:trialOfAbeSlaney a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trial of Abe Slaney" ;
    skos:altLabel "Norwich winter assizes" ;
    ex:description "Abe Slaney was tried at the winter assizes at Norwich. He was condemned to death, but his penalty was changed to penal servitude in consideration of mitigating circumstances and the certainty that Hilton Cubitt had fired the first shot." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :abeSlaney ;
    ex:occurredAt :norwich ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:abductionOfLordSaltire a ex:Kidnapping ;
    ex:prefLabel "Abduction of Lord Saltire" ;
    ex:description "Lord Saltire (Arthur) was lured from the Priory School on the night of May 13th. James Wilder opened the Duke's letter and inserted a note using the Duchess's name. At midnight Arthur found Hayes with a led pony at Ragged Shaw. Taken to the Fighting Cock Inn and confined in an upper room under the care of Mrs Hayes." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :lordSaltire ;
    ex:hasParticipant :jamesWilder ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reubenHayes ;
    ex:occurredAt :raggedShaw ;
    ex:occurredAt :priorySchool ;
    ex:occurredAt :fightingCockInn ;
    ex:narrativeDate "May 13" ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:arrestOfReubenHayes a ex:Event ;
    ex:prefLabel "Arrest of Reuben Hayes" ;
    ex:description "Reuben Hayes was arrested at Chesterfield at eleven o'clock at night on Holmes's information, communicated by telegram to the local police from Mackleton Station." ;
    ex:hasParticipant :reubenHayes ;
    ex:occurredAt :chesterfield ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:investigationPriorySchool a ex:Investigation ;
    ex:prefLabel "Investigation of the Priory School Case" ;
    ex:description "Holmes and Watson investigated the disappearance of Lord Saltire from the Priory School. They traced bicycle tracks on the moor, discovered Heidegger's body, identified the cow-track horseshoe ruse at the Fighting Cock Inn, observed Wilder's visit, and deduced the Duke's involvement. Hayes arrested at Chesterfield. Reward of 6000 pounds paid." ;
    ex:hasInvestigator :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:hasParticipant :johnWatson ;
    ex:hasParticipant :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
