# ============================================================================
# DEDUCTIONS — Full Individual Definitions
# ============================================================================

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sir Eustace Is Dead and the Case Is Murder" ;
    ex:description "On the train to Kent, Holmes reads Hopkins's urgent note and analyzes its language and context to determine the nature of the case before arriving at the scene." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sir Eustace Brackenstall is dead and the case involves murder, not suicide." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes inferred from Hopkins's agitated handwriting that something violent had occurred, noting that Hopkins is not an emotional man. He reasoned that a mere suicide would not have prompted Hopkins to send for him, and that the instruction to leave Sir Eustace undisturbed indicated a body left for inspection." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eustaceBrackenstall ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hopkinsLetterAbbeyGrange ;
    ex:confirmedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Crime Was Committed Before Midnight" ;
    ex:description "Still on the train, Holmes estimates the timing of the crime by working backward from the sequence of communications that brought them the case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The crime was committed before twelve o'clock the previous night." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes calculated backward from the 3:30 a.m. note: the local police had to be called, they communicated with Scotland Yard, Hopkins traveled out, and then sent for Holmes — all of which constituted a fair night's work, placing the crime before midnight." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderOfEustaceBrackenstall ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hopkinsLetterAbbeyGrange ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Wine Bottle Was Opened with a Pocket Corkscrew" ;
    ex:description "In the dining room, Holmes examines the cork of the wine bottle and the household corkscrew, determining they do not match." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The wine bottle was opened with a short pocket corkscrew, not the large household corkscrew found in the drawer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the cork had been pierced three times before extraction and was never transfixed, indicating a short screw approximately an inch and a half long — consistent with a multiplex pocket knife. The large household corkscrew would have transfixed the cork and drawn it in a single pull." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbeyGrangeWineBottle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeWineBottle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Only Two People Drank Wine, Not Three" ;
    ex:description "While reviewing the evidence on a bench at the railway station, Holmes explains to Watson the significance of the bees-wing distribution among the three wine glasses." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Only two glasses were actually used; the dregs of both were poured into a third glass to create the false impression that three people had been present." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that bees-wing sediment appeared only in one of the three glasses. If three glasses had been filled sequentially from a full bottle, the sediment would not concentrate in a single glass. The only explanation consistent with the evidence is that two glasses were used and their dregs combined into a third, concentrating all the bees-wing in one glass." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbeyGrangeWineGlasses ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeWineGlasses, :abbeyGrangeWineBottle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lady Brackenstall's Story Is a Fabrication" ;
    ex:description "At the railway station bench, Holmes presents Watson with a cumulative case against the burglar narrative, identifying multiple improbabilities in Lady Brackenstall's account." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Brackenstall and her maid deliberately lied; no burglars were involved and the entire Randall gang story is a fabrication." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified a series of improbabilities: burglars who had just done a successful job at Sydenham would not risk another so soon; burglars do not typically operate at such an early hour; striking a lady would cause her to scream rather than prevent it; three men would not need to commit murder to overpower one; professional burglars would not leave with so little plunder when more was available; and burglars would not leave a bottle half empty. Combined with the wine glass evidence, this meant the women had a strong reason for covering the real criminal." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryFraser ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theresaWright ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeWineGlasses ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bell-Rope Was Cut with a Knife from Above" ;
    ex:description "Upon returning to Abbey Grange, Holmes climbs the mantelpiece to examine the broken end of the bell-rope still attached to the wire above." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bell-rope was not torn down but was cut cleanly with a knife by someone standing on the mantelpiece, then the lower end was frayed to disguise the cut." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the rope broke three inches from the top rather than at the attachment point where a pulled rope would naturally snap. Examining it from the mantelpiece, he found the upper end was cut clean without any fraying, while the lower end visible from below had been deliberately frayed with a knife to make it appear naturally torn. A dust impression on the wall bracket showed where the man had knelt to reach the cord." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbeyGrangeBellRope ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeBellRope ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Killer Is a Single Powerful Man over Six Feet Tall" ;
    ex:description "After his examination of the dining room, Holmes describes the physical characteristics of the killer to Watson based on the evidence gathered." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killer is a single man, at least six foot three, immensely strong, agile as a squirrel, dexterous, and remarkably quick-witted." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The bent poker testified to enormous strength. Holmes could not reach the bell-rope from the bracket and fell short by at least three inches, so the man must be at least three inches taller than Holmes. The ability to spring up to the mantelpiece and use the bracket showed agility, while the entire staged burglary scene demonstrated quick-wittedness and ingenuity." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackCroker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangePoker, :abbeyGrangeBellRope ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lady Brackenstall Was Placed in the Chair After the Murder" ;
    ex:description "Holmes discovers a blood stain on the seat of the oaken chair to which Lady Brackenstall had reportedly been tied during the attack." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Brackenstall was not seated in the chair when the crime occurred but was placed in it afterward, as the blood on the seat proves." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "If Lady Brackenstall had been tied to the chair before Sir Eustace was struck down, as she claimed, there could be no blood on the seat beneath her. The presence of blood on the chair seat demonstrates that the blood splattered there during the killing and she was placed in the chair only afterward as part of the staged scene." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryFraser ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeOakenChair ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Killer Is a Sailor" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective summary to Captain Croker at Baker Street, Holmes explains how the bell-rope and the knots pointed specifically to a sailor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Only a sailor or acrobat could have climbed to the bell-rope from the bracket, and only a sailor could have tied the knots used to fasten the cord to the chair." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that reaching the bell-rope required the climbing ability of an acrobat or sailor. More conclusively, the knots used to tie the cord to the chair were distinctively nautical — only a sailor would have tied them. Since Lady Brackenstall had only been in contact with sailors on her voyage from Australia, and she was clearly trying to shield the man, it followed that she loved him and he was someone of her own social class from that voyage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackCroker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangeBellRope, :abbeyGrangeOakenChair ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Stolen Silver Was Discarded as a Blind" ;
    ex:description "After leaving Abbey Grange, Holmes notices the frozen pond with a hole in the ice and leaves a note for Hopkins suggesting the silver is there." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The stolen silver was taken not for profit but as a blind to support the burglary fiction, and was disposed of in the nearest convenient place — the pond." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that if the silver had been taken by persons who did not actually want it and merely took it to create the appearance of a burglary, they would naturally want to dispose of it quickly. The frozen pond with its single hole in the ice, directly in front of the French window exit, offered an obvious and tempting hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbeyGrangeStolenSilver ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangePond, :abbeyGrangeStolenSilver ;
    ex:confirmedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Captain Jack Croker as the Killer" ;
    ex:description "Holmes visits the Adelaide-Southampton shipping line office to trace the officers of the Rock of Gibraltar, the ship on which Mary Fraser traveled to England, and identifies the first officer who has since been promoted to captain." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killer is Captain Jack Croker, formerly first officer of the Rock of Gibraltar, the ship on which Lady Brackenstall traveled from Australia to England." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Having established the killer was a sailor who knew Lady Brackenstall from her voyage, Holmes traced the Adelaide-Southampton line — the route connecting South Australia with England. The passenger list confirmed Miss Fraser and her maid traveled on the Rock of Gibraltar in June 1895. The first officer at that time was Jack Croker, now promoted to captain and living at Sydenham — the same area where the Randall gang robbery had occurred, providing the cover story's source material." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackCroker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :rockOfGibraltar, :voyageOfRockOfGibraltar, :adelaideSouthamptonLine ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_hopkins_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins's Theory: The Randall Gang Committed the Burglary and Murder" ;
    ex:description "Upon Holmes's arrival at Abbey Grange, Inspector Hopkins confidently presents his theory that the crime was committed by the Randall gang, a known father-and-two-sons burglar team recently active in the area." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Randall gang — a father and two sons who had recently committed a burglary at Sydenham — broke into Abbey Grange, tied up Lady Brackenstall, and murdered Sir Eustace." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins identified the three intruders as the Randall gang based on Lady Brackenstall's description of an elderly bearded man accompanied by two younger hairless men, matching the known composition of the Randall gang. The gang had recently committed a robbery at Sydenham and had been seen and described, and the description of the intruders matched." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :randallGang ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sydenhamRobbery ;
    ex:refutedBy :arrestOfRandallsNewYork ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_05 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_abbeyGrange_hopkins_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins's Theory: The Silver Was Hidden in the Pond for Later Retrieval" ;
    ex:description "After the stolen silver is recovered from the pond based on Holmes's hint, Hopkins constructs his own explanation for why the burglars deposited the silver there." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The burglars hid the silver in the pond because it was early morning, people were on the roads, and they feared being seen carrying it — intending to return for it later." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins reasoned that the early hour meant people were beginning to appear on the roads, making it risky for the burglars to carry conspicuous silver plate. He concluded they sank it in the pond as a temporary hiding place, planning to return when the coast was clear to retrieve their haul." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbeyGrangeStolenSilver ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbeyGrangePond, :abbeyGrangeStolenSilver ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_abbeyGrange_holmes_10 ;
    ex:refutedBy :jackCroker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :abbeyGrangeDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_alexanderholder_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holder's Accusation: Arthur Stole the Beryls" ;
    ex:description "Upon finding Arthur holding the damaged coronet at two in the morning with three beryls missing, Alexander Holder concludes his son is a thief who broke the coronet and stole the gems." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Arthur broke the coronet and stole the three missing beryls." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holder found Arthur standing in the dressing-room at 2 AM holding the coronet with a corner missing. Arthur was known to be deeply in debt and had asked for money that very evening. The circumstantial evidence — motive, opportunity, and being caught with the damaged object — led Holder to the immediate conclusion of guilt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :berylCoronet ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_12 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Recognises a Distressed Client Approaching" ;
    ex:description "When Watson observes a frantic man running down Baker Street and assumes he is a madman, Holmes immediately recognises the man's behaviour as that of a potential client coming to consult him professionally." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The agitated man running down Baker Street is coming to consult Holmes professionally." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognised the symptoms of extreme distress combined with purposeful direction — the man was looking up at house numbers, indicating he sought a specific address rather than wandering aimlessly. Holmes's familiarity with the appearance of desperate clients led him to predict the man's destination." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alexanderHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Suggests Arthur Was Straightening the Coronet" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Holder's account, Holmes challenges the assumption of guilt by suggesting that Arthur, found holding the twisted coronet, may have been trying to straighten it rather than break it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Arthur may have been trying to straighten the damaged coronet rather than tearing it apart." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the remainder of the coronet was twisted. If Arthur were the thief, the twisting would be incidental to removal. But if he had recovered the coronet after someone else damaged it, the twisting would be something he would naturally try to repair before being discovered." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :berylCoronet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Arthur's Silence Suggests Innocence" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons about the significance of Arthur's refusal to explain himself, arguing that his silence is paradoxically more consistent with innocence than guilt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Arthur's refusal to explain himself suggests innocence rather than guilt, because a guilty man would invent a lie." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that if Arthur's purpose were innocent, his silence could be explained by anger or by protecting someone. If his purpose were guilty, he would have every reason to invent an exculpatory lie. The fact that he neither explained nor lied indicated he was concealing something for honourable reasons." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Dismisses the Police Theory About the Noise" ;
    ex:description "Holmes rejects the police theory that the sound which woke Holder from sleep was Arthur closing his bedroom door, calling it implausible." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The noise that woke Holder was not Arthur closing his bedroom door, as a man committing a felony would not slam a door loudly enough to wake the household." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes applied common sense: a person intent on committing a theft would take pains to be silent, not slam a door loudly enough to rouse a sleeping man. The noise must therefore have had another origin, pointing to events the police had not considered." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Demonstrates the Coronet Cannot Be Broken Silently by One Man" ;
    ex:description "At Fairbank, Holmes tests the coronet's strength by attempting to break off a matching corner, demonstrating that immense force is required and the act would produce a noise like a pistol shot." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The coronet could not have been broken silently by one ordinary man — it requires exceptional strength and produces a loud snapping noise." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes attempted to break the gold corner himself and found it extremely difficult despite his exceptional finger strength. He concluded that an ordinary man could not do it, and that the snapping would produce a loud report. Since Holder heard no such noise, the coronet must have been broken under different circumstances than Holder assumed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :berylCoronet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :stableLaneStruggle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Man at the Kitchen Door Has a Wooden Leg" ;
    ex:description "While examining the grounds at Fairbank, Holmes observes footprints near the kitchen door and deduces that Lucy Parr's visitor has a wooden leg, astonishing Mary Holder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Francis Prosper, the man who met Lucy Parr at the kitchen door, has a wooden leg." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that one set of footprints by the kitchen door left round impressions on one side rather than the normal outline of a shoe or boot, indicating a wooden peg leg. This identified the man as having a prosthetic limb." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :francisProsper ;
    ex:confirmedBy :maryHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reads the Kitchen Door Encounter from Tracks" ;
    ex:description "During his retrospective explanation, Holmes describes reading the snow tracks at the kitchen door to reconstruct the maid's encounter with her sweetheart, including her being disturbed and running back." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tracks at the kitchen door show a woman talked with a wooden-legged man, was suddenly disturbed and ran back to the door, while the man waited briefly then departed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the woman's return tracks showed deep toe impressions and light heel marks, indicating she ran back swiftly to the door. The wooden-legged man's tracks showed he waited a little after her departure before walking away. Holmes confirmed this matched the maid Lucy Parr and her sweetheart." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lucyParr ;
    ex:deductionSubject :francisProsper ;
    ex:confirmedBy :maryHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Two Sets of Tracks in the Stable Lane" ;
    ex:description "Examining the stable lane, Holmes finds two double lines of tracks — one from a booted man and one from a barefoot man — and determines the barefoot man passed after the booted one." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Two men were in the stable lane: one wearing boots and one barefoot, with the barefoot man (Arthur) having passed after the booted man." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified a double line of booted tracks and a second double line of barefoot tracks. The barefoot tread was marked in places over the depression of the boot prints, proving the barefoot man passed after the booted one. Given Holder's account that Arthur was found in bare feet, Holmes identified the barefoot tracks as Arthur's." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Struggle Occurred and the Booted Man Was Injured" ;
    ex:description "Following the tracks to the far end of the stable lane, Holmes finds evidence of a struggle and blood drops indicating the booted man was hurt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A struggle took place at the end of the stable lane, and the booted man was the one who was injured, as shown by blood drops along his retreat." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the snow at the far end of the lane was cut up as though there had been a struggle. A few drops of blood fell at the scene. Further drops of blood trailed along the booted man's retreat down the lane, proving it was the booted man — not the barefoot one — who had been hurt in the fight." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burnwellValet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Someone Passed Through the Hall Window" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examines the sill and framework of the hall window overlooking the stable lane with his magnifying lens and determines that someone climbed out and back in through it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Someone passed out through the hall window and returned through it, as evidenced by a wet footprint on the sill." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the window sill with his lens and could see that someone had passed out. He distinguished the outline of an instep where a wet foot had been placed in coming back in, confirming the window was used as an exit and entry point during the night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Crime from Physical Evidence" ;
    ex:description "Synthesising all the physical evidence from the stable lane and hall window, Holmes reconstructs the sequence of events: a man waited outside, someone brought the coronet from inside, Arthur witnessed it, pursued the thief, and struggled with him." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A man waited outside the hall window, someone from inside brought the coronet to him, Arthur witnessed and pursued the thief, and the two struggled over the coronet, causing it to break." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The booted tracks showed a man walking both ways and wearing the snow away while waiting by the window. The window sill showed someone passed out and back in. The barefoot tracks showed Arthur ran after the booted man. The disturbed snow and blood showed they fought, and neither alone could have broken the coronet — their combined tugging caused the damage. Arthur returned with the prize minus the fragment left in his opponent's grasp." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :berylCoronet ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :berylCoronet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mary Holder Brought the Coronet to the Window" ;
    ex:description "Using elimination and behavioural evidence, Holmes identifies Mary Holder as the person who took the coronet from the bureau and passed it through the window to the outside confederate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mary Holder was the one who took the coronet from the bureau and handed it through the hall window to her confederate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes eliminated Holder himself as the one who brought the coronet down, leaving only Mary or the maids. If a maid were responsible, Arthur had no reason to shield her by accepting arrest. Since Arthur loved his cousin Mary, he had an excellent motive to protect her by staying silent. Holmes further recalled that Mary was seen at the hall window earlier that evening and that she fainted upon seeing the damaged coronet — both behaviours consistent with guilty knowledge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryHolder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arthurHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Sir George Burnwell as the Outside Confederate" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deduces that Mary's confederate must be a lover and identifies Sir George Burnwell from the limited circle of visitors to Fairbank, given Burnwell's known reputation as a dangerous man with women." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sir George Burnwell was Mary Holder's lover and the man who waited outside the window, receiving the coronet and retaining the missing beryls." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The confederate had to be a lover, since only romantic attachment could outweigh Mary's love and gratitude for her uncle. Holder went out little and had a very limited social circle. Among the few visitors, Sir George Burnwell was a known man of evil reputation among women. He must have been the man in the boots who kept the missing gems, and even knowing Arthur had discovered him, he could feel safe because Arthur could not expose him without compromising Mary." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryHolder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burnwellValet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burnwellShoes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms Burnwell's Identity Through Undercover Investigation" ;
    ex:description "Disguised as a loafer, Holmes visits Sir George Burnwell's house, befriends his valet, learns Burnwell cut his head the previous night, and purchases Burnwell's cast-off shoes which exactly match the tracks at Streatham." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Burnwell's identity as the thief is confirmed by his valet reporting a head wound matching the struggle and by his shoes matching the bootprints in the stable lane." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes disguised himself and gained access to Burnwell's household through his valet. The valet confirmed Burnwell had cut his head the night before, consistent with Arthur striking him during the struggle. Holmes purchased a pair of Burnwell's discarded shoes for six shillings and journeyed back to Streatham, where they exactly fitted the booted tracks in the stable lane." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sirGeorgeBurnwell ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :burnwellShoes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burnwellValet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_berylCoronet_berylcoronetinspector_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Police Theory: The Noise Was Arthur Closing His Door" ;
    ex:description "The police investigating the case theorise that the sound which woke Alexander Holder from sleep was caused by Arthur closing his bedroom door as he went to steal the coronet." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The noise that woke Holder was Arthur closing his bedroom door." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The police attributed the sound to the most proximate source — Arthur's movement from his bedroom to the dressing-room. Since Arthur was found in the dressing-room, they assumed his departure from his own room created the noise that disturbed Holder's sleep." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :berylCoronetInspector ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurHolder ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_berylCoronet_holmes_04 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :berylCoronetDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Proves Extraordinary Strength Required to Harpoon a Man" ;
    ex:description "Before visiting the crime scene, Holmes spends a morning at Allardyce's butcher shop attempting to drive a harpoon through a pig carcass hung from a hook, establishing a baseline for the physical strength required to pin a man to the wall." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "No ordinary person could transfix a body with a harpoon in a single blow; the killer must possess extraordinary strength." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes attempted to drive the same type of steel harpoon through a dead pig carcass and found that by no exertion of his own considerable strength could he transfix it with a single blow. Since Peter Carey was pinned through the breast to the wall behind him, the killer must be far stronger and more practised with a harpoon than an average man." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :harpoonExperiment, :blackPeterHarpoon ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Tobacco Pouch Belongs to the Killer, Not Carey" ;
    ex:description "When Hopkins presents the seal-skin tobacco pouch found at the crime scene bearing the initials P.C., Holmes challenges the assumption that it belonged to Peter Carey, noting that Carey seldom smoked and no pipe was found in the cabin." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tobacco pouch with initials P.C. belongs to the murderer, not to Peter Carey, despite the matching initials." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Peter Carey smoked very little and no pipe was found in the cabin. A non-smoker would have no use for a tobacco pouch filled with strong ship's tobacco. The initials P.C. were a coincidence — they stood for Patrick Cairns, not Peter Carey. Holmes identified this as the starting-point of the investigation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cairnsTobaccoPouch ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cairnsTobaccoPouch ;
    ex:confirmedBy :patrickCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies C.P.R. as Canadian Pacific Railway" ;
    ex:description "When Hopkins presents the notebook found at the crime scene with the printed letters C.P.R. followed by lists of securities, Holmes immediately identifies C.P.R. as the Canadian Pacific Railway, correcting Hopkins's assumption that it was a client's initials." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letters C.P.R. in the notebook refer to the Canadian Pacific Railway, a stock exchange security, not a person's initials." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognised the abbreviation C.P.R. as the standard ticker designation for the Canadian Pacific Railway, a well-known stock exchange security. The notebook contained lists of securities from various countries including Argentine, Costa Rica, and San Paulo, confirming these were financial records, not a broker's client list." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:deductionSubject :canadianPacificRailway ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnNeligan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Blood-Stain Proves Notebook Dropped After Crime" ;
    ex:description "Examining the notebook's cover with his magnifying lens, Holmes identifies a discolouration as a blood-stain and reasons about its position relative to the floor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The blood-stain on the underside of the notebook proves it was dropped onto the bloody floor after the murder was committed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed a discolouration on the notebook cover which Hopkins confirmed was a blood-stain found on the side next to the floorboards. If the blood-stain was on the underside when the book was lying on the floor, the blood must already have been on the floor when the book was dropped, proving the book fell after the crime, not before." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:confirmedBy :patrickCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Significance of Untouched Brandy and Whisky" ;
    ex:description "During Hopkins's account, Holmes asks specifically whether whisky and brandy were available in the cabin. Learning that the tantalus was full and untouched while rum had been drunk, Holmes draws an inference about the killer's identity." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The fact that rum was consumed while brandy and whisky sat untouched indicates the killer was a seaman, not a landsman." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes asked whether spirits other than rum were present and learned the tantalus containing brandy and whisky was full — meaning neither had been drunk. The two men drank rum and water together despite having finer spirits available. Holmes reasoned that few landsmen would choose rum over brandy or whisky, so the killer's preference for rum pointed to a seaman's habits." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :careyRumBottle, :careyTantalus ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Someone Attempted to Force Entry to the Cabin" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at the cabin with Hopkins and Watson, Holmes examines the lock and window and identifies signs of attempted forced entry." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Someone tried to force both the lock and the window of the cabin using a small penknife but failed to gain entry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the lock and observed fresh scratches showing white through the paint, indicating recent tampering. The window bore similar marks. From the nature of the marks Holmes deduced a very small penknife was used — the tool of someone unprepared for the task, and therefore a very poor burglar." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnNeligan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :peterCareyCabin ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cabinAmbush ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts the Intruder Will Return" ;
    ex:description "After observing the failed forced entry, Holmes predicts the intruder will come back the following night with better tools, calling it good fortune for their investigation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person who failed to enter the cabin will return the next night with a more effective tool." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the intruder came expecting the door to be open and was equipped only with a small penknife, which proved inadequate. Since the intruder clearly had unfinished business inside the cabin and had already invested effort in the attempt, Holmes predicted he would return with a proper tool, giving them the opportunity to set an ambush." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnNeligan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :peterCareyCabin ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cabinAmbush ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Something Was Taken From the Shelf" ;
    ex:description "During his two-hour examination of the cabin interior, Holmes notices a discrepancy in the dust pattern on a shelf and concludes an object has been removed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "An object — possibly a book or box — has been removed from the cabin shelf since the crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that one corner of the shelf had less dust than the surrounding area, indicating that an object had rested there until recently. The shape of the dust-free area suggested it may have been a book lying on its side or a box. Since Hopkins confirmed nothing had been moved by the police, someone else had taken it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neliganTinBox ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :peterCareyCabin ;
    ex:confirmedBy :patrickCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Refutes Hopkins's Theory That Neligan Is the Killer" ;
    ex:description "After Hopkins presents his complete case against young Neligan at breakfast at Baker Street, Holmes systematically demolishes the theory by citing the harpoon experiment and other evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Neligan could not have killed Peter Carey — he lacks the physical strength to drive a harpoon through a man and does not match the profile of the killer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes cited his butcher shop experiment proving the blow required enormous strength and a practised arm. The anaemic, frail Neligan was physically incapable of such an assault. Furthermore, the shadow seen on the blind two nights before was of a bearded man — not Neligan. And it was implausible that a slight young gentleman would drink rum and water with Black Peter in the dead of night. The profile demanded a different and more formidable person." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnNeligan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :harpoonExperiment, :slaterSighting ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Killer Is a Seaman and Former Whaler" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation after Cairns's capture, Holmes reveals the converging lines of evidence that pointed to the killer being a professional seaman with whaling experience." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killer of Peter Carey was a seaman, specifically a whaler, as indicated by the extraordinary strength, harpoon skill, preference for rum, and the seal-skin tobacco pouch with coarse tobacco." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes enumerated the evidence: the amazing strength required to drive the harpoon through a man and into the wall, the professional skill in its use, the rum and water drunk in preference to available brandy and whisky, and the seal-skin tobacco pouch filled with coarse ship's tobacco. All of these pointed to a seaman, and specifically one who had been a whaler. The initials P.C. on the pouch were a coincidence, as Carey seldom smoked and owned no pipe." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackPeterHarpoon, :careyRumBottle, :cairnsTobaccoPouch, :careyTantalus ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Killer Sailed on the Sea Unicorn" ;
    ex:description "Having established the killer was a whaler, Holmes narrows the search to the crew of the Sea Unicorn, Peter Carey's own vessel." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killer must have sailed with Peter Carey on the Sea Unicorn, as Carey sailed in no other ship." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Once Holmes was certain the killer was a seaman who had known Black Peter personally, he reasoned that the man must have served under Carey. Since Carey had commanded only the Sea Unicorn, the killer must have been one of her crew. Holmes spent three days wiring to Dundee to ascertain the complete crew list from 1883." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionSubject :seaUnicorn ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :seaUnicorn ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Patrick Cairns as the Killer" ;
    ex:description "After obtaining the Sea Unicorn crew list from Dundee, Holmes discovers Patrick Cairns among the harpooners and devises a trap to lure him to Baker Street under the guise of a fictitious Arctic expedition." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Patrick Cairns, a harpooner from the Sea Unicorn, is the killer of Peter Carey." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found the name Patrick Cairns among the harpooners of the Sea Unicorn in 1883. He argued the man was probably in London and would desire to leave the country. Holmes therefore placed advertisements for harpooners willing to serve under Captain Basil on an Arctic expedition, which brought Cairns directly to Baker Street where Holmes arrested him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :seaUnicorn ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_stanleyhopkins_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins's Theory: The Tobacco Pouch Belonged to Peter Carey" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks about the tobacco pouch found at the crime scene, Hopkins dismisses it as belonging to the victim, citing the matching initials and the seal-skin material." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tobacco pouch was Peter Carey's own property, as the initials P.C. were inside it and it was made of seal-skin, consistent with Carey being an old sealer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins noted that the initials P.C. were inside the pouch flap, matching Peter Carey's name. The pouch was made of seal-skin, and Carey had been a seal and whale fisher. Hopkins concluded the pouch naturally belonged to the dead man and dismissed it as a lead." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cairnsTobaccoPouch ;
    ex:deductionSubject :peterCarey ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cairnsTobaccoPouch ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blackPeter_holmes_02 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_stanleyhopkins_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins's Theory: J.H.N. Are a Broker's Initials" ;
    ex:description "Examining the notebook found at the crime scene, Hopkins interprets the initials J.H.N. on the first page and C.P.R. on the second as the initials of a stockbroker and his client respectively." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The initials J.H.N. belong to a stockbroker and C.P.R. represents his client." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins found a notebook with J.H.N. and the date 1883 on the first page, followed by C.P.R. and lists of securities. He interpreted the format as a broker's record: J.H.N. being the broker's initials and C.P.R. the initials of a client. He searched the 1883 Stock Exchange lists for matching brokers but found none." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :neliganNotebook ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blackPeter_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_stanleyhopkins_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Deduces the Crime Was Committed in a Moment of Fury" ;
    ex:description "Based on the weapon being snatched from a rack on the wall rather than brought to the scene, Hopkins infers the murder was unpremeditated." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murder was committed in a sudden moment of fury, as the harpoon was seized from a wall rack rather than brought by the killer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins observed that the harpoon used to kill Carey was one of three mounted on a wall rack in the cabin, with a vacant place where it had been snatched. Since the weapon was already present in the room rather than brought by the attacker, Hopkins concluded the killing was an impulsive act of fury rather than a premeditated murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderOfPeterCarey ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackPeterHarpoon ;
    ex:confirmedBy :patrickCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_stanleyhopkins_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Deduces Carey Had an Appointment With the Murderer" ;
    ex:description "Hopkins infers from Carey being fully dressed at two in the morning, and the presence of two dirty glasses and a rum bottle, that the victim was expecting a visitor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Peter Carey had a late-night appointment with his murderer, as evidenced by his being fully dressed at 2 AM and the two drinking glasses." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The crime was committed at approximately two in the morning, yet Peter Carey was fully dressed rather than in sleeping clothes. A bottle of rum and two dirty glasses stood on the table, indicating he had been drinking with a companion. Taken together, these facts indicated Carey had an arranged meeting with the person who killed him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :peterCarey ;
    ex:deductionSubject :patrickCairns ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :careyRumBottle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :patrickCairns ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_stanleyhopkins_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins's Theory: Neligan Murdered Peter Carey" ;
    ex:description "After Neligan's arrest at the cabin ambush, Hopkins constructs a comprehensive theory identifying Neligan as the killer, which he presents confidently to Holmes at breakfast the following morning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Neligan murdered Peter Carey: he arrived at the hotel on the day of the crime, went to the cabin, quarrelled with Carey over the securities, killed him with the harpoon, and fled, dropping the notebook." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hopkins established that Neligan arrived at the Brambletye Hotel on the very day of the murder, had a ground-floor room enabling easy exit, and possessed clear motive regarding his father's stolen securities. The notebook bearing Neligan's initials J.H.N. was found blood-stained at the crime scene. Hopkins theorised Neligan went to the cabin to confront Carey about the securities, quarrelled with him, seized the harpoon and killed him, then fled in horror, dropping the notebook. His subsequent return to the cabin to search the log-books was interpreted as guilty knowledge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnNeligan ;
    ex:deductionSubject :peterCarey ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :neliganNotebook, :arrestOfNeligan ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blackPeter_holmes_09 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blackPeter_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Suggests the Lock Scratches Are From a Curious Villager" ;
    ex:description "Upon discovering the fresh scratches on the cabin lock, Watson offers the suggestion that a curious person from the village may be responsible." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The lock scratches were made by a curious villager." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed the fresh marks on the cabin lock and suggested the most innocent explanation — that someone from the village, motivated by curiosity about the murder scene, had attempted to enter the cabin." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :peterCareyCabin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :peterCareyCabin ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blackPeter_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blackPeterDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_jamesdodd_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Dodd's Theory: Godfrey Involved in Criminal Activity" ;
    ex:description "After the butler Ralph's anguished outburst that he wished Godfrey were dead, Dodd attempts to interpret the mystery on his own, arriving at a conclusion that proves entirely wrong." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey has become involved in criminal or disreputable activity, and his father has sent him away to protect the family honour." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Dodd interpreted Ralph's words as bearing only one meaning: that Godfrey had become involved in some criminal or disreputable transaction. He reasoned that the stern Colonel had sent his son away and hidden him from the world to prevent scandal, noting that Godfrey was reckless and easily influenced." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :jamesDodd ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_05 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Dodd Has Come From South Africa" ;
    ex:description "During their first meeting at 221B Baker Street in January 1903, Holmes immediately deduces that his new client James M. Dodd has recently returned from South Africa, impressing Dodd before the consultation has even begun." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James M. Dodd has come from South Africa." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Dodd's virile appearance and deep tan, noting that such coloring could never have been produced by an English sun, making a South African origin the clear conclusion." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesDodd ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesDodd ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Dodd Served in the Imperial Yeomanry" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his rapid-fire observations upon meeting Dodd, Holmes identifies his specific military branch as the Imperial Yeomanry rather than a regular army unit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dodd served in the Imperial Yeomanry, not a regular regiment." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted Dodd's short beard, which indicated he was not a regular soldier subject to military grooming regulations, and his cut as that of a riding-man, consistent with a cavalry volunteer unit." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesDodd ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesDodd ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Dodd Served in the Middlesex Corps" ;
    ex:description "Holmes narrows his identification of Dodd's military service to the specific regiment, the Middlesex Corps, astonishing his client completely." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dodd served in the Middlesex Corps of the Imperial Yeomanry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Dodd's visiting card identified him as a stockbroker from Throgmorton Street in London. Holmes reasoned that a City stockbroker volunteering for the Yeomanry would naturally join the Middlesex Corps, the regiment associated with that area." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesDodd ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesDodd ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Something Urgent Occurred at Tuxbury Old Park" ;
    ex:description "Before Dodd has explained his problem, Holmes identifies the location connected to his troubles, further demonstrating his observational method to the startled client." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Something sudden and important has occurred at Tuxbury Old Park." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Dodd's letter bore the heading of Tuxbury Old Park, and since he had fixed his appointment in very pressing terms, Holmes concluded that something sudden and important had happened at that location." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tuxburyOldPark ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesDodd ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates the Criminal Explanation for Godfrey's Seclusion" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation to the assembled household, Holmes describes how he systematically eliminated the first of three possible explanations for Godfrey Emsworth's concealment in the outhouse." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey is not being hidden because of involvement in crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes verified that no unsolved crime had been reported from the Tuxbury district. Furthermore, if Godfrey had committed an undiscovered crime, the family's rational interest would be to send him abroad rather than conceal him at home, making the criminal hypothesis untenable." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:confirmedBy :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates the Insanity Explanation for Godfrey's Seclusion" ;
    ex:description "Holmes describes how the second hypothesis — that Godfrey was being kept hidden due to madness — was tested and found wanting, despite some initially suggestive evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey is not being concealed because of insanity." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The presence of a keeper in the outhouse and the locked door initially suggested constraint consistent with insanity. However, the constraint was not severe, as Godfrey was able to roam at night and visit Dodd's window. Moreover, keeping a lunatic on private premises is legal with a qualified attendant and proper notification, so the family's desperate secrecy was disproportionate and inexplicable under the insanity theory." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:confirmedBy :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Concludes Godfrey Has Leprosy" ;
    ex:description "Having eliminated crime and insanity, Holmes arrives at his third and final hypothesis — that Godfrey Emsworth contracted leprosy in South Africa — which explains every observed fact, though the specific diagnosis ultimately proves incorrect." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey Emsworth contracted leprosy in South Africa and is being secretly segregated to avoid mandatory institutional isolation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Leprosy is not uncommon in South Africa, where Godfrey served. The bleaching of his skin is a common result of the disease. Great secrecy would be needed to prevent the authorities from enforcing segregation. A devoted medical man could be paid to attend him privately, and there was no reason he could not be allowed freedom after dark. Every detail of the case — the concealment, the paid surgeon, the night wandering, the blanched appearance — fit this diagnosis." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :godfreyWindowSighting ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_blanchedSoldier_saunders_01 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms Disease Hypothesis From Ralph's Disinfectant Gloves" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at Tuxbury Old Park, Holmes observes a critical piece of physical evidence that removes his last doubts about the disease hypothesis before confronting Colonel Emsworth." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Ralph the butler's leather gloves are impregnated with disinfectant, confirming that the household is managing a contagious disease." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noticed Ralph hastily removing brown leather gloves when the visitors arrived. Using a ruse of dropping his hat on the hall-table, Holmes brought his nose close to the gloves and detected a curious tarry odour of disinfectant, indicating precautions against contagion consistent with the disease hypothesis." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ralphButler ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :ralphDisinfectantGloves ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blanchedSoldier_sirjamessaunders_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Saunders Diagnoses Ichthyosis, Not Leprosy" ;
    ex:description "The eminent dermatologist Sir James Saunders, brought by Holmes as a specialist consultant, examines Godfrey Emsworth and delivers the correct diagnosis, overturning the assumption of leprosy that had driven the entire case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey Emsworth has pseudo-leprosy or ichthyosis, a scale-like skin condition that is unsightly and obstinate but possibly curable and certainly not contagious." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Sir James Saunders examined Godfrey and identified the condition as a well-marked case of ichthyosis rather than true leprosy. He speculated that the psychological apprehension from Godfrey's exposure to leprosy contagion may have produced physical symptoms simulating the feared disease." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sirJamesSaunders ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyEmsworth ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blanchedSoldierDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Is Highly Intellectual" ;
    ex:description "While examining the battered felt hat brought by Peterson the commissionaire, Holmes delivers a series of deductions about its unknown owner to Watson at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner is highly intellectual, based on the unusually large size of the hat." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes placed the hat on his own head and it came right over his forehead to the bridge of his nose, demonstrating the owner's exceptionally large head. Holmes reasoned that a man with so large a brain must have something in it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Was Formerly Well-to-Do" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his examination of the hat at 221B, Holmes infers the owner's financial decline from the quality and age of the hat." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner was fairly well-to-do within the last three years but has since fallen upon evil days." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The hat was three years old, of the very best quality with a band of ribbed silk and excellent lining. Since the owner could afford so expensive a hat three years ago but has had no replacement since, he has assuredly gone down in the world." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Suffers Moral Retrogression From Drink" ;
    ex:description "Holmes interprets the hat-securer's broken elastic as evidence of the owner's declining foresight and probable alcoholism." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner had foresight formerly but has undergone moral retrogression, probably due to drink." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The hat-securer disc and loop showed the owner once had the foresight to order this precaution against wind, but the broken elastic had never been replaced, indicating diminished foresight. Combined with the decline in fortunes, this pointed to some evil influence, probably drink, at work upon him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner's Wife Has Ceased to Love Him" ;
    ex:description "Holmes infers the state of the owner's marriage from the neglected condition of the hat and the goose's gift tag." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner's wife has ceased to love him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The hat had not been brushed for weeks, and Holmes reasoned that when a wife allows her husband to go out in such a state, she has lost affection for him. The card on the goose reading 'For Mrs. Henry Baker' confirmed the man was married and bringing a peace-offering home." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Is Middle-Aged With Recently Cut Grizzled Hair" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examines the hat lining under his lens and deduces several physical characteristics of the owner." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner is middle-aged with grizzled hair that has been recently cut, and he uses lime-cream." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The lens disclosed a large number of hair-ends in the lower lining, clean cut by barber's scissors, which appeared adhesive with a distinct odour of lime-cream. The grizzled colour indicated middle age." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Is Sedentary and Out of Training" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reads the dust and moisture marks on the hat to determine the owner's lifestyle and physical condition." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner leads a sedentary life, goes out little, and is entirely out of training." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The dust on the hat was the fluffy brown dust of the house rather than the gritty grey dust of the street, showing the hat was hung up indoors most of the time. Marks of moisture on the inside proved the wearer perspired very freely, indicating poor physical fitness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Has No Gas Laid On in His House" ;
    ex:description "Holmes notes multiple tallow stains on the hat and infers the owner's domestic lighting arrangements." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner very probably does not have gas laid on in his house and uses tallow candles." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed no fewer than five tallow stains on the hat. One or two might come by chance, but five indicated frequent contact with burning tallow, suggesting the owner walks upstairs at night with his hat in one hand and a guttering candle in the other, as tallow stains never come from a gas-jet." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hat Owner Retains Some Self-Respect" ;
    ex:description "Holmes finds evidence of the owner's attempt to maintain appearances despite his declining circumstances." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hat's owner has not entirely lost his self-respect despite his decline." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The owner had endeavoured to conceal some of the stains upon the felt by daubing them with ink, which Holmes interpreted as a sign that he retained some degree of self-respect." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerHat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Henry Baker Is Innocent of the Carbuncle Theft" ;
    ex:description "After Henry Baker visits 221B to reclaim his hat and goose, Holmes tests his knowledge of the carbuncle by offering the remains of the original bird." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Henry Baker is an absolutely innocent man who knows nothing about the blue carbuncle hidden in his goose." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes offered Baker the feathers, legs, crop, and other remains of the original goose. Baker laughed and declined with total indifference, showing no interest in the crop where the carbuncle had been found. His complete lack of concern confirmed he had no knowledge of the stone's presence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :henryBakerGoose ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryBaker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Breckinridge Can Be Drawn Out by a Wager" ;
    ex:description "After extracting the supplier information from Breckinridge by pretending to lose a bet, Holmes explains his reading of the salesman's character to Watson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Breckinridge is a betting man who can be manipulated into revealing information through a wager rather than direct questioning." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Breckinridge's style of side-whiskers and the Pink 'un sporting paper protruding from his pocket, concluding that such a man could always be drawn out by a bet. The stratagem of pretending to wager that the geese were country-bred provoked Breckinridge into revealing his supplier records." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :breckinridge ;
    ex:confirmedBy :breckinridge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Stranger as James Ryder" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes accosts the man who had been arguing with Breckinridge about the geese, the man gives the alias John Robinson, but Holmes penetrates the deception and identifies him." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The man calling himself John Robinson is actually James Ryder, head attendant at the Hotel Cosmopolitan." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had overheard the man's desperate inquiries about the geese sold to the Alpha Inn and recognised him as connected to the carbuncle case. When the man offered the alias John Robinson, Holmes detected the sidelong glance of deception and insisted on the real name, then confirmed the identification by naming Ryder's position at the Hotel Cosmopolitan." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesRyder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesRyder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Specific Goose Ryder Seeks" ;
    ex:description "At 221B Baker Street, Holmes tells Ryder the precise description of the goose he has been searching for, demonstrating his knowledge of the case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Ryder is interested in one specific goose: a white bird with a black bar across the tail." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes traced the supply chain from Henry Baker's goose club at the Alpha Inn back through Windigate, Breckinridge, and Mrs. Oakshott, and deduced that Ryder was searching not for geese in general but for one particular bird identifiable by its markings." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesRyder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :breckinridgeAccountBooks ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesRyder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_blueCarbuncle_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Entire Carbuncle Theft and Concealment" ;
    ex:description "Holmes presents his complete reconstruction of the crime to Ryder at 221B, detailing how the theft was planned, executed, and how the carbuncle came to be inside the goose." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Ryder learned of the carbuncle from Catherine Cusack, conspired with her to frame John Horner, stole the gem, and concealed it inside a goose at his sister Mrs. Oakshott's house." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assembled the full chain: Catherine Cusack, the Countess's maid, told Ryder about the carbuncle. Ryder and Cusack manufactured a pretext to get Horner, a plumber with a prior conviction, into the Countess's room. After Horner left, Ryder rifled the jewel-case, raised the alarm, and had the innocent Horner arrested. Ryder then hid the stone in a goose at his sister's to transport it safely to his fence Maudsley." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesRyder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnHorner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :catherineCusack ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blueCarbuncle, :henryBakerGoose ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesRyder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :blueCarbuncleDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson's Bedroom Window Position" ;
    ex:description "On the train to Herefordshire, Holmes demonstrates his observational method by deducing that Watson's bedroom window is on the right-hand side of the room." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson's bedroom window is on the right-hand side, based on his uneven shaving pattern." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Watson's shaving becomes less complete on the left side of his face, indicating that side receives less natural light. Since Watson shaves by sunlight and is a man of military neatness who would not accept an uneven result in equal lighting, the window must be on his right." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets James McCarthy's Arrest Reaction as Evidence of Innocence" ;
    ex:description "While reviewing the case on the train, Holmes analyzes James McCarthy's response to being arrested and his remark that it was 'no more than his deserts.'" ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James McCarthy's frank acceptance of arrest and self-reproachful remark indicate innocence rather than guilt." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasons that an innocent man would naturally recognize the damning circumstances and not feign surprise, while a guilty schemer would more likely perform surprise or indignation. James's remark about his deserts reflects genuine self-reproach for having quarreled with his father on the day of the murder, not a confession of guilt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :jamesMcCarthyArrest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces James McCarthy's Story Is True" ;
    ex:description "On the train, Holmes argues that James's account should be presumed true because its oddest elements — the dying reference to a rat and the vanishing cloth — are too outré to have been invented by a guilty man who could not even fabricate a plausible cause for the quarrel." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James McCarthy's testimony is credible because its strangest details are too bizarre to be fabricated by someone who lacked the imagination to invent a sympathetic motive for the quarrel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observes that critics simultaneously fault James for having too little imagination to invent a cause of quarrel that would win jury sympathy, yet too much imagination for concocting the dying reference to a rat and the vanishing cloth. This contradiction indicates the strange details are genuine recollections, not inventions." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :boscombeValleyInquest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the 'Cooee' Was Meant for Someone Other Than James" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies two crucial points in James McCarthy's testimony: the 'Cooee' cry and the dying reference to a rat. He analyzes the 'Cooee' first, noting it was uttered before the elder McCarthy knew his son had returned from Bristol." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Charles McCarthy's cry of 'Cooee' was not meant for his son but for another person with whom he had an appointment at the pool." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The son was supposed to be in Bristol, and the father did not know he had returned. The 'Cooee' was uttered before seeing James, so it must have been directed at whoever McCarthy had arranged to meet at Boscombe Pool." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :boscombeValleyInquest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McCarthy's Appointee Was Australian" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis of the 'Cooee' cry, Holmes identifies it as a distinctly Australian signal, narrowing the pool of suspects." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person Charles McCarthy expected to meet at Boscombe Pool had been in Australia, since 'Cooee' is a distinctly Australian cry used between Australians." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "'Cooee' is a call used specifically between Australians. Since McCarthy used it to summon the person he was meeting, there is a strong presumption that this person had been in Australia." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McCarthy's Dying Word Was 'Ballarat'" ;
    ex:description "At the hotel, Holmes reveals a map of the Colony of Victoria and demonstrates that the dying man's mumbled word, of which his son caught only 'a rat,' was actually the final syllables of 'Ballarat' — the Australian gold-mining town." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Charles McCarthy's dying utterance was not 'a rat' but 'Ballarat,' an attempt to name his murderer's place of origin." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes obtained a map of Victoria and showed that covering the first three letters of 'BALLARAT' yields 'ARAT.' The dying man was trying to utter the full name but his son only caught the last two syllables. McCarthy was attempting to identify his killer as someone connected to Ballarat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McCarthy Was Blackmailing Turner" ;
    ex:description "In the carriage to Hatherley Farm, Holmes questions Lestrade about Turner's generosity to McCarthy and points out the singular presumption of a dependent tenant demanding his son marry the landlord's heiress." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McCarthy's cocksure manner in pressing for a marriage between James and Alice Turner, despite being financially dependent on Turner and despite Turner's opposition, implies McCarthy held some power over Turner — a blackmail relationship." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "McCarthy had little of his own and was under heavy obligations to Turner, yet spoke of the marriage as a foregone conclusion. Turner himself was averse to it. The only explanation for such confident presumption by a dependant against his benefactor's wishes is that McCarthy possessed some hold over Turner." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnTurner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reads James McCarthy's Footprints as Corroborating His Story" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene near Boscombe Pool, Holmes examines three separate tracks made by James McCarthy's feet and finds they corroborate the young man's account." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James McCarthy's footprints confirm his testimony: he walked to the pool twice and ran swiftly once, consistent with running back after hearing his father's cry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified three tracks by James's feet. In two, the soles and heels were evenly marked, indicating walking. In the third, the soles were deeply impressed and the heels barely visible, indicating a swift run — consistent with James running when he saw his father on the ground." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Murder Weapon as the Jagged Stone" ;
    ex:description "Holmes finds a jagged stone lying among the moss near the crime scene and identifies it as the weapon used to kill Charles McCarthy." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A jagged stone found at the scene was the murder weapon, not the butt of James McCarthy's gun." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Grass was growing under the stone, indicating it had only been placed there recently. There was no sign of where it had been taken from originally. Its shape corresponded to the injuries described in the surgeon's deposition, and there was no sign of any other weapon." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderStone ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderStone ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Murderer's Physical Profile from Footprints and Evidence" ;
    ex:description "After examining the ground at Boscombe Pool, Holmes announces a detailed physical description of the murderer to Lestrade: a tall man, left-handed, who limps with his right leg, wears thick-soled shooting-boots and a grey cloak, smokes Indian cigars with a cigar-holder, and carries a blunt pen-knife." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderer is a tall, left-handed man who limps with his right leg, wears thick-soled shooting-boots and a grey cloak, smokes Indian cigars using a cigar-holder, and carries a blunt pen-knife." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Height was judged from stride length. The right footprint was always less distinct than the left, indicating a limp on the right leg. The boots left unusual square-toed impressions. The blow struck from behind landed on the left side of the skull, indicating a left-handed assailant. Cigar ash found behind a beech tree was identified as Indian cigar rolled in Rotterdam; the cigar end had not been in the smoker's mouth, indicating a holder; the tip was cut rather than bitten, but the cut was uneven, indicating a blunt pen-knife." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnTurner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderStone, :indianCigar, :greyCloak ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Murderer Returned for the Grey Cloak" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene, Holmes traces the unusual square-toed footprints and finds they come, go, and then return — deducing the murderer came back for the grey cloak that James McCarthy glimpsed on the ground." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderer fled after the killing but returned to retrieve the grey cloak he had dropped, consistent with James McCarthy's account of a vanishing grey garment." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes traced three sets of the same unusual square-toed footprints at the scene: arriving, departing, and returning. The return trip corresponded with James's testimony that he glimpsed something grey on the ground which disappeared while his back was turned. The murderer returned to collect the dropped garment." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :greyCloak ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :greyCloak ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Murderer Was Local to the District" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that the murderer must have been someone familiar with the area, since Boscombe Pool can only be reached through Hatherley Farm or Turner's estate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderer was someone at home in the district, as the pool is accessible only through the farm or the estate where strangers would be noticed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Boscombe Pool can only be approached by way of Hatherley Farm or the Turner estate. A stranger wandering through either property would attract attention. Therefore the person who met McCarthy at the pool was familiar with the area and its access routes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnTurner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :boscombePool ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies John Turner as the Murderer" ;
    ex:description "At the hotel, Holmes synthesizes all his findings — an Australian from Ballarat, familiar with the district, possessing a grey cloak, tall, left-handed, and limping — and identifies John Turner as the only person in the neighbourhood who fits every criterion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderer of Charles McCarthy is John Turner, the wealthy landowner of the Boscombe Valley estate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes narrowed the suspect to an Australian from Ballarat who wore a grey cloak, was tall, left-handed, limped with the right leg, and was familiar with the district. In a sparsely populated neighbourhood, only one person could match all these criteria: John Turner, the ex-Australian landowner whose estate bordered the crime scene." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnTurner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderStone, :indianCigar, :greyCloak ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: James McCarthy Murdered His Father" ;
    ex:description "Lestrade declares the case plain as a pikestaff and states his firm belief that Charles McCarthy was killed by his son James, dismissing all alternative theories." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James McCarthy killed his father Charles McCarthy, and all theories to the contrary are unfounded." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade bases his conclusion on the accumulation of circumstantial evidence: James was seen following his father toward the pool, witnesses observed a violent quarrel, James was found with blood on his hands and no other suspects were apparent. Lestrade considers the case self-evident and strengthened by further investigation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :boscombeValleyInquest ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_boscombeValley_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_boscombeValley_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Blow Was Struck from Behind" ;
    ex:description "Alone at the hotel, Watson reads the surgeon's deposition from the inquest and analyzes the nature of the head injuries to determine the direction of the blow." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The fatal blow was struck from behind, based on damage to the posterior parietal and occipital bones." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The surgeon's report stated that the posterior third of the left parietal bone and the left half of the occipital bone were shattered. Watson marked the corresponding spot on his own head and recognized that such injuries to the back of the skull must have been inflicted from behind, which somewhat favored the accused since he was seen quarreling face-to-face with his father." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesMcCarthy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :boscombeValleyInquest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :turnerConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :boscombeValleyMysteryDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mycroft's Visit Signals an Extraordinary Crisis" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes receives a telegram announcing Mycroft's imminent visit to Baker Street, he immediately recognizes the extraordinary nature of the event, comparing it to a tram-car appearing on a country lane." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mycroft's unprecedented break from his fixed routine of Pall Mall lodgings, the Diogenes Club, and Whitehall indicates a crisis of the highest magnitude." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes knows Mycroft has visited Baker Street only once before and never deviates from his habitual orbit. The fact that Mycroft is coming in person, rather than sending a message or summoning Sherlock to Whitehall, indicates the matter is too urgent and too sensitive for ordinary channels." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Links West's Government Employment and Technical Papers to Mycroft's Concern" ;
    ex:description "As Watson reads the newspaper account of Cadogan West's death, Holmes seizes upon the combination of government employment at Woolwich Arsenal and the technical papers found on the body, connecting them to Mycroft's telegram." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The chain of government employment, Woolwich Arsenal, and technical papers explains why Mycroft Holmes is personally involved in the Cadogan West case." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assembles the facts sequentially: Cadogan West was a government clerk at Woolwich Arsenal, and technical papers were found on his body. Since Mycroft's role involves coordinating sensitive government intelligence, these details explain why the case has reached Mycroft's attention and why he considers it urgent enough to break his routine." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brucePartingtonPlans ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Missing Railway Ticket Is Significant" ;
    ex:description "While reviewing the facts of the case with Watson before Mycroft's arrival, Holmes notes with interest that no railway ticket was found on Cadogan West's body." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The absence of a railway ticket on West's body is anomalous because Metropolitan train platforms require a ticket for access, suggesting the ticket was removed to conceal West's origin station or that he never entered the train normally." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observes that it is not possible to reach the platform of a Metropolitan train without exhibiting a ticket. Since West's body was found on the line, he presumably had a ticket at some point. Its absence suggests either it was deliberately taken from him to conceal his station of origin, or he dropped it in the carriage, making the missing ticket a point of curious investigative interest." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_brucePartington_holmes_04 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces West's Body Was on the Roof of the Train" ;
    ex:description "At Aldgate Station, Holmes examines where the body was found and notices the railway points and curve. During the cab ride to Woolwich, he presents his deduction to Watson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Cadogan West's body was transported on the roof of a train carriage and fell off when the train jolted over the points near Aldgate Station." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the body was found at the exact point where the train pitches and sways as it rounds the points — the place where an object on the roof would be dislodged, but which would not affect anything inside the carriages. Combined with the absence of blood on the line despite a significant head wound, and the missing ticket, all facts converge on the body having been on the roof rather than inside the train." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :aldgateStation ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryOfObersteinHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Speculates Sir James Walter's Death May Have Been Suicide" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning that Sir James Walter has died suddenly, Holmes speculates in the cab about whether the death was natural or self-inflicted." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sir James Walter may have killed himself out of self-reproach for neglected duty in safeguarding the Bruce-Partington plans." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes notes the unexpected timing of Sir James's death, coinciding with the theft scandal, and considers whether it indicates a guilty conscience over his failure to adequately protect the plans under his care, rather than a natural death from shock." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sirJamesWalter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deathOfSirJamesWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Notes Surface Evidence Incriminates Cadogan West" ;
    ex:description "After interviewing Violet Westbury about her fiancé's recent behavior, Holmes observes in the cab that the evidence has grown blacker against West." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "West's upcoming marriage provides a financial motive, his remarks to Violet show he was aware of the plans' value, and he nearly made her an accomplice by discussing the possibility of treason." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assembles the interview evidence: West's coming marriage gave him a motive for needing money, the idea of selling state secrets was already in his mind since he spoke of foreign spies paying for such plans, and he came close to telling Violet his intentions. All of this builds a circumstantial case for West's guilt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :violetWestbury ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_brucePartington_holmes_09 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Absence of Duplicate Keys Undermines the Case Against West" ;
    ex:description "During the interview with Sidney Johnson at the Woolwich Arsenal office, Holmes raises logical objections to the assumption of West's guilt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "If West stole the plans, he must have had duplicate keys to the building, office, and safe, yet none were found on his body; furthermore, it is illogical that a clerk with technical knowledge would take the originals rather than make copies." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes establishes that three keys are needed to reach the plans: outer door, office, and safe. Only Sir James Walter held all three, and Johnson held only the safe key. If West were the thief, he would need duplicates, but none were found on his body. Additionally, a clerk with technical knowledge could have copied the plans rather than risk taking the irreplaceable originals." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sidneyJohnson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Woolwich Office Window Evidence" ;
    ex:description "After the interview with Sidney Johnson, Holmes examines the exterior of the Woolwich Arsenal office and discovers that the iron shutters do not fully close and the laurel bush outside shows signs of disturbance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The damaged laurel bush and incompletely closing window shutters at the Woolwich office indicate someone observed the interior of the office from outside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the iron shutters and found they hardly met in the centre, making it possible for someone outside to see into the room. The laurel bush beneath the window had twisted and snapped branches, and there were dim marks on the earth beneath, suggesting someone had stood there watching the office. Though degraded by three days' delay, the indications pointed to an outside observer." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :woolwichArsenal ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs West as an Innocent Patriot Who Followed the Thief" ;
    ex:description "During a half-hour of silent reflection after gathering evidence at Woolwich, Holmes constructs an alternative theory that exonerates Cadogan West." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "West was not the thief but an innocent patriot who spotted a foreign agent heading toward the office in the fog, impulsively followed him, witnessed the theft of the plans, and pursued the thief to London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes hypothesizes that West had been approached by a foreign agent under pledges of secrecy, which explains his worried remarks to Violet. When West spotted the same agent heading toward the office while walking to the theatre, his impetuous nature drove him to follow. He witnessed the theft through the window, then pursued the thief. This explains why originals were taken rather than copies — an outsider could not make copies — and why West abandoned his fiancée without explanation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :violetWestbury, :woolwichArsenal ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Body Was Placed on the Roof From Oberstein's Window" ;
    ex:description "At Goldini's Restaurant, Holmes explains to Watson that the body was placed on the train roof from a window of a building overlooking the Underground tracks where trains frequently halt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "West's body was placed on the roof of a stationary train from the back-stair window of 13 Caulfield Gardens, where the Underground trains are held motionless due to a railway intersection." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since the train roofs are slightly rounded with no railing, the body could not have been dropped from a bridge but must have been deliberately placed from very close range. The only way to do this is from a window directly above the tracks at a point where trains halt. Holmes verified at Gloucester Road Station that the back windows of Caulfield Gardens open onto the line and that trains frequently stop there." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :13CaulfieldGardens, :gloucesterRoadStation ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryOfObersteinHouse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Oberstein as the Foreign Agent" ;
    ex:description "After receiving Mycroft's list of known international agents and consulting his map of London, Holmes identifies Hugo Oberstein of 13 Caulfield Gardens as the spy responsible for the theft." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Hugo Oberstein is the foreign agent who received the stolen Bruce-Partington plans, based on his address at Caulfield Gardens abutting the Underground tracks and his known departure from London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes cross-referenced Mycroft's list of international agents with his London map and discovered that Oberstein's residence at 13 Caulfield Gardens was in a row of houses that abutted the Underground line. Combined with Oberstein being known to have been in town on Monday and now reported as having left, this placed the leading international agent at the precise location from which a body could be placed on a train roof." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hugoOberstein ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :13CaulfieldGardens ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfOberstein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Pierrot Advertisements as Espionage Correspondence" ;
    ex:description "During the burglary of Oberstein's house, Holmes discovers newspaper clippings in a cash-box and identifies them as a series of coded agony column messages arranging the delivery of the stolen plans." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The newspaper clippings signed 'Pierrot' from the Daily Telegraph agony column constitute a correspondence record between Oberstein and his inside man, arranging terms and a meeting for the handover of the Bruce-Partington plans." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the clippings as Daily Telegraph agony column messages from their print and paper. Reading them in sequence, they form a coherent correspondence: initial contact, request for full report with payment promised, escalation of urgency, and finally a specific appointment for Monday night with payment in cash upon delivery." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pierrotAdvertisements ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :obersteinCashBox ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Fake Advertisement Can Lure Oberstein Back to London" ;
    ex:description "After decoding the Pierrot correspondence, Holmes places his own advertisement in the Daily Telegraph posing as Oberstein's contact, offering the missing three pages." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oberstein can be lured back to London by a fake advertisement in the Daily Telegraph offering the three missing pages of the Bruce-Partington plans, since Oberstein needs them to complete the set." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Oberstein retained only three of the ten pages and would be eager to acquire the remaining essential pages to complete the plans for sale. By placing an advertisement in the same agony column under the same pseudonym format, posing as the inside man offering the missing pages, Oberstein's desire to complete the coup of his lifetime would compel him to return to London." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hugoOberstein ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pierrotAdvertisements, :dailyTelegraph ;
    ex:confirmedBy :captureOfOberstein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Colonel Valentine Walter as the Inside Man" ;
    ex:description "When the man lured to Oberstein's house is unmasked as Colonel Valentine Walter rather than Oberstein himself, Holmes immediately recognizes the implications and deduces Walter's role as the traitor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Colonel Valentine Walter, the younger brother of Sir James Walter, was the inside man who stole the Bruce-Partington plans using impressions of his brother's keys and passed them to Oberstein." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized Colonel Valentine Walter and instantly connected the family relationship: as Sir James Walter's brother, Valentine had access to the keys that opened the building, office, and safe. Holmes stated that he saw the fall of the cards — Valentine's presence at Oberstein's house in response to the fake advertisement confirmed he was the correspondent behind the Pierrot messages, and his brother's keys explained how the plans were accessed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :captureOfColonelWalter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelValentineWalter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: West Sold the Plans and Was Murdered on the Train" ;
    ex:description "During the initial consultation at Baker Street with Mycroft, Lestrade proposes a complete theory of the crime that assumes West's guilt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "West stole the plans to sell them to a foreign agent, they could not agree on a price, the agent accompanied West on the train, murdered him in the carriage, took the most essential papers, and threw the body from the train." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade constructed a theory that accounted for the known facts: the plans were found on West's person, indicating he took them to sell. The missing three pages and absence of money suggest the transaction went wrong. The agent would have accompanied West on the return journey to Woolwich, murdered him during a dispute, retained the critical pages, and disposed of the body from the moving train." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brucePartingtonPlans ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_brucePartington_holmes_04 ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_brucePartington_holmes_09 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_brucePartington_lestrade_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: The Ticket Was Taken to Conceal the Agent's Location" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes raises the question of the missing railway ticket during the Baker Street consultation, Lestrade provides an explanation consistent with his overall theory." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The foreign agent removed the railway ticket from West's body to prevent the police from identifying the station nearest the agent's residence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade reasoned that the ticket would have shown which station West boarded at, which would indicate the station nearest the foreign agent's house where the transaction took place. Therefore the agent took the ticket from the murdered man's pocket to protect his own location." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurCadoganWest ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_brucePartington_holmes_04 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :brucePartingtonPlansDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reads Watson's Train of Thought" ;
    ex:description "While Watson sits in a brown study at Baker Street on a hot August day, Holmes suddenly declares that Watson is right — war is a preposterous way of settling a dispute, startling Watson by echoing his unspoken thoughts." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson was thinking that war is a most preposterous way of settling a dispute, having followed a mental chain from General Gordon's portrait to Henry Ward Beecher to the American Civil War." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Watson throw down his paper, then tracked his eye movements: Watson looked at his newly framed portrait of General Gordon, then at the unframed portrait of Henry Ward Beecher, then up at the bare wall space. Watson's expression shifted to studying Beecher's character, then grew passionate (recalling Beecher's Civil War mission and his hostile reception in England), then sad and head-shaking (the waste of war), then his hand moved to his old wound and he smiled at the absurdity of settling disputes by warfare." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :gordonPortrait, :beecherPortrait ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Seafaring Origin From Tarred Twine and Knot" ;
    ex:description "Examining the parcel's wrapping materials in Susan Cushing's garden, Holmes studies the string used to tie the package and identifies its nautical origin." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tarred twine and the particular knot used to tie the parcel indicate that the sender is connected to seafaring." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the string was tarred twine of the quality used by sail-makers aboard ship, and that the knot left intact by Miss Cushing's scissors-cut was of a type popular with sailors. Combined with the Belfast postmark (a port) and the male ear pierced for an earring (more common among sailors than landsmen), all actors in the case are connected to the sea." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tarredTwine, :cardboardBoxEars ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Determines the Ears Are Evidence of a Serious Crime" ;
    ex:description "After examining the severed ears in the outhouse, Holmes dismisses the medical student prank theory and asserts that a serious crime has been committed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The ears are not a dissecting-room prank but genuine evidence of a violent crime involving freshly severed human ears." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Bodies in dissecting-rooms are injected with preservative fluid, but these ears bear no signs of this and are fresh. They were cut off with a blunt instrument, which would hardly happen if a medical student had done it. A medical mind would use carbolic or rectified spirits as preservatives, certainly not rough salt. The evidence is inconsistent with a prank and consistent with real crime." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :severedEars ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :severedEars ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Two Victims From the Mismatched Ears" ;
    ex:description "Holmes observes that the two severed ears in the cardboard box are not a matching pair and deduces that two people — one male, one female — have been killed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The two ears belong to two different people, one a woman and one a man, who are presumably dead since no one has come forward to report the crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "One ear is a woman's — small, finely formed, and pierced for an earring. The other is a man's — sun-burned, discoloured, and also pierced for an earring. The ears are not a pair. Since no story of missing ears has surfaced, the two people are presumably dead." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryBrowner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecFairbairn ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :severedEars ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Suspects the Parcel Was Intended for One of Susan's Sisters" ;
    ex:description "Upon entering Susan Cushing's front room, Holmes notices a portrait group of three ladies on the mantelpiece and immediately considers that the parcel may have been meant for one of the other sisters." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cardboard box may have been intended for one of Susan Cushing's two sisters rather than for Susan herself, who appears innocent of any secret." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Susan Cushing appeared placid, respectable, and genuinely bewildered by the parcel. A portrait on the mantelpiece showed three ladies — Susan and two younger sisters who bore a strong family resemblance. Holmes set aside the hypothesis that the box was meant for one of these sisters as something to be confirmed or disproved." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sarahCushing ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Sender as a Man of Limited Education" ;
    ex:description "Examining the brown paper wrapper of the parcel in the garden, Holmes analyzes the handwriting, ink, and spelling to characterize the sender." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The parcel was addressed by a man of limited education who was unacquainted with the town of Croydon." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The address was printed in straggling characters rather than written in cursive, and the printing is distinctly masculine. It was done with a broad-pointed pen, probably a J nib, and with very inferior ink. The word 'Croydon' was originally misspelled with an 'i' and then corrected to 'y', indicating unfamiliarity with the town." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jimBrowner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brownPaperWrapper ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Matches Susan Cushing's Ear to the Female Severed Ear" ;
    ex:description "While questioning Susan Cushing in her front room, Holmes suddenly pauses mid-sentence and stares with singular intentness at her profile, having noticed a striking anatomical similarity between her ear and the female ear from the box." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The female severed ear matches Susan Cushing's ear in anatomical detail, proving the victim is a close blood relative — one of Susan's sisters." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had previously published two monographs on the distinctiveness of the human ear in the Anthropological Journal and examined the ears in the box with expert attention. When he observed Susan Cushing's ear, he perceived the same shortening of the pinna, the same broad curve of the upper lobe, and the same convolution of the inner cartilage. Such a match was entirely beyond coincidence and indicated a family relationship." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :susanCushing ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryBrowner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :severedEars, :anthropologicalJournal ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Parcel Was Meant for Sarah Cushing" ;
    ex:description "Combining the ear resemblance, the address on the parcel, and information learned from Susan Cushing about her sisters, Holmes concludes the package was misdirected." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The parcel was intended for Sarah Cushing and sent to Susan's address by mistake because Sarah had recently lived there and the sender did not know she had moved." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Sarah's first name also begins with 'S', and her address had until recently been the same as Susan's at Cross Street, Croydon. The sisters had parted about two months ago. A quarrel had stopped all communications between Sarah and the Browners for some months, so if Jim Browner had occasion to address a packet to Miss Sarah Cushing, he would undoubtedly have used her old address." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sarahCushing ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Jim Browner as the Murderer" ;
    ex:description "At the Croydon police-station, Holmes tells Lestrade he has found out everything and writes Jim Browner's name on his visiting card as the criminal." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jim Browner, the steward on the May Day, murdered his wife Mary and a male companion out of jealousy, then sent the severed ears to Sarah Cushing as a sign of what her meddling had caused." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes established that the victims were connected to the sea and that the female victim was a blood relative of Susan Cushing — pointing to Mary Browner. Jim Browner was an impulsive man of strong passions, a sailor who had quarrelled with Sarah, and whose wife had not been seen for days. The parcel was posted from Belfast, which was the first port of call for the May Day's line of boats. Browner had the motive (jealousy), the means (sailor with access to rough salt and tarred twine), and the opportunity (his ship's route passed through Belfast)." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jimBrowner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryBrowner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecFairbairn ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tarredTwine, :severedEars, :brownPaperWrapper ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestJimBrowner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Considers an Alternative Theory of an Outside Lover" ;
    ex:description "Before sending his telegram to Algar, Holmes considers a second possible solution: that an unsuccessful lover might have killed both Mr. and Mrs. Browner, with the male ear belonging to Jim Browner himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "An alternative theory is possible — that an outside lover killed both Browners — though Holmes considers it exceedingly unlikely." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Although Holmes thought the jealous-husband theory far more probable, a second solution was conceivable: an unsuccessful lover might have killed Mr. and Mrs. Browner, and the male ear could belong to the husband rather than a third party. Holmes acknowledged many grave objections to this theory but was determined to eliminate it before proceeding, so he sent a telegram to Algar to check whether Mrs. Browner was at home and whether Browner had departed on the May Day." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jimBrowner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryBrowner ;
    ex:refutedBy :telegramToAlgar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets Sarah Cushing's Brain Fever as Confirmation of Guilt Knowledge" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at Sarah Cushing's home in Wallington and being turned away by her doctor due to brain fever, Holmes interprets her sudden illness as confirmation that she understood the parcel's full significance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sarah Cushing's collapse into brain fever upon hearing of the parcel's arrival confirms she knew what it meant and who sent it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Sarah's illness dated from the time she heard of the parcel's arrival, and all Croydon was ringing with the news. She alone could have understood for whom the packet was meant. Had she been willing to help justice, she would have communicated with the police. Her brain fever, rather than contact with the police, made it clearer than ever that she understood the packet's full significance but could not or would not assist." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sarahCushing ;
    ex:confirmedBy :brownerConfessionEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_cardboardBox_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: Medical Students Sent the Ears as a Prank" ;
    ex:description "Lestrade, in charge of the case, endorses the police theory reported in the Daily Chronicle that the ears were sent as a grotesque prank by former medical student lodgers whom Susan Cushing had evicted years earlier." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The severed ears were sent to Susan Cushing as a vengeful practical joke by former medical student lodgers, one of whom came from Belfast." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Susan Cushing had once let apartments to three young medical students at Penge whom she was obliged to evict for noisy and irregular habits. One of these students came from the north of Ireland, and to the best of Miss Cushing's belief, from Belfast — the city from which the parcel was posted. Medical students would have access to dissecting-room specimens and a motive of grudge-based revenge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :susanCushing ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :severedEars ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_cardboardBox_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :cardboardBoxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Visited a Turkish Bath" ;
    ex:description "At 221B Baker Street, Holmes examines Watson's boots and deduces that Watson has recently visited a Turkish bath, despite Watson initially thinking Holmes is referring to the boots themselves." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has recently visited a Turkish bath." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Watson's boots were fastened with an elaborate double bow rather than his usual method of tying them, indicating they had been removed and retied by someone else. Since the boots were nearly new, a bootmaker was unlikely — leaving the attendant at a bath as the most probable explanation, and the expensive Turkish bath rather than an ordinary one." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Shared a Cab" ;
    ex:description "In the same opening conversation at 221B, Holmes deduces that Watson shared a hansom cab with a companion that morning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson shared his cab with a companion." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed mud splashes on the left sleeve and shoulder of Watson's coat. Had Watson sat in the centre of the hansom, any splashes would have been symmetrical. The asymmetric pattern on one side indicated Watson sat to one side, which meant there was a companion occupying the other seat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Shlessinger as Holy Peters" ;
    ex:description "After Watson returns from the Continent, Holmes reveals that the supposedly pious missionary Dr. Shlessinger is actually the notorious Australian criminal Holy Peters, and his wife is an Englishwoman named Fraser." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Shlessinger is the criminal Holy Peters of Adelaide, and his so-called wife is Annie Fraser." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the pattern of beguiling lonely ladies through religious manipulation as the specialty of Holy Peters, an unscrupulous Australian criminal. He confirmed the identification by requesting a description of Shlessinger's left ear via telegram to the Englischer Hof manager — Peters had a distinctive torn ear from a saloon fight in Adelaide in 1889." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryPeters ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annieFraser ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :earTelegram, :adelaideSaloonFight ;
    ex:confirmedBy :confrontationPeters ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lady Frances Is in London" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons about where Lady Frances is most likely being held, concluding she is probably in London rather than elsewhere on the Continent or in rural England." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Frances is most likely being held in London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Lady Frances probably reached London because Continental police registration systems make it difficult for foreigners to evade detection, making it improbable she never arrived. It was also unlikely the criminals passed through London to elsewhere, since London offered the easiest conditions in which to keep a person under restraint — the anonymity of a crowded city of millions." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:confirmedBy :rescueLadyFrances ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Peters Plan to Murder Lady Frances" ;
    ex:description "While driving to Poultney Square after learning of the coffin delivery, Holmes reconstructs the criminals' scheme and concludes they intend to murder Lady Frances." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Peters and Fraser have imprisoned Lady Frances, stolen her jewellery, and must now murder her to prevent her from denouncing them." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the criminals coaxed Lady Frances to London after alienating her from her maid, imprisoned her in a furnished house, and took possession of her valuable jewellery. Since they had already begun pawning the jewels, when she was released she would denounce them. They could not keep her imprisoned forever, so murder was their only solution." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryPeters ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annieFraser ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pawningPendant1, :pawningPendant2, :kidnappingLadyFrances ;
    ex:confirmedBy :rescueLadyFrances ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Coffin Means Lady Frances Is Dead" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis en route to Poultney Square, Holmes follows a second chain of reasoning starting from the coffin, concluding that Lady Frances is already dead and will receive an orthodox burial." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The arrival of the coffin proves Lady Frances is dead, and the criminals have simulated a natural death to obtain a legitimate medical certificate and burial." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes argued backward from the coffin: its presence pointed to an orthodox burial with medical certificate and official sanction. Had the murder been obvious, they would have buried her secretly. The open, regular procedure meant they had killed her in a way that deceived the doctor and simulated a natural end, possibly by poisoning — though it was strange they would allow a doctor near unless he were a confederate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oversizedCoffin ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_carfax_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Oversized Coffin Conceals Lady Frances" ;
    ex:description "After a sleepless night, Holmes suddenly recalls the undertaker's wife's remark that the coffin was delayed because it was 'out of the ordinary,' and realizes the oversized coffin was built to hold two bodies — Lady Frances hidden beneath the dead Rose Spender." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The coffin was custom-made to an unusually large size to conceal Lady Frances's body alongside the dead Rose Spender, so both would be buried under one death certificate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled the undertaker's wife saying the coffin 'took longer, being out of the ordinary,' meaning it was made to special measurements. He then remembered the deep sides of the coffin and the small, wasted figure of Rose Spender at the bottom — why so large a coffin for so small a body? The answer was to leave room for another body. Both would be buried under the one certificate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roseSpender ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oversizedCoffin, :spenderDeathCertificate ;
    ex:confirmedBy :rescueLadyFrances ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_carfax_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: The Bearded Stranger Is Pursuing Lady Frances" ;
    ex:description "While investigating at Baden, Watson pieces together information from Lausanne and Baden to form a theory about the mysterious bearded man who has been following Lady Frances across the Continent." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A sinister bearded stranger has been pursuing Lady Frances from place to place, and she fled Lausanne out of fear of him. He may have already overtaken her, explaining her silence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson linked the account of a tall, dark, bearded man who visited Lady Frances at Lausanne and was seen seizing her wrist on the promenade with the same man who appeared at Baden inquiring after her. Watson concluded Lady Frances feared this man and fled from him, and that the Shlessingers were shielding her from his violence or blackmail." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyFrancesCarfax ;
    ex:deductionSubject :philipGreen ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :wristSeizureLausanne ;
    ex:refutedBy :philipGreen ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :disappearanceLadyFrancesCarfaxDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Visitor Has a Love Problem" ;
    ex:description "While observing a woman hesitating on the pavement opposite 221B Baker Street, Holmes interprets her body language before she has entered the room or spoken a word." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The woman oscillating on the pavement has a love problem but is perplexed rather than angry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that oscillation upon the pavement always indicates an affair of the heart. Since a woman seriously wronged by a man no longer oscillates but instead breaks the bell wire in her urgency, this woman's hesitation indicates she is perplexed or grieved rather than angry, suggesting the matter involves a love question where she is uncertain rather than betrayed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :marySutherland ;
    ex:confirmedBy :marySutherland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sutherland Is a Short-Sighted Typist" ;
    ex:description "Upon Miss Sutherland's entrance, Holmes examines her in his characteristic abstracted fashion and immediately asks whether her short sight makes typewriting trying." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miss Sutherland is short-sighted and works as a typist." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the dint of a pince-nez at either side of Miss Sutherland's nose, indicating short sight. He also noticed a double line a little above the wrist on her plush sleeves, where the typewriter operator presses against the table — distinct from a sewing-machine mark, which would appear only on the left arm and on the side farthest from the thumb." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :marySutherland ;
    ex:confirmedBy :marySutherland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sutherland Left Home in a Hurry" ;
    ex:description "After Miss Sutherland departs, Holmes explains to Watson what he observed about her boots during the consultation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miss Sutherland left home in a hurry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that although the boots Miss Sutherland was wearing appeared similar, they were actually odd — one had a slightly decorated toe-cap and the other a plain one. Furthermore, one was buttoned only in the two lower buttons out of five, and the other at the first, third, and fifth. A neatly dressed young lady arriving with mismatched, half-buttoned boots must have left home in haste." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :marySutherland ;
    ex:confirmedBy :marySutherland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sutherland Wrote a Note Before Leaving" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his post-interview analysis with Watson, Holmes describes what he deduced from the state of Miss Sutherland's gloves." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miss Sutherland wrote a note in haste that morning after dressing but before leaving home." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that Miss Sutherland's right glove was torn at the forefinger and that both the glove and the finger beneath were stained with violet ink. This indicated she had written in a hurry, dipping her pen too deep. Since the ink mark was still clear on her finger, it must have been done that morning. She had written the note after being fully dressed, as evidenced by the ink being on the outside of the glove." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :marySutherland ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Recognizes the Case as a Known Pattern" ;
    ex:description "After Miss Sutherland leaves, Holmes tells Watson that her problem is a trite one, with parallel cases in Andover in 1877 and at The Hague the previous year." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The case follows a known pattern of deception that Holmes has encountered before." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the essential features of the case — a fictitious suitor who vanishes — as conforming to a pattern he had catalogued in his index, with prior instances in Andover in 1877 and at The Hague. This immediate pattern recognition indicated Holmes had already grasped the fundamental nature of the deception from Mary Sutherland's account alone." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :identityInvestigation ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :andoverCase, :hagueCase ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Typewritten Signature Is Conclusive" ;
    ex:description "Examining the letters from Hosmer Angel, Holmes draws Watson's attention to the fact that not only the letters but also the signature is typewritten, calling this detail conclusive." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The typewritten signature on Hosmer Angel's letters proves the writer's handwriting would be recognizable to the recipient." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A person who typewriters even his signature must have a compelling reason to conceal his handwriting. Holmes inferred that the writer's handwriting was so familiar to Miss Sutherland that she would recognize even the smallest sample of it — meaning the person behind the letters was someone she already knew well, not a stranger." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hosmerAngelLetters ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Hosmer Angel Is James Windibank in Disguise" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies the vanished bridegroom Hosmer Angel as Mary Sutherland's stepfather James Windibank, the central deduction of the case, formed from multiple converging lines of evidence during and after the client interview." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Hosmer Angel is James Windibank disguised as a fictitious suitor to keep Mary Sutherland's income in the household." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified that the only person who profited from Mary Sutherland remaining unmarried was her stepfather Windibank, who had the use of her hundred-pound annual income. The two men were never seen together, Angel appearing only when Windibank was supposedly in France. Angel's tinted spectacles, curious whispering voice, and bushy whiskers all suggested a disguise. The typewritten signature confirmed the writer's handwriting was familiar to Sutherland. Holmes verified this by stripping the disguise elements from Angel's published description, sending it to Windibank's employer, and receiving confirmation it matched their employee." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:deductionSubject :marySutherland ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hosmerAngelLetters, :chronicleAdvertisement, :windibanksTypewrittenLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Typewriter Match Between Angel and Windibank" ;
    ex:description "When Windibank arrives at Baker Street, Holmes demonstrates that the typewriter used for Hosmer Angel's letters is the same machine that produced Windibank's own correspondence, providing the physical proof of the deception." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Angel's letters and Windibank's letter were typed on the same machine, proving they are the same person." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes compared the typewritten letters purporting to come from Hosmer Angel with the typewritten letter he had elicited from James Windibank. Both showed identical defects: a slurring over of the letter 'e' and a slight defect in the tail of the 'r,' along with fourteen other matching characteristics. Since no two typewriters write exactly alike unless quite new, this proved both sets of correspondence came from the same machine." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hosmerAngelLetters, :windibanksTypewrittenLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesWindibank ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_caseOfIdentity_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Typewritten Signature to Deny Breach of Promise" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes points out the significance of Hosmer Angel's typewritten signature, Watson offers his own interpretation of why a man would typewrite his name rather than sign it by hand." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Angel typewrote his signature so he could deny it if sued for breach of promise of marriage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson reasoned that a man who typewritten his signature on love letters rather than signing by hand would do so to maintain plausible deniability — if an action for breach of promise were instituted, he could claim the signature was not his since it bore no handwriting characteristics." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hosmerAngel ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hosmerAngelLetters ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_caseOfIdentity_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :caseOfIdentityDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Excessive Salary Indicates Something Sinister" ;
    ex:description "During Violet Hunter's initial consultation at Baker Street, Holmes responds to her account of the Rucastles' offer by focusing on the anomalously high salary of one hundred and twenty pounds a year for a governess position." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Rucastles' offer of an extraordinarily high salary must conceal some strong ulterior reason, as they could hire any governess for a fraction of the price." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the offered salary of one hundred and twenty pounds was far above the market rate of approximately forty pounds for a governess. He reasoned that no rational employer would pay three times the going rate without a compelling hidden motive, concluding that the excessive pay was compensation for something beyond ordinary governess duties." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jephroRucastle ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetHunter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :jephroRucastleLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :imprisonmentOfAliceRucastle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Devises Seven Separate Explanations" ;
    ex:description "On the train journey to Winchester, Holmes tells Watson he has devised seven separate explanations that would each account for the known facts of Violet Hunter's situation, but declines to specify them until more data is available." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Seven distinct theories could account for the strange conditions at the Copper Beeches, but more information is needed to determine which is correct." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes applied his method of generating multiple hypotheses from incomplete data, noting that the unusual salary, hair-cutting requirement, dress stipulation, and prescribed seating arrangement could each be explained by different underlying schemes. He withheld specifics because the facts were insufficient to eliminate competing theories." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :violetHunterLetter, :jephroRucastleLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Was Brought to Impersonate a Prisoner" ;
    ex:description "At the Black Swan Hotel in Winchester, after hearing Violet Hunter's full account of events at the Copper Beeches, Holmes delivers his central deduction about the purpose of her employment." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Hunter has been hired to impersonate someone, and the real person is imprisoned in the locked wing of the house." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes synthesized the convergent evidence: Violet was made to wear a specific dress belonging to the absent daughter, cut her hair to match, sit with her back to the window at prescribed times, and laugh or read aloud as though content. The locked and barricaded wing with a living occupant, combined with the coil of hair matching Violet's in the locked drawer, pointed to a single conclusion — Violet was a stand-in for someone being held prisoner whose appearance she had been made to duplicate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetHunter ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aliceRucastle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :electricBlueDress, :aliceRucastleHair ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsTollerCB ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Prisoner as Alice Rucastle" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis at the Black Swan, Holmes identifies the imprisoned person as Alice Rucastle, Jephro's daughter from his first marriage, who was claimed to have gone to America." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The prisoner in the locked wing is Alice Rucastle, Jephro's daughter, not in Philadelphia as her father claimed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled that Rucastle's letter mentioned a daughter Alice supposedly in Philadelphia whose dress fit Violet perfectly. The matching hair in the locked drawer was the same peculiar chestnut tint as Violet's own, indicating it had been cut from someone with identical colouring. Alice's alleged departure to America provided a convenient cover story, while the imprisoned figure behind the barricaded and shuttered door was the actual daughter, whose hair had likely been cut during an illness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aliceRucastle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :aliceRucastleHair, :electricBlueDress, :jephroRucastleLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsTollerCB ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Man in the Road Is Alice's Suitor" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains that the bearded man Violet observed watching from the Southampton Road was Alice's suitor, and that the entire window performance was designed to convince him that Alice was content and no longer desired his attentions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The man watching from the road was Alice Rucastle's fiance, and the window impersonation was designed to make him believe Alice was happy and free, so he would abandon his suit." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the man's persistent watching from the road with the Rucastles' insistence that Violet sit in the window wearing Alice's dress. Because Violet resembled Alice in height, figure, and hair colour, the man would see what appeared to be Alice laughing and content. When Violet was made to wave him away, the deception was completed — the suitor was meant to conclude Alice had rejected him. The mastiff released at night prevented the man from approaching the house to verify directly." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrFowler ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aliceRucastle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :electricBlueDress, :carloMastiff ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsTollerCB ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Edward's Cruelty Reveals Rucastle's True Character" ;
    ex:description "When Watson questions the relevance of the child Edward's behaviour, Holmes explains that a child's disposition can reveal the character of the parents, and that Edward's abnormal cruelty bodes evil for the imprisoned Alice." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The child Edward Rucastle's abnormal cruelty reflects the true sadistic nature of his father Jephro Rucastle, which bodes evil for Alice in his power." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes inverted the standard medical principle that parents' tendencies illuminate a child's nature, arguing the converse is equally valid. Edward's disposition was abnormally cruel purely for cruelty's sake — killing small creatures for amusement with remarkable planning. Holmes reasoned this trait most likely derived from the smiling father rather than the passive mother, revealing a sadistic character beneath Jephro's genial exterior that endangered anyone in his control." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :edwardRucastle ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jephroRucastle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :imprisonmentOfAliceRucastle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Rucastle Discovered the Escape and Fowler Rescued Alice" ;
    ex:description "Upon finding the locked room empty with the skylight open, Holmes immediately deduces what has transpired and subsequently reconstructs the full escape mechanism from the evidence on the roof." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Rucastle guessed Miss Hunter's intentions and carried out the removal of Alice, but Fowler, aided by Mrs. Toller, had already rescued Alice via a ladder through the skylight." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the empty room with the open skylight and concluded the prisoner had been removed. Climbing to the roof, he found the end of a long light ladder against the eaves, explaining the escape route. When Rucastle arrived in a fury, Holmes deduced that Rucastle had returned and discovered the escape. Mrs. Toller's subsequent testimony confirmed that Fowler had enlisted her help, kept Toller drunk, and arranged the ladder for Alice's rescue while the Rucastles were away." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aliceRucastle ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrFowler ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsTollerCB ;
    ex:confirmedBy :escapeOfAliceRucastle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_copperBeeches_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Mrs. Rucastle Is a Lunatic" ;
    ex:description "During Violet Hunter's initial consultation, before Holmes offers his analysis, Violet presents a theory — which Watson notes seemed probable to those present — that Mrs. Rucastle is mentally ill and Jephro humours her bizarre fancies to avoid her being committed to an asylum." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Rucastle is a lunatic, and the bizarre conditions of employment reflect Jephro Rucastle's attempts to keep the matter quiet by indulging her eccentric demands." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The theory attempted to explain the strange requirements — cutting hair, wearing a specific dress, sitting in prescribed positions — as the irrational demands of a mentally unstable woman whose husband complied to maintain domestic peace and avoid scandal. The generous salary would then be compensation for enduring these eccentric whims." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsRucastle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :jephroRucastleLetter ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_copperBeeches_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :copperBeechesDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Bennett and Edith Presbury Are Romantically Involved" ;
    ex:description "When Edith Presbury arrives at Baker Street and Bennett springs up to meet her with outstretched hands, Holmes observes their interaction and remarks to Watson that they were already reaching that conclusion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Trevor Bennett and Edith Presbury are engaged to be married." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the spontaneous warmth and physical familiarity between Bennett and Edith when she arrived unexpectedly — Bennett sprang up with a cry and ran forward with his hands out to meet hers — and concluded they were romantically involved, which Bennett then confirmed by introducing her as his fiancée." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :trevorBennett ;
    ex:deductionSubject :edithPresbury ;
    ex:confirmedBy :trevorBennett ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Nine-Day Cycle in Presbury's Episodes" ;
    ex:description "During his review of Bennett's diary dates at the Chequers inn in Camford, Holmes identifies a precise periodicity in Presbury's bizarre behavioural episodes, noting that they recur at nine-day intervals." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's episodes of aberrant behaviour occur at regular nine-day intervals, a pattern too consistent to be coincidence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the dates Bennett had recorded in his diary — trouble on July 2nd, then at nine-day intervals through July 11th, July 20th, August 26th, September 3rd, and September 4th-5th — and recognized that the incidents fell into a consistent nine-day cycle with only one possible exception, ruling out coincidence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bennettDiary ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lowensteinLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Miscalculation: Presbury Has Poor Memory on Episode Days" ;
    ex:description "Based on Edith's report that her father has no recollection of his actions on certain days, Holmes deduces that Presbury's memory is unreliable during episodes and devises a plan to visit him under the pretence of a prior appointment." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's memory is impaired during his episodes, allowing Holmes and Watson to visit him by claiming a fictitious appointment he would not remember." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes relied on Edith's observation that her father seemed to live in a strange dream on certain days and remembered little of what occurred. Holmes concluded that Presbury would not recall whether he had arranged an appointment on such a day and would assume his own memory was at fault." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :edithSeesPresburyAtWindow ;
    ex:refutedBy :holmesPresburyConfrontation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Edith's Window Is Climbable via Creeper and Water-Pipe" ;
    ex:description "After the confrontation with Presbury, Holmes asks Bennett to show them Miss Presbury's second-floor window. He examines the exterior of the house and identifies a possible climbing route." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Despite the window's apparent inaccessibility, the creeper below and water-pipe above provide sufficient foothold for someone with extraordinary climbing ability to reach it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that while the second-floor window appeared hardly accessible, there was a creeper growing below it and a water-pipe running above it, which together provided handholds and footholds. He noted that while a normal man could not make such a climb, it would be possible for someone with abnormal capabilities." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :presburyHouse ;
    ex:confirmedBy :presburyClimbsWall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Connects Dorak's Slavonic Nationality to the Prague Visit" ;
    ex:description "When Bennett provides the name and address of Presbury's London correspondent, Holmes immediately identifies the name as Slavonic and connects it to the professor's earlier visit to Prague." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dorak is of Slavonic origin, and his nationality links him to Presbury's secret trip to Prague, establishing that the London correspondence is connected to whatever Presbury sought in Bohemia." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized 'Dorak' as a Slavonic name and immediately connected this to the professor's unexplained fortnight in Prague, reasoning that the London intermediary represented someone in the Bohemian capital." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dorak ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dorakLetters, :presburyPragueTrip ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mercerAgent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Presbury Takes a Strong Drug Every Nine Days" ;
    ex:description "At the Chequers inn, Holmes synthesizes the nine-day cycle, the Prague trip, the Bohemian intermediary, and the secret correspondence into a provisional theory about Presbury's condition." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Every nine days Presbury takes a strong drug with a passing but highly poisonous effect that intensifies his naturally violent nature, learned during his Prague visit and now supplied through a Bohemian intermediary in London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined the strict nine-day periodicity of the episodes, the professor's unexplained Prague journey after which the changes began, the secret correspondence with Slavonic-named Dorak in London, and the guarded wooden box to form the theory that Presbury was regularly dosing himself with a powerful substance obtained through a supply chain originating in Prague." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bennettDiary, :dorakLetters, :presburyPragueTrip, :presburyWoodenBox ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lowensteinLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :rejuvenationSerum ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets Presbury's Knuckles as Evidence of Quadrupedal Locomotion" ;
    ex:description "While waiting outside Presbury's house on the stakeout night, Holmes draws Watson's attention to the professor's unusually thick and horny knuckles, which he had observed during their earlier visit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's abnormally thick and horny knuckles can only be explained by habitual locomotion on his hands and feet." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had observed that Presbury's knuckles were thick and horny in a way unprecedented in his experience. Applying his principle of always examining the hands first, he connected this physical callusing to the mode of progression Bennett had witnessed — crawling on hands and feet — concluding that the knuckles had been hardened by repeated use in this manner." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bennettWitnessesCrawling ;
    ex:confirmedBy :presburyClimbingIncident ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Epiphany: All Evidence Points to a Simian Transformation" ;
    ex:description "Moments before Presbury emerges from the house, Holmes suddenly connects all the disparate evidence — the knuckles, the dog's hostility, the ivy climbing, the creeping — and realizes the truth of the professor's condition." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The knuckles, the dog's behaviour, the climbing, the creeping, and the drug all point in one direction: Presbury has been undergoing a simian transformation caused by an injected substance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the thick knuckles indicating quadrupedal movement, the dog's hostility toward its formerly beloved master, the seemingly impossible climbing to a second-floor window, the nocturnal creeping on hands and feet, and the nine-day drug cycle. He exclaimed at his own foolishness for not seeing the connection sooner — all points converged on the conclusion that the drug was inducing ape-like physical characteristics and behaviour." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bennettWitnessesCrawling, :edithSeesPresburyAtWindow, :roy, :rejuvenationSerum ;
    ex:confirmedBy :presburyClimbingIncident ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lowensteinLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Dog Attacked the Monkey, Not the Professor" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation after Presbury is attacked by Roy and the contents of the wooden box are revealed, Holmes explains the wolfhound's persistent hostility toward its master." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Roy the wolfhound attacked Presbury not out of illness or random aggression, but because the dog's keen sense of smell detected something fundamentally alien — the monkey — in its master." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the dog was aware of the change in Presbury far more quickly than any human could be, because its sense of smell would detect the alteration. The dog was not attacking the professor it had always loved but rather the monkey nature that had overlaid its master. This also explained why the dog only attacked on certain days — the days when the serum's effects were active." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roy ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :royAttacksPresbury ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lowensteinLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Presbury's Climbing to Edith's Window Was Incidental" ;
    ex:description "In his final retrospective explanation, Holmes addresses the disturbing episode of Presbury appearing at his daughter's second-floor window, dismissing any sinister intent." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's appearance at Edith's window was not deliberate; climbing was a natural joy for the simian nature induced by the serum, and reaching the window was mere chance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since the langur monkey is by nature a climber, the serum's effects would produce an irresistible compulsion to climb. The professor's ascent of the ivy-covered wall was driven by this simian instinct rather than any conscious intention to spy on his daughter. The fact that his route happened to pass her window was coincidental." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :edithPresbury ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :edithSeesPresburyAtWindow, :presburyClimbsWall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Root Cause: Love Affair Drove Presbury to Seek Rejuvenation" ;
    ex:description "After the Lowenstein letter is discovered, Holmes identifies the ultimate motivation behind Presbury's self-experimentation, tracing the entire chain of events back to the professor's infatuation with Alice Morphy." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's untimely love affair with the much younger Alice Morphy gave him the desperate idea that he could only win her by transforming himself into a younger man, driving him to seek Lowenstein's rejuvenation serum." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes traced the causal chain from Presbury's passionate engagement to Alice Morphy, through his secret trip to Prague where he consulted Lowenstein, to the regular injections of langur monkey serum. The professor's motive was to overcome the one obstacle to the match — his age — by artificially restoring his youth and vigour." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aliceMorphy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :lowensteinLetter, :presburyPragueTrip ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lowensteinLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :creepingManDoc .

:deduction_creepingMan_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Presbury's Crawling Is Caused by Lumbago" ;
    ex:description "When Bennett describes witnessing Professor Presbury crawling along the passage at night on his hands and feet, Holmes asks Watson for his opinion. Watson offers a medical explanation based on his clinical experience." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's nocturnal crawling is caused by a severe attack of lumbago, which would also explain his bad temper." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson drew on his medical experience, noting that he had known severe lumbago attacks to force a man to walk in just such a crouching manner, and that the pain would also account for the professor's foul temper when disturbed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
