:deduction_creepingMan_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Presbury's Case Is One for an Alienist" ;
    ex:description "After Holmes summarizes the facts of Presbury's case, Watson offers his medical assessment, attributing the professor's behavioural changes to a mental disturbance caused by his late-life love affair." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Presbury's case is a psychiatric matter; his cerebral processes were disturbed by the love affair, the journey abroad was an attempt to break the passion, and the letters and box relate to a private financial transaction." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson reasoned as a medical man that the elderly professor's dramatic personality change following his engagement suggested disturbed cerebral processes. He interpreted the foreign trip as an attempt to overcome the infatuation and proposed that the secret correspondence and guarded box related to an unrelated financial matter such as a loan or share certificates." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorPresbury ;
