:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Animal Is Carnivorous" ;
    ex:description "Holmes infers the creature's dietary nature from its behavior inside the room." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The animal is carnivorous, as it ran up the curtain in an attempt to reach the canary in its cage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found distinct traces that the creature had run up the curtain. A canary's cage was hanging in the window, and the animal's aim was evidently to get at the bird, demonstrating carnivorous instincts." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :teddy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :barclayCanary ;
    ex:confirmedBy :henryWood ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Something Occurred Between 7:30 and 9:00 to Alter Mrs. Barclay's Feelings" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies a narrow time window during which Mrs. Barclay's attitude toward her husband underwent a dramatic reversal." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Something happened to Mrs. Barclay between leaving the house at 7:30 and returning at 9:00 that completely changed her feelings toward the Colonel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Barclay was heard chatting with her husband in a friendly fashion when she left at half-past seven. Upon returning shortly after nine, she immediately went to the room she was least likely to encounter him in, called for tea in an agitated manner contrary to her habits, and then broke into violent recriminations when the Colonel joined her. The transformation was absolute." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nancyBarclay ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :barclayCoachman, :janeStewart ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missMorrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Miss Morrison Must Know What Happened" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that since Miss Morrison was with Mrs. Barclay during the entire critical time period, her denial of knowledge must be false." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miss Morrison must know what caused Mrs. Barclay's dramatic change, despite her denial to police." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Miss Morrison had been with Mrs. Barclay during the entire hour and a half between 7:30 and 9:00. Since something clearly occurred during that window that transformed Mrs. Barclay's mood, and Miss Morrison was her sole companion throughout, it was absolutely certain she must know something despite her denial." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :missMorrison ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missMorrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Dismisses the Theory of an Affair Between the Colonel and Miss Morrison" ;
    ex:description "Holmes considers and rejects the hypothesis that an affair between Colonel Barclay and Miss Morrison could explain the events." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There was no romantic involvement between Colonel Barclay and Miss Morrison." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes initially conjectured that perhaps some passages between the young lady and the old soldier had been confessed to the wife, which would account for the angry return and the girl's denial. However, the reference to David, the Colonel's known devotion to his wife, and the intrusion of the mysterious third man weighed against this theory. Holmes dismissed it in favor of the conviction that Miss Morrison held the real clue." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesBarclay ;
    ex:deductionSubject :missMorrison ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :janeStewart ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missMorrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Indian Rupee as Evidence of Wood's Origins" ;
    ex:description "Holmes notes that the coin Wood's landlady showed him was not a bad florin but an Indian rupee, connecting Wood to India." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The suspicious coin in Henry Wood's deposit was an Indian rupee, confirming his connection to India." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Wood's landlady believed he had given her a bad florin in his deposit. Holmes examined the coin and identified it as an Indian rupee, linking Wood to the subcontinent and corroborating the picture of a man recently arrived from the East." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryWood ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :indianRupee ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_crookedMan_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets 'David' as a Biblical Term of Reproach" ;
    ex:description "After the case is resolved, Watson asks Holmes about the name David that Mrs. Barclay was heard to utter. Holmes explains its significance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Barclay's use of 'David' was a biblical term of reproach, referencing King David's betrayal of Uriah the Hittite to claim Bathsheba." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The housemaid heard Mrs. Barclay utter the word David twice during the quarrel, though the Colonel's name was James. Holmes recognized this as a reference to the biblical King David, who sent Uriah to his death in battle in order to take his wife Bathsheba — a direct parallel to Barclay's betrayal of Henry Wood to claim Nancy." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nancyBarclay ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesBarclay ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :janeStewart, :davidBiblical ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :crookedManDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Will Not Invest in South African Securities" ;
    ex:description "While working on a chemical experiment at 221B Baker Street, Holmes suddenly announces that Watson does not propose to invest in South African securities, astonishing his companion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson does not intend to invest in South African securities." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed chalk between Watson's left finger and thumb from his billiards game the previous night. Watson only plays billiards with Thurston, who four weeks ago mentioned an option on South African property expiring within a month. Watson's chequebook remains locked in Holmes's drawer and he has not asked for the key, indicating he has decided not to invest." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Recognises the Dancing Men as a Substitution Cipher" ;
    ex:description "Upon examining the dancing men figures submitted by Hilton Cubitt, Holmes recognises that the apparently childish drawings are in fact a systematic cipher in which each figure represents a letter of the alphabet." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The dancing men figures constitute a substitution cipher, not a child's prank." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the figures were drawn systematically rather than randomly. Being familiar with all forms of secret writing and the author of a monograph analysing one hundred and sixty separate ciphers, he recognised the hallmarks of a substitution system designed to conceal that the characters convey a message by disguising them as childish sketches." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages, :holmesCipherMonograph ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies E as the Most Frequent Symbol" ;
    ex:description "Analysing the first message of dancing men, Holmes identifies the most frequently occurring symbol as representing the letter E, applying standard frequency analysis principles." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The most common dancing man symbol represents the letter E." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "E is the most common letter in the English alphabet and predominates markedly even in short sentences. Out of fifteen symbols in the first message, four were the same figure, making it reasonable to assign this symbol the value E." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Flags Mark Word Boundaries" ;
    ex:description "Holmes observes that some dancing men figures carry flags while others do not, and deduces that the flags serve as word separators rather than representing different letters." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Flags held by certain dancing men figures mark the ends of words in the cipher." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the same figure appeared both with and without a flag. From the distribution pattern of flagged figures within the messages, it was probable that the flags functioned to break the sentence into separate words rather than altering the letter value of the figure." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Decodes Elsie's Reply as 'NEVER'" ;
    ex:description "When Cubitt provides a short single-word message that appears to be a reply written by his wife, Holmes decodes it by identifying the five-letter word with E in the second and fourth positions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The single-word reply written by Elsie Cubitt reads 'NEVER'." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had already established E in the cipher. The single word contained five letters with E in the second and fourth positions. The possible words included 'sever,' 'lever,' or 'never.' Given the circumstances — a reply to an appeal — 'never' was by far the most probable, and the message appeared to have been written by Elsie Cubitt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies 'ELSIE' in the Cipher Messages" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deduces that a repeated combination at the end of messages, containing two E's with three letters between them, spells the name 'ELSIE', the name of Cubitt's wife." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The repeated terminal combination in the messages spells 'ELSIE'." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that if the appeals came from someone intimate with the lady in her early life, a pattern containing two E's with three letters between might well stand for the name 'ELSIE.' Upon examination, this combination formed the termination of a message which was three times repeated, confirming it as an appeal to Elsie and yielding the letters L, S, and I." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Decodes 'COME' Before 'ELSIE'" ;
    ex:description "Holmes determines that the four-letter word preceding 'ELSIE' in the messages, ending in E, must be 'COME', yielding three additional letters." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The four-letter word before 'ELSIE' is 'COME'." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "With L, S, I, and E already known, Holmes identified a four-letter word ending in E that preceded 'ELSIE.' He tried all possible four-letter words ending in E and found that only 'COME' fit the remaining symbol values, giving him C, O, and M." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Decodes the First Message as 'AM HERE ABE SLANEY'" ;
    ex:description "Using the accumulated letter values, Holmes applies them to the first message and, filling in gaps systematically, decodes the complete message identifying the sender." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The first dancing men message reads 'AM HERE ABE SLANEY'." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "With known letters substituted and dots for unknowns, the first message resolved to '.M .ERE ..E SL.NE.' — which could only be completed as 'AM HERE ABE SLANEY' once the first letter was identified as A (occurring three times) and H became apparent in the second word." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abeSlaney ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Decodes the Second Message as 'AT ELRIGES'" ;
    ex:description "Holmes decodes the second short message as 'AT ELRIGES', deducing it refers to a house or inn where the writer was staying." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The second message reads 'AT ELRIGES', indicating the sender's lodging." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Applying known letters to the second message yielded 'A. ELRI.ES.' — Holmes could only make sense of this by inserting T and G for the missing letters, producing 'AT ELRIGES' and supposing it referred to a local house or inn where the writer was staying." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elrigesFarm ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ridlingThorpeStableBoy ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Abe Slaney Is American" ;
    ex:description "Having decoded the sender's name, Holmes reasons that Abe Slaney is American based on multiple converging indicators." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Abe Slaney is an American." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had every reason to suppose Slaney was American since 'Abe' is an American contraction, and since a letter from America had been the starting point of all the trouble with Elsie Cubitt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abeSlaney ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :letterFromAmerica ;
    ex:confirmedBy :wilsonHargreave ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Criminal Secret in Elsie's Past" ;
    ex:description "Holmes infers that Elsie Cubitt's past involves some criminal secret, based on her behaviour and her reaction to the messages." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There is a criminal secret connected to Elsie Cubitt's past." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Elsie's allusions to disagreeable associations in her past life and her absolute refusal to take her husband into her confidence both pointed in the direction of a criminal secret. Holmes cabled Wilson Hargreave of the New York Police Bureau to verify, receiving confirmation that Abe Slaney was 'the most dangerous crook in Chicago.'" ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages, :letterFromAmerica ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hargreaveCable ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Decodes Slaney's Final Threat to Elsie" ;
    ex:description "Holmes decodes the last and longest dancing men message on the sundial as a direct death threat, prompting his urgent departure for Norfolk." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The final message reads 'ELSIE PREPARE TO MEET THY GOD'." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Working with all known letters from prior decipherments, Holmes decoded the final long message left on the sundial pedestal as 'ELSIE .RE.ARE TO MEET THY GO.' — with the addition of P and D completing the terrifying threat 'ELSIE PREPARE TO MEET THY GOD', showing Slaney had escalated from persuasion to death threats." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abeSlaney ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dancingMenMessages ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfHiltonCubitt ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Discovers the Third Bullet in the Window Sash" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene, Holmes identifies a bullet hole in the lower window sash that the police and doctor had missed, proving a third shot was fired and therefore a third person was involved." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A third bullet struck the window sash, proving a third person was present during the shooting." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The doctor accounted for only two bullets from the revolver matching two wounds. Holmes pointed out a hole drilled through the lower window sash about an inch above the bottom. When asked how he noticed it, Holmes replied 'Because I looked for it' — he had already deduced there must be a third party and searched for physical evidence to confirm it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abeSlaney ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cubittsRevolver, :brassCartridge ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Window Was Open During the Shooting" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deduces that both the window and the door were open at the time of the shooting, despite the servants finding the window shut and fastened." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The study window was open when the shots were fired." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The servants testified they smelled gunpowder the moment they ran out of their rooms on the top floor. Holmes reasoned that the fumes of powder could not have been blown so rapidly through the house unless both the window and door were open, creating a draught. He had drawn special attention to this testimony during the servants' examination." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ridlingThorpeStudy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Window Was Open Only Briefly" ;
    ex:description "Holmes determines that while the window was open during the shooting, it was open for only a very short time." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The window and door were open for only a very brief period." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the candle burning on the study table had not guttered, which would have occurred had the window remained open for any sustained period allowing a draught through the room." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ridlingThorpeStudy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Third Bullet Was Fired from Inside the Room" ;
    ex:description "Holmes determines from the splintering pattern of the wood around the bullet hole that the third shot was fired from inside the study outward through the window." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The third bullet was fired from inside the room toward someone outside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the bullet hole in the window sash and noted that the splintering of the wood clearly indicated the shot had been fired from inside the room, meaning someone in the study had fired at a person standing outside the window." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brassCartridge ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Elsie Shut the Window After the Shooting" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that it was Elsie Cubitt who shut and fastened the window after the shooting, explaining why it was found locked from inside despite an external intruder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Elsie Cubitt shut and fastened the window immediately after the shooting." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes stated that the woman's first instinct would be to shut and fasten the window. This explained the apparently impossible locked-room situation — the third shooter had fired from outside through the open window, and Elsie closed it after the exchange of shots." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elsiePatrick ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_18 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the First Explosion Was Two Simultaneous Shots" ;
    ex:description "Holmes infers that the loud first explosion heard by the servants was actually two shots fired almost simultaneously — one from inside and one from outside." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 18 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The first explosion was two shots fired nearly simultaneously by Cubitt and Slaney." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. King testified the first explosion seemed louder than the second. Holmes proposed that the apparent first explosion was in fact two shots fired almost at the same instant — one by the intruder outside and one by Cubitt inside — while the second, quieter shot was Elsie's self-inflicted wound." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hiltonCubitt ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abeSlaney ;
    ex:confirmedBy :abeSlaney ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dancingMenDoc .

:deduction_dancingMen_holmes_19 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Slaney Will Not Flee" ;
    ex:description "When Inspector Martin worries Slaney might escape, Holmes confidently predicts he will not attempt to flee." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 19 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Abe Slaney will not try to escape from Elrige's Farm." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that for Slaney to fly would be a confession of guilt. Slaney did not yet know the full extent of what had happened or that he had been identified, so flight would only incriminate him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
