:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Tregennis Made the Discovery" ;
    ex:description "When Roundhay and Mortimer Tregennis arrive at the cottage to report the tragedy, Holmes immediately determines which of the two men was the original discoverer of the scene, based on their clothing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mortimer Tregennis made the discovery first-hand while the vicar received the account second-hand, as evidenced by their respective states of dress." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Tregennis was formally dressed while the clergyman was hastily clad, indicating that Tregennis had been out and about earlier while the vicar had rushed from home after hearing the news. This told Holmes that Tregennis was the primary witness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roundhay ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Timing of the Attack" ;
    ex:description "While walking the cliffs with Watson after examining the crime scene at Tredannick Wartha, Holmes reasons about when the poisoning occurred relative to Mortimer Tregennis's departure." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The attack on the Tregennis siblings occurred immediately after Mortimer Tregennis left the room, not later than eleven o'clock at night." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The cards still lay on the table undisturbed and the victims had not moved from their positions or pushed back their chairs. It was already past their usual bedtime, yet they remained seated. This indicated the event struck within minutes of Mortimer's departure, before they had any chance to retire for the evening." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :brendaTregennis ;
    ex:deductionSubject :georgeTregennis ;
    ex:deductionSubject :owenTregennis ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tredannickWartha ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Verifies Mortimer Tregennis's Movements via Footprints" ;
    ex:description "At the Tredannick Wartha crime scene, Holmes deliberately stumbles over a watering-pot to wet the garden path, enabling him to obtain a clear imprint of Mortimer Tregennis's footprint for comparison with tracks on the sandy path." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mortimer Tregennis walked swiftly and directly from Tredannick Wartha to the vicarage after leaving his siblings, and his movements appear to be above suspicion." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes used the watering-pot trick to create a wet surface that captured a clear imprint of Tregennis's foot. He then matched this sample print against tracks on the wet, sandy path from the previous rainy night, confirming that Tregennis walked swiftly in the direction of the vicarage without deviation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tredannickWartha ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Rules Out an External Intruder at the Window" ;
    ex:description "During his analysis of the crime scene, Holmes considers whether someone could have approached the garden window of Tredannick Wartha to frighten the occupants, and concludes this is virtually impossible." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "No outsider approached the sitting-room window to terrorize the Tregennis siblings, as the flower border showed no footmarks and the dark, rainy night would have required the intruder to press against the glass to be seen." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The night was rainy, cloudy, and dark, meaning anyone attempting to alarm the occupants would have needed to place their face directly against the glass. There was a three-foot flower border outside the window with no indication of footmarks. Furthermore, Mortimer Tregennis's suggestion of something moving in the garden — which Holmes later identified as a deliberate misdirection — was the only evidence pointing in this direction." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tredannickWartha ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tredannickWartha ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sterndale's Disproportionate Interest" ;
    ex:description "After Dr. Leon Sterndale visits the cottage to inquire about the investigation, Holmes questions the explorer's claim that mere cousinship explains his abandoning his Africa voyage and returning to Cornwall." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sterndale's decision to abandon his journey to Africa and return to Cornwall upon hearing of the Tregennis tragedy suggests a deeper personal connection than distant family ties." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes verified via telegram to the Plymouth hotel that Sterndale had indeed spent the night there and allowed his baggage to go on to Africa while he returned. Abandoning a major expedition for distant cousins was disproportionate. Holmes identified this as an unexplained thread that might lead through the tangle of the case." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leonSterndale ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :roundhayTelegramToSterndale ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Combustion-Based Poison Caused the Deaths" ;
    ex:description "After examining the second crime scene where Mortimer Tregennis was found dead, Holmes synthesizes the common factors across both incidents to identify the mechanism of the poisoning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A toxic substance burned in a flame produced a poisonous atmosphere that caused madness and death, explaining both the Tredannick Wartha tragedy and Mortimer Tregennis's death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified three common factors: in each case, those who first entered the rooms were affected by the stuffy atmosphere (the doctor fainted, Mrs. Porter fainted, the servant fell ill); in each case there was combustion (a fire at Tredannick Wartha, a lamp in Tregennis's room); and the effects were proportional to ventilation — the fire partially vented up the chimney producing lesser effects (one death, two driven mad), while the lamp in the closed room produced complete lethality. The lamp had been burning long after daylight, as oil consumption measurements confirmed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :devilsFootRoot ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimerTregennisLamp, :tredannickWartha ;
    ex:confirmedBy :devilsFootExperiment ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Poison Residue on the Lamp Shield" ;
    ex:description "During his examination of Mortimer Tregennis's room at the vicarage, Holmes scrutinizes the talc shield atop the lamp chimney and discovers physical evidence of the poison." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Flaky ashes and a fringe of unconsumed brownish powder on the talc shield of Tregennis's lamp confirmed that a toxic substance had been burned on it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Having formed the hypothesis that a combustion-based poison was responsible, Holmes looked to the most logical place for residue — the talc smoke-guard of the lamp. There he found flaky ashes and brownish powder that had not yet been fully consumed, which he collected in an envelope for the self-experiment that followed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennisLamp ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimerTregennisLamp ;
    ex:confirmedBy :devilsFootExperiment ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Mortimer Tregennis as the First Poisoner" ;
    ex:description "After the self-experiment confirms the combustion-poison theory, Holmes reasons in the arbour with Watson about who committed the first crime at Tredannick Wartha, concluding it was Mortimer Tregennis himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mortimer Tregennis poisoned his own siblings by placing the devil's-foot powder in the fire as he left the room, motivated by a family quarrel over money." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes cited multiple converging lines of evidence: the family quarrel about money and Mortimer's unforgiving disposition; Mortimer originated the misleading suggestion about something moving in the garden, indicating a motive to misdirect the investigation; the poisoning happened immediately after his departure; and if anyone else had entered the room, the family would have risen from the table — in peaceful Cornwall, no visitors arrived after ten at night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tredannickWartha, :devilsFootRoot ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Sterndale as Mortimer Tregennis's Killer" ;
    ex:description "Holmes traces physical evidence from the vicarage crime scene to Dr. Sterndale's cottage, identifying the explorer as the person who killed Mortimer Tregennis in retribution." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Leon Sterndale killed Mortimer Tregennis by burning the devil's-foot powder on his lamp, as proven by gravel from Sterndale's gate found on the vicarage window-sill, the lamp burning in daylight, and powder residue on the shield." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The gravel on the bedroom window-sill was unlike anything in the vicarage garden but matched gravel at Sterndale's cottage gate. The lamp shining in broad daylight indicated it had been lit as a vehicle for the poison rather than for illumination. The powder residue on the talc shield completed the chain. Holmes had also followed Sterndale after his visit and observed him lingering near the vicarage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leonSterndale ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimerTregennisLamp, :sterndaleBungalow ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Sterndale's Exact Movements on the Murder Morning" ;
    ex:description "In his confrontation with Sterndale, Holmes presents a detailed reconstruction of the explorer's actions on the morning he killed Mortimer Tregennis, demonstrating comprehensive knowledge of every step." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sterndale left his cottage at dawn, gathered reddish gravel from the pile by his gate, walked to the vicarage, threw gravel at the lodger's window to rouse him, entered through the sitting-room window, confronted Tregennis, lit the lamp with the poison, and watched from outside as the man died." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes tracked Sterndale's ribbed tennis shoes from his cottage to the vicarage, observed the route through the orchard and side hedge to the lodger's window, and deduced the gravel-throwing from the pebbles on the window-sill. The sitting-room window provided the entry point, and the lamp with powder residue showed how the poison was administered. Holmes had previously followed Sterndale and noted his agitated behaviour near the vicarage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leonSterndale ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sterndaleBungalow, :tredannickWollasVicarage, :mortimerTregennisLamp ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_devilsFoot_leonsterndale_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sterndale Deduces Mortimer Tregennis Used His Poison" ;
    ex:description "Upon returning from Plymouth after receiving the vicar's telegram about the Tredannick Wartha tragedy, Dr. Sterndale independently concludes that Mortimer Tregennis must have stolen and used the devil's-foot root powder that Sterndale had shown him." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mortimer Tregennis stole the devil's-foot powder during a visit to Sterndale's cottage and used it to murder his sister Brenda and drive his brothers insane, motivated by greed over the family property." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Sterndale recalled that Mortimer had recently visited his cottage where he had shown him the devil's-foot root and explained its properties. Mortimer had plied him with questions about dosage and timing. Upon hearing of the tragedy's symptoms — terror-induced madness and death with no signs of violence — Sterndale immediately recognized the effects of the poison. He visited Holmes hoping for an alternative explanation but found none, confirming his conviction that Mortimer was the killer." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :leonSterndale ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimerTregennis ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :devilsFootRoot ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_devilsFoot_holmes_08 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :devilsFootDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Culverton Smith Murdered Victor Savage" ;
    ex:description "Prior to the events of the story, Holmes investigated the death of Victor Savage and formed suspicions of foul play by Culverton Smith, which he allowed Smith to perceive." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Culverton Smith murdered his nephew Victor Savage using a deliberately administered exotic disease." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted the singular coincidence that Victor Savage died of a rare Asiatic disease in the heart of London, and that Culverton Smith had made a special study of that very disease on his Sumatran plantation. The improbability of natural contraction combined with Smith's unique expertise and his position as heir pointed to deliberate murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :culvertonSmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :victorSavage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :investigationVictorSavageDeath, :murderOfVictorSavage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :smithConfessionAt221B ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Disease Was Delivered via a Mechanical Device" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deduced that the exotic disease was administered to Victor Savage through some kind of physical device rather than natural infection, a method Smith later attempted to use on Holmes himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The disease agent was delivered through a spring-loaded mechanism concealed in a small ivory box sent by post." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized that a rare tropical disease appearing in London required deliberate transmission. When he received an ivory box by post that contained a sharp spring which drew blood upon opening, he connected this device to the method by which Savage must have been similarly infected, comparing the spring to a viper's tooth." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dyingDetectiveIvoryBox ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dyingDetectiveIvoryBox, :attemptedMurderOfHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :smithConfessionAt221B ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts Smith Will Come to Gloat" ;
    ex:description "Holmes devised his elaborate feigned illness scheme based on his psychological assessment that Smith's vindictive nature would compel him to come to 221B Baker Street to witness Holmes's apparent death." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Culverton Smith's vindictive character would drive him to visit Holmes to observe the effects of his handiwork." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Knowing Smith's vindictive nature from their prior dealings over the Victor Savage case, Holmes was perfectly certain that Smith would come to look upon his handiwork if he believed his poisoned box had succeeded in fatally infecting Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :culvertonSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :investigationVictorSavageDeath ;
    ex:confirmedBy :smithConfessionAt221B ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson's Examination Would Expose the Ruse" ;
    ex:description "Holmes refused to allow Watson to approach or examine him, reasoning that Watson's medical competence would immediately reveal the absence of genuine illness." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson's medical examination would detect no rise in pulse or temperature and thus expose the feigned illness." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized that while he could produce convincing visual symptoms of disease through fasting, vaseline, belladonna, rouge, and beeswax, these cosmetic deceptions would not withstand a physician's clinical examination at close range. At four yards he could deceive Watson, but not by touch or pulse measurement." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesFeignedIllness ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Feigned Confession Can Be Extracted from Smith" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasoned that by pretending Smith's poisoned box had succeeded, he could surprise Smith into making an incriminating confession in the presence of a hidden witness." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Pretending the poisoned box had worked would surprise Smith into confessing to both the murder of Savage and the attempted murder of Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes calculated that if Smith believed Holmes was truly dying from the box's contents, Smith's vindictive and gloating nature would lead him to speak freely about the murder, not imagining Holmes could be feigning or that a witness might be concealed nearby. The gas-turning signal would then bring Inspector Morton to make the arrest." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :culvertonSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesFeignedIllness, :dyingDetectiveIvoryBox ;
    ex:confirmedBy :smithConfessionAt221B ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfCulvertonSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_dyingDetective_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Diagnosis: Holmes Is Genuinely Delirious and Dying" ;
    ex:description "Upon observing Holmes's gaunt appearance, feverish eyes, hectic flush, dark lip crusts, twitching hands, and erratic speech about oysters and half-crowns, Watson concluded that Holmes was suffering from genuine delirium caused by a deadly Eastern disease." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes is genuinely ill with a deadly contagious disease and is experiencing mental disorganization from fever and delirium." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed Holmes's wasted face, bright feverish eyes, hectic spots on the cheeks, dark crusts on the lips, twitching hands, croaking voice, and rambling speech about oysters and extraneous subjects. Combined with Holmes's refusal of medical help and Mrs. Hudson's report of three days without food or drink, Watson concluded Holmes was in the grip of a deadly tropical disease causing severe physical and mental deterioration." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesFeignedIllness ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_dyingDetective_holmes_04 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :dyingDetectiveDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Dangerous Confederate Was Present at Reichenbach" ;
    ex:description "After Moriarty fell from the Reichenbach ledge, Holmes was struck by a large rock hurled from the cliff above. A glance upward revealed a man's head silhouetted against the sky, confirming that Moriarty had not acted alone." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty had a dangerous confederate who remained at Reichenbach to finish Holmes off after the Professor's death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When a huge rock narrowly missed Holmes on the ledge, he initially considered it an accident, but a second stone and the sight of a man's head against the sky proved deliberate intent. Holmes noted that even a single glance revealed how dangerous this confederate was." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Feigning Death Will Expose His Enemies" ;
    ex:description "Immediately after Moriarty's death at Reichenbach, Holmes rapidly formulated a strategic plan to disappear rather than reveal his survival." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "If the world believes Holmes dead, his remaining enemies will grow careless and expose themselves, allowing him to destroy them." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes knew at least three dangerous men besides Moriarty sought his death. If convinced he was dead, they would take liberties and lay themselves open. Holmes could then return and destroy them at the opportune moment. He believed he had worked this out before Moriarty even reached the bottom of the falls." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :moriartyCriminalOrganization ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :confrontationAtReichenbach ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfRonaldAdair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Parker as the Sentinel Watching Baker Street" ;
    ex:description "Upon returning to Baker Street and glancing out of his window, Holmes recognized a man keeping watch on the building." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The sentinel watching 221B Baker Street is Parker, a garroter and performer on the Jew's harp." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized Parker by sight when he glanced out of his window at Baker Street. He identified him as a harmless garroter by trade, dismissing him as no direct threat but recognizing him as a lookout for a far more dangerous figure." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :parkerGarroter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Colonel Moran Is Behind the Surveillance" ;
    ex:description "Holmes dismissed the sentinel Parker as harmless but deduced that a far more formidable figure was directing the surveillance of Baker Street from behind the scenes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Colonel Sebastian Moran, Moriarty's chief lieutenant and the Reichenbach rock-thrower, is the dangerous mastermind watching Holmes's rooms." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the sentinel's presence to the remnants of the Moriarty organization, identifying the figure behind Parker as the bosom friend of Moriarty and the man who had thrown rocks at Holmes on the Reichenbach ledge — the most cunning and dangerous criminal in London." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :parkerGarroter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :camdenHouseStakeout ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Colonel Moran Murdered Ronald Adair" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning of the Park Lane Mystery during his time abroad, Holmes immediately connected the murder to Colonel Moran, recognizing it as the opportunity he had been waiting for." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Colonel Moran shot Ronald Adair through the open window of 427 Park Lane with an expanding bullet from Von Herder's air-gun." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had been watching criminal news for any chance to apprehend Moran. Knowing Moran's capabilities and character, Holmes recognized that Moran had played cards with Adair, followed him home from the club, and shot him through the open window. The distinctive expanding bullets from the silent air-gun were sufficient evidence to convict." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ronaldAdair ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :expandingBullets, :vonHerderAirGun ;
    ex:confirmedBy :camdenHouseStakeout ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts Moran Will Attempt Assassination" ;
    ex:description "Having deliberately revealed his return to London, Holmes predicted that Moran would be compelled to act immediately against him, and laid a trap using the wax bust at Baker Street." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moran will be driven to attempt Holmes's assassination using his air-gun upon learning of Holmes's return." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes allowed himself to be seen by the sentinel, knowing this would be reported to Moran. Moran could not fail to connect Holmes's sudden return with his crime and would be terribly alarmed, compelling him to bring his murderous weapon and attempt to eliminate Holmes at once. Holmes placed the wax bust as bait in the lighted window." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesWaxBust, :parkerGarroter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :camdenHouseStakeout ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Assesses Moran's Exceptional Marksmanship" ;
    ex:description "After Moran's capture, Holmes examined the shattered forehead of the wax bust and assessed the quality of the shot." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moran's shot struck precisely in the centre of the back of the head, confirming he remains one of the finest marksmen in London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes inspected the bullet's entry point on the wax bust and noted it hit plumb in the middle of the back of the head and passed through the brain. He connected this precision to Moran's reputation as the best shot in India, concluding few in London could match him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesWaxBust, :expandingBullets ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moran's Motive for Murdering Adair" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation to Watson at Baker Street, Holmes offered a theory about why Moran killed Adair, entering what he called the realms of conjecture." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Adair discovered Moran was cheating at cards and threatened to expose him, so Moran murdered Adair to prevent the ruin that expulsion from his clubs would bring." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Moran undoubtedly played foul at cards, and Holmes had long been aware of it. Holmes believed Adair discovered the cheating and privately threatened to expose Moran unless he resigned from the club. Rather than face ruin, Moran killed Adair, who at the time was calculating how much money he should return since he could not profit from his partner's dishonesty." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ronaldAdair ;
    ex:deductionSubject :colonelSebastianMoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :adairMoranCardWinnings, :adairMoneyPiles, :adairCardSheet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Disguised Man Is a Bibliophile" ;
    ex:description "Outside 427 Park Lane, Watson accidentally knocked books from the hands of an elderly, deformed man and attempted to assess his identity from the volumes he carried." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The elderly deformed man carrying obscure volumes is a poor bibliophile who collects rare books as a trade or hobby." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed the man carrying several books, noted the title of one — The Origin of Tree Worship — and concluded from its obscurity that the man must be a collector of rare volumes, either professionally or as a hobbyist." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :originOfTreeWorship ;
    ex:refutedBy :holmesReturnToLondon ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_emptyHouse_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Identifies Plainclothes Police in the Doorway" ;
    ex:description "During the stakeout at Camden House, Watson noticed two men sheltering in a doorway up the street and tried to draw Holmes's attention to them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The two men sheltering from the wind in a doorway near Baker Street are plainclothes police officers." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed two men who appeared to be deliberately sheltering themselves in the doorway of a house some distance up the street, and their behaviour struck him as significant enough to point out to Holmes. Holmes later confirmed Watson had spotted the police presence with unerring accuracy." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lestrade ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :emptyHouseDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_victorhatherley_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hatherley Deduces the Fuller's-Earth Story Is Fabrication" ;
    ex:description "While examining the hydraulic press at Colonel Stark's house, Hatherley inspects the interior of the main chamber after diagnosing the mechanical fault and realizes the stated purpose of the machine is a lie." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The fuller's-earth explanation is a fabrication; the press is being used for some other purpose involving metal, as evidenced by metallic deposits in the iron trough." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Hatherley observed that so powerful an engine could not possibly be designed for compressing fuller's-earth, an inadequate purpose for such force. The walls were of wood but the floor was a large iron trough covered with a crust of metallic deposit, which he stooped to scrape and examine." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :victorHatherley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :starkHydraulicPress ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :starkHydraulicPress ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Connects Hayling Disappearance to Stark's Scheme" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Hatherley's full account at 221B Baker Street, Holmes consults his commonplace book of newspaper cuttings and produces a year-old advertisement for the missing hydraulic engineer Jeremiah Hayling." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The missing hydraulic engineer Jeremiah Hayling was a previous victim of Colonel Stark, who used the same scheme of hiring an engineer to inspect his press and then silencing him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the pattern: Hayling was a hydraulic engineer of similar age who disappeared after leaving his lodgings at night, matching exactly the circumstances of Hatherley's commission. Holmes concluded that Hayling's disappearance represented the last time the colonel needed his machine overhauled." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jeremiahHayling ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lysanderStark ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :haylingAdvertisement ;
    ex:confirmedBy :elise ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the House Is Near Eyford, Not Twelve Miles Away" ;
    ex:description "On the train to Eyford, when Inspector Bradstreet draws a ten-mile circle on an ordnance map and each person guesses a different compass direction, Holmes places his finger on the centre of the circle." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The house is actually near Eyford itself, not ten or twelve miles away; the carriage drive was a ruse — six miles out and six miles back to the same vicinity." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that Hatherley himself said the horse was fresh and glossy when he boarded the carriage. A horse that had truly travelled twelve miles over heavy country roads could not have appeared fresh. Therefore, the hour-long drive was a deception, driving out and back to make Hatherley believe the house was far from the station when it was actually nearby." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :becherHouse ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :starkCarriage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :becherHouseFire ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Gang as Coiners" ;
    ex:description "Immediately after deducing the location, Holmes states with certainty the nature of the criminal operation that Stark and his associates were conducting." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The gang are coiners on a large scale who have been using the hydraulic press to form the amalgam that has taken the place of silver in counterfeit half-crowns." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined Hatherley's observation of metallic deposits in the press trough with the secrecy, the remote location, the enormous power of the hydraulic press, and the implausibility of the fuller's-earth cover story to conclude the press was being used to manufacture counterfeit coinage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :starkCounterfeitingGang ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :starkHydraulicPress, :counterfeitHalfCrowns ;
    ex:confirmedBy :counterfeiterMetals ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Hatherley's Oil-Lamp Caused the Fire" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at Eyford and discovering the house ablaze, Holmes immediately identifies the cause of the fire." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Hatherley's oil-lamp, left on the floor of the press chamber, was crushed when the hydraulic press descended and set fire to the wooden walls of the chamber." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled from Hatherley's account that the lamp was still standing on the floor when the press began descending. When the ceiling-piston crushed the lamp, the burning oil ignited the wooden walls of the press chamber. The criminals were too occupied chasing Hatherley to notice the fire starting." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :becherHouseFire ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :starkHydraulicPress ;
    ex:confirmedBy :becherHouseFire ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :engineersThumbDoc .

:deduction_engineersThumb_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Criminals Have Already Fled" ;
    ex:description "At the burning house, Holmes advises Hatherley to watch for his assailants in the crowd but expresses his belief that they are already long gone." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The criminals have fled and are already a hundred miles away from Eyford." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assessed that the criminals, upon discovering the fire, would have recognized their operation was exposed and fled immediately rather than attempt to save the burning house or remain in the area." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :starkCounterfeitingGang ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :becherHouseFire ;
