:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Moriarty as the Organizing Power Behind London Crime" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains to Watson that over years of investigating London's criminal world, he has detected a hidden organizing force behind many unrelated crimes, which he has traced to Professor Moriarty." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Professor Moriarty is the central organizer behind much of London's criminal activity, operating an invisible syndicate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed a recurring pattern across diverse criminal cases — forgery, robbery, murder — where an unseen power shielded wrongdoers and obstructed justice. Following this thread through a thousand cunning windings, he traced it to ex-Professor Moriarty, whose mathematical genius and criminal hereditary tendencies made him uniquely capable of orchestrating such an enterprise." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionSubject :moriartyCriminalOrganization ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :investigationOfMoriartyOrg ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfMoriartyGang ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Three Attacks Were Ordered by Moriarty" ;
    ex:description "After surviving a van nearly running him down, a brick falling from a rooftop, and a bludgeon assault all in one day, Holmes attributes all three to Moriarty's agents rather than to accident." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The van attack, brick incident, and bludgeon assault were all assassination attempts orchestrated by Moriarty's agents." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected three apparently separate incidents — a furiously driven two-horse van that nearly struck him on Welbeck Street crossing, a brick that fell from a roof on Vere Street, and a bludgeon attack by a rough — recognizing them as a coordinated series of murder attempts. Though the police attributed the brick to wind-toppled repair materials, Holmes knew better, and predicted no connection would ever be traced between the bludgeon-man and Moriarty." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :vanAttackOnHolmes, :brickAttackOnHolmes, :bludgeonAttackOnHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moriarty's Agents Watched Watson to Track Him" ;
    ex:description "At Victoria Station, after Moriarty appears on the platform trying to stop their train, Holmes deduces how Moriarty tracked them despite Holmes's own successful evasion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty's agents were surveilling Watson rather than Holmes, which is how Moriarty learned they were departing from Victoria Station." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since Moriarty's organization lost track of Holmes after the bludgeon-man's arrest — evidenced by their setting fire to Baker Street thinking Holmes had returned — they must have shifted surveillance to Watson instead. Watson's departure for Victoria led Moriarty directly to the station." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :moriartyAtVictoria, :fireAtBakerStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Baker Street Fire Proves Moriarty Lost His Trail" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning of the fire at 221B Baker Street, Holmes infers that Moriarty's agents had lost track of him and mistakenly believed he had returned to his rooms." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The arson attack on Baker Street proves Moriarty's organization lost track of Holmes after the bludgeon-man's arrest." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that the fire at Baker Street could only have been set if Moriarty's agents believed Holmes was inside. Since Holmes had not returned there, this meant they had lost his trail completely after the arrest of the bludgeon attacker." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fireAtBakerStreet, :bludgeonAttackOnHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts Moriarty Will Engage a Special Train" ;
    ex:description "When Watson suggests they have shaken Moriarty off by catching the Continental express, Holmes predicts Moriarty will hire a special train to overtake them at Canterbury." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty will engage a special train to catch up with Holmes and Watson at Canterbury." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes applied the principle that Moriarty is his intellectual equal and would do exactly what Holmes himself would do as a pursuer. Since the express stops at Canterbury with a delay at the boat, a special train could close the gap. Holmes asked Watson not to think so meanly of Moriarty as to assume a mere express train would baffle him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:confirmedBy :chaseAtCanterbury ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts Moriarty Will Track Their Luggage to Paris" ;
    ex:description "After evading Moriarty at Canterbury, Holmes predicts Moriarty's next move will be to follow their luggage to Paris and wait at the depot." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty will proceed to Paris, trace their luggage, and wait at the depot for two days expecting them to collect it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes again applied the principle that Moriarty would do what Holmes himself would do. Having missed them at Canterbury, the logical next step would be to track their luggage, which continued on the express to Paris. Holmes planned accordingly, abandoning their luggage and purchasing carpet-bags to travel incognito through Luxembourg and Basel to Switzerland." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moriarty Will Pursue Revenge After Escaping Arrest" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning that Moriarty alone escaped the police dragnet that captured the rest of his gang, Holmes deduces that Moriarty will devote all his energies to personal vengeance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty, having lost his criminal organization, will devote himself entirely to pursuing and killing Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes read Moriarty's character as that of a man whose occupation was now gone and who would be lost if he returned to London. Combined with Moriarty's explicit threat during their confrontation at 221B, Holmes concluded Moriarty would channel all his remaining resources into revenge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :moriartyHolmesConfrontation221B, :arrestOfMoriartyGang ;
    ex:confirmedBy :confrontationAtReichenbach ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Falling Rock at Daubensee Was Deliberate" ;
    ex:description "While crossing the Gemmi Pass, a large rock dislodges from the ridge and crashes into the Daubensee. Despite their guide's assurance it was a natural occurrence, Holmes races to the ridge to investigate and concludes it was deliberate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The falling rock near the Daubensee was a deliberate attempt by Moriarty's agents, not a natural rockfall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Though their Swiss guide attributed the falling rock to the common springtime occurrence of loose stones, Holmes rejected this explanation. He raced to the ridge and surveyed the area in every direction, then smiled at Watson with the air of a man seeing the fulfillment of what he expected — confirming his belief that Moriarty's agents were tracking them." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :rockIncidentDaubensee ;
    ex:confirmedBy :confrontationAtReichenbach ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Meiringen Letter Was a Hoax" ;
    ex:description "In his farewell letter left at Reichenbach Falls, Holmes reveals he had suspected the letter summoning Watson back to Meiringen was a trap designed to separate them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter from the Englischer Hof requesting Watson to attend a dying Englishwoman was a hoax designed by Moriarty to isolate Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes wrote in his farewell letter that he was quite convinced the letter from Meiringen was a hoax and deliberately allowed Watson to depart under the persuasion that some development of this sort would follow. He recognized the ruse as Moriarty's method of isolating him for the final confrontation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :forgedHotelLetter ;
