:deduction_finalProblem_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Reconstructs the Fatal Struggle at Reichenbach" ;
    ex:description "Returning to Reichenbach Falls to find Holmes missing, Watson applies Holmes's own methods to read the evidence at the scene and reconstruct what happened." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes and Moriarty engaged in a physical struggle at the end of the path and both fell to their deaths in the chasm." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson found Holmes's Alpine-stock still leaning where he left it, proving Holmes never departed for Rosenlaui. The soft blackish soil showed two lines of footmarks leading away toward the end of the path with none returning. Near the edge, the soil was ploughed into mud and the bordering branches and ferns were torn and bedraggled, indicating a violent struggle. Watson combined these observations to conclude both men had reeled over the precipice locked in combat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesAlpineStock, :reichenbachFalls ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesFarewellLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_finalProblem_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Swiss Messenger Was Moriarty's Agent" ;
    ex:description "In the narrative's closing reflections, Watson concludes that the young Swiss messenger who had accompanied them was in Moriarty's employ, having disappeared after leaving Holmes alone at the falls." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Swiss youth who served as their guide was one of Moriarty's agents, placed to abandon Holmes at the critical moment." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The young Swiss messenger vanished after being left alone with Holmes at the falls and was never found again. Watson reasoned that the messenger must have been in Moriarty's pay, having deliberately left the two men together to enable the final confrontation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :swissMessengerReichenbach ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :finalProblemDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Incorrect Conjecture About the Late Visitor" ;
    ex:description "On a stormy night at 221B Baker Street, Holmes hears the doorbell and speculates about who would venture out in such weather." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The late visitor is more likely a crony of the landlady's than a client, since the severe weather would deter most people from making a social or professional call." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the extreme storm would only bring out someone with a serious case, but then judged it more probable that the caller was merely an acquaintance of the landlady. The arrival of John Openshaw as a desperate client immediately disproved this." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:refutedBy :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Openshaw Travelled From the South-West" ;
    ex:description "Upon taking John Openshaw's coat and umbrella, Holmes immediately identifies the direction from which the young man has travelled." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Openshaw has come from the south-west, specifically from Horsham, based on the clay and chalk mixture on his boots." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed a distinctive clay and chalk mixture on Openshaw's toe caps, which he recognized as characteristic of the south-western region. Openshaw confirmed he had come from Horsham." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Colonel Openshaw Fled America Out of Fear" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Openshaw's account, Holmes sits by the fire and begins his analysis of the case, starting with Colonel Elias Openshaw's departure from America." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Colonel Openshaw had a compelling reason — fear of someone or something — for leaving the pleasant climate of Florida to live as a recluse in an English provincial town." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that men of the Colonel's age do not willingly abandon all their habits and exchange Florida's charming climate for lonely English rural life. The Colonel's extreme love of solitude and reclusive behavior in England suggest he was fleeing from a person or group he feared." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eliasOpenshaw ;
    ex:confirmedBy :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Pursuers Travel by Sailing Ship" ;
    ex:description "Building on Watson's observation about seaports, Holmes analyzes the time intervals between the threatening letters and the subsequent deaths to determine the type of vessel used." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The perpetrators travel by sailing ship rather than steamer, as the delay between threat and execution corresponds to the slower speed of a sailing vessel compared to the mail service." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "In the Pondicherry case, seven weeks elapsed between the letter and Elias's death, while in Dundee only three or four days passed. Holmes reasoned that if the perpetrators used a steamer, they would have arrived almost as soon as their letter. The seven-week delay from Pondicherry represents the difference between the fast mail-boat carrying the letter and the slow sailing vessel carrying the killers." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :loneStar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deathOfEliasOpenshaw, :deathOfJosephOpenshaw ;
    ex:confirmedBy :loneStar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Deadly Urgency of John Openshaw's Situation" ;
    ex:description "Holmes applies his sailing-ship theory to John Openshaw's case, noting that the latest letter was posted from London rather than a distant port." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Openshaw is in immediate mortal danger because the latest threatening letter was posted from London, meaning the killers are already nearby and there will be no delay between warning and attack." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "In previous cases, the victims had a grace period corresponding to the sailing time from the letter's origin to England. Since John's letter came from London itself, the perpetrators are already present and can strike at any moment without the delay that previously separated threat from execution." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_04 ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfJohnOpenshaw ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Multiple Perpetrators Are Involved" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons about the number of people behind the threatening letters and the deaths of Elias and Joseph Openshaw." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There must be several perpetrators rather than a lone killer, because a single person could not have carried out two deaths in ways that deceived two separate coroner's juries." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that both deaths were staged to appear accidental or self-inflicted — Elias was found drowned in a shallow pool and Joseph fell into a chalk pit — and both juries returned non-homicide verdicts. He concluded that engineering such convincing disguised murders on two separate occasions required the resources and coordination of multiple individuals." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :captainJamesCalhoun ;
    ex:deductionSubject :calhounMates ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deathOfEliasOpenshaw, :deathOfJosephOpenshaw ;
    ex:confirmedBy :loneStar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies K.K.K. as the Ku Klux Klan" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies the meaning of the mysterious initials that have terrorized the Openshaw family, drawing on his encyclopaedic knowledge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letters K.K.K. stand for the Ku Klux Klan, the American secret society formed by ex-Confederate soldiers that used intimidation tactics including sending warning tokens such as orange pips." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes consulted the American Encyclopaedia and matched the K.K.K. initials, the orange pips as a warning token, and the pattern of threats followed by death to the methods of the Ku Klux Klan. The encyclopaedia confirmed that the Klan's outrages were preceded by warnings sent in fantastic but recognized shapes, including orange pips, and that failure to comply invariably led to death." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :americanEncyclopaedia ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eliasOpenshawDiaryPage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Openshaw's Departure Caused the Klan's Collapse" ;
    ex:description "After reading the encyclopaedia entry, Holmes connects the timing of the Klan's sudden collapse with Colonel Openshaw's departure from America." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Colonel Openshaw's departure from America with the Klan's papers was the cause of — or at least coincident with — the Klan's sudden collapse around 1869, and the Klan's implacable pursuit of the family is driven by the need to recover those incriminating documents." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the encyclopaedia dates the Klan's sudden collapse to 1869, which coincides with Colonel Openshaw leaving America. He reasoned that the Colonel took with him a register and papers that could implicate prominent Southern men, and that the Klan's dissolution and subsequent pursuit of the Openshaw family were cause and effect." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eliasOpenshaw ;
    ex:deductionSubject :kuKluxKlan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :americanEncyclopaedia, :kkkBrassBox ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Diary Page as a Klan Operations Record" ;
    ex:description "Holmes interprets the cryptic entries on the surviving page from Colonel Openshaw's papers, connecting them to Klan activities described in the encyclopaedia." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The diary page records Klan operations: 'sent the pips' means sending the society's warning; 'cleared' means the target fled or complied; and 'visited' with its sinister implication means the target was killed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes read the entries — 'Set the pips on McCauley, Paramore, and John Swain,' followed by 'McCauley cleared,' 'John Swain cleared,' and 'Visited Paramore. All well' — and matched them to the Klan's known method of sending warnings before acting. 'Cleared' indicated the targets had submitted or fled, while 'Visited Paramore' with 'All well' carried a sinister implication that Paramore had been dealt with fatally." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eliasOpenshawDiaryPage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :eliasOpenshawDiaryPage, :americanEncyclopaedia ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces John Openshaw Was Murdered" ;
    ex:description "The morning after Openshaw's visit, Holmes reads a newspaper report of a body recovered near Waterloo Bridge and immediately concludes it was murder, not an accident." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Openshaw was murdered by the Klan agents, who decoyed him to the Embankment and pushed him into the Thames, despite the official verdict of accidental death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the Embankment is not on the direct line from Baker Street to Waterloo Station, meaning Openshaw must have been lured off his route. The dark, stormy night provided ideal cover. Holmes recognized the same pattern of disguised murder used against Elias and Joseph Openshaw — a death made to appear accidental that deceived the authorities." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnOpenshaw ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderOfJohnOpenshaw ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Captain Calhoun and the Lone Star" ;
    ex:description "After a full day of research at Lloyd's registers and old newspaper files, Holmes traces the source of the threatening letters to a specific vessel and its captain." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The perpetrators are Captain James Calhoun and two mates aboard the barque Lone Star of Savannah, Georgia, who are the only native-born Americans on the ship." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes searched Lloyd's registers for every vessel that touched at Pondicherry in January–February 1883, finding thirty-six ships. The Lone Star attracted his attention because its name references an American state despite being reported as clearing from London. He then confirmed the Lone Star was in Dundee in January 1885, matching the second letter's postmark. Finding the ship had recently arrived in London and departed for Savannah, Holmes identified the captain as James Calhoun and learned from the stevedore that Calhoun and two mates — the only Americans aboard — were all absent from the ship on the night of Openshaw's murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :captainJamesCalhoun ;
    ex:deductionSubject :calhounMates ;
    ex:deductionSubject :loneStar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :loneStar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_fiveOrangePips_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Letter Writer Was on a Ship" ;
    ex:description "During Holmes's analysis of the case, Watson contributes an inference when Holmes asks what can be deduced from the postmarks of the three threatening letters." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The writer of the threatening letters was on board a ship, since all three postmark cities — Pondicherry, Dundee, and East London — are seaports." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes pointed out that the letters were sent from Pondicherry, Dundee, and East London. Watson observed that all three are seaports and concluded the writer must have been aboard a vessel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :captainJamesCalhoun ;
    ex:confirmedBy :loneStar ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :fiveOrangePipsDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Fears a Personal Attack" ;
    ex:description "During an evening at Donnithorpe after dinner, old Trevor challenges Holmes to deduce something about him. Holmes immediately identifies that Trevor has been living in fear of a personal attack within the last twelve months." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor has gone about in fear of some personal attack within the last twelve months." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Trevor possessed a handsome walking stick less than a year old, as shown by its inscription. However, Trevor had taken pains to bore the head and pour melted lead into the hole, converting it into a formidable weapon. Holmes argued that such precautions would only be taken by a man who feared some danger." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :trevorWalkingStick ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Boxed in His Youth" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his reading of old Trevor during the after-dinner demonstration at Donnithorpe, Holmes identifies that Trevor was a boxer in his younger days." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor boxed a good deal in his youth." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the peculiar flattening and thickening of Trevor's ears, which he recognized as the distinctive marks of a boxing man. He noted that it was the ears, not the nose, that betrayed the habit." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Has Done Much Digging" ;
    ex:description "In the same demonstration at Donnithorpe, Holmes observes physical evidence on Trevor's hands that points to extensive manual labor involving digging." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor has done a good deal of digging." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the callosities on Trevor's hands and identified them as consistent with extensive digging work. Trevor confirmed that he made all his money at the gold fields." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Has Been in New Zealand" ;
    ex:description "During the after-dinner reading of old Trevor, Holmes states that Trevor has been in New Zealand. The specific reasoning is not detailed in the text." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor has been in New Zealand." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The text does not provide Holmes's specific chain of reasoning for this deduction. It is presented as one of a series of observations during his reading of Trevor, who confirms it without Holmes being asked to explain." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Has Visited Japan" ;
    ex:description "Continuing the demonstration, Holmes states that old Trevor has visited Japan. As with the New Zealand deduction, the specific reasoning is not explained in the text." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor has visited Japan." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The text does not provide Holmes's specific chain of reasoning for this deduction. Trevor confirms it simply with the words 'Quite true.' The basis may be connected to physical or material observations Holmes made but chose not to elaborate upon." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Old Trevor Was Associated With J.A. and Wished to Forget Them" ;
    ex:description "As the climax of his reading of old Trevor, Holmes reveals that Trevor was once intimately associated with someone whose initials were J.A., and whom he was afterwards eager to entirely forget. This deduction causes Trevor to faint." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Old Trevor was intimately associated with someone whose initials were J.A., whom he afterwards wished to entirely forget." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Trevor bared his arm while drawing a fish into the boat, Holmes observed that the letters J.A. had been tattooed in the bend of the elbow. Though still legible, the letters were blurred and the surrounding skin was stained, showing that efforts had been made to obliterate them. Holmes concluded that the initials had once been very familiar to Trevor but that he had later wished to forget them." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jaInitials ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesArmitage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Cracks the Coded Letter Using Every Third Word" ;
    ex:description "After old Trevor's death, Holmes examines the seemingly trivial letter from Fordingbridge that caused the fatal shock. Reasoning that the letter must contain a hidden meaning, Holmes tries several approaches before discovering the cipher." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The coded letter from Beddoes contains a hidden message readable by taking every third word beginning with the first: 'The game is up. Hudson has told all. Fly for your life.'" ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Fordingbridge was in Hampshire, where Beddoes lived, so the letter came from either Hudson or Beddoes. Since the son described it as trivial yet it killed the father, it must contain a secret code. The presence of the word Hudson confirmed the subject matter and suggested Beddoes as sender rather than the sailor. Holmes tried reading backwards and alternate words before discovering that every third word, beginning with the first, yielded the warning message." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :codedLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :codedLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :victorTrevor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Beddoes Is a Sportsman From the Cipher Filler Words" ;
    ex:description "After cracking the cipher, Holmes analyzes the filler words used between the meaningful words in the coded letter and draws a conclusion about the sender's interests." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Beddoes is either an ardent shot or interested in breeding, based on the sporting terminology used as filler words in the cipher." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the sender had to fill two words between each meaningful word to complete the cipher. The filler words naturally reflected the sender's sphere of interest, and many referred to sport — game, head-keeper, fly-paper, hen-pheasant, preservation. Holmes concluded the sender was likely a sportsman. Victor Trevor confirmed that his father used to receive invitations from Beddoes to shoot over his preserves." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beddoes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :codedLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :victorTrevor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_gloriaScott_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Theory: Beddoes Killed Hudson and Fled" ;
    ex:description "In his concluding remarks to Watson, Holmes offers his theory on the final fates of Hudson and Beddoes, both of whom disappeared after the letter of warning was written. His theory is the opposite of the police's belief." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Beddoes, pushed to desperation and believing himself already betrayed, killed Hudson and fled the country with as much money as he could gather." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The police believed Hudson had killed Beddoes and fled, since Hudson had been seen lurking about. Holmes reasoned the opposite: Beddoes, already desperate and believing himself betrayed by Hudson's threats, would have had stronger motive to act violently. No complaint had been lodged with the police, suggesting Beddoes had mistaken a threat for an accomplished deed, and had taken preemptive revenge upon Hudson before fleeing abroad." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beddoes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hudsonSailor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :gloriaScottDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_coram_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Coram's Theory: Willoughby Smith Committed Suicide" ;
    ex:description "During Holmes's visit to Yoxley Old Place, Professor Coram suggests that Willoughby Smith's death was self-inflicted rather than murder, proposing a hidden love affair as the motive." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Willoughby Smith committed suicide, possibly over a secret love affair, and the pince-nez were a love-token." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Coram argued that young men have hidden troubles such as love affairs, that the pince-nez could be a love-token carried by the deceased, that the footsteps on the grass could be mistaken, and that the knife might have been thrown far from Smith as he fell." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :professorCoram ;
    ex:deductionSubject :willoughbySmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :goldenPinceNez, :sealingWaxKnife ;
    ex:refutedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Late-Night Visitor Wants Their Help" ;
    ex:description "When a cab arrives at 221B Baker Street late at night during a storm, Holmes infers the visitor has come for them but does not need them to travel, since the cab was dismissed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The late-night visitor has come to consult Holmes and Watson but does not need them to travel immediately, as the cab was sent away." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the cab pulling up at their door and a man stepping out, inferring the visitor wanted them. When the cab departed, Holmes concluded the visitor did not need them to come somewhere that night, since he would have kept the cab if he required them to travel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:confirmedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Pince-Nez Owner's Physical Description" ;
    ex:description "After examining the golden pince-nez found clutched in the dead man's hand, Holmes writes out a detailed physical description of the owner for Hopkins." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The pince-nez belong to a refined, well-dressed woman with a remarkably thick nose, close-set eyes, a puckered forehead, peering expression, and probably rounded shoulders, who has visited an optician at least twice recently." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The delicacy of the glasses and the dying man's words indicated a woman. The solid gold mounting suggested refinement. The clips were too wide for a normal nose, indicating a very broad base. Holmes could not position his own eyes at the centre of the lenses, showing the owner's eyes were set very close to the nose. The concave lenses of unusual strength implied lifelong contracted vision producing characteristic forehead, eyelid, and shoulder changes. One cork nose-pad was new while the other was worn, indicating a replacement and thus at least two optician visits in recent months." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :goldenPinceNez ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bureau Scratch Is Recent" ;
    ex:description "While examining the crime scene at Yoxley Old Place, Holmes discovers a scratch on the bureau's brass keyhole plate and determines it was freshly made." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The scratch on the bureau beside the keyhole was made during the crime, not earlier." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The brass shone brightly where it was cut, whereas an old scratch would have tarnished to the same colour as the surrounding surface. Shreds of varnish remained on either side of the scratch, which a duster would have swept away. Mrs. Marker confirmed she had dusted the bureau the previous morning and had not noticed any scratch." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :coramBureau ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :coramBureau ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsMarker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Targeted the Locked Cupboard" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene, Holmes determines that the intruder came specifically for something in the locked central cupboard of the bureau, not the open drawers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder came for something in the locked cupboard of the bureau, not the open drawers." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The drawers were always left open and contained nothing of value. If anything worth taking had been in the drawers, it would have been locked away. The cupboard, however, was locked with a Chubb's key and contained papers of importance, making it the logical target." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :coramBureau ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :coramBureau, :chubbKey ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Crime Sequence" ;
    ex:description "Holmes presents a reconstruction of events in the study: the intruder entered, went to the bureau, was interrupted by Smith, and stabbed him in a struggle to escape." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The woman entered the study, attempted to open the bureau, was seized by Willoughby Smith who entered unexpectedly, and she struck him with the sealing-wax knife to free herself." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The scratch on the bureau door indicated the woman was hurriedly withdrawing a key when interrupted. The position of the body near the bureau placed Smith at the point of confrontation. The knife was part of the desk fittings, meaning she grabbed the nearest available object rather than bringing a weapon, and struck to make Smith release his hold." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :willoughbySmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :coramBureau, :sealingWaxKnife, :goldenPinceNez ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Had Her Own Key" ;
    ex:description "After examining the Professor's bureau key, Holmes determines that the intruder possessed a separate key, and that the Professor was not an accessory to the intrusion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder used her own key to the bureau; the Professor's key showed no discolouration from varnish contact, proving he was not complicit in the entry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the Professor's key and found no slight discolouration that contact with the scratched varnish would have produced. Since the scratch was made by a key scraping the bureau face, and the Professor's key bore no such mark, the intruder must have had a different key." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :chubbKey, :coramBureau ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Remained Inside the House" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning the intruder would have had to walk back along the narrow grass strip, Holmes realizes a nearly blind woman without her glasses could not have managed this, and concludes she must still be in the house." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The extremely short-sighted intruder, having lost her glasses, could not have navigated the narrow grass border to escape and must have remained inside the house." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The pince-nez indicated extremely poor vision, making the wearer helpless without them. Walking along a narrow strip of grass between a path and flower-bed without stepping onto either surface would be a remarkable performance for someone who was virtually blind. Holmes judged it an impossible feat and was forced to consider the hypothesis that the woman had never left the house." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :goldenPinceNez ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Woman Took the Wrong Corridor to the Professor's Room" ;
    ex:description "Holmes notes that both corridors from the study are lined with coconut matting and realizes the disoriented, nearly blind woman mistook the corridor to the Professor's room for the exit corridor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The blinded intruder mistook the corridor leading to the Professor's bedroom for the exit corridor, as both were identically lined with coconut matting." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Both the corridor to the garden door and the corridor to the Professor's room were lined with coconut matting, making them indistinguishable by feel. A nearly blind woman fleeing in panic would easily confuse the two, ending up in the Professor's room with her retreat cut off." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Professor Is Feeding a Hidden Person" ;
    ex:description "Holmes questions the housekeeper Mrs. Marker about the Professor's appetite, learning that despite the shock of the murder, he consumed a remarkably large breakfast and ordered cutlets for lunch." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Professor's unusually increased food consumption indicates he is secretly supplying food to a second person hidden in the house." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes wagered that the Professor would have no appetite after the trauma and heavy cigarette smoking. Mrs. Marker reported the opposite: the Professor ate a remarkably big breakfast and ordered a hearty lunch. This contradiction suggested the extra food was being shared with someone else concealed on the premises." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorCoram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Locates the Hidden Woman Using Cigarette Ash" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies a specific bookcase as the hiding place by noting it was the only one left clear of piled books, then confirms his theory by spreading cigarette ash on the floor and observing that it was disturbed during their absence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The woman is concealed behind a bookcase in the Professor's room, identified because it alone was clear of piled books and confirmed when cigarette ash spread before it showed signs of disturbance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes searched for a hiding place in the Professor's room. The carpet was continuous with no trap-door. Books were piled on the floor at all other points, but one bookcase was left clear, suggesting a concealed door. Holmes smoked numerous cigarettes and dropped ash on the carpet before the suspected bookcase. When the cigarette box was later upset, giving him a view of the floor, he observed that the ash had been disturbed, confirming someone had emerged from behind the bookcase in their absence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets Willoughby Smith's Dying Words" ;
    ex:description "After Anna Coram's confession reveals that Smith had met her on the road that morning, Holmes explains the meaning of Smith's final words." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Smith's dying words 'The Professor—it was she' referred to the woman Smith had met on the road earlier that morning and subsequently discussed with Professor Coram." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Smith had encountered a woman on the road who asked directions to Professor Coram's house. He returned and told the Professor about this encounter. When Smith was fatally stabbed and recognized his attacker, his dying breath attempted to convey that the killer was the same woman—'she'—whom he had just discussed with the Professor." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :willoughbySmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Killing Was Accidental" ;
    ex:description "Holmes concludes that the stabbing of Willoughby Smith was an unplanned act of desperation rather than premeditated murder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killing was accidental, as the intruder came unarmed and seized the knife from the writing table only in the moment of struggle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The idea of murder was not in the intruder's mind, or she would have provided herself with a weapon rather than having to snatch a knife from the writing-table. An assassin does not come unarmed. The use of a desk implement as the weapon indicated a desperate, unplanned act rather than deliberate intent to kill." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annaCoram ;
    ex:deductionSubject :willoughbySmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sealingWaxKnife ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_hopkins_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Deduces the Assassin's Entry and Exit Route" ;
    ex:description "Upon investigating the Yoxley Old Place crime scene, Hopkins determines that the assassin entered and left through the garden path and back door, which provides direct access to the study." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The assassin entered and exited the house through the garden path and back door, as the other exits from the study were blocked." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The back door provided direct access to the study via the garden path. Of the two other exits from the study, one was blocked by Susan running downstairs and the other led only to the Professor's bedroom. Therefore entry and escape must have been through the garden path and back door." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderOfWilloughbySmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hopkinsChart ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_goldenPinceNez_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_hopkins_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Deduces a Cautious Criminal Walked on the Grass Border" ;
    ex:description "Hopkins's examination of the garden path reveals no footprints on the path itself but trodden grass along the border, indicating a cautious intruder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A cautious and expert criminal walked along the grass border of the garden path to avoid leaving footprints on the saturated path surface." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The rain-saturated path would certainly have shown any footmarks, but none were found. The grass border lining the path was trodden down, indicating someone had deliberately walked on it to avoid leaving tracks. This could only have been the intruder, since neither the gardener nor anyone else had been there that morning and the rain had begun during the night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderOfWilloughbySmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_hopkins_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Concludes No Robbery Was Committed" ;
    ex:description "After examining the study, Hopkins determines that nothing was stolen, eliminating robbery as a motive." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "No robbery was committed: the open drawers contained nothing of value, the locked cupboard was untampered with, and the Professor confirmed nothing was missing." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The drawers were always left open and held nothing valuable. The cupboard was locked and showed no signs of tampering. The Professor assured Hopkins that nothing was missing from either the drawers or the cupboard." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :coramBureau ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :coramBureau ;
    ex:refutedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_goldenPinceNez_hopkins_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Hopkins Deduces the Pince-Nez Were Snatched From the Assassin" ;
    ex:description "Hopkins presents the golden pince-nez found clasped in the dead man's right hand as evidence snatched from the killer during the struggle." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The golden pince-nez were torn from the assassin's face or person by Willoughby Smith during the struggle, as Smith had excellent sight and no need for glasses." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Willoughby Smith had excellent eyesight and would have had no personal use for the pince-nez. The glasses were found tightly clasped in his right hand, consistent with having been seized from the attacker during the struggle. His raised right hand as he died suggested he was trying to draw attention to the evidence he had secured." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :stanleyHopkins ;
    ex:deductionSubject :goldenPinceNez ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :goldenPinceNez ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annaCoram ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :goldenPinceNezDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Billiard-Marker" ;
    ex:description "At the bow-window of the Diogenes Club, Mycroft invites Sherlock to observe two men approaching on the street. Holmes immediately identifies one as a billiard-marker." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "One of the two passersby is a billiard-marker." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed distinguishing signs of the billiard-playing profession on the man. Watson independently confirmed chalk marks over the waistcoat pocket as the visible indicator." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :billiardMarker ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Passerby Is an Old Soldier" ;
    ex:description "Continuing the Diogenes Club window observation exercise, Holmes identifies the second passerby as an old soldier based on his physical presentation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The small, dark passerby is an old soldier." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the man's military bearing, expression of authority, and sunbaked skin, concluding these traits collectively indicate a soldier who is more than a private and not long returned from service." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Soldier Served in India" ;
    ex:description "Continuing the collaborative deduction at the Diogenes Club window, Holmes specifies the theatre of the soldier's service." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier served in India." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes inferred Indian service from the man's sunbaked skin, which indicated prolonged exposure to a tropical climate consistent with military deployment to India." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Soldier Is Royal Artillery" ;
    ex:description "Holmes narrows the soldier's branch of service through a process of elimination based on physical characteristics observed from the Diogenes Club window." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier served in the Royal Artillery." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted the absence of a cavalry stride, ruling out mounted regiments. The man wore his hat on one side, evidenced by lighter skin on that side of his brow. His weight was against his being a sapper. By elimination, Holmes concluded Royal Artillery." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Soldier Has a Child" ;
    ex:description "Holmes observes that the soldier has been purchasing items for children, deducing the existence of at least one child." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier has a child." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the man had been buying things for children, including a rattle visible among his packages, indicating at least one very young child." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sophy Had Been in England but Latimer Had Not Been in Greece" ;
    ex:description "Walking home from the Diogenes Club after hearing Melas's account, Holmes corrects Watson's assumption that Sophy was carried off from Athens by analyzing the language evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sophy had been in England for some time, but Latimer had not been to Greece." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Greek prisoner could not speak English at all, while Sophy could speak English fairly well. Holmes inferred that her English proficiency meant she had been in England for some time, while Latimer's complete inability to communicate in Greek meant he had not been in Greece." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sophyKratides ;
    ex:deductionSubject :haroldLatimer ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :interrogationOfKratides ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Case Can Be Solved by Tracing Sophy Kratides" ;
    ex:description "After endorsing Watson's theory, Holmes identifies the investigative path forward by reasoning about the identifiability of the victim's sister." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "If the girl's name is Sophy Kratides, she can be traced, and this is their best hope for finding the house where Kratides is imprisoned." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the brother was a complete stranger in London and untraceable, but if Melas's covert intelligence was correct about the name Sophy Kratides, she would be traceable through public records or inquiries. Since time had elapsed for the brother to learn of the situation in Greece and travel to England, the conspirators had likely been in one place long enough to be findable through the advertisement." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sophyKratides ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :interrogationOfKratides, :mycroftAdvertisement ;
    ex:confirmedBy :davenportLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Suspects Have Fled The Myrtles with Heavy Luggage" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at The Myrtles in Beckenham, Holmes examines the wheel-tracks visible in the light of the gate-lamp and deduces that the suspects have already fled." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A heavily-loaded carriage departed The Myrtles within the last hour, indicating the suspects have fled with their luggage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed wheel-tracks going both directions through the gate. The outward-bound tracks were much deeper than the inward-bound ones, indicating a very considerable weight on the departing carriage — consistent with heavy luggage rather than just passengers. This meant the occupants had packed and fled." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :haroldLatimer ;
    ex:deductionSubject :wilsonKemp ;
    ex:confirmedBy :flightFromMyrtles ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Gang Is Particularly Dangerous" ;
    ex:description "Before departing for Beckenham, Holmes takes his revolver from the table-drawer, explaining to Watson that the evidence points to a dangerous gang." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The conspirators Latimer and Kemp constitute a particularly dangerous gang." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "From the details of Melas's account — the abduction at bludgeon-point, the imprisonment and starvation of Kratides, the threats of death, and Kemp's menacing demeanor — Holmes concluded the gang would not hesitate to use lethal violence, warranting armed preparation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :haroldLatimer ;
    ex:deductionSubject :wilsonKemp ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :firstKidnappingOfMelas, :imprisonmentOfKratides ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deathOfPaulKratides ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Theorizes Sophy Kratides Avenged Her Brother's Death" ;
    ex:description "Months after the case, a newspaper cutting from Budapest reports that two Englishmen travelling with a woman were found stabbed to death. Holmes forms a theory about the killings." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sophy Kratides was responsible for the stabbing deaths of Latimer and Kemp in Budapest, avenging her brother's murder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Budapest report described two Englishmen travelling with a woman who were found stabbed, with police suggesting they quarreled and killed each other. Holmes rejected this explanation, believing instead that the Grecian girl — Sophy Kratides — had avenged the wrongs done to herself and her brother by killing his captors." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sophyKratides ;
    ex:deductionSubject :haroldLatimer ;
    ex:deductionSubject :wilsonKemp ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :budapestNewsCutting ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Identifies Adams as the Manor House Criminal" ;
    ex:description "When Sherlock visits the Diogenes Club, Mycroft casually reveals that he had expected Sherlock to consult him about the Manor House case, and immediately identifies the culprit as Adams without having investigated." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Adams was the perpetrator of the Manor House crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mycroft applied his superior powers of deduction to the publicly available facts of the Manor House case and concluded that Adams was responsible, demonstrating the armchair reasoning ability Holmes attributes to his brother." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :adamsManorHouse ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Deduces the Soldier Was Very Recently Discharged" ;
    ex:description "Adding to Sherlock's identification of the passerby as a soldier, Mycroft refines the observation by noting evidence of very recent discharge from military service." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier has not left the service long." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mycroft observed that the man was still wearing his 'ammunition boots,' standard military-issue footwear that a recently discharged soldier would not yet have replaced with civilian shoes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Deduces the Soldier Is a Non-Commissioned Officer" ;
    ex:description "Mycroft further refines the soldier's rank, building on the collective observations made at the Diogenes Club window." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier is a non-commissioned officer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mycroft inferred NCO rank from the man's expression of authority, which indicated a position of command above private rank but below commissioned officer status." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Deduces the Soldier Is a Widower" ;
    ex:description "Mycroft observes personal details about the soldier's domestic circumstances from the Diogenes Club window." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier is a widower whose wife likely died in childbed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The man's complete mourning dress indicated the recent loss of someone very dear. The fact that he was doing his own shopping suggested the deceased was his wife, as a wife would normally handle such errands." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Deduces the Soldier Has Multiple Children" ;
    ex:description "Mycroft corrects and extends Sherlock's observation about the soldier's children, demonstrating his keener eye for detail in the Diogenes Club window exercise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The soldier has multiple children, not just one." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The rattle indicated one very young child, while a picture-book under the man's arm showed there was an older child as well. The wife probably died in childbed, explaining both the mourning and the very young infant." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldSoldierDiogenes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :greekInterpreterDoc .

:deduction_greekInterpreter_mycroft_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mycroft Deduces Characteristics of the Davenport Letter-Writer" ;
    ex:description "Upon receiving a reply to his newspaper advertisement seeking information about Sophy Kratides, Mycroft immediately deduces physical characteristics of the letter's author from the handwriting and paper." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter was written by a middle-aged man with a weak constitution using a J pen on royal cream paper." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mycroft analyzed the physical properties of the letter — the type of pen nib (J pen), the quality of paper (royal cream), and characteristics of the handwriting — to deduce the writer's age, sex, and state of health." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mycroftHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jDavenport ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :davenportLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
