:deduction_hisLastBow_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Von Bork's Intelligence Is Untrustworthy" ;
    ex:description "After capturing Von Bork, Holmes revealed that much of the intelligence Von Bork had collected and sent to Germany was deliberately false, having been supplied or manipulated by Holmes himself during his undercover operation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduced and confirmed that Von Bork's collected intelligence was thoroughly untrustworthy because Holmes himself had supplied much of it as disinformation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had been feeding false intelligence to Von Bork throughout his undercover mission. He concluded that the German admiral would find the new guns larger than expected and the cruisers faster than reported, because the specifications Von Bork transmitted were deliberately inaccurate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vonBork ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vonBorkEspionageCampaign ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesCounterEspionageMission ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:deduction_hisLastBow_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts the Coming War Will Transform England" ;
    ex:description "Standing on the terrace overlooking the moonlit sea on the eve of the First World War, Holmes told Watson that a devastating east wind — meaning war — was coming that would be cold and bitter but would ultimately leave a cleaner, better, stronger England." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes predicted that a terrible war was imminent but that England would emerge from it transformed and strengthened." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Drawing on his years of intelligence work infiltrating the German spy network and his knowledge of Germany's war preparations, Holmes concluded that war was inevitable and imminent. He characterized it metaphorically as an east wind that would cause great suffering but ultimately purify the nation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesCounterEspionageMission ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:deduction_hisLastBow_vonbork_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Von Bork's Assessment: The English Are Docile and Easy to Deceive" ;
    ex:description "In conversation with Baron Von Herling on the terrace of his country house, Von Bork expressed his confident assessment that the English people were simple, docile, and not difficult to deceive, based on his four years of successful espionage operations in England." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Von Bork concluded that the English were a docile, simple folk who were not hard to deceive." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Von Bork based his assessment on four years of apparently successful espionage in England, during which he had gathered an extensive collection of military secrets while maintaining his cover as a sporting country squire. His social acceptance among the English upper class reinforced his belief in their gullibility." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :vonBork ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :vonBorkEspionageCampaign ;
    ex:refutedBy :captureOfVonBork ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:deduction_hisLastBow_vonbork_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Von Bork's Belief: Altamont Is a Genuine Irish-American Traitor" ;
    ex:description "Von Bork was fully convinced that his chief agent Altamont was an authentic bitter Irish-American with genuine anti-British sentiments, trusting him with the most sensitive espionage tasks including the acquisition of naval signals." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Von Bork believed Altamont was a real Irish-American traitor motivated by hatred of England, fully trusting his cover identity." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Von Bork accepted Altamont's carefully constructed persona based on his convincing Irish-American dialect, his documented background from Chicago and Irish secret societies in Buffalo, his apparent anti-British passion, and his consistent delivery of intelligence. Von Bork even defended Altamont's loyalty to Baron Von Herling, calling him a wonderful worker." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :vonBork ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:refutedBy :captureOfVonBork ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:deduction_hisLastBow_baronvonherling_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Von Herling's Assessment: England Is Unprepared for War" ;
    ex:description "Baron Von Herling assessed British military readiness during his conversation with Von Bork, concluding that England was fundamentally unprepared for war despite Germany's openly provocative military buildup." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Von Herling concluded that England was not ready for war, citing lack of munitions storage, submarine preparation, and explosives manufacturing." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Von Herling observed that even Germany's special war tax of fifty million had not roused the British public, that storage of munitions, preparation for submarine attack, and arrangements for making high explosives were all lacking. He also noted that internal distractions — Irish civil unrest and suffragette violence — were keeping British attention focused domestically." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :baronVonHerling ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :hisLastBowDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mortimer Is a Young Hospital-Trained Doctor" ;
    ex:description "After praising Watson's attempt, Holmes corrects most of his conclusions by reinterpreting the walking stick's inscription, date, and tooth-marks to construct a far more detailed and accurate profile of Dr. Mortimer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Mortimer is a young man under thirty, formerly a house-surgeon at Charing Cross Hospital, who left upon marriage, is amiable, unambitious, and absent-minded, and owns a dog larger than a terrier but smaller than a mastiff." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified 'C.C.H.' as Charing Cross Hospital, deduced the presentation was made when Mortimer left the hospital, reasoned he could only have been a house-surgeon given his country practice, calculated his age from the 1884 date, inferred his personality from the testimonial and career choice, and read dog tooth-marks on the stick to estimate the dog's size." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimersStick ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Dog as a Curly-Haired Spaniel" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his examination of the walking stick, Holmes narrows down the breed of Mortimer's dog from the tooth-marks, then confirms his deduction moments later when the dog arrives at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes identifies the specific breed of Mortimer's dog as a curly-haired spaniel based on the jaw width indicated by tooth-marks on the stick." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes measured the space between the tooth-marks on the stick, determining the jaw was too broad for a terrier and not broad enough for a mastiff, concluding it was a curly-haired spaniel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mortimersSpaniel ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimersStick ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mortimersSpaniel ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mortimer Makes His Own Cigarettes" ;
    ex:description "Upon meeting Mortimer in person, Holmes immediately observes a detail about his hands and invites him to light a cigarette, which Mortimer then rolls with surprising dexterity." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes observes from Mortimer's forefinger that he rolls his own cigarettes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted the staining and condition of Mortimer's forefinger, characteristic of someone who habitually rolls cigarettes by hand." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Dates the Baskerville Manuscript to 1730" ;
    ex:description "When Mortimer produces a family manuscript, Holmes demonstrates his expertise in dating documents by examining the handwriting visible in the portion exposed during their conversation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes dates the Baskerville family manuscript to approximately 1730 based on the calligraphy." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the manuscript's use of the alternative long 's' and short 's' and other calligraphic features, placing it within a decade of 1730. The actual date was 1742, making this close but not precise." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :baskervilleManuscript ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :baskervilleManuscript ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sir Charles Was Running in Fear" ;
    ex:description "During his evening analysis of the case with Watson, Holmes reinterprets the key physical evidence of the changed footprints in the Yew Alley, contradicting the official finding." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Sir Charles was running desperately for his life down the Yew Alley, not walking on tiptoe as the inquest suggested." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes rejected the inquest's interpretation that Sir Charles walked on tiptoe, reasoning that the altered footprints indicated running — a man fleeing desperately until his heart burst and he fell dead upon his face." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesBaskerville ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sir Charles Was Waiting for Someone at the Gate" ;
    ex:description "Analyzing the circumstances of Sir Charles's death, Holmes identifies the anomaly of the old man standing at the moor-gate and concludes he had an appointment there." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Sir Charles was waiting for someone at the moor-gate on the night of his death, not merely taking his usual evening walk." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that an elderly, infirm man would not stand for five to ten minutes at the moor-gate on a damp, inclement night during his regular evening stroll. The cigar ash evidence proved he waited there, and his planned departure for London the next day suggested a specific reason." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesBaskerville ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lyonsLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Spent the Day at His Club" ;
    ex:description "When Watson returns to Baker Street in the evening, Holmes casually deduces how he spent his day from the condition of his clothing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Watson spent all day at his club." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Watson went out on a showery, miry day but returned immaculate with the gloss still on his hat and boots, meaning he had been indoors all day. Since Watson had no intimate friends, the only place he could have spent the entire day was his club." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Warning Letter Source as the Times" ;
    ex:description "Examining the anonymous warning letter received by Sir Henry Baskerville, Holmes identifies not only that the pasted words came from a newspaper, but identifies the specific newspaper and article." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes identifies that the words in the anonymous warning letter sent to Sir Henry were cut from the previous day's Times leading article." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the typeface as the distinctive leaded bourgeois type of a Times article, distinguished from other newspapers as readily as a specialist distinguishes skulls. He confirmed this by finding the exact source words in the previous day's leading article on free trade." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :warningLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :warningLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Letter Was Composed by an Educated Man in a Hurry" ;
    ex:description "Holmes provides a detailed analysis of the warning letter's construction, deducing the sender's education level, emotional state, and likely location when composing it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces the warning letter was composed by an educated person who wished to appear uneducated, was working in haste, and wrote the address at a hotel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the Times is read only by the highly educated, yet the address was printed in rough characters to disguise handwriting — suggesting an educated compositor feigning illiteracy. The uneven placement indicated hurry. The pen had spluttered and run dry, indicating poor-quality hotel ink and pen." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :warningLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :warningLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Scissors Were Nail-Scissors" ;
    ex:description "During the examination of the warning letter, Holmes makes a precise observation about the cutting implement used to assemble the message." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the letter was assembled using nail-scissors rather than regular scissors." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the cutter had to take two snips over the phrase 'keep away,' indicating a very short-bladed implement — nail-scissors rather than ordinary scissors." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :warningLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :warningLetter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sir Henry Is Being Followed" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning that no one could have known Sir Henry's hotel choice in advance, Holmes deduces that active surveillance must have been in place since Sir Henry's arrival in London." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Sir Henry Baskerville has been closely followed since arriving in London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since nobody except Mortimer knew Sir Henry was going to the Northumberland Hotel, and yet the warning letter was correctly addressed there, someone must have followed Sir Henry from his first arrival." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henryBaskerville ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :warningLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cabSurveillance ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Spy's Beard Was False" ;
    ex:description "After the failed pursuit of the mysterious hansom cab on Regent Street, Holmes analyzes what they observed about the shadower and concludes the beard was a deliberate disguise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the bearded man following Sir Henry in the hansom cab was wearing a false beard." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that both he and Watson could only identify the man's beard, not his face. He reasoned that a clever man on such a delicate errand would only use a beard to conceal his features, implying it was a disguise." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cabSurveillance ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Spy Is Not Staying at Sir Henry's Hotel" ;
    ex:description "At the Northumberland Hotel, Holmes checks the register and uses a ruse about knowing the recent guests to verify their identities, confirming that Sir Henry's shadow is based elsewhere." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the people following Sir Henry are not staying at the Northumberland Hotel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes checked the hotel register and cleverly questioned the porter about the two new guests, Johnson and Oldmore, establishing they were well-known legitimate guests. Since no suspicious person was registered, the watchers must be operating from elsewhere." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates Desmond as a Suspect" ;
    ex:description "Before Watson departs for Dartmoor, Holmes reports the results of his own investigations, ruling out the most obvious suspect based on motive." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes eliminates James Desmond, the next heir after Sir Henry, as a suspect based on his character." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes's inquiries established that James Desmond, the elderly clergyman who is next in line for the estate, is of very amiable disposition, confirming the persecution does not arise from him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesDesmond ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Watson by His Cigarette Stub" ;
    ex:description "When Watson confronts Holmes at the stone hut on the moor, Holmes reveals that he knew Watson was inside from the discarded cigarette stub bearing the tobacconist's mark." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces Watson's presence in the stone hut from the stub of a Bradley, Oxford Street cigarette found on the path." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the distinctive brand marking on the discarded cigarette stub and knew Watson's tobacconist, allowing him to identify his friend's presence before entering the hut." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Stapleton as Married, Not a Brother" ;
    ex:description "In the stone hut on the moor, Holmes reveals to Watson his most significant discovery — that the woman presented as Stapleton's sister is in fact his wife, establishing the central deception of the case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Miss Stapleton is actually Mrs. Stapleton — the naturalist's wife, not his sister." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Stapleton had mentioned running a school in the north of England. Holmes traced this through scholastic agencies, finding that a school had failed under atrocious circumstances and the owner — under a different name — had disappeared with his wife. The descriptions matched, and the man's devotion to entomology completed the identification." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :berylStapleton ;
    ex:confirmedBy :berylStapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Stapleton Is the Enemy Who Dogged Them in London" ;
    ex:description "Holmes connects all the London events — the surveillance, the warning letter, the stolen boots — to Stapleton as the orchestrator of a murder plot." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that Stapleton was the bearded man who followed them in London and is the mastermind behind the threats to Sir Henry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Having established Stapleton's true identity and his wife's role as unwilling accomplice, Holmes concluded that Stapleton — disguised with a false beard — was the man in the cab, and that the warning letter came from his wife. Stapleton's motive as a secret Baskerville heir explained everything." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cabSurveillance ;
    ex:confirmedBy :berylStapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_18 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Hound Tracked Selden by Sir Henry's Clothes" ;
    ex:description "Upon discovering that the hound's victim is actually the convict Selden dressed in Sir Henry's castoff clothing, Holmes immediately explains the mechanism of the misdirected attack." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 18 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the hound was set upon Selden because the convict was wearing Sir Henry's old clothes, which carried Sir Henry's scent." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "After discovering the dead man was Selden, Holmes connected the wardrobe that Sir Henry gave to Barrymore, who passed it to Selden. The boot stolen at the hotel was used to give the hound Sir Henry's scent, so it pursued anyone wearing Sir Henry's clothing." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :selden ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackBoot ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_19 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Stapleton in the Hugo Baskerville Portrait" ;
    ex:description "During supper at Baskerville Hall, Holmes becomes fascinated by the portrait of Hugo Baskerville. He later demonstrates to Watson that covering the hat and hair reveals Stapleton's face, proving the family connection." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 19 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes recognizes that the portrait of the wicked Hugo Baskerville bears a striking resemblance to Stapleton, proving Stapleton is a Baskerville." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes studied the family portraits at Baskerville Hall and noticed that the Cavalier portrait of Hugo Baskerville, when the hat and ringlets were covered, revealed a face identical to Stapleton's. Holmes's training in examining faces rather than their trimmings allowed him to see through the period costume." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hugoPortrait ;
    ex:confirmedBy :berylStapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_20 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Stolen Boot Proved a Real Hound" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective summary of the case, Holmes explains how the boot theft incident at the Northumberland Hotel was the key early proof that they faced a flesh-and-blood hound." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 20 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the theft and return of Sir Henry's boots proved they were dealing with a real hound, not a supernatural one." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The first boot stolen was new and therefore useless for scent-tracking. It was returned and an old, worn boot was taken instead. This anxiety to obtain a boot carrying the owner's scent, and indifference to a new unworn one, proved conclusively that a real hound was involved." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackStapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackBoot, :brownBoot ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_holmes_21 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Warning Letter Came from Beryl Stapleton" ;
    ex:description "In the retrospective chapter, Holmes reveals that he had detected perfume on the warning letter paper, which was one of the early clues pointing him toward the Stapletons and the true sender of the warning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 21 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes deduces that the anonymous warning letter to Sir Henry was sent by Beryl Stapleton, based on the scent of white jessamine on the paper." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When examining the paper upon which the warning words were pasted, Holmes detected a faint smell of white jessamine perfume. Since there are seventy-five perfumes a criminal expert must distinguish, this scent suggested a lady's involvement, and Holmes's thoughts turned toward the Stapletons." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :berylStapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :warningLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :berylStapleton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Mortimer Is a Successful Elderly Country Practitioner" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks Watson to reconstruct the owner of a forgotten walking stick, Watson examines the engraved silver band and worn ferrule to build a profile of their unknown visitor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson deduces from the walking stick that Dr. Mortimer is a successful, elderly country doctor who received the stick from a local hunt." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed the inscription 'C.C.H.' on the stick, the worn ferrule indicating much walking, and the presentation inscription, concluding Mortimer was an elderly country practitioner who received the stick from a local hunt whose members he had assisted surgically." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesMortimer ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mortimersStick ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_hound_holmes_01 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces Mrs. Barrymore Was the Woman Sobbing" ;
    ex:description "After hearing a woman sobbing on their first night at Baskerville Hall, Watson confronts the evidence the next morning when he sees Mrs. Barrymore's tell-tale red eyes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson deduces that Mrs. Barrymore was the woman heard sobbing in the night, contradicting Barrymore's denial." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson encountered Mrs. Barrymore the morning after the sobbing with the sun full upon her face, observing her red, swollen eyes between swollen lids. Since Barrymore had denied it was his wife, Watson concluded the butler had lied." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :elizaBarrymore ;
    ex:confirmedBy :elizaBarrymore ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_watson_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces Barrymore's Signal Light" ;
    ex:description "During the second night's surveillance of Barrymore's nocturnal movements, Watson takes the initiative to test whether the candle at the window is a signal, and discovers the answering light." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson deduces that Barrymore was holding his candle at the window as a signal to someone on the moor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "After observing Barrymore crouching at the window with a candle pressed against the glass, staring intently at the moor, Watson seized the candle and held it in the same position, discovering an answering light on the moor — confirming it was a signal system." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnBarrymore ;
    ex:confirmedBy :elizaBarrymore ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_hound_watson_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces Barrymore's Window Was Chosen for Its View of the Moor" ;
    ex:description "Watson investigates the room where Barrymore was spotted the night before, discovering the unique vantage point provided by that particular window." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson deduces that Barrymore chose that specific window because it offered the only clear view of the moor from the house." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson examined the room the next morning and discovered that the western window had a unique feature — an opening between two trees that enabled a direct view of the moor, while all other windows only offered distant glimpses." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnBarrymore ;
    ex:confirmedBy :elizaBarrymore ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_adelbertgruner_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Gruner Deduces Watson Is Holmes's Spy" ;
    ex:description "During Watson's visit to Vernon Lodge posing as Dr. Hill Barton, Baron Gruner tests Watson's knowledge of Chinese pottery and, finding it shallow, concludes that Watson is an agent sent by Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The visitor calling himself Dr. Hill Barton is actually an emissary of Sherlock Holmes, sent to spy on Gruner under a false pretext." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Gruner grew suspicious when Watson could not explain how he obtained the rare saucer and had not read Gruner's own book on Chinese pottery. When Watson could not answer specific expert questions about Emperor Shomu and the Northern Wei dynasty, Gruner concluded the pottery interest was a pretext and identified the visitor as Holmes's agent, reasoning that the supposedly dying Holmes had sent a proxy to keep watch." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mingDynastySaucer, :watsonVisitVernonLodge ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryVernonLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Baron Gruner as a Murderer" ;
    ex:description "When Sir James Damery first names Baron Gruner during his visit to Baker Street, Holmes immediately identifies him as 'the Austrian murderer' before any details of the current case are presented." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Baron Gruner is a murderer whose guilt in his wife's death is beyond doubt despite his legal acquittal." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had followed the details of Continental crime closely and recognized Gruner's name at once. He cited the events at Prague and the suspicious death of a witness that led to Gruner's acquittal, concluding that only a technical legal point saved him from conviction." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderBaronessGruner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :kittyWinter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Gruner Killed His Wife in the Splugen Pass" ;
    ex:description "Expanding on his initial identification, Holmes states with absolute certainty that the so-called accident in the Splugen Pass was in fact murder committed by Gruner against his wife." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gruner deliberately killed his wife in what was staged as an accident in the Splugen Pass." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes declared himself as certain of the murder as if he had witnessed it personally, based on his reading of the Prague trial proceedings and the circumstances of the wife's death. The acquittal rested on a technical legal point and the convenient death of a witness, which Holmes interpreted as further evidence of Gruner's ruthlessness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grunerWifeDeceased ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :splugenPass, :murderBaronessGruner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :kittyWinter ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Anonymous Client Is General de Merville" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Damery's account of the situation involving Violet de Merville and her father, Holmes infers that the unnamed client must be General de Merville himself, noting that Damery has inadvertently revealed this." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The anonymous illustrious client is General de Merville." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since the entire case concerned the General's daughter and the General had the most direct interest in preventing the marriage, Damery must have inadvertently identified the client by describing the General's personal distress." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :illustriousClient ;
    ex:refutedBy :jamesDamery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Assesses Gruner as Genuinely Dangerous After Meeting Him" ;
    ex:description "After visiting Baron Gruner at Vernon Lodge and engaging him in direct conversation, Holmes reports his assessment to Watson over dinner at Simpson's." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gruner is not a blusterer but a man who says less than he means, making him truly dangerous." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes contrasted Gruner with empty boasters, noting that Gruner's cool, silky manner and veiled threats about Le Brun's fate at the hands of Apaches were understated rather than exaggerated. Holmes read Gruner's aristocratic composure and indirect warning as signs of a man who acts on his threats without needing to bluster." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesFirstVisitGruner, :attackOnLeBrun ;
    ex:confirmedBy :attackOnHolmesRegentStreet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Is Under Quasi-Hypnotic Influence" ;
    ex:description "After his failed attempt to persuade Violet de Merville at Berkeley Square, Holmes reflects on her immunity to all emotional appeals and concludes that Gruner has effectively conditioned her mind against any warning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gruner has used a form of post-hypnotic suggestion to inoculate Violet against any attempt to dissuade her from the marriage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled Gruner's own boast about post-hypnotic suggestion and his claim that a man of personality can use hypnotism without vulgar passes. Observing Violet's complete emotional detachment during the confrontation—her icy calm despite passionate pleas from both Holmes and Kitty Winter—Holmes concluded that Gruner had pre-conditioned her to dismiss all opposition as slander." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetDeMerville ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :visitToVioletDeMerville, :holmesFirstVisitGruner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :visitToVioletDeMerville ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Love Diary as the Decisive Weapon" ;
    ex:description "When Kitty Winter describes Gruner's brown leather book containing photographs, names, and details of the women he has ruined, Holmes immediately recognizes it as the one piece of evidence that could break Violet's attachment." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gruner's private love diary, written in his own hand and documenting his treatment of women, is the only evidence capable of breaking Violet de Merville's devotion." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since Violet had already pardoned Gruner's known crimes and dismissed verbal testimony from both himself and Kitty Winter, only incontrovertible physical evidence in Gruner's own handwriting could penetrate her conditioned defenses. The diary's personal nature and graphic content would reveal a moral reality that abstract accusations could not convey." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grunerLoveDiary ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :kittyWinter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cancellationGrunerMarriage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Gruner's Collector Obsession Can Override His Caution" ;
    ex:description "Planning the operation to steal the diary, Holmes devises a scheme based on his assessment that Gruner's passion for Chinese pottery will override his natural suspicion and engage his full attention." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gruner's collector mania for Chinese pottery is so acute that presenting him with a rare Ming specimen will fully engage his attention and override his caution." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes knew from Damery's briefing and his own visit that Gruner was an acknowledged authority on Chinese pottery with the collection mania in its most acute form. Holmes reasoned that presenting an irresistible specimen—an egg-shell Ming saucer of supreme rarity—would compel Gruner to give it his undivided attention, creating a window for the burglary." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :grunerPotteryBook, :mingDynastySaucer ;
    ex:confirmedBy :watsonVisitVernonLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Exaggerating Injuries Will Lull Gruner Into False Security" ;
    ex:description "Immediately after being attacked and beaten on Regent Street, Holmes instructs Watson to exaggerate the severity of his injuries to the press, reasoning this will make Gruner lower his guard." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "If Gruner believes Holmes is dying, he will relax his precautions, creating an opportunity to act against him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Gruner had ordered the attack to neutralize him, and that reports of Holmes being at death's door would satisfy Gruner that the threat had been eliminated. With his enemy apparently incapacitated, Gruner would feel safe to proceed with his plans without maintaining heightened vigilance." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :adelbertGruner ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :attackOnHolmesRegentStreet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryVernonLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Diary's Location in Gruner's Inner Study" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes reveals that he needed to confirm the exact position of the book before acting and had only minutes to retrieve it during Watson's distraction." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The love diary is kept in the pigeon-hole of the bureau in Gruner's inner study, behind the outer study with the Chinese pottery collection." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined Kitty Winter's description of where the diary was kept—in the pigeon-hole of the old bureau in the inner study—with his own earlier reconnaissance during his first visit to Vernon Lodge, where he had been in the outer study and observed the layout. He concluded the book would still be there, given Gruner's precise and tidy habits." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grunerLoveDiary ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vernonLodge ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :kittyWinter, :holmesFirstVisitGruner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryVernonLodge ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Only Moral Evidence Can Break Violet's Attachment" ;
    ex:description "After the vitriol attack on Gruner, when Sir James suggests the disfigurement alone should prevent the marriage, Holmes disagrees and insists on using the diary." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet de Merville would only love Gruner more as a disfigured martyr; only the moral evidence in the diary, not his physical ruin, can break her attachment." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assessed that women of Violet's type—idealistic, spiritually inclined, and devoted to a redemptive narrative—would interpret Gruner's physical suffering as further reason for loyalty. He reasoned that the diary's evidence of systematic, deliberate exploitation of women in Gruner's own handwriting would destroy the moral narrative Violet had constructed, which no amount of physical disfigurement could accomplish." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetDeMerville ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grunerLoveDiary ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :visitToVioletDeMerville ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cancellationGrunerMarriage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_illustriousClient_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Identifies the Illustrious Client From the Armorial Bearings" ;
    ex:description "As Sir James Damery departs Baker Street in his brougham, Watson spots the armorial bearings on the carriage panel despite Damery's attempt to conceal them with his overcoat, and identifies the illustrious client." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson identifies the anonymous illustrious client by recognizing the armorial bearings on Sir James Damery's departing brougham." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed Sir James fling his overcoat over the carriage panel to hide the armorial bearings, but the fanlight illuminated them before they were covered. Watson recognized the coat of arms, which revealed the identity of the high-ranking person who had engaged Damery as intermediary." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :illustriousClient ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :jamesDamery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :illustriousClientDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_inspectorbardle_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Bardle's Theory: Ian Murdoch Murdered McPherson" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Bardle of the Sussex Constabulary presents his case for arresting Ian Murdoch, having gathered circumstantial evidence pointing to the mathematics coach as the killer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Ian Murdoch is the murderer, based on his violent character, quarrel with McPherson, possible jealousy over Maud Bellamy, and preparations for departure." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Bardle cited Murdoch's ferocious temper as shown in the dog-throwing incident, his past quarrel with McPherson, possible resentment over McPherson's attentions to Miss Bellamy, and the fact that Murdoch seemed to be making preparations for departure. The isolated location narrowed the field of suspects considerably. Bardle reasoned that if Murdoch did not do it, no one else plausibly could have." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBardle ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ianMurdoch ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dogThroughWindowIncident ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_09 ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_inspectorbardle_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Bardle's Observation: Wound Pattern Resembles a Wire Net" ;
    ex:description "During Holmes's presentation of the enlarged wound photographs, Inspector Bardle offers his own forensic interpretation of the distinctive pattern of marks on McPherson's body." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The pattern of dots at intervals along the wound marks resembles the crossing points of a red-hot wire net laid across the back." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Bardle observed that the dots of extravasated blood at regular intervals along the weals corresponded to points where the lines of a mesh would cross each other, suggesting the instrument resembled a red-hot wire net. Holmes praised this as 'a most ingenious comparison' and offered an alternative of a stiff cat-o'-nine-tails with hard knots, but noted there might be a very different cause entirely." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBardle ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deathOfMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :enlargedPhotographWounds ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McPherson Stripped to Bathe but Never Entered the Water" ;
    ex:description "While examining the beach where McPherson had gone for his morning swim, Holmes finds McPherson's towel folded and dry on a rock, alongside prints of both canvas shoes and naked feet, indicating McPherson had undressed but apparently never bathed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McPherson stripped to bathe but apparently never entered the water, as his towel was folded and dry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The folded, dry towel on the rock indicated McPherson had not dried himself after swimming. The presence of both shod and naked footprints confirmed he had undressed to bathe. His dishevelled, unfastened clothing showed he had hurriedly re-dressed. Holmes concluded he had prepared to bathe but returned without doing so — though this was later revealed to be misleading, as McPherson had entered the water but never had the chance to dry himself." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroyMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mcPhersonTowel ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McPherson Collapsed Repeatedly While Ascending" ;
    ex:description "Examining the cliff path from the beach, Holmes reads the physical traces left by McPherson during his final agonised ascent to determine the severity and progression of his suffering." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McPherson fell multiple times while climbing the cliff path, based on handprints and knee impressions in the clay." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the print of an open hand with fingers pointing towards the incline, which could only mean McPherson had fallen while ascending. Rounded depressions in the clay further indicated he had come down upon his knees more than once during the climb." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroyMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fulworthCliffPath ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates Human Attackers From the Beach Scene" ;
    ex:description "From the top of the cliff path, Holmes surveys the entire beach to determine whether any person could have been responsible for the attack on McPherson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "No human attacker could have been present — the beach was deserted, distant figures were too far away and separated by the lagoon, and fishing boats were at too great a distance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the beach was absolutely deserted save for two or three distant figures moving towards Fulworth, too far away to have been involved. The broad lagoon lay between McPherson's bathing spot and those figures. Fishing boats offshore were similarly too distant. Only McPherson's own ascending and descending footsteps appeared on the path that morning." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deathOfMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fulworthBathingPool, :fulworthCliffPath ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Note as Evidence of a Love Affair" ;
    ex:description "Searching the dead man's pockets, Holmes finds a note signed 'Maudie' and interprets its contents as evidence of a romantic assignation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The note found in McPherson's pocket indicates a love affair and an assignation with a woman named Maudie." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The note reading 'I will be there, you may be sure. Maudie.' was written in a feminine hand and read like a love affair with an arranged meeting, though the time and place were not specified. This was later confirmed when Stackhurst's investigation of McPherson's desk revealed intimate correspondence with Miss Maud Bellamy of Fulworth." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroyMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maudBellamy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :maudNoteToMcPherson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mcPhersonLetters ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Was Hand-Delivered" ;
    ex:description "After reading Maud Bellamy's reply note confirming the assignation, Holmes turns the paper over and questions how she received McPherson's original note, inferring it was not posted." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McPherson's note to Maud Bellamy was hand-delivered rather than posted, implying a go-between carried their messages." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the physical note and stated 'This never came by post,' questioning how Maud received it. Maud refused to answer, saying it had nothing to do with the investigation. It was later revealed that Ian Murdoch had served as the go-between carrying messages for the secret couple." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mcPhersonNoteToMaud ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mcPhersonNoteToMaud ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ianMurdoch ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Suspects Murdoch Is Positioning to Flee" ;
    ex:description "Upon encountering Ian Murdoch emerging from the Bellamy house and observing his hostile, evasive reaction when questioned, Holmes's suspicions about Murdoch begin to crystallize." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Murdoch's visit to the Bellamys and his hostile, evasive behavior suggest he is taking the first opportunity to establish an escape route from the scene of the crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Murdoch was the first to visit the Bellamys after McPherson's death, gave only a sideways glance and tried to pass without stopping, and reacted with fury when questioned. Holmes noted that Murdoch appeared to be taking the first chance to open a path of escape. Combined with his known violent temper, quarrel with McPherson, and possible jealousy over Maud Bellamy, suspicion took definite shape." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ianMurdoch ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :visitToBellamys ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Peculiarities in the Wound Pattern" ;
    ex:description "Using an enlarged photograph and a lens, Holmes examines McPherson's wounds in detail and identifies distinctive irregularities inconsistent with a conventional weapon." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The wound marks show unequal intensity with dots of extravasated blood at intervals, indicating the weapon was not a simple whip or scourge." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the weals with a lens and photographed them at enlargement. He observed that the marks were unequal in intensity, with dots of extravasated blood at specific points along the weals. These peculiarities suggested the injuries were not inflicted by any conventional instrument such as a whip, and that whatever caused the marks would define the nature of the attacker." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deathOfMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :enlargedPhotographWounds ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Rules Out 'Ian' as McPherson's Dying Words" ;
    ex:description "When Inspector Bardle wonders whether McPherson's dying words might have referred to 'Ian' Murdoch rather than 'the Lion's Mane,' Holmes considers and rejects this interpretation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McPherson's dying words were definitively 'the Lion's Mane' and not a reference to 'Ian' Murdoch." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had heard the dying words directly and noted McPherson delivered them almost in a shriek. The second word bore no resemblance to 'Murdoch' — Holmes was certain the word was 'Mane.' This confirmed the phrase was a descriptive reference rather than an accusation against a person." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroyMcPherson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Dog's Death Eliminates All Human Suspects" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes learns that McPherson's dog was found dead at the exact same spot on the beach where its master died, he recognizes this as the crucial evidence that redirects the entire investigation away from any human perpetrator." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The dog's death at the identical location by the same cause eliminates all human suspects, since no murderer would kill a dog in the same elaborate manner." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The dog had been found dead at the very edge of the bathing pool — the exact spot where McPherson met his end. Holmes reasoned that while the dog's faithfulness in returning to its master's death-place was natural, its dying there was not. A human killer would have no reason to murder a dog using the same mysterious method. This meant the cause of death was something present at that specific location — a permanent hazard rather than a human agent." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mcPhersonDog ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deathOfMcPhersonDog ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deathOfMcPhersonDog ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_lionsMane_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Cyanea Capillata as the Killer" ;
    ex:description "Triggered by the dog's death and his dim memory of a relevant passage, Holmes searches his library and identifies the lion's mane jellyfish from J.G. Wood's book as the true cause of McPherson's death, then locates the creature in the bathing pool." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The killer is Cyanea capillata, the lion's mane jellyfish, whose nearly invisible tentacles filled the tidal pool and fatally stung McPherson while he entered the water to swim." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The phrase 'the Lion's Mane' had haunted Holmes's memory as something he had encountered in an unexpected context. After the dog's death proved no human was responsible, Holmes recalled J.G. Wood's Out of Doors, which described the deadly sting of Cyanea capillata — the lion's mane jellyfish — with symptoms exactly matching McPherson's injuries: scarlet reticulated lines on the skin, agonising chest pains, and cardiac distress. The southwest gale had likely brought the creature into the shallow tidal lagoon. Holmes found the specimen in the bathing pool and destroyed it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cyaneaCapillata ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deathOfMcPherson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :outOfDoorsBook, :deathOfMcPhersonDog, :fulworthBathingPool ;
    ex:confirmedBy :attackOnMurdoch ;
    ex:confirmedBy :destructionOfCyanea ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :lionsManeDoc .

:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Is a Busy Medical Man" ;
    ex:description "When Watson volunteers to stay and help, claiming he has nothing to do for a day or two, Holmes immediately contradicts him by reading the signs of a busy medical practice." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson is a busy medical man with calls on him every hour, despite his claim of having free time." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Watson bore every sign of a busy medical practitioner with patients calling on him constantly, exposing Watson's offer to stay as a well-intentioned fib motivated by concern for Holmes's safety." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :mazarinStoneDoc .

:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Sylvius and Merton as the Diamond Thieves" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reveals to Watson that he has identified the two men responsible for stealing the Mazarin Stone: Count Negretto Sylvius, a dangerous big-game hunter, and Sam Merton, a boxer serving as Sylvius's muscle." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Count Negretto Sylvius and Sam Merton stole the Mazarin Stone, with Sylvius as the mastermind and Merton as his accomplice." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Through his investigation Holmes identified Sylvius as the principal thief — a dangerous criminal he likens to a shark — and Merton as his subordinate accomplice, a strong but unintelligent boxer whom Sylvius has manipulated into the scheme. Holmes has cast his net around both men but withholds arrest because the stone's location remains unknown." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
