:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Sylvius's Visit Proves He Feels Cornered" ;
    ex:description "When Billy brings Count Sylvius's calling card, Holmes interprets the Count's bold decision to come directly to 221B Baker Street as proof that Holmes's pursuit has thoroughly rattled him." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sylvius's decision to visit Holmes at Baker Street proves that Holmes's close surveillance has made the Count desperate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that a dangerous man like Sylvius — a shooter of big game who might consider adding Holmes to his bag — would only risk coming directly to his adversary's home if he felt Holmes's pursuit closing in on him. The visit itself is proof that Sylvius feels Holmes's toe very close behind his heel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:confirmedBy :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :mazarinStoneDoc .

:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Traps Sylvius Into Admitting Knowledge of the Diamond's Location" ;
    ex:description "During their confrontation at 221B, Holmes uses a verbal gambit to trick Count Sylvius into inadvertently confirming that he knows where the Mazarin Stone is hidden." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sylvius knows the current location of the Mazarin Stone, as revealed by his own inadvertent admission." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes declared he could see to the very back of Sylvius's mind. When Sylvius sarcastically retorted that Holmes must then see where the diamond is, Holmes seized on the reply as an admission — Sylvius's phrasing presupposed that he himself knew the location, which he would not have said if he were truly ignorant of it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mazarinStone ;
    ex:confirmedBy :recoveryOfMazarinStone ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :mazarinStoneDoc .

:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Establishes Sylvius's Full Criminal History" ;
    ex:description "Holmes produces his crime notebook and confronts Sylvius with a documented record of his past criminal activities, using the Count's selective denials to confirm the accuracy of the remaining charges." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sylvius is responsible for the death of Mrs. Harold, the exploitation of Minnie Warrender, and the robbery on the Riviera train de luxe, as confirmed by his denial of only the forged check." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes accumulated evidence of Sylvius's crimes in his notebook: the suspicious death of Mrs. Harold who left him the Blymer estate, the case of Minnie Warrender, the Riviera train robbery of February 1892, and a forged check on the Credit Lyonnais. When Sylvius denied only the forgery charge, Holmes applied the logical principle that a selective denial constitutes implicit admission of the undenied charges." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesCrimeNotebook, :deathOfMrsHarold, :rivieraTrainRobbery, :creditLyonnaisForgery ;
    ex:confirmedBy :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :mazarinStoneDoc .

:deduction_mazarinStone_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Complete Chain of Evidence for the Diamond Theft" ;
    ex:description "Holmes presents to Count Sylvius a complete reconstruction of the Mazarin Stone theft, demonstrating that he possesses sufficient evidence for a conviction even without recovering the stone itself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The diamond theft is fully reconstructed: Sylvius was transported to and from Whitehall by cab, observed near the display case by a commissionaire, and betrayed by Ikey Sanders who refused to cut the stone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assembled testimony from the cabman who drove Sylvius to Whitehall, the cabman who brought him away, the commissionaire who witnessed Sylvius near the jewel case, and the confession of Ikey Sanders, the fence who refused to cut the stone and subsequently informed on Sylvius. Together these witnesses establish a complete evidentiary chain proving Sylvius committed the theft." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :countNegrettoSylvius ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theftOfMazarinStone ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :ikeySanders ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfSylviusAndMerton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :mazarinStoneDoc .

:deduction_milverton_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Burglary Is the Only Option to Recover Lady Eva's Letters" ;
    ex:description "After the failed negotiation with Milverton and days of intelligence-gathering through his engagement to Milverton's housemaid Agatha, Holmes concludes that breaking into Appledore Towers is the sole remaining course of action." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Burglary of Appledore Towers is the only possible way to recover Lady Eva Brackwell's compromising letters before Milverton's deadline." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned from multiple converging facts: the negotiation had failed, Lady Eva lacked the money to pay, there was no one in whom she could confide, and the next day was the last day of grace before Milverton would send the letters. He further noted that the documents were kept in a safe in Milverton's study, that Milverton was a heavy sleeper retiring at ten-thirty, and that the secretary guarded the study by day — making a nighttime burglary the only viable approach." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyEvaBrackwell ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyEvaLetters ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :milvertonNegotiation, :holmesAgathaEngagement ;
    ex:confirmedBy :appledoreTowersBurglary ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Senses Danger From the Unlocked Outer Door" ;
    ex:description "While burgling Milverton's study, Watson discovers that the outer door to the veranda is neither locked nor bolted. Holmes is visibly startled and whispers that something is not right." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The unlocked and unbolted outer door to Milverton's study indicates an unexpected and potentially dangerous situation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes's intelligence from Agatha had given him detailed knowledge of Appledore Towers' security arrangements. Finding the outer door unsecured contradicted his expectations — a door that should have been locked was open, suggesting an unknown variable. Holmes whispered 'I don't like it. I can't quite make it out,' recognizing the anomaly without being able to explain it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milvertonStudy ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holmesAgathaEngagement ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Veiled Avenger as a Famous Noblewoman" ;
    ex:description "The morning after witnessing Milverton's murder, Holmes suddenly recalls where he has seen the avenger's face and rushes with Watson to a photograph shop near Regent Circus, where he identifies her portrait among the displayed celebrities." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The veiled woman who shot Milverton is a specific famous noblewoman whose photograph is publicly displayed, the wife of a great nobleman and statesman." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had observed the avenger's distinctive features from behind the curtain — a dark, handsome face with a curved nose, strong dark eyebrows, and a straight thin-lipped mouth. After a morning of intense recollection, he matched those features to a portrait in the photograph shop, identifying her as the wife of a renowned nobleman and statesman whose husband had died after Milverton's blackmail destroyed him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milvertonAvenger ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :avengerPhotograph, :murderOfMilverton ;
    ex:confirmedBy :identificationOfAvenger ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: Two Men of Good Position Murdered Milverton" ;
    ex:description "The morning after the murder, Lestrade visits Baker Street and presents his theory of the crime to Holmes, describing two male suspects based on the evidence gathered at Appledore Towers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Two men of good social position broke into Appledore Towers, murdered Milverton, and burned his blackmail papers to prevent social exposure." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade reported that footmarks and descriptions from witnesses indicated two intruders. The under-gardener had physically grappled with one — a middle-sized, strongly-built man with a square jaw, thick neck, and moustache wearing a mask. No valuables were taken and the blackmail papers were burned, leading Lestrade to conclude the criminals were men of good position motivated by preventing exposure rather than theft." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesAugustusMilverton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :appledoreTowersBurglary ;
    ex:refutedBy :murderOfMilverton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_charlesaugustusmilverton_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Milverton Deduces Holmes Is Bluffing About Telling the Earl" ;
    ex:description "During negotiations at 221B Baker Street, Holmes threatens to advise Lady Eva to confide the whole story to the Earl of Dovercourt and trust to his generosity. Milverton instantly perceives that Holmes is bluffing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes is bluffing about advising Lady Eva to tell the Earl of Dovercourt, because Holmes knows the Earl would not be forgiving." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Milverton responded 'You evidently do not know the Earl,' and Watson observed from Holmes's baffled expression that Milverton was correct — Holmes did know the Earl's character and was aware the strategy would fail. Milverton read Holmes's negotiating posture as a bluff rather than a genuine intention." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :charlesAugustusMilverton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_charlesaugustusmilverton_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Milverton Anticipates Holmes Will Attempt Physical Force" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes springs from his chair and orders Watson to block the door, Milverton calmly retreats to the wall and reveals he came armed, having anticipated this exact move." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes would attempt to use physical force to seize Milverton's notebook during the negotiation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Milverton stated 'I have been expecting you to do something original. This has been done so often,' indicating he had predicted Holmes would resort to physical intimidation. He came prepared with a revolver concealed in his coat, demonstrating premeditated anticipation of Holmes's aggressive tactics." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :charlesAugustusMilverton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :milvertonNegotiation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_charlesaugustusmilverton_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Milverton Deduces Holmes Assumed the Letters Were in the Notebook" ;
    ex:description "After thwarting Holmes's lunge for his pocket-book, Milverton correctly identifies the false assumption behind Holmes's attack." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes assumed the compromising letters were physically present in Milverton's notebook, which was incorrect." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Milverton declared 'your supposition that I would bring the letters here in a note-book is entirely mistaken. I would do nothing so foolish.' He correctly deduced that Holmes's attempt to seize the notebook was motivated by the belief that it contained the blackmail material, and pointed out the naivety of that assumption." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :charlesAugustusMilverton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milvertonNotebook ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Discovers the Outer Door Is Suspiciously Unlocked" ;
    ex:description "While Holmes works on the safe, Watson checks the outer door as a precaution for their retreat and finds it neither locked nor bolted, immediately recognizing this as anomalous." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The outer door to Milverton's study being unlocked and unbolted is suspicious and unexpected, suggesting their retreat route may be compromised." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson wisely examined their escape route and discovered the veranda door was completely unsecured. Given that they had entered through the greenhouse precisely because this door was bolted from inside, finding it now open was alarming. Watson alerted Holmes by touch, and both recognized the situation as unexpected." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milvertonStudy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfMilverton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :milvertonDoc .

:deduction_milverton_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Unlocked Door Was for Milverton's Late-Night Visitor" ;
    ex:description "When a veiled woman arrives through the veranda door for a late-night meeting with Milverton, Watson immediately connects this to the previously unexplained unlocked door." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The unlocked outer door and Milverton's nocturnal vigil are explained by his having a late-night appointment with a visitor who would enter through the veranda." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson narrates: 'So this was the explanation of the unlocked door and of the nocturnal vigil of Milverton.' He connected three anomalies — the unlocked door, Milverton's unexpected presence in his study rather than his bedroom, and his repeated checking of his watch — into a single coherent explanation: Milverton was awaiting a scheduled visitor." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesAugustusMilverton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milvertonAvenger ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfMilverton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
