:deduction_missingThreeQuarter_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Suggests Kidnapping Theory to Motivate Lord Mount-James" ;
    ex:description "When Lord Mount-James arrives at the hotel and refuses to fund the investigation, Holmes proposes a kidnapping theory to frighten the miser into cooperation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Staunton may have been kidnapped by a gang seeking information about Lord Mount-James's house, habits, and treasure." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that Staunton appeared to be a poor man with nothing worth kidnapping him for personally, but that Lord Mount-James's fame as one of the richest men in England made it possible that thieves had secured the nephew to extract information about the uncle's wealth. Holmes later admitted to Watson this was not a probable explanation but was the theory most likely to interest the unpleasant old miser." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyStaunton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordMountJames ;
    ex:refutedBy :deathOfStauntonWife ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc .

:deduction_missingThreeQuarter_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Proposes Alternative Theories for Disappearance" ;
    ex:description "In the cab to King's Cross Station, Holmes outlines alternative theories for Staunton's disappearance to Watson, acknowledging the kidnapping theory was a ruse." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The disappearance may be connected to betting interests seeking to remove a key player before the match, or Staunton may have been held for ransom as heir to a great property." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted it was curious and suggestive that the disappearance occurred on the eve of the important match and involved the one indispensable player. While amateur sport is free from betting, outside betting among the public could make it worth someone's while to get at a player. A second theory was that Staunton, as heir to great property, could have been seized for ransom." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyStaunton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :disappearanceOfGodfreyStaunton ;
    ex:refutedBy :deathOfStauntonWife ;
