:deduction_missingThreeQuarter_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Telegram Recipient as Dr. Armstrong" ;
    ex:description "Holmes obtains the identity of the telegram's recipient through a ruse at the telegraph office and later confirms it by reading the counterfoil at the Cambridge office." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Staunton's urgent telegram was addressed to Dr. Leslie Armstrong in Cambridge." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes used a subterfuge at the London telegraph office, posing as the telegram's sender to get a glimpse of the counterfoil. He later confirmed at the Cambridge end that the obliging young lady at the office allowed him to read the name Dr. Armstrong on the counterfoil of Staunton's urgent message." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :telegramCounterfoil, :stauntonTelegram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc .

:deduction_missingThreeQuarter_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Armstrong Knows Staunton's Whereabouts" ;
    ex:description "After confronting Dr. Armstrong and being ejected from his house, Holmes observes Armstrong's daily carriage journeys and concludes the doctor is visiting Staunton." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Armstrong knows where Staunton is and is visiting him on his regular carriage journeys." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Armstrong's brougham went out for three hours at a time, covering a radius of ten or twelve miles, once or sometimes twice daily. Armstrong was a lecturer and consultant who did not care for general practice, making such long journeys unusual. Combined with Armstrong's furious reaction when confronted about the telegram and his denial of contact with Staunton, Holmes concluded Armstrong was concealing Staunton's location and actively visiting him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyStaunton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :armstrongBrougham ;
    ex:confirmedBy :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc .

:deduction_missingThreeQuarter_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Armstrong's Detour Was Deliberate Misdirection" ;
    ex:description "While following the draghound Pompey on Dr. Armstrong's scent trail, Holmes realizes the circuitous route was designed to mislead pursuers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Armstrong's elaborate detour through side roads was entirely designed to throw off anyone following him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The draghound's trail led from the main road into a grass-grown lane, then back toward town and away in the opposite direction from the starting point. Holmes recognized this as the explanation for why his earlier inquiries at villages along the direct route had yielded nothing — the doctor had deliberately driven a circuitous path to prevent anyone from determining his true destination." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leslieArmstrong ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :armstrongBrougham, :pompey ;
    ex:confirmedBy :armstrongNote ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :missingThreeQuarterDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Three Mysteries Are One Connected Case" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Musgrave's account of Brunton's disappearance, Howells' disappearance, and the strange bag from the mere, Holmes becomes convinced that these are not three separate mysteries but a single interlinked chain of events, with the Musgrave Ritual at its centre." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The butler's disappearance, the maid's disappearance, and the Ritual are all parts of one connected mystery." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes considered the sequence of events — Brunton was caught studying the Ritual, then vanished; Rachel Howells, who had loved and then hated Brunton, became hysterical after his disappearance and then vanished herself, leaving tracks to the mere where a bag of strange relics was found. Holmes recognised these as links in a single chain rather than independent incidents." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :musgraveRitualInvestigation ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bruntonDisappearance, :rachelHowellsDisappearance, :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryOfBruntonsBody ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Ritual Encodes Directions to a Physical Location" ;
    ex:description "Upon reading the text of the Musgrave Ritual, Holmes immediately recognises that its cryptic references to sun, oak, elm, shadow, and stepped measurements are encoded geographical directions pointing to a specific spot on the estate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Musgrave Ritual's measurements and references encode directions to a physical location on the estate grounds." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the Ritual's questions about where the sun was, where the shadow fell, and how paces were to be stepped in cardinal directions constituted a set of spatial instructions rather than mere ceremonial catechism. The specificity of compass directions and step counts indicated a concrete destination." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:confirmedBy :decodingMusgraveRitual ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Brunton Recognised the Ritual's Practical Significance" ;
    ex:description "Holmes tells Musgrave that his butler appears to have been a very clever man who had a clearer insight than ten generations of Musgrave masters, inferring that Brunton had decoded the Ritual's true meaning and had studied it on previous occasions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Brunton recognised the Ritual as practical directions and had studied it before the night he was caught, using a chart of his own calculations." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes inferred that Brunton's intelligence, combined with his secret nocturnal study of the Ritual alongside a chart or map of his own making, indicated he had decoded its meaning and was refreshing his memory for a planned expedition. Brunton had also previously asked Musgrave about the height of the elm tree, confirming advance preparation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :richardBrunton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bruntonCaughtReading, :bruntonsChart ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryOfBruntonsBody ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Oak and Elm as the Ritual's Reference Points" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at Hurlstone, Holmes identifies the magnificent patriarch oak in front of the house as the Ritual's 'oak' reference, and the scar on the lawn where a large elm had stood before being struck by lightning as the Ritual's 'elm' reference." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The ancient oak in front of the house and the former location of the elm on the lawn are the two reference points specified in the Ritual." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Ritual specified 'over the oak' for the sun's position and 'under the elm' for the shadow. Holmes found that only one ancient oak stood before the house, making identification certain. For the elm, he inquired about old elms on the property and learned one had been destroyed by lightning ten years prior, its former location still visible on the lawn between the oak and the house." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hurlstoneGrounds ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:confirmedBy :decodingMusgraveRitual ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Calculates the Shadow Length to Locate the Starting Point" ;
    ex:description "Holmes uses proportional trigonometry to calculate where the shadow of the now-absent sixty-four-foot elm would have fallen when the sun was just above the oak. He confirms his calculation by discovering Brunton's own peg mark within two inches of his result." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Using a six-foot rod that cast a nine-foot shadow, Holmes calculated the sixty-four-foot elm would cast a ninety-six-foot shadow, locating the Ritual's starting point near the house wall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes waited until the sun grazed the top of the oak, then measured the shadow of a six-foot fishing rod at nine feet. By simple proportion, a sixty-four-foot tree would cast a shadow of ninety-six feet. Measuring this distance from the elm's former position brought him almost to the house wall, where he found a conical depression in the ground — Brunton's own peg mark — confirming the calculation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hurlstoneGrounds ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument, :fishingRod, :measuringPeg ;
    ex:confirmedBy :decodingMusgraveRitual ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Follows the Ritual's Compass Directions to the Old Wing Threshold" ;
    ex:description "From the starting point near the house wall, Holmes paces out the Ritual's compass directions — ten north, five east, two south, one west — arriving precisely at the threshold of the old door to the ancient wing of Hurlstone." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Ritual's stepped directions lead from the shadow's end to the threshold of the old wing's door." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes took cardinal bearings with his pocket compass and stepped the Ritual's instructions: ten paces north (parallel to the house wall), five east, two south (reaching the old door threshold), and two west (into the stone-flagged passage). The specificity of the directions and the meaningful terminus confirmed they were intentional." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hurlstone ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:confirmedBy :decodingMusgraveRitual ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Misinterprets 'And Under' as an Instruction to Dig" ;
    ex:description "Upon reaching the stone-flagged passage at the end of the Ritual's directions, Holmes initially interprets the final instruction 'and so under' as meaning they should dig beneath the floor, and is disappointed to find the stones firmly cemented. Musgrave corrects him, pointing out it means the cellar beneath." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes initially interprets 'and under' as an instruction to dig through the passage floor rather than descend to the cellar below." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had successfully followed all the directional steps to the stone-flagged passage. Reading 'and so under' in the Ritual, he assumed it meant excavation at that spot. When the floor proved undisturbed and firmly cemented, he experienced doubt until Musgrave noted the omitted phrase referred to the cellar accessible by a door and winding stair beneath that very passage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hurlstoneCellar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument ;
    ex:refutedBy :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Brunton Enlisted Rachel Howells as His Accomplice" ;
    ex:description "Sitting in the cellar after the discovery of Brunton's body, Holmes reconstructs the butler's actions, deducing that Brunton could not lift the heavy flagstone alone and would have recruited the devoted Rachel Howells — whose love he would have tried to rekindle — as his accomplice." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Brunton enlisted Rachel Howells to help him lift the heavy flagstone and access the hidden chamber." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes put himself in Brunton's position: he knew something valuable was concealed, had located the spot, but found the stone too heavy for one person. He could not seek outside help without risking detection. Howells had been devoted to him, and Holmes judged that Brunton would have tried to reconcile with her through renewed attentions in order to secure her as an inside accomplice." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :richardBrunton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rachelHowells ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cellarFlagstone, :bruntonsMuffler ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets Wood Billets as Evidence of How the Stone Was Raised" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examines the scattered wood billets on the cellar floor and finds one with a marked indentation at one end and several flattened at the sides, deducing these were used as levers and wedges to prop open the flagstone during Brunton and Howells' excavation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The indented and flattened wood billets in the cellar were used by Brunton and Howells as levers to raise the heavy flagstone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the wood pieces and found physical evidence consistent with their use as mechanical aids: one piece showed a deep indentation at one end from bearing the stone's weight on the slab edge, while others were flattened from compression. He deduced that as the pair raised the stone, they thrust wood into the widening gap until the opening was large enough to crawl through, then held it open with a lengthwise billet." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cellarFlagstone ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Rachel Howells' Vengeance Against Brunton" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that Rachel Howells, seeing the man who had wronged her now trapped and helpless in the chamber below the flagstone, either allowed the supporting wood to slip or deliberately knocked it away, sealing Brunton in what became his tomb." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Rachel Howells killed Brunton by removing or allowing the collapse of the wood support, trapping him beneath the flagstone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes envisioned the scene: only Brunton could fit in the hole, so Howells waited above. After Brunton unlocked the box and presumably handed up its contents, Howells — consumed by vengeance against the man who had jilted her — either let the wood slip by chance or struck it away deliberately, sending the slab crashing down. Her blanched face, shaken nerves, and hysterical laughter the next morning confirmed her psychological state after the act." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rachelHowells ;
    ex:deductionSubject :richardBrunton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bruntonDeath, :rachelHowellsDisappearance ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Rachel Disposed of the Treasure in the Mere" ;
    ex:description "Holmes connects the bag of old rusted metal and pebbles that Musgrave's men had dredged from the mere to Rachel Howells, deducing she took the contents of the ancient chest and threw them into the lake to remove the last trace of her crime." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Rachel Howells threw the contents of the ancient chest into the mere to dispose of evidence linking her to Brunton's death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the box in the cellar was nearly empty, the bag dredged from the mere contained old metal and stones, and Rachel's tracks led to the mere's edge. He concluded she had taken what Brunton passed up from the chest, fled up the winding stair clutching the treasure, and threw it into the lake at the first opportunity to eliminate evidence of the night's events." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rachelHowells ;
    ex:deductionSubject :linenBag ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :discoveryOfLinenBag, :rachelHowellsDisappearance ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hurlstoneMere ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_musgraveRitual_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Relics as the Ancient Crown of England" ;
    ex:description "After examining the tarnished metal and dull stones from the bag, Holmes rubs one stone on his sleeve to reveal its lustre and recognises the bent metal circlet as the ancient crown of the kings of England, hidden by a Cavalier ancestor during the English Civil War." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The battered metal circlet and dull stones from the mere are the ancient crown of the Stuart kings, hidden during the Civil War." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes interpreted the Ritual's opening catechism: 'Whose was it? His who is gone' referred to Charles I after his execution; 'Who shall have it? He who will come' referred to the anticipated Charles II. Combined with the physical evidence — a double-ring metal form bent out of shape, stones that glowed when cleaned, and coins of Charles I in the chest — and Musgrave's statement that Sir Ralph Musgrave was a prominent Cavalier, Holmes concluded the relic was the crown entrusted to the Musgraves for safekeeping." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ancientCrownOfEngland ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :musgraveRitualDocument, :coinsOfCharlesI, :linenBag ;
    ex:confirmedBy :reginaldMusgrave ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :musgraveRitualDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_forbes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Forbes's Theory: Mrs. Tangey Is Involved in the Theft" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Forbes of Scotland Yard focuses his investigation on Mrs. Tangey, the commissionaire's wife, believing she knows more about the theft than she has revealed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Tangey, the commissionaire's wife, is implicated in the theft of the naval treaty." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Forbes noted that Mrs. Tangey was present at the Foreign Office on the night of the theft, that she hurried away from the building, that she ran into the back kitchen upon arriving home (apparently to hide something), and that she is generally of bad character. Forbes had her shadowed and sent a female agent to befriend her while she was drinking, but could get nothing out of her." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :forbes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsTangey ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_forbes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Forbes's Suspicion of Charles Gorot" ;
    ex:description "The police investigation also focused on Charles Gorot, the clerk who stayed late in Phelps's office on the night of the theft." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Charles Gorot, who was working overtime in Phelps's office that evening, may be involved in the theft." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Gorot had remained behind in Phelps's office to finish arrears of work, giving him potential knowledge of the treaty. His French name further attracted police suspicion given that the treaty concerned Anglo-French-Italian relations. However, investigation showed Gorot had left before Phelps began copying, and his family were English Huguenots with no foreign connections." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :forbes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlesGorot ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Letter Writer as a Woman of Rare Character" ;
    ex:description "Upon reading Phelps's letter requesting help, Holmes observes that while Phelps claims to have dictated the letter, the handwriting belongs to a woman, and moreover a woman of exceptional nature." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter was written by a woman of rare character who is in close contact with the client." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the handwriting of the letter Phelps sent to Watson. Despite Watson assuming it was a man's hand, Holmes identified it as a woman's writing, and from the characteristics of the penmanship deduced that the writer possessed an exceptional nature." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :annieHarrison ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :phelpsLetterToWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :annieHarrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Joseph Harrison Is Not a Family Member" ;
    ex:description "When greeted at Briarbrae by a stout, ruddy-faced man, Holmes perceives that this person is not a member of the Phelps family." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The man greeting them at Briarbrae is not a member of the Phelps family." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the JH monogram on the man's locket, which did not match the Phelps family name, leading him to conclude that the man was not a blood relation. Joseph Harrison confirmed this, explaining he was Percy's future brother-in-law." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josephHarrison ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :harrisonLocket ;
    ex:confirmedBy :josephHarrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Treaty Assignment Could Not Have Been Overheard" ;
    ex:description "Through careful questioning of Phelps about the circumstances of Lord Holdhurst's instructions, Holmes establishes that the conversation took place privately in a large room, at low volume, with no possibility of eavesdropping." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The conversation between Holdhurst and Phelps about copying the treaty could not have been overheard by anyone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes questioned Phelps about whether anyone else was present, the size of the room (thirty feet each way), their position in it (centre), and the volume of speech (Holdhurst's voice remarkably low). These factors eliminated the possibility that an eavesdropper learned of the treaty assignment." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :navalTreaty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :holdhurstRoomFO ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lordHoldhurst ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Thief Arrived by Cab" ;
    ex:description "During the train journey back to London, Holmes reasons about the absence of wet footprints on the linoleum floor of the Foreign Office corridor, despite the rainy night." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The thief arrived at the Foreign Office by cab rather than on foot." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The corridor had creamy linoleum that showed impressions easily, yet no muddy footmarks were found despite it having rained since seven o'clock. Since the thief came from outside and left no trace of damp, Holmes deduced the thief must have arrived by cab, which would have kept his feet dry." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :phelpsOfficeFO ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Theft Was Opportunistic" ;
    ex:description "After confirming with both Phelps and Lord Holdhurst that neither told anyone about the treaty assignment, Holmes concludes the theft was not premeditated." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The thief's presence in the room was purely accidental and the theft was opportunistic." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since Phelps told no one about the commission, Holdhurst told no one, and the conversation could not have been overheard, no one outside the two of them knew the treaty would be in that room. Therefore the thief could not have come specifically for the treaty — he saw his chance and took it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theftOfNavalTreaty ;
    ex:confirmedBy :josephHarrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Considers Lord Holdhurst as a Possible Suspect" ;
    ex:description "On the train to London, Holmes identifies those who profit from the treaty's disappearance, including the surprising suggestion of Lord Holdhurst himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Holdhurst could conceivably benefit from the treaty being destroyed, if he found himself in a position where the document was inconvenient." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes systematically considered who profits from the theft: the French ambassador, the Russian ambassador, anyone who might sell to either, and Lord Holdhurst. Holmes reasoned that a statesman might find himself in a position where he was not sorry to have such a document accidentally destroyed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordHoldhurst ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Treaty Has Not Reached a Foreign Power" ;
    ex:description "During the interview with Lord Holdhurst at Downing Street, Holmes reasons about the lack of diplomatic consequences after ten weeks." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The stolen treaty has not been delivered to any foreign government." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes established with Holdhurst that if the treaty had reached the French or Russian Foreign Office, there would have been observable diplomatic repercussions. Since nearly ten weeks had elapsed with no such consequences, Holmes deduced the treaty had not reached any foreign power, suggesting it was being held for a better price or the thief had been prevented from acting." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :navalTreaty ;
    ex:confirmedBy :navalTreatyRecovery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lord Holdhurst Is Under Financial Strain" ;
    ex:description "As they leave Lord Holdhurst's chambers, Holmes makes a passing observation about the nobleman's economic circumstances." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Holdhurst is struggling financially despite his prominent position." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Lord Holdhurst's boots had been re-soled, indicating that a man of his social standing was economizing on personal expenses, which suggested he was far from rich and had many financial calls upon him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordHoldhurst ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Knew the Household Routines" ;
    ex:description "After hearing about the attempted break-in at Briarbrae, Holmes becomes intensely excited and examines the grounds, questioning the circumstances of the intrusion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder who attempted to enter Phelps's bedroom was someone familiar with the household, not an ordinary burglar." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the attempted break-in targeted a bedroom rather than rooms likely to contain valuables (drawing-room, dining-room), and occurred on the very first night the nurse was absent. An ordinary burglar would have no reason to target that specific room, while someone who knew the household routines would know this was the first opportunity to enter without being observed by a nurse." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :briarbraeIntrusion ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :briarbrae ;
    ex:confirmedBy :josephHarrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Joseph Harrison as the Thief" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes reveals that he had begun to suspect Joseph Harrison based on the convergence of several facts about opportunity and the attempted bedroom intrusion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Joseph Harrison stole the naval treaty from the Foreign Office and hid it in Phelps's sickroom at Briarbrae." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes suspected Joseph because Phelps had intended to travel home with him that night, making it likely Joseph would call at the Foreign Office. Joseph knew his way around the building. The attempted break-in at the bedroom — where only Joseph could have concealed anything, since Joseph had been bundled out of that room when Phelps arrived with the doctor — confirmed that the treaty was hidden there. The attempt was made on the first night without a nurse, showing the intruder knew the household intimately." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josephHarrison ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :briarbraeIntrusion ;
    ex:confirmedBy :navalTreatyRecovery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Treaty Was Hidden Under the Floor in Phelps's Room" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deduces the specific hiding place of the treaty based on his analysis of where Joseph could have concealed it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The stolen treaty was hidden under the floorboards in the sickroom at Briarbrae, specifically under a plumber's access board near the gas-pipe T-joint." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since the bedroom intrusion attempt targeted Phelps's room specifically, and only Joseph had been in that room before Phelps took it over as a sickroom, Holmes concluded the papers were probably in the room. Rather than rip up planking to find them, Holmes set a trap to let Joseph retrieve the papers himself, confirming the hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :navalTreaty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :briarbraeIntrusion ;
    ex:confirmedBy :navalTreatyRecovery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Joseph Had Drugged Phelps's Nightly Draught" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes suggests that Joseph took steps to ensure Phelps would be unconscious during the initial break-in attempt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Joseph Harrison had tampered with Phelps's nightly medicinal draught to ensure he would be unconscious during the attempted retrieval." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that on the night of the attempted intrusion, Phelps had not taken his usual draught, and was therefore awake to detect the intruder. Holmes fancied that Joseph had taken steps to make the draught efficacious as a sedative and had relied upon Phelps being unconscious. Phelps's unusual decision to skip the medicine thwarted the plan." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josephHarrison ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Joseph's Method of Theft at the Foreign Office" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation, Holmes reconstructs how Joseph Harrison entered the Foreign Office and stole the treaty." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Joseph entered through the Charles Street door, found Phelps's room empty, rang the bell (alerting the commissionaire), spotted the treaty on the desk, pocketed it, and escaped before the commissionaire responded." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that Joseph entered through the Charles Street side door, which he knew about from previous visits. Finding Phelps absent, Joseph promptly rang the bell — his eyes then caught the treaty on the table. He realized its value at a glance, thrust it into his pocket, and fled before the commissionaire could respond. The few minutes' delay before the sleepy commissionaire noticed the bell gave Joseph time to escape." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josephHarrison ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theftOfNavalTreaty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :phelpsBellFO, :charlesStreet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :navalTreatyRecovery ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_percyphelps_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Phelps Deduces the Thief Entered via the Side Stairs" ;
    ex:description "Immediately upon discovering the treaty missing, Phelps reasons about the thief's route of entry." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The thief must have come up the stairs from the Charles Street side door, since Phelps would have encountered him on the main corridor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Phelps had walked down the main corridor and staircase to find the commissionaire. Since there was no concealment possible in the dimly-lit corridor or the room, and Phelps did not encounter anyone, the thief must have used the alternative route: the second passage leading to the Charles Street side door." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :percyPhelps ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theftOfNavalTreaty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :phelpsOfficeFO, :charlesStreet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_percyphelps_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Phelps's Theory: A Political Conspiracy Targets His Life" ;
    ex:description "After the nighttime intrusion at Briarbrae, Phelps theorizes during the train journey to London that he is the target of a political conspiracy." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A deep political intrigue is being directed against Phelps, with conspirators targeting both his career and his life." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Phelps reasoned that a thief breaking into a bedroom window — where no plunder could be expected — made no sense as an ordinary burglary. The intruder carried a long knife rather than a burglar's tool. Combined with the treaty theft, Phelps concluded that political conspirators were behind both events and that his life was in danger." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :percyPhelps ;
    ex:deductionSubject :percyPhelps ;
    ex:deductionSubject :briarbraeIntrusion ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :josephKnife ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_navalTreaty_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Burglar and Treaty Thief Are the Same Person" ;
    ex:description "While discussing the case with Phelps on the train to London, Watson reasons that the nighttime intruder at Briarbrae and the Foreign Office thief must be connected." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The burglar who attempted to break into Phelps's bedroom and the person who stole the naval treaty are the same individual." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson argued that it would be absurd to suppose Phelps had two separate enemies — one who robbed him and another who threatened his life. If Holmes could identify the nighttime intruder, he would have gone a long way towards finding who took the treaty." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :briarbraeIntrusion ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theftOfNavalTreaty ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_navalTreaty_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :navalTreatyDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces St. Simon's Letter Was Written with a Quill Pen" ;
    ex:description "Upon reading Lord St. Simon's letter requesting a consultation, Holmes makes several observations about the letter's physical characteristics before the client arrives at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter was written with a quill pen, and Lord St. Simon has a smear of ink on the outer side of his right little finger." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the physical properties of the letter — the character of the ink strokes and the presence of an ink smear on the envelope — to deduce the writing instrument used and the consequent ink stain on the writer's hand." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bride Was Willing but Changed Her Mind" ;
    ex:description "Before Lord St. Simon arrives, Holmes forms his initial conclusions from the newspaper accounts Watson has read aloud, later elaborating the reasoning in his retrospective explanation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bride had been entirely willing to undergo the wedding ceremony but repented of it within a few minutes of returning home." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed two facts from the press reports: the ceremony proceeded without incident from the bride's side, yet she vanished almost immediately after returning to the house for the wedding breakfast. The abruptness of the change indicated something specific had occurred to alter her feelings." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bride Saw Someone During the Morning" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis of the newspaper reports, Holmes reasons about what could have caused the bride's sudden change of heart between the ceremony and the breakfast." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Something occurred during the wedding morning that caused the bride to change her mind — specifically, she must have seen someone, since she could not have spoken to anyone while in the company of the bridegroom." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since the bride was in the bridegroom's company throughout the morning and could not have spoken privately to anyone, Holmes eliminated conversation as the trigger. By process of exclusion, she must have seen someone whose mere sight was sufficient to change her plans completely." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Person the Bride Saw Was American" ;
    ex:description "Holmes narrows the identity of the person who influenced the bride by considering her brief time in England and the depth of influence required to make her abandon her wedding." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person the bride saw must have been an American, since she had spent so short a time in England that no one there could have acquired such deep influence over her." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The bride had only recently arrived in England for the London season. For someone's mere appearance to cause her to abandon her wedding, the influence must have been profound and long-standing. By process of exclusion, this person must have come from her past in America." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the American Was a Lover or Previous Husband" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons about the nature of the relationship between the bride and the American she saw, drawing on his knowledge of her unconventional upbringing in the mining camps of California." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The American who influenced the bride was either a lover or a previous husband, with the latter being more probable given the circumstances." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The depth of influence — sufficient to make the bride abandon her wedding upon mere sight — pointed to an intimate relationship. Her youth had been spent in rough scenes and under strange conditions in the mining camps, making a prior romantic attachment or secret marriage plausible. The chances favoured a previous husband over a mere lover." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:deductionSubject :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms the Prior Husband Theory from St. Simon's Account" ;
    ex:description "When Lord St. Simon describes the man in the pew, the bride's changed manner, the dropped bouquet, the resort to her confidential maid, and the 'claim-jumping' allusion, Holmes finds his conjecture fully confirmed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bride had gone off with a man who was her previous husband — confirmed by the man in the pew who returned the bouquet, the bride's use of mining slang 'claim-jumping' meaning taking possession of what another has prior claim to, and her consultation with her American maid." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "St. Simon's narrative provided converging evidence: a man in the front pew handed back the dropped bouquet (a transparent device for exchanging a note), the bride immediately consulted her confidential American maid, and she used the mining term 'claim-jumping' — which in miners' parlance means taking possession of that which another person has a prior claim to. The whole situation became clear: she had left with a previous husband." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:deductionSubject :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hattyBouquet, :fhmNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Hotel Bill to Trace Francis Hay Moulton" ;
    ex:description "When Lestrade produces the note signed F.H.M. found in the bride's dress pocket, Holmes examines the reverse side and discovers a fragment of a hotel bill, which Lestrade had dismissed as unimportant." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hotel bill fragment on the reverse of the F.H.M. note indicates a select and expensive London hotel, which Holmes uses to trace Francis Hay Moulton to a hotel on Northumberland Avenue and thence to his lodgings at 226 Gordon Square." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that eight shillings for a bed and eightpence for a glass of sherry pointed to one of the most expensive hotels in London. The initials F.H.M. were important, but the hotel bill was more valuable still: it showed the man had recently settled his bill. Holmes visited hotels on Northumberland Avenue, found Moulton's name in the register at the second one, matched the bill items, and followed the forwarding address to Gordon Square." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hotelBillFragment, :fhmNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Declares Lady St. Simon Is a Myth" ;
    ex:description "Before Lestrade departs, Holmes delivers his conclusion that Lady St. Simon does not exist as a legal entity, stunning both Lestrade and Watson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady St. Simon is a myth — there is not and never has been any such person, because Hatty Doran's prior marriage to Francis Hay Moulton made the St. Simon marriage bigamous and therefore void." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since Hatty Doran was already married to Francis Hay Moulton at the time of the ceremony with Lord St. Simon, the second marriage was legally void. Therefore the title 'Lady St. Simon' was never validly conferred, and no such person exists." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:confirmedBy :hattyDoran ;
    ex:confirmedBy :francisHayMoulton ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lestrade Has Been Working Outdoors in Wet Conditions" ;
    ex:description "When Lestrade arrives at 221B wearing a pea-jacket and cravat, Holmes immediately infers he has been working outdoors in the rain." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lestrade has been working outdoors in wet conditions, as evidenced by the dampness of his pea-jacket." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes laid his hand upon the arm of Lestrade's pea-jacket and noted it was very wet, inferring that Lestrade had been engaged in outdoor work in the rain. Lestrade confirmed he had been dragging the Serpentine." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lestrade ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
