:deduction_nobleBachelor_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: Flora Millar Decoyed Lady St. Simon" ;
    ex:description "After recovering the bride's wedding clothes from the Serpentine and finding a note signed F.H.M. in the dress pocket, Lestrade presents his theory to Holmes at 221B Baker Street." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Flora Millar decoyed Lady St. Simon away from the wedding breakfast and, with confederates, was responsible for her disappearance, as proved by the note signed with her initials F.H.M. found in the bride's dress pocket." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade found the bride's wedding clothes floating in the Serpentine and a note reading 'You will see me when all is ready. Come at once. F.H.M.' in the dress pocket. He attributed the initials F.H.M. to Flora Millar, believing the note was slipped to the bride at the door, luring her into Flora's trap. The presence of the clothes in the Serpentine further suggested foul play." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :floraMillar ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fhmNote, :hattyWeddingDress ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_nobleBachelor_lordrobertstsimon_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lord St. Simon's Theory: His Wife Became Suddenly Deranged" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks Lord St. Simon for his own theory about his wife's disappearance, St. Simon suggests a psychological explanation rooted in class anxiety." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The excitement of the affair and the consciousness of having made so immense a social stride caused a nervous disturbance in the bride, rendering her temporarily deranged." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lord St. Simon reasoned that when he considered his wife had turned her back upon so much that many had aspired to without success, he could hardly explain it in any other fashion than sudden derangement brought on by the overwhelming nature of her social elevation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lordRobertStSimon ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hattyDoran ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_nobleBachelor_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :nobleBachelorDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces McFarlane Is a Bachelor, Solicitor, Freemason, and Asthmatic" ;
    ex:description "When John Hector McFarlane bursts into 221B Baker Street in a frantic state, Holmes calmly observes him and announces four facts about the stranger before McFarlane has explained anything about himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McFarlane is a bachelor, a solicitor, a Freemason, and an asthmatic." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed McFarlane's untidy attire indicating a bachelor without a woman's care, the sheaf of legal papers protruding from his pocket identifying his profession, a watch-charm indicating Masonic membership, and his laboured breathing revealing his asthmatic condition." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Will Was Written on a Train" ;
    ex:description "After McFarlane's arrest, Holmes examines the rough draft of the will and draws Lestrade's attention to its varying handwriting quality, deducing the circumstances of its composition." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The will was drafted by Jonas Oldacre while travelling on a suburban train between Norwood and London Bridge." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the handwriting alternated between clear passages and illegible ones, with the good writing corresponding to stations where the train was stationary, the bad writing to the train in motion, and the very bad writing to the train passing over railway points. The quick succession of points indicated a suburban line, and the pattern suggested an express stopping only once between Norwood and London Bridge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreWill ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oldacreWill ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Will Was Not Intended to Be Effective" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his examination of the will's draft, Holmes draws an inference about Oldacre's true intentions from the haphazard manner in which so important a document was composed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oldacre did not intend the will to have genuine legal effect, since a man would not draft so important a document so carelessly unless he expected it to be meaningless." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that a man who genuinely intended to leave his estate to someone would not compose the will in such a haphazard fashion on a moving train, suggesting Oldacre viewed the document as a prop rather than a binding instrument." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreWill ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oldacreWill ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Argues the Case Against McFarlane Is Too Obvious" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Lestrade lay out the prosecution's theory, Holmes challenges the logical coherence of the case by posing three questions about McFarlane's supposed behaviour." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The circumstantial case against McFarlane is implausibly convenient, suggesting the evidence was arranged to frame him rather than resulting from genuine criminal carelessness." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes pointed out three logical flaws: a guilty man would not choose the very night the will was signed to commit murder, would not do so when known to be in the house with a servant as witness, and would not take pains to destroy the body while leaving his own walking stick behind as identification." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mcFarlaneWalkingStick, :oldacreWill ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Proposes Alternative Tramp Theory" ;
    ex:description "To demonstrate to Lestrade that the evidence admits alternative explanations, Holmes constructs a hypothetical scenario involving a passing tramp who could have committed the crime." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A passing tramp could have seen the documents through the half-drawn blind, entered after McFarlane left, killed Oldacre with the stick, and burned the body to conceal the murder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the bedroom blind was only half down and the French window open, meaning a passing stranger could have observed the valuable documents, entered the room, seized the available stick, killed Oldacre, and then burned the body to hide that any murder had occurred at all." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:refutedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Will Is the Key to the Case" ;
    ex:description "After Lestrade departs with McFarlane, Holmes announces his intention to investigate at Blackheath rather than Norwood, explaining his reasoning to Watson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The logical starting point for the investigation is the curious will, not the crime scene, because the will's suspicious circumstances precede and may explain the apparent crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified two singular incidents in close succession — the sudden, unexpected will and the apparent murder — and argued that the police erred by concentrating on the criminal second incident while ignoring the first. Understanding why Oldacre made such a strange will to an unknown heir would illuminate what followed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreWill ;
    ex:deductionSubject :norwoodBuilderCase ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oldacreWill ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Important Papers Are Missing from the Safe" ;
    ex:description "While examining the contents of Oldacre's safe at Deep Dene House, Holmes notices discrepancies between the documents present and those referenced in other papers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Some of Oldacre's most valuable documents, including certain deeds, appear to have been removed from the safe, which would undermine the prosecution's case since McFarlane as heir had no reason to steal what he would inherit." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found allusions in the remaining papers to deeds — possibly the more valuable ones — that were absent from the safe. If proven, this would turn Lestrade's argument against itself, as no heir would steal property he was about to inherit legally." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreSafe ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreBuildingDocuments ;
