:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Housekeeper Has Guilty Knowledge" ;
    ex:description "After interviewing Mrs. Lexington at Deep Dene House and finding her uncooperative, Holmes reports to Watson his conviction that she is concealing information." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Lexington possesses guilty knowledge about the case and is deliberately withholding information." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes detected a sort of sulky defiance in the housekeeper's eyes, which in his experience accompanies guilty knowledge rather than mere reticence. Despite her cooperative words, her manner betrayed concealment." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsLexington ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Suspicious Payments to Mr. Cornelius" ;
    ex:description "Reviewing Oldacre's bank book, Holmes discovers that large cheques made out to a Mr. Cornelius account for the depleted state of Oldacre's finances, raising questions about this unknown party." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oldacre's low bank balance is principally due to large cheques paid to a Mr. Cornelius, suggesting either a hidden business relationship or financial irregularity." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the bank book and found that the balance was low primarily because of large cheques written to a Mr. Cornelius, yet no corresponding scrip or securities were found among Oldacre's papers to explain these as legitimate investments." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreBankBook ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oldacreBankBook ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldacreBankingFraud ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Thumbprint Was Planted Overnight" ;
    ex:description "When Lestrade triumphantly presents the bloody thumbprint as conclusive evidence against McFarlane, Holmes reacts with suppressed amusement rather than dismay, having noticed a critical flaw in the evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The thumbprint on the wall was not present when Holmes examined the hall the previous day, proving it was placed there overnight — after McFarlane was already in custody." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes stated that he had carefully examined the hall during his visit and was certain the wall was clear. Since McFarlane was in jail, he could not have made the mark, meaning someone else placed it there during the night to strengthen the case against him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Oldacre Is Hiding in the House" ;
    ex:description "Having concluded that the thumbprint was planted by someone within Deep Dene House, Holmes forms the conviction that Oldacre himself is concealed somewhere on the premises." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jonas Oldacre is alive and hiding within Deep Dene House." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The planted thumbprint proved that someone inside the house was actively working to frame McFarlane. Combined with the missing documents, the suspicious will, and the housekeeper's guilty demeanour, Holmes concluded that Oldacre had faked his own death and was still present in the building." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deepDeneHouse ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesFireRuse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Locates the Hidden Room by Measuring Corridors" ;
    ex:description "Holmes inspects the house from basement to attics and discovers a discrepancy in corridor lengths on the top floor that reveals the location of a concealed space." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A hidden room exists at the end of the top-floor corridor, revealed by the corridor being six feet shorter than its counterpart on the floor below." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes paced the top corridor and found it was six feet shorter than the corresponding corridor on the floor below, making it clear that a concealed space had been constructed behind a partition at the end of the passage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hiddenRoom ;
    ex:deductionSubject :deepDeneHouse ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesFireRuse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Oldacre Would Panic at a Fire Alarm" ;
    ex:description "Rather than simply breaking into the hidden room, Holmes devises a stratagem to force Oldacre to reveal himself, reasoning about the hidden man's psychological state." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oldacre would lack the nerve to remain hidden if he believed the house was on fire, and would flee his hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes judged that a man concealed in a cramped hidden room, hearing shouts of fire and smelling smoke, would not have sufficient nerve to remain quiet and risk being burned alive, and would instead reveal himself by emerging from his hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesFireRuse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Thumbprint Was Fabricated from a Wax Seal" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation to Lestrade, Holmes explains the precise method by which Oldacre manufactured the damning thumbprint evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oldacre obtained McFarlane's thumbprint by having him press his thumb into soft wax when sealing documents, then used this wax impression moistened with blood from a pin-prick to stamp the mark on the wall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled that when the legal packets were sealed, Oldacre had McFarlane secure one seal by pressing his thumb on the soft wax — a natural action the young man would not question or remember. Oldacre later took the wax impression, moistened it with blood from a pin-prick, and pressed it against the wall during the night, either personally or through his housekeeper." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:deductionSubject :waxThumbSeal ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :waxThumbSeal, :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Cornelius Is Oldacre Under an Alias" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation, Holmes identifies the mysterious Mr. Cornelius as Jonas Oldacre operating under a false name to siphon his own assets." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mr. Cornelius is Jonas Oldacre himself using a false identity, and the large cheques were Oldacre transferring his wealth to himself under this alias at a provincial bank." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the large cheques to Cornelius with Oldacre's scheme to disappear, reasoning that Oldacre had been banking the money under the Cornelius name at a provincial town where he led a double existence, intending to draw out the funds after his staged death and start a new life." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreBankingFraud ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :oldacreBankBook ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Oldacre's Complete Vindictive Scheme" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation to Lestrade, Holmes lays out the full scope of Oldacre's elaborate plot, tracing it from its origin in romantic rejection to its execution as a combined fraud and framing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Oldacre's entire scheme was motivated by decades-old vindictive hatred toward McFarlane's mother for rejecting his courtship, combined with a plan to defraud his creditors by faking his death and framing her son for murder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes synthesised multiple strands: Oldacre's romantic rejection by McFarlane's mother had festered into a lifelong desire for revenge; his financial difficulties from secret speculation drove him to swindle creditors via the Cornelius alias; he combined both motives into a single plan — the will created an obvious motive for McFarlane, the secret visit provided opportunity, the retained stick and planted evidence provided means, and the animal remains and fire simulated a murder, allowing Oldacre to disappear with his hidden funds while the son of the woman who spurned him faced the gallows." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mrsMcFarlanePhotograph, :oldacreBankBook, :oldacreWill, :thumbprintOnWall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bonfire Contained Animal Remains" ;
    ex:description "In his closing remarks, Holmes identifies the organic material found in the timber-yard bonfire as animal remains rather than human." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The charred organic remains and blood found in the bonfire came from dead rabbits or similar animals, not from a human body." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes challenged Oldacre to reveal what he put into the wood-pile besides his old trousers, and when Oldacre refused to answer, Holmes suggested that a couple of rabbits would account both for the blood traces and for the charred organic remains found in the ashes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bonfireAnimalBones ;
    ex:deductionSubject :timberYardFire ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bonfireAnimalBones ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_norwoodBuilder_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: McFarlane Murdered Oldacre for His Inheritance" ;
    ex:description "Lestrade presents his comprehensive theory of the crime to Holmes, arguing that the circumstantial evidence conclusively points to McFarlane as the murderer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "McFarlane learned he stood to inherit Oldacre's fortune, visited him that night, waited until the housekeeper retired, murdered him in his bedroom, burned the body in the wood-pile, and fled to a nearby hotel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade assembled the evidence: McFarlane had a clear financial motive from the will, arranged a private visit that night telling no one, was the last known person to see Oldacre alive, his walking stick was found bloodstained at the scene, blood was in the bedroom, charred remains and trouser buttons were in the bonfire, and no papers had been stolen — all pointing to a murder committed by the sole beneficiary." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnHectorMcFarlane ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonasOldacre ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :mcFarlaneWalkingStick, :oldacreWill, :trouserButtons, :bonfireAnimalBones ;
    ex:refutedBy :oldacreFakedMurder ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_norwoodBuilder_holmes_11 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :norwoodBuilderDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_dukeofholdernesse_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Duke's Theory: Lord Saltire Fled to the Duchess in France" ;
    ex:description "During the initial interview at the Priory School, the Duke offers his theory that the boy may have fled to his estranged wife in the South of France, aided by the German master Heidegger." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Saltire may have fled to the Duchess in France, assisted by the German master." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Duke noted that Lord Saltire's sympathies were strongly with his mother, who had recently departed for the South of France. The boy was known to have moped after the separation. Heidegger, as a foreigner, might plausibly have helped the boy travel abroad. The Duke considered this the most natural explanation for the simultaneous disappearance of boy and master." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordSaltire ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_priorySchool_holmes_14 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Huxtable Travelled from Mackleton" ;
    ex:description "While Watson examines the unconscious Huxtable, Holmes draws a return ticket from the man's watch-pocket and identifies his point of origin." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Huxtable has travelled from Mackleton in the North of England and started very early that morning." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found a return ticket from Mackleton in Huxtable's watch-pocket and noted it was not yet twelve o'clock, indicating the man must have caught a very early morning train from the north to arrive in London by that hour." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Three Days Have Elapsed Since the Disappearance" ;
    ex:description "During Huxtable's initial account, Holmes observes the headmaster's unshaven chin and infers the time that has passed since the crisis began." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Three days have elapsed since Lord Saltire's disappearance, as indicated by Huxtable's chin." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the state of Huxtable's chin — the degree of stubble growth — and used it to calculate that approximately three days had passed since the man had last attended to his grooming, coinciding with the onset of the crisis." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Dismisses the Bicycle-as-Blind Theory" ;
    ex:description "During questioning at Baker Street, Holmes dismantles Huxtable's suggestion that Heidegger's missing bicycle was a blind to mislead investigators." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The missing bicycle was not a blind; a cunning kidnapper hiding bicycles would have hidden two to simulate departure by both parties." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Huxtable suggested the bicycle might have been hidden to create a false trail. Holmes pointed out that if someone wished to create the impression of departure by bicycle, they would have hidden two bicycles — not just one — since other bicycles were available in the shed. The single missing bicycle was therefore genuine evidence, not misdirection." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :heideggerBicycle ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :heideggerBicycle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Fugitives Went North Across the Moor" ;
    ex:description "Studying the ordnance map at the Priory School, Holmes systematically eliminates possible escape routes and concludes the fugitives must have headed north across Lower Gill Moor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The fugitives did not use the road and must have crossed the moor to the north toward Holdernesse Hall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A constable was posted at the eastern crossroads from midnight to six and saw nobody pass. The Red Bull Inn on the western end had people watching the road all night awaiting a doctor, and they also saw no one. The road was therefore blocked in both directions. To the south lay arable land with stone walls making bicycle travel impossible. Only the northern moor — with its paths, open terrain, and proximity to Holdernesse Hall — remained as a viable escape route." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordSaltire ;
    ex:deductionSubject :heidegger ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :lowerGillMoor ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Dunlop Tyre Track as Not Heidegger's" ;
    ex:description "Upon discovering a bicycle track in the moor path, Holmes examines the tyre impression and determines it does not belong to Heidegger's bicycle." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bicycle track on the moor was made by a Dunlop tyre with a patch, not by Heidegger's Palmer-tyred bicycle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes was familiar with forty-two different tyre impressions. The track showed a Dunlop tyre with a patch on the outer cover, whereas Heidegger's bicycle had Palmer tyres leaving longitudinal stripes — confirmed by Aveling, the mathematical master. The track therefore belonged to a different cyclist." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :heideggerBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_priorySchool_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Determines the Bicycle's Direction of Travel" ;
    ex:description "Examining the tyre tracks on the moor path, Holmes determines the direction of travel from the relative depth of the wheel impressions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bicycle was travelling away from the school, not toward it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the more deeply sunk impression was the hind wheel, which bears the rider's weight. At several points the hind wheel's track crossed and obliterated the shallower front wheel mark. This pattern indicated the bicycle was heading away from the school's direction." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Considers the Possibility of a Deliberate Tyre Change" ;
    ex:description "After tracing the Dunlop tracks back toward the Ragged Shaw, Holmes pauses to consider whether a cunning criminal might have deliberately changed a bicycle tyre to leave misleading tracks." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A cunning criminal might have changed the tyre to leave unfamiliar tracks, though this remains speculative." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted it was possible that someone could change a bicycle tyre to leave misleading impressions, and remarked that a criminal capable of such forethought would be a worthy adversary. He left this theory undecided and continued investigating." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Heidegger Was Sprinting When He Fell" ;
    ex:description "Following the Palmer tyre tracks across the moor, Holmes reads the impression patterns to determine Heidegger was riding at maximum speed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Heidegger was forcing the pace and sprinting when he fell from his bicycle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that both tyre impressions were equally deep at certain points, meaning the rider was throwing his weight forward onto the handle-bar as a man does when sprinting. The track then showed a broad irregular smudge indicating a fall, followed by footmarks and the tyre reappearing as the rider remounted." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :heidegger ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :heideggerBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfHeidegger ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lord Saltire Left of His Own Free Will" ;
    ex:description "After discovering Heidegger's body, Holmes reconstructs the sequence of events on the night of the disappearance, beginning with the boy's voluntary departure." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Saltire left the school voluntarily; he was not abducted from his room." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The boy was fully dressed in his school suit when he departed, indicating he foresaw what he intended to do and prepared accordingly. He climbed down the ivy from his window deliberately. No signs of forced entry or struggle were found in his room, and the sleeping boys in the adjacent room heard nothing." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordSaltire ;
    ex:confirmedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Heidegger Acted on Short Notice and Pursued the Boy" ;
    ex:description "Holmes contrasts the boy's full dress with the German master's partial dress to reconstruct their respective states of mind on the night of the disappearance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Heidegger acted on very short notice, spotted the boy's flight from his window, and pursued him on his bicycle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Unlike the fully dressed boy, Heidegger left without his socks and only partly dressed, indicating he acted on sudden impulse rather than premeditation. Holmes reasoned that Heidegger saw the boy's flight from his bedroom window and immediately seized his bicycle to pursue and bring him back. The fact that Heidegger chose the bicycle rather than running on foot indicated he could see the boy had some swift means of escape." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :heidegger ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :heideggerBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Boy Had a Companion on Horseback" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that the boy must have had an accomplice, and that the murder of Heidegger could not have been committed by a cyclist or by the boy alone." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Saltire had a companion who killed Heidegger with a savage blow; the companion was neither a cyclist nor on foot, and the boy had access to some swift conveyance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Heidegger was killed five miles from the school by a violent blow from a vigorous arm — not a bullet a boy might discharge. This proved a companion was present. The death occurred after a five-mile pursuit, indicating swift flight. Yet the ground around the murder scene showed only cattle tracks and no human footprints or second bicycle track within fifty yards. The absence of footmarks meant the companion's mode of transport left no conventional human trace." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordSaltire ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderOfHeidegger ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_priorySchool_holmes_12 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cow Tracks Were Made by Horses with Modified Shoes" ;
    ex:description "At the Fighting Cock Inn, Holmes suddenly recalls the cow tracks seen throughout the day and realizes they are not genuine cattle prints but were made by horses wearing specially modified horseshoes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cow tracks on the moor were made by horses shod with shoes shaped to resemble cloven hoofprints, explaining the absence of human or horse tracks near the murder scene." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled seeing cow tracks at the morass, on the path, and near Heidegger's body — yet they had not seen a single cow anywhere on the moor. He further recalled that the track patterns varied: sometimes evenly spaced, sometimes alternating, sometimes in a different pattern — corresponding to a walk, canter, and gallop respectively. A real cow does not canter or gallop in that fashion. The tracks were made by horses whose shoes had been modified to leave cloven-foot impressions, a deception devised to throw pursuers off the trail." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :reubenHayes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :medievalHorseshoes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :medievalHorseshoes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Dunlop Bicycle as James Wilder's" ;
    ex:description "After observing James Wilder cycling frantically to the Fighting Cock Inn, Holmes creeps to the door and examines the bicycle Wilder left against the wall." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Dunlop bicycle with the patched tyre that left tracks on the moor belongs to James Wilder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes struck a match and held it to the back wheel of the bicycle Wilder had ridden to the Fighting Cock Inn, revealing a patched Dunlop tyre — identical to the distinctive track they had followed across the moor from near the school. This identified Wilder as the second cyclist whose tracks they had been tracing." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesWilder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :wilderBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :wilderBicycle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lord Saltire Is at the Fighting Cock Inn" ;
    ex:description "At Holdernesse Hall, Holmes confronts the Duke and reveals that he knows the boy's location, having traced the evidence across the moor and observed the secretive activities at the inn." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lord Saltire is being held at the Fighting Cock Inn, approximately two miles from the Hall park gate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had traced the modified horse tracks and the Dunlop bicycle trail toward the Fighting Cock Inn. He observed Wilder's frantic visit there, the departure of Hayes's dog-cart in apparent flight, and then Wilder meeting an unidentified person at the inn that night. By peeping through the upstairs window, Holmes confirmed the boy's presence. The convergence of physical evidence and observed behaviour at the inn established it as the boy's hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lordSaltire ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fightingCockInn ;
    ex:confirmedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Accuses the Duke of Complicity in the Kidnapping" ;
    ex:description "In the dramatic confrontation at Holdernesse Hall, after confirming the reward and the boy's location, Holmes astounds everyone by directly accusing the Duke himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Duke of Holdernesse is complicit in concealing his son's whereabouts and protecting those responsible for the kidnapping." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had observed the Duke arriving at the Fighting Cock Inn the previous night — the person Wilder was waiting for at the door. The Duke's secretive nocturnal visit to the very inn where Lord Saltire was hidden proved the Duke knew his son's location and was actively involved in concealing it. Holmes also inferred that the Duke had funded Hayes's attempted flight from the money provided through Wilder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fightingCockInn ;
    ex:confirmedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Reuben Hayes as Heidegger's Murderer" ;
    ex:description "Holmes arranges for the arrest of Reuben Hayes at Chesterfield, having identified him as the man who killed the German master during the kidnapping." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Reuben Hayes is the murderer of Heidegger, and Holmes has him arrested at Chesterfield." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the modified horseshoe tracks at the murder scene to the horses stabled at the Fighting Cock Inn. Hayes was the landlord of the inn and a former coachman to the Duke with expertise in horses. The short metal-headed stick Hayes brandished at Holmes matched the type of weapon that could deliver the fatal blow to Heidegger's skull. After observing Hayes's flight by dog-cart toward Chesterfield, Holmes telegraphed the local police to intercept him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :reubenHayes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderOfHeidegger, :hayesStick ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfReubenHayes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces James Wilder Is Not the Murderer" ;
    ex:description "During the confrontation with the Duke, Holmes clarifies that his accusation does not extend to murder, recognizing that Wilder orchestrated the kidnapping but did not commit the killing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "James Wilder conspired in the kidnapping but was not the murderer of Heidegger." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes stated that he realized the Duke's anguished words referred to James Wilder, and that Wilder was not the murderer. Holmes had observed that the fatal blow was struck by a vigorous arm with a heavy weapon at a remote location where Hayes operated, while Wilder had travelled by bicycle on a different route. The murder was the work of Hayes, the brutal accomplice, not the conspiring secretary." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jamesWilder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :murderOfHeidegger ;
    ex:confirmedBy :dukeOfHoldernesse ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_priorySchool_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Diagnoses Huxtable's Collapse as Exhaustion" ;
    ex:description "When Thorneycroft Huxtable collapses on the Baker Street hearthrug, Holmes asks Watson for his medical assessment, and Watson diagnoses the condition from the man's pulse." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Huxtable's collapse is caused by absolute exhaustion, possibly hunger and fatigue." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson examined Huxtable's thready pulse, noting the stream of life was thin and small, and diagnosed absolute exhaustion rather than any acute illness, recognizing the signs of prolonged physical deprivation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorneycroftHuxtable ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :priorySchoolDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Printed Note Was Torn to Remove Identifying Mark" ;
    ex:description "Examining the printed slips of paper brought by Mrs. Warren, Holmes notices that the paper has been torn away at the side after the printing was done, partially removing a letter." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The lodger tore the edge of the printed note to remove a mark — such as a thumbprint or other identifying clue — that might reveal the person's identity." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the paper was torn at the side after the word was printed, cutting through the 's' of 'soap.' He concluded that there was some mark, thumbprint, or other identifying feature on the torn portion that the lodger wished to conceal." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Cigarette Stub Indicates a Clean-Shaven Smoker" ;
    ex:description "Mrs. Warren brings Holmes burnt matches and a cigarette end found on the lodger's tray. Holmes examines the cigarette stub and notes it could only have been smoked by a clean-shaven person, contradicting the description of the bearded lodger." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cigarette stub was smoked down so far that only a clean-shaven person could have smoked it without singeing facial hair, contradicting the bearded male lodger's description." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the cigarette end was matted and smoked very close to the tip, far closer than a bearded or moustached person could manage without singeing. He noted that even Watson's modest moustache would have been singed, and ruled out a cigarette holder because the end was matted rather than clean-cut." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cigaretteEvidence ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Lodger Has Been Substituted" ;
    ex:description "After Mrs. Warren departs, Holmes presents to Watson his theory that the person currently occupying the rooms is not the same person who originally rented them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The current occupant of Mrs. Warren's rooms is a different person from the one who originally took the lodgings." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined several observations: the lodger went out only on the first night and someone returned when all witnesses were in bed, so there is no proof the same person came back. The original lodger spoke fluent English, but the printed notes use 'match' instead of 'matches,' suggesting someone who took the word from a dictionary and lacks fluency. The laconic style conceals the absence of English knowledge. Combined with the clean-shaven cigarette evidence contradicting the bearded lodger, Holmes concluded a substitution had occurred." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cigaretteEvidence ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Agony Column Messages as Communications to the Lodger" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons that a person in total seclusion who cannot receive letters must be contacted through newspaper advertisements, and searches the Daily Gazette agony column to find messages signed 'G' that correspond to the lodger's arrival." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The agony column messages signed 'G' in the Daily Gazette are communications directed to the hidden lodger, providing instructions and reassurance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that a person in complete isolation who cannot be approached by letter can only receive outside communication through newspaper advertisements. He noted the lodger requested the Daily Gazette each morning. Searching the agony column, Holmes found messages signed 'G' beginning two days after the lodger's arrival, with content matching the situation: promises of arrangements, patience, and eventually a signal code using candle flashes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionSubject :gennaroLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :agonyColumnBook, :dailyGazette ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deciphers Candle Signals as Italian Warning Messages" ;
    ex:description "Watching from the lodging-house window at dusk, Holmes observes candle flashes from the high red house across the street and decodes the signals using the alphabet cipher described in the agony column." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The candle signals spell 'ATTENTA' and 'PERICOLO' — Italian words meaning 'Beware' and 'Danger' — confirming the lodger is an Italian woman being warned of imminent threat." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Using the code from the agony column ('One A, two B, and so on'), Holmes decoded the flashes as spelling ATTENTA, repeated three times for urgency, followed by PERICOLO. He recognized these as Italian words, with the 'A' ending of 'ATTENTA' indicating the message was addressed to a woman, confirming both the Italian nationality and female sex of the lodger." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :howeStreetCandle, :howeStreetSignaling ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Attack on Mr. Warren Was Mistaken Identity" ;
    ex:description "When Mrs. Warren reports that her husband was abducted on the street by two men, bundled into a cab, and released on Hampstead Heath, Holmes immediately connects the attack to the lodger." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The men who attacked Mr. Warren mistook him for the lodger in the foggy morning light; they are enemies of the lodger who do not know about the substitution." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the lodger is in danger, and the attackers, lying in wait near the door, mistook Mr. Warren for the lodger in the fog. On discovering their mistake they released him unharmed. This confirmed that the enemies are unaware of the substitution of the female lodger for the male." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrWarren ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abductionOfMrWarren ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Full Situation of the Fugitive Couple" ;
    ex:description "After glimpsing the lodger through the mirror and confirming she is a woman, Holmes synthesizes all his observations into a comprehensive reconstruction of the situation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A couple sought refuge in London from terrible danger; the man installed the woman secretly in lodgings while he worked elsewhere, using printed messages to hide her sex and the agony column to communicate indirectly." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes confirmed the substitution upon seeing the woman's face through the mirror. He then reconstructed the full picture: a couple fleeing serious danger came to London. The man needed to do some work and hid the woman in absolute safety at Mrs. Warren's. The printed messages prevented her handwriting from revealing her sex. The man cannot approach her directly or he would lead their enemies to her, so he communicates through the agony column. The attack on Mr. Warren showed the enemies were near but unaware of the substitution. The woman's terrified face confirmed the matter is one of life or death." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:deductionSubject :gennaroLucca ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cigaretteEvidence, :abductionOfMrWarren, :agonyColumnBook ;
    ex:confirmedBy :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redCircle_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces Lodger Prints Notes to Conceal Handwriting" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks Watson what the lodger's use of printed rather than written notes might suggest, Watson immediately offers an inference." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The lodger prints rather than writes notes in order to conceal their handwriting from the landlady." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed that printing is a deliberate choice over writing and inferred the most obvious motive: the lodger wished to prevent the landlady from seeing their handwriting, which might reveal something about their identity." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :emiliaLucca ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_redCircle_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redCircleDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Wilson Has Done Manual Labour" ;
    ex:description "After Watson's unsuccessful attempt to read Wilson's appearance, Holmes rattles off a series of deductions about the client, beginning with the observation that Wilson has at some time done manual labour." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jabez Wilson has at some time done manual labour." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Wilson's right hand is quite a size larger than his left, indicating that he has worked extensively with it and the muscles are more developed. Wilson confirmed he began as a ship's carpenter." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jabezWilson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jabezWilson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
