:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Spaulding Has an Ulterior Motive for Half Wages" ;
    ex:description "During his questioning of Wilson about the assistant Vincent Spaulding, Holmes notes with evident significance that Spaulding accepted the position at half wages, recognising this as a critical clue." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Spaulding has a strong ulterior motive for securing the position at Wilson's pawnshop, since no competent worker would accept half wages without one." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that from the time he heard of the assistant having come for half wages, it was obvious that Spaulding had some strong motive for securing the situation, as the financial sacrifice was inconsistent with the behaviour of a capable worker who could earn twice the salary elsewhere." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnClay ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfJohnClay ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Spaulding as John Clay" ;
    ex:description "When Wilson describes his assistant as having a white splash of acid upon his forehead, Holmes sits up in considerable excitement and confirms his suspicion by asking about pierced ears, recognising the description as matching the criminal John Clay." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Vincent Spaulding is actually the notorious criminal John Clay." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognised the description of a white acid splash on the forehead and pierced ears as identifying marks of John Clay, a murderer, thief, smasher, and forger whom Holmes had encountered before. Holmes later ranked him as the fourth smartest man in London." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnClay ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfJohnClay ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the League Scheme Exists to Keep Wilson Away" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation at Baker Street after the arrest, Holmes reveals that the true purpose of the Red-Headed League and the Encyclopaedia copying was immediately obvious to him as a device to secure Wilson's absence from his shop." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The only possible object of the Red-Headed League advertisement and the copying of the Encyclopaedia was to get Wilson out of his pawnshop for a number of hours every day." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognised that the elaborate and expensive scheme of the League, paying four pounds a week for nominal work copying the Encyclopaedia, could have no purpose other than to secure the regular absence of the pawnbroker from his premises, as there was no other rational explanation for such expenditure." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :redHeadedLeague ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :redHeadedLeagueAdvertisement ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfJohnClay ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Clay Is Tunneling from the Cellar" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons through what Clay could be doing in Wilson's cellar during the daily absences, eliminating possibilities until arriving at the conclusion that a tunnel is being dug." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Clay is using Wilson's cellar to dig a tunnel to another building." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes eliminated a vulgar intrigue because there were no women in the house, and ruled out anything inside the house because Wilson's business was too small to justify such elaborate preparations. Combining the assistant's fondness for photography with his trick of vanishing into the cellar, Holmes concluded it must be something outside the house, and could think of nothing save that Clay was running a tunnel to some other building." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnClay ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :tunnelDigging ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bankVaultAmbush ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Tunnel Target Is the City and Suburban Bank" ;
    ex:description "During the visit to Saxe-Coburg Square, Holmes taps the pavement with his stick to determine the cellar's direction, then walks around the corner to identify the tunnel's destination." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tunnel from Wilson's cellar is directed toward the City and Suburban Bank, which abuts Wilson's premises from behind." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes beat upon the pavement with his stick to ascertain whether the cellar stretched out in front or behind the shop, determining it was not in front. He then walked round the corner and saw the City and Suburban Bank abutted on Wilson's premises, concluding the bank was the tunnel's target. He also observed that Clay's trouser knees were worn, wrinkled, and stained, confirming hours of burrowing." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cityAndSuburbanBankCoburgBranch ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bankVaultAmbush ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :redHeadedLeagueDoc .

:deduction_redHeadedLeague_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Robbery Attempt Will Come Saturday Night" ;
    ex:description "After the League offices are dissolved, Holmes predicts the timing of the robbery attempt and arranges the ambush in the bank vault accordingly." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The criminals will attempt the bank robbery on Saturday night." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the closure of the League offices signalled that the tunnel was complete and Wilson's absence was no longer needed. The criminals had to act quickly before the tunnel was discovered or the bullion removed. Saturday was ideal because it gave them two days for their escape before Monday business hours." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :attemptedBankRobbery ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :redHeadedLeagueDissolutionNotice ;
