:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Notes the Odd Assortment Stolen From Acton's" ;
    ex:description "On the evening of their arrival at Colonel Hayter's, Holmes hears the list of items stolen from Acton's house and begins to observe that the burglary is significant, though Watson silences him before he can elaborate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The peculiar assortment of items stolen from Acton's house — a volume of Pope's Homer, candlesticks, a letter-weight, a barometer, and twine — is not random but reveals something about the burglars' true purpose." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized that the odd, low-value collection of stolen items did not match the behavior of ordinary thieves seeking profit. The seemingly random haul suggested the burglars were after something specific and grabbed miscellaneous items to disguise their true objective." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :actonBurglary ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :popesHomer ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldCunningham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Two Local Burglaries Are Connected and Unusual" ;
    ex:description "Over breakfast the morning after the murder, Holmes reflects on the pattern of two burglaries occurring in the same district within days of each other." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A gang of burglars would normally vary the scene of their operations rather than crack two cribs in the same district within a few days, making this pattern suspicious." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Professional burglars would be expected to move to different areas to avoid detection. Two break-ins targeting the largest houses in the same parish within days suggested either local perpetrators or a specific motive connecting the two crimes rather than opportunistic theft." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :actonBurglary ;
    ex:deductionSubject :williamKirwanMurder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Paper Fragment as the Key to the Case" ;
    ex:description "After examining the scrap of paper found in William Kirwan's hand, Holmes declares that the fragment is of extreme importance and represents the key to the mystery." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The torn paper fragment in the dead man's hand, bearing the time of his death, is the central clue to solving the case." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The fragment bore the exact hour at which William met his death, indicating whoever wrote the note lured him out at that time. The fact that someone tore the rest of the sheet from the dead man's grip showed the note incriminated the killer, and recovering the remainder would go a long way toward solving the mystery." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :reigateNote ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Alec Cunningham Tore the Paper From the Dead Man" ;
    ex:description "During his investigation at the crime scene, Holmes reasons about who could have torn the paper from William Kirwan's hand, given the timeline Alec Cunningham described." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Alec Cunningham himself must have torn the paper from the dead man's hand, not the fleeing burglar." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "If Alec Cunningham's own narrative was correct and the assailant fled immediately after shooting William, then the fleeing man could not have stopped to tear paper from the corpse's hand. By the time old Cunningham descended, servants were already on the scene. The only person who had access to the body before others arrived was Alec, who claimed to have knelt beside the dying man." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :reigateNote ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Was Written by Two Persons Alternating Words" ;
    ex:description "During his detailed examination of the paper fragment at the Cunningham house, Holmes performs a handwriting analysis that reveals the note was not written by one person." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The note fragment was written by two different persons who alternated words, each writing every other word." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes compared the strong t's in 'at' and 'to' with the weak ones in 'quarter' and 'twelve,' demonstrating two distinct hands. The stronger hand wrote 'learn' and 'maybe' while the weaker hand wrote 'what.' The alternating pattern of strong and weak letter formations across adjacent words proved two writers took turns." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :reigateNote ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Ringleader From the Handwriting" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his handwriting analysis, Holmes determines which of the two writers planned the criminal enterprise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The man with the stronger hand who wrote 'at' and 'to' was the ringleader who planned the affair." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Examination of the spacing showed the stronger-hand writer wrote all his words first, leaving blanks for the other to fill in. The second writer had to squeeze his word 'quarter' into an insufficient gap between 'at' and 'to,' proving the first writer composed the note's structure. The man who wrote all his words first and left blanks was undoubtedly the planner." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldCunningham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Ages of the Two Writers" ;
    ex:description "Holmes applies his expertise in determining age from handwriting to the two hands present in the note fragment." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "One writer was a young man and the other was advanced in years, based on the characteristics of their handwriting." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The bold, strong hand of one writer indicated youth and vigor, while the broken-backed appearance of the other hand, whose t's had begun to lose their crossing yet retained legibility, indicated an elderly writer who was not yet positively decrepit. Holmes noted that handwriting age analysis can place a person in their true decade with tolerable confidence in normal cases." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Two Writers Are Blood Relatives" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies a family resemblance in the handwriting of the two authors of the note, pointing to a biological relationship between them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The two writers of the note are blood relatives, as indicated by shared handwriting characteristics that represent a family mannerism." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed common features between the two hands, most obviously in the formation of the Greek e's, but also in numerous smaller points. These shared characteristics indicated a family mannerism traceable across both specimens of writing, leading Holmes to conclude the writers were blood relatives." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Cunninghams as Authors of the Note" ;
    ex:description "Synthesizing his handwriting analysis — two writers, one old and one young, blood relatives, one the ringleader — Holmes concludes that the Cunningham father and son wrote the incriminating note." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Cunninghams, father and son, jointly wrote the note that lured William Kirwan to his death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Combining all handwriting findings — two alternating writers who are blood relatives, one elderly and one young, with the elder as ringleader — Holmes identified the only pair matching all criteria: old Mr. Cunningham and his son Alec. Holmes confirmed this by tricking old Cunningham into writing 'twelve' on a reward notice and comparing it with the 'twelve' on the note fragment." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNotFragment, :reigateRewardNotice ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldCunningham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces No Experienced Burglar Would Break In With Lights Visible" ;
    ex:description "While questioning the Cunninghams at their house, Holmes points out a logical inconsistency in the supposed burglary scenario." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "An experienced burglar would not deliberately break into a house when lit lamps in two windows showed members of the family were still awake." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Alec was smoking in his dressing-room with a lamp lit, and his father also had a lamp burning. Both rooms had windows visible from the outside. A burglar with previous experience, as the Acton robbery suggested, would have seen the lights and known the household was not yet asleep, making it extraordinary that he would choose that moment to force entry." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cunninghamHouse ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Alec Lied About the Struggle" ;
    ex:description "Holmes's examination of the dead man's wound reveals that Alec Cunningham's account of the shooting cannot be true." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The fatal shot was fired from over four yards away, proving Alec Cunningham lied when he claimed the two men were struggling when the shot was fired." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes determined with absolute confidence that the revolver wound was inflicted from a distance of something over four yards, as there was no powder-blackening on William Kirwan's clothes. This directly contradicted Alec Cunningham's statement that the burglar and coachman were wrestling when the shot was fired, which would have required close contact." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :williamKirwanMurder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces No Unknown Man Was Ever at the Scene" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examines the supposed escape route of the alleged burglar and finds physical evidence disproving the Cunninghams' story entirely." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There was never any unknown burglar at the scene — the Cunninghams fabricated the intruder entirely." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Both father and son agreed the man escaped into the road at a specific point. However, at that point there was a broadish ditch, moist at the bottom. The complete absence of bootmarks in or around the ditch proved that no one had crossed it, demonstrating not only that the Cunninghams had lied again but that there had never been any unknown man upon the scene at all." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cunninghamArrest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cunninghams Burgled Acton's for Lawsuit Documents" ;
    ex:description "Holmes connects the Acton burglary to the ongoing lawsuit between the Acton and Cunningham families, deducing the true motive behind the break-in." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Cunninghams broke into Acton's library to steal documents that would be important in the ongoing lawsuit over the Cunningham estate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes learned from Colonel Hayter that a lawsuit had been going on between Acton and the Cunninghams. It instantly occurred to him that they had broken into the library with the intention of getting at some document of importance to the case. Finding nothing, they carried off miscellaneous items to make it appear an ordinary burglary and divert suspicion." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oldCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionSubject :actonBurglary ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :actonBurglary ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrActon ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_reigateSquires_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces William Was Murdered to End His Blackmail" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation, Holmes reveals the complete motive for William Kirwan's murder, which was confirmed by old Cunningham's confession." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "William Kirwan had secretly followed his masters during the Acton raid and was blackmailing them, prompting Alec Cunningham to devise a plan to murder him under cover of the burglary scare." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that William had knowledge giving him power over the Cunninghams, explaining why the coachman was lured out by a note at a specific time rather than confronted directly. Old Cunningham's confession confirmed that William had followed them to Acton's, witnessed the break-in, and levied blackmail. Alec saw in the ongoing burglary scare an opportunity to plausibly eliminate the blackmailer by staging another break-in." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :williamKirwan ;
    ex:deductionSubject :alecCunningham ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :reigateNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :oldCunningham ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :reigateSquiresDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Brougham Belongs to a General Practitioner" ;
    ex:description "Upon returning to Baker Street and seeing a brougham waiting at their door, Holmes immediately deduces the visitor's profession and experience level before entering the house." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The visitor is a doctor in general practice, not long established but already busy." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the nature and state of the various medical instruments visible in the wicker basket hanging in the lamplight inside the brougham. The instruments identified the owner as a medical man, while their condition and variety indicated a general practitioner rather than a specialist, one who had not been long in practice but had already accumulated considerable work." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :trevelyanBrougham ;
    ex:confirmedBy :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Trevelyan Has Been Waiting Only Minutes" ;
    ex:description "Upon meeting Dr. Trevelyan in their sitting-room, Holmes remarks that the doctor has only been waiting a very few minutes, surprising Trevelyan who assumes Holmes spoke to his coachman." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Trevelyan has only been waiting a very few minutes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the candle on the side-table rather than speaking to the coachman. The state of the candle — how far it had burned down since being lit — indicated only a brief period of waiting." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:confirmedBy :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Young Man Infiltrated Blessington's Room" ;
    ex:description "After visiting Blessington and being rebuffed, Holmes explains to Watson on the walk home that the young man penetrated to Blessington's room on both occasions while his confederate kept the doctor occupied." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The young man posing as the Russian nobleman's son entered Blessington's room both times while his confederate distracted Dr. Trevelyan with feigned symptoms." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "On both visits, the older patient kept Trevelyan occupied in the consulting room — first through a prolonged examination and then through a cataleptic seizure that required the doctor to leave the room for medication. Meanwhile, the younger man was left unattended in the waiting room with access to the upper floors. The footprints found in Blessington's room matched the timing of both visits." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianSon ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfBlessington ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Catalepsy Was Fraudulent" ;
    ex:description "Walking home from Brook Street, Holmes tells Watson that the Russian patient's cataleptic attack was a deliberate imitation, noting he would hardly dare suggest this to the specialist Trevelyan." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The old man's cataleptic seizure was a fraudulent imitation designed to distract Dr. Trevelyan." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognised catalepsy as a very easy complaint to imitate, noting he had done it himself. The seizure occurred at precisely the moment needed to draw Trevelyan away from the consulting room and send him downstairs to his laboratory, providing the young man with unobserved time upstairs." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianCount ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :firstRussianVisit, :secondRussianVisit ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfBlessington ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Unusual Consultation Hour Was Deliberate" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains to Watson that the choice of quarter past six for the consultation was calculated to ensure no other patients would be in the waiting room." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The unusual evening consultation hour was deliberately chosen to ensure no other patients would witness the young man's movements." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A quarter past six was well outside normal consulting hours, making it virtually certain that the waiting room would be empty and the young man could move freely through the house without being observed by other patients. The timing happened to coincide with Blessington's daily constitutional walk, though Holmes noted this appeared coincidental rather than planned, suggesting the intruders were not fully acquainted with his daily routine." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianCount ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianSon ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :firstRussianVisit, :secondRussianVisit ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Blessington Knows His Persecutors" ;
    ex:description "After Blessington refuses to provide honest information during Holmes's visit, Holmes concludes on the walk home that Blessington certainly knows the identity of his persecutors and is deliberately suppressing it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Blessington knows who the two men are and is deliberately concealing their identity and his connection to them." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes read in Blessington's eyes that it was his own skin he feared for, not merely his possessions. If the intruders were merely after plunder, they would have searched the room, but nothing was taken. It was inconceivable that a man could have made two such vindictive enemies without knowing of it. Holmes therefore held it certain that Blessington knew the men and was suppressing their identity for reasons of his own." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blessingtonPistol ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfBlessington ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms a Third Party From Stair-Carpet Footprints" ;
    ex:description "When Watson suggests Trevelyan may have fabricated the Russian patient story, Holmes dismisses the theory by citing footprint evidence from the stair-carpet that independently corroborates the doctor's account." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The stair-carpet footprints prove a third party distinct from both Trevelyan and Blessington visited the upper floors." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The young man left prints on the stair-carpet that Holmes examined. The shoes were square-toed rather than pointed like Blessington's, and were quite an inch and a third longer than the doctor's shoes. This physical evidence made it superfluous to examine the footprints in Blessington's room and conclusively established the individuality of the intruder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianSon ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Murder Not Suicide From Cigar Evidence" ;
    ex:description "At the scene of Blessington's death, Holmes examines the cigar case and four cigar ends found in the fireplace, and declares that Blessington was murdered, not a suicide." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Blessington's death was not suicide but a deeply planned and cold-blooded murder by multiple people." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Blessington's cigar case contained a single Havana cigar, but the four cigar ends in the fireplace were of a different type — Dutch East Indian cigars imported from the colonies, thinner for their length than any other brand. Furthermore, two of the ends had been smoked from a holder and two without, two had been cut by a not very sharp knife and two had been bitten off by a set of excellent teeth. This proved at least two other people had been smoking in the room during the night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cigarEnds, :blessingtonCigarCase, :blessingtonCigarHolder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Entry Through Front Door Barred by Confederate" ;
    ex:description "When Inspector Lanner challenges how intruders could have entered given the barred front door, Holmes states they came through the front door and it was barred after them by a confederate inside the house." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderers entered through the front door, which was then barred behind them by an accomplice already inside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed traces at the door that indicated entry from outside. Since the door was found barred from the inside in the morning, someone inside the house must have barred it after the intruders departed. Holmes identified the page boy — who had only recently entered Trevelyan's service — as the most likely confederate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :trevelyanPageBoy ;
    ex:confirmedBy :trevelyanPageBoy ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Murder of Blessington" ;
    ex:description "After examining the bedroom, Holmes delivers a detailed reconstruction of the night's events to Inspector Lanner and Dr. Trevelyan, tracing the movements and actions of the three intruders from entry to departure." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Three men — the fake Russian count, his supposed son, and a third unknown man — were admitted by the page, ascended on tiptoe in a specific order, forced Blessington's locked door with a wire, gagged him, held a judicial proceeding while smoking cigars, then hanged him from the lamp hook." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced the number and order of the intruders from superimposed footmarks on the stairs, which he could identify from having observed the young man's prints the night before. The elder man went first, the younger second, and the unknown third. Scratch marks on the door ward showed where a wire had been used to force the key round from outside. The cigar evidence placed three smokers in distinct positions — the older man in the wicker chair using a holder, the younger knocking ash against the chest of drawers, the third pacing. A screwdriver and screws indicated they had brought equipment for a gallows but used the existing lamp hook instead. The door was barred afterward by their confederate." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cigarEnds, :screwdriverAndScrews, :blessingtonRope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Blessington as Sutton of the Worthingdon Bank Gang" ;
    ex:description "After taking Blessington's photograph and making inquiries, Holmes returns to reveal that Blessington was really Sutton, a member of the Worthingdon bank gang who turned informer, and his killers are the surviving gang members Biddle, Hayward, and Moffat." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Blessington's true identity is Sutton, the informer of the 1875 Worthingdon bank gang. His assailants are Biddle, Hayward, and Moffat, released gang members seeking revenge for his betrayal." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes took Blessington's photograph and used it to make inquiries, discovering that the man was well known at police headquarters under his real name Sutton. In 1875, five men — Biddle, Hayward, Moffat, Cartwright, and Sutton — committed the Worthingdon bank robbery, murdering the caretaker Tobin. Sutton turned informer, leading to Cartwright's hanging and fifteen-year sentences for the other three. Having recently been released, the three survivors tracked down the traitor to exact revenge for their comrade's death." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blessingtonPhotograph ;
    ex:confirmedBy :inspectorLanner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_inspectorlanner_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lanner's Theory: Blessington Committed Suicide From Fright" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Lanner, first on the scene of Blessington's death, concludes that the man was driven to suicide by terror, noting the bed had been slept in and the early morning hour is when suicides are most common." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Blessington committed suicide, driven out of his senses by fright." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lanner observed that the bed had been well slept in, showing a deep impression. He noted that approximately five in the morning is when suicides are most common, which would correspond to the apparent time of death. The affair appeared deliberate to him, consistent with a man who had been visibly terrified in the preceding days." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorLanner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_residentPatient_holmes_08 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_percytrevelyan_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Trevelyan Deduces the Visitor Ascended to Blessington's Room" ;
    ex:description "After Blessington discovers footprints in his room, Dr. Trevelyan reasons from the evidence that the man in the waiting room must have gone upstairs to Blessington's quarters during the consultation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The young man from the waiting room ascended to Blessington's room while Trevelyan was busy with the older patient." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Trevelyan observed that the footprints on Blessington's carpet were certainly much larger than any Blessington could have made, and were evidently fresh. Since it had rained hard that afternoon and the Russian patients were the only callers, Trevelyan concluded the man in the waiting room had ascended to Blessington's room for some unknown reason while the doctor was occupied with the other patient." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fakeRussianSon ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_residentPatient_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Trevelyan Fabricated the Russian Patient Story" ;
    ex:description "On the walk home from Brook Street, Watson suggests to Holmes that the entire story of the cataleptic Russian and his son might be Trevelyan's own fabrication, and that it was the doctor himself who had been in Blessington's rooms." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Trevelyan may have invented the Russian patients and entered Blessington's rooms himself." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson acknowledged the theory was grotesquely improbable but still just conceivable. He reasoned that Trevelyan, having his own purposes, could have concocted the whole story of the cataleptic Russian nobleman and his son as a cover for his own intrusion into Blessington's private quarters." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :percyTrevelyan ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_residentPatient_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_residentPatient_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Estimates Time of Death From Muscular Rigidity" ;
    ex:description "At the scene of Blessington's death, Watson offers a professional medical opinion on the time of death based on his examination of the body." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Blessington has been dead about three hours, based on the rigidity of his muscles." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "As a trained army surgeon, Watson judged the rigidity of the muscles in Blessington's body and estimated that death had occurred approximately three hours before their morning examination." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blessington ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :residentPatientDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley Has an Artificial Limb" ;
    ex:description "While Watson describes Amberley's physical appearance after visiting Lewisham, Holmes interjects with a detail Watson missed — the wrinkled left shoe and smooth right shoe." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Josiah Amberley has an artificial limb, as evidenced by the differing condition of his shoes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Amberley's left shoe was wrinkled while his right was smooth, indicating the right leg is artificial — a wrinkled shoe shows natural foot movement, while a smooth shoe indicates a prosthetic that does not flex." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley's Seat Number From the Ticket" ;
    ex:description "After Watson reports that Mrs. Amberley's unused theatre ticket was number thirty-one, Holmes immediately infers Amberley's seat number." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley's theatre seat was either number thirty or thirty-two, as adjacent to his wife's ticket number thirty-one." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Theatre seats are numbered consecutively, so a couple purchasing tickets together would have adjacent seats. Since the wife's ticket was number thirty-one, the husband's seat must have been either thirty or thirty-two in row B." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :unusedTheatreTicket ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Suspects the Painting Is Meant to Conceal Another Smell" ;
    ex:description "After Watson reports that Amberley was painting the interior of his house despite his supposed distress over his wife's departure, Holmes questions this unusual behaviour." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley's painting activity is suspicious — painting at such a time suggests he is trying to cover another smell with the strong odour of paint." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes asked Watson specifically about the painting and noted it was strange for a supposedly grief-stricken man to be filling his house with strong paint odours. The logical inference was that the paint smell was intended to mask some other guilty smell that would arouse suspicion." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :greenPaint ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesBurglaryHaven ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Tall Dark Man as Barker" ;
    ex:description "When Watson describes being followed by a tall, dark, heavily moustached man, Holmes immediately identifies the individual and adds details Watson had not mentioned." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The man following Watson was Barker, a rival private detective, identifiable by his gray-tinted sun-glasses and Masonic tie-pin." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson described a tall, dark, heavily moustached, military-looking man who followed him from Lewisham to London Bridge. Holmes, already aware of Barker as his professional rival on the Surrey shore, recognized the description and completed it by specifying the gray-tinted sun-glasses and Masonic tie-pin — details Holmes knew from prior acquaintance with Barker." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :barkerDetective ;
    ex:confirmedBy :barkerDetective ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley Never Went to the Theatre" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examined the box-office chart at the Haymarket Theatre and discovered that neither seat B30 nor B32 was occupied on the night in question, destroying Amberley's alibi." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley did not attend the theatre on the night of the supposed elopement, as the seats adjacent to his wife's ticket were unoccupied." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Having deduced Amberley's seat number from Watson's report of the wife's ticket, Holmes checked the Haymarket Theatre box-office chart and found that neither seat B30 nor B32 in the upper circle had been occupied that night. This proved Amberley's alibi was fabricated." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :unusedTheatreTicket, :haymarketTheatre ;
    ex:confirmedBy :confrontationAmberley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Strong-Room Was Used as a Gas Chamber" ;
    ex:description "During his covert examination of the house, Holmes discovered a gas pipe running into the sealed strong-room, revealing the murder method." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The hermetically sealed strong-room was converted into a gas chamber using a pipe connected to a tap in the corridor, allowing the room to be flooded with gas." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined two facts: the strong smell of paint intended to conceal another odour, and the existence of a hermetically sealed room with iron door and shutters. Examining the house during the burglary, he found a gas-pipe running along the skirting into the strong-room, ending in a concealed plaster rose in the ceiling, with an external tap that could flood the sealed room with gas." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :amberleyStrongRoom ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :gasPipe, :greenPaint, :amberleyStrongRoom ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesBurglaryHaven ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley Murdered His Wife and Dr. Ernest" ;
    ex:description "Holmes confronts Amberley at Lewisham with Barker present, directly accusing him of murder by asking what he did with the bodies — triggering Amberley's attempted suicide." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley murdered his wife and Dr. Ray Ernest by luring them into the sealed strong-room and gassing them, then staged a fake elopement to cover the crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined multiple lines of evidence: the suspicious painting to mask the gas smell, the fabricated theatre alibi, the sealed strong-room with hidden gas pipe, and Amberley's jealous and scheming nature. The supposed elopement was a cover story for double murder, with Amberley playing the victim while having killed both his wife and her alleged lover." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsAmberley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rayErnest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :greenPaint, :gasPipe, :amberleyStrongRoom, :unusedTheatreTicket ;
    ex:confirmedBy :confrontationAmberley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Wall Writing as a Dying Message" ;
    ex:description "Holmes shows the inspector a scribbled message on the strong-room wall just above the skirting, written in purple indelible pencil, reading 'We we—'." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The incomplete wall inscription 'We we—' was a dying message from one of the victims attempting to write 'We were murdered.'" ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The writing was only a foot above the ground, indicating the writer was on the floor and dying. Written in purple indelible pencil so it could not easily be removed, the incomplete message 'We we—' was the beginning of 'We were murdered' — the victim lost consciousness before completing it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rayErnest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :purpleIndeliblePencil ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bodies Are Hidden in a Disused Well" ;
    ex:description "When the inspector asks where the bodies might be found, Holmes directs him to search for a disused well in the cellars or garden." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bodies of the victims are concealed in a disused well on the property, likely covered by a dog-kennel." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the house is older than the water-pipes, meaning it must have a disused well somewhere on the property. This provided a ready-made hiding place for the bodies. He directed the police to try the cellars and garden, and the bodies were indeed found in a well concealed by a dog-kennel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsAmberley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :rayErnest ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :theHavenLewisham, :dogKennel ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderAmberleyErnest ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley Hid the Securities Himself" ;
    ex:description "The inspector notes that there was clearly no robbery, yet Amberley did possess the bonds. Holmes explains Amberley's plan for the securities." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley hid his own securities in a safe place and planned to later claim the 'guilty couple' had returned or dropped the plunder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since the elopement was staged, there was no actual theft. Amberley possessed the bonds and hid them, planning to 'discover' them after the supposed elopement had faded from memory, claiming the fugitives had relented and sent back the money or dropped it along the way." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :amberleyDeedBox ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Amberley Consulted Him Out of Arrogance" ;
    ex:description "The inspector wonders why Amberley, having committed murder, would consult Sherlock Holmes. Holmes explains it as overconfidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Amberley consulted Holmes out of pure swank and arrogance, believing himself so clever that no one could expose him, and wanting to point to the consultation as proof of his innocence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Amberley felt so clever and sure of himself that he imagined no one could touch him. By consulting both the police and Sherlock Holmes, Amberley could tell any suspicious neighbour that he had taken every step to find his missing wife, using the consultation itself as a shield of innocence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahAmberley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_retiredColourman_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Infers He Is Being Followed by the Tall Dark Man" ;
    ex:description "After visiting Amberley at Lewisham, Watson notices the same tall, dark, heavily moustached man he had seen lounging outside The Haven now boarding a train at Blackheath Station and again at London Bridge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson concludes that the tall dark man he encountered outside The Haven followed him from Lewisham to London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson first noticed the man smoking outside The Haven when he asked for directions. Later, at Blackheath Station, the same man darted into the carriage next to Watson's. Watson spotted him again at London Bridge before losing him in the crowd. The repeated sightings convinced Watson he was being followed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :barkerDetective ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :retiredColourmanDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_ireneadler_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Adler Deduces the Clergyman Was Holmes and the Fire Was a Ruse" ;
    ex:description "After the fire-alarm incident at Briony Lodge, Irene Adler pieces together that the kindly clergyman was Sherlock Holmes in disguise and that the entire affair was engineered to locate the photograph, as revealed in her letter left for Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The clergyman who was brought into Briony Lodge was Sherlock Holmes in disguise, and the fire alarm was a ruse to make her reveal the photograph's hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Adler had been warned months ago that the King might employ Holmes. After the fire alarm caused her to instinctively rush to the photograph, she realized she had betrayed its location. Despite initially finding it hard to suspect the kind old clergyman, her training as an actress made her sensitive to disguise. She then followed Holmes in male costume to Baker Street, confirming he was the celebrated detective, and decided to flee with the photograph." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :ireneAdler ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :scandalPhotograph ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brionyLodgeFireRuse ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Has Gained Weight Since Marriage" ;
    ex:description "Upon Watson's visit to Baker Street after a period of separation, Holmes looks him over and immediately comments that wedlock suits him and that he has gained seven and a half pounds." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has put on seven and a half pounds since his marriage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Watson's general appearance and physical changes since their last meeting, using his knowledge of Watson's prior build to estimate the precise weight gain associated with the settled domestic life of marriage." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Has Returned to Medical Practice" ;
    ex:description "During the same initial exchange at Baker Street, Holmes observes that Watson has gone back into medical practice without being told." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has returned to active medical practice." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes detected the smell of iodoform on Watson, observed a black mark of nitrate of silver on his right forefinger, and noticed a bulge on the right side of his top-hat where he had secreted his stethoscope — all unmistakable signs of an active member of the medical profession." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Has Been Out in Wet Weather" ;
    ex:description "Holmes further deduces that Watson has recently been getting himself very wet, which Watson confirms was from a country walk on Thursday." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has recently been out in vile weather and gotten very wet." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that on the inside of Watson's left shoe, where the firelight struck it, the leather was scored by six almost parallel cuts caused by someone carelessly scraping round the edges of the sole to remove crusted mud — evidence of having been out in wet, muddy conditions." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Has a Clumsy Servant Girl" ;
    ex:description "From the same observation of Watson's shoe, Holmes deduces that Watson employs a particularly careless servant girl, which Watson confirms is the incorrigible Mary Jane." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has a clumsy and careless servant girl." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The parallel cuts on Watson's shoe leather were caused by someone who had very carelessly scraped round the edges of the sole to remove crusted mud, indicating an incompetent servant rather than careful cleaning — a 'malignant boot-slitting specimen of the London slavey' as Holmes put it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryJane ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Anonymous Note Is Written on Bohemian Paper" ;
    ex:description "Examining the anonymous note that announces a mysterious visitor, Holmes identifies the paper's origin from the watermark, which Watson had mistaken for a maker's monogram." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The anonymous note was written on paper manufactured in Egria, Bohemia." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified the watermark letters 'Eg' 'P' and 'Gt' as standing for 'Egria' (a Bohemian town), 'Papier' (German for paper), and 'Gesellschaft' (German for company), and confirmed via the Continental Gazetteer that Egria was in Bohemia, known for its paper-mills." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :anonymousNote ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :anonymousNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Writer Is German" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis of the anonymous note, Holmes identifies the writer as German based on the sentence construction." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The writer of the anonymous note is a German." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted the peculiar sentence construction 'This account of you we have from all quarters received,' with the verb displaced to the end — a distinctly German syntactic pattern that a Frenchman or Russian could not have produced." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :anonymousNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Visitor as the King of Bohemia" ;
    ex:description "When the masked visitor arrives and introduces himself as Count Von Kramm, Holmes sees through the disguise and addresses him as 'Your Majesty,' identifying him as Wilhelm Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein, hereditary King of Bohemia." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The masked visitor calling himself Count Von Kramm is actually the King of Bohemia." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had already deduced from the Bohemian paper and German syntax that a wealthy German-speaking Bohemian of royal standing was involved. Upon meeting the visitor — his extraordinary height, rich dress, authoritative manner, and the deference implied by needing a mask — Holmes combined these observations with his prior analysis to identify the King before he removed his mask." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :anonymousNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :wilhelmVonOrmstein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Norton-Adler Relationship Is Romantic" ;
    ex:description "After spending a morning in disguise gathering intelligence near Briony Lodge, Holmes reasons about the nature of Godfrey Norton's frequent visits to Irene Adler and their implications for the photograph's location." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Godfrey Norton's relationship with Irene Adler is romantic rather than professional, meaning she likely has not transferred the photograph to his keeping." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Norton visiting daily or twice daily, noted the urgency of their joint rush to the Church of St. Monica for a hasty wedding, and reasoned that if the relationship were merely legal (client-lawyer), she would likely have transferred the photograph to his keeping; as a romantic partner, she would retain personal custody of it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :godfreyNorton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ireneAdler ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :adlerNortonWedding ;
    ex:confirmedBy :adlerNortonWedding ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Photograph Is Hidden in Adler's House" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reasons through the possible locations of the compromising photograph and concludes it must be kept in Adler's own home at Briony Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The compromising photograph is hidden somewhere in Irene Adler's house rather than with a banker, lawyer, or on her person." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes eliminated the possibility that Adler carries it (cabinet-sized, too large to conceal on her person, and the King has already had her waylaid and searched). He dismissed a banker or lawyer as custodian because women are naturally secretive and prefer their own guardianship, and because Adler could not know what political influence might be brought to bear on a businessman. Since she planned to use it within days, it must be where she can lay her hands on it immediately — in her own house." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :scandalPhotograph ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Locates the Photograph Behind the Sliding Panel" ;
    ex:description "Using the fire-alarm ruse at Briony Lodge, Holmes observes Adler's instinctive reaction and identifies the exact hiding place of the compromising photograph." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The photograph is concealed in a recess behind a sliding panel just above the right bell-pull in the sitting-room of Briony Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes applied his principle that when a woman believes her house is on fire, her instinct is to rush to the thing she values most. When the smoke-rocket alarm was raised, Adler instinctively rushed to a recess behind a sliding panel above the right bell-pull, and Holmes caught a glimpse of the photograph as she half-drew it out before realizing it was a false alarm." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :scandalPhotograph ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :brionyLodgeFireRuse, :smokeRocket ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ireneAdler ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Marriage Simplifies the Case" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning of the Adler-Norton wedding, Holmes reasons that the marriage changes Adler's incentives regarding the photograph." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Adler's marriage to Norton makes the photograph a double-edged weapon, as she would now be as averse to its exposure as the King is." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that a married woman would not want a compromising photograph with a former lover to come to her new husband's attention, just as the King does not want it reaching his princess. The marriage therefore reduces the blackmail threat because Adler now has her own reputation to protect." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ireneAdler ;
    ex:deductionSubject :scandalPhotograph ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :adlerNortonWedding ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :scandalInBohemiaDoc .

:deduction_scandalInBohemia_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Assumes Adler Will Not Act Before Morning" ;
    ex:description "After the fire-ruse success, Holmes confidently tells Watson they will return at eight in the morning to retrieve the photograph, assuming Adler will not anticipate them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Adler will not take any protective action before Holmes returns in the morning, and the photograph will still be in its hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes assumed that Adler would not connect the evening's events to an attempt on the photograph, and that she would not be up at eight in the morning, giving them a clear field. He underestimated her intelligence and her capacity to see through his disguise." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
