:deduction_secondStain_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Theft Window and That the Document Is Already Gone" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Trelawney Hope's account of the missing letter, Holmes analyzes the timeline and concludes that recovery is likely impossible." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The document was taken between 7:30 and 11:30 p.m., probably near the earlier hour, and has already been passed on to those who need it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that since Hope and his wife were both in the bedroom from 11:30 p.m. onward, the theft must have occurred during the four-hour window when the despatch-box was unguarded. The thief, knowing the document's location, would have secured it as early as possible and immediately forwarded it to interested parties, making recovery impossible." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :diplomaticLetterSecondStain ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :despatchBoxSecondStain ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_secondStain_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Three Possible Agents Behind the Theft" ;
    ex:description "After the statesmen depart, Holmes narrows the field of suspects to three international spies capable of such a theft and plans to visit each of them." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Only three agents — Oberstein, La Rothiere, and Eduardo Lucas — are capable of orchestrating the theft of a state document of this importance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes drew on his knowledge of the international espionage community to identify the three heads of their profession. He reasoned that the thief would have passed the document to an independent agent rather than an embassy, since these agents work independently and their relations with embassies are often strained." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :oberstein ;
    ex:deductionSubject :laRothiere ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eduardoLucas ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lucas's Murder Is Connected to the Document Theft" ;
    ex:description "Upon learning from the morning paper that Eduardo Lucas was murdered the same night the document disappeared, Holmes immediately rejects Watson's suggestion that it is a coincidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murder of Eduardo Lucas and the theft of the diplomatic letter are connected events, not a coincidence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes calculated that one of only three possible suspects meeting a violent death on the very night the document was stolen presented odds enormously against coincidence. He concluded the two events must be connected and that the task was to find the connection." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eduardoLucas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :murderEduardoLucas ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lucas Was the Most Likely Agent Due to Proximity" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies a geographic detail that singles out Lucas from the other two agents as the most probable recipient of the stolen document." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Eduardo Lucas was the most likely agent to have received the document because his residence at Godolphin Street, Westminster, is only minutes from Whitehall Terrace, making it easier for him to establish a connection with someone in Hope's household." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that Godolphin Street is only a few minutes' walk from Whitehall Terrace, while the other two agents lived in the extreme West End. In a compressed timeframe, proximity would have been essential for establishing contact or receiving a message from the Secretary's household." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eduardoLucas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :16GodolphinStreet, :whitehallTerrace ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lady Hilda's Visit Is Suspicious" ;
    ex:description "After Lady Hilda Trelawney Hope visits 221B Baker Street to inquire about the stolen document, Holmes analyzes her behavior and concludes her stated purpose does not fully explain her manner." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Hilda's appearance, suppressed excitement, tenacity in questioning, and deliberate positioning with her back to the light indicate she has a hidden motive beyond wifely concern." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed her emotional agitation, her restlessness, her persistent questioning, and the fact that she deliberately chose the one chair that placed the light behind her so they could not read her expression. He noted she comes from a class that does not lightly show emotion, making her visible distress all the more significant." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Document Has Not Left England" ;
    ex:description "After three days of silence with no European complications arising, Holmes reasons that the stolen letter has not been forwarded to any foreign power." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The diplomatic letter has not been passed on to any foreign chancellery, because if it were loose in Europe there would already be signs of trouble." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes received almost hourly reports from the Government confirming no sign of trouble anywhere in Europe. He reasoned that if the letter had been sent to a foreign power, its provocative contents would have produced visible diplomatic consequences within three days. The silence proved it was being held back somewhere." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :diplomaticLetterSecondStain ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Carpet Was Turned Round" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene in Godolphin Street, Lestrade shows Holmes that the bloodstain on the carpet does not correspond with a second stain on the floor beneath. Holmes instantly explains the discrepancy." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The carpet has been turned round, which is why the stain on the carpet no longer aligns with the stain on the floor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the carpet was a square drugget, unfastened and simply laid on a polished floor. Since both surfaces bore matching stains that no longer aligned, the simplest explanation was that someone had rotated the carpet after the blood had soaked through." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :druggetSecondStain ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :druggetSecondStain ;
    ex:confirmedBy :constableMacPherson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Hiding Place Exists Under the Carpet" ;
    ex:description "Holmes becomes intensely excited upon learning that someone moved the carpet, and engineers a diversion to search beneath it. He finds a hinged floorboard concealing a small cavity." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There is a hiding place beneath the drugget — a hinged floorboard concealing a cavity — where Lucas hid the stolen document." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the fact that the carpet had been moved with the missing document. If Lucas had received the letter, he needed a hiding place. The turned carpet indicated someone had accessed something beneath it. Holmes distracted Lestrade by sending him to interrogate the constable, then tore up the drugget and found a hinged floorboard opening to a small black cavity — but the document was already gone." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eduardoLucas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :diplomaticLetterSecondStain ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :druggetSecondStain ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Lady Hilda as the Woman Who Visited the Crime Scene" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Constable MacPherson's description of the woman who gained access to the crime scene, Holmes shows the constable a portrait cutout, which is recognized. Holmes identifies the visitor as Lady Hilda Trelawney Hope." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The tall, handsome woman who talked her way into the Godolphin Street crime scene, fainted on the carpet, and was left alone in the room was Lady Hilda Trelawney Hope." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes matched MacPherson's description — a tall, handsome, well-spoken, genteel young woman in a long mantle — with Lady Hilda, whose suspicious visit to 221B had already raised his suspicions. He confirmed the identification by showing MacPherson a portrait cutout he had been carrying, which the constable recognized." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cutOutPortrait ;
    ex:confirmedBy :constableMacPherson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Lady Hilda's Complete Role in the Affair" ;
    ex:description "Having identified Lady Hilda as the visitor and found the empty hiding place, Holmes assembles the full picture: Lady Hilda stole the document, gave it to Lucas, and then returned to retrieve it after his murder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Hilda took the document from her husband's despatch-box, delivered it to Eduardo Lucas, and after his murder returned to Godolphin Street to recover it from the hiding place under the carpet." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected Lady Hilda's suspicious visit to Baker Street, her emotional state, Lucas's proximity to Whitehall Terrace, the moved carpet at the crime scene, the empty hiding place beneath the floorboard, and MacPherson's account of the tall woman who fainted on the carpet and was left alone. The faint was a ruse to be left alone in the room, during which she recovered the letter from under the turned drugget." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:deductionSubject :diplomaticLetterSecondStain ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :druggetSecondStain, :cutOutPortrait ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: Mme Fournaye Murdered Lucas in a Jealous Rage" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene, Lestrade presents his reconstruction of the murder based on the Paris news identifying Mme Henri Fournaye as Lucas's secret wife." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mme Fournaye arrived at Godolphin Street as a surprise visit, was admitted by Lucas, reproached him, and in a jealous fury stabbed him with the Indian dagger from the wall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade reconstructed the scene: Lucas could not keep his wife in the street so he let her in, she traced him and reproached him, one thing led to another, and with the dagger conveniently at hand from the wall trophy she struck. The overturned chairs showed a struggle in which Lucas tried to hold her off with a chair." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :henriFournaye ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eduardoLucas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :indianDaggerSecondStain ;
    ex:confirmedBy :ladyHildaTrelawneyHope ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_secondStain_lestrade_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade Observes the Second Stain Anomaly" ;
    ex:description "Lestrade discovers that the bloodstain on the carpet does not correspond to a stain on the floor beneath, and deduces that someone must have been admitted to the room to move the carpet." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Someone was admitted to the crime scene who moved or disturbed the carpet, as demonstrated by the non-corresponding stains." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade noted that while the carpet bore a large bloodstain, no corresponding stain appeared on the white woodwork directly beneath it. A second stain on the floor at a different position proved the carpet had been shifted. Since a constable was on duty, someone must have been improperly admitted." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :druggetSecondStain ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :druggetSecondStain ;
    ex:confirmedBy :constableMacPherson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :secondStainDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Glue Linking Cap to Picture-Frame Maker" ;
    ex:description "At Baker Street, Holmes demonstrates his microscopic analysis of a cap found beside the dead policeman in the St. Pancras case, identifying a substance that connects the accused man to the crime." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The substance on the cap is glue, linking it to the accused picture-frame maker who habitually handles glue." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined scattered materials on the cap under a low-power microscope, identifying tweed fibres, dust, epithelial scales, and brown blobs which he determined to be glue. Since the accused man is a picture-frame maker who routinely works with glue, the cap's contamination connects it to him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pictureFrameMaker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stPancrasCase ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Theory: Quarrel Stems from Sir Robert's Affair with Carrie Evans" ;
    ex:description "During Mason's consultation at Baker Street, Holmes constructs a theory to explain the estrangement between Sir Robert and Lady Beatrice, based on Watson's description of Sir Robert's character and Mason's hints about the maid's loyalties." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The quarrel between Sir Robert and Lady Beatrice arose because Lady Beatrice discovered Sir Robert's affair with her maid Carrie Evans." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned from Watson's characterization of Sir Robert as a man no woman is safe from, combined with Mason's insinuation that the maid Carrie Evans is devoted to Sir Robert rather than to Lady Beatrice. Holmes proposed that Lady Beatrice suddenly discovered the scandal, wanted to dismiss the maid, but Sir Robert would not permit it, leading the bedridden invalid to sulk, drink, and withdraw, while Sir Robert retaliated by giving away her beloved spaniel." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :robertNorberton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beatriceFalder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carrieEvans ;
    ex:refutedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Someone Other Than Sir Robert Burned the Bones" ;
    ex:description "After Mason presents the charred bone fragment and confirms that Sir Robert was away in London the previous night, Holmes draws an immediate logical conclusion about who was responsible for the burning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Whoever was burning bones in the furnace, it was not Sir Robert, since he was in London that night." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mason confirmed that Sir Robert had gone to London and was not home the previous night. Since the bone was found freshly burned in the furnace tended overnight, Holmes concluded by simple elimination that someone else — an accomplice with access to the furnace — must have been responsible for the burning." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :robertNorberton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charredBoneFragment, :shoscombeFurnaceCellar ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Spaniel Was Given Away to Conceal an Impersonation" ;
    ex:description "While reviewing the case data with Watson at the Green Dragon inn, Holmes draws Watson's attention to the significance of Sir Robert giving away Lady Beatrice's favourite dog, implying the dog would expose that the woman in the carriage is not its mistress." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sir Robert gave away Lady Beatrice's spaniel not from spite but because the dog would recognize that the woman being presented as Lady Beatrice is an impostor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the dog was Lady Beatrice's most devoted companion, yet Sir Robert gave it away violently. Holmes reasoned that a dog's loyalty to its owner would cause it to react noticeably if confronted with a stranger impersonating its mistress, and that Sir Robert removed the spaniel to eliminate this risk of exposure." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beatriceSpaniel ;
    ex:deductionSubject :concealmentOfDeath ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :beatriceSpaniel ;
    ex:confirmedBy :spanielTest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Hypothesizes Sir Robert Killed Lady Beatrice and Is Using an Impersonator" ;
    ex:description "In conversation with Watson at the Green Dragon, Holmes proposes a comprehensive hypothesis connecting the evidence along his two lines of inquiry, suggesting Sir Robert has murdered his sister and arranged an impersonation to maintain access to her estate until after the Derby." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Sir Robert has killed Lady Beatrice, hidden her body in the crypt, and is using the maid's accomplice to impersonate her until the Derby race secures his fortune." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes synthesized multiple data points: Sir Robert's desperate financial position dependent on his sister's life interest in the estate, his need to keep creditors at bay until the Derby, the changed behaviour of the supposed Lady Beatrice, the secret crypt visits, the burning of remains in the furnace, and the maid as a willing confederate. He reasoned that if Lady Beatrice were dead, Sir Robert would need to conceal the death, dispose of the body in the seldom-visited crypt, and arrange an impersonation using the maid's cooperation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :robertNorberton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beatriceFalder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charredBoneFragment, :mummyRemains, :beatriceSpaniel ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:refutedBy :deathOfBeatriceFalder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms via Spaniel Test That the Woman in the Carriage Is Not Lady Beatrice" ;
    ex:description "Holmes arranges an experiment at the park gates, releasing Lady Beatrice's spaniel as the carriage passes. The dog's initial joy turning to furious hostility toward the occupant confirms Holmes's suspicion." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The spaniel's hostile reaction to the woman in the carriage proves she is not Lady Beatrice but a stranger impersonating her." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes released the spaniel as the carriage slowed at the park gates. The dog first rushed joyfully toward the carriage, recognizing the familiar vehicle, but upon reaching the occupant it turned hostile and snapped at the figure's skirt. Holmes concluded that the dog initially expected its mistress but discovered a stranger, and that dogs do not make such mistakes of recognition." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :norlett ;
    ex:deductionSubject :concealmentOfDeath ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :beatriceSpaniel, :spanielTest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Predicts the Mummy Remains Have Been Burned in the Furnace" ;
    ex:description "Upon entering the crypt with Mason, Holmes is unsurprised to find the mummy bones missing from their corner, having anticipated that they would have been destroyed in the same furnace used to burn other evidence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The mummy remains previously found in the crypt have been removed and burned in the central heating furnace." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had already connected the charred bone fragment from the furnace to clandestine activity in the crypt. When Mason showed the empty corner where the mummy remains had been stored, Holmes expected their absence, reasoning that whoever placed a body in the crypt would need to dispose of the displaced ancient remains and would use the same furnace that had already been employed for burning evidence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mummyRemains ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charredBoneFragment, :shoscombeFurnaceCellar ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Discovers Lady Beatrice's Body Hidden in an Ancestral Coffin" ;
    ex:description "During a careful examination of the crypt graves, Holmes identifies a leaden coffin with recently disturbed edges, opens it with a jemmy, and discovers the recently deceased body of Lady Beatrice concealed within." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lady Beatrice's body has been hidden inside one of the ancestral coffins in the family crypt." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes systematically examined the graves in the crypt, progressing from the oldest Saxon tombs through the Norman-era coffins to the eighteenth-century Falder monuments. He found a leaden coffin standing on end before the vault entrance whose lid edges showed signs of recent disturbance under his magnifying lens. Using a jemmy, he levered open the front and revealed a recently deceased body wrapped in a sheet." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beatriceFalder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leadenCoffin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :leadenCoffin, :shoscombeChapel ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Identifies the Charred Bone as a Human Femur" ;
    ex:description "When Mason presents a charred bone fragment recovered from the furnace ashes, Watson applies his medical expertise to identify its anatomical origin." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The charred bone fragment is the upper condyle of a human femur." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Despite the bone being burned to a black cinder, Watson drew on his medical training to recognize its anatomical features, identifying it as the upper condyle of a human femur — confirming that human remains had been burned in the furnace." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charredBoneFragment ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charredBoneFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_shoscombeOldPlace_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Recognizes the Voice from the Carriage as Male" ;
    ex:description "Immediately after the spaniel experiment at the park gates, Watson identifies that the harsh voice shouting 'Drive on!' from the carriage was unmistakably that of a man, not a woman." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person in the carriage who shouted at the coachman spoke with a man's voice, not a woman's." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson heard the occupant of the carriage shriek 'Drive on! Drive on!' in a harsh voice when the spaniel became aggressive. Watson immediately recognized that the vocal quality was distinctly male, providing independent evidence that the figure dressed as Lady Beatrice was in fact a man." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :norlett ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :spanielTest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gunRoomConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :shoscombeOldPlaceDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Visited Wigmore Street Post Office" ;
    ex:description "During a discussion of observation versus deduction at 221B Baker Street, Holmes demonstrates his method by telling Watson he visited the Wigmore Street Post Office that morning." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson visited the Wigmore Street Post Office that morning." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed reddish mould on Watson's instep, matching the distinctive earth dug up opposite the Seymour Street office entrance, which is difficult to avoid when entering." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Sent a Telegram" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his demonstration, Holmes deduces that Watson dispatched a telegram at the post office rather than posting a letter or buying stamps." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson sent a telegram at the post office." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had sat opposite Watson all morning and knew he had not written a letter. Watson's desk contained stamps and postcards, so the only remaining reason to visit the post office was to send a wire. By eliminating all other possibilities, the telegram remained." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watch Belonged to Watson's Elder Brother" ;
    ex:description "Watson challenges Holmes to deduce the character of the late owner of a pocket watch. Holmes determines the watch belonged to Watson's elder brother, who inherited it from their father." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The watch belonged to Watson's elder brother, inherited from their father." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The initials H.W. on the back suggested Watson's family name. The watch was nearly fifty years old with equally old initials, indicating the previous generation. Jewelry customarily descends to the eldest son, who typically shares the father's name. Watson's father being long dead, the watch passed through the elder brother." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson's Brother Was Careless and Dissipated" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his examination of the pocket watch, Holmes constructs a portrait of Watson's brother as untidy, careless, left with good prospects but dissolute, alternating between poverty and prosperity, and ultimately dying of drink." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson's brother was careless, left with good prospects, fell into poverty with occasional prosperity, took to drink, and died." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The watch case was dinted and scratched from being kept with hard objects like coins or keys, indicating carelessness with a valuable fifty-guinea watch. Four pawnbroker's numbers scratched inside the case showed the brother was frequently at low water, with occasional bursts of prosperity when he redeemed the pledge. Thousands of scratches around the keyhole showed the unsteady hand of a habitual drunkard winding it at night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Pearl Box and Letter as Same Author" ;
    ex:description "When Mary Morstan presents the anonymous letter and the pearl-box address papers, Holmes examines the handwriting and determines they are by the same person despite attempts at disguise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The pearl-box addresses and the anonymous letter were written by the same person, and the handwriting is unlike Captain Morstan's." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the pearl-box addresses were in disguised hands but the letter was not. Despite the disguise, the irrepressible Greek 'e' and the twirl of the final 's' appeared consistently, proving common authorship. He asked Miss Morstan to compare with her father's hand, which she confirmed was entirely different." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :anonymousLetterToMary ;
    ex:confirmedBy :maryMorstan ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Analyzes Anonymous Letter Writer's Character" ;
    ex:description "After Miss Morstan departs, Holmes analyzes the handwriting of the anonymous correspondent, disagreeing with Watson's assessment of force of character." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter writer is a man of vacillation and self-esteem, not force of character as Watson supposed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson judged the writing legible and regular, suggesting business habits and force of character. Holmes countered that the long letters hardly rise above the common herd, the 'd' might be an 'a' and the 'l' an 'e'. Men of character always differentiate their long letters. Holmes identified vacillation in the writer's k's and self-esteem in his capitals." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :anonymousLetterToMary ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Links Sholto's Death to the Pearl Sendings" ;
    ex:description "After researching the Times back files, Holmes connects Major Sholto's death to the beginning of the anonymous pearl deliveries to Mary Morstan, constructing a theory about the Morstan disappearance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Major Sholto's heir knew the secret of Captain Morstan's fate and began sending pearls as compensation immediately after the Major's death." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Captain Morstan disappeared and the only person he could have visited in London was Major Sholto, who denied knowledge. Four years later Sholto died, and within a week Mary began receiving valuable pearls, continuing annually until a letter calling her a wronged woman. The wrong could only refer to the deprivation of her father, and the presents beginning immediately after Sholto's death indicated the heir knew the mystery and sought to make compensation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maryMorstan ;
    ex:deductionSubject :majorJohnSholto ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pearlChaplet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thaddeusSholto ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Analyzes the Agra Plan Document" ;
    ex:description "In the cab en route to the Lyceum Theatre, Holmes examines the curious paper found in Captain Morstan's desk, identifying its material, construction, and contents." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The paper is of native Indian manufacture, was pinned to a board, contains a plan of a large building with a marked location, and bears the sign of the four with the names Jonathan Small, Mahomet Singh, Abdullah Khan, and Dost Akbar." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes methodically examined the document with his double lens, identifying the paper as Indian manufacture, noting pin-holes showing it had been affixed to a board, reading the diagram as a building plan with a red-ink cross and measurement notation, and deciphering the hieroglyphic of four crosses with the four signatories' names. He recognized it as evidently important since it had been carefully preserved in a pocket-book." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :agraPlan ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :agraPlan ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Bartholomew's Cause of Death as Poison" ;
    ex:description "Upon examining Bartholomew Sholto's body in the locked room at Pondicherry Lodge, Holmes immediately identifies the cause of death as a poisoned thorn, recognizing the symptoms before Watson does." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Bartholomew Sholto was killed by a poisoned thorn driven into his scalp, delivering a powerful vegetable alkaloid." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the drawn muscles of the face as indicative of a powerful alkaloid poison upon first sight. He then searched for the means of delivery and found a dark thorn driven into the scalp just above the ear, at the point that would be turned toward the hole in the ceiling if the victim were erect in his chair. The extreme muscular contraction exceeding normal rigor mortis, combined with the risus sardonicus, confirmed a strychnine-like substance producing tetanus." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bartholomewSholto ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stoneHeadedClub ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Entry via Window by Wooden-Legged Man" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene, Holmes examines the window, sill, and floor to reconstruct how the intruders entered and exited Bartholomew's locked room." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A wooden-legged man climbed up to the window using a rope lowered by an accomplice, entered the room, and departed the same way while the accomplice sealed the window from inside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The window was snibbed on the inner side with a solid framework. Holmes found a footprint in mould on the sill and circular muddy marks on the floor — the impression of a wooden stump alongside a boot-mark with a broad metal heel. A rope in the corner and a great hook in the wall provided the means of ascent. Blood marks on the rope, especially toward the end, showed the wooden-legged man slipped down rapidly, skinning his hands. The accomplice drew up the rope, shut the window, and snibbed it from inside before exiting through the roof." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Wooden-Legged Man Is Not a Sailor" ;
    ex:description "While examining the rope used to enter the crime scene, Holmes observes that the wooden-legged climber, though capable, was not a professional sailor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The wooden-legged man was a fair climber but not a professional sailor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes's lens revealed that the man's hands were far from horny, and there were blood marks on the rope especially toward the end, indicating he slipped during descent and tore the skin off his hands — something a practiced sailor would not do." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Accomplice Entered Through the Roof" ;
    ex:description "After eliminating the door, window, and chimney as means of entry for the accomplice, Holmes applies his elimination principle to determine the route." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The accomplice entered through the hole in the roof leading to the garret above." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The door was locked from inside, the window was snibbed from inside, and the chimney grate was too small. Since the accomplice could not have been concealed in the room, and all other means of entry were impossible, he must have come through the hole in the ceiling connecting to the secret garret where the treasure had been stored." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tonga ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Accomplice's Footprints as Non-European" ;
    ex:description "In the garret above the murder room, Holmes examines the small naked footprints in the dust and determines they belong to someone who has never worn boots." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The footprints belong to someone whose feet have never been confined by boots, indicated by the distinctly separated toes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes compared the footprints to his own naked footprint, demonstrating that his toes were cramped together from habitual boot-wearing while the prints showed each toe distinctly divided. This indicated someone who had never worn boots — ruling out a child, as Watson initially suggested." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tonga ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Creosote Trail for Tracking" ;
    ex:description "Holmes discovers that the accomplice stepped in a leaking carboy of creosote in Bartholomew's chemical laboratory, leaving a traceable scent trail." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The accomplice stepped in creosote from a cracked carboy, creating a scent trail that can be followed by a tracking dog." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found the outline of the accomplice's small foot at the edge of a dark, pungent liquid that had leaked from a cracked carboy. Recognizing the strong tarry smell of creosote on the wood-work of the trap-door where the accomplice exited, Holmes realized a trained dog could follow this distinctive scent." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tonga ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Jonathan Small as the Wooden-Legged Man" ;
    ex:description "Before departing the crime scene, Holmes provides Athelney Jones with a detailed description of one of the two intruders, identifying him as Jonathan Small." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The wooden-legged intruder is Jonathan Small, a poorly-educated, middle-aged, sunburned, bearded man with his right leg off, wearing a wooden stump worn on the inner side, with a coarse square-toed left boot with iron-banded heel, and skin missing from his palm." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the name Jonathan Small from the Agra plan document with the sign of the four card left at the scene. The wooden-legged footprints confirmed a man with his right leg off. Major Sholto had feared a wooden-legged man and specifically a white man (having fired at a white tradesman), and only one white name appeared on the chart. Small must be middle-aged and sunburned from years in the Andamans, his height calculable from his stride length, and bearded as Thaddeus described the face at Major Sholto's window. The rope damage showed skin missing from his palm." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :agraPlan, :signOfTheFourCard ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Jonathan Small's Movements After Sholto's Death" ;
    ex:description "During the tracking expedition with Toby, Holmes explains his complete reconstruction of the case to Watson, tracing Jonathan Small's actions from his arrival in England to the murder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Small came to England seeking vengeance and the treasure, established contact with a confederate in the Sholto household (likely the butler Lal Rao), watched Pondicherry Lodge, appeared at Major Sholto's deathbed window, searched the papers that night and left the sign of the four, then waited years until the treasure was rediscovered before entering with his accomplice to steal it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Two officers commanding a convict-guard learned of buried treasure from an Englishman named Jonathan Small. The chart was dated when Morstan associated with convicts, so Small and his associates were themselves convicts who could not retrieve it. Major Sholto guarded against a wooden-legged white man, matching the sole white name on the chart. Small came to England with a double purpose of treasure and revenge, found Sholto's residence, likely through the butler Lal Rao. Unable to find the treasure's location, Small appeared at the dying Sholto's window, later searched the room and left the sign of the four. When the garret treasure was rediscovered, his confederate informed him, and he brought his accomplice to reach the lofty room." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:deductionSubject :majorJohnSholto ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :agraPlan, :signOfTheFourCard ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Accomplice Is an Andaman Islander" ;
    ex:description "Back at Baker Street, Holmes reveals his theory about the identity of the mysterious small accomplice, rejecting Watson's suggestion of an Indian associate." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The accomplice is an Andaman Islander, a member of one of the smallest races on earth, explaining the diminutive footprints, bare feet, poisoned darts from a blowpipe, and the stone-headed club." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes rejected Watson's suggestion of an Indian because the remarkable character of the footmarks ruled it out — the Hindu proper has long thin feet, and sandal-wearing Mohammedans have the great toe separated. The darts could only be shot from a blowpipe. Consulting a gazetteer, Holmes identified the Andaman Islanders as averaging below four feet, fierce and intractable, wielding stone-headed clubs and poisoned arrows. Since Small had come from the Andamans, it was natural this islander would accompany him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tonga ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stoneHeadedClub, :blowPipe ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_18 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Aurora Was Sent to a Boatyard for Concealment" ;
    ex:description "After failing to locate the Aurora through the Baker Street Irregulars, Holmes reasons out where Jonathan Small would have hidden the steam launch." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 18 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Small sent the Aurora to a boatyard for a trivial repair, effectively concealing it while keeping it available at short notice." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that Small would not scuttle the launch, as he lacked the finesse for that. Small needed time to arrange his affairs before leaving London. He could not leave the launch at a wharf or send it back, as that would make pursuit easy. The only way to conceal the launch while keeping it accessible was to hand it to a boat-builder with directions for a trifling change, which would remove it to a shed. Holmes confirmed this by visiting boatyards in disguise, finding the Aurora at the sixteenth — Jacobson's Yard." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:deductionSubject :theAurora ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mordecaiSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_holmes_19 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Lal Rao Was the Household Confederate" ;
    ex:description "In the final conversation after the case is resolved, Holmes confirms his earlier suspicion that Lal Rao, the butler, was Jonathan Small's confederate inside Pondicherry Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 19 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Lal Rao the butler was Small's confederate in the Sholto household, as Holmes had surmised throughout the investigation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Bernstone had given Lal Rao a poor character. Holmes had theorized early in the case that Small required a confederate inside the household to learn of the treasure's rediscovery and Bartholomew's habits. The butler was the only plausible candidate. Jonathan Small's confession confirmed this, noting he made friends with someone who could help him but naming no names." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lalRao ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_athelneyjones_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Jones's Theory: Thaddeus Sholto Murdered His Brother" ;
    ex:description "Athelney Jones arrives at Pondicherry Lodge and quickly constructs a theory that Thaddeus Sholto killed his brother during a quarrel and stole the treasure." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Thaddeus Sholto quarreled with his brother, killed him in a fit, and walked off with the treasure, escaping through the roof." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Jones noted that Thaddeus was, by his own confession, with his brother the previous night. The brother was dead and the jewels were gone. No one saw the brother after Thaddeus left, his bed had not been slept in, and Thaddeus appeared disturbed. Jones identified the Indian curiosities, poisoned splinter, and trap-door as supporting evidence, claiming Thaddeus brought up the weapon and the card was a blind." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :athelneyJones ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thaddeusSholto ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_signOfFour_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Inference: A Child Committed the Crime" ;
    ex:description "Upon seeing the small naked footprints in the dusty garret above the murder room, Watson concludes that a child committed the murder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A child committed the murder of Bartholomew Sholto." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed the footprints covering the garret floor — clear, well-defined, perfectly formed, but scarce half the size of an ordinary man's. He concluded from their small size alone that a child must have been responsible." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tonga ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_signOfFour_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_signOfFour_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Identifies Cause of Death as Vegetable Alkaloid" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks Watson to examine the body's extreme muscular contraction and facial distortion, Watson provides a medical diagnosis." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Bartholomew Sholto died from a powerful vegetable alkaloid, a strychnine-like substance producing tetanus." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed that the muscles were hard as a board, in a state of extreme contraction far exceeding normal rigor mortis. Coupled with the distortion of the face — the Hippocratic smile or risus sardonicus — Watson concluded this indicated death from a powerful vegetable alkaloid that would produce tetanus." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bartholomewSholto ;
    ex:confirmedBy :jonathanSmall ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :signOfTheFourDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_inspectorgregory_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Gregory's Theory: Fitzroy Simpson Murdered Straker and Stole Silver Blaze" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Gregory presents his theory that Fitzroy Simpson drugged the stable boy, obtained a duplicate key, took the horse, and killed Straker when confronted on the moor." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Fitzroy Simpson drugged the stable boy with opium, used a duplicate key to enter the stables, stole Silver Blaze, and murdered John Straker with his heavy stick when the trainer tried to stop him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Gregory built his case on circumstantial evidence: Simpson had a strong financial interest in the horse's disappearance with five thousand pounds bet against it; he was present at the stables that evening attempting to bribe the stable boy; the opium was attributed to him; his cravat was found in the dead man's hand; his heavy Penang-lawyer stick could have inflicted the fatal injuries; and he was out in the storm that night." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorGregory ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroySimpson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :simpsonCravat, :penangLawyerStick, :simpsonBettingBook, :simpsonStableEncounter ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_02 ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Calculates Train Speed From Telegraph Posts" ;
    ex:description "During the train journey to Dartmoor, Holmes announces their speed as fifty-three and a half miles per hour, surprising Watson who has not been counting mile posts." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The train is travelling at fifty-three and a half miles per hour, calculated from the spacing of telegraph posts." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the telegraph posts along the line are sixty yards apart and timed their passage, performing a simple arithmetic calculation to derive the train's speed without needing the quarter-mile posts Watson expected." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Curried Mutton Eliminates Simpson" ;
    ex:description "While arriving at the trainer's house, Holmes realizes the immense significance of the curried mutton served the night of the crime, a clue he initially overlooked in the newspaper reports." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Fitzroy Simpson could not have caused curry to be served at the trainer's household, so an insider — not Simpson — must have drugged the stable boy's supper." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Powdered opium has a perceptible taste that would be detected in any ordinary dish, but curry would disguise it. Simpson, a stranger, could not possibly have arranged for curried mutton to be served that night. It is too monstrous a coincidence that he arrived with opium on the very night a dish capable of masking it was served. Therefore the drugging was arranged by someone in the household — either Straker or his wife." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fitzroySimpson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :druggingOfNedHunter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Dog Knew the Midnight Visitor" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies the silence of the stable dog as a crucial clue, famously noting the curious incident of the dog in the night-time — that it did nothing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The stable dog did not bark during the night because the midnight visitor was someone it knew well — its master, John Straker." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Simpson incident earlier that evening proved a dog was kept in the stables, yet when someone entered and took out the horse, the dog did not bark enough to rouse the two lads sleeping in the loft. The midnight visitor must therefore have been someone whom the dog knew well." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :kingsPylandDog ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :simpsonStableEncounter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Straker Took the Horse for a Dishonest Purpose" ;
    ex:description "Combining the curried mutton deduction with the silent dog inference, Holmes concludes that John Straker himself led Silver Blaze out of the stables during the night." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Straker went down to the stables in the dead of night and took out Silver Blaze for a dishonest purpose." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Having established that the midnight visitor was known to the dog, and that an insider drugged the stable boy, Holmes concluded Straker himself took the horse. The purpose must have been dishonest, or else why drug his own stable boy? Trainers have been known to lay against their own horses through agents and then prevent them from winning by fraud." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_02, :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_03 ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Cataract Knife as a Surgical Instrument" ;
    ex:description "Examining the contents of Straker's pockets at the trainer's house, Holmes lifts the delicate knife and recognizes it as a surgical instrument unsuitable as a weapon." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The knife found in Straker's hand is a cataract knife — a delicate surgical instrument intended for a precise operation, not a weapon for self-defence." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the knife's very delicate, inflexible blade and noted it was a strange thing for a man to carry on a rough expedition, especially as it would not close in his pocket. Watson confirmed it as a cataract knife, used for the most delicate operations in surgery. Holmes concluded it was carried for a deliberate delicate task, not as a weapon." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cataractKnife ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cataractKnife ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Straker Was Leading a Double Life" ;
    ex:description "Examining Straker's pocket contents, Holmes notes the milliner's account made out to William Derbyshire for an expensive dress and deduces Straker was maintaining a secret mistress." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The milliner's bill for an expensive dress, addressed to the alias William Derbyshire, reveals that Straker was leading a double life and keeping a second establishment with a woman of expensive tastes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that men do not carry other people's bills in their pockets, and immediately concluded Straker was living under the alias Derbyshire. The nature of the bill — a twenty-two-guinea costume from a Bond Street milliner — showed a lady with expensive tastes was involved, far beyond what a trainer's salary could support." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :strakerMistress ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :millinersAccount ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lesurierShop ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Confirms the Dress Never Reached Mrs. Straker" ;
    ex:description "Holmes pretends to have met Mrs. Straker at a Plymouth garden party, describing a dove-colored silk dress with ostrich-feather trimming, to test whether the expensive dress from the milliner's bill belonged to her." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The expensive dress purchased under the Derbyshire alias was not for Mrs. Straker, confirming the existence of Straker's secret mistress." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes fabricated a scenario in which he described a specific expensive dress to Mrs. Straker. Her denial that she had ever owned such a dress confirmed that the milliner's purchases under the name Derbyshire were for another woman, validating the double-life hypothesis." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :strakerMistress ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :millinersAccount ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsStraker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Overcoat Was Deliberately Placed" ;
    ex:description "At the crime scene hollow, Holmes inquires about wind conditions on the night of the crime and draws an inference about Straker's overcoat found on a furze-bush." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Straker's overcoat was deliberately placed on the furze-bush, not blown there, since there was no wind that night." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes confirmed with Inspector Gregory that there was no wind on the night of the crime, only heavy rain. Since the overcoat could not have been blown against the bush, it must have been deliberately laid there — indicating Straker removed it intentionally before undertaking his task." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :strakerOvercoat ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :strakerOvercoat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :inspectorGregory ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Expects and Finds a Wax Vesta at the Crime Scene" ;
    ex:description "While examining the trampled mud in the hollow, Holmes discovers a half-burned wax vesta buried in the mud, telling Gregory he was looking for it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A wax vesta would be present at the crime scene because Straker needed to strike a light in the hollow to perform the delicate operation on the horse's tendon." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes knew from his theory that Straker had led the horse to the hollow to perform a covert operation requiring visual precision. Straker would have needed to strike a light to see what he was doing, so a spent match was expected. Holmes found the buried vesta, confirming Straker had lit a flame in the hollow." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :waxVesta ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :waxVesta ;
    ex:confirmedBy :waxVesta ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Silver Blaze Went to Mapleton" ;
    ex:description "Walking across the moor with Watson, Holmes reasons through where the horse could have gone after the tragedy, using the animal's gregarious nature and process of elimination." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Silver Blaze must have gone to the Mapleton training stables, since a gregarious horse would seek the nearest stable and it was not at King's Pyland." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that a horse left to itself would instinctively return to its own stable or go to the nearest one, not run wild on the moor. Gypsies would have no motive to take such a recognizable horse. Silver Blaze was not at King's Pyland, therefore it must be at Mapleton. Holmes confirmed this by finding the horse's tracks in soft ground leading toward Mapleton, matched by the cast horseshoe." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mapleton ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :silverBlazeHorseshoe ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesBrownConfrontation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Silas Brown Found and Concealed Silver Blaze" ;
    ex:description "Following the horse's tracks to Mapleton, Holmes observes a man's square-toed boot prints joining the horse's trail and later confronts Silas Brown with a detailed reconstruction of his actions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Silas Brown discovered Silver Blaze wandering on the moor, recognized the valuable horse, and concealed it at Mapleton to ensure his own horse Desborough would win the Wessex Cup." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed square-toed boot prints appearing alongside the horse's tracks near Mapleton, with the double track first heading toward King's Pyland then turning back to Mapleton. The square toes exactly matched Brown's own boots. No subordinate would have dared such an act. Holmes reconstructed that Brown, being first down in the morning as was his custom, found the wandering horse, recognized it by its white forehead, and seized the opportunity to hide it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silasBrown ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :silverBlazeHorseshoe ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesBrownConfrontation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Straker Practiced Tendon-Nicking on Sheep" ;
    ex:description "As they leave King's Pyland, Holmes suddenly asks a stable lad about the sheep in the paddock and learns that three have recently gone lame, confirming his surmise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Straker practiced the delicate tendon-nicking operation on the paddock sheep before attempting it on Silver Blaze." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that an astute man like Straker would not attempt such a delicate subcutaneous tendon nick on a valuable racehorse without prior practice. The sheep in the paddock were the obvious practice subjects. When the stable lad confirmed that three sheep had recently gone lame, Holmes's surmise was validated." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Straker's Crime and Death" ;
    ex:description "In the retrospective explanation on the train back to London, Holmes presents his full reconstruction of Straker's scheme and accidental death." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Straker drugged the stable boy, led Silver Blaze to a hollow on the moor, and attempted to nick the horse's tendon with the cataract knife to lame it and profit from betting against it. The horse kicked Straker in the head, killing him, and the knife gashed Straker's own thigh as he fell." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined multiple evidential threads: the curried mutton drugging pointed to an insider; the silent dog confirmed Straker as the intruder; the cataract knife was a surgical tool for tendon-nicking, not a weapon; the milliner's bill revealed Straker's debts from a secret mistress, providing motive; the overcoat was removed deliberately; and the wax vesta showed Straker struck a light in the hollow. Straker led the horse to the hollow so it would not rouse the sleepers, but the horse sensed danger, kicked Straker fatally, and the knife cut Straker's thigh as he collapsed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cataractKnife, :waxVesta, :millinersAccount, :druggingOfNedHunter, :strakerOvercoat ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryOfStrakersBody ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Silver Blaze as Straker's Killer" ;
    ex:description "At the Winchester racecourse after Silver Blaze wins the Wessex Cup, Holmes reveals that the murderer of John Straker is present — and points to the horse itself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Silver Blaze killed John Straker by kicking him in the head, acting in self-defence when Straker attempted to lame it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes's complete reconstruction showed that no human murdered Straker. The horse, frightened by the sudden glare of the match and sensing that mischief was intended, lashed out with its steel shoe, striking Straker full on the forehead. The death was an act of animal self-defence, not human violence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :silverBlaze ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deduction_silverBlaze_holmes_13 ;
    ex:confirmedBy :murderOfJohnStraker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_silverBlaze_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Suggests Straker's Thigh Wound Was Self-Inflicted" ;
    ex:description "During the train journey to Dartmoor, Watson suggests that the incised wound on Straker's thigh may have been caused by his own knife during the convulsive struggles that follow a brain injury." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Straker's thigh wound was self-inflicted by his own knife during convulsions caused by the head injury, rather than being inflicted by an attacker." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson applied his medical knowledge to observe that convulsive struggles commonly follow severe brain injuries, and that the knife in Straker's own hand could have cut his thigh during such involuntary movements. Holmes endorsed this as more than possible — probable." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnStraker ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cataractKnife ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :silverBlazeDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Bust-Smasher Is Not a General Napoleon-Hater" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Lestrade's account of the three smashed busts, Holmes observes that all three came from the same mould and were sold by the same dealer, making a coincidence-based monomania theory untenable." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The criminal is not motivated by a general hatred of Napoleon but is targeting these specific busts from the same batch." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that all three destroyed busts were duplicates taken from the same mould and purchased from Morse Hudson. With hundreds of Napoleon statues in London, the probability of a random iconoclast beginning with three specimens from the same source was too remote to accept as coincidence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sixNapoleonBusts ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Method in the Criminal's Proceedings" ;
    ex:description "Holmes observes that the criminal behaved differently at each of Dr. Barnicot's two locations, adapting his method to the risk of detection at each site." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bust-smasher acts with rational method rather than irrational compulsion, adjusting his behaviour based on the risk of being heard." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "At Barnicot's hall, where a sound might arouse the family, the bust was taken outside before being broken. At the surgery, where there was less danger of an alarm, it was smashed where it stood. This adaptive behaviour indicates rational planning rather than blind monomania." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :burglaryBarnicotResidence, :breakInBarnicotSurgery ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Was Extremely Agile" ;
    ex:description "Examining the window at Horace Harker's house, Holmes concludes that the burglar who stole the bust possessed unusual physical capabilities." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The burglar had either very long legs or was an exceptionally active man, based on the difficulty of reaching the window-ledge above an area." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the carpet and window at Harker's house and observed that with an area beneath the window, reaching the window-ledge and opening the window required exceptional agility or long reach. He noted that getting back out was comparatively simple." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfBeppo ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Criminal Needed Light to Examine the Bust" ;
    ex:description "At Campden House Road, where the fragments of Harker's stolen bust were found, Holmes deduces why the criminal carried the bust past a closer empty house to one beneath a street lamp." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The criminal carried the bust to a location with a street lamp because he needed light to examine the fragments, indicating he was searching for something inside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the criminal passed another empty house farther up the street before reaching the one in whose garden the bust was destroyed. Since every additional yard increased the risk of being seen, there had to be a compelling reason. Holmes pointed to the street lamp overhead — the criminal could see what he was doing here but could not at the closer house." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Beppo as the Common Factor" ;
    ex:description "After visiting Morse Hudson's shop and showing the photograph found on the dead man, Holmes identifies the former employee Beppo as the link between the Kennington and Kensington bust incidents." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Beppo, formerly employed at Morse Hudson's shop and identified from the dead man's photograph, is the common factor connecting the bust-smashing incidents across London." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Morse Hudson recognised the photograph as Beppo, a former Italian piece-work man who could carve, gild, and frame. Beppo had left the shop two days before the bust was smashed on the counter. Since Beppo was connected to the Kennington busts through his employment and the Kensington bust through the same trail, Holmes identified him as the common factor worth a ten-mile drive to investigate further." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :beppoPhotograph ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfBeppo ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Traces the Busts to Gelder and Co. and Links Beppo's Arrest" ;
    ex:description "At the Gelder and Co. factory in Stepney, Holmes discovers that Beppo worked there, was arrested on the premises for stabbing a man, and that the six Napoleon busts were manufactured in the same period." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Beppo was arrested at the very factory where the six busts were made, and the timing of his arrest corresponds with the production of the batch." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Gelder and Co. manager confirmed that six casts were made — three sent to Morse Hudson and three to Harding Brothers. Holmes checked the ledger and found the busts were sold on June 3rd, then asked for Beppo's arrest date — he was last paid on May 20th. This established that Beppo was working at the factory during the precise period the busts were manufactured and was arrested there before they were dispatched." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sixNapoleonBusts ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Plants a False Trail via the Press" ;
    ex:description "Holmes deliberately tells Lestrade to inform Horace Harker that a dangerous homicidal lunatic with Napoleonic delusions was responsible, knowing this false theory would be published and lull the real criminal into continuing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes uses the press as a tool, planting a false lunatic theory to give the criminal a sense of impunity so he will attempt to retrieve the remaining busts." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes instructed Lestrade to tell Harker about the supposed Napoleonic lunatic, knowing the journalist would publish it. When the newspaper ran the story attributing the incidents to lunacy, Holmes was satisfied — the criminal would read it and believe the police were on the wrong track, making him more likely to attempt the remaining busts." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfBeppo ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Criminal Will Target the Chiswick Bust Next" ;
    ex:description "After tracing the six busts to their buyers, Holmes predicts that the criminal will go for the Chiswick bust belonging to Josiah Brown before the Reading bust, since it is closer to London." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The criminal will target Josiah Brown's bust at Chiswick next, as it is the nearer of the two remaining busts." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had traced all six busts: three sold via Morse Hudson (all accounted for) and three via Harding Brothers (one smashed at Harker's, leaving Brown in Chiswick and Sandeford in Reading). Holmes reasoned the criminal would go for the London address first, and predicted Chiswick as the next target, setting up the ambush at Laburnum Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionSubject :josiahBrown ;
    ex:confirmedBy :arrestOfBeppo ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Calculates the Odds Against the Pearl Being in Harker's Bust" ;
    ex:description "After the Harker bust is smashed and its fragments examined, Holmes calculates the probability that the hidden object was in that specific bust." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The chances were two to one against the pearl being in Harker's bust, since it was one of three remaining unsearched busts at that point." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Harker's bust was one in three busts from the Harding Brothers batch that had not yet been searched. Holmes calculated the odds as exactly two to one against the pearl being inside it. When the fragments yielded nothing, this confirmed the pearl remained in one of the final two busts." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blackPearlOfBorgias ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Pietro Venucci's Connection to the Pearl Theft" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes reveals he connected the murdered man Pietro Venucci to the original pearl theft through his sister Lucretia Venucci, the maid of the Princess of Colonna who was suspected in the disappearance of the Borgia Pearl." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murdered Pietro Venucci was the brother of Lucretia Venucci, the princess's maid suspected in the pearl's disappearance, confirming the connection between the murder and the pearl." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had been consulted on the original pearl case and knew suspicion fell on the Princess of Colonna's Italian maid, Lucretia Venucci, who had a brother in London. After researching old newspaper files, Holmes confirmed that the pearl disappeared exactly two days before Beppo's arrest at Gelder and Co. The murdered man's name — Venucci — linked the bust-smashing to the pearl theft." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pietroVenucci ;
    ex:deductionSubject :lucretiaVenucci ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blackPearlOfBorgias ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pietroVenucci ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Black Pearl Is Hidden Inside a Napoleon Bust" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reconstructs the full chain of events: Beppo had the stolen Borgia Pearl when pursued by police, hid it in the wet plaster of one of six Napoleon busts at Gelder and Co., served a year in prison, and then systematically tracked down each bust to find the pearl." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Borgia Pearl was concealed inside one of six Napoleon busts by Beppo during his arrest at Gelder and Co., and his systematic destruction of the busts is an attempt to recover it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected multiple threads: the pearl vanished two days before Beppo's arrest; Beppo was arrested at the very factory making the busts; the busts were still drying when Beppo was taken; and the criminal needed light to search each bust's fragments. The only explanation unifying all the evidence was that Beppo had hidden the pearl in the wet plaster of one of the six busts and was now breaking each to find it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blackPearlOfBorgias ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sixNapoleonBusts ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :disappearanceBlackPearl, :beppoOriginalArrest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Beppo Killed Pietro Venucci" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation, Holmes identifies Beppo as the killer of Pietro Venucci, reasoning that Venucci was pursuing Beppo over the pearl and was stabbed in the resulting confrontation at Harker's house." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Beppo stabbed Pietro Venucci during a scuffle at Harker's house; Venucci had been dogging Beppo as a confederate who held him responsible for the loss of the pearl." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Pietro Venucci carried Beppo's photograph as a means of tracking him. As Beppo's confederate in the pearl theft, Venucci held Beppo responsible for the pearl's loss. Venucci dogged Beppo to Harker's house, where a scuffle occurred and Beppo stabbed him. The blood-stained sheath knife found on Beppo at his arrest confirmed he was the killer." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pietroVenucci ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :beppoPhotograph, :beppoSheathKnife ;
    ex:confirmedBy :beppoSheathKnife ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_lestrade_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Initial Theory: A Napoleon-Hating Monomaniac" ;
    ex:description "When presenting the case to Holmes, Lestrade suggests the bust-smashing is the work of a madman with an irrational hatred of Napoleon." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A monomaniac with an irrational hatred of Napoleon is responsible for systematically destroying busts of the Emperor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade observed that someone was specifically targeting images of Napoleon, smashing a bust in Morse Hudson's shop and burglarising Dr. Barnicot's premises to destroy two more. He concluded this pattern indicated madness — a person living in modern London with such intense hatred of Napoleon that he would break any image he could find." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :bustSmashingMorseHudson, :burglaryBarnicotResidence, :breakInBarnicotSurgery ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_01 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_lestrade_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: The Busts Are a Local Coincidence" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes challenges the monomania theory by noting all three busts came from the same mould, Lestrade counters that Morse Hudson was the only local supplier, making the coincidence natural for a local fanatic." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The three busts were the only Napoleon busts available in the Kennington district, so a local fanatic would naturally begin with them." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade conceded Holmes's point about the coincidence but argued that since Morse Hudson was the only purveyor of such busts in that part of London, and these three were the only ones in his shop for years, a local Napoleon-hater would inevitably target them first." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:refutedBy :discoveryBlackPearl ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_lestrade_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Lestrade's Theory: Pietro Was Killed in a Mafia Vendetta" ;
    ex:description "After identifying the murdered man as Pietro Venucci, a known Mafia figure, Lestrade constructs a theory that the murder was a Mafia enforcement killing entirely separate from the bust-smashing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murder of Pietro Venucci was a Mafia execution: Pietro was tracking a fellow Italian who had broken the society's rules, followed him to Harker's house, and was killed in the resulting confrontation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Lestrade identified Venucci through his Catholic emblem and dark complexion via Inspector Hill's knowledge of the Italian quarter. Knowing Venucci was connected to the Mafia, Lestrade theorised the photograph found on Venucci was of the man he was pursuing — a fellow Mafia member who had broken the society's rules. Pietro dogged his target, saw him enter Harker's house, waited outside, and received his death-wound in the scuffle." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :lestrade ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pietroVenucci ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beppo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pietroCatholicEmblem, :beppoPhotograph ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_12 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_sixNapoleons_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Monomania as Idée Fixe" ;
    ex:description "When asked for his opinion, Watson offers a medical explanation for the bust-smashing, suggesting the perpetrator may suffer from an idée fixe — a trifling obsession accompanied by otherwise complete sanity." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The bust-smasher suffers from an idée fixe about Napoleon, possibly rooted in deep reading or a hereditary family injury from the Napoleonic wars, which drives him to destroy Napoleon's image." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson drew on contemporary French psychology, citing the concept of the idée fixe — a condition where a trifling obsession coexists with complete sanity in every other respect. He suggested a person who had read deeply about Napoleon or had a hereditary grievance from the wars might form such a fixation and be capable of any fantastic outrage under its influence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_sixNapoleons_holmes_01 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sixNapoleonsDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Smith Is an Ardent Bicyclist" ;
    ex:description "Upon Violet Smith's arrival at Baker Street, Holmes immediately observes physical evidence of her cycling habits before she has mentioned any connection to bicycling." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Smith is an ardent bicyclist, as evidenced by the wear on her shoes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the slight roughening of the side of the sole of Violet's shoe, caused by the friction of the edge of the bicycle pedal. This physical wear pattern indicated regular and vigorous cycling." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :violetsBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :violetSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Smith Is a Musician" ;
    ex:description "Examining Violet Smith's ungloved hand at Baker Street, Holmes initially considers typewriting but corrects himself and identifies her as a musician." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Smith is a musician, not a typewriter, despite the spatulate finger-ends common to both professions." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined Violet's hand and noted the spatulate finger-ends common to both musicians and typewriters. He nearly fell into the error of supposing typewriting, but observed a spirituality about her face which typewriting does not generate, leading him to conclude she was a musician." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:confirmedBy :violetSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Smith Lives in the Country" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his rapid initial assessment of Violet Smith, Holmes infers her rural residence from her appearance." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Smith lives in the country rather than in town." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed Violet's complexion and inferred from it that she lived in the country rather than in London. A country complexion would show the effects of outdoor air and sunlight distinct from an urban pallor." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:confirmedBy :violetSmith ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cyclist Escaped Toward Charlington Hall" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Violet's account of the cyclist's mysterious disappearance when she doubled back on the road, Holmes applies a process of elimination to determine his escape route." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The mysterious cyclist escaped from the road by taking a path toward Charlington Hall." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes established that only two or three minutes elapsed between Violet turning the corner and discovering the road was clear. The cyclist could not have retreated down the road in that time, there were no side roads, and he could not have crossed the open heath without being seen. By the process of exclusion, he must have made his way toward Charlington Hall, which was situated in its own grounds on the other side of the road." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charlingtonHall ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charlingtonHeath ;
    ex:confirmedBy :watsonReconnaissance ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Knows the Cyclist" ;
    ex:description "After Watson's reconnaissance report, Holmes criticizes Watson's positioning and argues that the cyclist's behaviour proves Violet knows him, even though she claims otherwise." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Smith knows the mysterious cyclist, despite her claim to the contrary, because he is desperately anxious to avoid her recognizing him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the cyclist bent over the handle-bar to conceal his features and was desperately anxious that Violet should not get close enough to see his face. If the cyclist were a complete stranger, there would be no need for such concealment. The very effort to avoid recognition indicated that Violet would know him if she saw him clearly." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carrutherssFalseBeard ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Anomalous Governess Arrangement" ;
    ex:description "During his initial analysis of Violet's case, Holmes identifies several suspicious features of her employment arrangement that suggest an ulterior motive behind the generous offer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The household that pays double the market price for a governess yet keeps no horse despite being six miles from the station has a suspicious arrangement suggesting hidden motives." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified multiple anomalies: the connection between Carruthers and Woodley despite their different types, their shared keenness to look up Ralph Smith's relations, and most pointedly the contradiction of a household paying a hundred pounds a year for a governess — double the market rate — while not keeping a horse or carriage despite being six miles from the nearest station. These incongruities suggested the governess position was a pretext rather than a genuine employment need." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :chilternGrange ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Williamson Is Not the Cyclist" ;
    ex:description "After Watson reports that the tenant of Charlington Hall is an elderly white-bearded man named Williamson, Holmes eliminates him as the mysterious cyclist." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Williamson, the elderly white-bearded tenant of Charlington Hall, cannot be the active cyclist who sprints away from Violet Smith." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson's inquiries established that Williamson was a white-bearded elderly man. Holmes noted that if Williamson is elderly, he cannot be the active cyclist who sprints away from the athletic young lady's pursuit. The physical demands of the cyclist's behaviour were incompatible with an elderly man's capabilities." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :williamsonExClergyman ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :watsonReconnaissance ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Williamson Has a Disreputable Clerical Past" ;
    ex:description "Through inquiries at the local public house and a clerical agency, Holmes determines that the tenant of Charlington Hall has a dark ecclesiastical history." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Williamson is or has been a clergyman whose career has been singularly dark, with his behaviour at the Hall being peculiarly unecclesiastical." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The pub landlord informed Holmes that there was rumour Williamson was a clergyman, but incidents during his residence struck Holmes as peculiarly unecclesiastical. Holmes then made inquiries at a clerical agency, which confirmed that a man of that name in orders had a career that had been singularly dark." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :williamsonExClergyman ;
