:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the South African Inheritance Scheme" ;
    ex:description "In the final confrontation at Charlington Hall, Holmes walks Carruthers and Williamson through the full conspiracy, deducing that Carruthers and Woodley came from South Africa knowing Ralph Smith would die and that his niece would inherit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Carruthers and Woodley came from South Africa to exploit Ralph Smith's impending death, having discovered that his niece Violet would inherit his fortune." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that two men came from South Africa on a planned scheme. They had known Ralph Smith and had reason to believe he would not live long. They found out that his niece would inherit his fortune and hunted up the girl to position one of them to marry her. The telegram announcing Ralph Smith's death confirmed the timing of their scheme." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackWoodley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ralphSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :ralphSmithDeathTelegram ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Violet Was Next of Kin and Ralph Smith Died Intestate" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his reconstruction, Holmes deduces that Violet was Ralph Smith's nearest relative and that the old man would make no will." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Violet Smith was next of kin to Ralph Smith, who would die intestate because he could neither read nor write." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes stated that Violet was next of kin and that the conspirators were aware the old fellow would make no will. Carruthers confirmed this by revealing that Ralph Smith could not read or write, making a will impossible and ensuring the inheritance would pass to Violet as the nearest living relative." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ralphSmith ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces One Conspirator Was to Marry Violet for the Plunder" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies the core mechanism of the scheme: one of the two men was designated to marry Violet while the other would receive a share of the fortune." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The plan was for one of the conspirators to marry Violet Smith and share the inheritance with the other, with Woodley chosen as the husband." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that the idea was for one man to marry Violet and the other to have a share of the plunder, and that for some reason Woodley was chosen as the husband. Carruthers revealed they had played cards for Violet on the voyage from South Africa and Woodley had won." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackWoodley ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cardGameOnVoyage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Carruthers Fell in Love With Violet" ;
    ex:description "Holmes identifies the complication that disrupted the original scheme: Carruthers genuinely fell in love with Violet and could no longer tolerate Woodley's claim to her." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Carruthers fell in love with Violet Smith during her employment, which upset the original arrangement with Woodley." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the arrangement was upset by the fact that Carruthers had himself fallen in love with the lady and could no longer bear the idea of the ruffian Woodley owning her. This explained Carruthers's protective behaviour, his proposal of marriage, and his willingness to defy his former partner." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionSubject :violetSmith ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carruthersProposalToViolet ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Quarrel Split Carruthers and Woodley" ;
    ex:description "Holmes traces the falling-out between the two conspirators to a quarrel that led Woodley to begin making independent plans with Williamson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A quarrel between Carruthers and Woodley caused Woodley to leave in a rage and begin making independent plans for the forced marriage." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes deduced that there was a quarrel between the two men, that Woodley left in a rage, and began to make his own plans independently of Carruthers. This explained why Woodley allied with Williamson at Charlington Hall and ultimately orchestrated the forced marriage without Carruthers's cooperation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackWoodley ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carruthersWoodleyQuarrel ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Forced Marriage Is Legally Invalid" ;
    ex:description "After the rescue of Violet Smith from the forced wedding ceremony, Holmes declares the marriage invalid on two legal grounds." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The forced marriage of Violet Smith to Jack Woodley is legally invalid because Williamson was defrocked and because a forced marriage is no marriage at all." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes identified two independent grounds for invalidity. First, Williamson had been ordained but also unfrocked, which called into question his right to solemnize a marriage regardless of his claim that ordination is permanent. Second, even if the license were valid, a forced marriage performed under coercion constitutes a serious felony rather than a binding ceremony." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :forcedMarriageOfVioletSmith ;
    ex:deductionSubject :williamsonExClergyman ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :forcedMarriageLicense, :williamsonsSurplice ;
    ex:confirmedBy :trialWilliamsonWoodley ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_solitaryCyclist_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Realizes the Necktie Adjustment Revealed the Cyclist's Disguise" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective self-criticism, Holmes acknowledges that Watson's report of the cyclist apparently adjusting his necktie in the shrubbery should have immediately revealed the man's identity as someone wearing a false beard." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cyclist's apparent adjustment of his necktie in the shrubbery was actually the handling of a false beard disguise, which should have identified him as someone Violet would recognize." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson had reported seeing the cyclist standing among the trees with his hands raised, apparently settling his necktie. Holmes belatedly realized this observation alone should have told him everything — a man adjusting something at his chin in private after following someone was handling a disguise, specifically a false beard, rather than adjusting a necktie. This confirmed the cyclist was someone who needed to conceal his identity from Violet." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carrutherssFalseBeard, :watsonReconnaissance ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bobCarruthers ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :solitaryCyclistDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Helen Stoner Arrived by Train" ;
    ex:description "Upon meeting the distressed Helen Stoner at Baker Street early in the morning, Holmes immediately observes that she has travelled to London by train." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Helen Stoner came in by train this morning." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed the second half of a return ticket in the palm of Helen Stoner's left glove, indicating she had recently travelled by rail." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :helenStoner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :helenStoner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Helen Stoner Drove a Dog-Cart on Heavy Roads" ;
    ex:description "Immediately following his observation about the train ticket, Holmes deduces that Helen Stoner had a long drive in a dog-cart along muddy roads before reaching the station." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Helen Stoner had a good drive in a dog-cart along heavy roads before reaching the station." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the left arm of Helen's jacket was spattered with mud in no fewer than seven places, the marks being perfectly fresh. He noted that only a dog-cart throws up mud in that particular pattern, and only when the passenger sits on the left-hand side of the driver." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :helenStoner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :helenStoner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Helen Stoner Is Being Physically Abused" ;
    ex:description "After Helen Stoner claims to have told Holmes everything, he pushes back the lace frill on her wrist to reveal bruises, deducing that she has been concealing her stepfather's violence." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Helen Stoner has been cruelly used by her stepfather, who has gripped her wrist with enough force to leave finger marks." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed five livid spots on Helen Stoner's white wrist — the marks of four fingers and a thumb — which she had been concealing beneath a lace frill. He confronted her with the evidence, stating she had not told him everything and was screening her stepfather." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :helenStoner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:confirmedBy :helenStoner ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Roylott's Financial Motive to Prevent Marriages" ;
    ex:description "After visiting Doctors' Commons to examine the will of the deceased Mrs. Stoner, Holmes calculates that Roylott has a powerful financial motive to prevent either stepdaughter from marrying." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Dr. Roylott has the very strongest motives for standing in the way of his stepdaughters' marriages, as each marriage would significantly reduce his income." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the will and worked out the current value of the investments. The total income had fallen from approximately £1100 to £750 through agricultural price declines. Each daughter's marriage would claim £250, meaning both marriages would reduce Roylott to a mere pittance, and even one would cripple him financially." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :grimesByRoylott ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stonerWill ;
    ex:confirmedBy :roylottDeathEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Ventilator Connects the Bedrooms" ;
    ex:description "Before visiting Stoke Moran, Holmes deduces from Helen's testimony that there must be a communication between Julia's bedroom and Roylott's room, specifically predicting they would find a ventilator." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There must be a ventilator or similar opening connecting Julia Stoner's bedroom to Dr. Roylott's room." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Helen had mentioned that Julia could smell Dr. Roylott's cigar smoke from her own room. This indicated an air passage between the two chambers. Holmes reasoned it could only be a small one, or it would have been noticed at the coroner's inquiry, and deduced a ventilator." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roylottVentilator ;
    ex:confirmedBy :roylottVentilator ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes's Initial Theory Involving the Gypsies" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Helen Stoner's account, Holmes forms an initial theory connecting the gypsies on the estate to Julia's death, linking the dying word 'band' to a band of people and the metallic clang to the shutters." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The nocturnal whistles, the presence of gypsies on intimate terms with Roylott, the dying allusion to a 'band,' and the metallic clang suggest the mystery may be solved along the lines of the gypsy band's involvement." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined the whistles at night, the fact that gypsies camped on Roylott's grounds and were on intimate terms with him, the financial motive, Julia's dying reference to a 'band,' and the metallic clang that might have been a shutter bar falling back into place. He acknowledged objections to the theory but thought it worth investigating." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :juliaDeathEvent ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_speckledBand_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Ventilator, Bell-Rope, and Clamped Bed Form a Delivery Mechanism" ;
    ex:description "During his examination of the bedroom at Stoke Moran, Holmes discovers that the ventilator opens into Roylott's room rather than outside, the bell-rope is a dummy attached to a hook beside the ventilator, and the bed is clamped to the floor — all installed at the same time." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The danger to the occupant of the room cannot come through window or door; the dummy bell-rope, the ventilator into Roylott's room, and the clamped bed form an integrated mechanism for delivering something from Roylott's room to the bed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes found the shutters impenetrable and the doors locked, eliminating external entry. He discovered the bell-rope was a dummy not attached to any wire, fastened to a hook beside the ventilator opening. The ventilator connected to Roylott's room rather than the outside air. The bed was clamped to the floor so it could not be moved away from the ventilator and rope. All three modifications were installed at the same time, creating a fixed pathway from Roylott's room to the bed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dummyBellRope ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roylottVentilator ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dummyBellRope, :roylottVentilator ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nightVigilStokeMoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces a Venomous Creature Is Kept in the Safe" ;
    ex:description "In Roylott's room, Holmes examines the safe, the saucer of milk, the dog whip tied into a loop, and the wooden chair, and deduces that Roylott keeps a dangerous creature in the safe." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The saucer of milk, the dog whip fashioned into a loop of whipcord, and the iron safe indicate that Roylott keeps a venomous creature — too small for a cheetah — housed in the safe and controlled with the whip." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the saucer of milk could not be for a cat (there was none) and was too small for the cheetah. The dog lash was curled and tied into a loop of whipcord — not a normal configuration for a leash. He examined the wooden chair seat closely and found evidence of someone standing on it, which would be necessary to reach the ventilator. Combined with the safe and the knowledge that Roylott had Indian animals sent to him, Holmes concluded a dangerous creature was being kept and deployed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :swampAdder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :saucerOfMilk, :dogWhip, :roylottIronSafe ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nightVigilStokeMoran ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Murder Weapon as a Swamp Adder" ;
    ex:description "Holmes synthesizes his findings into a complete reconstruction of the murder method: Roylott trained a venomous Indian swamp adder to crawl through the ventilator and down the dummy bell-rope onto the clamped bed, using a whistle to recall it and milk to reward it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murder weapon is a swamp adder — the deadliest snake in India — which Roylott trained to pass through the ventilator, descend the bell-rope to the bed, and return when summoned by whistle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes combined the ventilator-rope-bed mechanism with Roylott's supply of Indian creatures, the saucer of milk for training the snake, and the whistle heard at night to recall the serpent before daylight. The snake's venom would be undetectable by any chemical test — a method suited to a clever man with Eastern medical training. The snake might not bite on any given night, but repeated attempts would eventually prove fatal, explaining the weeks of whistling Julia reported before her death." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :swampAdder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :juliaDeathEvent ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dummyBellRope, :roylottVentilator, :saucerOfMilk, :dogWhip, :roylottIronSafe ;
    ex:confirmedBy :roylottDeathEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Metallic Clang as the Safe Closing" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes identifies the metallic clang heard by Helen on the night of Julia's death as the sound of Roylott hastily closing the iron safe upon the snake." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The metallic clang heard by Helen Stoner on the night of Julia's death was caused by Roylott hastily closing the door of his iron safe upon the snake after recalling it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that after sending the snake through the ventilator and hearing Julia's scream, Roylott would have urgently whistled the snake back and shut it in the safe. The metallic clang that Helen heard from the corridor was obviously the sound of the heavy safe door being closed hastily on the returning serpent." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :roylottIronSafe ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :roylottIronSafe ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_speckledBand_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Inference That Julia Stoner Died Alone in a Locked Room" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Helen Stoner's account, Watson reasons aloud that if the room was truly sealed — solid walls, barred windows, locked door, barred chimney — then Julia must have been entirely alone when she died." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Julia Stoner must have been undoubtedly alone when she met her end, given that the flooring and walls are sound and the door, window, and chimney are impassable." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson accepted Helen's testimony that the door was locked from the inside, the windows blocked by shuttered iron bars, the walls solid, the flooring examined, and the chimney barred with staples. He concluded that no person could have entered or exited the room, meaning Julia was alone." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :juliaStoner ;
    ex:deductionSubject :juliaDeathEvent ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :speckledBandDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson Has Been Unwell Recently" ;
    ex:description "Visiting Watson at his Paddington practice, Holmes immediately perceives that Watson has recently suffered a summer cold, despite Watson believing he has fully recovered." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson has recently been confined to the house by illness." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Watson's new patent leather slippers had scorched soles, yet the shopman's price wafer was still attached near the instep. Damp would have removed the wafer, so the slippers had not been wet — ruling out drying by the fire after rain. Watson must therefore have been sitting with his feet outstretched to the fire for warmth, something a healthy man would not do in June, indicating recent illness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Watson's Practice Is More Successful Than His Neighbour's" ;
    ex:description "As they leave Watson's house, Holmes glances at the two neighbouring brass plates and declares that Watson got the better of the two practices." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson's medical practice receives more patients than his neighbour's identical practice." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes compared the stone steps leading to Watson's door with those of the neighbouring doctor. Watson's steps were worn three inches deeper, indicating significantly more foot traffic and therefore a more successful practice, despite both practices being established when the houses were built." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnWatson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Written Declaration Was to Obtain a Handwriting Specimen" ;
    ex:description "During the retrospective explanation in the train to Birmingham, Holmes reveals his reasoning about why Pinner required Pycroft to write out a formal declaration of employment — an unusual requirement with no legitimate business purpose." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The written declaration was a pretext to obtain a specimen of Pycroft's handwriting for forgery purposes." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that employment arrangements of this kind are usually verbal, and there was no earthly business reason to require a written declaration. The only adequate explanation was that someone needed to learn to imitate Pycroft's handwriting, and required a specimen to practise from." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hallPycroft ;
    ex:deductionSubject :pycroftWrittenDeclaration ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pycroftWrittenDeclaration ;
    ex:confirmedBy :robberyAtMawsons ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Someone Is Impersonating Pycroft at Mawson's" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his chain of reasoning, Holmes explains that Pinner's insistence that Pycroft not resign from Mawson's was designed to ensure the firm expected a 'Hall Pycroft' to arrive on Monday morning — a man no one at Mawson's had ever seen." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "An impostor using Pycroft's forged handwriting has taken his place at Mawson & Williams." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Pinner specifically asked Pycroft not to write a resignation letter, ensuring that Mawson's still expected a Mr. Hall Pycroft on Monday. Combined with the handwriting specimen, this meant the impostor could arrive at Mawson's, write in Pycroft's hand, and take up the position without suspicion since nobody at the firm had ever met the real Pycroft." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hallPycroft ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pycroftWrittenDeclaration ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Two Pinners Are the Same Man" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains that the supposed brothers Arthur and Harry Pinner are in fact one person, confirming the suspicion Pycroft himself had raised based on the matching gold tooth." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Arthur Pinner and Harry Pinner are the same individual, not brothers." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "There were evidently only two conspirators in the scheme. One was impersonating Pycroft at Mawson's, so the other had to play both roles — the London engager and the Birmingham employer. He changed his appearance with a razor and lighter hair, but the identical gold tooth filling gave him away. The resemblance was too exact for mere family likeness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Scheme's Purpose Is Robbery From Within Mawson's" ;
    ex:description "Holmes synthesises all the elements of the plot — the handsome salary, the busywork in Birmingham, the isolation from London — and concludes that the purpose was to keep Pycroft occupied while his double robbed Mawson & Williams from the inside." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The entire scheme was designed to place an impostor inside Mawson & Williams to commit a robbery, while keeping the real Pycroft isolated in Birmingham." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The handsome advance and inflated salary kept Pycroft committed. The pointless directory-copying task in Birmingham kept him busy and away from London. The instruction not to resign ensured his double's position at Mawson's was secure. All elements converged to a single purpose: preventing Pycroft from discovering his double and interfering with a robbery being planned from within the firm." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :hallPycroft ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mawsonAndWilliams ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :hundredPoundNote, :pycroftWrittenDeclaration, :parisDirectory ;
    ex:confirmedBy :robberyAtMawsons ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Refutes Watson's Theory That Pinner Suspects Them of Being Detectives" ;
    ex:description "When Watson suggests that Pinner's visible terror at the Birmingham office is because he suspects them of being detectives, Holmes dismisses this by noting a critical detail about the timing of Pinner's distress." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Pinner's terror was not caused by the arrival of Holmes and Watson, because he was already pale before they entered the room." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Pinner did not turn pale upon seeing them — he was already pale when they entered the room. His horror and perspiration predated their visit, ruling out their presence as the cause of his distress. Something else had already terrified him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Newspaper Explains Pinner's Behaviour and Suicide Attempt" ;
    ex:description "After cutting Pinner down from his attempted hanging, Holmes suddenly remembers the evening newspaper Pinner had purchased in the street and realises it must contain the explanation for his terror and suicide attempt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The evening newspaper Pinner bought contains news that explains both his terror upon their arrival and his subsequent attempt to hang himself." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recalled that Pinner had bought an evening newspaper in the street just before entering the office, and was reading it when they arrived — already in a state of horror. Holmes berated himself for being so focused on the visit that the newspaper's significance never entered his head. Flattening it out, he found the headline reporting the robbery attempt at Mawson & Williams and the arrest of Pinner's brother." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eveningStandardClerk ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Pinner's Suicide Was Motivated by Fraternal Loyalty" ;
    ex:description "After the newspaper account reveals the full story, Holmes reflects on why the surviving Beddington brother attempted suicide rather than simply fleeing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Pinner attempted suicide because he learned from the newspaper that his brother had been captured and would likely face execution, and fraternal affection drove him to despair." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that even a villain and murderer can inspire enough affection that his brother turns to suicide when he learns that his brother's neck is forfeited. The newspaper reported the arrest of the brother at Mawson's for robbery and murder of the watchman — a capital crime — and this news was the direct cause of the surviving brother's attempt to hang himself." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:deductionSubject :beddingtonBrother2 ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :eveningStandardClerk, :pinnerSuicideAttempt ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_hallpycroft_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Pycroft Deduces Arthur and Harry Pinner Are the Same Man" ;
    ex:description "While being dismissed from his Friday meeting with 'Harry Pinner' in Birmingham, Pycroft notices an identical gold tooth filling to the one he had observed in 'Arthur Pinner' in London, leading him to conclude the two brothers are actually one person." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The men calling themselves Arthur Pinner and Harry Pinner are the same individual, distinguished only by superficial changes in grooming." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Harry Pinner laughed, Pycroft noticed that his second tooth on the left-hand side had been stuffed with gold in an identical fashion to Arthur Pinner's tooth, which he had observed during their London meeting. Combined with the same voice and figure — with only a shaved beard and lighter hair as differences — Pycroft concluded that one man was playing both roles, as two brothers might resemble each other but would not have the same tooth filled the same way." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :hallPycroft ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_05 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_stockBrokersClerk_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Pinner Suspects Them of Being Detectives" ;
    ex:description "When the group encounters Pinner in a state of visible terror at the Birmingham office, Watson suggests an explanation for his extreme distress." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Pinner is terrified because he suspects that Holmes and Watson are detectives who have come to investigate him." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson observed Pinner's extreme distress — blanched face, perspiration, wild staring eyes — and interpreted this as the reaction of a guilty man who has recognised that investigators have arrived at his door." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :arthurPinnerBeddington ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_stockBrokersClerk_holmes_07 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :stockBrokersClerkDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Ferguson Is Writing About Himself" ;
    ex:description "After reading Robert Ferguson's letter describing a 'friend' troubled by his wife's apparent vampirism, Holmes immediately recognizes that Ferguson is the affected party, not merely acting on behalf of another." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Ferguson is writing about his own situation, not that of a friend." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The letter's intimate detail, emotional intensity, and the transparent fiction of acting for 'a friend' revealed that Ferguson was describing his own domestic crisis. Holmes corrected Watson's assumption by pointedly replying 'Your case!' when sending the telegram." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :robertFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fergusonLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :robertFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Assaults on Jack and Baby Have Different Causes" ;
    ex:description "During his interview with Ferguson at Baker Street, Holmes carefully questions whether the assaults on the baby and on Jack occurred at the same time, learning that in the second instance only Jack was attacked while the baby was unharmed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The wife's assaults on Jack and the apparent attacks on the baby have separate motivations and are not part of a single pattern of madness." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that in the first episode both children were targeted simultaneously, but in the second episode only Jack suffered while Mrs. Mason reported no complaint about the baby. This asymmetry indicated the two types of assault had different underlying causes rather than being expressions of a single frenzy." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackFerguson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :babyFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :assaultsOnJack, :babyPoisoningIncidents ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesRevelation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mrs. Ferguson Was Sucking Poison From the Wound" ;
    ex:description "Holmes forms his central deduction before even leaving Baker Street: the apparent vampirism was actually a mother sucking poison from her baby's wound to save its life, not drinking its blood." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Ferguson was not drinking the baby's blood but was sucking poison from a wound on its neck to save the child's life." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes rejected vampirism as absurd in English criminal practice. A bleeding wound may be sucked for purposes other than drawing blood — historically, wounds were sucked to extract poison. Given a South American household, Holmes's instinct pointed to exotic poisons even before seeing physical evidence at Cheeseman's." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :babyFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fergusonLetter, :secondBabyAttack ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Connects South American Weapons to Poison Source" ;
    ex:description "Upon arriving at Cheeseman's, Holmes examines the collection of South American utensils and weapons on the wall with intense curiosity, returning with his eyes full of thought." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The South American weapons displayed in the house are the source of the poison used on the baby." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had already theorized poison from a South American household. When he saw the collection of South American weapons on the wall, including a small bird-bow with an empty quiver, he recognized these as the instruments used to deliver curare or similar poison. The empty quiver confirmed an arrow had been removed and used." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :southAmericanWeaponsCollection ;
    ex:deductionSubject :birdBowAndQuiver ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :southAmericanWeapons, :birdBow, :curareArrows ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesRevelation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Dog Was Poisoned as a Test" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes observes the spaniel Carlo dragging its hind legs with a sort of paralysis, he calls the dog's condition 'very remarkable, very suggestive' and 'a confirmation of what I had already thought.'" ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The dog Carlo was poisoned with the same substance used on the baby, as a preliminary test of the poison's potency." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The dog suffered sudden-onset paralysis approximately four months earlier, consistent with the effects of curare or a similar South American nerve poison. Someone wishing to use such a poison on the baby would logically test it first to confirm it had not lost its power. The dog's symptoms fit this reconstruction perfectly." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :carlo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :carloPoisoning, :poisoningOfCarlo ;
    ex:confirmedBy :holmesRevelation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Observes Jack's Hatred in the Window Reflection" ;
    ex:description "While Ferguson fondled the baby, Holmes fixed his gaze on the window where a half-closed shutter formed a background, observing Jack Ferguson's face clearly reflected in the glass." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jack Ferguson's face, reflected in the window glass, revealed intense jealousy and cruel hatred directed at the baby." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes watched Jack's unguarded expression in the window reflection while the boy observed his father showing affection to the baby. The glass with the shutter behind it acted as a mirror, revealing jealousy and cruel hatred that Jack concealed when facing others directly. This confirmed Jack as the true threat to the infant." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackFerguson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Jack Poisoned the Baby With Curare Arrows" ;
    ex:description "In his final explanation to Ferguson, Holmes reconstructs the full crime: Jack had been pricking the baby with arrows dipped in curare or a similar poison taken from the South American weapons collection." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jack Ferguson pricked the baby with poison-tipped arrows from the South American weapons collection on the wall, and his mother discovered this and sucked out the venom to save the child." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The empty quiver beside the small bird-bow confirmed an arrow had been taken. The baby's small neck wound was consistent with a pin-prick from a poisoned arrow rather than a bite. Mrs. Ferguson, being South American, would have recognized the danger of curare poisoning and known that sucking the wound was the emergency treatment, explaining her blood-stained lips." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackFerguson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :babyFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :curareArrows, :birdBowAndQuiver, :secondBabyAttack ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Jack's Motive Is Jealousy and Distorted Love" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains to the devastated Ferguson that Jack's actions stem from a pathological jealousy rooted in his devotion to his father and possibly to his dead mother's memory." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Jack's poisoning of the baby was motivated by jealous, distorted love for his father and resentment that the healthy new child displaced him in his father's affections." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Jack was deeply devoted to his father and to his dead mother's memory. The arrival of a new, healthy, beautiful baby from the second marriage threatened Jack's position. His physical disability made the contrast with the thriving infant more painful. Holmes identified this as a maniacal exaggerated love that consumed Jack's soul with hatred for the child whose health and beauty contrasted with his own weakness." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackFerguson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mrs. Ferguson Attacked Jack to Protect the Baby" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains that Mrs. Ferguson's violent assaults on her stepson Jack were not unprovoked cruelty but a mother's desperate retaliation against the boy she knew was poisoning her infant." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Ferguson struck Jack because she knew he was poisoning the baby and was driven to violence by maternal fury and desperation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Ferguson's attacks on Jack coincided with the poisoning incidents, and she openly declared she hated him. A loving mother who discovered her stepson was attempting to murder her baby would reach the limit of her patience. Her refusal to explain her actions to her husband stemmed from knowing how deeply Ferguson loved Jack and fearing the revelation would break his heart." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jackFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :assaultsOnJack, :firstAssaultOnJack, :secondAssaultOnJack ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mrs. Mason Was Informed of the Truth" ;
    ex:description "Holmes asks how Mrs. Ferguson dared leave the baby unprotected during her last two days of self-imposed confinement, and when told she had informed Mrs. Mason, Holmes confirms he had already imagined this was the case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Ferguson told the nurse Mrs. Mason the truth about Jack's poisoning so the baby would be properly guarded during her confinement." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Ferguson had locked herself in her room for two days yet the baby remained safe. A mother who knew the true danger would not leave her child unprotected unless she had arranged for someone trustworthy to guard it. Mrs. Mason, the devoted nurse, was the logical confidante." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsMason ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :sussexVampireDoc .

:deduction_sussexVampire_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Diagnoses Mrs. Ferguson's Condition as Nervous Distress" ;
    ex:description "Watson examines Mrs. Ferguson in her locked room and determines that despite her high pulse and temperature, her condition is psychological rather than the result of a physical illness." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Ferguson's fever and distress are caused by mental and nervous excitement rather than any actual physical seizure or disease." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson took Mrs. Ferguson's pulse and temperature, finding both elevated. However, his medical assessment was that the clinical presentation was consistent with mental and nervous excitement — the distress of a woman concealing a terrible secret and separated from her husband and child — rather than an organic illness or infection." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsFerguson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :watsonExaminesMrsFerguson ;
