:deduction_thorBridge_sergeantcoventry_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Coventry's Theory: Neil Gibson May Be the Murderer" ;
    ex:description "While walking to the crime scene with Holmes and Watson, Sergeant Coventry quietly confides his private suspicion that Neil Gibson himself may have murdered his wife." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Neil Gibson himself may have murdered his wife, given his violent character, his possible motive to be rid of her, and the fact that the murder weapon was his own pistol." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Coventry noted that Gibson is a man of violent temperament who may have wished his wife removed so he could pursue Miss Dunbar. The murder weapon was Gibson's own pistol, and Americans are readier with firearms. These factors pointed to Gibson as a suspect rather than Miss Dunbar." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sergeantCoventry ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neilGibson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :thorBridgeMurderRevolver ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_thorBridge_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cook's Poor Eggs Are Due to Reading the Family Herald" ;
    ex:description "Over breakfast at 221B Baker Street, Holmes remarks on the poor quality of the hard-boiled eggs prepared by their new cook, linking it to a periodical he observed on the hall table." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The new cook's poorly prepared eggs are the result of her reading the Family Herald, which distracted her from timing the cooking properly." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed a copy of the Family Herald on the hall table the previous day and connected it to the cook's inattention. He reasoned that cooking an egg demands conscious attention to the passage of time, which is incompatible with absorption in a love romance periodical." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bakerStreetCookThorBridge ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :familyHerald ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Gibson Has Deep Feelings for Miss Dunbar" ;
    ex:description "After Gibson denies any personal relationship with Miss Dunbar, Holmes dismisses him from 221B, later explaining to Watson the reasoning behind his bluff." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Neil Gibson harbors deep personal feelings for Miss Dunbar that go beyond an employer-employee relationship." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes contrasted the passionate, unconventional, unbusinesslike tone of Gibson's letter with his self-contained manner and appearance in person. This disparity made it clear that some deep emotion centered upon the accused woman rather than upon the victim. Holmes then bluffed Gibson by feigning absolute certainty to force a confession of the truth." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neilGibson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :graceDunbar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :gibsonLetterToHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :neilGibson ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Gibson Will Return After Being Dismissed" ;
    ex:description "After dismissing Gibson from 221B for lying, Holmes calmly tells Watson that Gibson is certain to come back." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gibson will inevitably return because he cannot leave the matter unresolved when Miss Dunbar's fate is at stake." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes understood that Gibson's deep attachment to Miss Dunbar and desperation to save her would override his wounded pride. A man who had written such an impassioned letter could not simply walk away from his only hope of clearing her name." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :neilGibson ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :gibsonLetterToHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gibsonConsultation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Considers the Accidental Death Theory" ;
    ex:description "During Gibson's second visit to 221B, Holmes acknowledges Gibson's theory that Mrs. Gibson may have confronted Miss Dunbar with a gun, leading to an accidental shooting." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Gibson may have attempted to murder or threaten Miss Dunbar with a gun, and in a resulting struggle the gun went off and killed Mrs. Gibson instead." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Given Mrs. Gibson's intense jealousy and tropical temperament, she might have planned to murder Miss Dunbar or to threaten her with a gun to frighten her into leaving. A scuffle could have ensued in which the gun discharged and killed Mrs. Gibson. Holmes acknowledged this as the only obvious alternative to deliberate murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mariaGibson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :graceDunbar ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_thorBridge_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Was Clutched Deliberately Before Death" ;
    ex:description "At Thor Bridge, Holmes questions Sergeant Coventry about the note found in Mrs. Gibson's hand and draws an important inference from how tightly it was held." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The note was clutched so tightly in Mrs. Gibson's left hand that it must have been held deliberately before death, excluding the possibility that someone placed it there afterward." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Coventry reported that the fingers could hardly be opened to retrieve the note. Holmes reasoned that this degree of grip excluded the idea that anyone could have placed the note in the dead woman's hand after death to furnish a false clue — the clutching was a pre-mortem action." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dunbarNote ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dunbarNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sergeantCoventry ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Mrs. Gibson's Retention of the Note Was Purposeful" ;
    ex:description "At the bridge, Holmes questions why Mrs. Gibson was still clutching the appointment note in her hand at the time of death when she would have received it hours earlier." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Gibson's continued retention of the note long after receiving it was deliberate and purposeful rather than accidental." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the note was received at least one or two hours before the meeting. Mrs. Gibson had no need to refer to it during the interview, yet she carried it carefully and clutched it at the moment of death. This deliberate retention suggested a purpose beyond merely keeping the appointment — she wanted the note to be found on her body." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mariaGibson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dunbarNote ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dunbarNote ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_thorBridge_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Chip in the Bridge Stonework" ;
    ex:description "Holmes examines a fresh chip on the stone parapet of Thor Bridge, fifteen feet from where the body lay, using his lens and testing the stone's hardness with his cane." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The chip on the bridge parapet was caused by a violent blow from below rather than from above, as it appears on the lower edge of the stonework." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the chip closely and noted it was on the lower edge of the parapet, indicating the impact came from below, not above. He tested the stone with his cane and could not reproduce a mark, confirming that considerable violence was required. The location — fifteen feet from the body on the opposite parapet — was curious and warranted further investigation." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :thorBridge ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :thorBridge ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorBridgeExperiment ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Wardrobe Pistol Exonerates Dunbar" ;
    ex:description "On the train from Thor Place to Winchester, Holmes explains to Watson why the pistol found in Miss Dunbar's wardrobe is actually evidence of her innocence rather than her guilt." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The finding of the pistol in Miss Dunbar's wardrobe exonerates rather than incriminates her, because a premeditated killer would never have kept the weapon in such an obvious location." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes argued that a woman who had coolly premeditated a murder would also coolly premeditate the means of covering it. She could easily have flung the weapon into the adjacent reed-beds where it would never be found. Instead, carrying it home and placing it in her own wardrobe — the first place to be searched — was so inconsistent with premeditated crime that it pointed to her innocence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :graceDunbar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :plantedRevolver ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorBridgeExperiment ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Revolver Was Planted to Frame Dunbar" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his analysis on the train, Holmes reasons that if Miss Dunbar is innocent, the revolver must have been placed in her wardrobe by the true perpetrator." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "If Miss Dunbar is speaking truth when she disclaims knowledge of the revolver, then it was placed in her wardrobe by someone who wished to incriminate her — and that person is the actual criminal." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reversed the perspective: once one accepts Dunbar's innocence, the damning evidence becomes a clue to the truth. The revolver was placed in her wardrobe by someone who wished to incriminate her. That person must be the actual perpetrator of the crime, opening a fruitful line of inquiry into who had access to her room and motive to frame her." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :graceDunbar ;
    ex:deductionSubject :plantedRevolver ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :plantedRevolver ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_thorBridge_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs Mrs. Gibson's Suicide-Framing Scheme" ;
    ex:description "In the cell at Winchester, Holmes experiences a sudden flash of insight that connects the chip in the stonework, the missing weapon, and the weight of Watson's revolver into a complete reconstruction of the crime. He confirms the theory through a dramatic experiment at Thor Bridge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Gibson committed suicide by shooting herself at the bridge, using a revolver tied by string to a heavy stone hung over the parapet, so that when she released the weapon it was whisked into the mere, making her death appear to be murder. She had previously planted a matching revolver in Miss Dunbar's wardrobe and engineered the incriminating note to frame the governess." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected multiple observations: the chip on the lower edge of the parapet (caused by a heavy object striking it from below), the absence of any weapon near the body, the pair of matching revolvers, and the weight of a revolver sufficient to be pulled by a stone on a string. Mrs. Gibson tied one revolver to a stone via string, hung the stone over the parapet, shot herself, and upon releasing her grip the stone's weight whisked the revolver over the bridge into the water, chipping the stonework in the process. She had extracted the appointment note from Dunbar through a deceptive request and held it deliberately so it would be found on her body." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mariaGibson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :graceDunbar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :thorBridge, :plantedRevolver, :dunbarNote, :watsonsRevolver ;
    ex:confirmedBy :thorBridgeExperiment ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_thorBridge_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces Holmes Has a New Case" ;
    ex:description "At breakfast on a wild October morning, Watson observes Holmes's unusually bright and joyous mood and correctly infers that he has received a new case." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Holmes has a new case, as indicated by his bright and joyous demeanor at breakfast despite the gloomy weather." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson expected Holmes to be in depressed spirits due to the wild autumn weather, knowing that Holmes was easily impressed by his surroundings. Instead, finding Holmes in a particularly bright and cheerful mood — with the sinister cheerfulness characteristic of his lighter moments — Watson inferred that only a new case could account for such a reversal of his expected mood." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :thorBridgeDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Steve Dixie and His Criminal Connections" ;
    ex:description "When a hulking stranger bursts into 221B Baker Street to threaten Holmes, Holmes calmly identifies him by name and criminal association, then leverages knowledge of an unsolved killing to cow him into submission." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder is Steve Dixie, a bruiser from the Spencer John gang, who is connected to the killing of young Perkins outside the Holborn Bar." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized Dixie from his knowledge of the Spencer John gang and their recent criminal activities. By mentioning the killing of young Perkins — a crime Dixie was apparently involved in — Holmes demonstrated he had leverage over Dixie, causing the man to turn pale and become cooperative." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :steveDixie ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :killingOfPerkins ;
    ex:confirmedBy :steveDixie ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Detects Susan Eavesdropping Outside the Door" ;
    ex:description "While Mrs. Maberley is narrating the strange events at her house, Holmes raises his hand for silence, strides across the room, and drags in the maid Susan, who had been listening outside the door." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The maid Susan was eavesdropping on Holmes's conversation with Mrs. Maberley." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had been listening to Susan's presence for five minutes, detecting her by her wheezy breathing, which he noted was too heavy for covert surveillance work." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :susanStockdale ;
    ex:confirmedBy :susanStockdale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Susan Informed Barney Stockdale About the Letter" ;
    ex:description "After catching Susan eavesdropping, Holmes questions Mrs. Maberley and establishes that Susan posted the letter to Holmes, then confronts Susan directly with the accusation that she passed word to Barney Stockdale." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Susan sent a message to Barney Stockdale revealing that Mrs. Maberley had written to Holmes for help." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Maberley confirmed she told no one about writing to Holmes, and Susan was the one who posted the letter. Holmes deduced that Susan must have been the information leak, and specifically named Barney Stockdale as her contact — which Susan's reaction confirmed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :susanStockdale ;
    ex:confirmedBy :susanStockdale ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Employer Is a Rich Woman" ;
    ex:description "While questioning Susan about who is behind Barney Stockdale, Holmes reads her facial reaction to narrow down the identity of the gang's employer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person behind Barney Stockdale and the conspiracy is a wealthy woman." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Susan said someone could lay down a thousand pounds for every ten Holmes had, Holmes first guessed a rich man, but noticed Susan smiled at this — indicating the guess was wrong in a telling way. He corrected to a rich woman, which Susan's continued reactions confirmed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:confirmedBy :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Desired Object Is Unknown to Its Owner" ;
    ex:description "After learning that Mrs. Maberley has nothing obviously valuable, Holmes reasons through why the buyers insist on purchasing everything in the house rather than simply naming what they want." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The house contains something valuable that Mrs. Maberley does not know she possesses and would not willingly surrender if she did." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that if the buyers merely coveted a specific known item such as the Crown Derby tea-set, they could offer a price for it directly without buying the entire house and contents. The insistence on acquiring everything — lock, stock, and barrel — indicated the target was something the owner did not recognize as valuable." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maberleyManuscript ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryThreeGables ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Connects Douglas's Trunks to the Mystery" ;
    ex:description "As Holmes and Watson leave the Three Gables, Holmes notices several trunks and cases labeled from Milano and Lucerne piled in the hall — the personal effects of Mrs. Maberley's recently deceased son Douglas, arrived from Italy only the previous week." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Douglas Maberley's recently arrived trunks from Italy are the missing link — they contain whatever the conspirators are after." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had established that the desired object must have arrived recently, since no one showed interest in the house during Mrs. Maberley's nearly two years of residence. The Italian-labeled trunks, which arrived only the previous week containing Douglas's effects, perfectly matched this timeline and provided the connection between the sudden interest in the house and Douglas's death abroad." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :douglasTrunks ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :douglasTrunks ;
    ex:confirmedBy :burglaryThreeGables ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Manuscript Fragment as Autobiographical" ;
    ex:description "After the burglary, Holmes examines a single page of manuscript torn from the burglar's hands by Mrs. Maberley and notices a revealing grammatical shift in the text." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The manuscript is autobiographical — the author was writing about his own experience, as revealed by the involuntary shift from third person to first person." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that in the fragment, the pronoun suddenly changed from 'he' to 'my,' indicating the writer was so carried away by his own story that he momentarily dropped the fictional mask and wrote as himself, revealing the novel to be a thinly disguised account of the author's real experience." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :manuscriptFragment ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :manuscriptFragment ;
    ex:confirmedBy :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Isadora Klein as the Mastermind" ;
    ex:description "After consulting his social intelligence source Langdale Pike and piecing together Douglas Maberley's romantic history, Holmes identifies the celebrated beauty Isadora Klein as the person behind the entire conspiracy." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Isadora Klein — the wealthy Spanish-born widow of the German sugar king and former lover of Douglas Maberley — is the mastermind behind the intimidation, the purchase offer, and the burglary." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected several threads: Douglas Maberley had been romantically involved with Isadora Klein, a notorious adventuress now engaged to the Duke of Lomond. Douglas had written an autobiographical novel about their affair. Klein's impending high-society marriage would be destroyed by the scandal if the novel were published. The wealth and influence behind the gang matched Klein's resources. Information from Langdale Pike confirmed the connection." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :manuscriptFragment, :langdalePike ;
    ex:confirmedBy :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Klein's Motive Was to Suppress the Manuscript" ;
    ex:description "In the cab ride to Grosvenor Square, Holmes explains the full conspiracy to Watson — how Klein's fear of Douglas's autobiographical novel drove the entire scheme, from the purchase offer to the burglary." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Klein orchestrated the entire conspiracy to steal and destroy Douglas Maberley's manuscript novel, which depicted their affair and would ruin her forthcoming marriage to the Duke of Lomond." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Douglas wrote a novel based on his affair with Klein, sending her a copy as a form of revenge after she had him beaten. With Douglas dead, the second copy was among his effects being returned to his mother. Klein first tried to buy the house and everything in it to obtain the manuscript legitimately. When that failed, she deployed the Stockdale gang and Susan as an inside agent to steal it by force. The entire operation — from the house purchase offer with its unusual clause forbidding removal of any contents, to the burglary targeting Douglas's trunks — was aimed at a single objective: destroying the manuscript before it could reach a publisher." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:deductionSubject :maberleyManuscript ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :manuscriptFragment, :langdalePike ;
    ex:confirmedBy :isadoraKlein ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_inspectorthreegables_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Inspector's Theory: Burglars Grabbed Whatever Came First to Hand" ;
    ex:description "After the burglary at the Three Gables, the rubicund inspector dismisses the manuscript page as meaningless, theorizing that the burglars simply snatched whatever they could find in their hurry." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The burglars found nothing valuable downstairs and simply grabbed at whatever came first to hand upstairs, including the worthless manuscript pages." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The inspector assumed the burglary was a conventional break-in where the thieves, finding nothing of value on the ground floor, went upstairs and hastily seized whatever they could carry. He considered the torn manuscript page to be of no significance, merely an accidental byproduct of a rushed robbery." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorThreeGables ;
    ex:deductionSubject :burglaryThreeGables ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :manuscriptFragment ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_threeGables_holmes_08 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGables_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Desired Object Arrived Recently" ;
    ex:description "During the initial consultation at the Three Gables, Holmes prompts Mrs. Maberley to consider why demands have suddenly arisen after nearly two years of quiet residence. Watson provides the logical answer before Holmes can." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The object the conspirators are seeking has only just come into the house, since no interest was shown during the previous two years." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson reasoned that if Mrs. Maberley had lived undisturbed in the house for nearly two years and only now faced urgent demands, the timing indicated the target object must have arrived recently rather than being a longstanding feature of the property." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:confirmedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGablesDoc .

:deduction_threeGarridebs_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces John Garrideb Has Been in England a Long Time" ;
    ex:description "During their first meeting at 221B Baker Street, Holmes observes the clothing of the man calling himself John Garrideb, Counsellor at Law from Kansas, and immediately challenges his claim to have recently arrived from America." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Garrideb has been residing in England for a considerable time despite claiming to be a recently arrived American lawyer." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the shoulder cut of John Garrideb's coat and the toes of his boots were distinctly English in style. Since the man claimed to have come from Kansas recently, his entirely English outfit contradicted his story and indicated long residence in London." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :killerEvans ;
    ex:confirmedBy :evansDossier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
