:deduction_threeGarridebs_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces John Garrideb's Entire Story Is a Fabrication" ;
    ex:description "After John Garrideb departs from 221B, Holmes reveals to Watson that the visitor's entire account was a tissue of lies, citing multiple points of falsification he detected during the interview." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "John Garrideb's story about the Garrideb inheritance and his identity as a Kansas lawyer is entirely fabricated." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted the English coat frayed at the elbow and trousers bagged at the knee with a year's wear, contradicting the claim of a provincial American recently landed in London. He confirmed there had been no advertisements in the agony columns, which he monitors closely. He had never known a Dr. Lysander Starr of Topeka, the reference the American confidently cited. Holmes concluded the man was probably American by birth but had smoothed his accent through years of London residence." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :killerEvans ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :garridebFoolscapDocument ;
    ex:confirmedBy :evansDossier ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGarridebsDoc .

:deduction_threeGarridebs_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Nathan Garrideb's Name Is Genuine" ;
    ex:description "As Holmes and Watson arrive at Nathan Garrideb's residence on Little Ryder Street, Holmes draws Watson's attention to the brass nameplate beside the door." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Nathan Garrideb's name is genuine and he has lived at the address for years, as evidenced by his aged brass nameplate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the small brass plate bearing the name Garrideb had a discoloured surface indicating years of exposure, confirming that the name was real and the occupant long-established at the address rather than a recent fabrication connected to the American's scheme." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nathanGarrideb ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :nathanGarridebBrassPlate ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nathanGarrideb ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGarridebsDoc .

:deduction_threeGarridebs_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Howard Garrideb Advertisement Was Planted by the American" ;
    ex:description "Back at Baker Street after dinner, Holmes draws Watson's attention to the advertisement for Howard Garrideb, Constructor of Agricultural Machinery, which John Garrideb had presented as evidence of a third Garrideb found in Birmingham." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The advertisement for Howard Garrideb in Birmingham was composed and planted by the American himself, not discovered through genuine inquiry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the word 'plough' was spelled in the American fashion, buckboards are an American vehicle term, and artesian wells are more commonly referenced in American usage. The advertisement was typeset as received, meaning the printer reproduced American English verbatim. A genuine English agricultural firm would not use these Americanisms, proving the advertisement was authored by the American to create a fictitious third Garrideb." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :howardGarridebAdvertisement ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :howardGarridebAdvertisement ;
    ex:confirmedBy :discoveryOfCounterfeitingPress ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeGarridebsDoc .

:deduction_threeGarridebs_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Garrideb Scheme Was Invented to Lure Nathan From His Rooms" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains to Watson while lying in wait at Nathan Garrideb's flat that the entire elaborate Garrideb inheritance story was contrived for one purpose: to get Nathan Garrideb out of his rooms." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The entire Garrideb inheritance invention was designed solely to lure the reclusive Nathan Garrideb away from his flat so the American could access something hidden in the premises." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that Nathan Garrideb was a recluse who virtually never left his rooms, making it extremely difficult to gain access to the flat in his absence. The elaborate three-Garrideb scheme, culminating in sending Nathan to Birmingham, was the only way to engineer his departure. The queer name of the tenant gave the criminal an opening he could hardly have expected, and he wove his plot with remarkable cunning around it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nathanGarrideb ;
    ex:deductionSubject :killerEvans ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :howardGarridebAdvertisement, :garridebWill ;
