    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reconstructs the Intruder's Copying Method" ;
    ex:description "Examining Soames's sitting room, Holmes reconstructs how the intruder operated, carrying the papers from the central table to the window table to copy them while maintaining a lookout." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder carried the proof sheets one by one from the central table to the window table to copy them, positioning himself where he could watch for Soames's return across the courtyard." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The evidence on the window table (pencil shavings, displaced proof sheet) indicated copying took place there rather than at the central table. The window position offered a view of the courtyard approach, allowing the copier to watch for Soames's return." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fortescueExamTampering ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pencilShavings ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Pencil as a Johann Faber" ;
    ex:description "From pencil shavings and a broken chip found on the window table, Holmes identifies the specific make, size, colour, and remaining length of the pencil used by the intruder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The pencil was an unusually large Johann Faber pencil with soft lead, dark blue exterior, silver lettering, approximately one and a half inches remaining." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined a small chip bearing the letters 'NN' and clear wood after them. Recognizing that Johann Faber is the most common pencil maker's name, he deduced the 'NN' was the end of 'Johann,' establishing how much pencil remained. The shavings indicated its large size, soft lead, and dark blue colouring." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johannFaberPencil ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pencilShavings ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Possesses a Large Blunt Knife" ;
    ex:description "From the pencil shavings found at the scene, Holmes deduces that the intruder used a large and very blunt knife to sharpen the pencil." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder possesses a large, very blunt knife, as evidenced by the manner of the pencil sharpening." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The character of the pencil shavings and the way the pencil was cut indicated the sharpening instrument was large and notably blunt rather than a fine blade or penknife." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :pencilShavings ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Hid in the Bedroom" ;
    ex:description "Upon discovering a second pyramid of black clay in Soames's bedroom, Holmes deduces that the intruder fled into the bedroom to hide when Soames returned unexpectedly by the side door." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder hid in Soames's bedroom when surprised by Soames's unexpected return through the side door." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A second pellet of black clay, identical to the one on the study table, was found on the bedroom floor. Since the intruder had no warning of Soames's return via the side door, he grabbed his belongings and rushed into the only available hiding place — the bedroom behind the curtain." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fortescueExamTampering ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackClayPellets ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Must Be Unusually Tall" ;
    ex:description "When first approaching Soames's room, Holmes examined the window from outside, measuring the height needed to see the central table. He later reveals this was to determine whether a passerby could have spotted the papers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Only someone at least six feet tall could have seen the papers on the central table through the sitting-room window while passing outside." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes measured the window height from the courtyard and determined that he, at six feet, could barely see the table surface with effort. Anyone shorter would have no chance of glimpsing the papers, meaning the intruder had to be of unusual height." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Intruder Knew the Papers Were Present" ;
    ex:description "During his retrospective explanation, Holmes dismisses the possibility that the intruder entered the room by coincidence and happened upon the exam papers." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder knew the papers were on the table before entering; the intrusion was not coincidental." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since no one except the printer knew the proofs would be in Soames's room, and the printer could examine them in his own office, the intruder must have discovered their presence by some other means. An unthinkable coincidence that someone would dare to enter and by chance find the papers on the table was dismissed in favour of prior knowledge gained by seeing them through the window." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fortescueExamTampering ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates Daulat Ras as a Suspect" ;
    ex:description "In his retrospective explanation, Holmes rules out the Indian student Daulat Ras, reasoning that Ras could not have identified the rolled-up proofs during his earlier visit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Daulat Ras is eliminated as a suspect because he could not have known the rolled proofs were examination papers." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Daulat Ras visited Soames's room earlier, the proofs were rolled up. In that state, they could not be recognized as exam papers. Since the intruder must have known the papers were there, and Ras had no way to identify them, he was not the culprit." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :daulatRas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :fortescueExamPaper ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Eliminates McLaren by Height" ;
    ex:description "After visiting the three students' rooms, Holmes asks Soames for McLaren's exact height. Learning McLaren is approximately five foot six, Holmes eliminates him as a suspect." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miles McLaren is eliminated as a suspect because at approximately five foot six he is too short to have seen the papers through the window." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes had established that only a man of at least six feet could see the papers on the central table from outside the window. McLaren's height of approximately five foot six made it impossible for him to have spotted the papers while passing." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milesMcLaren ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Gilchrist as the Culprit" ;
    ex:description "When Soames describes Gilchrist as a long-distance jumper, Holmes connects the black clay evidence to the jumping pit and Gilchrist's exceptional height, identifying him as the culprit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Gilchrist is the culprit, identified through his unusual height, his use of the athletic grounds, and the black clay from the jumping pit found at the scene." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Soames's description of Gilchrist as a long-distance jumper caused the whole case to crystallize. Gilchrist was tall enough to see through the window, his jumping shoes with spikes explained the cut in the leather desk, the black clay with sawdust matched the jumping pit material, and his athletic practice that afternoon placed him passing the window in spiked shoes." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :gilchrist ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackClayPellets, :cutInLeatherDesk, :gilchristsJumpingShoes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Traces the Black Clay to the Jumping Pit" ;
    ex:description "Early the next morning, Holmes walks to the athletic grounds and confirms the black clay with sawdust-like grains found at the scene originated from the jumping pit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The black doughy clay with sawdust grains found at the crime scene came from the tenacious black clay used in the athletic grounds' jumping pit." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes visited the athletic grounds at six in the morning, observed that tenacious black clay was used in the jumping pit with fine tan or sawdust strewn over it to prevent slipping, and collected a specimen that matched the pellets found in Soames's rooms." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :blackClayPellets ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :blackClayPellets, :jumpingPit ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Interprets the Desk Scratch Direction" ;
    ex:description "During the final explanation, Holmes notes the scratch on Soames's leather desk begins thin on one side and deepens toward the bedroom door, interpreting its directional pattern." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The scratch on the desk deepens toward the bedroom door, indicating the spiked shoe was dragged in that direction as the culprit fled to hide." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The cut in the leather desk surface began as a thin scratch on one side and ended in a jagged hole deepening toward the bedroom door. This directional pattern showed the spiked jumping shoe had been swept off the table toward the bedroom as the culprit grabbed it during his hasty flight to the hiding place." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cutInLeatherDesk ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cutInLeatherDesk ;
    ex:confirmedBy :gilchristsConfession ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Bannister Sat in the Chair to Conceal Gloves" ;
    ex:description "During the confrontation, Holmes challenges Bannister about why he chose to sit in a specific chair far from the door, suggesting he did so to conceal an object that would identify the culprit." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Bannister deliberately sat in the chair near the window to conceal Gilchrist's tan gloves, which had been left on it and would have identified the culprit." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Bannister claimed he nearly fainted near the door, yet he crossed the room to sit in a chair by the window corner rather than the nearer chairs. This deliberate choice of a specific distant chair suggested he needed to conceal something on or near it — later revealed to be Gilchrist's recognizable tan gloves." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bannisterServant ;
    ex:deductionSubject :gilchristsTanGloves ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :gilchristsTanGloves ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bannisterServant ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Bannister Released Gilchrist from the Bedroom" ;
    ex:description "Holmes confronts Bannister with the logical conclusion that he must have released the hidden intruder from the bedroom after Soames left to fetch Holmes." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Bannister released Gilchrist from the bedroom after Soames departed, as Bannister was the only person left in the room with the door locked." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Since the intruder was hidden in the bedroom, and Bannister was left alone in the room after Soames departed, only Bannister could have released the man. Escape through the bedroom window was dismissed as incredible given the courtyard exposure, leaving Bannister as the sole means of egress." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :bannisterServant ;
    ex:deductionSubject :gilchrist ;
    ex:confirmedBy :bannisterServant ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_threeStudents_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: McLaren Is the Most Likely Suspect" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks Watson for his opinion on the three suspects, Watson names Miles McLaren as the most likely culprit, with some suspicion also directed at Daulat Ras." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Miles McLaren is the most likely suspect based on his having the worst record among the three students and his suspicious refusal to open his door." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson judged McLaren as the prime suspect because he had the worst reputation of the three students (nearly expelled for a card scandal, wayward and unprincipled). Watson also noted the Indian student's suspicious pacing and sideways glances, but settled on McLaren as the primary suspect." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :milesMcLaren ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_threeStudents_holmes_10 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :threeStudentsDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_inspectorbarton_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Barton's Theory: Evidence Points to Abominable Crime Against St. Clair" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Barton, who had charge of the initial investigation at the opium den, examined the premises and concluded from the blood on the windowsill, the presence of St. Clair's clothing, and the absence of the man himself that an abominable crime had been committed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The physical evidence — blood on the windowsill, St. Clair's clothes hidden behind a curtain, and the open window over the tidal strip — indicates that Neville St. Clair was the victim of a violent crime." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Barton found traces of blood on the bedroom windowsill and scattered drops on the floor, all of St. Clair's garments except his coat hidden behind a curtain, no other exit besides the window, and the tide at its highest beneath. These combined to suggest the victim had been attacked and his body disposed of through the window into the river." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBarton ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairCoat ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_twistedLip_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Believes Neville St. Clair Is Dead" ;
    ex:description "At The Cedars, when Mrs. St. Clair presses Holmes for his frank opinion on whether her husband is alive, Holmes tells her plainly that he believes Neville is dead, most likely killed on Monday." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Neville St. Clair is dead, probably murdered on the Monday of his disappearance." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Based on the circumstantial evidence available at this stage — blood on the windowsill, the missing body, the clothes found behind the curtain, and the weighted coat recovered from the Thames mud — Holmes judges that St. Clair met his death at the opium den on Monday." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairCoat ;
    ex:refutedBy :stClairLetter ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_twistedLip_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Envelope Addresser Was Unfamiliar with the Address" ;
    ex:description "Examining the letter Mrs. St. Clair received from her husband, Holmes analyzes the ink on the envelope and deduces that whoever addressed it had to stop and inquire about the address before writing it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The person who addressed the envelope was not familiar with the St. Clair address and had to pause to look it up." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the name on the envelope was written in perfectly black ink that had dried naturally, while the address below was in a greyish colour indicating blotting paper had been used. If the entire address had been written in one go, the ink would be uniformly blotted. The pause between writing the name and the address meant the writer had to inquire about the address, proving unfamiliarity with it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :stClairLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Letter Was Posted by a Tobacco-Chewing Man with Dirty Hands" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his examination of the letter at The Cedars, Holmes makes several observational deductions about the physical characteristics of the person who handled and posted the envelope." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letter was posted in Gravesend by a man with a dirty thumb who chews tobacco, and the enclosure was written in pencil on the fly-leaf of an octavo book with no watermark." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted a dirty thumbprint on the envelope, identified the flap as having been gummed by a person who had been chewing tobacco rather than using the adhesive, and observed the material properties of the enclosure — pencil on a fly-leaf of an octavo book with no watermark. These details indicated a working-class intermediary handled the posting." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :stClairLetter ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Reinterprets Mrs. St. Clair's Sighting as Surprise Rather Than Distress" ;
    ex:description "During his questioning of Mrs. St. Clair about the moment she saw her husband at the window, Holmes methodically suggests an alternative interpretation of what she witnessed — that her husband's cry and gestures were expressions of surprise at seeing her, not a call for help, and that he leaped back rather than being pulled away." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "St. Clair's cry and frantic gestures at the window were caused by astonishment at unexpectedly seeing his wife, not by an attack, and he leaped back voluntarily rather than being pulled by force." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that the window was open and St. Clair could have called out but only gave an inarticulate cry. He suggested that astonishment at the unexpected sight of his wife could cause a man to throw up his hands. The sudden disappearance could equally be explained by leaping back as by being pulled. Additionally, Mrs. St. Clair had not seen anyone else in the room, and St. Clair was missing his collar and tie — unusual for a man who had left home dressed for business." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionSubject :mrsStClair ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Constructs Working Hypothesis That Boone Murdered St. Clair and Disposed of the Body" ;
    ex:description "While narrating the case to Watson during the drive to Lee, Holmes presents a speculative reconstruction of how Hugh Boone might have killed St. Clair and disposed of the evidence, presenting it explicitly as a working hypothesis." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Hugh Boone thrust St. Clair through the window, then seized the coat, stuffed it with coins from his begging hoard to ensure it would sink, and threw it into the river before the police arrived." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that if Boone pushed St. Clair through the window, no eye could have witnessed it. Boone would immediately need to dispose of the tell-tale garments. Seizing the coat, he would realize it would float, so he would rush to his begging hoard and stuff coins into the pockets to weight it down. He would have thrown out the other garments too, but the rush of constables up the stairs gave him only time to close the window." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairCoat ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_twistedLip_holmes_06 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Hugh Boone Is Neville St. Clair in Disguise" ;
    ex:description "After spending the entire night at The Cedars sitting upon five pillows and consuming an ounce of shag tobacco in concentrated thought, Holmes arrives at the breakthrough conclusion that Hugh Boone the beggar and Neville St. Clair are the same person, and that washing Boone's face will prove it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Hugh Boone and Neville St. Clair are the same man — St. Clair has been living a double life as a professional beggar, using makeup and disguise to transform himself into Boone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes spent all night reconsidering the evidence: the letter proving St. Clair was alive, St. Clair's cry of surprise (not distress) at seeing his wife, his missing collar and tie (consistent with changing clothes), the blood from a minor cut (not violence), the weighted coat (St. Clair's own begging coins), Boone's refusal to wash his face in custody, and the fact that no body was ever found. All the evidence pointed not to murder but to a man caught in the act of transitioning between two identities. The 'key' was in the bathroom — a sponge to wash away the disguise." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairLetter, :stClairCoat, :stClairSignetRing ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Lascar Delayed Posting the Letter" ;
    ex:description "After St. Clair's full confession, Holmes confirms his deduction about the delayed delivery of the letter, noting that the Lascar, under police surveillance, likely handed it to a sailor customer who forgot about it for days." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Lascar, watched by police, could not post the letter himself and handed it to a sailor who neglected to deliver it for several days, explaining the delay." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the police surveillance of the Lascar with the letter's delayed arrival — despite being written on Monday, it was postmarked from Gravesend days later. Under watch, the Lascar could not post it directly and instead entrusted it to a sailor customer, who forgot about it before eventually posting it from Gravesend." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :barOfGoldLascar ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairLetter ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_twistedLip_mrsstclair_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Mrs. St. Clair's Intuition: Her Husband Is Still Alive" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes tells Mrs. St. Clair that he believes Neville is dead, she counters by producing a letter she received that day. She insists her husband is alive, citing both the letter and an intuitive sympathy between them that she believes would alert her to his death." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Neville St. Clair is alive, as evidenced by his letter and the intuitive bond between husband and wife." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. St. Clair presented the letter containing her husband's handwriting and his signet ring as physical proof. She further argued from a keen sympathetic connection with her husband, citing a previous occasion when he merely cut himself in the bedroom and she instantly sensed something had happened from the dining room. She reasoned that if she could respond to such a trifle, she would certainly know if he had died." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :mrsStClair ;
    ex:deductionSubject :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :stClairLetter, :stClairSignetRing ;
    ex:confirmedBy :nevilleStClair ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :manWithTheTwistedLipDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Porlock's Handwriting" ;
    ex:description "Upon receiving a mysterious envelope at 221B Baker Street, Holmes examines it carefully and identifies it as the writing of his secret informant within Moriarty's organization." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The envelope was written by the informant Porlock, identified by the distinctive Greek 'e' with a peculiar top flourish." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the handwriting from two previous letters, noting the distinctive formation of the Greek letter 'e' with its peculiar top flourish as a reliable identifier." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :fredPorlock ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :fredPorlock ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Message as a Book Cipher" ;
    ex:description "Examining the slip of paper containing numbers interspersed with the plaintext words DOUGLAS and BIRLSTONE, Holmes determines the nature of the cipher." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cipher is a book cipher referencing words on a page of some book, with DOUGLAS and BIRLSTONE written in plaintext because they did not appear on the referenced page." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The numerical sequences clearly referenced word positions in a text, while the two plaintext names were included because the source page did not contain those proper nouns." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cipherMessage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :whitakersAlmanac ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cipher Book Is a Large, Common, Double-Column Volume" ;
    ex:description "Through systematic reasoning at 221B Baker Street, Holmes narrows down the characteristics of the book used to create the cipher, working through the problem with Watson." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cipher book must be a large volume printed in double columns that is standardized and in common use." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The number 534 indicates a large book; C2 means column two, not chapter two, indicating double columns; word number 293 shows long columns; Porlock intended to send only the key, meaning the book is one Holmes would readily possess; standardized pagination rules out most books." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cipherMessage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :whitakersAlmanac ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deciphers the Warning Using Last Year's Almanac" ;
    ex:description "After the current year's Whitaker's Almanac produces nonsense, Holmes realizes Porlock used the previous year's edition and successfully decodes the warning message." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Porlock used last year's Whitaker's Almanac for the cipher; the decoded message warns that danger is pressing for one Douglas, a rich country gentleman at Birlstone." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The current almanac's page 534 yielded nonsensical results ('Mahratta government pig's-bristles'). Since it was January 7th, the new edition had just arrived. Porlock would have used the previous year's copy, which decoded to: 'There is danger may come very soon one DOUGLAS rich country now at BIRLSTONE House BIRLSTONE confidence is pressing.'" ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage, :whitakersAlmanac ;
    ex:confirmedBy :birlstoneInvestigation ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moriarty's Illegal Wealth from the Greuze Painting" ;
    ex:description "While briefing Inspector MacDonald about Professor Moriarty, Holmes presents evidence of the professor's unexplained wealth derived from observing his possessions." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty must have an enormous illegal income, as he owns an extremely valuable Greuze painting while earning only seven hundred pounds a year as a professor." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A Greuze painting sold for over forty thousand pounds at the Portalis sale. Moriarty's university salary is only seven hundred a year, he is unmarried, and his brother is merely a station master. Yet he possesses such a painting, proving wealth far beyond his legitimate means." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :greuzePainting ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moriarty Conceals His Wealth Across Multiple Banks" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reveals to MacDonald his investigation into Moriarty's financial arrangements, demonstrating the professor's deliberate concealment of wealth." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty uses at least six different banks for ordinary household expenses, indicating deliberate concealment of his true financial position, likely with twenty or more accounts including foreign banks." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes tracked down Moriarty's household checks and found them drawn on six different banks. This deliberate fragmentation ensures no single institution can gauge his total wealth, suggesting extensive financial concealment including foreign accounts." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Theorizes Two Possible Moriarty Motives for the Murder" ;
    ex:description "Before departing for Birlstone, Holmes outlines two possible scenarios connecting Moriarty to the murder of Douglas." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Either Douglas betrayed Moriarty and was executed as punishment to instill fear, or Moriarty was hired to arrange the murder as a business commission." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Moriarty rules with a code of death for betrayal, making execution of a traitor one possibility. Alternatively, Moriarty's known business model of arranging crimes for profit suggests he may have been engaged by outside parties to engineer the murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Gun Maker as Pennsylvania Small Arms Company" ;
    ex:description "During the examination of the murder weapon at Birlstone Manor, White Mason describes the partial lettering on the shotgun barrels and Holmes immediately identifies the manufacturer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The letters P-E-N on the barrel fluting identify the weapon as made by the Pennsylvania Small Arms Company, a well-known American firm." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes recognized the distinctive lettering style — a big P with a flourish above it, followed by smaller E and N — as the marking of the Pennsylvania Small Arms Company, confirming the weapon's American origin." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :sawedOffShotgun ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sawedOffShotgun ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Douglas Was Not Attacked Immediately Upon Entering" ;
    ex:description "During the examination of the crime scene at Birlstone Manor, Holmes observes the state of the candle and draws a conclusion about the timing of the attack." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Douglas was not attacked the instant he entered the room, as the candle was placed on the table before the attack and had burned only half an inch." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "A new candle burned only half an inch. Douglas must have placed it on the table before being attacked; otherwise it would have fallen when he fell. This shows a brief interval between entry and the assault." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Douglas Was Nervous Before the Murder" ;
    ex:description "Holmes questions the butler Ames about a small piece of plaster on the dead man's jaw and Douglas's recent behavior, detecting signs of prior apprehension." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Douglas was nervous and apprehensive before the murder, as shown by an unusual shaving cut and restless, excited behavior the day before." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The plaster at the angle of the jaw indicated a shaving cut, which Ames confirmed was extremely unusual for Douglas. Combined with Ames's observation that Douglas had been restless and excited, Holmes inferred that Douglas had reason to apprehend danger before the attack." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the V.V. Card Was Not Written in the Study" ;
    ex:description "Holmes tests the ink from bottles on the study desk against the ink used on the V.V. 341 card, determining the card was prepared elsewhere." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The V.V. 341 card was not printed in the study; the study contains black ink and fine pens, while the card was written in purplish ink with a thick pen." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes dabbed ink from each bottle in the study onto blotting paper and compared it with the card. The study ink was black and the pens were fine, whereas the card had been written in purplish ink with a thick pen, proving it was prepared at another location." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vv341Card ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :vv341Card ;
    ex:confirmedBy :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_12 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Notes the Discrepant Footprints: Splay-Foot on Sill vs. Shapely Boot in Corner" ;
    ex:description "Examining the blood mark on the windowsill with his lens, Holmes observes that the broad, splay-footed print does not match the more shapely boot marks in the muddy corner." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 12 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The blood mark on the windowsill was made by a remarkably broad, splay-footed sole, inconsistent with the more shapely bootmarks found in the muddy corner behind the curtain." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes's lens examination revealed the sill mark was clearly a shoe tread of remarkable breadth, suggesting a splay-foot. However, the bootmarks traceable in the mud-stained corner showed a more shapely sole, indicating two different types of footwear had left marks in the room." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_15 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_13 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Notes the Significance of the Missing Dumb-Bell" ;
    ex:description "While examining the study, Holmes discovers only one dumb-bell under the side table where a pair should logically exist, and marks this as a critical clue." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 13 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Only one dumb-bell is present under the side table; the missing second dumb-bell is a key piece of evidence in the case." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "An athletic man would have no use for a single dumb-bell, as they are always used in pairs. The absence of the second one, in a room near water, suggested it had been used as a weight to sink something in the moat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dumbbell ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dumbbell ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_18 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_14 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Suspicious Discrepancy in Candle and Lamp Timing" ;
    ex:description "During the questioning of Cecil Barker, Holmes raises a pointed observation about the lighting in the study between Barker's discovery and the servants' arrival." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 14 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Barker found only a candle lit in the study, but within a minute when servants arrived, the lamp was lit and candle extinguished — suggesting Barker had more time alone in the room than he claimed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Barker stated he entered the room by candlelight, saw the body, and immediately rang the bell. Yet when help arrived within a minute, the candle was out and the lamp was burning. Switching from candle to lamp would be unnecessary in a moment of genuine shock and haste, suggesting Barker had additional time and purpose in the room." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_15 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Proves Barker's Slipper Made the Blood Mark on the Windowsill" ;
    ex:description "Holmes retrieves Barker's bedroom slippers from the hall and matches one to the blood mark on the windowsill, proving the escape evidence was fabricated." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 15 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The blood mark on the windowsill was made by Cecil Barker's bedroom slipper, not by an escaping murderer climbing through the window." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes placed Barker's blood-stained slipper upon the blood mark on the sill and found it corresponded exactly. The broad, splay-footed impression matched the slipper's sole rather than any boot, proving that Barker had deliberately placed the mark to simulate a murderer's escape through the window." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_16 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Barker and Mrs. Douglas Are Lying and Conspiring" ;
    ex:description "Back at the Westville Arms inn, Holmes presents Watson with his comprehensive analysis of the evidence, concluding that the accounts given by Barker and Mrs. Douglas are fabrications." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 16 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Barker and Mrs. Douglas are both lying about the circumstances of the murder and are engaged in a conspiracy to conceal the truth about what happened and when." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The assassin could not have removed the wedding ring (which was beneath another ring), replaced the upper ring, and left the card in under one minute. The candle evidence shows no lengthy interview. Barker fabricated the blood mark on the windowsill. Mrs. Douglas showed no grief and was easily turned away from her husband's body. Their entire story is a clumsy fabrication." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ivyDouglas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_14, :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_15 ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_17 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Murder Occurred at 10:45 PM, Not 11:15" ;
    ex:description "Through acoustic experiments conducted at the Manor House and analysis of the housekeeper's testimony, Holmes determines the actual time of the gunshot." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 17 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murder actually occurred at approximately a quarter to eleven, a full half hour before Barker and Mrs. Douglas raised the alarm." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Mrs. Allen heard what she described as a door slamming about half an hour before the alarm bell rang. Holmes's sound experiments showed that noise from the study could reach the housekeeper's room but not the distant pantry. A muffled shotgun blast at close range would sound like a slamming door to a somewhat deaf woman. This places the actual shot at 10:45, with Barker and Douglas spending thirty minutes staging the scene before sounding the alarm at 11:15." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ivyDouglas ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_18 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Missing Dumb-Bell Was Used to Sink Evidence in the Moat" ;
    ex:description "Holmes connects the missing dumb-bell to the proximity of the moat, reasoning that something was weighted and submerged in the water, and confirms this by fishing the bundle out with Watson's umbrella." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 18 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The missing dumb-bell was used to weight a bundle of evidence that was sunk in the moat; Holmes retrieved the bundle by fishing it out with an umbrella handle." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When water is near and a weight is missing, the natural supposition is that something has been sunk. Holmes used the crook of Watson's umbrella to fish the moat from the study window, recovering a bundle weighted with the dumb-bell containing a complete set of clothing, boots, and a knife." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :dumbbell ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dumbbell ;
    ex:confirmedBy :cecilBarker ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_19 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Notes the Physical Resemblance Between Hargrave and Douglas" ;
    ex:description "When MacDonald reads the hotel description of the mysterious cyclist, Holmes immediately observes the striking similarity to Douglas himself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 19 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The description of the cyclist 'Hargrave' — about fifty, grizzled hair and moustache, similar height — closely matches John Douglas, suggesting a connection between the two men." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The hotel staff described Hargrave as about five foot nine, roughly fifty years old, with slightly grizzled hair and a grayish moustache. Holmes noted that, apart from the expression, this could almost be a description of Douglas himself, who was just over fifty with grizzled hair and moustache of the same height." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_20 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Connects the Overcoat to Vermissa and the Valley of Fear" ;
    ex:description "After recovering the weighted bundle from the moat, Holmes examines the clothing and discovers a tailor's label linking the garments to Vermissa, connecting the V.V. card to the Valley of Fear." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 20 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The overcoat was made by Neal, Outfitter of Vermissa, USA, connecting V.V. 341 to Vermissa Valley and identifying the Valley of Fear that Douglas had spoken of with such dread." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The tailor's tab reading 'Neal, Outfitter, Vermissa, U.S.A.' placed the clothing's origin in a coal and iron valley town. Holmes connected Vermissa to the V.V. on the card (Vermissa Valley), to Barker's association of Douglas's first wife with coal districts, and to the 'Valley of Fear' that Mrs. Douglas had reported her husband mentioning with terror." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vv341Card ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :vv341Card ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_21 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Douglas Is Alive and Hidden in the Manor House" ;
    ex:description "Holmes reveals his culminating deduction: the dead man is not Douglas but the American cyclist, and Douglas himself is alive, concealed in a secret room within the ancient Manor House." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 21 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The body is that of the cyclist from Tunbridge Wells, not John Douglas. Douglas killed his attacker in self-defense, swapped identities with the corpse, and has been hiding in a concealed room in the Manor House — a building known to have hiding places dating to the Civil War." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Holmes found the complete suit of American clothes in the moat, it became apparent the body wearing Douglas's dressing gown could not be Douglas, since the clothes belonged to the cyclist. The dead man must therefore be the cyclist, and Douglas must be alive. The balance of probability placed him in the house itself, which a local historical pamphlet revealed had concealment rooms used since the Civil War era. His wife and friend's conspiracy was to protect a living man, not to cover a murder." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :dumbbell ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_22 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Douglas's Death at Sea Was Murder by Moriarty" ;
    ex:description "In the Epilogue at Baker Street, when Barker brings news that Douglas was lost overboard during a gale off St. Helena, Holmes immediately identifies the death as murder orchestrated by Moriarty." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 22 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Douglas's death at sea was not an accident but was murder arranged by Professor Moriarty, recognizable by its sophisticated execution compared to the crude methods of the American Scowrers." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "An enigmatic note ('Dear me, Mr. Holmes') foreshadowed the event. The method — a man lost overboard in a gale with no witnesses — bore the hallmarks of a master criminal rather than the sawed-off shotguns and crude violence of the Scowrers. Holmes recognized Moriarty's characteristic thoroughness: a man who cannot afford to fail, whose unique position depends on unfailing success." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_23 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Moriarty's Escalating Involvement in the Douglas Case" ;
    ex:description "Holmes explains to Barker the chain of Moriarty's involvement, from initial consultant to final executioner, after the Scowrers' direct agent failed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 23 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Moriarty was hired by the American Scowrers as a consultant in crime: first he used his network to locate Douglas, then indicated how the matter should be handled, and finally stepped in personally with a 'master touch' after Baldwin's failed attempt." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The first intelligence about the plot came from Porlock, one of Moriarty's lieutenants. The Americans, needing help with an English operation, engaged Moriarty as a consultant. When Baldwin's crude attempt resulted in his own death rather than Douglas's, Moriarty intervened directly, arranging the fatal 'accident' at sea with the sophistication that distinguishes his work from common criminals." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :professorMoriarty ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_macdonald_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "MacDonald's Theory: No Outside Intruder — Evidence Could Be Staged by Insiders" ;
    ex:description "At the Westville Arms inn before visiting the crime scene, MacDonald challenges White Mason's assumption that a stranger entered the house, arguing that all physical evidence could have been arranged by the residents." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "There is no proof an outsider was ever in the house; the open window, blood on the sill, card, boot marks, and American gun could all have been arranged by Douglas or Barker, both of whom had American connections." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "MacDonald argued that every piece of evidence cited for an intruder — the window, the blood, the card, the footprints, and the American gun — could have been staged. Both Douglas and Barker had lived in America, eliminating the need to import an American perpetrator to explain American elements." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :alecMacDonald ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sawedOffShotgun, :vv341Card ;
    ex:confirmedBy :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_15 ;
    ex:refutedBy :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_macdonald_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "MacDonald's Theory: V.V. 341 and Brand Mark Indicate a Secret Society" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes asks for interpretations of the V.V. 341 card, MacDonald connects the card with the branded triangle-in-circle mark on the dead man's forearm." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The V.V. 341 inscription and the branded forearm mark both point to a secret society connection." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The unusual combination of initials and a number on the card, together with the branded triangle inside a circle on the forearm — clearly a mark inflicted by others — suggested to MacDonald the hallmarks of a secret society identification system." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :alecMacDonald ;
    ex:deductionSubject :vv341Card ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :vv341Card ;
    ex:confirmedBy :lodge341 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_macdonald_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "MacDonald's Theory: American Hargrave Came by Bicycle with Shotgun and Assassinated Douglas" ;
    ex:description "After tracing the bicycle to a hotel in Tunbridge Wells, MacDonald constructs a comprehensive narrative of the outsider's movements leading to the murder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "An American using the name Hargrave arrived in Tunbridge Wells with a concealed sawed-off shotgun, cycled to Birlstone, hid his bicycle, entered the house during daylight, concealed himself behind a curtain, shot Douglas at quarter past eleven, and escaped through the moat." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The bicycle was identified at the Eagle Commercial hotel as belonging to Hargrave, an American guest with a London valise. He had a cycle map, left the morning of the murder, and his valise could have held the sawed-off gun. MacDonald reconstructed his route from the hotel to the concealed bicycle, through the open door before the bridge was raised, hiding behind the curtain, then shooting Douglas on his nightly round and escaping through the window and moat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :alecMacDonald ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sawedOffShotgun, :hargraveBicycle ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_21 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_macdonald_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "MacDonald Suspects Romantic Conspiracy Between Barker and Mrs. Douglas" ;
    ex:description "After Mrs. Douglas's interview, MacDonald speculates about a romantic motive connecting Barker, Mrs. Douglas, and the removal of the wedding ring." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Barker's frequent visits, Douglas's admitted jealousy, and the removal of the wedding ring suggest a possible romantic connection between Barker and Mrs. Douglas as a motive for murder." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Barker was a frequent visitor whom Douglas was known to be jealous of. He admitted the jealousy himself. The deliberate removal of a wedding ring from a dead man's finger strongly suggests the marriage itself was targeted, pointing to a love triangle as possible motive." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :alecMacDonald ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cecilBarker ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ivyDouglas ;
    ex:refutedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_wilson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Sergeant Wilson's Theory: Intruder Entered Before Bridge Was Raised and Hid Behind Curtain" ;
    ex:description "The local police sergeant, examining the muddy bootmarks behind the window curtain, constructs a theory of how the murderer gained entry to the house and waited for his victim." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder entered the house after four o'clock when the curtains were drawn but before six when the bridge was raised, hid behind the curtain in the study, waited until Douglas entered after eleven, shot him, and escaped through the window." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Muddy bootmarks were visible in the corner behind the curtain. The curtains were drawn at four and the bridge raised at six, creating a window of entry. The study was the first room inside the entrance. The sergeant concluded the intruder's main intent was burglary, with murder occurring when Douglas discovered him." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :bartholomewWilson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces C2 Means Column" ;
    ex:description "During the collaborative cipher analysis at 221B, Watson correctly identifies the meaning of the C2 notation after Holmes eliminates the chapter interpretation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The C2 in the cipher stands for 'Column 2,' not 'Chapter 2.'" ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "After Holmes demonstrated that chapter numbering would be redundant when a page number is given, Watson inferred that C must refer to a column on the page." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cipherMessage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :whitakersAlmanac ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_watson_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson Deduces the Cipher Book Is an Almanac" ;
    ex:description "Continuing the cipher analysis, Watson suggests the type of book after Holmes eliminates the Bible, Bradshaw, and the dictionary." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The cipher book is an almanac, a standardized common reference work fitting all the established criteria." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "With Bible eliminated for inconsistent pagination across editions, Bradshaw for limited vocabulary, and the dictionary for similar reasons, Watson identified an almanac as the remaining candidate matching all criteria: large, double-columned, standardized, and commonly possessed." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :cipherMessage ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :cipherMessage ;
    ex:confirmedBy :whitakersAlmanac ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_mason_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "White Mason Deduces the Murderer Was American" ;
    ex:description "After Holmes identifies the gun manufacturer, White Mason draws an inference about the killer's nationality from the American weapon." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The murderer was likely American, based on the American-made sawed-off shotgun, a weapon type associated with certain parts of America." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "The Pennsylvania Small Arms Company gun and the sawed-off shotgun design, known as a weapon used in some parts of America, provided evidence that the intruder who killed the master of the house was an American." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :whiteMason ;
    ex:deductionSubject :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sawedOffShotgun ;
    ex:confirmedBy :tedBaldwin ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_valleyOfFear_mason_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "White Mason's Comprehensive Theory: Outsider Assassination Through the Moat" ;
    ex:description "White Mason presents his full reconstruction of the crime to Holmes and MacDonald at the Manor House, systematically eliminating suicide and insider theories before settling on an outsider explanation." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Suicide is impossible due to the staged evidence. An insider crime is practically impossible given the one-minute window. Therefore an outsider entered between dusk and bridge-raising, hid behind the curtain, demanded the wedding ring, shot Douglas, dropped the V.V. card, and escaped through the window and moat." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "White Mason eliminated suicide by showing the staging would require the victim to fake his own murder scene. He eliminated insider action by demonstrating the impossibility of fabricating footmarks, opening the window, marking the sill, removing the ring, and staging the card in under one minute. The outsider theory fit the timing: entry between 4:30 and 6:00, hiding behind the curtain, a brief confrontation ending in murder, and escape through the moat." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "partially correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :whiteMason ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnDouglas ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :sawedOffShotgun, :vv341Card ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnDouglas ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_valleyOfFear_holmes_21 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :valleyOfFearDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Lion's Behavior Was Inconsistent With the Official Account" ;
    ex:description "While reviewing the Abbas Parva case with Watson at Baker Street, Holmes reconstructs the lion's movements and identifies a fundamental inconsistency in the accepted version of events." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The freed lion's behavior was illogical: it bounded forward to Ronder and struck him down, then instead of escaping returned to the woman near the cage and attacked her, which is inconsistent with natural animal behavior upon liberation." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned from the lion's perspective: a liberated animal would be expected to bound forward and escape, yet this lion struck Ronder down ten yards from the cage and then doubled back to attack Mrs. Ronder, who was close to the cage door. This unnatural return suggested the official account of a simple accident was wrong." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :saharaKing ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbasParvaIncident ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbasParvaInquest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies a Third Man's Voice During the Attack" ;
    ex:description "Continuing his review of the Abbas Parva evidence with Watson, Holmes recalls testimony indicating that a man's voice was heard shouting in terror at the moment of the attack, which could not have been Ronder." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "A third man was present during the attack, as at least two witnesses reported hearing a man shouting in terror mingled with the woman's screams, yet Ronder's skull was smashed and he could not have cried out." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that if Ronder's skull was crushed by the initial blow, he could hardly have shouted afterward. Yet at least two witnesses heard a man's cries mingled with the woman's screams, meaning a third person — neither Ronder nor Mrs. Ronder — was present at the scene and shouting in terror." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :leonardo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbasParvaInquest ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Fatal Flaw in Watson's Reconstruction" ;
    ex:description "After Watson proposes his own theory of events at Abbas Parva, Holmes identifies the single logical flaw that invalidates it." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Watson's reconstruction fails because if both Ronders were ten paces from the cage when the lion attacked, no one was at the cage to release the animal, meaning someone else must have let it loose." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson placed both Ronders ten yards from the cage at the moment the lion got loose, but Holmes pointed out that the cage door had to be opened by someone. If neither Ronder was near the cage, a third party must have released the lion, which Watson's theory did not account for." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :abbasParvaIncident ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :deduction_veiledLodger_watson_01 ;
    ex:confirmedBy :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Detects Mrs. Ronder's Suicidal Intent" ;
    ex:description "As Holmes and Watson rise to leave Mrs. Ronder's room after hearing her confession, Holmes detects something in her voice that reveals she is contemplating ending her own life." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Mrs. Ronder is contemplating suicide, as revealed by something in her voice and manner when she says the case is closed." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "When Mrs. Ronder echoed Holmes's words that the case was closed, something in her voice arrested Holmes's attention. He turned swiftly upon her and warned her that her life was not her own, indicating he had perceived suicidal intent from her tone and demeanor." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:confirmedBy :prussicAcidBottle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Sender of the Prussic Acid Bottle" ;
    ex:description "Two days after visiting Mrs. Ronder, Holmes receives a small blue bottle of prussic acid by post with an unsigned note, and he identifies the sender." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The prussic acid bottle sent to Baker Street with a note reading 'I send you my temptation. I will follow your advice' was sent by Eugenia Ronder, who has chosen to live." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes connected the anonymous package containing prussic acid and the message about following his advice to his recent conversation with Mrs. Ronder, in which he had urged her not to take her own life. The poison she had been keeping as her means of suicide was now surrendered." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :prussicAcidBottle ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_veiledLodger_watson_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Watson's Theory: Mrs. Ronder Fled Toward the Cage for Refuge" ;
    ex:description "During the discussion of the Abbas Parva case at Baker Street, Watson proposes his own reconstruction of the events, which Holmes calls brilliant but fatally flawed." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The Ronders were together ten yards from the cage when the lion escaped; Ronder turned to flee and was struck down; Mrs. Ronder ran toward the cage as her only refuge but was knocked over by the lion; her cries of 'Coward!' were directed at her husband for turning and provoking the beast instead of facing it." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson reasoned that Mrs. Ronder's only possible refuge from the loose lion was the cage itself. She ran for it but the beast overtook her. Her cries of 'Coward!' were explained as anger at her husband for turning to flee rather than standing his ground, since facing the lion together might have cowed it." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "incorrect" ;
    ex:deducedBy :johnWatson ;
    ex:deductionSubject :eugeniaRonder ;
    ex:deductionSubject :ronder ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :abbasParvaInquest ;
    ex:refutedBy :deduction_veiledLodger_holmes_03 ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :veiledLodgerDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_inspectorbaynes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Baynes Recovers the Note From the Dog-Grate" ;
    ex:description "Inspector Baynes produces the partially burned note that Garcia attempted to destroy in the fireplace at Wisteria Lodge, demonstrating his thorough examination of the crime scene." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Garcia failed to fully burn the note because he overpitched it into the dog-grate, and a pellet of paper survived unburned at the back." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Baynes conducted a meticulous search of Wisteria Lodge and noticed that the fireplace was a dog-grate. He reasoned that Garcia had thrown the note too far, overshooting the fire. He recovered the folded, discoloured scrap from the back of the grate where it had landed unburned." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBaynes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_inspectorbaynes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Baynes Identifies Henderson as Don Murillo, the Tiger of San Pedro" ;
    ex:description "When Holmes reveals he has been investigating Henderson of High Gable, Baynes discloses that he has independently identified Henderson's true identity through international tracing." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Henderson is Don Murillo, the deposed dictator of San Pedro known as the Tiger of San Pedro, who fled with the national treasury and has been hiding under an assumed identity since 1886." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Baynes traced Henderson's movements backward through Paris, Rome, and Madrid to Barcelona, where Murillo's ship arrived in 1886 after his escape from San Pedro. He connected the San Pedro national colours — green and white — to the colour references in the note found at Wisteria Lodge, confirming the link between Henderson and the San Pedro conspiracy." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBaynes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :donMurillo ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_inspectorbaynes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Baynes's Strategy: Arrest the Cook as a Decoy to Lure Henderson Into Flight" ;
    ex:description "After Holmes expresses surprise at Baynes's arrest of the mulatto cook, Baynes reveals it was a deliberate tactical deception rather than a genuine theory about the murderer." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Baynes deliberately arrested the wrong man — the mulatto cook — to make Henderson believe police attention had shifted away from him, thereby inducing Henderson to feel safe enough to flee and expose Miss Burnet." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Baynes was certain Henderson felt he was under suspicion and would lie low as long as he believed he was in danger. By publicly arresting the mulatto cook as the supposed murderer, Baynes created the appearance that the investigation had concluded. He expected Henderson would then attempt to leave, giving Baynes access to Miss Burnet as a witness. Baynes had stationed a plain-clothes man at the station all week to track Henderson's movements." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :inspectorBaynes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :donMurillo ;
    ex:deductionSubject :missBurnet ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :arrestOfMulattoCook ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_01 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Telegram Sender Is a Man" ;
    ex:description "Upon receiving a telegram signed 'Scott Eccles' from Charing Cross Post Office, Watson asks whether the sender is a man or woman. Holmes answers immediately based on the method of communication." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 1 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The telegram sender is a man, because no woman would send a reply-paid telegram — she would have come in person." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the message was sent as a reply-paid telegram and reasoned that a woman seeking consultation would come in person rather than use this impersonal method, concluding the sender must be male." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_02 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Eccles's Disturbance Dates From Waking" ;
    ex:description "When Scott Eccles arrives at 221B Baker Street, Holmes observes his disheveled appearance and deduces the timing and nature of his distress before Eccles explains anything." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 2 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Scott Eccles's disturbance dates from the moment of his waking, as evidenced by his unbrushed hair, unshaven chin, dress boots, and waistcoat buttoned awry." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes noted that Eccles's telegram was sent at about one o'clock but he did not arrive until quarter-past two. Observing that Eccles's toilet and attire were completely neglected — unbrushed hair, unshaven chin, dress boots, waistcoat buttoned awry — Holmes concluded the disturbance began the moment Eccles woke and that he had been too agitated to attend to his appearance." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:confirmedBy :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_03 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Garcia Used Eccles as an Alibi" ;
    ex:description "After hearing Eccles's account and the inspectors' report of Garcia's murder, Holmes reconstructs Garcia's motive for inviting the respectable Englishman to stay overnight at Wisteria Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 3 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Garcia deliberately cultivated Eccles's friendship and invited him to stay the night to use him as an alibi witness for a criminal enterprise planned for that evening." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the sudden, forced friendship between Garcia and the conventional Eccles was unnatural — Eccles had no charm or intelligence to attract a quick-witted Spaniard. His one outstanding quality was his air of unimpeachable British respectability, making him the ideal witness. Garcia told Eccles it was one o'clock when it was likely earlier, and Garcia's nocturnal visit to Eccles's room was to establish that Eccles could testify Garcia was home. Only a man planning a criminal enterprise would need such an alibi." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aloysiusGarcia ;
    ex:deductionSubject :johnScottEccles ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_04 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Seal as a Sleeve-Link and Scissors as Bent Nail Scissors" ;
    ex:description "After Inspector Baynes presents the recovered note to Garcia and describes its physical characteristics, Holmes adds further observations about the seal and the cutting instrument." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 4 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The oval seal on the note is a plain sleeve-link, and the paper was cut with bent nail scissors." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes observed that the oval seal impression could only have been made by a plain sleeve-link, as no other common object has that precise shape. He also noted that the two short snips cutting the quarter-sheet of paper both showed the same slight curve, characteristic of bent nail scissors." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_05 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces Garcia's Servants Were Confederates, Not Murderers" ;
    ex:description "After the inspectors leave 221B, Holmes discusses the case with Watson and rejects the theory that Garcia's servants killed him, reasoning instead that they were co-conspirators who fled according to a contingency plan." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 5 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "Garcia's servants were his confederates in a planned criminal enterprise, not his murderers. Their disappearance was a prearranged escape triggered by Garcia's failure to return." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes pointed out that it would be strange for servants conspiring against their master to attack him on the one night he had a guest, when they had him alone every other night. Instead, he reasoned that the servants were confederates in Garcia's enterprise. If Garcia returned safely, Eccles's testimony would provide cover. If Garcia did not return by a certain hour, it meant his life had been sacrificed, and the servants were to flee to a prearranged spot to escape investigation and potentially renew the attempt." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :aloysiusGarcia ;
    ex:deductionSubject :jose ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_06 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Is Navigation Instructions for a Large House Near Oxshott" ;
    ex:description "Holmes interprets the cryptic note recovered from Garcia's fireplace, breaking down its coded directions and connecting them to the geography around Wisteria Lodge." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 6 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The note contains navigation instructions through a large house — 'green and white' are signal colours, 'main stair, first corridor, seventh right, green baize' are directions to a specific room — and the target house must be within a mile or two of Oxshott." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes parsed the note systematically: 'green and white' suggested signal colours (like racing), 'green open, white shut' was clearly a signal system, and 'main stair, first corridor, seventh right, green baize' described a route through a very large house with numbered corridors. Since Garcia was walking toward Oxshott and needed to return to Wisteria Lodge before one o'clock to use his alibi, the house could not be more than a mile or two away. Holmes obtained a list of large houses near Oxshott from the land agents." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:deductionSubject :highGable ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_07 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies Giant Footprints Outside the Window" ;
    ex:description "At Wisteria Lodge, after Constable Walters describes a terrifying face at the window, Holmes examines the grass bed outside with his pocket lantern." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 7 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The intruder who appeared at the window wore a size twelve shoe and was likely a giant in proportion to his foot size." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the grass bed beneath the window with his pocket lantern and identified footprints from a number twelve shoe. He reasoned that if the intruder's body was in proportion to his feet, he must have been a very large man. He also traced the intruder's path through the broken shrubbery toward the road." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "unverified" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_08 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies the Charred Bones as a Lamb or Kid" ;
    ex:description "When Inspector Baynes shows Holmes the charred bone fragments raked from the kitchen fire at Wisteria Lodge, Holmes identifies their origin." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 8 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The charred bones found in the kitchen fire are from a lamb or kid, not a human." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes examined the platter of small charred bone pieces that Baynes had recovered from the fire. Based on their size and characteristics, he identified them as the remains of a lamb or kid. This assessment was consistent with the doctor's earlier determination that the bones were not human." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :charredBones ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :charredBones ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_09 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Note Writer Is English, Not Spanish" ;
    ex:description "When Watson suggests 'D' in the note stands for 'Dolores,' a common Spanish name, Holmes rejects the theory based on the language of the note itself." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 9 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The writer of the note to Garcia is English, not Spanish, because a Spaniard would write to a Spaniard in Spanish, yet the note is in English." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Watson proposed that 'D' stood for Dolores, a common female name in Spain, since Garcia was a Spaniard. Holmes praised the suggestion but called it inadmissible, reasoning that a Spaniard writing to a fellow Spaniard would naturally use Spanish. Since the note was written entirely in English, the author must be English." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_10 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Identifies High Gable and Henderson as the Target" ;
    ex:description "During his retrospective explanation to Watson at the Bull inn, Holmes reveals the results of his days of investigation around Esher and Oxshott, identifying the specific large house and its suspicious occupant." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 10 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "High Gable, home of the reclusive Mr. Henderson, is the house referenced in the note. Henderson is a foreigner or long-time tropical resident surrounded by suspicious secrecy, and Miss Burnet the governess is the note's author and Garcia's confederate." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes limited the large houses near Oxshott using the land agents' list, then spent days conducting reconnaissance disguised as botanical rambles and cultivating village gossip. Only High Gable, a Jacobean grange less than half a mile from the murder scene, housed people to whom curious adventures might befall. Henderson was a fierce, masterful foreigner who never walked alone, whose household was segregated and secretive, and whose servants said he was terribly afraid of something. Miss Burnet, the English governess aged about forty, was the only English woman in the household, matching the note's English handwriting. Her age ruled out a romantic motive." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :highGable ;
    ex:deductionSubject :donMurillo ;
    ex:deductionSubject :missBurnet ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :noteToGarcia, :johnWarner ;
    ex:confirmedBy :missBurnet ;
    ex:memberOfOntology ex:SherlockOntology ;
    dc:source :wisteriaLodgeDoc .

:deduction_wisteriaLodge_holmes_11 a ex:Deduction ;
    ex:prefLabel "Holmes Deduces the Cook Returned for the Voodoo Fetish" ;
    ex:description "In the final retrospective discussion, Watson asks why the mulatto cook returned to Wisteria Lodge. Holmes explains the cook's motive based on the strange creature found in the kitchen." ;
    ex:deductionSequence 11 ;
    ex:deductionSummary "The mulatto cook returned to Wisteria Lodge to retrieve the voodoo fetish he had been forced to leave behind when he and his companion fled." ;
    ex:deductionReasoning "Holmes reasoned that the strange mummified creature found in the kitchen was the cook's religious fetish. When the cook and his companion fled to their prearranged retreat, the companion persuaded him to leave the compromising article behind. But the cook's devotion to his fetish drove him back the next day, where he saw Constable Walters through the window. He waited three more days before trying again, walking into Baynes's ambush. Holmes confirmed the voodoo context through research at the British Museum." ;
    ex:deductionOutcome "correct" ;
    ex:deducedBy :sherlockHolmes ;
    ex:deductionSubject :voodooFetish ;
    ex:deductionBasedOn :voodooFetish, :voodooismBook, :arrestOfMulattoCook ;
