This story presents a fascinating case for the critic: it contains some of the finest things in the entire canon — the "BALLARAT" revelation is one of Doyle's most elegant deductive strokes, Watson's portrait of Holmes on the scent is unforgettable, and Turner's confession is arguably the most emotionally powerful passage Doyle ever wrote in short fiction. Yet the whole edifice rests on a coincidence so astronomical — that a former highway robber's one living victim would happen to follow him from the Australian goldfields to a quiet corner of Herefordshire — that the plot cannot survive a moment's rational scrutiny. It is, in miniature, the paradox of Doyle's art: the surface brilliance is so compelling that one forgives the structural impossibility beneath it.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The opening paragraph of "The Boscombe Valley Mystery" is a small domestic triumph that has received less attention than it deserves. Watson is at breakfast with his wife; a telegram arrives from Holmes proposing a trip to the West Country with the breezy enticement that "air and scenery perfect"; and Mrs. Watson, with the serene practicality of a woman who has taken the full measure of her husband, dispatches him at once, observing that he has been looking pale and that Anstruther can manage his patients. The comedy is quiet but exact. Watson is a man whose marriage exists in cheerful subordination to his friendship, and Doyle captures this with a single exchange that tells us more about the Watsonian household than any amount of exposition could supply. The railway journey that follows — Holmes rummaging through papers, rolling them into a gigantic ball and tossing them onto the rack, then pulling out his pocket Petrarch and refusing another word until Swindon — is a vignette of companionable silence that belongs among the finest things in the canon.
The tale's central deductive sequence, the deciphering of the dying man's last word, is justly celebrated and demonstrates Doyle's narrative ingenuity at its most economical. The son hears his father mumble something about "a rat"; Holmes produces a map of Victoria, covers the first syllables, and reveals "BALLARAT" — the murdered man was naming his killer's origin, not raving about vermin. It is a moment of genuine surprise and elegance, and one notes with admiration how Doyle has planted the Australian connection throughout the preceding pages so that the revelation feels at once unexpected and inevitable. The complementary analysis of footprints at the pool — the tiptoe tracks of unusual square-toed boots, the left-handed blow struck from behind, the Indian cigar smoked behind a beech tree — displays Holmes's method at its most persuasive, and Watson's description of the detective transformed upon the scent, his nostrils dilating "with a purely animal lust for the chase," is one of the most physically vivid portraits in all the stories.
Yet the tale rests upon a coincidence so extravagant that it very nearly collapses the edifice. We are asked to accept that a former Australian highway robber, having migrated to England, purchased an estate in Herefordshire, and settled into respectable life, is discovered there by the one man on earth who had witnessed his crime — a wagon-driver whom he held at gunpoint decades earlier in the goldfields — and that this man, McCarthy, has followed him across the globe for the sole purpose of blackmail. The odds against this encounter would stagger an actuary, and Doyle makes no effort whatever to render them plausible. Turner simply bumps into McCarthy in Regent Street, and the parasitic relationship commences. One would think that a man wishing to escape his past might at least have chosen a county where former Australian wagon-drivers were less likely to turn up at the local race-meetings. The coincidence is the engine of the entire plot, and the plot does not survive its examination.
What saves the story, and what elevates it to the first rank of the Holmes tales, is Turner's confession — a passage of sustained moral power that is perhaps the finest thing Doyle ever wrote in the short form. The dying man's account of his youthful wildness, his slow reformation through the love of his daughter, and his agonised recognition that McCarthy's blackmail threatened to drag his child into the same moral swamp from which he had spent a lifetime climbing, is rendered with an emotional directness that transcends the requirements of the detective plot entirely. Holmes's response — "I pray that we may never be exposed to such a temptation" — and his subsequent invocation of Baxter's famous remark, "There, but for the grace of God, goes Sherlock Holmes," reveal a depth of moral sympathy in the detective that the pyrotechnics of deduction ordinarily conceal. The final image of Turner, "tottering and shaking in all his giant frame," stumbling from the room, achieves a pathos worthy of Hardy. It is in passages such as these that one glimpses the writer Doyle might have been had he not been so thoroughly, and so profitably, claimed by Baker Street.
""" .

