This is one of the great Holmes stories, and the review reflects that — the fog-shrouded opening is among the finest atmospheric prose Doyle ever wrote, the portrait of Mycroft as the human clearinghouse of empire is a masterstroke of political imagination, and the body-on-the-roof deduction is mechanically superb. The comical flaw lies in poor Cadogan West's decision to pursue a dangerous criminal alone across London in impenetrable fog rather than simply raising an alarm — a choice that requires the patriotic young clerk to behave with the reckless stupidity of a man in a penny dreadful. The review also highlights the rare moment of tenderness between Holmes and Watson before the burglary, which is among the most emotionally revealing passages in the entire canon.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
""The Bruce-Partington Plans" opens with what is very possibly the finest sustained passage of atmospheric prose in the entire Holmes canon: four days of impenetrable yellow fog enveloping London, the greasy brown swirl drifting past the Baker Street windows and condensing in oily drops upon the panes, while Holmes paces the sitting-room biting his nails and chafing against the inaction that is poison to his temperament. His meditation on what a criminal might accomplish in such weather — roaming London "as the tiger does the jungle, unseen until he pounces" — culminates in the magnificently sinister observation, "It is fortunate for this community that I am not a criminal." Then the telegram from Mycroft, which Holmes receives with the astonishment of a man encountering a tram-car in a country lane — for Mycroft, that great sedentary planet, never deviates from his orbit between Pall Mall, the Diogenes Club, and Whitehall. Doyle is working here with an atmospheric intensity and a comic precision that are mutually reinforcing, and the result is an opening that can stand comparison with the finest pages of Stevenson's London fiction.
The portrait of Mycroft Holmes is the tale's most enduring contribution to the mythology, and it is drawn with a brilliance that reveals Doyle's capacity for political imagination. The elder Holmes is presented as nothing less than a human clearinghouse for the British government — a man of four hundred and fifty pounds a year, without ambition or title, who is nevertheless the one indispensable mind in the empire, the only intelligence capable of seeing how the Navy, India, Canada, and the bimetallic question bear simultaneously upon one another. The physical description is superb: the gross, unwieldy body surmounted by a head "so masterful in its brow, so alert in its steel-gray, deep-set eyes" that after the first glance one forgets everything below the neck. It is a portrait of pure cerebration embodied, and one suspects that Doyle, in creating Mycroft, was imagining what Sherlock Holmes might have become had the restless energy been replaced by perfect inertia — the same omnivorous analytical power, but content to sit in an armchair and let others do the legwork. The comedy of Mycroft "absolutely and indignantly" declining to climb the railings at Oberstein's house is a touch worthy of the finest character novelists.
The mechanism of the mystery — the body placed on the roof of an Underground carriage from a window overlooking the track, then jolted off at the points near Aldgate — is among Doyle's most ingenious inventions, and the deduction is presented with admirable clarity. Holmes's chain of reasoning, from the absence of blood on the line to the absence of a ticket to the location near a junction where trains sway on the points, has a satisfying cumulative logic that few of the stories can match. Yet the tale asks the reader to swallow one considerable absurdity: that young Cadogan West, having spotted the thief entering the Woolwich office on a night of dense fog when one "could not see three yards," elected to follow him silently to Kensington rather than raise an alarm, alert a watchman, or simply shout. He is a clerk at an arsenal, not a trained agent, and his decision to pursue a dangerous criminal alone across London in impenetrable fog, abandoning his fiancée without a word of explanation, strains the bounds of what heroic patriotism can plausibly explain. West's nobility requires his foolishness, and Doyle, as is his custom, asks us not to notice.
What gives the story its weight, however, and what lifts it above the level of even the best detective puzzles, is the sustained note of moral gravity that accompanies the espionage plot. The death of Sir James Walter, broken by the scandal before the truth is known; the wretched Colonel Valentine, ruined by a Stock Exchange debt and drawn into treason; the grieving fiancée who begs Holmes to save her dead lover's honour; and above all the sense, conveyed through Mycroft's agitation and the references to the Prime Minister, the Admiralty, and "the very highest quarter," that the fate of nations rests upon the solution — all this gives the narrative a seriousness that the drawing-room mysteries of the earlier collections never quite achieve. The closing image — Holmes returning from Windsor with an emerald tie-pin, a gift from a lady whose "august name" Watson decorously declines to mention — is the perfect final chord: understated, wryly monarchical, and tinged with the awareness that in this case the private detective has been, however briefly, a servant of the Crown. It is Watson at his best, and there is a quiet moment earlier, when Holmes sees "something in his eyes which was nearer to tenderness than I had ever seen," that suggests Doyle understood the emotional depths of his own creation better than he is sometimes given credit for.
""" .

