    ex:reviewersNotes """
This is, I think, the most extraordinary story in the entire canon — and the most difficult to write about, because its power lies almost entirely outside the detective machinery. The mystery is solved over lunch; what remains is Jim Browner's confession, which is domestic tragedy of a quality that would not disgrace Hardy. The comical flaw is Lestrade's wonderfully oblivious letter claiming he always thought it was "an extremely simple one" and thanking Holmes for his assistance — a moment of police vanity so perfectly timed that Holmes reads it aloud with audible relish. But what truly distinguishes the tale is Holmes's closing question about the purpose of human suffering — the only moment in the stories where the great rationalist admits that reason has reached its limit. Doyle suppressed the story, then restored it; the review argues he was right both times.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
""The Cardboard Box" is the darkest tale in the Holmes canon, and its darkness is of a kind that the detective story, as a form, is peculiarly ill-equipped to contain. The mystery itself is solved with almost indecent swiftness — Holmes identifies the killer, the motive, and the method during what amounts to an afternoon's excursion to Croydon, pausing only for a pleasant lunch at which he discourses on Paganini and his bargain Stradivarius — and the tale's real weight falls not upon the detection but upon the extraordinary confession of Jim Browner, the ship's steward who has murdered his wife and her lover and posted their severed ears to his sister-in-law. Doyle recognised, one suspects, that he had produced something that exceeded the tolerances of his chosen genre, for the story was suppressed from the Memoirs and its celebrated opening thought-reading scene was transplanted to "The Resident Patient" like an organ salvaged from a body the author preferred to bury. The suppression was understandable; the story is genuinely harrowing. But it was also a loss, for "The Cardboard Box" contains some of Doyle's finest and most unsettling prose.
The opening is among the most accomplished in the series: a blazing August day, Baker Street like an oven, the yellow brickwork painful to the eye, Holmes curled upon the sofa while Watson falls into a reverie about the American Civil War. The thought-reading sequence that follows — Holmes tracing Watson's wandering mind from General Gordon's portrait to Henry Ward Beecher's, thence to the Civil War, the gallantry, the waste, and finally the absurdity of settling disputes by violence — is a virtuoso set-piece, justly famous, and its placement at the head of this particular tale is no accident. The observation that war is a preposterous way of resolving conflict prepares the ground, with quiet structural cunning, for a story about a man who resolves his domestic anguish with an oak stick and a knife in a rowing boat off New Brighton. The grand futility and the squalid futility mirror one another, and Holmes's closing meditation — "What object is served by this circle of misery and violence and fear?" — returns us to the theme with a solemnity that the detective story almost never attempts.
Browner's confession, which occupies the final quarter of the tale and is presented as a verbatim statement, is a passage of remarkable psychological realism that transcends anything else in the Holmes stories. The steward's account of his happy marriage, its slow poisoning by the jealous Sarah, his return to drink, and the terrible moment when he sees a light of welcome on his wife's face that fades to disappointment when she realises it is only him — this is domestic tragedy rendered with a compression and emotional precision that would not disgrace Hardy or George Moore. The pursuit to New Brighton, the hired boat, the haze closing like a curtain around the three of them, and that unforgettable image of the lovers' faces as they see who is rowing towards them — Doyle achieves here a pitch of horror that owes nothing to the supernatural and everything to the simple recognition of what human beings are capable of doing to one another. One notes, too, the comical inadequacy of Lestrade's letter, in which he blandly claims that "the affair proves, as I always thought it would, to be an extremely simple one," and thanks Holmes for "assisting" in the investigation — a touch of police vanity so perfectly judged that Holmes cannot resist reading it aloud with editorial commentary.
What makes the story finally remarkable, however, is its refusal to offer the consolation that detective fiction conventionally provides. The crime is solved, the criminal is caught, but nothing is restored. The victims are dead, the murderer is already destroyed by his own conscience, and the wretched Sarah Cushing lies in brain fever, confronting the consequences of her malice. Holmes, who in other tales releases criminals with a brisk word of mercy or a pragmatic shrug, can do nothing here but sit in silence and ask the unanswerable question: what purpose does such suffering serve? It is the only moment in the canon when the great rationalist confesses that reason itself has reached its limit, and the passage has a gravity — an almost theological gravity — that Doyle never approached again. That he chose to suppress the story suggests he understood, perhaps uneasily, that he had written something that did not quite belong in the world of Baker Street; that he later restored it suggests he knew, equally well, that it was too good to lose.
""" .

:caseOfIdentityDoc 
