This is one of the lesser Holmes stories in terms of mystery, but it's rich territory for a critic. The comical flaw is truly spectacular: the entire plot depends on a woman failing to recognise her own stepfather — a man five years her senior who lives in her house — despite multiple walks, parlour visits, and a journey to a church, all because he has put on whiskers and spectacles. No degree of myopia can plausibly explain this. But what makes the story most interesting for criticism is its unexpectedly dark conclusion: Holmes solves the case, discovers there is no legal remedy, decides not to tell the victim the truth, and walks away — leaving Miss Sutherland to spend years waiting for a phantom lover while her stepfather continues to pocket her income. For a tale that opens with flying false teeth, it ends in a remarkably cold place.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
""A Case of Identity" is a slight tale by the standard of the Holmes canon, and it knows it. Holmes himself dismisses the problem as "rather a trite one," citing parallel cases in Andover in '77 and The Hague the previous year, and one suspects that Doyle, having conceived an ingenious but essentially simple deception, understood that the story's interest would have to reside elsewhere than in its mystery. And so it does. The opening conversation between Holmes and Watson — a small essay on the superiority of life to fiction — is among the wittiest passages Doyle ever wrote, culminating in the magnificent revelation that the Dundas separation case, which Watson has dismissed as the most predictable of domestic brutalities, involved a teetotalling husband whose offence consisted entirely in "winding up every meal by taking out his false teeth and hurling them at his wife." It is a joke worthy of Dickens at his most exuberant, and it establishes the tone of genial absurdity that carries the reader through a plot which might otherwise feel thin. The image of Holmes offering Watson snuff from a gold box set with amethyst — a souvenir from the King of Bohemia — while discoursing on the inexhaustibility of human strangeness, is a vignette of pure comic pleasure.
The portrait of Miss Mary Sutherland is the story's real achievement, and it is drawn with a sympathy that Doyle does not always extend to his female clients. She arrives oscillating on the pavement, plunges across the street "as of the swimmer who leaves the bank," and looms behind the page-boy "like a full-sailed merchant-man behind a tiny pilot boat" — three similes in rapid succession, each more vivid than the last, composing a portrait of nervous determination that is both comic and genuinely touching. Her account of the courtship — the gasfitters' ball, the shy gentleman with tinted glasses and a whispering voice, the meetings only when the stepfather was conveniently in France, the typewritten love letters with their typewritten signatures — is narrated in a voice so artlessly trusting that the reader grasps the deception long before Holmes pronounces upon it, and yet cannot help feeling the pathos of a woman whose innocence is being exploited by the very people charged with her protection. Watson's observation, after her departure, that "for all the preposterous hat and the vacuous face, there was something noble in the simple faith of our visitor which compelled our respect," is one of the most generous sentences in the canon.
The comical flaw of the story — and it is a very considerable one — is that the entire scheme depends upon Miss Sutherland's inability to recognise her own stepfather at a distance of approximately eighteen inches. He is, we are told, only five years her senior. He lives in her house. She sees him daily. Yet the addition of tinted spectacles, bushy whiskers, and a whispering voice renders him completely unrecognisable to her over the course of multiple walks, multiple visits to her parlour, an engagement, and a journey to the very door of a church. Her short-sightedness is offered as mitigation, but one feels that a degree of myopia sufficient to explain such a failure of recognition would leave its sufferer unable to cross a London street without assistance, let alone operate a typewriter at twopence a sheet. The disguise is the structural foundation upon which the entire plot rests, and it will not bear the weight of a moment's reflection.
What lingers in the mind after the plot has been dismissed is the story's troubling moral conclusion, which is darker than its comic surface would suggest. Holmes identifies the villain, confronts him, and is met with a cold sneer: "It is you who are breaking the law now, and not me." The scoundrel is right. There is no legal remedy for what Windibank has done, and Holmes can only reach for a hunting crop before the man flees down the stairs. More disturbing still is Holmes's decision not to tell Miss Sutherland the truth, on the ground that she would not believe him — invoking, with a flourish of oriental fatalism, the Persian proverb about the danger of snatching a delusion from a woman. It is an oddly callous conclusion. The woman will go on waiting for a lover who does not exist, while the man who invented him continues to collect her income, and the great detective, having solved the case, washes his hands of the human wreckage. Holmes predicts that Windibank will "rise from crime to crime until he does something very bad, and ends on a gallows," but offers no protection to the woman who stands most immediately in his path. The story's final note is not resolution but resignation, and it leaves an aftertaste considerably more bitter than the gasfitters' ball and the flying false teeth had prepared us to expect.
""" .

:copperBeechesDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This is a richly layered story for criticism. The comical flaw is structurally devastating: Holmes deduces the entire mystery correctly, races to Hampshire to liberate the imprisoned daughter — and arrives to find she has already escaped through a skylight, rescued by her own fiancé and a bribed housekeeper who then explains everything in a few plain sentences. The great detective has been rendered entirely superfluous. But what redeems the tale magnificently is Holmes's speech about the hidden wickedness of the English countryside — a passage of social insight that anticipates the darker recognitions of twentieth-century rural fiction and gives the story a subject far more interesting than its locked-room mechanics. The portrait of Rucastle, charming and monstrous by turns, is among Doyle's finest villains, and the detail of the cockroach-killing child as a mirror of paternal cruelty is characteristically unsettling.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Copper Beeches" opens with an exchange between Holmes and Watson about the nature of sensational writing that amounts to a brief but pointed essay on the aesthetics of the detective story. Holmes accuses Watson of having "degraded what should have been a course of lectures into a series of tales"; Watson retorts, with unusual coldness, that he has done his friend full justice. The quarrel is resolved only by a telegram from Miss Violet Hunter — who arrives, freckled like a plover's egg, brisk and self-possessed, to consult Holmes about a governess position of such surpassing strangeness that Holmes's professional boredom evaporates on the instant. The irony of this opening is delicious: Holmes has just finished complaining that Watson puts too much colour and life into his narratives, and the very next scene introduces one of the most vividly coloured clients in the canon, offering a tale that will prove to be almost nothing but sensation. Doyle is gently mocking his own creation, and the result is one of the most enjoyable openings in the series.
The portrait of Jephro Rucastle is Doyle's most accomplished study in villainy, and it succeeds precisely because the villain is, for the greater part of the story, entirely charming. The prodigiously stout man with his folding chin, his shining slit-eyes, and his overflowing geniality — crying "Tut, tut! Sweating — rank sweating!" when Miss Hunter mentions her previous salary, enthusing over his son's talent for killing cockroaches ("Smack! smack! smack! Three gone before you could wink!") — is rendered with a comic exuberance that makes his menace all the more effective when it finally surfaces. The moment when the genial smile hardens into a grin of demonic rage and he threatens to throw the governess to his mastiff is electrifying because it has been so meticulously prepared by everything that preceded it. One notices, too, the sinister acuity of Doyle's observation that the child's cruelty — his planning of the capture of mice, birds, and insects, his pleasure in the pain of creatures weaker than himself — is a mirror of the father's character, a point Holmes makes explicit with characteristic unsentimental precision.
The tale harbours, however, a structural absurdity of a high order. Holmes is summoned to Winchester, hears Miss Hunter's account, and deduces — correctly and almost instantly — that she has been hired to impersonate a prisoner held in the locked wing of the house: the daughter, Alice Rucastle, whose hair has been cut in illness, whose fiancé stands in the road watching the window, and whose inheritance her father means to control. This is well enough. But when Holmes, Watson, and Miss Hunter arrive at the Copper Beeches to liberate the captive, they discover that Alice has already escaped through the skylight with the help of Mrs. Toller and the faithful Mr. Fowler, who has bribed the servants and fetched a ladder. The detective, in short, has been rendered entirely superfluous. The prisoner has been rescued by her own suitor, operating independently and with considerably more practical efficiency than the great Sherlock Holmes, who arrives only in time to be chased by a mastiff and to hear the housekeeper explain the whole business in a few plain sentences. It is Mrs. Toller, not Holmes, who solves the case; and Holmes, with unusual candour, admits as much.
Yet the story transcends its mechanical deficiencies through the remarkable speech Holmes delivers on the train to Winchester — a passage that may be the most psychologically revealing in the canon. Watson rhapsodises about the beauty of the Hampshire countryside; Holmes replies that the scattered farmsteads fill him with horror, for there is no place where crime may be committed with greater impunity than in the smiling English country. The pressure of public opinion, he observes, does in the town what the law cannot accomplish: a scream, a blow, a cry for help will bring neighbours and police. But in the isolation of these pretty houses, "the deeds of hellish cruelty, the hidden wickedness which may go on, year in, year out" need never reach the light. It is a passage of extraordinary social perception, anticipating by decades the darker recognitions of rural fiction, and it gives the tale its real subject: not the mystery of the locked wing but the mystery of what genteel English domesticity may conceal behind its copper beeches and its clumps of flowers. That Watson notes, with quiet disappointment, that Holmes manifested no further interest in the admirable Miss Hunter once the case was closed only deepens the melancholy. The great detective can see through the walls of country houses, but he cannot see past his own indifference to the human beings who inhabit them.
""" .

:creepingManDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This is a fascinating late-canon story to examine — one whose parts are wildly at war with one another. The opening is superb (Watson's "whetstone for his mind" passage is the most psychologically honest account of the partnership he ever wrote), and the Gothic horror scenes are genuinely effective: the professor crawling down a darkened passage, his face at the moonlit window, the bat-like figure scaling his own house in a dressing gown. But the revelation — monkey-gland injections from a Prague rejuvenation quack — is not so much a comical flaw as a catastrophic one that retroactively demolishes the carefully built atmosphere. The crawling man was frightening; the crawling monkey-man is merely ridiculous. What saves the tale from total ruin is Holmes's closing meditation on the dystopian implications of rejuvenation science — a passage of startling prescience trapped inside a potboiler about simian serum, which is itself perhaps the deepest comedy in the story.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Creeping Man" belongs to the late period of the Holmes canon, and it shows. There is about the story the unmistakable air of a writer who has long since exhausted his affection for his own creation and is now rummaging in the lumber room of popular science for materials that the earlier, surer hand would have disdained. Yet the tale opens magnificently. Watson's account of his late-period role in the partnership — "I was a whetstone for his mind," his remarks "would have been as appropriately addressed to his bedstead," his methodical slowness serving only to make Holmes's flame-like intuitions flash more vividly — is the most candid and psychologically acute description of their relationship that Watson ever committed to paper. It is a portrait of companionable inequality rendered without self-pity and with a kind of melancholy dignity, and it deserves a better story than the one that follows it. Holmes's summons — "Come at once if convenient — if inconvenient come all the same" — is deservedly among the most quoted lines in the canon, and the opening meditation on dogs as mirrors of their owners' characters is vintage Baker Street philosophising, witty and just fanciful enough to sustain the reader's faith.
The narrative builds its atmosphere with genuine skill. Bennett's account of the professor crawling down a darkened passage on hands and feet, face sunk between his hands, moving with horrible ease — and then springing erect and spitting an atrocious word before vanishing down the stairs — is one of the most effectively uncanny scenes Doyle ever wrote. Edith Presbury's testimony is finer still: her father's face pressed against her second-floor window in the moonlight, one hand raised as if to push up the sash, while she lies paralysed below. This is pure Gothic horror, and it achieves its effect precisely because no explanation is yet available; the reader experiences the daughter's terror without mediation. The stakeout scene, too, is powerfully rendered: the professor crouching and skipping across the moonlit drive, then ascending the ivy-covered wall of his own house "sure of foot and firm of grasp," his dressing-gown flapping on either side like the wings of some huge bat — and then, in a scene of calculated nastiness, squatting before the chained wolfhound and goading it with pebbles and a stick, flicking his hands inches from the maddened animal's jaws. It is a portrait of cruelty performed for its own pleasure, and it gains its power from our knowledge that this is not merely a villain but a distinguished physiologist who has done this to himself.
The flaw is not comical but catastrophic, and it resides in the revelation itself. After this careful and genuinely disturbing buildup, we are asked to believe that Professor Presbury has been injecting himself with the serum of a black-faced langur monkey — obtained from an obscure Prague rejuvenation specialist named Lowenstein — in the hope of making himself young enough to win a girl, and that this serum has caused him, at nine-day intervals, to crawl on all fours, scale walls, torment dogs, and peer into his daughter's bedroom window. The explanation belongs not to the detective story but to the penny dreadful, and not to the better class of penny dreadful at that. One might accept the premise in a frankly fantastical tale — Stevenson's Hyde, after all, operates on similar ground — but Doyle presents it within the framework of rational detection, asking Holmes to deduce the monkey serum from thickened knuckles and a nine-day cycle, and the result is an absurdity so thoroughgoing that it retroactively diminishes the horror of everything that preceded it. The crawling man was frightening; the crawling monkey-man is merely ridiculous.
What redeems the story from total failure is Holmes's closing speech, which is one of the most remarkable passages in the late canon and suggests that Doyle, whatever his weariness with the detective formula, had lost none of his capacity for moral imagination. If the science of rejuvenation were to succeed, Holmes observes, it would be "the material, the sensual, the worldly" who would prolong their worthless lives, while "the spiritual would not avoid the call to something higher. It would be the survival of the least fit. What sort of cesspool may not our poor world become?" It is a meditation that anticipates, with startling prescience, the anxieties of the century to come — the fear that technological mastery over nature will serve not wisdom but appetite, not the best of humanity but the worst. That this reflection arises from a tale about monkey glands is itself a kind of comedy, and perhaps a deeper one than Doyle intended. The prophet is trapped inside a potboiler, and we catch only a glimpse of him before Holmes springs from his chair, declares the case closed, and suggests that there is just time for a cup of tea before the early train.
