    ex:reviewersNotes """
This is one of the finest stories in the Memoirs, and it rewards close attention. The opening — Holmes arriving uninvited at Watson's married home at quarter to twelve, delivering a fusillade of deductions while asking for a bed — is a small masterpiece of comic affection, a scene about the irresistible pull of the old partnership. The Biblical allusion ("David" = King David = the man who sent Uriah to his death) is the tale's most elegant stroke, giving the locked-room puzzle a moral dimension that transcends its mechanics. The comical flaw is the mongoose named Teddy, whose escape during the fatal confrontation sends it scrambling up a curtain after a caged canary — an incongruity so perfect that the story's emotional climax and its zoological sideshow are essentially competing for the reader's attention, and one cannot quite tell whether Doyle noticed. But the portrait of Colonel Barclay's thirty years of conscience — the inexplicable gloom, the dread of darkness, the smile struck from his face as if by an invisible hand — is among the most penetrating psychological studies in the canon, achieved almost entirely through retrospective detail.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Crooked Man" begins with one of the most perfectly judged domestic openings in the Holmes canon: Watson nodding over a novel by his own hearth, his wife already upstairs, the servants retired, when the clang of the bell at a quarter to twelve brings not a patient but Sherlock Holmes himself, erupting into married life with a volley of deductions — the Arcadia mixture, the handkerchief in the sleeve, the workman's nail-marks on the linoleum — that crackle with the energy of a man who has come to reclaim his companion from domesticity. Holmes's request to stay the night is outwardly casual but structurally purposeful: it restores, for one evening, the old Baker Street intimacy of two men smoking pipes and talking through a problem, and Watson's confession that he was sleepy before Holmes arrived but is "quite wakeful now" carries a quiet charge of rekindled pleasure. The scene is a small masterpiece of tonal management, at once comic and affectionate, and Holmes's aside that Watson's published sketches are "entirely meretricious" — delivered while begging a bed for the night — is a touch of ingratitude so characteristic as to amount to a term of endearment.
The mystery itself is architecturally elegant. A colonel of the Royal Munsters is found dead in a locked room, his face frozen in an expression of terror so extreme that more than one person fainted at the sight of it; his wife, who had been heard screaming "You coward!" through the door, lies insensible on a couch; the key has vanished. Holmes's investigation uncovers footprints on the lawn, the tracks of a mysterious small creature, and — crucially — the word "David," overheard by the housemaid, which should, as Holmes confesses with appealing self-reproach, have told him the whole story at once. The Biblical allusion is the tale's finest stroke: Nancy Barclay has called her husband David because, like King David, he sent a rival to his death — not Uriah to the siege of Rabbah, but Corporal Henry Wood into the hands of rebel sepoys at Bhurtee, by deliberately drawing a route that led him into ambush. The parallel is precise, economical, and devastating, and it elevates the story from a locked-room puzzle to a meditation on guilt that has festered for thirty years.
Henry Wood's confession is the emotional centre of the tale, and it is rendered with the compressed power that Doyle commanded at his best. The young soldier's account of his betrayal, his capture and torture, his wandering through Nepal and Afghanistan, and his eventual return to England as a broken conjurer performing tricks in army canteens — all this is delivered in a voice of plain, exhausted dignity that refuses self-pity. The comical element resides not in the confession but in its zoological accompaniment: Wood travels everywhere with a mongoose named Teddy, which escaped during the fatal confrontation and ran up a curtain to get at a canary, leaving behind the mysterious animal prints that so baffled Holmes. That the emotional climax of the story — the moment when Barclay sees the man he betrayed and drops dead of sheer terror — shares its stage with a mongoose chasing a caged bird is an incongruity so perfect that one cannot quite determine whether Doyle intended it as comic relief or simply failed to notice that his melodrama and his menagerie were working at cross-purposes.
What gives the story its lasting gravity, however, is its treatment of conscience as a force more lethal than any weapon. Barclay dies not of the wound to his head but of apoplexy — the sight of Wood, appearing like a ghost from the Indian past, strikes him dead where he stands. Holmes recognises this at once: "I read death on his face as plain as I can read that text over the fire," Wood tells him, and Holmes does not dispute it. The colonel's thirty years of intermittent gloom, his superstitious dread of being left alone after dark, the smile struck from his face at the mess-table "as if by some invisible hand" — all are now explained as the symptoms of a guilt that never slept. It is one of Doyle's most penetrating psychological portraits, achieved almost entirely in retrospect, and it invests the locked-room mystery with a moral weight that the apparatus of keys and footprints could never generate alone. Holmes's closing observation — that there is no object in raking up scandal against a dead man, "foully as he has acted" — is delivered with a restraint that only deepens the story's force. The justice of the case is already complete; the law has nothing left to do.
""" .

:dancingMenDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This is one of the most celebrated stories in the canon, and it deserves the reputation — but it also deserves the scrutiny. The cryptographic solution is Holmes's finest sustained demonstration of analytical method, presented with a pedagogical clarity that lets the reader follow every step. Hilton Cubitt is among the most sympathetically drawn clients Doyle ever created, his quiet Norfolk stubbornness — "A promise is a promise" — making him both admirable and heartbreakingly vulnerable.
The flaw here is not comical but devastating: Holmes decodes an explicit death threat ("ELSIE PREPARE TO MEET THY GOD"), identifies the sender as the most dangerous criminal in Chicago, determines the situation is urgent — and then goes to bed because the last train has left. He does not telegraph Cubitt to warn him, does not alert the local police, does not use any of the means available to convey that a known killer has announced his intention to act that very night. He takes the morning train and arrives to find his client dead. It is the most catastrophic failure in the canon, and Doyle's silence about it — Holmes never acknowledges the oversight — makes it all the more haunting. The closing sentence, recording that Elsie Cubitt recovered, remained a widow, and devoted her life to the poor and her husband's estate, is the quietest and most desolating line Watson ever committed to paper.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Dancing Men" is one of those Holmes stories in which the intellectual apparatus is so dazzling that the reader may not notice, until long afterwards, the human catastrophe it has failed to prevent. The opening deduction — Holmes divining Watson's refusal to invest in South African securities from chalk dust between finger and thumb — is a six-link chain of reasoning so transparently contrived that Watson's cry of "How absurdly simple!" is both the inevitable response and a gentle joke at the reader's expense. The introduction of the cipher is managed with superb narrative economy: Hilton Cubitt arrives from Norfolk carrying scraps of paper covered in what appear to be children's drawings of stick figures dancing across the page, and his account of his wife's terror — she turns deadly white, she drops in a dead faint, she wears a look as if "waiting and expecting" — establishes at once that these absurd little figures are instruments of mortal danger. Cubitt himself is drawn with an admiration that amounts nearly to reverence: a man of the old English soil, ruddy and blue-eyed, who seems to carry a whiff of the east-coast air into Baker Street. His refusal to press his wife for her secret — "A promise is a promise, Mr. Holmes" — is repeated with a quiet obstinacy that makes him one of the most sympathetically rendered clients in the canon, and one of the most doomed.
The cryptographic solution is Holmes's most sustained and methodically displayed feat of analytical reasoning, and Doyle presents it with an expository clarity that any professor of mathematics might envy. The identification of E by frequency analysis, the inspired guess that a five-letter word with E in the second and fourth positions might spell the name ELSIE, the progressive unlocking of the alphabet until "AM HERE ABE SLANEY" emerges from the dancing figures — all this is conducted with a lucidity that allows the reader to follow each inferential step and feel, however briefly, that they too might have cracked the code. It is the one occasion in the canon where Holmes does not merely announce his deductions but teaches them, and the passage has the quality of a demonstration in which the audience arrives at understanding alongside the demonstrator. The masterstroke is Holmes's use of the decoded cipher to lure Slaney to the house: having learned the enemy's language, he turns it against him, writing a note in dancing men that the criminal cannot imagine came from anyone but Elsie herself. It is one of the most elegant traps in detective fiction.
Yet the story contains a flaw so glaring that it darkens everything around it, and it is not comical but tragic. Holmes decodes the final message — "ELSIE PREPARE TO MEET THY GOD" — recognises it as an explicit death threat from a man his New York contacts have identified as the most dangerous criminal in Chicago, and determines that they must travel to Norfolk at once. The last train has gone. Holmes proposes that they breakfast early and take the first morning train. He does not send a telegram warning Cubitt of the imminent danger. He does not contact the local police. He does not, by any of the several means available to a man in 1898 London, convey to the threatened household that a known killer has announced his intention to act that very night. Instead, he goes to bed. Watson records that Holmes sent Cubitt a message, but its contents are never disclosed, and whatever it contained, it manifestly did not say: "You are in mortal danger tonight; arm yourself; summon the police; do not let your wife near the windows." The great detective, having broken the code, having identified the criminal, having read the death threat in plain English, takes the morning train and arrives to find his client shot through the heart. It is the most catastrophic failure in the canon, and Doyle's silence on the subject — Holmes never acknowledges the oversight, never reproaches himself, never explains why he did not act — is itself remarkable.
What rescues the tale from the bitterness of this failure is the emotional architecture that surrounds it. Watson's prose, as the train approaches Norfolk, achieves a gravity that is rare for him: the enormous square-towered churches bristling from the flat green landscape, the violet rim of the German Ocean appearing over the coast, the driver pointing his whip toward two old gables projecting from a grove of trees — these images are rendered with a painter's eye and a mourner's heart, for Watson knows, as the reader knows, what they will find at journey's end. Holmes's seven-mile silence in the carriage — "seldom have I seen him so utterly despondent" — is the most eloquent confession of guilt he ever makes, precisely because it contains no words. And Slaney's anguished cry when told that Elsie has been shot — "You're crazy! It was he that was hurt, not she. Who would have hurt little Elsie?" — is one of the few moments in the canon where a villain's grief is rendered with absolute conviction, so that for an instant the criminal and the detective are united in the same horror at what their contest has produced. The epilogue records that Mrs. Hilton Cubitt recovered, that she remained a widow, that she devoted her life to the care of the poor and to the administration of her dead husband's estate. It is the quietest and most desolating sentence Watson ever wrote.
""" .

