The review addresses the Cornish landscape writing as genuinely transcendent prose, praises the hallucinatory poison-experiment scene and the rare emotional vulnerability it reveals between Holmes and Watson, and identifies the comical flaws — particularly Dr. Sterndale's inexplicable decision to showcase an undetectable murder weapon to the one man with motive to use it, and Holmes's transparently staged watering-pot pratfall. The closing paragraph wrestles with Doyle's recurring habit of letting Holmes play God with the law, while acknowledging the emotional honesty that redeems the gesture.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
One is grateful to Mr. Conan Doyle for opening this tale with an evocation of the Cornish peninsula that is, by any honest reckoning, the finest sustained descriptive writing he has yet accomplished in the Holmes chronicles. The sinister semicircle of Mounts Bay, the rolling dun-coloured moors scored with the monuments of vanished races, the surge-swept reefs that have swallowed innumerable seamen — here the prose achieves a gravitas and atmospheric density that recalls the best passages of Mr. Hardy's Wessex. One feels genuinely transplanted into that ancient, haunted landscape, and for a few paragraphs the author lifts himself entirely above the machinery of popular detective fiction into something approaching authentic literary art. The image of the bay as a siren, lying placid under a northerly breeze only to unleash destruction from the southwest, carries a symbolic resonance — nature as deceiver — that enriches the whole narrative architecture. It is the best setting Doyle has constructed since the great Dartmoor passages of The Hound of the Baskervilles, and in some respects surpasses them.
The central horror of the tale — three people seated at a card table, one dead and two driven permanently mad, with no visible cause — is conceived with a genuinely macabre power that owes something to the sensation fiction of Mr. Le Fanu and something to the antiquarian ghost stories then being perfected by Mr. M. R. James. The scene in which Watson glimpses the contorted, grinning faces of the mad brothers through the window of a passing carriage is achieved with admirable economy and restraint; Doyle wisely allows the image to do its own terrible work without editorial embellishment. Still more striking is the experimental scene in which Holmes and Watson subject themselves to the fumes of the devil's-foot root, where Watson's narration of his own disintegrating consciousness — the thick black cloud, the unspeakable dweller upon the threshold — rises to a pitch of hallucinatory intensity that is genuinely startling in a magazine story. That Watson must physically drag Holmes from the room, and that both men lie gasping on the grass in the Cornish sunshine, produces a moment of human vulnerability between the two that is unmatched in the canon. Holmes's subsequent apology and Watson's declaration of devotion achieve, within the severe constraints of popular serial fiction, a note of authentic emotional truth.
It must be said, however, that the tale is not without its comical absurdities, which the discerning reader may catalogue with some amusement. Dr. Leon Sterndale, the great African explorer whose beard is golden at the fringes and white near the lips, save for nicotine stains — a man whose head nearly brushes the cottage ceiling — appears to have been assembled from a kit of spare parts belonging to every Victorian adventure-novel hero simultaneously. His confession strains credulity to the breaking point: we are asked to believe that this man of science casually displayed a secret and undetectable African ordeal poison to a weasel-faced acquaintance with known grudges against his own family, helpfully explained its lethal properties and the impossibility of detection, then turned his back long enough for said weasel to pocket a quantity of it. One might call this naïveté, but it looks rather more like authorial convenience of the most brazen sort. Equally droll is Holmes's celebrated watering-pot stratagem, in which the great detective contrives to "stumble" over a watering-pot to obtain a footprint — a ruse so transparently theatrical that one wonders the Cornwall constabulary did not arrest him for public nuisance.
The moral conclusion, in which Holmes permits a confessed murderer to walk free on the grounds that he acted from romantic passion, is the sort of private dispensation of justice that has become a troubling habit in these tales. Holmes appoints himself judge, jury, and pardoner with a breezy self-assurance that would alarm any student of jurisprudence, and Watson, ever the faithful subaltern, ratifies the decision without a murmur. Yet there is, even here, a curious honesty in the writing. Holmes's quiet admission that he has never loved, but that if he had and his beloved had met such a fate, he might have acted as Sterndale did — this is not mere plot resolution but a rare window into a character whom Doyle usually keeps at a careful emotional distance. It is precisely such moments, scattered like gold dust through these otherwise mechanical narratives, that ensure the Holmes stories will outlive the age that produced them.
""" .

