The review highlights the brilliant opening comic dialogue as transcending the genre, notes the peculiar structural experiment of sending Watson abroad without Holmes (and the comical cruelty of Holmes's demolition of Watson's efforts), and praises the vivid villainy of Holy Peters and the rare narrative honesty of Holmes's humiliation at Poultney Square. The principal comical flaw identified is Holmes's inexplicable overnight failure to grasp the significance of the oversized coffin — a clue so obvious that the mind which deduces Turkish baths from bootlaces has no business missing it for even an hour, let alone an entire sleepless night. The review also notes the quiet absurdity that Lady Frances, the title character, never speaks a single word in her own story.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
The opening gambit of this tale — Holmes deducing a Turkish bath from the knot in Watson's bootlaces — is among the most perfectly tuned pieces of comic dialogue in the entire canon. Watson's riposte that "a fresh illustration is not an explanation" is genuinely witty, a rare moment in which the good doctor lands a blow upon his imperious friend, and Holmes's admiring "Bravo, Watson!" acknowledges the hit with disarming grace. This sparkling overture, however, gives way to something considerably less assured: a lecture on the perils of the "drifting and friendless woman" that reads, even by the standards of Edwardian paternalism, as a curious little essay in sociology. Lady Frances Carfax is introduced not as a person but as a type — the migratory spinster, the stray chicken among foxes — and one feels from the first that Mr. Conan Doyle is more interested in the machinery of her disappearance than in the substance of her character. She never speaks a single word in the story that bears her name. This is a notable achievement in literary erasure.
The continental middle section, in which Watson is dispatched alone to Lausanne, Baden, and Montpellier, represents one of Doyle's more interesting structural experiments — the detective sent abroad without his detective. Watson's earnest tramping across Europe, his careful note-taking, his proud conviction that Holmes himself could not have been more adroit, followed by Holmes's devastating verdict that he cannot recall any possible blunder Watson has omitted, produces a comedy of professional humiliation that is rather more cruel than amusing. The scene in which Holmes materialises as a French workman in a blue blouse, cudgel in hand, to rescue Watson from being throttled in a Montpellier street is preposterously contrived: we are told that Holmes could not possibly leave London because Scotland Yard feels lonely without him, and yet here he is, lounging in a French cabaret, having apparently crossed the Channel on a whim. One cannot help noticing that the great detective's reason for sending Watson abroad was, by his own subsequent admission, entirely futile — a contrivance to occupy the faithful biographer while the real work waited in London.
The villain of the piece, Holy Peters of Adelaide, masquerading as the Reverend Dr. Shlessinger, is rendered with genuine relish. His unctuous manner, his pendulous cheeks, his "make-everything-easy voice" concealing a cruel and vicious mouth — here Doyle's gift for the swift, vivid sketch of character serves him admirably. The confrontation at Poultney Square, in which Holmes half-draws a revolver and cheerfully describes himself and Watson as a burglar and a dangerous ruffian, crackles with energy, and Peters's sneering triumph when the coffin reveals only a withered old woman rather than the expected Lady Frances constitutes a genuine reversal — one of the few occasions in the canon where Holmes is publicly humiliated and must retreat. That Peters is allowed to gloat over the great detective's gaping, staring face is a moment of narrative honesty that lifts the story above the formulaic.
And yet the resolution, when it comes, is comically reliant upon coincidence and the most extraordinary slowness of mind on Holmes's part. The vital clue — the undertaker's wife remarking that the coffin was delayed because it had been made to some special measurement — is overheard by Philip Green, reported to Holmes, and then simply forgotten by the master logician until dawn breaks over Baker Street. Holmes himself confesses to this eclipse with an almost endearing self-reproach, but the reader may be forgiven for wondering how a mind that can deduce Turkish baths from bootlaces could fail, for an entire restless night, to ask why a coffin for a tiny old woman should be built to unusual dimensions. It is the sort of plot device that works only if one does not pause to examine it, which is perhaps the defining characteristic of popular detective fiction — and which, to his credit, Doyle has the candour to acknowledge rather than conceal. The final image of Lady Frances hauled unconscious from her chloroformed coffin is potent and horrible, but it is purchased at the cost of making Holmes rather less than Holmes.
""" .

