The review identifies Holmes's calculated cruelty toward Watson as the story's true and most psychologically complex subject — writing that transcends the genre. It praises the Culverton Smith portrait as a masterwork of the grotesque, particularly the mirror-scene where Watson's own charitable nature blinds him. The comical flaws centre on Smith's pantomime-villain confession (no cunning murderer would recite a complete account of his methods to the one man investigating him) and Holmes's absurd claim that the worst possible hiding-place is therefore the least suspicious one. The closing paragraph argues that Holmes's quiet cigarette-and-match revelation, together with the bittersweet compliment-as-insult to Watson's honest nature, earns the story its place despite the machinery that creaks beneath it.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
This tale belongs to a species of narrative one might term the theatre of cruelty practised upon the faithful. Its essential subject is not murder, nor even detection, but the spectacle of Sherlock Holmes systematically tormenting his dearest friend for the better part of a day — starving himself into ghastliness, painting his face with vaseline and rouge and beeswax, and then savaging Watson with a calculated brutality that ranks among the most psychologically complex passages in popular fiction. The insult to Watson's medical qualifications — delivered with the precision of a scalpel to a man who has rushed across London in genuine terror for his friend's life — is not merely a plot device to prevent examination; it is a wound inflicted upon the one relationship in these stories that carries authentic emotional weight. That Watson records it without bitterness, interpreting it as the fever speaking, testifies to a loyalty so absolute it verges on the saintly. Mr. Conan Doyle has seldom written anything so quietly painful, and one suspects he understood rather more about the moral cost of Holmes's methods than he is generally credited with.
The portrait of Culverton Smith is a small masterpiece of the grotesque, worthy of comparison with the best character work of Mr. Stevenson. The great yellow face, coarse-grained and greasy; the enormous skull perched upon a body twisted by childhood rickets; the velvet smoking-cap poised coquettishly upon the pink curve of that bald head — here every physical detail carries moral freight. His gloating bedside manner, in which he dispenses water to a dying man solely to keep him conscious for further torment, achieves a note of intimate, drawing-room sadism that is considerably more disturbing than the operatic villainy one usually encounters in these chronicles. The scene in which Watson catches Smith's face in the mirror — set in what can only be a malicious smile — and then persuades himself it must have been a nervous contraction, is a stroke of genuine artistry: Watson's charitable nature becomes the instrument of his own deception, and Doyle trusts the reader to see what the narrator cannot.
The comical difficulties of the plot, however, are considerable, and the attentive reader will find them accumulating like unpaid bills. We are asked to accept that Culverton Smith, a known amateur of tropical disease who has already murdered one person by precisely these means, will walk into the sickroom of the man who publicly accused him of that murder and, finding himself apparently alone with a dying witness, obligingly recite a complete confession — including the mechanism of the ivory box, the identity of the victim, and his own motive — simply because he cannot resist gloating. This is not the behaviour of a cunning murderer; it is the behaviour of a villain in a pantomime who has been told he must explain the plot before the curtain falls. Equally delightful is Holmes's instruction that Watson must arrive before Smith and conceal himself behind the headboard of the bed, in a room that Holmes himself admits does not lend itself to concealment — a difficulty resolved by the breezy assurance that the very impossibility of the hiding-place makes it less suspicious, a species of logic that would make Euclid weep.
Yet the tale's final movement redeems much. Holmes's revelation — accomplished not with thunder but with the quiet request for a match and a cigarette, spoken suddenly in his natural voice — is among the most theatrically satisfying moments in the canon. And the closing explanation, in which Holmes cheerfully catalogues his techniques of malingering (vaseline, belladonna, rouge, beeswax, and occasional remarks about oysters to simulate delirium), carries a self-mocking wit that transcends the genre entirely. One notes, too, the delicate irony of Holmes's apology for having deceived Watson — an apology built upon the frank admission that he exploited Watson's very inability to dissemble. It is a compliment disguised as an insult, or an insult disguised as a compliment; with Holmes, one can never be entirely certain. The closing image of the two men setting off to Simpson's for something nutritious has the quiet warmth of an old marriage, and one forgives the creaking machinery of the plot for the sake of the human truth that survives it.
""" .

