The review praises the resurrection scene in Watson's study as authentic literary enchantment, and finds in Watson's unspoken bereavement — a dead wife and a friend who chose to let him grieve a fiction — an emotional complexity Doyle wisely leaves unresolved. The stakeout sequence is identified as some of Doyle's finest atmospheric prose. The comical flaws are rich: Holmes's three-year itinerary (visiting Mecca as an Englishman, calling on the Khalifa mid-jihad, and that immortal "head Llama" — Buddhist dignitary or Andean livestock?), the mysterious martial art of "baritsu" unknown to any reference work, and the deeper structural comedy that Moran obligingly chooses to fire from the one building in London where Holmes happens to be hiding, a coincidence Holmes then pretends to find mildly surprising.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
This is, before it is anything else, a resurrection narrative, and one must acknowledge at the outset that Mr. Conan Doyle has managed the central theatrical coup — Holmes's return from the dead — with a craftsmanship that transcends the merely ingenious. The scene in Watson's study, in which the croaking old bibliophile directs Watson's gaze toward the bookshelf and then simply becomes Holmes when Watson turns back, possesses the quality of genuine enchantment. Watson's fainting — the only such episode in his long career — is exactly right; no lesser response could have honoured the magnitude of the moment. And the brief, devastating sentence in which we learn of Watson's "sad bereavement," passed over by Holmes with sympathy shown in manner rather than in words, carries an emotional freight that the author wisely declines to unpack. Here is a man who has lost his wife, who has spent three years mourning his closest friend, and who now discovers that at least one of these griefs was manufactured by the friend himself. That Watson responds with unalloyed joy rather than rage is either the most generous act in English fiction or the most pitiable; Doyle, to his great credit, allows both readings to coexist.
The stakeout in the empty house opposite Baker Street is rendered with a taut, atmospheric mastery that represents Doyle at his most assured. The passage in which Holmes leads Watson through the dark labyrinth of mews and stables into the pitch-black room, where his cold thin fingers close around Watson's wrist, achieves a physical immediacy — one can feel the bare planking underfoot, smell the dust — that is superior to anything the sensation novelists were producing at the time. Colonel Moran's entrance, creeping through the darkness to assemble his air-gun at the window, is choreographed with the precision and silence of a ballet of menace. Watson's description of the marksman's long moustache drooping over the stock as his eye gleams along the sights is a detail of startling visual exactness — the kind of observed particular that lifts narrative prose above the mechanical.
The comical absurdities, however, are prodigious, and they cluster thickly around Holmes's account of the three years between Reichenbach and his return. Having disposed of Moriarty by means of "baritsu" — a Japanese wrestling art unknown to any encyclopaedia of martial science — Holmes proceeds to narrate a Grand Tour of such staggering implausibility that one suspects Doyle of a private joke at the reader's expense. In the space of three years, Holmes has visited Tibet and spent some days with the "head Llama" (the spelling suggesting either a Buddhist prelate or a South American ruminant, and offering no means of distinguishing between them), passed through Persia, "looked in at Mecca" — a feat which, for a conspicuously English non-Muslim, would have required either a thoroughgoing disguise or a willingness to court execution — and paid a social call upon the Khalifa at Khartoum, a gentleman who was at that period actively engaged in holy war against the British Empire. That Holmes then spent several months in a chemistry laboratory at Montpellier studying coal-tar derivatives is the one element of this itinerary that rings true, being sufficiently dreary to be believable.
Yet there is a deeper comedy embedded in the tale's very structure that one suspects the author did not wholly intend. Holmes's elaborate stratagem — the wax bust, Mrs. Hudson crawling on her knees to adjust it every quarter-hour, the police stationed in doorways — depends upon the absolute certainty that Colonel Moran will attempt assassination on this particular evening, from this particular angle, at this particular window. When Moran obligingly does exactly that, choosing to fire from the very house in which Holmes lies in ambush, Holmes professes mild surprise at this single deviation from his plan — a claim that strains credulity, since the empty house directly opposite one's own rooms is so obviously the ideal sniper's perch that a child might have anticipated it. One cannot escape the suspicion that the great detective, having scripted the evening's drama down to the final curtain, has reserved this small confession of fallibility as a courtesy to the audience, lest the performance seem too perfect to be sporting. It is this mixture of audacity and theatrical self-awareness — Holmes quoting Shakespeare as he admires his own waxwork — that gives the tale its peculiar flavour and ensures that, however loudly the machinery creaks, the showmanship never fails.
""" .

