The review identifies the consulting-room opening as a masterful blend of the clinical and the horrible, with Hatherley's hydraulics quip about his own severed thumb transcending the sensation genre. The hydraulic press scene is praised as the finest claustrophobic horror of the period, particularly the condemned man's terrible leisure in choosing which way to face his own crushing. The central comical flaw is devastating: the Colonel's elaborate scheme of midnight carriages, frosted windows, fifty-guinea fees, and murder by industrial machinery is all in service of diagnosing a shrunken rubber band — a fault any competent mechanic could have fixed with a spanner. The review closes by noting that Holmes is largely decorative here, contributing one brilliant deduction (the six-miles-out-and-back ruse) but solving nothing, and that the story's honest admission that detection does not equal justice gives it an unusual integrity among popular fiction of the time.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
This is a tale of unusual construction among the Holmes chronicles, for it is almost entirely given over to the testimony of a single witness — the young hydraulic engineer Victor Hatherley — and in this respect it reads less as a detective story than as a conte cruel in the French manner, a narrative of entrapment and mutilation that might comfortably sit alongside the more gruesome productions of Mr. de Maupassant. The opening scene in Watson's consulting-room is managed with a quiet, professional excellence that deserves notice. The railway guard who delivers the wounded man like a trapper presenting his catch, the young engineer's fit of hysterical laughter that raises all of Watson's medical instincts, and that wonderfully understated moment when Hatherley asks the doctor to attend to his thumb, "or rather to the place where my thumb used to be" — here the mingling of the clinical and the horrible achieves a tone that is peculiarly Doyle's own. Watson's dry compliment, "You should have been a surgeon," and Hatherley's reply that stopping the bleeding was merely a question of hydraulics, produces a grim comedy of professional detachment that transcends anything the sensation novelists could manage.
The central narrative — Hatherley's midnight journey to the house of Colonel Lysander Stark — is sustained with genuinely mounting dread. The frosted glass of the carriage windows, the labyrinthine corridors of the decaying house with its peeling plaster and damp-blotched walls, the beautiful woman who appears in a doorway holding a lamp above her head like a figure from a Flemish painting — Doyle constructs his atmosphere with an economy of means that puts more ambitious practitioners to shame. The scene inside the hydraulic press, in which the ceiling descends with remorseless mechanical patience while Hatherley screams against the locked door, is as fine a piece of claustrophobic horror as the period has produced. One notes that Doyle resists the temptation to rush the crisis; Hatherley has time to consider whether he would rather be crushed face-down upon his spine or face-up watching the shadow descend, and this morbid deliberation — the condemned man's terrible leisure — is more frightening than any amount of breathless narration could be.
Yet the story contains absurdities that are very nearly as impressive as its virtues, and they cluster most thickly around the question of why any of it happens at all. Colonel Lysander Stark requires an engineer to diagnose a stiffness in his hydraulic press. The fault proves to be a shrunken india-rubber band around a driving-rod — a defect so elementary that any competent mechanic could have identified it, and which the Colonel's gang, who have been operating the machine for some time, might reasonably have discovered for themselves. For this trivial repair, the Colonel engages a young stranger, pays him fifty guineas (a sum Hatherley himself recognises as tenfold the going rate), transports him through the night in a carriage with frosted windows, and then attempts to murder him with his own press when the young man notices metallic residue on the floor. The Colonel has, we later learn, done all of this before, with a previous engineer named Jeremiah Hayling who was never seen again — meaning that he has erected an elaborate murder apparatus around a problem that any ironmonger's apprentice could have solved with a spanner and a replacement gasket. One is reminded of those Gothic villains who construct fiendishly complex deathtraps when a locked door and a pistol would serve rather better.
Holmes himself, it must be said, is present in this story chiefly as a decorative figure. He orders breakfast, asks a shrewd question about the colour and condition of the horse, and delivers the single flash of genuine deduction — that the twelve-mile drive was in fact six miles out and six miles back — with the quiet satisfaction of a man who has earned his fee with one observation. But the criminals escape, the counterfeiting operation burns to the ground through the accident of a smashed oil-lamp, and Holmes is left to offer his client the cold consolation that the loss of a thumb and a fifty-guinea fee has at least furnished him with an excellent dinner-party anecdote. It is a remarkably honest ending. The tale admits, with a candour unusual in popular fiction, that detection is not the same as justice, that the world's problems do not arrange themselves into solvable puzzles, and that sometimes the best a man can salvage from catastrophe is a story worth telling. In this last respect, at least, one cannot deny that Mr. Hatherley got his money's worth.
""" .

:finalProblemDoc  
    ex:reviewersNotes """
The review identifies two passages as transcending not merely popular fiction but belonging to English prose literature entire: the Holmes-Moriarty interview at Baker Street, where dialogue reaches the limit of language between two matched minds (with Moriarty's memorandum-book of grievance dates singled out as simultaneously chilling and absurd), and the Reichenbach Falls description as Ruskinian sublime. The comical flaw is the most fundamental one in the canon — Moriarty himself, conjured from nowhere in the penultimate story, draped in magnificent rhetoric about spiders and webs, yet never previously mentioned by anyone, whose supposedly impregnable criminal empire collapses the instant Holmes files his evidence. The review argues that Doyle, weary of his creation, simply invented the grandest executioner he could and trusted the prose to carry the weight. The closing assessment is that Watson's grief at the falls — the Alpine-stock, the footprints that do not return, the Platonic valediction — constitutes the finest writing Doyle ever produced.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
Let us begin with what is extraordinary about this story, for it contains two passages that belong not merely to the literature of detection but to English prose fiction entire. The first is the interview between Holmes and Moriarty at Baker Street, a scene conducted with the economy and formal tension of a duel in Racine. Each man knows precisely what the other thinks; words are exchanged not to communicate but to confirm what has already been understood. When Moriarty says "All that I have to say has already crossed your mind" and Holmes replies "Then possibly my answer has crossed yours," we are in the presence of a dialogue that operates at the very limit of language — two intellects so evenly matched that speech becomes almost redundant. The subsequent exchange, in which Moriarty produces not a weapon but a memorandum-book and reads aloud the dates on which Holmes progressively inconvenienced him, is a stroke of genius: the criminal mastermind keeps accounts of his persecutor as tidily as a grocer tracking bad debts. It is at once chilling and absurd, and Mr. Conan Doyle manages both registers simultaneously without the slightest wobble of tone. The second great passage is the description of the Reichenbach Falls — that creaming, boiling pit of incalculable depth, the half-human shout booming up through the spray — which achieves a sublimity of natural description that recalls Mr. Ruskin at his most powerful, and which transforms a Swiss tourist attraction into something approaching a mythological landscape, a portal between the world of the living and whatever lies beyond.
The architecture of the flight to the continent is constructed with a momentum and propulsive energy unprecedented in these chronicles. The van in Welbeck Street, the brick from the rooftop, the bludgeon-man on the pavement — three separate murder attempts catalogued by Holmes with the calm precision of a man reading a railway timetable — establish a pitch of danger that Doyle sustains magnificently through the evasion from Victoria Station, the special train glimpsed as a thin spray of smoke rising from the Kentish woods, and the wandering progress through the Alpine landscape with its constant atmosphere of surveillance and pursuit. Mycroft Holmes at the reins of the brougham is a delicious touch, and the disguise as the venerable Italian priest — Watson helping the very man he is looking for without recognising him — provides precisely the comic relief the narrative requires before its descent into darkness. One observes how skilfully Watson is deployed as an emotional instrument: his wistful glance at the disappearing luggage-van containing his wardrobe is the gesture of a man who knows the adventure has already gone wrong.
Yet the tale carries within it absurdities that even the most indulgent reader must acknowledge, and the greatest of these is Professor Moriarty himself. He arrives fully formed in the penultimate story of the series, this Napoleon of crime who has supposedly organised half the evil in London for years, and yet Watson has never heard his name — nor, indeed, has anyone else. Holmes explains this by calling it the genius of the thing, but one might equally call it the convenience of it: the author requires an antagonist grand enough to justify killing his hero, and so conjures one from thin air, drapes him in the iconography of the spider and the web, and furnishes him with a treatise on the Binomial Theorem and a reptilian oscillation of the head. That Moriarty's criminal empire, allegedly the most brilliantly concealed organisation in Europe, collapses entirely the moment Holmes assembles his evidence — all save the Professor himself — suggests that the web was rather less formidable than advertised. One suspects that Mr. Conan Doyle, weary of his creation and desperate for a worthy executioner, simply invented the grandest villain he could imagine and trusted the rhetoric to do the rest. The rhetoric, it must be said, very nearly succeeds.
The closing paragraphs, however, transcend everything that precedes them. Watson's return to the falls — the Alpine-stock leaning where Holmes left it, the two lines of footmarks leading away and none returning, the ploughed mud and torn ferns at the path's end — is narrated with a grief so restrained it achieves a power that more demonstrative writing could never match. Watson lying on his face at the lip of the chasm, peering into the spray while his own voice echoes back to him as the only answer, is an image of desolation that belongs to the literature of loss, not of adventure. Holmes's farewell letter, written with the courtesy of Mr. Moriarty's permission and in handwriting as firm as if composed in his study, is the gesture of a man who has arranged his own death as neatly as he arranges his case-files: pigeonhole M, blue envelope, inscribed "Moriarty." And Watson's closing tribute — "the best and the wisest man whom I have ever known" — echoing, as many have noted, Plato's valediction for Socrates, elevates a magazine serial into something approaching genuine elegy. Whether Mr. Conan Doyle fully understood what he had accomplished here is an open question, but the passage itself is beyond dispute: it is the finest thing he ever wrote.
""" .

