The review identifies the storm-opening as the finest atmospheric writing in the canon, with the dissolution of boundary between Watson's sea-novel and the gale outside praised as Stevensonian in quality. Uncle Elias's portrait — bravado and terror in alternation — is singled out as psychological writing above the genre, and the diary page's bureaucratic language of horror ("McCauley cleared… Visited Paramore. All well") is noted as achieving its effect through what it conceals rather than what it states. The central comical flaw is devastating and structural: Holmes establishes with visible agitation that the killers are already in London and no delay can be expected, cries "Incredible imbecility!" at the police for their inaction, and then sends his client out alone into a violent storm to walk to Waterloo Station, where the young man is promptly murdered. Holmes's subsequent remark — "That hurts my pride" — is identified as a sentence of almost comical inadequacy for a man whose client has just been killed through what amounts to his own negligence. The closing image of the Atlantic swallowing the Lone Star is praised as structural artistry that makes this, paradoxically, the most honest story in the canon — one where detection operates flawlessly yet the world remains unsaved.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
The opening paragraph of this tale is among the most accomplished pieces of atmospheric writing in the Holmes canon, and it deserves to be considered as something finer than mere scene-setting. The equinoctial gale that shrieks at mankind through the bars of his civilisation, like untamed beasts in a cage, is an image of genuine metaphorical power, and the subsequent passage in which Watson's sea-novel seems to merge with the storm outside — the howl of the wind blending with the text, the splash of rain lengthening into the swash of waves — achieves a dissolution of the boundary between fiction and reality that is more characteristic of Mr. Stevenson than of popular detective fiction. When John Openshaw's story then arrives, as Watson puts it, like a sheet of seaweed blown in upon a gale and afterwards reabsorbed by the elements, we feel the narrative itself has been shaped by forces larger than any human contrivance. It is weather-writing of the first order, and it transforms the Baker Street sitting-room from a stage-set into a fragile outpost of reason besieged by the irrational. One notes, too, the quiet excellence of the exchange in which the young man praises Holmes's reputation and Holmes replies that he has been beaten four times — three times by men, and once by a woman. It is a throwaway line, delivered with an almost offhand modesty, but it reverberates across the entire chronicle.
The hereditary narrative — uncle, father, son, each receiving the five dried pips, each dying in sequence — is constructed with the relentless logic of a Greek tragedy, or more precisely of a family curse in which the sins of one generation are visited upon the next. Uncle Elias's drunken sallies into the garden with a revolver, screaming that he fears no man, followed by his terrified bolting of the doors — this portrait of a man brazen enough to defy his persecutors but unable to outrun the terror at the roots of his soul — is drawn with a psychological acuity that belongs to a higher order of fiction than the detective tale usually affords. The diary page from March 1869, with its laconic entries — "Set the pips on McCauley, Paramore, and John Swain," followed by "McCauley cleared," "John Swain cleared," "Visited Paramore. All well" — achieves its horror through bureaucratic understatement, the language of administrative routine applied to terrorisation and likely murder. One shudders not at what is said but at what "cleared" and "all well" are made to conceal.
Yet the tale contains what must be reckoned the most spectacular failure in all of Holmes's career, and its treatment of that failure reveals a comical disproportion between the detective's analytic brilliance and his practical competence that the reader can only regard with bewildered amusement. Holmes has deduced, with impeccable logic, that the letter posted from London means the killers are already at hand and that no delay can be expected. He has told Openshaw, with visible agitation, that two days have already been wasted. He has cried "Incredible imbecility!" at the police for their inaction. And then, having established the supreme urgency of the case, he sends his client out alone into a violent storm, on foot, to catch a train from Waterloo — telling him only that the streets will be crowded and that he trusts he may be in safety. The young man is murdered that very evening, within hours of leaving Baker Street. Holmes's response — "That hurts my pride" — is a sentence of almost comical inadequacy, as though a surgeon who had left his patient on the operating table to fetch a cup of tea were to describe the resulting death as a professional embarrassment. That Holmes then spends the following day brilliantly tracing the Lone Star through Lloyd's registers, only to discover the ship has already sailed, merely compounds the irony: the detective's research is magnificent, but it is research conducted upon a corpse.
The conclusion, in which the equinoctial gales that opened the story return to swallow the Lone Star and her crew somewhere in the Atlantic, is a stroke of structural artistry that nearly redeems the tale's logical difficulties. The storm that blew Openshaw's story into Baker Street ultimately delivers the justice that Holmes could not, and there is something both satisfying and deeply unsettling in this substitution of natural catastrophe for human agency. Holmes's theatrical gesture of sending five pips to Captain Calhoun — initialled "S. H. for J. O." — never arrives, and one is left with the uncomfortable recognition that the great detective has been reduced to the role of a spectator in his own narrative, his web unspun, his quarry claimed by the sea. It is, in its way, the most honest of all the Holmes stories: a tale in which the machinery of detection operates flawlessly and yet the world remains, stubbornly and tragically, unsaved.
""" .

:goldenPinceNezDoc  
