The four paragraphs move from praise of Doyle's atmospheric opening (which I think genuinely transcends the popular fiction of the period), through the comical absurdities of Holmes's cigarette-ash detection method and his preposterous optical deductions, to the structural problem of the rushed confession — and finally to what redeems it all: the unexpected tragic dignity of Anna's final scene. I tried to channel Arnold's insistence on measuring literature against the highest standard alongside James's sensitivity to the architecture of narrative and the life of characters within it.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
There is in Dr. Doyle's latest contribution to the Holmes canon a tension between the machinery of the detective tale and the aspirations of something considerably finer, and it is this tension which makes "The Adventure of the Golden Pince-Nez" at once a satisfying entertainment and a curiously uneven performance. The opening paragraphs achieve a genuine atmospheric distinction: Watson's meditation upon the storm over London, that wonderful image of the elemental forces reducing the whole of the city to nothing more than "molehills that dot the fields," possesses a brooding, almost Hardyesque grandeur that one does not expect from the pages of the Strand. For a moment, popular fiction lifts its head above the shop counter and breathes the air of literature. It is a passage one might set beside the best of Stevenson's scene-painting — the metropolis rendered suddenly fragile and provisional against the indifferent machinery of nature.
Yet the comical weaknesses intrinsic to the Holmes formula reassert themselves with a persistence that no amount of atmospheric grace can quite redeem. One must observe, with some amusement, that Holmes's celebrated method of detection here depends upon what can only be called a prodigious act of littering: the great reasoner solves his case by chain-smoking an extraordinary quantity of cigarettes and scattering their ash across the Professor's carpet, then contriving to knock over a cigarette-box so that he might crawl about the floor inspecting his own deposits. It is a method that owes less to ratiocination than to the habits of an untidy undergraduate. One pictures Mrs. Hudson in quiet despair. Equally risible is the degree to which Holmes extracts, from a single pair of spectacles, a portrait so minute and particular — the puckered forehead, the rounded shoulders, the precise number of visits to the optician — that it strains not merely credulity but the very contract between author and reader upon which the detective story depends. The deductions are not reasoned; they are conjured, and the distinction matters.
The tale's deeper flaw, however, is structural. Doyle has constructed a mystery whose resolution depends entirely upon a confession delivered in the final pages — a confession which arrives with the mechanical punctuality of a deus ex machina and which must perform, in a few breathless paragraphs, the work of an entire novella. We are asked to absorb an entire history of Russian nihilism, marital betrayal, Siberian exile, and undying romantic devotion in the space that might properly accommodate the ordering of a railway timetable. The woman Anna emerges from behind the bookcase and from behind the narrative simultaneously, and in neither case has Doyle prepared us adequately for her arrival. One cannot suppress the observation that a woman hidden for days behind a bookcase, surviving on shared cutlets in a room fetid with tobacco smoke, would present to the assembled company something rather more alarming than a dusty complexion and a noble bearing.
And yet — and this is what distinguishes Doyle at his best from the common run of sensational writers — the figure of Anna herself, in her brief and doomed appearance, achieves a certain tragic weight that the artifice of the plot scarcely deserves. Her arraignment of her husband, delivered with the poison already working in her veins, carries a moral authority that momentarily transcends the genre. When she turns upon the wretched Sergius and demands why he clings to his miserable life, there is a flash of genuine dramatic power — the power of a character who has suffered beyond the capacity of the adventure story to contain her. Doyle, one suspects, occasionally stumbles upon depths he has not entirely intended to plumb. It is this happy carelessness, this gift for accidentally touching upon the real, that keeps the Holmes stories alive when so many more carefully wrought fictions of the period have long since crumbled into dust.
""" .

:gloriaScottDoc
    ex:reviewersNotes """
The triple-nested narration is structurally unprecedented in the canon — Watson frames Holmes, who frames Trevor, who frames a written confession, producing a Chinese-box effect that distances the reader from every event of consequence. Holmes's famous deductions about the elder Trevor occupy barely two pages and function as a parlor trick rather than as investigation; the real "case" is handed to him as a document to read aloud. Doyle seems almost embarrassed by the detective machinery and far more energized by the mutiny set-piece, which reads like a suppressed desire to write Stevenson. The bull terrier that initiates the Holmes-Trevor friendship is a wonderfully absurd origin for a legendary career — the great consulting detective owes his vocation to a dog bite. Hudson is a blackmailer of remarkable incompetence: he drinks his host's brandy, insults the household, and announces his next victim by name before departing. Old Trevor's death by cipher is operatically excessive — apoplexy from a note about hen-pheasants. The story's emotional center is actually paternal shame, not crime, which gives it an unexpectedly domestic gravity beneath the adventure trappings. Doyle misspells "Prendergast" as "Predergast" mid-narrative, a slip suggesting hasty composition.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Gloria Scott" occupies a curious position in the Holmes canon, for it is a story almost entirely without Holmes in it. Doyle frames the tale as a reminiscence — Holmes's very first case — yet the detective is reduced to little more than a reading-lamp for other men's confessions. The narrative plunges through no fewer than three layers of retrospection: Watson recounts Holmes recounting Victor Trevor recounting old Trevor's written confession. The effect is rather like peering through a succession of keyholes, each one smaller than the last, until the reader finds himself watching a mutiny aboard a convict ship that has nothing whatever to do with detection. One cannot help suspecting that Doyle, having promised us the origin story of the world's foremost reasoner, discovered midway through that he would rather write a ripping yarn about pirates.
The comical flaw that most rewards attention is the cipher upon which the entire plot turns. Holmes, with an air of triumph befitting the Rosetta Stone's decipherment, announces that every third word of the message reveals its secret meaning. The reader, pencil in hand, may verify this and feel a glow of satisfaction — until reflecting that any conspirator who chose so fragile a device deserves his ruin. The filler words, drawn from the sporting life — "head-keeper," "hen-pheasant," "fly-paper" — are meant to suggest an innocent letter about game preserves, yet no sane recipient would read "the supply of game for London is going steadily up" without sensing that something had gone badly wrong with the English language. That old Trevor died of the shock rather than of laughter is perhaps the most implausible detail in the entire canon.
Yet the story is not without passages that rise above the ordinary machinery of popular fiction. The portrait of old Trevor — the thick-set magistrate with eyes "keen to the verge of fierceness," generous on the bench yet harboring a felon's past — carries a psychological weight that the adventure scarcely requires. And the long confession, for all its structural awkwardness, contains a genuinely powerful image in the first mate seated beside the open powder-barrel with a matchbox in his hand, calmly promising annihilation. That tableau, compressed into a single sentence, achieves a concentration of dramatic force that Doyle's more celebrated stories do not always equal. The destruction of the Gloria Scott itself, rendered as a black cloud hanging "like a monstrous tree upon the sky line," is writing that earns its melodrama honestly.
One must finally note, however, that Doyle's architectural sense fails him badly here. The young Holmes who deduces that Trevor senior has boxed, dug gold, and traveled to New Zealand is an electric presence — alert, presumptuous, brilliant. He then vanishes for twenty pages while a convict narrates his memoirs. When Holmes reappears at the close, offering a tidy speculation about Beddoes and Hudson, the reader has nearly forgotten that a detective story was in progress. The tale's real energy belongs not to ratiocination but to violence, treachery, and the sea — subjects for which Doyle possessed an instinct so natural that he could not help writing well about them, even when they had wandered entirely beyond his announced purpose.
""" .

:greekInterpreterDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This story offered particularly rich material: the brilliant introduction of Mycroft (which I argue transcends the detective genre entirely), the comical overreach of the window-deduction scene where Mycroft leaps from a shopping bag to death in childbed, the remarkable structural failure of a mystery whose author simply gives up and resolves it via a newspaper clipping from Budapest months later, and the genuinely fine writing in Melas's interrogation scene and the portrait of the giggling villain Wilson Kemp. The tension between Doyle's considerable gifts as a scene-painter and his occasional laziness as a plot-architect felt very much like the kind of thing both Arnold and James would have seized upon.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Greek Interpreter" opens with what is, by the standards of the Holmes tales, an extraordinary gambit: Dr. Doyle permits us, for the first time, to glimpse the roots of the tree rather than merely the fruit. The conversation between Watson and Holmes on heredity and atavism — culminating in the magnificent revelation that there exists a superior Holmes — gives the early pages a richness of characterisation that the canon seldom attempts. The introduction of Mycroft is a small masterpiece of economical portraiture. That image of the immense, corpulent intelligence, lodged permanently between Pall Mall and Whitehall like some great brain pickled in aspic, taking no exercise from one year's end to the next, possessing powers that dwarf his brother's yet lacking the smallest inclination to employ them — this is comic invention of a high order, and it belongs less to the detective story than to the English tradition of eccentric character-writing that runs from Sterne through Dickens. The Diogenes Club, that sanctuary for men who desire comfort without companionship, where speech itself is a punishable offence, is the sort of invention one wishes Doyle had lavished upon a novel rather than buried in a monthly instalment.
The celebrated window-scene, in which the two brothers perform their duelling deductions upon the passing soldier, is at once the tale's most entertaining set-piece and its most instructive absurdity. The exercise is delightful as theatre — the rapid stichomythia, Watson's helpless laughter, the elegant one-upmanship — but it collapses under the gentlest rational pressure. That a man carries a rattle and a picture-book tells us he has bought things for children; it does not, by any legitimate chain of reasoning, tell us his wife has died in childbed. Mycroft's leap from mourning clothes and a shopping bag to a specific cause of death is not deduction at all but divination dressed in the borrowed robes of logic. One smiles at the audacity rather than at the reasoning, and the honest reader must confess that Doyle has simply determined the answer in advance and is working backward to fabricate the appearance of inference. It is a conjuring trick, and a good one, but it is not what it claims to be.
The story's structural deficiency, however, is more damaging than any local implausibility. Doyle has constructed a genuinely arresting situation — the kidnapped interpreter, the plaster-faced prisoner writing desperate answers on a slate, the sinister giggling villain, the woman's sudden irruption and the anguished cry of recognition — and then proves quite unable to resolve it through the agency of his detective. Holmes and his companions arrive too late; the villains have fled; the resolution is supplied not by deduction but by a newspaper clipping from Budapest, arriving months afterward, reporting that the two Englishmen have been stabbed under ambiguous circumstances. Watson concedes openly that the explanation remains "involved in some mystery." It is as though Doyle, having imagined a splendid complication, simply grew weary of engineering its solution and chose instead to cut the knot by postal delivery. One cannot imagine the mature craftsman of the later tales — the Doyle of "The Devil's Foot" or "The Bruce-Partington Plans" — permitting himself so casual an abdication.
And yet the tale's very failures illuminate what is most genuinely gifted in its author. The scene of Melas's interrogation — that eerie half-spoken, half-written dialogue in which the interpreter smuggles his own desperate questions beneath the tyrants' commands — is a narrative invention of real originality, a passage in which the mechanics of suspense and the texture of lived fear operate together with a precision worthy of Wilkie Collins. The portrait of Wilson Kemp, peaky and sallow, his lips twitching with nervous malady, giggling as he threatens murder, achieves something more disturbing than mere villainy; it touches upon the pathological in a manner that anticipates the darker realism of the coming century. Doyle is never so fine a writer as when he is rendering the phenomenology of dread, and in these passages "The Greek Interpreter" earns its place among the tales that justify the enormous popularity of the series — not because the detective triumphs, but because the storyteller does.
""" .

:hisLastBowDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This was a fascinating story to assess because it's such a departure from the canon — no Watson narration, no mystery, no deduction. The comical flaws practically announce themselves: Holmes's music-hall Irish-American dialect, the chloroform-sponge assault, and above all Von Bork's absurdly prophetic safe combination of "August 1914" set four years in advance. But the closing passage on the terrace, with the east wind speech and Watson's touchingly literal response about the weather, struck me as genuinely transcendent — an elegy not just for two characters but for the entire pre-war world Doyle had been chronicling. It's one of those rare moments where popular fiction accidentally produces something that earns comparison with the literature of its age.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"His Last Bow" is, one must acknowledge at once, an anomaly in the Holmes canon so thoroughgoing that the literary critic scarcely knows by which handle to seize it. Dr. Doyle has abandoned Watson's first-person narration — the very instrument that gives the series its distinctive texture of credulous warmth — in favour of a third-person omniscience more suited to the thriller than the detective tale. The result is that we are presented not with a mystery to be solved but with a trap already laid, and the pleasure offered is not intellectual but theatrical: we watch the machinery close around its victim with the satisfaction one takes in a well-executed practical joke. The opening paragraph, however, aspires to something altogether grander than jest. That image of the blood-red gash of sunset over the Channel on the eve of the Great War, the awful hush of a continent tilting toward catastrophe, possesses a sombre eloquence that lifts these pages entirely out of the realm of popular entertainment. Doyle writes here not as the entertainer of the Strand but as a man who has felt the shadow of history fall across his desk, and the prose registers that weight with a dignity one associates with the opening movements of Conrad or the darker passages of Kipling.
Yet the comical deficiencies of the tale are quite as striking as its rhetorical ambitions, and a candid critic must name them. The story's central conceit — that Sherlock Holmes has spent two years impersonating an Irish-American agitator named Altamont, complete with goatee beard and a vocabulary liberally seasoned with expressions like "gol-darned" and "bringing home the bacon" — strains credulity well past the breaking point. We are asked to believe that the greatest analytical mind in England devoted two years to perfecting a stage-Yankee dialect so broad that Von Bork himself confesses he can "hardly understand him," and that this same performance fooled a man described as one of the Kaiser's most astute agents. The disguise belongs less to the world of espionage than to the music hall. One notes with further amusement that Holmes's method of subduing his adversary — a chloroformed sponge clapped over the face from behind — is a technique more commonly associated with penny dreadfuls than with the dignified retirement of literature's most celebrated reasoner. And the matter of Von Bork's safe combination, set four years earlier to "August 1914," requires us to accept that a German spy possessed prophetic gifts rivalling those of the Delphic oracle, a conceit so preposterous that Doyle seems almost to wink at the reader as he delivers it.
The tale's deeper oddity, and its deeper interest, lies in its confused relationship to its own genre. There is, properly speaking, no detection in "His Last Bow" at all. Holmes deduces nothing; he infiltrates, deceives, and ultimately assaults. The story is an espionage narrative grafted onto the Holmes franchise, and the graft does not quite take. Watson, demoted from narrator to chauffeur, sits in the car for the duration of the action and is rewarded with a glass of Tokay for his patience. The secondary characters — Von Herling with his ponderous diplomatic complacency, Martha the agent-housekeeper — are sketched with an efficiency that suggests Doyle understood he was writing a conte rather than a proper detective story, and was content to let situation do the work of characterisation. The exchanges between Von Bork and Altamont, in which the spy boasts of his triumphs while his supposed agent methodically catalogues the failures that Holmes himself has engineered, achieve a fine irony of dramatic structure, even if the American dialect wobbles between Chicago and the county Cork.
What redeems the story — what makes it, in fact, something approaching the memorable — is its closing passage, which belongs among the finest things Doyle ever wrote. The two old friends standing upon the terrace in the moonlight, the war about to break, and Holmes's grave prophetic speech about the east wind that will blow cold and bitter across England: here the accumulated sentiment of twenty-five years of shared adventure finds its proper valedictory note. Watson's innocent misunderstanding — "I think not, Holmes. It is very warm" — and Holmes's reply, "Good old Watson! You are the one fixed point in a changing age," achieve a poignancy that the cleverest plotting could never manufacture. For one luminous paragraph, the detective story transcends itself entirely and becomes an elegy — not merely for two fictional companions, but for the settled world they inhabited, the gaslit Victorian certainties that were about to be swept away by the mechanised horrors of the twentieth century. It is the work of a writer who knows, with the terrible clarity of 1917, that the age he has been chronicling is already dead.
""" .

:houndOfTheBaskervillesDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
This was the most rewarding of the four pieces to write, because the novel genuinely warrants serious critical engagement in a way the shorter tales only intermittently do.
The four paragraphs address what I take to be the essential critical questions: first, the Dartmoor landscape as the novel's true achievement, prose that earns comparison with Hardy; second, the brilliant structural gamble of removing Holmes and its paradoxical consequences — Watson's finest hour undermined by the revelation that Holmes was watching all along; third, the comical absurdities (the walking-stick deductions confirmed by the dog's convenient arrival at the door, the boot-theft mechanism, and the phosphorus problem — a real hound daubed in the stuff would suffer chemical burns, not supernatural radiance); and finally, what transcends the genre — the Grimpen Mire as moral emblem, Stapleton as the canon's most sophisticated villain, and that magnificent Gothic moment with Hugo's portrait. The final retrospective chapter, where Holmes briskly explains everything over dinner, struck me as a failure of nerve that Arnold in particular would have seized upon — a retreat from the novel's own dark ambitions back into the safe conventions of the form.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
It must be said at once that The Hound of the Baskervilles represents Dr. Doyle's most sustained and ambitious attempt to make the detective novel answer to the demands of serious fiction, and that the attempt succeeds more completely than one might have dared to hope. The moor is the making of it. Dartmoor enters this book not as setting but as presence — vast, indifferent, older than the human quarrels enacted upon its surface, and rendered with a descriptive power that places Doyle, for once, in the company he would not have thought to claim. The approach to Baskerville Hall, that magnificent passage in which the sunlit Devon lanes give way by imperceptible degrees to dripping moss and rotting vegetation, the distant granite hills rising like a dream landscape, the soldier silhouetted on the ridge — here is prose that does what Hardy's Egdon Heath does, subordinating human action to the geological and the elemental. Watson's lonely weeks on the moor, with their accumulating dread, their nocturnal howlings, their sense of unseen watchers and ancient malevolence, achieve an atmosphere more commonly associated with the sensation novels of Collins or Le Fanu than with the brisk rationalism of Baker Street. Doyle has stumbled, perhaps half-knowingly, upon the great truth that the detective story is at bottom a Gothic form, and that its proper territory is not the well-lit drawing-room but the haunted landscape where reason and superstition conduct their ancient war.
Yet the novel is structurally a rather curious hybrid, and the candid critic must observe that its most daring narrative decision — the removal of Sherlock Holmes from the central action for fully half its length — produces consequences that are at once its greatest distinction and its most conspicuous weakness. Watson, dispatched to Dartmoor as Holmes's proxy, becomes for the first and only time in the canon a protagonist in his own right, and the effect is unexpectedly moving: shorn of his oracle, the good doctor proves himself a man of genuine courage, keen observation, and touching self-doubt, and his reports back to Baker Street have a quality of lonely, worried honesty that Holmes's omniscient narrations could never possess. But when Holmes reappears from his hiding-place on the tor, the novel's carefully constructed atmosphere of isolation and dread collapses rather too suddenly into the familiar machinery of the detective plot. The revelation that Holmes has been lurking in a Neolithic hut all along, perfectly well-informed and merely waiting for the right moment to spring his trap, retroactively diminishes every moment of Watson's anxious solitude. We had thought ourselves alone with a brave, limited man in a terrifying place; we discover we were being stage-managed throughout. The betrayal is Holmes's, but the disappointment is the reader's.
The comical flaws of the piece are not few, and they cluster, as is Doyle's habit, around the apparatus of detection. Holmes's deductions from Dr. Mortimer's walking-stick in the opening chapter are vintage Doyle — brilliantly theatrical and cheerfully fraudulent, for the inference from tooth-marks to a dog "larger than a terrier and smaller than a mastiff" is confirmed not by logic but by the convenient arrival of the spaniel itself at the front door, a coincidence that amounts to authorial confession. The business of the stolen boots, upon which the entire plot supposedly depends (the hound requires a scent), is an intricate mechanism that Doyle never quite makes plausible: we are asked to believe that a criminal of Stapleton's ingenuity could devise no better method of obtaining Sir Henry's scent than pilfering footwear from a London hotel, and that the theft of a new boot followed by its return and the substitution of an old one would escape the notice of everyone except Holmes. The climactic revelation that the spectral hound is in fact a mortal beast dabbed with phosphorus is at once the tale's most famous moment and its most delicious absurdity — for phosphorus, as any chemist of the period might have observed, is a substance whose application to a living animal would be likely to produce not supernatural terror but chemical burns of a singularly unspectral character. One smiles and forgives, for the image of the great flaming beast bursting from the fog is too magnificent to be spoiled by chemistry.
What finally elevates The Hound above its own machinery, and indeed above nearly everything else in the literature of popular detection, is the quality that Henry James would have called its "sense of place" operating in the service of moral atmosphere. The Grimpen Mire — that great sucking bog which swallows the Dartmoor ponies and, at the last, presumably claims the villain himself — is not merely a geographical feature but a moral emblem, the physical manifestation of the quicksand upon which Stapleton's elaborate deceptions are constructed. And Stapleton himself, that lean-jawed naturalist with his butterfly net and his gentle scholarly manner, is a villain of considerably more interest than the common run of Holmes's adversaries. He is the only antagonist in the canon who matches Holmes's own method — patience, disguise, the long game — and the scene in which Holmes covers Hugo Baskerville's portrait with his hand to reveal Stapleton's face staring out from the seventeenth century is a stroke of Gothic imagination that fuses the detective plot with the ancestral curse in a manner at once rational and deeply unsettling. That Doyle cannot quite sustain this fusion to the end — the final retrospective chapter, in which Holmes tidies up every loose thread over dinner with the weary efficiency of a solicitor reading a will — is a failure of nerve rather than of talent. He had, for one sustained performance, written something that deserved to outlast its genre. That it has done so is perhaps the most instructive verdict criticism can offer.
""" .

:illustriousClientDoc 
