The comical flaw practically writes itself — Watson's doomed impersonation as a ceramics collector, undone by a single question about the Emperor Shomu, is one of the canon's most enjoyable absurdities. But the deeper interest lies in the moral territory Doyle wanders into, seemingly without fully realizing it. Holmes succeeds through burglary and the exploitation of a damaged woman's rage. The vitriol scene is written with a horrifying power that the late stories almost never achieve. And the confrontation between Kitty Winter and Violet de Merville — the ruined woman and the infatuated virgin, fury against ice — is a scene of dramatic compression that I think genuinely earns comparison with the confrontation scenes in James's own novels. The closing image of the illustrious client's coat of arms glimpsed on a departing brougham, and Holmes's quiet refusal to let Watson name the name, struck me as the most Jamesian moment in the entire canon: a study in the accommodations between power and justice, rendered entirely through what is left unsaid.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Illustrious Client" opens in the Turkish bath on Northumberland Avenue, and the setting is no accident: what follows is a tale in which the familiar certitudes of the Holmes canon are subjected to a prolonged steaming and emerge in a condition that would have been unrecognisable to readers of the earlier adventures. Dr. Doyle has written, whether entirely by design or not, the most morally unsettling story in the entire series — a narrative in which the great detective succeeds not through deduction but through burglary, deception, and the calculated exploitation of a woman's anguish, and in which the nominal victory is attended by an act of violence so grotesque that it casts its shadow backward across every preceding page. The prose itself registers this shift in register. Watson's description of Kitty Winter — that "slim, flame-like young woman" whose face bore "the leprous mark" of terrible years — achieves a quality of social portraiture more commonly found in the pages of George Gissing or Arthur Morrison than in the genteel precincts of the Strand. For the first and perhaps only time in the canon, the Holmes stories acknowledge the existence of a world of sexual predation, ruined women, and class brutality that the earlier tales had scrupulously kept outside the sitting-room door at Baker Street.
The comical deficiencies of the piece, however, are considerable, and they concentrate themselves upon the figure of poor Watson, who is here required to impersonate a collector of Chinese ceramics after twenty-four hours of cramming at the London Library. The resulting scene is one of the most deliciously absurd in the entire canon: Watson arrives at Vernon Lodge armed with a Ming saucer and a head stuffed with the names of the Hung-wu and Yung-lo periods, only to be cross-examined by the Baron on the Emperor Shomu and the Shoso-in near Nara — questions to which, naturally, he has no answer whatever. His simulated indignation at being "examined as if I were a schoolboy" is a masterpiece of bluster over vacancy, and one cannot suppress the thought that Holmes, in dispatching his friend on this errand, has committed an act of theatrical cruelty scarcely less refined than the Baron's own. That the disguise fools no one for more than five minutes — Gruner identifies Watson as Holmes's emissary almost at once — merely confirms what the attentive reader has long suspected: that Holmes's elaborate plans succeed not because they are clever but because Doyle requires them to succeed, and the villain's intelligence is permitted to operate only up to the point where the plot demands its failure.
Yet the tale's most striking feature, and its most troubling, is the moral architecture that Doyle has constructed — or, more precisely, that he has constructed without appearing to notice its implications. Holmes solves this case by committing burglary. He exploits Kitty Winter's hatred and pain as an instrument, gathering her up "at the last moment" as a tool for distraction without troubling to inquire what the "little packet" under her cloak might contain. The packet, of course, is vitriol, and the scene of its deployment — the Baron's beautiful face dissolving under the acid, one eye already white and glazed, his features transformed into something that Watson compares to a painting over which the artist has passed "a wet and foul sponge" — is written with a power that transcends anything the late Holmes stories typically achieve. Watson's confession that he "could have wept over the ruin had I not remembered very clearly the vile life which had led up to so hideous a change" is one of the most morally honest sentences in the canon, a moment where the comfortable machinery of popular justice gives way to something raw and genuinely disturbing. Doyle does not flinch, and neither, to his credit, does Watson.
What elevates "The Illustrious Client" above the common run of the Case-Book tales, then, is precisely this quality of moral discomfort — the sense that Doyle has stumbled, late in his career, upon a story that his own formula cannot quite contain. The confrontation between Kitty Winter and Violet de Merville — "flame and ice face to face," as Holmes puts it — is a scene of extraordinary dramatic compression, in which the fury of the ruined woman crashes against the glacial self-possession of the infatuated virgin, and neither emerges with the reader's unqualified sympathy. Holmes himself, beaten nearly to death in Regent Street and appearing at the Baron's window like a ghost swathed in bloody bandages, is stripped of the Olympian detachment that defines him and reduced to something far more interesting: a man who has been hurt, who is improvising desperately, and whose ultimate triumph depends upon a woman's act of vengeance that he neither orchestrated nor foresaw. The final tableau — the illustrious client's armorial bearings glimpsed on the brougham panel, Watson's excited recognition silenced by Holmes's grave "Let that now and forever be enough for us" — is a conclusion worthy of Henry James himself: a study in what cannot be spoken, in the accommodations that power makes with justice, and in the particular reticence that obtains when the interests of the very great are served by the sufferings of the very small.
""" .

