This was an irresistible story for a critic in the Arnold-James tradition, because its formal experiment — Holmes as narrator — fails so instructively.
The central argument is that Watson's voice was never mere scaffolding but the essential artistic medium of the series, and that Holmes narrating his own adventures produces something inadvertently comic: the priggish disclaimer about women being no attraction to him, delivered just after he has described Maud Bellamy's beauty at length, is a moment of unintentional self-revelation that Watson would never have permitted. The jellyfish solution violates the fundamental compact of the detective story by depending on knowledge the reader cannot possess. And there's a genuine logical flaw I flagged: if the dry towel proves McPherson never entered the water, how did a jellyfish sting him on dry shingle? Doyle seems to want the lagoon both full and empty as the plot requires.
But the Sussex landscape writing — the chalk cliffs, the darkening lagoon, the dead Airedale loyally following its master's scent — achieves a pastoral beauty that nearly transcends the botched mechanics, and Holmes's confession that the case brought him to "the limit of my powers" carries an elegiac weight that feels like the true, unintended subject of the story: the fading of a great mind in retirement.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Lion's Mane" is a tale remarkable chiefly for the boldness of its formal experiment and the completeness of its artistic failure, and a critic who respects Dr. Doyle's considerable gifts must in honesty say so. The experiment is this: for the first and only time in the canon, Holmes himself assumes the mantle of narrator, banishing Watson to a distant periphery and attempting to tell his story "in my own plain way." The result is, as Holmes himself might say, instructive. What we discover is that the great detective, stripped of his Boswell, is a bore. Watson's narrative voice — warm, credulous, perpetually astonished, humanly limited — was never merely a technical convenience; it was the very medium through which Holmes's brilliance could be perceived, the background of common clay against which the diamond showed its fire. Holmes narrating his own exploits produces a tone of insufferable self-regard that no amount of false modesty can leaven. His observation that Maud Bellamy "would have graced any assembly in the world," followed by the priggish disclaimer that "women have seldom been an attraction to me, for my brain has always governed my heart," is a passage that achieves, quite without authorial intention, one of the richest comical effects in the entire canon. One imagines Watson reading this in his morning paper and quietly smiling into his tea.
The mystery itself, however, is where the tale's real difficulties reside, for it belongs to a species of detective fiction that can only be called the zoological deus ex machina. The reader is invited to puzzle over the death of Fitzroy McPherson — the terrible welts upon his body, the agonised dying words, the absence of any human assailant — and to consider the various suspects whom Holmes parades before us with his customary methodical suspicion: the dark-tempered Ian Murdoch, the protective Bellamy father and son, even the distant figures upon the beach. All of this is conventional and competently managed. But the solution — that the murderer is Cyanea capillata, the lion's mane jellyfish, lurking in a tidal pool — is a resolution that no reader, however attentive, could possibly have anticipated, because it depends not upon the evidence presented but upon the contents of an obscure volume of popular natural history by J. G. Wood which happens to sit in Holmes's garret. The detective story, as a form, rests upon a compact between author and reader: the clues shall be visible to both, and the solution shall be one that the reader might, with sufficient ingenuity, have reached. Doyle violates this compact with a cheerful shamelessness that would make a lesser writer blush. The jellyfish might as well be a dragon.
There is, moreover, a structural absurdity that the attentive critic cannot overlook. The death of McPherson's Airedale terrier at the identical spot — the clue that finally stirs Holmes's memory — is the tale's pivot, and yet its logic is curiously backward. Holmes tells us that the folded, dry towel had already indicated that McPherson never entered the water, and that this fact ought to have directed his thoughts toward a creature of the sea. But if the victim never entered the water, in what conceivable manner did a jellyfish, however prodigious its trailing filaments, reach him upon the dry shingle? Doyle appears to want the lagoon both very full and very empty as the needs of the plot require. The second victim, Murdoch, is similarly stung at "the edge of the water," which at least preserves a minimal plausibility, but the damage to the tale's internal logic has already been done. One suspects that Doyle, having discovered the remarkable account in Wood's Out of Doors and found in it a ready-made detective plot, proceeded to write the story backward from the solution without troubling to verify that the physical circumstances of the crime were consistent with the physical habits of the criminal.
And yet the Sussex setting, one must acknowledge, achieves a quality of landscape writing that nearly redeems the implausible mechanics. Holmes in retirement among his bees, walking the chalk cliffs above the Channel in the early morning light, standing in solitary meditation beside the darkening lagoon as the shadows lengthen — these passages possess a twilight beauty that belongs not to the detective story but to the English pastoral tradition, and they give the tale an autumnal resonance that its plot does not deserve. The image of the dead Airedale, stiff and contorted upon the mat, loyally following its master's scent to the very place of death, touches upon something more durable than the ingenuities of detection — the mute fidelity of the animal world, rendered with the plain directness that is Doyle's surest gift. If "The Lion's Mane" fails as a detective story, it half-succeeds as an elegy for retirement, for solitude, and for the fading of powers that were once supreme. Holmes confesses, in a rare moment of genuine self-knowledge, that the case brought him "so completely to the limit of my powers" — and the reader, noting the ageing detective groping alone through his garret for a half-remembered book, may feel that the admission carries a weight beyond the merely professional.
""" .

