Here is the critical review of "The Man with the Twisted Lip." I think this may be the strongest of the stories you've given me to assess — and consequently the review that gave me the most pleasure to write.
The comical flaw is a beauty: Holmes spends the entire tale constructing an elegant theory of murder from bloodstains, a weighted coat, and a vanished body — every inference impeccable, every conclusion wrong. He then sits up all night on a mountain of pillows consuming an ounce of tobacco in heroic meditation, only to arrive at a solution whose chief instrument is a bath sponge. The symmetry of the double disguise — Holmes wiping away his opium-den makeup in the same story where he wipes away the beggar's face to reveal the gentleman — struck me as almost too perfect to have been entirely deliberate.
But the deeper interest is moral and social. St. Clair's confession is quietly devastating to Victorian assumptions about respectability: a man earns more in a day of theatrical begging than in a week of honest journalism, and the story's sympathies are entirely with the impostor. Holmes pats him on the shoulder, the inspector agrees to hush it up, the wife is never told. The opium den opening, meanwhile, belongs to the literature of the urban inferno — Dickens and Conrad, not detective fiction. And Mrs. St. Clair in her doorway, hand raised in hope, refusing to be patronised, demolishing Holmes's murder theory with a single letter, is one of the most finely drawn women in the canon. The story ends not with the usual satisfaction of the solved puzzle but with an unanswerable question about the distance between a respectable man and a very good actor.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Man with the Twisted Lip" is that rarest of achievements in the Sherlock Holmes canon: a story in which the detective plot, the social observation, and the moral imagination are so thoroughly fused that the tale arrives at a destination more interesting than its machinery could have predicted. It begins in an opium den, and the opening pages — Watson's nocturnal descent into the Bar of Gold in Upper Swandam Lane — constitute some of the most accomplished descriptive prose Doyle ever wrote. The steep steps worn hollow by drunken feet, the long low room thick with brown smoke, the terraced wooden berths like the forecastle of an emigrant ship, and those glimmering red circles of light waxing and waning in the bowls of metal pipes: here is a passage that belongs not to the tidy world of detective fiction but to the literature of the urban inferno, a scene that earns its place beside the East End of Dickens and the London docks of Conrad. That Holmes himself should materialise out of this vaporous hell — the decrepit old man by the brazier suddenly filling out, his wrinkles vanishing, his dull eyes regaining their fire — is a coup de théâtre that Doyle would attempt many times thereafter but never surpass. The disguise is not merely a plot device; it is a metaphor for the story's deepest concern, which is the distance between appearance and identity, between the face one shows the world and the self that crouches behind it.
For the mystery that Holmes is investigating turns out, with exquisite irony, to be no crime at all. Neville St. Clair, respectable gentleman of Lee in Kent, loving husband and affectionate father, is in fact Hugh Boone, the celebrated beggar of Threadneedle Street — a man who earns seven hundred pounds a year by painting a scar on his face and twisting his lip with a slip of flesh-coloured plaster. The comical absurdities of the tale cluster around this revelation and the elaborate chain of false inference that precedes it. Holmes, the great rationalist, constructs an entirely plausible theory of murder from bloodstains, a weighted coat, and an open window — every detail dovetailing beautifully and every conclusion entirely wrong. The blood came from a cut finger. The coat was thrown into the Thames by the supposed victim himself. The murder scene is in fact a dressing-room. One relishes the spectacle of the master detective spending an entire night perched upon a mound of pillows, consuming an ounce of shag tobacco in heroic cogitation, only to arrive at a solution whose chief instrument is a bath sponge. That Holmes wipes away the beggar's face to reveal the gentleman beneath, while he himself has spent the evening wiping away his own disguise as a decrepit opium-smoker, is a symmetry so perfect that one suspects Doyle achieved it half by instinct rather than design.
Yet the tale's most remarkable quality — the quality that lifts it above the ingenuity of its plot — is its uneasy moral reckoning with the world of Victorian respectability. St. Clair's confession is at once pathetic and deeply subversive. A man of education discovers that he can earn more in a day by smearing paint on his face and sitting on a pavement than he can in a week of honest journalism. The "long fight between my pride and the money" is settled, as such fights generally are, in favour of the money, and the result is a comfortable villa, a loving wife, two children, and a life constructed entirely upon fraud. Doyle, who was himself a struggling young doctor when he turned to fiction, must have felt the force of this parable more keenly than he perhaps intended, for the story's sympathies are unmistakably with the impostor. Holmes pats St. Clair kindly on the shoulder. The inspector agrees to suppress the case. The wife is never told. The only punishment proposed is that the begging must cease — and even this is softened by the understanding that a man who earns seven hundred pounds annually by his wits has perhaps committed a sin against nothing more substantial than propriety. The tale that began as a murder mystery ends as a comedy of bourgeois manners, and the laughter, if one listens carefully, has a distinctly nervous edge.
What finally distinguishes this story, and secures for it a place among the finest half-dozen tales in the canon, is its rendering of the domestic world that St. Clair's double life both sustains and betrays. Mrs. St. Clair, standing in the doorway of The Cedars in her pink chiffon with one hand raised in eager hope, is drawn with a tenderness and economy that Watson — and through him, Doyle — rarely lavishes upon his female characters. Her quiet interrogation of Holmes over the cold supper, her refusal to be patronised ("I am not hysterical, nor given to fainting"), and her triumphant production of the letter that demolishes Holmes's theory of murder, constitute one of the most finely managed domestic scenes in the entire series. Against this warmth, the midnight ride through the deserted London streets — the murky river, the dull wrack drifting across the sky, the heavy footfall of the policeman — achieves the quality of a moral landscape, the dark through which the comfortable classes must pass on their way home from the places where their comfort is manufactured. Doyle would write more ingenious plots, but he would rarely again write a story in which the mystery, once solved, leaves the reader not with satisfaction but with a question that has no comfortable answer: what, precisely, is the difference between a respectable man and a very good actor?
""" .

:mazarinStoneDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
The story's origins as a one-act stage piece (The Crown Diamond) explain nearly every deficiency: the action confined to a single room, the characters entering and exiting like clockwork, the dialogue that announces every motive aloud. The third-person narration is its most damaging feature — Watson is present but shunted offstage like an inconvenient supernumerary, and the resulting voice has neither his warmth nor any compensating virtue. The villains are music-hall types rather than characters: Count Sylvius with his eagle beak and flamboyant necktie, Sam Merton scratching his pate and saying "guv'nor."
The comical absurdities are legion. The gramophone-for-violin substitution is the most egregious — a 1903 phonograph playing through a closed door, mistaken for live performance. The waxwork dummy is recycled from "The Empty House" without the plot justification it had there. And Holmes slipping a Crown jewel into Lord Cantlemere's pocket as a practical joke is Doyle at his most recklessly self-indulgent, a conjurer so delighted with the trick that he has forgotten it's supposed to serve the story. Still, there are flashes — the lion-hunting exchange, Holmes's quip about horizontal and perpendicular exits, Billy's backstage gossip — that remind us what the old machinery could still produce when a genuine spark caught.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
One approaches "The Mazarin Stone" with the uncomfortable sensation of watching a once-distinguished author rummage through his own wardrobe of theatrical properties and discover that the costumes no longer fit. Every device on display here — the waxwork dummy in the window, the air-gun pointed from across the street, the villain who arrives at Baker Street to confront Holmes personally, even the faithful Billy the page-boy — has been employed before in the canon, and employed better. The dummy reprises its appearance from "The Empty House," where it drew the fire of Colonel Sebastian Moran with genuine dramatic force; here it serves no function that the plot requires, for Count Sylvius has arrived to commit his violence in person with a loaded stick rather than from a sniper's distance. The tale is, in fact, an adaptation of Doyle's own one-act play The Crown Diamond, and it reads as one: the action is confined almost entirely to a single room, the characters enter and exit with the mechanical regularity of stage doors, and the dialogue, though intermittently lively, has that quality of over-articulated exposition — every motive announced, every scheme narrated aloud — that belongs to the footlights rather than to the page. One misses, acutely, the texture of the world beyond the sitting-room walls, the London streets and fog-bound alleys and rattling hansoms that give the best Holmes stories their density of lived experience.
The most conspicuous formal peculiarity, however, is the narration itself, which has been wrenched into a lame and unsatisfying third person. Watson is present but demoted to a bystander whom the plot must eject from the room before the action proper can begin, and the resulting voice — "It was pleasant to Dr. Watson to find himself once more in the untidy room" — possesses neither Watson's endearing warmth nor the focused intensity that Holmes brought to his own narration in "The Lion's Mane." It is the voice of a theatrical stage direction dressed up as fiction, and it produces a fatal distance between the reader and the events described. Watson is sent off to Scotland Yard as one dispatches an inconvenient character into the wings, and his departure leaves us alone with Holmes and a pair of villains who, for all the menace attributed to them, are drawn with the broad strokes of melodrama rather than the careful observation of character. Count Negretto Sylvius, with his eagle nose and flamboyant necktie and big-game-shooting credentials, is the stuff of penny dreadfuls; Sam Merton, the dim-witted boxer who says "guv'nor" and scratches his pate, could have wandered in from a music-hall sketch. They are types, not persons, and the story never troubles to make them otherwise.
The central trick upon which the tale depends — Holmes retiring to the bedroom to play his violin, substituting a gramophone for himself, then creeping through a second door to replace the waxwork dummy and overhear the villains' private conference — is the comical centrepiece of the story, and it is, one must say plainly, preposterous. We are asked to believe that two hardened criminals, sitting in the very room where a life-sized effigy has already been pointed out to one of them as a fake, will fail to notice that the same effigy has been replaced by a living man. We are asked to accept that a gramophone of 1903 vintage, playing through a closed bedroom door, could be mistaken for the sound of a violin in the next room — though Merton does, to his credit, register a dim suspicion about the curtains. And we are asked to swallow the final indignity: that Holmes, having recovered a Crown jewel of incalculable value, will slip it into the overcoat pocket of a sceptical peer as a practical joke, risking the loss of the very object for which the entire enterprise was undertaken, merely for the pleasure of seeing Lord Cantlemere stammer. The scene is Doyle at his most self-indulgent, a conjurer so pleased with his sleight of hand that he has forgotten the trick is supposed to serve the story rather than interrupt it.
And yet even here, in what must be reckoned among the weakest tales in the canon, there are flashes of the old vitality that remind one of what Doyle could do when his invention was fully engaged. The exchange between Holmes and the Count on the subject of lion-hunting — the Count's boast of sport, excitement, and danger met by Holmes's dry "And, no doubt, to free the country from a pest?" — is managed with the epigrammatic precision of the best Baker Street repartee. Holmes's observation that his own exit is unlikely to be horizontal while the Count's may well prove perpendicular has a lethal elegance that briefly raises the temperature of an otherwise tepid encounter. And Billy the page, dispensing his backstage gossip about the Prime Minister, the Home Secretary, and the insufferable Lord Cantlemere with the cheerful authority of a man who has seen it all, is a minor comic creation of considerable charm. These fragments remind us that even in decline, Doyle's theatrical instincts could still produce individual moments of sharp pleasure. The misfortune of "The Mazarin Stone" is that these moments occur not within a living narrative but within a mechanism — a clockwork entertainment in which the springs are visible, the paint is chipped, and the figures jerk through their appointed motions with the stiff predictability of automata.
""" .

:milvertonDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
It posed the rewarding challenge of a tale that is morally subversive precisely because it is so thoroughly entertaining.
The comical pleasures are wonderful: Holmes's sham engagement to the housemaid, his exhibition of the nickel-plated burgling kit like a boy with Christmas presents, Watson's absurd threat to inform on Holmes to the police unless allowed to come along, the two of them in evening dress and black silk masks cutting circles from greenhouse glass. But the deeper current runs toward something genuinely disturbing. Milverton himself is the canon's most effective villain because he is the only one who operates entirely within the law — that Pickwickian face purring over the mathematics of other people's ruin. The murder scene behind the curtain is Doyle at his most compressed and powerful: the unnamed woman's speech without self-pity, the heel ground into the dead face, Holmes's cold restraining grip on Watson's wrist conveying the entire moral argument in a single physical gesture.
The coda is masterfully managed. Holmes's calm declaration to Lestrade that "there are certain crimes which the law cannot touch" is a philosophical position delivered by a man concealing his own presence at the scene. And that final image — recognising the murderess in a shop-window photograph, the finger silently pressed to the lips — extends the conspiracy of silence from Holmes to Watson to the reader. Doyle has written a story in which law, morality, and justice are three entirely separate things, and his hero's serene choice of the last over the first two is, as I noted, a distinction that Arnold himself might have appreciated.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"Charles Augustus Milverton" is the tale in which Doyle most fully surrenders to an impulse that had been growing quietly throughout the canon — the impulse to make Holmes not the servant of the law but its superior, a moral agent who operates by a private code that the official machinery of justice is too blunt, too timid, or too compromised to enforce. The result is what one might call the most thrilling and the most ethically reckless story in the entire series, a narrative in which the great detective commits burglary, witnesses murder, destroys evidence, lies to a police inspector, and declines to investigate the crime — and in which the reader, carried along by the magnificent velocity of the prose, applauds him at every step. Doyle achieves this moral seduction through the portrait of Milverton himself, who is among the finest villains in the literature of crime. The Pickwickian benevolence of that plump, bespectacled face, the frozen perpetual smile, the smooth voice purring over the mathematics of ruin — "It is almost incredible, but the absurd sum of twelve hundred pounds would have settled the whole question" — these details produce a figure more disturbing than any of the canon's murderers, because Milverton operates entirely within the protection of the law. Holmes's famous declaration that he has dealt with fifty murderers but never felt the repulsion this man inspires is not mere rhetoric; it is the moral premise upon which the entire tale is constructed, and it is persuasive because Doyle has taken the care to make us feel it.
The comical dimensions of the piece, however, should not be overlooked, for they are considerable and they cluster, with characteristic Doylean irony, around Holmes's preparations for crime. His sham engagement to Milverton's housemaid — the rakish young plumber "Escott" who walks out with the girl each evening to learn the layout of the house — is an act of romantic fraud that Watson protests and Holmes waves away with the assurance that a "hated rival" will conveniently appear the moment his back is turned. The heartlessness of this is played as comedy, and Holmes's exhibition of his burgling kit — the nickel-plated jemmy, the diamond-tipped glass-cutter, "every modern improvement which the march of civilization demands" — has the quality of a boy showing off his Christmas presents. Watson, for his part, threatens to inform on Holmes to the police unless permitted to join the expedition, which must rank as the most affectionately absurd ultimatum in the history of friendship. That the two men put on evening dress to look like theatre-goers returning home, then proceed to don black silk masks and cut a circle of glass from a greenhouse window, produces a tonal mixture of drawing-room comedy and Gothic sensation that only Doyle at the height of his powers could sustain without the seams showing.
But the tale's centre of gravity, and the passage that raises it from the level of superior entertainment to something approaching the genuinely disturbing, is the murder scene witnessed from behind the curtain. The unnamed woman — veiled, mantled, quivering with controlled fury — who confronts Milverton with the ruin of her husband and empties her revolver into his body is rendered with a dramatic compression that Doyle rarely equalled. Her speech is spare and devastating, entirely without self-pity, and her final gesture — grinding her heel into the upturned face of the dead man — is an image of such savage, deliberate violence that it shocks even in a tale that has prepared us for moral extremity. Holmes's response is the most revealing moment: his cold hand gripping Watson's wrist, restraining him from interference, communicating in that single physical gesture the complete moral argument — that this is justice, that it is not their affair, that they have their own duties. It is a moment in which the reader is made complicit in a moral calculus that the official world would find monstrous, and the fact that it feels not monstrous but inevitable is the measure of Doyle's narrative authority.
What finally secures the tale's distinction is its coda, which manages in a few pages to be at once the most audacious and the most delicate passage in the Return collection. Holmes and Watson flee across Hampstead Heath at a dead run, scale a glass-topped wall, and arrive home to breakfast and their morning pipe as though nothing had occurred. Lestrade appears to invite Holmes to investigate the murder, and Holmes's refusal — "there are certain crimes which the law cannot touch, and which therefore, to some extent, justify private revenge" — is delivered with the calm of a man stating a philosophical position rather than concealing his own presence at the scene. The description of the fugitives could be Watson's own, and Holmes's impudent observation that it "might be a description of Watson" sends both men into shared, silent, incriminating laughter. The final image — Holmes recognising the murderess's photograph in a shop window on Oxford Street, and silently pressing his finger to his lips — closes the tale with a gesture of complicity that extends from Holmes to Watson to the reader, binding all three in a conspiracy of silence that is, in its way, more subversive than any crime the canon has to offer. Doyle has written a story in which law, morality, and justice are three entirely different things, and in which his hero chooses the last of these with a serenity that Matthew Arnold, who insisted always upon the distinction between conduct and convention, might well have admired.
