The comical pleasures are considerable: Holmes's lordly ignorance of rugby, Overton's bewildered sixteen-stone dismay that anyone could not know Godfrey Staunton, the entire Varsity crisis resolved in a throwaway newspaper report buried near the end. Lord Mount-James, that "noble miser" who arrives dressed like an undertaker's mute and offers a fiver — "or even a tenner" — is a comic grotesque worthy of Dickens. But the real delight is Dr. Armstrong, who may be the most satisfying adversary in the entire canon precisely because he is not a villain: his sardonic courtesy in catching Holmes on the bicycle, his note the following morning, his elaborate detour roads across the flat Cambridgeshire countryside — all of it conducted not in the service of crime but in the service of compassion.
The syringe-and-draghound solution is wonderful comedy, the cocaine instrument repurposed as a detective tool in a jest that works against the accumulated dread of the whole series. But the real destination — the dead wife, the kneeling husband, Armstrong's devastating rebuke — transforms the tale into something that questions the fundamental premise of detective fiction: that hidden things must always be brought to light. Holmes's silent exit into the pale winter sunlight, with nothing to say and nothing gained, is the most quietly devastating moment in the Return collection. Doyle has written a story in which the detective's success is indistinguishable from a violation of privacy, and the only proper response is the silence with which it ends.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Missing Three-Quarter" is a detective story that has the peculiar distinction of being about the wrong thing, and of arriving at a destination so entirely unrelated to its point of departure that the reader may be forgiven for suspecting Dr. Doyle of having begun one tale and finished another. It opens in the world of University rugby football — a world that Holmes announces he knows nothing about, in a passage of lordly condescension toward amateur sport that is itself one of the tale's unintentional comedies. Cyril Overton, sixteen stone of bone and muscle, arrives in Baker Street in a state of operatic distress over the disappearance of his three-quarter, and proceeds to deliver a speech of such earnest tactical specificity — Moorhouse edges into the scrum, Stevenson cannot drop from the twenty-five line, Morton and Johnson would romp round him — that Holmes listens with the expression of a man hearing a foreign language he has resolved not to learn. The comedy of mutual incomprehension is beautifully managed: Overton cannot conceive of a man who has not heard of Godfrey Staunton; Holmes cannot conceive of a world in which such ignorance would be remarkable. That the entire crisis of the Varsity match is ultimately resolved in a two-sentence newspaper report — Oxford won by a goal and two tries — buried deep in the final pages, is Doyle's quiet joke upon the reader who imagined that sport was the point.
The real business of the story, however, lies in the investigation at Cambridge, and here one encounters what may be the most engaging of all Holmes's adversaries: Dr. Leslie Armstrong, the formidable physician with the granite jaw and the European reputation, who outwits the detective at nearly every turn. Armstrong detects Holmes following his brougham on a bicycle and turns back with devastating courtesy to inquire whether his carriage is impeding the passage — a scene of such delicious social mortification that Holmes himself can only admire it. He sends Holmes a note the following morning that is a masterpiece of sardonic economy. He employs detour roads and rear-window surveillance to shake off pursuit across the flat Cambridgeshire countryside. For two full days, the great detective is stymied, reduced to tramping fruitlessly through Chesterton, Histon, Waterbeach, and Oakington — the litany of failed villages constituting a rare and rather touching confession of impotence. That Holmes finally resorts to squirting aniseed from a hypodermic syringe onto the wheel of Armstrong's brougham and borrowing a draghound named Pompey is at once an admission of defeat by conventional methods and a moment of pure comic invention. The syringe, which Watson associates with horror and which the reader has been trained to dread as the instrument of Holmes's cocaine habit, is here redeemed as a detective tool — a jest that works precisely because it plays against the accumulated anxiety of the entire canon.
But the tale's true surprise, and its most considerable achievement, lies in what the detection uncovers: not crime, not conspiracy, not even the kidnapping that Holmes floats to terrify the miserable Lord Mount-James, but grief — private, desperate, consuming grief. Godfrey Staunton has disappeared because his secretly married wife is dying of consumption in a lonely cottage outside Cambridge, and because Dr. Armstrong, out of love for his young friend and respect for the sanctity of suffering, has been orchestrating an elaborate campaign of concealment to keep the world from intruding upon the deathbed. The final scene — Holmes pushing open the cottage door to find the beautiful young woman dead upon the bed, her golden hair tangled about her, and Staunton kneeling at her feet racked with sobs — achieves a quality of restrained pathos that the canon very rarely attempts and still more rarely earns. Armstrong's rebuke is devastating: "You have attained your end, and have certainly chosen a particularly delicate moment for your intrusion." Holmes, for once, has nothing clever to say. His investigation, technically brilliant, has been morally superfluous. The mystery was never a mystery at all; it was a secret, and secrets, unlike crimes, have a right to remain unviolated.
What finally secures the tale's distinction among the Return stories is the closing passage, which manages in a few spare sentences to accomplish what many of the more celebrated adventures never quite achieve: a genuine reckoning between the demands of detection and the claims of private life. Holmes grasps Dr. Armstrong's hand — the hand of the man who has bested him, lied to him, and been entirely right to do so. "Come, Watson," he says, and they pass from the house of grief into the pale sunlight of the winter day. It is the most quietly devastating exit in the canon: no explanation, no retrospection, no tying-up of threads. The football match has been lost, the young wife is dead, the investigation has served no purpose that decency could approve. Doyle has written, perhaps without fully recognising what he had done, a story that calls into question the fundamental premise of the detective form — that the truth is always worth discovering, that the hidden must always be brought to light — and has answered the question with a silence that Matthew Arnold, who understood better than most the difference between curiosity and wisdom, would have recognised as the highest form of critical intelligence.
""" .

