This is one of the great stories — a tale in which Doyle fuses the detective plot with the historical romance and discovers that each illuminates the other.
The comical flaw I identified is the trigonometry of the shadow. Holmes's calculation depends on an elm that was sixty-four feet tall when measured in the nineteenth century, but the Ritual dates from the seventeenth century, and elms do not hold a fixed height across three hundred years. The whole treasure-map mechanism requires a tree to function as a constant when trees are by nature variables. Brunton's cover story for inquiring about the elm's height — "some little argument with the groom" — is a fabrication so transparent one can only admire his nerve and marvel at Musgrave's credulity. Doyle's arithmetic works only if one does not think about trees, which is perhaps the most characteristic demand the Holmes stories make upon their readers.
But the deeper achievements are remarkable. The Ritual itself is a genuine piece of literary creation — liturgical prose that sounds authentically seventeenth-century without being traceable to any source. Brunton is one of the most interesting figures in the canon: a man whose intelligence was trapped by class, whose mind was sharper than ten generations of his masters', and whose very brilliance led to his destruction in a cellar beneath a flagstone. Holmes's reconstruction of Rachel Howells's vengeance — the questions he leaves half-unanswered about whether the wooden prop slipped by chance or by design — is Doyle at his most morally scrupulous.
And the crown itself, battered and shapeless, its stones lustreless until rubbed on a sleeve to reveal a spark — recovered by a dead butler and a mad housemaid — is an image worthy of Scott at his most elegiac. Doyle has written a treasure story in which the treasure is the least important thing discovered.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Musgrave Ritual" occupies a singular position in the canon, for it is a tale in which Doyle discovers — almost, one suspects, to his own surprise — that the detective story and the historical romance are not merely compatible but can be made to illuminate one another with a force that neither possesses alone. The opening is among the most celebrated domestic passages in the series: Watson's exasperated catalogue of Holmes's personal habits, the cigars in the coal-scuttle, the tobacco in the Persian slipper, the unanswered correspondence transfixed by a jack-knife to the mantelpiece, and above all the patriotic V.R. done in bullet-pocks upon the sitting-room wall. This is comic writing of a very high order, and it achieves something more than comedy, for it establishes the texture of a shared life — the daily friction of two temperaments yoked by affection and proximity — with a vividness that persuades us to trust whatever follows. When Holmes drags forth his tin box of early cases and begins to handle the bundles of paper with a "tender, caressing sort of way," we are in the presence of a man revealing not merely his professional history but his emotional interior, and the tale that emerges — of the young Holmes in his Montague Street rooms, hungry for his first real case — has an autobiographical intimacy that the more conventional adventures rarely attempt.
The Ritual itself is the tale's great invention, and Doyle manages it with a sureness of touch that conceals considerable structural ingenuity. The catechism — "Whose was it?" "His who is gone." "Who shall have it?" "He who will come." — is a fragment of genuine literary creation, a piece of liturgical prose that sounds authentically seventeenth-century without being traceable to any actual source, and whose riddling cadences produce in the reader precisely the mixture of bafflement and half-apprehension that they produced in ten generations of bewildered Musgraves. That the butler Brunton should be the one to crack the code — a man of first-rate intelligence trapped by class in a position beneath his capacities — adds a note of social irony that enriches the tale without ever becoming tendentious. Holmes's tribute to Brunton's mind, delivered to the face of the man's employer — "your butler appears to me to have been a very clever man, and to have had a clearer insight than ten generations of his masters" — is a remark that would not be out of place in the social fiction of Gissing, and it establishes the butler as something more than a victim: a figure whose intelligence was simultaneously his distinction and his destruction.
The outdoor investigation — Holmes's trigonometric pursuit of a shadow cast by a tree that no longer exists — is the comical and intellectual centrepiece, and it must be said that the mathematics, while presented with an air of triumphant precision, do not altogether survive scrutiny. Holmes measures a six-foot rod's shadow at nine feet, calculates the sixty-four-foot elm would cast a shadow of ninety-six feet, and proceeds confidently to his destination. But the Ritual, if its directions are to have remained valid across centuries, must refer to a specific date and hour — the sixth month, when the sun is over the oak — and the shadow of an elm that was sixty-four feet in the seventeenth century cannot have been sixty-four feet in the nineteenth, since elms, unlike oaks, do not survive three hundred years at a fixed height. Brunton, we are told, had the foresight to ask Musgrave the elm's height "some months ago, in connection with some little argument with the groom" — a fabrication so transparent that one can only admire the butler's nerve and wonder at the squire's credulity. Doyle's arithmetic, in short, works only if one does not think about trees, which is perhaps the most characteristic demand the Holmes stories make upon their readers. It is a tribute to the narrative momentum that almost no one notices.
But what finally elevates "The Musgrave Ritual" above its ingenious machinery is the discovery in the cellar and the imaginative reconstruction that follows it. The body of Brunton, squatting on his hams with his face pressed against the empty box, his countenance liver-coloured from the stagnant blood drawn downward by his posture of death — this is an image of genuine Gothic power, the more disturbing for being rendered with clinical precision rather than melodramatic excess. And Holmes's reconstruction of Rachel Howells's vengeance — the passionate Welsh girl watching from above as her faithless lover crouches in the pit, the sudden removal of the wooden prop, the slab crashing down to seal his tomb — is narrated not as certainty but as speculation, a sequence of questions that Holmes puts to himself and leaves half-unanswered: "Was it a chance that the wood had slipped?" "Had she only been guilty of silence as to his fate?" This is Doyle at his most scrupulous, refusing to resolve the moral ambiguity that gives the scene its power. The crown of the Stuarts, battered and shapeless, fished from the mere where the mad girl flung it — this "relic" that once encircled the brows of kings, now reduced to blackened metal and lustreless stones that must be rubbed on a sleeve to reveal a spark — is an image worthy of Sir Walter Scott at his most elegiac, a meditation upon the ruin that time works upon all human grandeur. That it should be recovered by a butler who died for it and a housemaid who went mad makes the moral perfectly, and perfectly without comment. Doyle has written a treasure story in which the treasure itself is the least important thing discovered.
""" .

