This is a story that gave me the interesting challenge of a tale that is simultaneously overlong and genuinely distinguished — a structure that creaks and a centre that shines.
The rose passage is the heart of the matter: Holmes breaking off an investigation to deliver a meditation on flowers as evidence of Providence, while Phelps and Miss Harrison stare at him in bewildered disappointment. It's the most unexpected moment in the canon, and a critic in the Arnold-James tradition must recognise it as a point where Doyle stumbles upon something his formula was never designed to contain — a detective whose interior life is richer and stranger than his analytical method can express. The board-school eruption on the railway viaduct belongs to the same vein: Holmes gazing upon a sordid London vista and seeing lighthouses and beacons of the future.
The structural weakness is real, however. The long middle investigation — Forbes, Lord Holdhurst, the fruitless cab advertisement — generates enormous investigative energy that leads nowhere. Holmes solves the case not by deduction but by squatting in a rhododendron bush all night, which is stakeout work rather than ratiocination. The breakfast dish-cover revelation is a moment of theatrical cruelty so extravagant that even Holmes confesses it was "too bad" — nine weeks of brain-fever resolved as a conjuring trick over curried chicken. But the portrait of Phelps himself, querulous and nervous and unable to speak of anything but the treaty while Watson vainly tries to interest him in Afghanistan, is the most fully realised client portrait in the Memoirs. And Joseph Harrison — plump, merry-eyed, a stock-market gambler with a knife — embodies Doyle's quiet understanding that the most dangerous people are not criminal masterminds but desperate ordinary men.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Naval Treaty" is the longest and most ambitiously constructed of the Memoir stories, and it exhibits with peculiar clarity both the reach of Doyle's narrative gifts and the structural weaknesses to which his method was susceptible when he allowed a tale to sprawl beyond its natural dimensions. The opening is magnificently managed. Watson's memory of "Tadpole" Phelps — the brilliant schoolboy whom it was "a piquant thing to chevy about the playground and hit over the shins with a wicket" — establishes in a single sentence the cruelty of English boyhood and the fragility of the man who has never outgrown it. When that same Phelps reappears, nine weeks into a brain-fever, dictating his desperate letter in a woman's hand, the transformation from triumphant scholar to shattered invalid is complete, and we feel it because Doyle has made us feel the boy first. The journey to Woking, the balmy summer air through the open window, the pale young man clutching his nurse's hand upon the sofa — these are rendered with a quiet domestic tenderness that Doyle reserved for his best work. And then, at the precise centre of Phelps's painstaking recitation of the theft, Holmes breaks off the investigation to admire a moss-rose, and delivers his astonishing meditation upon flowers as evidence of divine benevolence. It is the single most unexpected passage in the canon — the great rationalist arguing from a rose to the goodness of Providence — and the bewildered silence of Phelps and Miss Harrison, staring at the detective with "surprise and a good deal of disappointment," is one of Doyle's finest comic touches. Holmes has solved the case, or very nearly; the rose is not a digression but a celebration, though no one in the room but Holmes yet knows it.
The investigation itself, however, is where the tale's machinery creaks most audibly. Phelps's account of the theft from the Foreign Office is narrated with admirable circumstantial precision — the corridor, the staircase, the Charles Street door, the sleeping commissionaire, the ringing bell — and yet when Holmes arrives at his solution, the chain of reasoning that connects these facts to Joseph Harrison is thin almost to the point of invisibility. Holmes deduces the thief's identity from two slender facts: that Harrison knew the Foreign Office well enough to have entered by the side door, and that the papers were hidden in Phelps's bedroom, from which Harrison was ejected when the invalid was carried home. These are suggestive, but they are not the products of the dazzling analytical method the tale has promised us. The long middle section — the visit to the frigid Forbes at Scotland Yard, the interview with Lord Holdhurst in Downing Street, the cab advertisement that yields nothing — is an elaborate display of investigative energy that leads precisely nowhere, and the true solution is reached not by deduction but by Holmes's decision to squat all night in a rhododendron bush and wait for the thief to return. This is stakeout work, not ratiocination, and the admission is quietly devastating to the tale's intellectual pretensions. Watson's observation that when Holmes is taciturn he is generally on the scent is a charming piece of misdirection, but it cannot entirely conceal the fact that the great detective has, for two-thirds of this very long story, been marking time.
The comical dimensions are considerable and, characteristically, unintended. The breakfast scene at Baker Street — in which Holmes conceals the recovered treaty under a dish-cover and invites the wretched Phelps to "try the dish before you," knowing full well that the man will discover a cylinder of blue-grey paper where he expected curried chicken — is a moment of theatrical cruelty so extravagant that Holmes himself acknowledges it with a grin: "It was too bad to spring it on you like this." It is indeed too bad. Phelps has been nine weeks in a brain-fever, his career and honour hang in the balance, and Holmes converts the moment of his salvation into a conjuring trick at breakfast, complete with a mischievous twinkle and an audience of two. That Phelps seizes Holmes's hand and kisses it rather than striking him across the face is a measure of the power differential between detective and client that the tale has everywhere exploited. Equally comical, though perhaps more intentionally so, is Holmes's excursion past the board-schools on the railway viaduct — "Lighthouses, my boy! Beacons of the future!" — an outburst of civic optimism so wildly incongruous with the sordid view from the carriage window that Watson reasonably assumes his friend is joking. These sudden eruptions of feeling — the rose, the schools, the wounded hand passed off as a scratch — suggest a Holmes whose interior life is far richer and stranger than the analytical machine Watson customarily presents.
What finally redeems the tale's structural looseness and secures its place among the notable adventures is the portrait of Percy Phelps himself, who is the most fully realised client in the Memoir collection. His querulousness, his nervous vanity, his touching reliance upon Holmes's opinion, his inability to eat or sleep or talk of anything but the lost treaty — these are not the conventional marks of the detective-story victim but the observed symptoms of a man in genuine psychological distress, and Watson, who remembers him as a boy, records them with a diagnostic precision that belongs to the medical man as much as to the chronicler. The long evening at Baker Street, in which Watson tries vainly to interest Phelps in Afghanistan, India, social questions, "anything which might take his mind out of the groove," is a passage of quiet, realistic comedy that no other writer of detective fiction in the 1890s could have produced. And Joseph Harrison — the plump, merry-eyed brother-in-law who shakes hands with effusion and turns out to be a stock-market gambler with a knife — is a villain whose very ordinariness is more unsettling than the theatrical menace of a Moriarty. Doyle understood, as his imitators generally did not, that the most dangerous people in the world are not criminal masterminds but desperate men who happen to be standing in the right corridor at the wrong moment.
""" .

