This is a fascinating case for the critic — a story in which the mystery is essentially nonexistent, solved before the client even arrives, and yet which succeeds on entirely different grounds than those it advertises.
Lord St. Simon is the real subject, and he's drawn with a comic precision that suggests Doyle understood the English aristocracy far better than his detective plots usually demanded. "I was amused by her society, and she could see that I was amused" — that reduction of courtship to condescension is worthy of Wilde. His theory that his bride must have gone mad, since no sane woman could turn her back upon what he represents, achieves a vanity so monumental it becomes almost touching. And Holmes's "No, I am descending" — from a king to a lord — sails cleanly over St. Simon's head.
The structural weakness is plain: there is no real detection. Holmes finds the Moultons through a hotel register in an afternoon. The elaborate cold supper ordered to Baker Street in advance tells us everything — this is a man preparing a dinner party, not closing a case. Lestrade dragging the Serpentine in his pea-jacket, solemnly presenting a wet wedding dress as evidence of murder, is delicious comedy but not investigation.
What saves the tale is Hatty Doran's voice — her American plainness cutting through all the social machinery: "We can't command our love, but we can our actions." That single sentence contains more ethical substance than the whole of St. Simon's self-presentation. Beneath the disguise of a detective story, Doyle has written a small transatlantic comedy in which the New World's candour defeats the Old World's ceremony — a collision that James himself might have recognised with professional respect.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Noble Bachelor" is a tale that presents itself as a detective story and turns out to be a comedy of manners — or rather, a comedy of two civilisations colliding across a breakfast-table, in which the mystery is solved almost before it is posed and the real interest lies not in the detection but in the social embarrassment that follows. Holmes announces that he has formed his conclusions before Lord St. Simon has even entered the room, and the admission, delivered with a whisky and soda in hand, ought to deflate the tale entirely. That it does not is owing to Doyle's decision to fill the vacuum left by absent suspense with something rarer in the canon: sustained social comedy of a quality that belongs less to the literature of crime than to the drawing-room fiction of the period. The newspaper extracts that Watson reads aloud — the society column's acid observation that "the present free-trade principle appears to tell heavily against our home product," the curt Morning Post paragraph, the breathless account of the vanishing bride — constitute a miniature anthology of Victorian journalistic styles, each voice perfectly differentiated, and the cumulative effect is that of a world in which reputation is currency and scandal is bankruptcy. Into this world of carefully managed surfaces Holmes introduces himself as a demolition expert.
Lord St. Simon is the tale's true achievement, and he is drawn with a precision that suggests Doyle understood the English aristocracy rather better than his detective stories usually require. The forward stoop, the slight bend of the knees, the curly-brimmed hat, the yellow gloves, the golden eyeglasses swung on their cord — every physical detail conveys a man whose elegance is both a natural inheritance and a conscious performance. His conversational manner is a masterpiece of class comedy: "I was amused by her society, and she could see that I was amused" reduces courtship to a transaction in condescension, while his theory that his bride's departure must be attributed to sudden derangement — for who in her right mind could turn her back "upon so much that many have aspired to without success" — achieves a vanity so monumental that it becomes, paradoxically, rather touching. When Holmes remarks that in taking this case he is "descending" from a king, the barb passes entirely over St. Simon's head, and the noble lord inquires with genuine curiosity which king it was. Doyle understood that the most effective comic characters are those who are incapable of hearing themselves. Yet the tale's generosity toward St. Simon is finally its most distinctive quality: Holmes's closing observation that one should not judge harshly a man who has been "deprived in an instant of wife and of fortune" refuses the easy satirical kill, and the violin drawn out to while away the autumn evening seals the tale not with triumph but with a quiet, almost melancholy, tolerance.
The comical absurdities are, as always, considerable. Holmes's deduction that the bride must have departed in a cab — argued from the absence of muddy footprints on the linoleum — is perfectly sound, yet leads nowhere useful; the actual discovery is made through a hotel bill fragment on the back of a note that Lestrade has been waving about without examining. Lestrade himself, arriving in a nautical pea-jacket having spent the day dragging the Serpentine for a body that was never there, is subjected to Holmes's most devastating witticism: "Have you dragged the basin of Trafalgar Square fountain?" The discovery of the wedding-dress floating in the lake, solemnly presented as evidence of murder, is met with the observation that "by the same brilliant reasoning, every man's body is to be found in the neighbourhood of his wardrobe." These are excellent jests, but they expose the tale's structural weakness: there is no real investigation and no real danger. Holmes locates the Moultons through a hotel register in what appears to be a single afternoon's work, and the only obstacle to resolution is the social delicacy of the reunion, not the difficulty of the case. The elaborate cold supper — woodcock, pheasant, pâté, cobwebby bottles — ordered to Baker Street in advance of the confrontation tells us everything: this is a host preparing for a dinner party, not a detective closing a case.
What redeems the tale from the inconsequence that threatens it is the voice of Hatty Doran Moulton herself, who delivers her narrative with a directness and emotional honesty that belongs to no other character in the Adventures collection. Her account of the mining camp, the secret marriage, Frank's disappearance among the Apaches, the newspaper report of his death, and his sudden resurrection in the church pew — "I thought it was his ghost at first; but when I looked again there he was still, with a kind of question in his eyes" — is told with an American plainness that cuts through the elaborate social machinery of the tale like a blade through tissue. Her moral clarity is absolute and unselfconscious: "We can't command our love, but we can our actions." That single sentence contains more ethical substance than the whole of Lord St. Simon's careful self-presentation, and Doyle clearly knows it. The final tableau — St. Simon stalking out with a sweeping bow, the Moultons staying for supper, Holmes proposing a toast to Anglo-American union — is resolved not by detection but by a contest of manners in which the New World's candour defeats the Old World's ceremony. Doyle has written, beneath the disguise of a detective story, a small but perfectly formed transatlantic comedy, and if its mystery would not detain a competent constable for half an hour, its social observation belongs to a tradition that Henry James himself — who spent a career examining precisely this collision of American openness with European form — might have recognised with a nod of professional respect.
""" .

