This is a tale of considerable interest for what it reveals about Doyle's method after the great hiatus — a writer who must prove the resurrection was worth the trouble, and who succeeds unevenly but with several genuinely brilliant touches.
The opening is superb: Holmes catching himself mid-word — "This is really most grati — most interesting" — his pleasure at another man's catastrophe exposed in a single broken syllable. And the quiet revelation that Holmes secretly purchased Watson's practice through a distant relation is characteristic of a man who arranges the world to suit himself while preserving the appearance of accident.
The tale's most unusual quality is that Holmes genuinely loses for most of it. This isn't performative bafflement — he returns haggard, admits his instincts and the facts are pulling in opposite directions, and flings himself on his violin in real distress. The thumbprint deduction is fine: recognising that evidence absent yesterday and present today must have been planted. But the leap from a six-foot corridor discrepancy to the complete solution arrives without the intermediate steps that would make it feel earned.
The fire-alarm set-piece is tremendous fun and thoroughly preposterous. Holmes could simply open the hidden door. Instead he orders straw, commands everyone to shout "Fire!" three times, and stands with the air of a conjurer performing a trick — because, as he admits, he owes Lestrade a humiliation. The detection has become theatre. But Oldacre himself is a genuinely disturbing creation: the cat-in-the-aviary man grown old, his cruelty refined by decades into something methodical and cold, whimpering that framing an innocent man for murder was merely "a practical joke." That mutilated photograph — his rejected sweetheart's portrait, slashed and sent on her wedding morning — explains the entire scheme in a single physical object.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Norwood Builder" is the tale with which Doyle reopened his detective's practice after the long interregnum of the Reichenbach Falls, and it betrays, in both its strengths and its considerable weaknesses, the anxiety of a writer who must demonstrate that the resurrection was worth the trouble. The opening is shrewd: Holmes at breakfast, lamenting the dullness of London since the death of Moriarty, is interrupted by the headlong arrival of John Hector McFarlane — pale, dishevelled, palpitating, announcing himself as though his name were a household word and discovering that it means nothing to the great detective. Holmes's response is among the most revealing self-portraits in the canon: "This is really most grati — most interesting," he begins, catching himself in the act of expressing pleasure at another man's catastrophe, the stumble from "gratifying" to "interesting" accomplishing in a single broken word what most writers would require a paragraph to convey. The parenthetical revelation that Watson's return to Baker Street was financed by Holmes himself, through a distant relation who purchased the Kensington practice "with astonishingly little demur," is a beautiful touch — a quiet act of manipulation disguised as generosity, characteristic of a man who arranges the world to suit his needs while preserving the appearance of accident.
The investigation itself, however, presents the curious spectacle of Holmes losing — convincingly, genuinely, and for most of the tale. This is not the performative bafflement of stories in which he conceals his solution for dramatic effect; Holmes returns from Norwood haggard and anxious, confesses that "all my instincts are one way and all the facts are the other," and flings himself upon his violin in evident distress. The admission is bracing: here is the great machine struggling against evidence it cannot dismantle. Lestrade, for once, holds the stronger hand, and his "little cock-a-doodle of victory" — the bloody thumbprint that appears overnight on the whitewashed wall — ought to be decisive. That it is not, that Holmes recognises the print was absent when he examined the wall the previous day, is the tale's pivotal deduction, and it is a fine one, for it turns the prosecution's strongest evidence into proof of conspiracy. But the logic by which Holmes proceeds from this insight to the discovery that Oldacre is alive and hidden behind a false partition in his own house is never adequately explained. He measures a corridor, finds it six feet shorter than the one below, and concludes that the builder has constructed a secret room. The deduction is mechanically sound but arrives without the intermediate steps that would make it feel earned; Holmes leaps from a discrepancy in corridor length to the complete solution with a swiftness that belongs to theatrical revelation rather than to the patient accumulation of evidence the tale has elsewhere promised.
The comical set-piece in which Holmes flushes Oldacre from his hiding-place is the tale's most entertaining passage and its most instructive failure. Holmes orders constables to carry straw to the upper corridor, instructs Watson to light it, and commands everyone to shout "Fire!" in unison — once, twice, three times — until the little wizened builder comes darting out "like a rabbit out of its burrow." The scene is pure theatre: Holmes standing before his audience with "the air of a conjurer who is performing a trick," Lestrade's face progressing through amazement, expectation, and derision, the constables grinning like schoolboys. It is tremendous fun, and it is also, on reflection, preposterous. Holmes could simply have opened the hidden door and arrested the man. He stages the fire-alarm instead because, as he cheerfully admits, he owes Lestrade "a little mystification" for the morning's chaff. The detection has become a performance in which the audience's humiliation is at least as important as the criminal's exposure, and while one cannot help enjoying the spectacle, one notes that it belongs to the tradition of stage conjuring rather than criminal investigation. Doyle is aware of this — Holmes's remark that he has always fancied he would have made "a highly efficient criminal" recurs throughout the Return stories as a kind of running confession — but awareness does not altogether redeem the substitution of showmanship for method.
What finally gives the tale its distinction, however, is the portrait of Jonas Oldacre, who belongs to a category of villain that Doyle understood with particular acuteness: the man whose malice is rooted not in greed or ambition but in the slow fermentation of a private grievance. Oldacre's scheme — to fake his own death, frame the son of the woman who rejected him decades ago, swindle his creditors through payments to a fictitious "Mr. Cornelius," and vanish into a new identity — is a plan of such patient, elaborately vindictive ingenuity that Holmes himself calls it a "masterpiece of villainy." The mutilated photograph that Mrs. McFarlane produces from her bureau — her own portrait, slashed with a knife and sent to her on her wedding morning — is an image of concentrated hatred that explains the entire scheme in a single physical object. Oldacre is the cat-in-the-aviary man grown old, his cruelty refined by decades of brooding into something methodical and cold. His whimpering plea that it was all "a practical joke" — offered while a young man sits in a cell awaiting trial for his murder — achieves a moral ugliness that the canon's more theatrical villains rarely match. Holmes's observation that Oldacre lacked "the supreme gift of the artist, the knowledge of when to stop" — that in planting the thumbprint he overreached a scheme that was already perfect — is criticism delivered in the language of aesthetics, and it reminds us that for Holmes, as for his creator, the distinction between a crime and a work of art is disturbingly narrow.
""" .

