This is one of the longest and most ambitious of the Return stories, and it gave me the satisfying challenge of a tale that operates on two entirely different registers — physical terrain and moral complexity — and succeeds unevenly at each.
The opening is superb comic prose: Huxtable's collapse from the embodiment of academic dignity to "ponderous piece of wreckage" on the hearthrug is managed with a mock-heroic grandeur that is simultaneously funny and genuinely moving. The moor investigation is technically ambitious — a detective story whose evidence is landscape rather than testimony — and Heidegger's body discovered among flowering gorse dabbled with crimson achieves genuine sombre power.
The celebrated cow-track deduction is the tale's comic centrepiece and its most conspicuous logical embarrassment. Holmes arranges bread-crumbs Watson cannot remember seeing, announces that cows do not gallop — and the medieval horseshoes that explain the whole trick sit in a glass case at Holdernesse Hall with a printed card describing their purpose. The solution was on public display the entire time.
But the confrontation with the Duke gives the tale its real distinction. The confession — the illegitimate son whose face preserves the dead mother's features, the inability to banish what he loves — belongs to the dynastic novel rather than detective fiction. Holmes is simultaneously judge, counsellor, and accomplice, and the tale makes no pretence that justice and discretion are the same thing. The final image — Holmes folding his six-thousand-pound cheque and declaring himself "a poor man" — is the most honestly mercenary moment in the canon, and one of its most endearing.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Priory School" opens with the most magnificent collapse in the canon. Thorneycroft Huxtable, M.A., Ph.D., etc. — whose card "seemed too small to carry the weight of his academic distinctions" — enters Baker Street as the very embodiment of self-possession and solidity, and in the next sentence is prostrate upon the bearskin hearthrug, a "ponderous piece of wreckage, which told of some sudden and fatal storm far out on the ocean of life." The prose is doing something quite extraordinary here: the metaphor of shipwreck, applied to a portly headmaster on a hearth-rug, achieves a mock-heroic grandeur that is simultaneously comic and genuinely affecting, for Huxtable's distress is real even if his dignity is absurd. Watson's clinical notation — "the stream of life trickled thin and small" — and Holmes's quiet extraction of the return ticket from the watch-pocket while the man lies insensible establish the two modes in which the tale will operate throughout: the medical and the forensic, compassion and analysis working side by side. The entire opening sequence, from the fainting through the glass of milk and biscuit to Holmes's deduction of three days' growth upon the chin, is managed with a comic precision that the middle sections of the tale never quite equal.
For the middle sections belong to the moor, and on the moor Doyle attempts something technically ambitious: a detective story whose primary evidence is physical terrain rather than human testimony. The ordnance map spread upon the bed, the lamp balanced in its centre, Holmes smoking over it with his reeking amber pipe — this is the image of a military strategist rather than a consulting detective, and the investigation that follows has the character of a campaign across hostile country. The tracking of the Palmer tyre and the Dunlop with its patched cover is carried out with a rigour that approaches the scientific paper; Holmes's claim to be familiar with forty-two different tyre impressions is one of those assertions of superhuman competence that Doyle deploys without irony but which the reader receives with a mixture of admiration and incredulity. The discovery of Heidegger's body — the flowering gorse dabbled with crimson, the bicycle tracks curving fantastically on the wet path, the shoe projecting from the bushes — achieves a sombre power that elevates the scene beyond the mechanics of investigation. But the celebrated cow-track deduction, upon which the tale's reputation partly rests, is at once the story's comic centrepiece and its most conspicuous logical embarrassment. Holmes arranges bread-crumbs on a table to demonstrate patterns Watson cannot remember seeing and which the reader has no means of evaluating, then announces that cows do not canter or gallop. The insight is splendid theatre — and it is also, on reflection, rather less brilliant than it first appears, for the horseshoes that counterfeit bovine hoofprints are displayed in a glass case at Holdernesse Hall with a printed inscription explaining their medieval purpose, so that the trick was quite literally on public exhibit and discoverable by any visitor with functioning eyesight. Holmes's cry — "What a blind beetle I have been!" — is truer than he intends.
The tale's most considerable achievement, and its most morally complex passage, is the confrontation between Holmes and the Duke of Holdernesse in the ducal study. The scene is managed in three movements, each more devastating than the last. First, Holmes's demand for the cheque — rubbing his thin hands together with an "appearance of avidity" that startles Watson — which reveals itself as a tactical instrument rather than greed, for the money is a lever by which Holmes compels the Duke to acknowledge the seriousness of what has occurred. Second, the accusation — "I accuse you" — and the Duke clawing at the air "like one who is sinking into an abyss," followed by that extraordinary effort of aristocratic self-command that restores him to his desk. And third, the confession itself: the youthful love, the illegitimate son whose face preserves the dead mother's features, the inability to send James away because "I could see his mother's face in his." This is material that belongs not to detective fiction but to the dynastic novel — the entail, the bastard heir, the legitimate child endangered by his half-brother's jealousy — and Doyle handles it with a restraint that permits the Duke's genuine anguish to register without sentimentality. But it is Holmes's response that gives the scene its moral weight: the cold rebuke — "you have exposed your innocent younger son to imminent and unnecessary danger" — followed by the practical command to send the carriage at once for the boy, followed in turn by the accommodation with scandal that leaves Hayes to the gallows, James Wilder to Australian exile, and the Duke to a reconciliation with his Duchess. Holmes is simultaneously judge, counsellor, and accomplice, and the tale makes no pretence that justice and discretion are the same thing. The final image — Holmes folding the six-thousand-pound cheque into his notebook and declaring himself "a poor man" — is a moment of such brazen, self-aware comedy that it rescues the tale from the moral seriousness into which it has been sinking, reminding us that the detective, like his creator, is a professional who works for money and finds the admission not shameful but liberating. It is the single most honestly mercenary moment in the canon, and one of its most endearing.
""" .

