This is a fascinating case of a story that breaks cleanly in two — and the break is both its weakness and, unexpectedly, the source of its most interesting effects.
The first half is pure Baker Street miniaturism at its best: printed slips, a cigarette no bearded man could smoke, agony column messages building toward a revelation. Holmes's observation that printing is a clumsy process and therefore must be deliberate is the kind of quiet deduction that seems obvious only after it has been stated. The mirror-glimpse of the hidden woman — a dark, beautiful, horrified face glaring through a narrow opening — compresses recognition, surprise, and dread into a single image.
But the second half abandons this delicate mechanism for a killing that occurs entirely offstage, committed by a character we've never met, upon a villain whose existence Holmes has just learned of. The mystery is solved not by Holmes but by Gennaro Lucca's knife. Holmes's contribution to the resolution amounts to lighting a candle and flashing "Vieni" across the London rooftops — elegant, but not detection.
The comical implausibility is considerable: Italian assassins track the couple to the very street and abduct the wrong man from outside the door, yet cannot identify which house shelters their quarry — a concealment defeated by a looking-glass in a box-room.
What redeems the tale is Emilia Lucca's voice, particularly her portrait of Gorgiano — "His voice was like thunder in our little house. There was scarce room for the whirl of his great arms" — and the extraordinary moment when she discovers his body and dances around the room in delighted wonder before stopping to ask where her husband is. Watson calls it "terrible and amazing," and for once his adjectives are precisely chosen. It's a moment of uncensored operatic passion that belongs to verismo rather than English detective fiction, and the reader remembers Emilia dancing long after the mechanism of the plot has faded.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Red Circle" is a tale of two distinct halves that do not quite belong to the same story, and the fracture between them is at once its structural weakness and, paradoxically, the source of its most interesting effects. The first half is pure Baker Street: a domestic mystery of exquisite miniature proportions, in which a London landlady's complaint about a lodger who will not show his face generates, through Holmes's patient accumulation of small details, a puzzle of considerable charm. The printed slips — SOAP, MATCH, DAILY GAZETTE — the cigarette stub that no bearded man could have smoked, the singular grammar of "match" where "matches" was wanted, the agony column messages tracking toward their climax — these are the materials of the classic detective story, and Doyle handles them with the sureness of a craftsman working in his most familiar medium. Holmes's observation that printing is a clumsy process and that its employment must therefore be deliberate is the sort of quiet, penetrating remark that distinguishes the best of the short stories: a deduction that seems obvious only after it has been stated. The revelation that the lodger is a woman — glimpsed through a mirror in a box-room, a "dark, beautiful, horrified face glaring at the narrow opening" — is managed with a theatrical economy that compresses recognition, surprise, and dread into a single image.
But the tale's second half abandons the domestic mystery for something altogether larger and more violent, and the transition is neither smooth nor entirely earned. The candle signals across the London rooftops — ATTENTA, PERICOLO — are a fine invention, and Holmes decoding Italian in real time while the flame flickers in the darkened window is a genuinely atmospheric set-piece, the winter evening thickened into "one gray curtain, a dead monotone of colour, broken only by the sharp yellow squares of the windows and the blurred haloes of the gas-lamps." But when the signal is abruptly cut short and the party rushes to the Howe Street flats, we find not the culmination of a detective investigation but the aftermath of a killing that has occurred entirely offstage, committed by a character we have never met, upon a villain whose existence Holmes has only just learned of. Gorgiano lies on the bare boards in his crimson halo of blood, the white knife-haft projecting from his throat, and the image is powerful — but it belongs to a different story from the one about Mrs. Warren's lodger. Holmes's role in the resolution amounts to having lit a candle and flashed "Vieni" across the rooftops to summon Emilia Lucca, a piece of quick-wittedness that is elegant but hardly constitutes detection. The mystery, such as it was, has been solved not by Holmes but by Gennaro Lucca's knife.
The comical dimensions are quieter than usual but no less present. Holmes's initial dismissal of Mrs. Warren — "I really have other things to engage me" — overcome by the twin forces of flattery and kindliness, is a deft portrait of a man whose vanity and compassion operate in tandem, each providing the other with an excuse to act. His remark that "education never ends" and that the case is undertaken "for art's sake" belongs to the late-period Holmes who has become, somewhat self-consciously, a philosopher of his own method. The meeting with Gregson at the doorstep of the Howe Street flats — "Journeys end with lovers' meetings" — is managed with a genial absurdity that momentarily transforms a murder scene into a social call, and Watson's tribute to the official detectives — "they may blunder in the matter of intelligence, but never in that of courage" — is one of his most gracefully backhanded compliments. But the tale's most comically implausible element passes without remark: Emilia Lucca has been imprisoned in her lodging for ten days, communicating entirely through printed slips, never once seen by her landlady, fed through a closed door — and yet Doyle expects us to believe that two Italian assassins, who have tracked the couple to the very street and are sufficiently well-informed to abduct Mr. Warren in mistake for his lodger, cannot manage to identify which house she is in. The concealment that baffles professional killers is defeated by a looking-glass in a box-room.
What redeems the tale, and gives it a claim to attention beyond its mechanical ingenuity, is the voice of Emilia Lucca herself. Her narrative — the elopement from Posilippo, the flight to America, the Bowery rescue that wins Castalotte's patronage, and the slow encroachment of Gorgiano upon their domestic peace — is told with an emotional directness that belongs to no English character in the canon. Her portrait of Gorgiano is the tale's most accomplished piece of writing: "His voice was like thunder in our little house. There was scarce room for the whirl of his great arms as he talked." The physical compression of that image — a giant literally too large for the space he occupies — conveys menace more effectively than any enumeration of crimes could. And the scene in which Emilia, upon discovering Gorgiano's body, dances around the room clapping her hands in delighted wonder, pouring forth "a thousand pretty Italian exclamations," before stopping suddenly to ask where her husband is — this is a moment of such raw, uncensored emotion that it belongs to a different literary tradition entirely, closer to the operatic passions of verismo than to the restrained drawing-rooms of English detective fiction. Watson records it as "terrible and amazing," and for once his adjectives are precisely chosen. Doyle understood that the Mediterranean temperament, as he conceived it, could provide his tales with an emotional register the English characters could not reach, and if the understanding is sometimes reductive — the hot-blooded Italian set against the cool-headed Englishman — it here produces a moment of genuine power. Holmes's exit line — "it is not eight o'clock, and a Wagner night at Covent Garden!" — seals the tale with characteristic deflection, the aesthete retreating from passion into art. But the reader remembers Emilia dancing.
""" .

