This review covers the story's comic strengths and Dickensian characterization of Jabez Wilson, the delightfully absurd logical flaws in Clay's supposedly brilliant scheme (a criminal mastermind who founds an entire philanthropic society just to get a dim pawnbroker out of the house), the concert passage as a moment that genuinely transcends popular fiction, and Doyle's masterful command of tonal modulation across the narrative arc.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
One must confess at the outset that "The Red-Headed League" is among the happiest of Dr. Doyle's productions — a tale in which the machinery of sensational fiction is so gaily decorated with comic invention that one very nearly forgets to notice the gears turning beneath. The central conceit — that a secret society devoted to the remuneration of red-headed men should lure a credulous pawnbroker into copying out the Encyclopaedia Britannica while criminals tunnel beneath his shop — possesses the kind of baroque absurdity that transforms what might have been a mere puzzle-narrative into something approaching genuine farce. Jabez Wilson, that stout, florid monument to British credulity, is drawn with a Dickensian relish that elevates him well above the procession of forgettable suppliants who ordinarily populate the Baker Street consulting room. His wounded dignity upon discovering that Holmes and Watson find his predicament amusing — flushing crimson to the roots of his flaming head — is a small triumph of comic characterisation, the pompous tradesman rendered simultaneously ridiculous and sympathetic.
Yet one cannot examine the plot too closely without encountering difficulties of a decidedly comical nature. We are asked to believe that John Clay, a criminal of supposedly supreme intelligence — Eton and Oxford educated, grandson of a royal duke, the fourth smartest man in London — has devised a scheme whose success depends entirely upon the continued gullibility of a man who is, by every account, not especially bright. The plan requires Clay to work for half-wages as a pawnbroker's assistant for months, to fund the rental of an office and the salary of a confederate impersonating "Duncan Ross," and to pay Wilson four pounds a week — all to ensure that Wilson leaves his shop for four hours each morning. One might reasonably ask whether a criminal mastermind with royal blood and a first-rate education might not have contrived to burgle the City and Suburban Bank by means rather less elaborate than founding an entire philanthropic society. The sheer expense of the ruse — which Wilson himself calculates at two-and-thirty pounds, though the true cost in rent, salaries, and newspaper advertisements must have been considerably higher — sits rather awkwardly against the supposed brilliance of its architect.
There is, however, a passage in the story that rises quite above the demands of the adventure-tale and touches something genuinely fine. Watson's observation of Holmes at the Sarasate concert — that languid, dreamy figure gently waving his thin fingers in time to the music, utterly transfigured from the relentless criminal agent into a creature of poetic contemplation — constitutes a portrait of divided sensibility worthy of more ambitious fiction. The reflection upon Holmes's "dual nature," the pendulum-swing between extreme languor and devouring energy, renders in a few deft strokes what the psychological novel labours to achieve across whole chapters. It is precisely in such moments — brief, almost incidental, yet vibrating with an awareness of the complexity of consciousness — that Doyle transcends the genre he has so profitably mastered and reminds us that even the literature of entertainment may harbour genuine insight into human character.
One must finally note the story's most enduring achievement: its architecture of tone. Doyle manages the remarkable feat of sustaining comedy, mystery, and genuine suspense within a single narrative without permitting any element to devour the others. The transition from Wilson's farcical account of the League, through the meditative interlude of the concert, into the taut darkness of the bank vault — where Watson crouches with his cocked revolver and can distinguish the breathing of each companion — represents a command of modulation that many a more self-consciously literary artist might envy. If the dénouement is somewhat mechanical, and if John Clay's aristocratic hauteur upon arrest strains credulity nearly as much as the scheme that led to it, one forgives these blemishes readily. The tale succeeds because it understands, with an instinct surer than mere craft, that the reader's deepest pleasure lies not in the solution of the puzzle but in the varied texture of the journey toward it.
""" .

