This review addresses the tantalizing but abandoned premise of Holmes's nervous prostration, the comical absurdity of the Cunninghams composing their decoy note in alternating handwriting (essentially gift-wrapping a confession), the genuinely thrilling physical confrontation where Holmes is nearly murdered for a scrap of paper, and the broader structural weakness of a fictional universe in which criminals obligingly behave exactly as the plot requires them to.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Reigate Squires" opens with what is, for this series, a genuinely unusual psychological premise: Sherlock Holmes is ill, depleted, depressed — a great machine run past its tolerances and now shuddering to a halt amid ankle-deep congratulatory telegrams he cannot bring himself to read. There is something almost poignant in this image of the convalescent detective, bundled off to the Surrey countryside by a Watson who, for once, holds the paternal authority in their partnership. Doyle has here touched upon a vein of real interest — the cost of intellectual brilliance, the melancholy that follows upon the expenditure of extraordinary energies — and one senses, briefly, the possibility of a tale that might explore the interior life of its hero with something approaching the depth such a character deserves. That the story promptly abandons this rich premise the instant a local inspector arrives with a scrap of paper is, of course, entirely characteristic; one must learn to appreciate what Doyle gestures toward as much as what he delivers.
The central detection — Holmes's analysis of the torn note, his demonstration that two hands wrote alternating words, his deduction that the writers were blood relations of different ages — represents some of the most satisfying forensic reasoning in the canon, grounded as it is in observable physical evidence rather than the conjurer's sleight-of-hand that too often passes for deduction in these tales. Yet the plot into which this clever analysis is embedded creaks alarmingly under scrutiny. We are asked to accept that the Cunninghams, men of wealth and standing, having committed burglary at a neighbour's house and then murdered their own coachman to silence his blackmail, composed the decoy note in a manner so astonishingly incriminating — writing in alternating words so that each man's hand was literally woven into every line — that they might as well have signed a confession. One can only suppose that the Cunningham intelligence, which was apparently sufficient to orchestrate a plausible staged burglary, suffered a catastrophic failure at precisely the moment when penmanship was required. That these county magnates, engaged in a lawsuit over half an estate and therefore presumably experienced in the care one must take with written documents, should produce such a forensic gift for their adversary belongs less to the literature of crime than to the literature of farce.
There is, however, a passage of considerable theatrical power in the physical confrontation at the story's climax. Holmes's feigned collapse — eyes rolling upward, features writhing, the suppressed groan and fall to the ground — followed by the deliberate smashing of the water carafe to create a diversion, and then the terrible cry for help as the two Cunninghams discover him rifling the dressing-gown, constitutes a sequence of genuine dramatic vitality. The moment when Watson, having been falsely blamed for the broken carafe, hears the voice of his friend screaming for his life and dashes through the rooms to find Holmes being strangled by one man and wrist-twisted by the other, achieves a physical immediacy that elevates the narrative above mere puzzle-solving into something approaching real peril. Watson's cool observation afterward — that Holmes's feigned fit was, speaking professionally, admirably done — is a delicious touch, the physician's clinical eye momentarily overriding the friend's alarm, and it reminds us that at his best Doyle possessed a gift for revealing character through a single, perfectly placed remark.
One must finally observe that the tale is weakened by the very contrivance that most distinguishes it. Holmes's stratagem of tricking old Cunningham into writing the word "twelve" — by deliberately misstating the time on a reward notice and thus compelling his suspect to correct it — is undeniably ingenious. But it requires Holmes to have anticipated, while still supposedly enfeebled by nervous prostration, that Cunningham would not merely note the error but would take pencil in hand and inscribe the correction himself, and that the resulting sample would prove sufficiently diagnostic when compared with the fragment. This is the characteristic weakness of the Holmes stories as a class: the detective's brilliance is demonstrated not through the honest accumulation of evidence, but through a series of gambits whose success depends upon other characters behaving with precisely the degree of obligingness that the plot requires. Doyle has constructed, in short, a world in which the criminal class exists primarily to be outwitted in the most theatrically satisfying manner possible — and if one cannot quite call this realism, one must at least concede that it makes for uncommonly good entertainment.
""" .

