This review examines Holmes's conspicuous absence from the story's central action (with Watson's opening apology read as a genuine plea for forgiveness), the comical absurdity of a prize-winning catalepsy specialist being twice fooled by a fake cataleptic seizure, the genuinely powerful atmospheric writing in the darkened staircase scene and the almost Balzacian portrait of Blessington's physical and moral decay, and the morally evasive dénouement in which Doyle drowns his villains offstage rather than confront the darker implications of his own narrative.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Resident Patient" opens with a preamble in which Watson, in a moment of disarming critical self-awareness, confesses the fundamental difficulty of his biographical enterprise: his best cases for displaying Holmes's reasoning involve dull facts, while his most dramatic cases leave Holmes with embarrassingly little to do. One wishes Doyle had attended more carefully to this confession, for the tale that follows is a rather stark illustration of the latter predicament. Holmes is essentially peripheral to the central action — a gang of former bank robbers infiltrate a physician's house, conduct what amounts to a private tribunal upon their treacherous former confederate, and hang him from a lamp-hook — all of which transpires while our detective is at home in Baker Street, having walked away in a huff because the victim would not tell him the truth. It is a curious narrative strategy to have one's protagonist absent for the murder that constitutes the story's dramatic centre, and one suspects that Watson's opening apology is less a literary device than a genuine plea for forgiveness.
The story's most conspicuous flaw — and it rises very nearly to the level of comedy — is the extraordinary credulity of Dr. Trevelyan, a man whose entire professional reputation rests upon his expertise in catalepsy. We are asked to believe that a specialist who won the Bruce Pinkerton prize for his research into this very condition cannot recognise a fraudulent cataleptic seizure when one is performed directly in his consulting chair. Holmes, who makes no claim to medical expertise, sees through the imposture at once; Trevelyan, who has devoted his career to the subject, is so thoroughly deceived that he rushes downstairs to fetch nitrite of amyl, leaving his supposed patient unsupervised for a full five minutes. That the same ruse succeeds on the second visit — and that Trevelyan relates the whole affair to Holmes without a flicker of professional embarrassment — suggests either a specialist of remarkable obtuseness or an author who has momentarily forgotten what credentials he has bestowed upon his own character. It is one of those delicious inadvertencies that remind us how swiftly Doyle composed, and how little he was inclined to look backward once the pen was moving forward.
Yet the tale contains passages of genuine atmospheric power that deserve recognition beyond the constraints of the genre. The scene in which Holmes and Watson ascend the darkened staircase at Brook Street — the light suddenly whisked out above them, the reedy, quivering voice from the blackness announcing that it has a pistol, the long scrutiny from the darkness before the terrified Blessington permits them to advance — possesses a quality of mounting dread that is quite superior to anything the mechanical requirements of the plot demand. And the portrait of Blessington himself is drawn with an almost Balzacian specificity: the loose, hound-like pouches of skin testifying to a body that has shrunk within its own flesh, the sandy hair bristling with terror, the man weeping in his armchair yet still unable to confess the truth that might save his life. Here is a figure whose physical decay is the outward expression of a moral corruption, and Doyle renders him with a compression and vividness that many a more self-consciously serious novelist might study with profit.
The dénouement, in which Holmes reconstructs the nocturnal murder from cigar-ends, footprints, and a screwdriver, is among the most grimly satisfying in the canon — the image of three men smoking in the darkness while conducting a kangaroo court over their gagged former accomplice has the stark, dreadful economy of a Goya etching. But the story's final paragraph undermines whatever moral weight has accumulated. The murderers, we are told, were probably lost aboard the steamer Norah Creina off the coast of Portugal; the prosecution of the page collapsed for want of evidence; and the entire affair was never properly dealt with in print. This is not a resolution but an evasion — the narrative equivalent of a shrug. One senses Doyle's fundamental impatience with the messier implications of his own story: having conjured a world in which betrayal begets revenge and vengeance escapes justice, he has no appetite for inhabiting that moral landscape, and so he drowns his villains offstage and moves briskly on to the next adventure.
""" .

