    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Retired Colourman" opens with a passage of surprising philosophical weight — Holmes in a melancholy mood, musing upon the futility of all human striving, the shadow and misery that remain when we have finished grasping at life. One detects in this autumnal register something of the weariness of a series approaching its own conclusion, as though Doyle, having sent his detective through decades of adventures, has permitted the cumulative toll of so many sordid encounters to settle at last upon the character's shoulders. Yet the story that follows is itself a curious study in diminishment. Watson is dispatched to Lewisham as Holmes's understudy, only to have his observations dismissed with a briskness that borders on cruelty: he has "missed everything of importance," though "no one else would have done better." This backhanded compliment, delivered with the breezy assurance of a man who has solved the case by telephone while his friend endured a hot train and a disagreeable companion, captures something rather unflattering about the partnership as it has evolved — Watson reduced less to a chronicler than to a decoy, sent on a fool's errand to Essex so that Holmes might burgle a house undisturbed.
The tale's most conspicuous comic flaw lies in the behaviour of Josiah Amberley himself, a murderer whose cunning is repeatedly insisted upon yet whose actions constitute a sustained exercise in self-incrimination. Having gassed his wife and her lover in a sealed strong-room and concealed their bodies in a disused well, this supposedly diabolical schemer proceeds to invite Sherlock Holmes — of all people — to investigate the case, apparently reasoning that consulting the world's foremost detective will make him appear innocent. He then paints the interior of his house in a frenzy that practically announces the presence of a noxious odour requiring concealment. He preserves the unused theatre ticket that demolishes his own alibi. And he fails to notice that one of his dying victims has scrawled the beginning of an accusation upon the wall of the murder chamber in indelible pencil. Holmes himself remarks that the man's destination is more likely Broadmoor than the scaffold, and one is inclined to agree — not because of the medieval Italian mentality Holmes invokes, but because no murderer of ordinary competence would have left quite so many signposts pointing toward his own guilt.
There is, however, a passage of genuinely arresting prose in Watson's description of his arrival at The Haven — the old house standing as a little island of ancient culture amid the monotonous brick streets of Lewisham, surrounded by its high, sun-baked, lichen-mottled wall, the garden running to seed in wild neglect. Watson is building toward something here, a metaphor for the decay of a life turned inward upon its own avarice, and the image of Amberley himself emerging from this ruin — that great frame tapering to spindled legs, the snaky locks of grizzled hair curling from beneath the straw hat, the pot of green paint in the hall like some grotesque emblem of domestic renovation undertaken far too late — possesses a descriptive energy that transcends the requirements of the detective plot. That Holmes cuts him short with a curt instruction to abandon the poetry and note only the height of the wall is both characteristic and regrettable; one feels that Watson, left to his own literary instincts, might occasionally have produced something rather finer than Holmes's appetite for bare facts would permit.
The story's final stroke — a newspaper clipping in which Inspector MacKinnon receives fulsome credit for deductions that were entirely Holmes's — provides a neat ironic coda, and Holmes's tolerant response carries a weary magnanimity appropriate to a detective nearing the end of his career. Yet one cannot escape the sense that Doyle, too, is going through familiar motions with diminished vitality. The rival detective Barker is introduced and disposed of with perfunctory haste; the murdered victims remain faceless ciphers whose deaths serve merely as the machinery of the puzzle; and the philosophical note struck in the opening paragraphs — that life itself is pathetic and futile, that we grasp only at shadows — is never permitted to deepen into genuine moral inquiry. The old colourman, with his miserliness and his jealous mania and his gas-pipe running into the plaster rose of the ceiling, deserved a darker and more searching examination than this brisk late tale is willing to provide. Doyle has given us the materials of tragedy and assembled them as a parlour trick — which is, perhaps, the shadow and misery that lies at the end of any series prolonged beyond the reach of its author's passion.
""" .

