The opening passage achieves genuine aphoristic quality — "grit in a sensitive instrument" and the seeing-versus-observing distinction belong to essay writing, not magazine fiction, and Watson's Boswellian function is shrewder than it appears. The King of Bohemia is an unintentional comic masterpiece: he arrives incognito dressed in astrakhan, flame-silk, and a jewelled brooch visible from across the street, making Holmes's penetration of the disguise less deduction than eyesight. Holmes's fire-alarm scheme rests on a sweeping generalization about female behaviour — unmarried women rush to jewel-boxes — which is precisely the sort of untested universal he elsewhere scorns Watson for accepting; this is either authorial carelessness or an early signal of the gendered blind spot Adler will exploit. The wedding-witness coincidence is pure farce, rescued only by narrative velocity. The story's real achievement is moral and structural: Adler defeats Holmes using his own methods — disguise, surveillance, decisive action — then surpasses him in character by choosing mercy over revenge. Holmes's cold rebuke to the King and his preference for her photograph over the emerald ring constitute a genuine emotional reversal, cracking open the "reasoning machine" portrait Watson had so carefully established in the opening lines.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"A Scandal in Bohemia" announces itself with one of the finer opening passages in recent popular fiction — a paragraph of such controlled irony that one suspects Mr. Doyle of having ambitions somewhat above his station as a writer of detective romances. Watson's portrait of Holmes as a man to whom emotion is merely "grit in a sensitive instrument" possesses a genuinely epigrammatic quality, and the famous distinction between seeing and observing rises nearly to the aphoristic. The prose here achieves a compression and a clarity that recall Stevenson at his most disciplined. That the tale is narrated by a man of sturdy ordinariness looking upon a figure of extraordinary capacity gives the whole a Boswellian warmth that is shrewder than it first appears — Watson's honest bewilderment becomes the reader's own, and Doyle manages this transference with a craftsman's quiet authority.
The architecture of the plot, however, cannot sustain the promise of these opening pages. We are asked to accept that the King of Bohemia — a man who arrives in London incognito yet wearing a costume so flamboyantly regal that a child of five would mark him as foreign royalty — possesses sufficient diplomatic cunning to govern a kingdom. The entire masquerade with the vizard mask is rendered comical by Holmes's instant penetration of it, and one cannot help but feel that the King's disguise is less a narrative device than a pantomime entrance. Similarly, Holmes's scheme to locate the photograph by staging a street brawl, feigning injury with red paint, and then crying "Fire!" in a lady's sitting-room constitutes an extraordinary chain of contingencies, any one of which might have failed disastrously. That a mind we are told is the most precise in Europe should rely upon the hope that an opera singer will behave exactly as all women supposedly behave in a fire is, to put it charitably, a theory somewhat beneath the great reasoner's professed empiricism.
Yet it is precisely in its resolution that the story transcends the mechanical tidiness of the detective tale and touches something unexpectedly alive. Irene Adler's triumph over Holmes is not merely a plot reversal; it is a moral reversal. She has seen through his disguise as completely as he saw through the King's, has followed him home in male attire with a boldness that mirrors his own theatrical methods, and has chosen mercy where she might have chosen revenge. Her letter is a masterpiece of generous intelligence, and Holmes's cold rebuke to the King — that the lady appears to be on "a very different level" to His Majesty — carries a sting of real moral seriousness. In this moment Doyle achieves what the best popular fiction only rarely manages: he allows a character's ethical stature to exceed the machinery of the plot that produced her.
One must note, finally, the delicious absurdity of Holmes being pressed into service as witness at the very wedding that complicates his case — a coincidence so brazen that it would embarrass a French farce, yet Doyle carries it off through sheer velocity of narration. The story's lasting distinction rests not upon its somewhat rickety detective logic but upon the portrait of Irene Adler herself, a woman permitted to be cleverer than the cleverest man in London. That Holmes keeps her photograph rather than the King's emerald ring suggests a capacity for admiration that Watson's opening paragraphs had laboured to deny him, and it is this quiet contradiction — this crack in the reasoning machine — that gives the tale its enduring human resonance.
""" .

