The opening scene is Doyle's finest political theatre — Bellinger's blue-veined hands on the umbrella, Hope's momentary collapse before the aristocratic mask reasserts itself — achieving psychological compression worthy of a genuine novel of statecraft. The security premise is absurd: the Secretary for European Affairs carries a war-triggering document home nightly in a despatch-box with one key and leaves it unguarded for four hours. Constable MacPherson is an unintentional comic masterpiece, admitting a pretty stranger to an active crime scene on the strength of a typewriting-advertisement story, then abandoning his post to fetch brandy from the pub; Lestrade's preening satisfaction at extracting this confession while missing its true significance compounds the comedy. Lady Hilda is the story's real achievement — her predicament between marital ruin and national catastrophe has genuine tragic weight, and her recovery of the document through feigned fainting and nerve places her alongside Irene Adler as a woman whose ingenuity surpasses Holmes's own. The resolution is morally extraordinary: Holmes deceives both Prime Minister and client, becoming Lady Hilda's co-conspirator, choosing gallantry over truth. His parting line about diplomatic secrets transforms him into the very species of diplomatist he has been hired to outwit — a deeply ironic close to the series.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Second Stain" arrives dressed in the robes of grand consequence — two Prime Ministers, European war, a stolen state paper of apocalyptic significance — and this elaborate costuming is both its distinction and, at moments, its undoing. The opening scene in Baker Street, in which Lord Bellinger and Trelawney Hope present their crisis, is among the most accomplished pieces of political theatre in the Holmes canon. Doyle draws the Premier with a vividness that suggests genuine portraiture: those blue-veined hands gripping the ivory umbrella head, that fierce gleam before which a Cabinet has cowered. The younger statesman's momentary collapse — that glimpse of the "natural man, impulsive, ardent, keenly sensitive" before the aristocratic mask returns — achieves a psychological compression worthy of a far more ambitious form of fiction. One feels, briefly, that Doyle has within his reach a novel of real political and domestic complexity.
That he does not quite grasp it owes much to the machinery of the detective plot, which creaks rather audibly beneath its diplomatic drapery. We are asked to believe that the Secretary for European Affairs carries the most dangerous document in Europe home each evening in a despatch-box, secured by a single key worn on his watch-chain, and leaves it unguarded for four hours while his wife attends the theatre. The security arrangements of Her Majesty's Government here would embarrass a provincial solicitor guarding a contested will. More comically still, the constable MacPherson — charged with preserving an inviolate murder scene — cheerfully admits a handsome stranger because she claimed to be answering a typewriting advertisement at the wrong address, then leaves her alone in the room while he fetches brandy from the pub around the corner. Lestrade's pompous satisfaction at extracting this confession, while remaining magnificently oblivious to what actually occurred, is a small comic triumph Doyle seems not entirely to have intended.
Yet the tale's deepest interest lies not in diplomacy or detection but in its portrait of Lady Hilda Trelawney Hope, whose moral predicament is drawn with a seriousness that transcends the conventions of the form. She is a woman trapped between two forms of exposure — an old indiscretion that would destroy her marriage and a new crime that might destroy nations — and her resourcefulness in recovering the document from beneath the murdered man's carpet constitutes one of the most daring acts in the entire canon. That she accomplishes this through charm, acting, and sheer nerve — feigning a faint so convincingly that the constable abandons his post — places her in the company of Irene Adler as a woman whose intelligence operates on a plane Holmes can only belatedly recognize. Her final confession, with its anguished declaration that her husband's honour stands so high he could never pardon a lapse in another, carries a note of genuine domestic tragedy that the surrounding apparatus of spies and statesmen does not earn.
The resolution is the tale's finest stroke and its most troubling one simultaneously. Holmes conspires to deceive his own clients — the Prime Minister and the Secretary — by slipping the letter back into the despatch-box and allowing Hope to believe it was never missing. He becomes, in effect, Lady Hilda's co-conspirator, screening her guilt from both husband and state. His parting line to the Premier — "We also have our diplomatic secrets" — is exquisite in its irony, for it casts Holmes himself as precisely the kind of diplomatist he has spent the story outwitting. That Doyle permits his great rationalist to choose gallantry and mercy over disclosure suggests an author who, at the close of a long series, had come to understand that the most interesting mysteries are not those solved by logic but those that logic wisely declines to unravel.
""" .

