The opening microscope scene and Watson's wound-pension quip are pleasantly efficient, and the Regency-buck thumbnail of Norberton shows Doyle's descriptive economy still functioning — but these are habitual fluencies, not inspired efforts. The mystery is fatally transparent: a lady who stops visiting her horse, gives away her spaniel, and hides behind shawls is obviously dead or replaced, and the spaniel experiment at the gates, while charming, eliminates all doubt far too early. The central comic absurdity is that a rat-faced actor impersonates a noblewoman well enough to fool an entire household for a week while her own dog penetrates the fraud in three seconds — a devastating implied commentary on the English servant class that Doyle seems not to have noticed. The resolution is laughably lenient: concealing a death, desecrating a medieval corpse, and hiding a body in a crypt are all forgiven because the horse won the Derby and the debts were paid. Yet the midnight crypt scenes achieve genuine Gothic atmosphere, and the image of lantern light reflected from coffin-plates carrying family honours to the gate of Death is sombre poetry that transcends the surrounding machinery. Even in decline, Doyle's pictorial gifts flash unexpectedly into something finer than the genre required.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of Shoscombe Old Place," published as the final tale in the Sherlock Holmes canon, reads less as a culminating achievement than as a valedictory sketch — agreeable in its parts, negligible in its whole, and touched throughout by the fatigue of a series that has long since exhausted its inventor's appetite for the form. The opening exchange over the microscope and glue is vintage Baker Street domestic comedy, efficiently rendered, and Watson's confession that he pays for his knowledge of racing with half his wound pension is a line of such wry self-awareness that it nearly redeems the perfunctory pages that follow. The thumbnail portrait of Sir Robert Norberton as a man who "overshot his true generation" and should have been a Regency buck possesses genuine descriptive economy. Yet these pleasures are incidental; they belong to Doyle's habitual fluency rather than to any sustained effort of imagination.
The mystery itself is fatally transparent. From the moment we learn that Lady Beatrice has ceased visiting her beloved horse, has given away her devoted spaniel, and has taken to heavy drinking while remaining invisible behind a huddle of shawls, no reader of moderate attentiveness can fail to suspect that the lady is either dead or replaced. Doyle compounds this legibility with the spaniel experiment at the park gates — the dog rushing joyfully to the carriage, then snapping in fury at the impostor — which is charming as animal theatre but removes any remaining doubt a full third of the story before the revelation. The crypt, the charred femur, the burned mummy: these Gothic properties arrive with the air of furniture dragged onto a stage for a play whose denouement has already been guessed by the gallery.
One must note, too, the comical implausibility of Sir Robert's scheme. We are asked to accept that a rat-faced actor can impersonate an elderly woman of rank well enough to deceive an entire household of servants — butler, coachman, stable hands — by the simple expedient of sitting in a carriage wrapped in shawls. That the lady's own spaniel penetrates the disguise in three seconds while the humans around her remain oblivious for a week is either a devastating commentary on the English servant class or an oversight Doyle did not pause to consider. The resolution compounds the absurdity: the police and coroner take "a lenient view" of concealing a death, hiding a corpse in a family crypt, and burning a medieval body in a furnace, apparently because the horse won the Derby and the debts were paid. One feels that English justice has seldom been so candidly subordinated to the fortunes of the turf.
And yet there is, beneath all this mechanical contrivance, something faintly moving in the spectacle of a desperate man whose entire existence depends upon the speed of a horse running on a Tuesday afternoon. Sir Robert's midnight visits to the crypt where he has hidden his sister's body possess a genuinely eerie quality, and the image of the lantern light reflected from the coffin-plates of generations of Falders, carrying their honours "even to the gate of Death," achieves a sombre poetry that momentarily lifts the tale above its station. The description of the crypt — dismal, evil-smelling, with rough-hewn walls and a groined roof losing itself in shadow — is Doyle writing with a pictorial vividness he does not always trouble to summon. That such passages appear in what is otherwise one of the slightest entries in the canon only confirms that Doyle's gifts, even in decline, could flash without warning into something rather better than the detective story typically aspired to be.
""" .

