The opening cocaine scene is genuinely disturbing and psychologically sophisticated, establishing Holmes as something more than a detective hero, and the novel's return to the cocaine bottle in its final line creates a structural circularity of real artfulness — a bleakness the adventure genre can barely contain. Doyle attempts triple-decker sensation novel architecture within novelette length, and the seams show badly. Thaddeus Sholto is magnificent Dickensian grotesquerie wasted on a single expository scene. The gazetteer passage on the Andaman Islanders and the portrayal of Tonga as a chattering, gnashing "unhallowed dwarf" constitute the tale's moral catastrophe — the colonial unconscious is not incidental but structural, since the entire plot requires an Andaman Islander to function as trained weapon rather than human being. The London fog passage and Watson's glimpse of the stair-rods and stained glass achieve prose poetry worthy of Gissing or early Conrad. The Thames chase is cinematic action writing a generation ahead of its time. Jonathan Small's confession is the novel's deepest surprise — a fully dimensional picaresque voice whose grievance is legitimate and whose loyalty is absolute, creating a villain tinged with tragedy. The empty treasure box makes loss and gain so entangled that the conventional happy ending cannot contain them.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Sign of the Four" opens with one of the most arresting paragraphs in the popular fiction of our day — Holmes adjusting his hypodermic needle, the sinewy forearm dotted with puncture-marks, the long sigh of satisfaction — and in this single image Doyle accomplishes something no mere detective story has any right to achieve: he makes his hero genuinely disturbing. Watson's impotent moral protest and Holmes's languid, devastating reply — that his mind rebels at stagnation, that he craves mental exaltation and has therefore created his own profession — establishes a psychological dynamic between the two men that is richer and more disquieting than anything the ensuing plot will demand of it. The cocaine is not decoration; it is the dark corollary of genius, and Doyle handles it with a clinical directness that anticipates the concerns of a more psychologically sophisticated literature. That the novel ends as it began, with Holmes reaching for the bottle, gives the whole a structural circularity that is genuinely artful, and the final line possesses a bleakness that the conventions of the adventure story can barely contain.
The plot machinery, alas, strains and clatters in ways the opening had not prepared us to expect. Doyle attempts the architecture of a triple-decker sensation novel — a present-day mystery, a colonial backstory, a treasure hunt, a romance, and a Thames boat chase — within the compass of a work scarcely longer than a novelette, and the seams show. Thaddeus Sholto, with his bald pate rising like a mountain-peak from fir-trees, his anxious mitral valve, and his Bouguereau, is a triumph of grotesque portraiture that belongs to Dickens rather than to detective fiction, yet he vanishes from the narrative almost the moment he has served his expository purpose. The gazetteer description of the Andaman Islanders, from which Holmes reads aloud with evident satisfaction, is a passage of ethnographic fantasy so lurid and so credulous that it reads today as an inadvertent comic set-piece — we are told these people are naturally hideous, intractable, and fierce, with heads like misshapen fungi, and the portrait of Tonga himself, that chattering, gnashing "unhallowed dwarf," proceeds from the same poisoned well. One must observe that Doyle's imagination, so generous to the eccentricities of Englishmen, extends no such charity to the peoples of the Empire. The colonial unconscious of the tale is not merely present; it is structural, for the entire plot depends upon the assumption that an Andaman Islander is essentially a trained weapon rather than a human being.
Yet amid this mechanical contrivance there are passages of atmospheric writing that transcend anything the genre ordinarily attempts. The cab ride through foggy London — mud-coloured clouds over muddy streets, yellow glare streaming through vaporous air, the endless procession of faces flitting from gloom to light and back to gloom — achieves a prose poetry of urban desolation that one might encounter in Gissing or the early Conrad. Watson's glimpse of Miss Morstan's household as he departs — the two clinging figures, the half-opened door, the hall light through stained glass, the bright stair-rods — constitutes a miniature of domestic tenderness all the more moving for its brevity, set as it is against the wild darkness of the night's business. And the Thames pursuit, with its roaring furnaces, its flickering search-light, and the Aurora thundering through a starlit river crowded with barges and steamers, is action writing of the highest popular order, managed with a cinematic economy that would not become standard technique for another generation. Holmes's philosophical aside during the stakeout — that while the individual man is an insoluble puzzle, in the aggregate he becomes a mathematical certainty — is a remark that belongs more properly to a novel of ideas than to a detective romance, and it sits with surprising ease in its setting.
The novel's deepest surprise, however, is Jonathan Small. His confession in the final chapter, occupying fully a quarter of the book, is a piece of sustained first-person narration that accomplishes what the rest of the novel only gestures toward: the creation of a fully dimensional human being whose moral complexity resists the categories of detective fiction. His account of the crocodile taking his leg, of the card games on the Andaman Islands where the prison officials methodically fleeced the soldiers, of the midnight meeting at which Major Sholto's eyes shone with excitement and greed — these are passages of vivid, economical storytelling that owe nothing to the conventions of the mystery and everything to the picaresque tradition. Small's furious speech about justice — twenty years in a fever-ridden swamp, rice and water while a fortune waited outside — possesses a raw eloquence that momentarily places the reader's sympathy in the most uncomfortable possible location. That Watson confesses horror at this speech while Holmes quietly observes that they have not yet heard enough to judge is one of the shrewdest moral moments in the canon. Doyle, one suspects, did not fully understand what he had created in Small: a villain whose grievance is legitimate, whose loyalty to his confederates is absolute, and whose defeat is tinged with something very close to tragedy. The treasure scattered in the Thames, the empty box opened in Miss Morstan's lamplight, Watson's involuntary cry of gratitude that the golden barrier between himself and the woman he loves has been destroyed — in these images the novel achieves a genuine complexity of feeling, in which loss and gain are so entangled that the conventional happy ending cannot entirely contain them. It is a better book than its author knew.
""" .

