The opening deduction sequence — roughened sole, spatulate fingertips, spirituality distinguishing musician from typewriter — is assured and witty. Violet Smith is among Doyle's most convincing female clients; her instinct to charge directly at her pursuer tells us more than a page of exposition. The tale's comic structural flaw: Holmes is essentially irrelevant to the action. He dispatches Watson to learn nothing he didn't already know, scolds him for it, gets punched in a pub, miscalculates the train schedule, and arrives too late. Carruthers — the lovelorn velocipedal guardian angel cycling in disguise behind his governess for weeks — actually shoots the villain and rescues the girl. Holmes merely disarms participants afterward: less detective work than crowd control. Yet this incompetence gives the story unusual truthfulness. Watson's visual composition of the two cyclists — the graceful girl upright, the furtive man bent low — is genuinely beautiful against the golden gorse and lichen-studded gateways. The "settling his necktie" detail is a perfectly concealed clue. Carruthers achieves real moral complexity: a man who gambled for a girl on a sea voyage becomes, through twisted infatuation, her secret protector and would-be avenger. His declaration that this is the only time he ever knew what love was briefly transforms magazine adventure into psychological fiction.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Solitary Cyclist" is a tale whose most memorable qualities exist in perpetual tension with its structural deficiencies — a story that Doyle the scene-painter and Doyle the plot-mechanic might have written with different hands on the same morning. The opening consultation is managed with characteristic deftness: Holmes's deduction from the roughened sole and the spatulate fingertips, his gentle turning of the lady's face toward the light to distinguish the musician from the typewriter by the "spirituality" he finds there, and his subsequent observation that it is part of the settled order of Nature that such a girl should have followers, "but for choice not on bicycles in lonely country roads" — these are passages of assured and witty writing that establish both the detective's method and the story's atmosphere with admirable economy. Violet Smith herself is among the more convincingly drawn of Doyle's female clients: composed, spirited, and possessed of the excellent instinct to charge directly at her pursuer rather than flee, an action that tells us more about her character than a page of exposition could accomplish.
The tale's comic flaw — and Holmes has the grace to acknowledge it — is that the great detective is essentially irrelevant to the action. He dispatches Watson on a reconnaissance that yields nothing he did not already know, scolds him savagely for the manner in which he failed to learn it, then conducts his own investigation in Surrey only to get punched in the face by Woodley at the local public house and return to London with a cut lip and no more information than Watson obtained. When the crisis finally arrives, Holmes miscalculates the train schedule, arrives too late to prevent the abduction, and is reduced to commandeering an empty dog-cart and galloping after events that have already occurred without him. It is Carruthers — the lovelorn co-conspirator who has been cycling in disguise behind his governess for weeks like some heartbroken velocipedal guardian angel — who actually shoots the villain and rescues the girl. Holmes's role is confined to disarming the participants after the drama has concluded, which is less detective work than crowd control.
Yet this very incompetence, if one may call it that, gives the tale a quality of truthfulness unusual in the canon. Holmes's admission that he has been "very obtuse" and his self-reproach for not allowing for the earlier train are marks of an honesty that the infallible detective of popular legend would never permit himself. Watson's report of the solitary cyclist — the graceful girl sitting straight upon her machine, the furtive man bending low over his handle-bar two hundred yards behind — is a visual composition of considerable beauty, and the Surrey landscape through which these two figures pass, with its golden gorse, its lichen-studded gateways, and the grim Tudor hall bristling out from ancient oaks, is among Doyle's finest evocations of the English countryside as a place where menace and loveliness cohabit without the slightest incongruity. The image of Carruthers pausing among the trees to remove his false beard, which Watson innocently reports as a man "settling his necktie," is a detail whose significance is invisible until the revelation, and it is precisely the kind of clue that the best detective fiction conceals in plain sight.
The resolution in the bowling alley, for all its melodramatic machinery, achieves a genuine moral complexity. Carruthers, who gambled for the girl on a sea voyage, hired her under false pretences, and conspired to deliver her to a brute, has also — by the twisted logic of an infatuation he never sought — become her protector, her secret guardian, and ultimately the man willing to hang for her safety. His line upon shooting Woodley — "No, she's your widow" — possesses a laconic ferocity that would not disgrace a Jacobean revenge drama. That a forced marriage conducted by an unfrocked clergyman in a shrubbery carries no legal weight is Holmes's final, coolly delivered reassurance; but the emotional weight of the scene rests not on the detective's legal expertise but on Carruthers's tortured declaration that this is the only time he ever knew what love was. It is a speech that momentarily transforms a magazine adventure into something approaching the territory of the genuine psychological novel, and it is one of those moments — scattered unevenly across the Holmes canon — where Doyle's reach exceeds his habitual grasp, and the popular story briefly touches a depth that neither its author nor its audience quite expected to find there.
""" .

