The chain of knockings-up is a perfect theatrical opening — client to landlady to detective to doctor in a single compressed paragraph. Helen Stoner's composed terror is more frightening than hysteria; her narrative builds Roylott through cumulative strokes until the man himself crashes through the door. The Baker Street confrontation is the canon's finest comic scene: Holmes's crocuses remark, the escalating insults at which his smile only broadens, and the magnificent silent theatre of the bent and straightened poker. Stoke Moran's crab-claw architecture physically embodies ancestral decay. The bedroom investigation has the satisfactions of a mathematical proof — systematic elimination until the dummy bell-rope, clamped bed, and ventilator converge on a single explanation. Deducing the ventilator from Julia's remark about cigar smoke is pure Holmesian method. The zoological absurdities are formidable: no snake answers a whistle, climbs a bell-rope, drinks milk, and kills within ten seconds. Doyle has invented a creature combining canine obedience with cobra lethality and simian agility — carried off purely by narrative velocity. The baboon as Gothic furniture that briefly terrifies Holmes himself is a rare humanising touch. The night vigil achieves genuine terror. Holmes's cool admission that he drove the snake back to kill its master cracks open the detective story to reveal the protector as instrument of extralegal retributive justice.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Speckled Band" is the tale which Doyle himself reportedly judged his finest, and one can understand why: it is the most perfectly theatrical of the Holmes stories, constructed with the economy and inevitability of a well-made play in which each scene advances the action, deepens the menace, and narrows the possibilities until only one terrible explanation remains. The opening is a small masterpiece of atmospheric compression — Holmes standing fully dressed beside Watson's bed at quarter past seven, the chain of knockings-up from client to landlady to detective to doctor, and then the veiled woman by the window whose shiver comes not from cold but from terror. Helen Stoner's narrative, delivered with a composure more frightening than hysteria, builds the portrait of Grimesby Roylott with cumulative strokes — the beaten butler, the hurled blacksmith, the wandering cheetah and baboon — until the man himself crashes through the door of Baker Street like a figure from melodrama given physical weight. The confrontation that follows is among the most celebrated in the canon: Holmes's imperturbable remarks about crocuses while Roylott screams, the escalating insults from meddler to busybody to Jack-in-office at which Holmes's smile only broadens, and the magnificent piece of silent theatre in which Roylott bends the poker and Holmes, after his departure, quietly straightens it again.
The investigation at Stoke Moran is conducted with a narrative logic so rigorous that it approximates the satisfactions of a mathematical proof. The grey, lichen-blotched house with its crab-claw wings, one ruined and one inhabited, is among Doyle's most vivid architectural inventions — a physical embodiment of ancestral decay pressing inward upon its last living occupants. Holmes's examination of the bedroom proceeds by systematic elimination: the shutters cannot be forced, the floor is sound, the chimney is barred, therefore danger must come from the one remaining aperture. The dummy bell-rope that leads not to the housekeeper but to the ventilator, the bed clamped immovably to the floor beneath it, the saucer of milk that cannot be for the cheetah — each discovery tightens the logical vice until the solution becomes, in retrospect, the only possibility. Holmes's deduction of the ventilator from Julia's remark about smelling her stepfather's cigar is the kind of reasoning that makes the reader feel simultaneously admiring and foolish, which is precisely the emotional transaction the detective story exists to provide.
One must, however, register the zoological absurdities upon which this splendid architecture rests, and they are formidable. There is no snake known to herpetology as a "swamp adder," and no Indian serpent that answers to a whistle, climbs a bell-rope on command, drinks milk from a saucer, and kills within ten seconds with invariable certainty. Doyle has invented a creature that combines the obedience of a trained dog with the lethality of a cobra and the acrobatic gifts of a monkey — a biological impossibility that the story's Gothic atmosphere is designed to render unquestionable. That it succeeds is the supreme demonstration of Doyle's narrative authority: we accept the impossible animal because the story does not permit us time to consult a naturalist. The baboon darting across the lawn like "a hideous and distorted child" is similarly deployed not as zoology but as Gothic furniture, and serves the additional comic purpose of momentarily terrifying Holmes himself — a rare vulnerability that makes the detective briefly, endearingly human before the deadly vigil begins.
The night scene in the darkened bedroom achieves, within the compass of popular fiction, something approaching genuine terror. Watson's account of the vigil — the absolute darkness, the silence broken only by the distant parish clock tolling the quarters, the hours crawling past from midnight to one to two to three — is an exercise in sustained tension that owes more to the tradition of the Gothic tale than to the detective story. The sudden gentle hissing, Holmes's furious lashing at the bell-rope, Watson's bewildered cry of "You see it?" answered by nothing visible, and then the scream that rises from the adjacent room, swelling from pain through fear to rage before choking into silence — this is writing of visceral power that transcends its magazine context entirely. Yet the story's deepest achievement may be moral rather than atmospheric. Holmes's closing observation — that he drove the maddened snake back through the ventilator to kill its master, and that he cannot say this is likely to weigh heavily upon his conscience — is a sentence of extraordinary ethical coolness. The detective has become, by his own quiet admission, an instrument of retributive justice operating outside the law, and Watson records this confession without comment. It is a moment that cracks open the reassuring surface of the detective story to reveal something darker and more complicated beneath: the recognition that the protector of the innocent may also be, when circumstances demand it, a killer, and that the distinction between justice and murder may be measured in nothing more than the direction a snake happens to turn.
""" .

