The domestic prelude is the most persuasive glimpse of Watson's life away from Baker Street — old Farquhar's St. Vitus's dance, the shrinking practice, the observation that the public looks askance at a healer whose own case is beyond his drugs. The scorched slippers deduction pivots neatly on the surviving price-wafer; Holmes's remark that results without causes are much more impressive belongs to the permanent literature of intellectual showmanship. The worn doorstep compared to the neighbour's has epigrammatic compression. Pycroft is engaging precisely because of his frank self-awareness — sitting up half the night hugging himself over his good fortune is comic and touching. The gold tooth is genuine detection: the one detail a razor and wig cannot alter. Holmes leaning back like a connoisseur taking his first sip of a comet vintage is a simile so unexpected it illuminates by sheer extravagance. The scheme is preposterous — why not forge the application letter in the first place? The office crisis is the tale's real achievement: Pinner's fish-belly pallor, his courteous bow before withdrawing to hang himself, the terrible drumming of heels against the door. Watson's clinical rescue details are precisely observed medical writing. Holmes's closing remark — that even a villain can inspire such affection that his brother turns to suicide — redeems the entire mechanical contrivance by locating fraternal loyalty beyond the law's categories.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Stock-Broker's Clerk" is a minor tale in the Holmes canon that nonetheless possesses, in its opening pages and its closing crisis, moments of writing that rise well above the mechanical requirements of the plot they serve. The domestic prelude — Watson's account of his purchased Paddington practice, old Mr. Farquhar's St. Vitus's dance thinning the patient list, the shrewd observation that the public looks askance at the curative powers of a man whose own case is beyond his drugs — is the most persuasive glimpse we are given of Watson's life away from Baker Street, and it grounds the adventure in a world of ordinary professional anxiety that makes the ensuing fantasia of the Franco-Midland Hardware Company all the more absurd by contrast. The deduction from Watson's scorched slippers, with its neat pivot on the surviving shopman's price-wafer that damp would have dissolved, is a small gem of the Holmesian method; and Holmes's rueful observation that results without causes are much more impressive belongs to the permanent literature of intellectual showmanship. The comparison of his worn doorstep to the neighbour's — three inches deeper, proving the busier practice — has the compressed wit of an epigram.
Hall Pycroft is among the more engaging of the canon's bewildered clients, and his narrative of seduction by Arthur Pinner has the quality of a confidence trick rendered with something approaching affection for its victim. Pycroft's frank admission that he is showing himself up as a confounded fool, his honest pleasure at being told his financial abilities are the talk of the City, and the delicious detail of his sitting up half the night hugging himself over his good fortune — these give the story a warmth and comic humanity that the plot mechanics cannot quite sustain. The gold tooth is a genuinely clever detection: the single physical detail that a razor and wig cannot alter, noticed by a man whose observational powers are decidedly above his station. Holmes's response — leaning back like a connoisseur who has taken his first sip of a comet vintage — is a simile so unexpected and precise that it illuminates by sheer extravagance. One must observe, however, that the entire scheme is preposterous beyond even the generous allowances of the genre: that two master criminals should construct an elaborate Birmingham decoy to keep one junior clerk from appearing at Mawson's on Monday morning, when they might simply have forged the application letter in the first place, is a logical absurdity the story cannot survive if one pauses to examine it.
The confrontation in the bare office above Corporation Street is, however, managed with genuine skill, and it is here that the tale briefly achieves something beyond its station. Pinner's face — the dead white of a fish's belly, the wild staring eyes, the perspiration glistening on his brow — is a portrait of a man who has already read his own death sentence in the evening paper and is conducting a grotesque pantomime of normality while his mind composes its farewell. The quiet courtesy with which he begs three minutes' patience, the bow as he withdraws, and then the terrible sounds from behind the closed door — the knocking, the gargling, the brisk drumming of heels — constitute a sequence of mounting horror that Doyle handles with remarkable restraint, allowing the noises to tell what narration need not. Watson's clinical account of the rescue — the elastic bands buried in the livid creases of skin, the clay-coloured face, the purple lips puffing in and out — is precisely observed medical writing that serves the narrative better than any amount of melodramatic commentary.
The tale's deepest note, however, is struck by Holmes's closing observation, delivered almost as an afterthought while gazing at the haggard figure by the window: that human nature is a strange mixture, and that even a villain and murderer can inspire such affection that his brother turns to suicide when he learns that his neck is forfeited. It is a sentence that redeems the entire mechanical contrivance of the plot by locating, at its centre, a truth about fraternal loyalty that the detective story has no obligation to discover but is immeasurably enriched for having found. The Beddington brothers are never developed as characters — we know one only through a newspaper report and the other only through the wreckage of his attempted death — yet in that single remark Doyle suggests an entire relationship of criminal devotion, fierce and absolute, that exists entirely beyond the reach of the law's categories. It is the kind of moral observation that Henry James might have expanded into a novella; that Doyle delivers it in a sentence and moves on is both his limitation and, in this instance, his peculiar strength.
""" .

