collection of notes should not exceed 200 words.11:07 AMThe two halves are so violently mismatched they might be by different authors. Watson's opening — Afghan wound, enteric fever, eleven shillings and sixpence a day — is clinically precise imperial aftermath. London as "great cesspool" is Dickensian savagery. The Bart's Hospital meeting is among the great introductory scenes in English fiction: "I've found it!" followed by "You have been in Afghanistan, I perceive" establishes a complete character in a single page. Stamford's vegetable alkaloid warning is the most economical character sketch in the canon. Holmes demolishing Dupin and Lecoq is audacious literary throat-clearing — the new detective announcing himself by destroying his predecessors. The Lauriston Gardens scene achieves genuine urban desolation beyond what detection requires. The structural catastrophe: Doyle abandons Holmes, Watson, London, and the narrative entirely for sixty pages of Utah romance, collapsing the mystery's tension by explaining it in another genre. The Mormon portrayal is lurid propaganda bearing the same relationship to reality as the swamp adder to herpetology. Jefferson Hope redeems everything — the match struck to illuminate his own face, the nosebleed that explains the physical evidence while revealing vengeance's cost upon the avenger's body. Hope's death before justice reaches him renders the law irrelevant. A deeply flawed, occasionally brilliant foundation stone whose architect didn't yet understand his design.
