    ex:reviewDetailed """
A Study in Scarlet is a work of two halves so violently mismatched in method, tone, and literary ambition that one might reasonably suppose them the products of two different authors — and indeed, in a sense, they are: the detective-story writer of Part I and the adventure-romance writer of Part II share a name but appear to have communicated only through the most cursory of editorial memoranda. The first half, however, is a work of genuine originality. Watson's opening paragraphs — the Afghan wound, the enteric fever, the troopship Orontes, the landing at Portsmouth with health irretrievably ruined and an income of eleven shillings and sixpence a day — compose a portrait of imperial aftermath that is both clinically precise and quietly devastating. London as a "great cesspool into which all the loungers and idlers of the Empire are irresistibly drained" is an image worthy of Dickens at his most savage. The meeting at Bart's Hospital is among the great introductory scenes in English fiction: Holmes's cry of "I've found it!" as he springs forward with his test-tube, followed immediately by the throwaway miracle of "You have been in Afghanistan, I perceive," establishes in a single page a character so complete that the next forty years of stories will essentially be variations upon this first extraordinary impression. Stamford's warning — that Holmes might give a friend a pinch of the latest vegetable alkaloid, not from malevolence but from a spirit of inquiry — is the most economical character sketch in the canon, and it is never surpassed.
The Baker Street domestic comedy that follows constitutes Doyle's most lasting contribution to popular fiction: the list of Holmes's accomplishments and deficiencies, his ignorance of the Copernican theory and his mastery of sensational literature, his violin, his chemical experiments, his long silences and sudden bursts of energy — these are the elements from which an entire mythology will grow, and Doyle lays them out with the confidence of a man who does not yet know what he has created. Holmes's dismissal of Dupin as "a very inferior fellow" and of Lecoq as "a miserable bungler" is youthful literary throat-clearing of the most audacious kind: the new detective announcing himself by demolishing his predecessors. The Lauriston Gardens crime scene is presented with a visual specificity — the vulgar flaring paper, the strips of mildew, the dead man's expression of horror and hatred giving him a "singularly simious and ape-like appearance" — that goes considerably beyond what the detection requires and achieves a genuine atmosphere of urban desolation. Holmes's examination of the scene, conducted in total silence while Watson watches in bewilderment, followed by his brisk analysis in the cab, constitutes the template from which every subsequent investigation in the canon will be built.
The comical flaw — and it is structural rather than incidental — is the entire second half. Doyle, having constructed a mystery of considerable ingenuity, finds himself unable to resolve it within the detective framework he has established, and so resorts to the extraordinary expedient of abandoning Holmes, Watson, London, and the narrative altogether in order to deliver a sixty-page romance set among the Mormon settlements of Utah. The reader, who has been following a murder investigation in Brixton with keen attention, is transported without warning to the Great Alkali Plain, where a dying man and a small child are rescued by a wagon train of Latter Day Saints. Whatever the merits of the Utah chapters considered independently — and they possess a certain raw energy in the courtship of Lucy Ferrier and the menace of Brigham Young's visit — their effect upon the detective story is catastrophic. The sustained tension of the investigation collapses entirely; the mystery, which Holmes is on the verge of solving, is simply explained by the author in another genre. Doyle's portrayal of the Mormons, moreover, is a lurid fantasy of abduction, forced marriage, secret assassination, and omniscient tyranny that bears approximately the same relationship to historical reality as the "swamp adder" of "The Speckled Band" bears to herpetology. It is anti-Mormon propaganda dressed in the borrowed robes of the sensation novel, and it damages the book's reputation more gravely with each passing decade.
Yet the novel's deepest achievement survives this structural catastrophe, and it resides in Jefferson Hope. His confession in the final chapters — the twenty-year pursuit across two continents, the pill-box with its gamble of poison and harmless duplicate, the vision of old John Ferrier and sweet Lucy walking ahead of his cab through the rain-swept London streets — possesses a quality of obsessive, righteous fury that elevates the narrative from detective puzzle to something approaching tragic romance. Hope's account of the confrontation with Drebber — the match struck to illuminate his own face, the question "who am I?", the horror dawning in the drunken man's bleared eyes — is a scene of theatrical power that Doyle would rarely surpass. The detail of Hope's nosebleed, the blood that gushes from him at the moment of his greatest emotional intensity and which he then smears upon the wall as the word RACHE, is a stroke of inspired narrative logic: it explains the physical evidence while simultaneously revealing the spiritual cost of vengeance upon the avenger's own body. That Hope dies of his aneurism the night after his confession, with a placid smile upon his face, before justice can reach him, is the novel's final structural irony — the law is rendered irrelevant by a body that has consumed itself in the pursuit of a private reckoning. Holmes's bitter closing remark, that what matters is not what you do in this world but what you can make people believe you have done, and the newspaper's complacent attribution of the case to Gregson and Lestrade, provide a coda of acid comedy that the mature Doyle would repeat many times but never quite improve upon. The novel is, taken whole, a deeply flawed and occasionally brilliant piece of work — the foundation stone of an edifice whose architect did not yet understand its design.
""" .

