    ex:reviewersNotes """
The Morrison, Morrison, and Dodd letter is Dickensian institutional comedy — machinery assessors solemnly forwarding a vampire inquiry. Holmes browsing his index is pure world-building pleasure; the giant rat of Sumatra has generated more speculation than stories Doyle actually wrote. "No ghosts need apply" is magnificently peremptory. The "Re Vampires" framing gives structural elegance the middle cannot sustain. Watson on meeting a ruined athlete touches something universal about time and the body — a sentence that escapes its story entirely. Ferguson's admission of cultural distance in his marriage is unusually honest for a Doyle client; the wife's silence under accusation creates genuine moral complexity. The detection is solved before they leave Baker Street — everything at Cheeseman's is confirmation, not discovery. Curare raises questions Doyle wisely ignores: how does a crippled boy obtain and prepare arrow poison? The South American weapons are props arranged to be noticed rather than discovered. Jacky's motive is so transparent the mystery is less who than how. The window-glass reflection is fine theatre but confirms what we already suspect. Holmes's exit — taking Dolores by one elbow — is among his most graceful, the detective recognising where deduction ends and marriage resumes. The closing letter's symmetry with the opening is almost musical.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Sussex Vampire" opens with one of the most accomplished comic passages in the entire Holmes canon — indeed, one suspects Doyle enjoyed writing it more than anything that follows. The letter from Morrison, Morrison, and Dodd, specialists in the assessment of machinery, solemnly referring their client's inquiry concerning vampires to Baker Street with the notation "per E. J. C." is a small masterpiece of institutional absurdity, a joke about professional jurisdictions that belongs more to Dickens's Circumlocution Office than to the detective story. Holmes's browsing through his index volume — the Gloria Scott, the forger Victor Lynch, the venomous gila lizard, Vittoria the circus belle — is a passage of pure world-building pleasure, a man fondling his own past, and the tantalising mention of the giant rat of Sumatra, "a story for which the world is not yet prepared," has generated more delighted speculation among readers than many a story Doyle actually wrote. The declaration that this agency stands flat-footed upon the ground and that no ghosts need apply is Holmes at his most magnificently peremptory, and the framing device — the solicitors' letter opening the narrative, Holmes's dry reply closing it, both headed "Re Vampires" — gives the tale a structural elegance that its middle sections struggle to deserve.
Ferguson himself is drawn with unusual physical and emotional specificity for a Holmes client. Watson's observation upon meeting his former rugby opponent — that there is surely nothing in life more painful than to meet the wreck of a fine athlete whom one has known in his prime — is a sentence that transcends its narrative occasion entirely and touches something universal about time, the body, and masculine friendship. Ferguson's account of his Peruvian wife is handled with more psychological nuance than Doyle typically permits his distressed gentlemen: the admission that her foreign birth and alien religion had created a separation of feelings, that his love may have cooled, that there were sides of her character he could never explore or understand — these are not the protestations of a stage husband but the confused recognitions of a man who married across a cultural divide and discovered, too late, the distances it conceals. The wife's silence under accusation, her refusal to defend herself because defence would mean betraying her stepson and breaking her husband's heart, gives the tale a moral centre more complex than its vampire apparatus would suggest.
The detection itself, however, is both the story's cleverest trick and its most conspicuous weakness. Holmes announces that he had solved the case before leaving Baker Street, which is to say the intellectual work is complete by the end of the consultation scene, and everything that follows at Cheeseman's is merely confirmation. The South American weapons upon the wall, the paralysed spaniel, the empty quiver beside the small bird-bow — these are props arranged for Holmes to notice rather than clues he must discover, and the solution, once revealed, has the faintly mechanical quality of a demonstration rather than an investigation. The curare hypothesis is ingenious but raises practical questions Doyle wisely declines to examine: how a fifteen-year-old cripple obtained and prepared arrow poison, how he administered it to the dog as a test without detection, and how he repeatedly pricked an infant's neck without the wound pattern suggesting something other than maternal vampirism. That Holmes catches the boy's jealous hatred reflected in the window glass is a fine theatrical detail, but it confirms what the reader has likely already suspected, for Doyle has made young Jacky's motive so transparent — the exaggerated devotion, the twisted spine that makes the beautiful baby an intolerable reproach — that the mystery, in truth, is less who than how.
Yet the story achieves, in its final scene, a moment of genuine emotional power that its detective machinery does not quite earn but that Doyle's instinct for human feeling delivers nonetheless. The wife's cry of mingled joy and surprise at Holmes's note, her refusal to see her husband followed by her desperate need for her child, Ferguson standing by the bed choking with his hands outstretched and quivering — this is domestic anguish rendered with an economy that approaches real tenderness. Holmes's quiet withdrawal, taking Dolores by one elbow while Watson takes the other, and his murmured suggestion that they may leave the rest to be settled among themselves, is among the most graceful exits in the canon — the detective recognising that his work ends where the marriage begins again, and that no further deduction can help two people learn to trust one another across the distances that divide them. The closing letter to Morrison, Morrison, and Dodd, reporting that the matter has been brought to a satisfactory conclusion, returns us to the comedy of the opening with a symmetry almost musical in its precision, and one is left with the suspicion that Doyle cared rather more about the framing than the picture — and that he was not entirely wrong to do so.
""" .

