The tin dispatch-box paragraph is the finest opening in the later canon — Phillimore's umbrella, the cutter Alicia, Persano's worm function as negative space, enlarging the world by refusing to explain it. Watson as curator, not merely chronicler. The hard-boiled eggs and the cook's Family Herald is a delightful domestic miniature — even cooking demands attention incompatible with love romance. Gibson as Abraham Lincoln keyed to base uses compresses an entire character into one simile. Holmes's bluff-and-dismissal technique is not detection but management of personality by superior intelligence. Gibson's return is predicted with theatrical certainty. The marriage confession is genuinely complex — cruelty as attempted mercy, trying to kill her love because reciprocal hatred would have been easier. Marlow Bates is a fine nervous sketch wasted on a single scene. The bridge mechanism is ingenious but demands engineering precision from a deranged woman in darkness beside a windy mere — a suicide device that would tax a calm professional. Holmes raising Watson's pistol to his own head is superb theatre. Miss Dunbar's real interest: she stayed not from love but to redirect destructive financial power, making the governess a political agent rather than a romantic object. "Schoolroom of sorrow" is a sentence of quiet dignity that exceeds its genre.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Problem of Thor Bridge" opens with one of the most tantalising passages Watson ever wrote — a paragraph so rich in invention that it nearly overwhelms the story it introduces. The tin dispatch-box at Cox and Co., crammed with records of seventy-odd cases; Mr. James Phillimore, who stepped back into his house for his umbrella and was never seen again; the cutter Alicia, which sailed into a patch of mist and vanished with all hands; Isadora Persano, found stark staring mad before a matchbox containing a worm unknown to science — these are not merely throat-clearing but a deliberate conjuring of the inexhaustible world that lies behind every Holmes adventure, the vast archive of stories Watson will never tell. That none of these mysteries is explained is precisely their power; they function as negative space in a painting, enlarging the canvas by refusing to fill it. The paragraph establishes Watson not merely as chronicler but as curator, a man who selects and withholds, and the transition to the present case — a mere specimen drawn from the residue — gives the subsequent narrative a quality of offhandedness that is itself a kind of art.
Neil Gibson, the Gold King, is among the most fully realised characters in the later Holmes stories, and his scenes in Baker Street constitute a confrontation between two formidable temperaments that Doyle manages with the assurance of a dramatist at the height of his powers. The portrait of Gibson as an Abraham Lincoln keyed to base uses is a simile of extraordinary compression — it gives us the gaunt frame, the moral capacity, and the corruption of that capacity in a single stroke. Holmes's handling of the interview — the bluff that forces Gibson to confess his feelings for Miss Dunbar, the calm dismissal that sends the millionaire away in fury, the quiet certainty that he will return — is the method of Baker Street at its most theatrically satisfying: not detection but the management of a powerful personality by a still more powerful intelligence. Gibson's confession, when it comes, achieves something rare in the canon: a genuinely complex account of a marriage destroyed not by villainy but by the asymmetry of passion, in which one partner's love cannot be killed and the other's cruelty is itself a desperate attempt to extinguish it. His observation that he had tried to be harsh in the hope of converting her love into hatred, because hatred would have been easier for both of them, is a sentence that belongs to the literature of failed marriages rather than to detective fiction.
The physical solution — the revolver tied by string to a stone, fired at the temple and then whisked over the parapet of the bridge into the mere — is among the most ingenious mechanical devices in the canon, and Doyle stages its demonstration with superb theatrical instinct: Holmes raising Watson's own pistol to his head, releasing it, the crack against the stonework, the weapon vanishing into the water, and then the joyous cry as the second chip is discovered on the parapet's underside. Yet one must register the considerable absurdity that Mrs. Gibson, a woman consumed by suicidal jealousy and operating in the dark beside a windy mere, successfully ties a loaded revolver to a length of string weighted with a stone, balances this apparatus so that it will fire cleanly at her temple and then be pulled away without tangling in her hair, her shawl, or the balustrade — all while clutching a note in her other hand. It is a suicide device that would tax an engineer's patience in broad daylight, and we are asked to believe it was executed by a woman in the extremity of emotional derangement. Holmes himself acknowledges the plot's subtlety with a straight face that amounts, in its way, to Doyle's silent confession that he knows the mechanism is more elegant than plausible.
The story's deepest surprise, however, is Miss Dunbar. Watson's account of her — the noble figure, the commanding presence, the dark eyes with their appealing helpless expression — is conventional enough, but her moral position is not. She stayed in the household not from love of Gibson but from the discovery that she could influence his commercial decisions, that she could redirect the financial power that crushed communities and ruined men toward something more just. This is a quietly extraordinary detail: it transforms the governess from romantic interest into something closer to a political agent, a woman who has calculated that proximity to destructive power is itself a form of moral action. Her acknowledgment that she was wrong — that nothing could justify remaining where she was a cause of unhappiness — gives the admission a moral seriousness that the detective plot neither requires nor deserves, and Holmes's closing speculation, that Gibson and Dunbar may yet join forces and that Gibson has learned something in "that schoolroom of sorrow where our earthly lessons are taught," is a sentence whose quiet dignity reaches well beyond the conventions of the form. It suggests, with characteristic Doylean brevity, that the detective story may occasionally stumble upon the materials of the novel of conscience, even if it lacks the compass to develop them.
""" .

