Steve Dixie's entrance is the most uncomfortable passage in the canon — minstrel phonetics, physical caricature, Holmes's remark about smell. This is not incidental colour but the scene's organising principle, and it damages the moral authority of the character. Must address directly; cannot review around it. Mrs. Maberley is quietly effective — the three gables making only the most apologetic attempt to justify the name. The logical chain is elegant: offer to buy everything means buyers cannot specify the object; urgency means recent arrival; Italian trunks spotted in hallway. Susan dragged through doorway like a squawking chicken is brutal comic economy. "Paregoric is the stuff" — throwaway cruelty. The manuscript fragment is the real surprise: the pronoun shift from "he" to "my" is literary criticism delivered as detection. The burned novel sounds more interesting than the detective story containing it. Langdale Pike in his bow window — human dial registering every swirl in London's turbid depths — is a splendid sketch wasted on a single paragraph. Isadora Klein magnificent in her half-lit drawing-room: steel to velvet in an instant. But Holmes's resolution is strikingly feeble — wagging finger and five thousand pounds for a woman who commissioned burglary and chloroforming. The tale's moral economy mirrors its racial one: power purchases indulgence.
