    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Three Gables" opens with a scene that constitutes the single most uncomfortable passage in the Holmes canon — a passage one must address directly precisely because so much of the story's subsequent energy depends upon pretending it did not happen. Steve Dixie's entrance is drawn with every crude instrument of racial caricature available to the popular fiction of the period: the dialect rendered in minstrel phonetics, the "flattened nose," the "sullen dark eyes" with their "smouldering gleam of malice," Holmes's remark that he does not like the smell of him, the reference to his "woolly head." These are not incidental details but the passage's organising principle, and Holmes — elsewhere in the canon a figure of cosmopolitan rationality — becomes here an instrument of racial contempt that damages not merely this story but the moral authority of the character himself. Watson's narration, usually the kindly voice of Victorian decency, participates without flinch. One cannot review the tale without acknowledging that its opening scene is a failure not merely of taste but of moral imagination, and that Doyle, writing in the mid-1920s, might have known better and chose not to.
Having registered this, one must also note that the rest of the tale, while decidedly minor, possesses structural qualities that deserve examination. Mrs. Maberley is a quietly effective creation — an elderly woman of refinement and culture, recently bereaved, inhabiting a house whose three feeble gable-projections make only the most apologetic attempt to justify its name. The investigation proceeds by a chain of logical inference that is, in its compressed way, rather elegant: the offer to buy everything including personal effects can only mean the buyers seek something whose nature they cannot specify without revealing their purpose; the urgency of the demand means the object has only recently arrived; the trunks from Italy, spotted by Holmes in the hallway, provide the answer. The eavesdropping Susan, dragged through the doorway like "some huge awkward chicken, torn, squawking, out of its coop," is a comic sketch of brutal economy, and Holmes's parting advice — "Paregoric is the stuff" — has a throwaway cruelty that one might admire more if the story had not already exhausted one's tolerance for casual unkindness.
The manuscript fragment torn from the burglar's hands is the tale's one genuine literary surprise. The passage from Douglas Maberley's autobiographical novel — the beaten man looking up at the beautiful woman who smiles from her window as he bleeds — is a compressed vignette of erotic humiliation that possesses more raw emotional power than anything else in the story. Holmes's observation that the pronoun shifts from "he" to "my" as the writer becomes absorbed in his own experience is a fine piece of literary criticism delivered as detective work: the grammatical slip that reveals autobiography beneath the fiction. It is a pity that the manuscript exists only as a single surviving page, for what it suggests — a novel of passion and revenge written by a dying man in Rome — is considerably more interesting than the detective story in which it is embedded. Doyle has, perhaps inadvertently, created a fragment that makes the reader regret the book that was burned rather than mourn the mystery that was solved.
Isadora Klein, when she finally appears in her Arabian Nights drawing-room, is the story's most vivid achievement and its most revealing failure. She is magnificent — the mask-like face, the Spanish eyes that look murder, the instantaneous transformation from steel to velvet when she perceives that Holmes cannot be faced down — and her account of her affair with Douglas Maberley has a candour unusual for the canon: the admission that she discarded him when he became pertinacious, that she had his ruffians beat him beneath her own window, that she now faces ruin because the man she destroyed found the strength to write her destruction into a novel. Yet Holmes's resolution is strikingly feeble. He extracts five thousand pounds for Mrs. Maberley's world tour and delivers a wagging finger — "Have a care! You can't play with edged tools forever" — that amounts to little more than an avuncular scolding of a woman who has commissioned burglary, assault, and the chloroforming of an elderly widow. The story compounds a felony and calls it justice. One is left with the uncomfortable suspicion that Isadora Klein's beauty, her rank, and her gender have purchased an indulgence that Steve Dixie, hauled before the magistrate for the killing of young Perkins, will never receive — and that the tale's moral economy, like its racial one, is arranged for the comfort of those already in possession of power.
""" .

