The opening has an autumnal, valedictory quality — Holmes refusing a knighthood mentioned in passing, the whimsical Garrideb name, Doyle writing in comfortable exercise of long-practised craft rather than under compulsion of invention. Nathan Garrideb's room is the most lovingly catalogued interior in the later canon: butterflies flanking the entrance, Syracusan coins polished with chamois leather, plaster skulls labelled Neanderthal and Cro-Magnon. Character understood entirely through habitat. His ambition to become the Hans Sloane of his age is touching. The gentle collector living unknowingly above a counterfeiter's cellar is the tale's one genuinely poetic irony. Holmes's exposure of Evans works through patient professional attention rather than brilliance: frayed English coat, bagged trousers, nonexistent Dr. Lysander Starr, misspelt "plough." The trap's structural deficiency: two armed men crouching behind a cupboard somehow permit the criminal to draw and fire twice. Watson's wound transparently contrived for what follows. But what follows redeems everything — "For God's sake, say that you are not hurt!" is the emotional centre of the entire canon across sixty stories. The movement from vulnerability to menace in a single breath — dimmed eyes to flint-set face — tells us more about the friendship than all the deductions combined. Poor Nathan's castle in the air burying him beneath its ruins strikes the proper elegiac note.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Three Garridebs" is a tale of frankly modest ambitions — its plot is a variation on an established template, its villain is identified early and without great surprise, and its detective mechanism turns on a counterfeit that is, in every sense, the story's governing metaphor. Yet it contains, in a single paragraph near its close, what may be the most emotionally significant passage Watson ever wrote, and it is for this paragraph alone that the story survives and will continue to survive when more ingenious constructions have been forgotten. The opening is characteristic of the later canon's relaxed, almost valedictory manner: Watson fixing the date by reference to the knighthood Holmes refused, the pleasant absurdity of the Garrideb name discovered in the telephone directory, the whimsical quality Holmes himself attributes to the case. There is an autumnal geniality to these pages that suggests Doyle writing not under the compulsion of invention but in the comfortable exercise of a long-practised craft, and the effect is curiously agreeable, like the company of an old friend who has told better stories but tells this one with undiminished warmth.
Nathan Garrideb is the tale's quiet triumph of characterisation. The cadaverous face, the round spectacles, the goat's beard, the stooping posture of peering curiosity — these compose a portrait of the harmless scholar-collector that is both affectionate and exact. His room, with its butterflies and moths flanking the entrance, its fossil bones and plaster skulls labelled Neanderthal, Heidelberg, Cro-Magnon, its Syracusan coins polished with chamois leather, is among the most lovingly catalogued interiors in the canon, and it achieves what the best descriptive writing always does: it makes us understand a character through his habitat. His ambition to become the Hans Sloane of his age, his inability to imagine leaving his collection even for five million dollars, his reluctance to travel as far as Birmingham — these are the details of a man whose inner world is so complete that the outer one has become merely an inconvenience. That this gentle, unworldly figure should be the unwitting custodian of a counterfeiter's cellar, his entire life lived on the surface above a criminal's buried machinery, is the tale's one genuinely poetic irony, and Doyle handles it with a lightness that suggests he recognised its quality.
Killer Evans himself is a rather more conventional creation — the chubby, childlike face concealing the violent American criminal is a type the canon has deployed before — but Holmes's method of exposing him is managed with quiet efficiency. The English coat frayed at the elbow, the trousers bagged at the knee with a year's wear, the nonexistent Dr. Lysander Starr of Topeka, the misspelt "plough" and the American "buckboards" in what purports to be an English advertisement — these are the small, accumulating inconsistencies from which Holmes constructs his case, and they have the satisfying quality of detection conducted not through brilliance but through patient, professional attention. The trap at Ryder Street, however, brings us to the story's comical structural deficiency: Holmes and Watson crouch behind a cupboard waiting for a criminal whose identity, method, and purpose they have already deduced, armed with revolvers against a man they know to be dangerous, and yet they permit him to draw and fire two shots before Holmes brings a pistol butt down upon his skull. It is a scene that depends entirely upon Watson being wounded, and the narrative arranges his wound with the transparent contrivance of an author who needs it for what follows.
And what follows redeems everything. Watson is shot; the wound is superficial; but Holmes does not yet know this. His cry — "You're not hurt, Watson? For God's sake, say that you are not hurt!" — and Watson's response constitute the emotional centre not merely of this story but, one might argue, of the entire Holmes-Watson relationship across four novels and fifty-six stories. Watson's narration of the moment — "It was worth a wound — it was worth many wounds — to know the depth of loyalty and love which lay behind that cold mask" — is a sentence of such unguarded feeling that it seems to have been written not by the cautious memoirist we know but by the man himself, momentarily freed from the habits of reticence by the extremity of the occasion. The clear hard eyes dimmed for a moment, the firm lips shaking, the glimpse of a great heart as well as a great brain — and then, almost immediately, the mask restored, the face set like flint, the cold threat to the prisoner: "If you had killed Watson, you would not have got out of this room alive." It is writing of extraordinary emotional compression, moving from vulnerability to menace in the space of a breath, and it tells us more about the central friendship of the canon than all the deductions and adventures combined. The story ends, as it must, with Nathan Garrideb's shattered dreams and his removal to a nursing home in Brixton — his castle in the air fallen, the ruins burying him beneath — and the note of elegy is entirely appropriate, for this is a tale in which the things that matter most are the things most easily broken: an old man's hopes, a counterfeiter's hidden workshop, and the composure of a man who had spent a lifetime pretending he had no heart.
""" .

