Watson's opening paragraph of elaborate suppression — college, town, criminal all anonymised — sets a tone of hushed institutional anxiety perfectly suited to a world where a stolen glance at Greek proofs constitutes catastrophe. Holmes out of sorts without Baker Street, his chemicals, his scrap-books — "an uncomfortable man" — and his ungracious acceptance of the case nearly amounts to boredom. Calls it a parlour game, a three-card trick. The method stripped to essentials: measuring window heights, pencil shavings, direction of a scratch on leather. The pencil-borrowing ruse under cover of architectural sketching is among the neatest small deceptions in the canon — Watson himself doesn't see it happening. The three suspects are transparently loaded dice: the "inscrutable" Indian innocent, the dissolute card-cheat innocent, the fine manly athletic Blue guilty — because only his fall carries tragic weight and only colonial rehabilitation provides acceptable resolution. Social prejudice as narrative structure. The landlady babbled of green peas at seven-thirty — a perfect domestic detail. Three yellow squares of light in the gathering gloom is a fine visual. Bannister's confession is the emotional heart: feudal loyalty surviving ruin, descending from great house to college servitude, attaching itself to the next generation. He sat on the gloves rather than betray the boy he had dandled on his knee. Holmes's parting generosity redeems his earlier irritability.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Three Students" is, by common consent and by any reasonable critical standard, among the slightest tales in the Holmes canon — a mystery whose stakes are an examination paper, whose setting is deliberately anonymised into featurelessness, and whose solution depends upon a ball of black clay from a jumping-pit. Yet within these modest boundaries Doyle achieves something interesting: a story in which the emotional weight lies not in the crime or its detection but in the relationship between a servant and the son of his former master, and in which the detective story's usual machinery is deployed in service of what is, at bottom, a tale about loyalty, shame, and the fragile social architecture of an English university. Watson's opening paragraph, with its elaborate promise to suppress all identifying details — the college, the town, the criminal himself — sets a tone of hushed institutional anxiety that Doyle sustains throughout, and if the effect is occasionally stifling, it is also precisely appropriate to a world in which a stolen glance at a Greek examination paper constitutes a crisis of the first magnitude.
Holmes is notably out of sorts in this story, and Doyle makes something unexpectedly productive of his irritability. Deprived of Baker Street, his scrap-books, his chemicals, and his homely untidiness, he is, as Watson observes, an uncomfortable man, and his ungracious acquiescence to Soames's plea has none of the eager appetite for mystery that characterises his greater investigations. The case is, as he tells Watson, mental rather than physical, a "parlour game" and a "three-card trick," and there is a quality of professional condescension in his engagement that nearly amounts to boredom. Yet Doyle turns even this to narrative advantage: Holmes's method here is stripped to its essentials — measuring window heights, examining pencil shavings, noting the direction of a scratch on a leather desk — and the very modesty of the evidence gives the detection a procedural purity that more sensational cases lack. The ruse of borrowing pencils and knives from the suspects under the pretext of architectural sketching is among the neatest small deceptions in the canon, conducted with a sleight-of-hand so unobtrusive that Watson himself does not see what Holmes is doing, and neither, on a first reading, does the reader.
The tale's comical flaw is its treatment of its three suspects, which amounts to a exercise in the most transparently loaded narrative dice-throwing in Doyle's career. Daulat Ras, the Indian, is "quiet, inscrutable," and "sly" — adjectives that do considerably more work as racial characterisation than as evidence — yet he is innocent. Miles McLaren, the dissolute card-cheat who roars obscenities through a locked door, is the obvious culprit by every convention of popular fiction, yet he too is innocent. Gilchrist, "a fine, manly fellow" with a "pleasant, open face" and a Blue for athletics, whose father was a ruined baronet, is the guilty party — and the story takes elaborate pains to ensure that his guilt is immediately sympathetic, that it was the product of impulse rather than premeditation, and that his remorse is so complete he has already written a letter of withdrawal before Holmes arrives. The three-card trick, in other words, is rigged: the most English, the most athletic, the most socially distinguished suspect must be the one who cheated, because only his fall carries the weight of tragedy, and only his rehabilitation — the commission in the Rhodesian Police, the fresh start in the colonies — can provide the story with the resolution it requires. It is social prejudice operating as narrative structure, and Doyle does not appear to notice.
Yet the story's final scene achieves a quality of feeling that its mechanical plot does not deserve. Bannister's confession — that he had been butler to old Sir Jabez Gilchrist, that he had watched the son all he could for the sake of the old days, that when he saw the tan gloves lying on the chair he understood their message and sat upon them rather than betray the boy he had dandled on his knee — is a passage of considerable emotional power, precisely because it comes from the most minor and apparently least interesting character in the tale. Bannister's loyalty is feudal in its nature, surviving the ruin of the master, the descent from great house to college servitude, and attaching itself to the next generation with an intensity that the story's university setting, with its examinations and scholarships and competitive anxieties, cannot quite contain. Holmes's response — "No, indeed" — delivered heartily as he springs to his feet, and his parting words to Gilchrist — "For once you have fallen low. Let us see in the future how high you can rise" — have a generosity that redeems the detective's earlier irritability and lifts the story, in its closing sentences, to a dignity its subject matter has done nothing to earn. It is characteristic of Doyle that his smallest tales should occasionally, and almost by accident, discover reserves of human sympathy that his more ambitious ones labour toward in vain.
""" .

:valleyOfFearDoc 
    ex:reviewersNotes """
The cipher-cracking scene — Watson guessing Bible, Bradshaw, almanac — is among the finest comic dialogues in the canon; Holmes's "pig's-bristles" when Whitaker's fails is superb. Moriarty discussion with MacDonald brilliantly structured: the Greuze painting on a seven-hundred-a-year salary is devastating proof through indirection. MacDonald seduced by Moriarty's fatherly hand on his shoulder — the spider's charm. Birlstone Manor House genuinely atmospheric: moat as quicksilver, centuries of births and fox hunters, then this dark business. The splay-foot slipper matching the blood mark is excellent physical detection. The missing dumb-bell is Holmes at his most maddening — "the unilateral development, the imminent danger of a spinal curvature." Mrs. Douglas's flickering smile when asked about the wedding ring is a masterstroke of contained duplicity. Watson catching her laughing with Barker behind the hedge — his moral outrage is the reader's. The structural catastrophe repeats Scarlet: Part II abandons Holmes entirely for a Vermissa Valley narrative. But Doyle learned from his earlier mistake — the material is incomparably stronger. McMurdo/Edwards is perhaps his finest sustained character. The revelation scene — "I am Birdy Edwards" — is theatrical perfection. The hissing kettle and seven white faces. The epilogue's Moriarty shadow turns self-defence into doom. Douglas lost overboard: crushing the nut with the hammer.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Valley of Fear" opens with what may be the most purely entertaining chapter in all of Holmes — a sustained comic duet between detective and doctor that unfolds, without the smallest loss of wit or momentum, into the arrival of a cipher, the identification of a book, the cracking of a code, and the announcement of a murder. Watson's progress from Bible to Bradshaw to almanac, guided by Holmes's silken condescension, is a passage of intellectual comedy as finely managed as anything in the canon, and Holmes's cry of despair when Whitaker's yields "Mahratta government pig's-bristles" achieves a level of absurdist bathos that suggests Doyle, for once, was writing purely for his own pleasure. The Moriarty discussion that follows is managed with equal assurance: MacDonald's account of the professor — the reflector lantern and the globe, the fatherly hand upon his shoulder as they parted — is a portrait of seduction that does more to establish the villain's power than any amount of direct menace, and Holmes's demolition of it through the single detail of a Greuze painting purchased on a salary of seven hundred a year is detection by indirection raised to an art. That the novel begins at this pitch of sustained brilliance makes what follows the more painful to assess, for it is a book that will betray its own opening twice over before it reaches its end.
Part I, the Birlstone mystery, is among the most carefully constructed of all Holmes's longer investigations. The moated Jacobean manor house — three centuries of births, homecomings, and fox hunts now shadowed by violent death — is rendered with a visual and historical specificity that goes well beyond the requirements of the puzzle, and the investigation proceeds through a series of discoveries each of which simultaneously clarifies and complicates: the sawed-off American shotgun with its wired triggers, the missing wedding ring that could only be removed by first removing the nugget ring above it, the splay-footed bloodstain that proves to be Barker's bedroom slipper, and above all the missing dumbbell, which Holmes elevates into an obsessive refrain of maddening opacity. Mrs. Douglas is superbly handled — her composed manner, her faintly flickering smile when asked about the ring, the moment Watson catches her laughing with Barker behind the yew hedge while her husband's body lies barely cold — and the reader's moral indignation is managed with such skill that the eventual revelation, that Douglas is alive and has been hiding in the priest-hole all along, arrives as both surprise and retrospective inevitability. It is the finest sustained piece of detective plotting in the four novels.
Then Doyle does it again. As in A Study in Scarlet, he abandons Holmes, Watson, Baker Street, and the detective framework altogether, asking the reader to travel twenty years backward and thousands of miles westward into the coal and iron valleys of Pennsylvania. The structural catastrophe is identical in kind: a detective novel interrupted by a historical romance. But it is not identical in quality, and this is the crucial distinction. The Vermissa Valley chapters are not the lurid Mormon fantasy of the earlier novel but a sustained work of social fiction that possesses, at its best, a genuine power of its own. The opening passage — the evening train crawling through gorges of snow and slag, the red glow of furnaces pulsing through the gloom, the huddled wooden houses and swarthy inhabitants — establishes an industrial landscape rendered with a harshness that suggests not the adventure romance but the naturalist novel, and the world of the Scowrers, with its reign of terror over an entire valley, its corrupted courts, its alibied murderers and silenced witnesses, has a political specificity that the Utah chapters of Scarlet never approached. Brother Morris's confession on the hilltop — the hands crimson to the wrists, the child screaming behind them as they leave the lonely house — is a passage that achieves the quality of genuine moral horror, and the atmosphere of pervasive dread that gives the novel its title is sustained with a consistency that represents Doyle's most ambitious attempt at extended narrative.
McMurdo himself — who is, of course, Birdy Edwards of Pinkerton's — is the finest piece of sustained characterisation in all of Doyle's work. The scene in which he faces McGinty for the first time, bearing the boss's loaded revolver with a cocked pistol already covering him from his own pocket, establishes a quality of cold nerve that the subsequent chapters develop into something approaching tragic complexity: the man who must become the thing he hunts, who must participate in violence to prevent worse violence, who cannot reveal himself even to the woman he loves. The revelation scene — McMurdo's face setting into granite firmness, his quiet announcement "I am Birdy Edwards," the ten seconds of silence broken only by the hissing of a kettle upon the stove, the seven white faces, and then the shattering of glass as rifle barrels bristle through every window — is among the great theatrical moments in popular fiction, managed with a compression and restraint that Doyle's more celebrated scenes rarely equal. His closing speech to the assembled murderers possesses a moral authority — the deliverer who went down into hell — that elevates what might have been mere melodrama into something with the cadences of judgment itself. That the novel then returns to Baker Street for an epilogue in which Moriarty's shadow reaches across the Atlantic to destroy what the Scowrers could not, Douglas lost overboard in a gale off St. Helena, gives the whole structure a tragic shape that neither of its halves, considered separately, quite possesses. The Valley of Fear remains a divided, deeply imperfect novel; but its imperfections are of a different order than those of its predecessor, for here the two halves, however violently sundered, speak to each other across the gap, and what they say — that no courage and no cunning can finally outrun the reach of organised malice — is worthy of the name it bears.
""" .

:veiledLodgerDoc 
