Watson's opening paragraph is pure throat-clearing — Doyle using his narrator to apologize for having nothing much to narrate, then dangling that magnificent red herring about "the politician, the lighthouse, and the trained cormorant" as if to remind us what fun we could be having. Mrs. Merrilow is a delight; the verb "waddled" is doing more characterization work than some entire Holmes stories manage. Note the curious structural echo: woman who kept beasts in cages becomes herself a caged beast — Doyle sees it and flags it directly, which is both the strength and weakness of his method, never trusting the reader to catch the symbolism unaided. Holmes sitting cross-legged on the floor "like some strange Buddha" is a throwaway image that deserves more attention than it gets — the detective as contemplative mystic rather than man of action, which is really the whole story in miniature. The cold partridge and Montrachet feel like Doyle rewarding himself with a pleasant lunch mid-composition. Why does Watson remember Edmunds's hair color but not the entire Abbas Parva tragedy? Doyle's Watson is conveniently amnesiac whenever exposition requires it — a running joke the author never seems to notice.
""" ;
    ex:reviewDetailed """
"The Adventure of the Veiled Lodger" is among the slightest entries in the Sherlock Holmes canon, and one must confront at the outset the central absurdity of its premise: it is a detective story in which the detective does almost nothing. Holmes neither deduces, nor investigates, nor unravels. He is summoned to a boarding house in South Brixton to sit in a chair and listen to a woman confess. Watson, that eternal supernumerary, is brought along as a "witness," though one struggles to understand what he is witnessing beyond an exercise in passive audition. The great engine of ratiocination, the mind that once teased truth from a battered hat and a discarded pipe, is here reduced to the role of parish priest — and not a particularly active one at that.
Yet if the machinery of detection has been abandoned, something else has taken its place, and it would be unjust to dismiss it. The portrait of Eugenia Ronder is drawn with a compression and sympathy that rises, in places, genuinely above the level of magazine fiction. Her monologue — the circus girl sold into a brutal marriage, the desperate conspiracy with her lover Leonardo, and the hideous betrayal at the moment of crisis when the lion's jaws close upon her face — possesses a stark, almost classical economy. Doyle's instinct for the theatrical image has rarely served him better than in the moment when Mrs. Ronder lifts her veil to answer Holmes's platitude about patient suffering with the devastating challenge: "I wonder if you would bear it." It is a line worthy of Sophocles, and it earns its power precisely because Doyle, for once, has the restraint not to overexplain it. The final image of the prussic acid bottle arriving by post, accompanied by a note of quiet courage, achieves a genuine pathos that the more elaborate adventures rarely approach.
One must, however, note the comical difficulties that attend the plot's construction. We are asked to believe that Leonardo, a professional strongman of magnificent physique, fabricated a club studded with five steel nails arranged in the precise spread of a lion's paw — a contrivance so ingenious it fooled a coroner's inquest — and yet this same mastermind's plan required him to swing said club at a moving target in pitch darkness, a feat at which he proved so incompetent that the couple walked clean past him before he could strike. The lion, too, performs with a narrative convenience that strains credulity: it ignores the raw meat it was about to be fed, instantly scents human blood in the darkness, bounds past the actual corpse to attack the woman near the cage, and then obligingly returns to its enclosure to be locked in. One pictures Sahara King consulting the manuscript to determine his blocking. Furthermore, Holmes informs us that he and young Edmunds of the Berkshire Constabulary found the case troubling at the time, yet neither man, it seems, thought to interview the strongman who was conspicuously present at the scene, in love with the victim's wife, and the first to arrive with a rescue party.
What redeems the tale, finally, is its emotional honesty — a quality not always abundant in the Holmes adventures. The closing exchange between Holmes and Mrs. Ronder achieves something rare in popular fiction of the period: a confrontation with suffering that refuses the consolation of easy resolution. Holmes's admonition that her life is not her own to take is met not with grateful submission but with a mute, terrible rebuttal that silences even him. Doyle, so often content to restore order with a flourish of deduction and a cab ride home, here allows the wound to remain open. It is a small story, almost negligible as a detective narrative, but in its final pages it touches something that the more ingenious puzzles of the canon never quite reach — the recognition that some human wreckage lies beyond the power of even the most brilliant mind to mend.
""" .

