Holmes's casual remark that no woman would send a reply-paid telegram — "she would have come" — is one of those tossed-off sexisms that Doyle clearly considered charming; it has aged like milk. The encoding error in the text — "tete-a-tete" — is a delicious irony: a story about foreign intrigue defeated by foreign characters. Watson claims to remember nothing of the Tiger of San Pedro, then instantly recalls the man's entire biography in florid detail the moment Baynes names him — the most transparent authorial convenience in a story full of them. Doyle's treatment of the mulatto cook is wretchedly racialized even by 1908 standards: "savage," "creature," "fierce as the devil," barely speaks, bites policemen. The fictional Eckermann's Voodooism and the Negroid Religions that Holmes quotes is doing heavy lifting to give scholarly cover to what amounts to sensationalism. Note that Holmes spends a week pretending to study botany while conducting his real investigation — Watson never once questions this, which says everything about their dynamic. "Mr. Hynes Hynes, J.P." — did Doyle actually write that name with a straight face? The story's real structural problem: two chapters promise a novel's architecture but deliver a novella's hasty compression.
