"The Adventure of Wisteria Lodge" is that curious thing in the Holmes canon: a story ambitious enough to require two chapters and a table of contents, yet so tangled in its own machinery that even its author seems to lose confidence in the enterprise. Doyle attempts something genuinely unusual here — a political thriller grafted onto a domestic mystery, spanning two continents and braiding together a deposed Central American dictator, a secret society of avengers, voodoo rituals, and the vanishing household of a Surrey villa — and the sheer profusion of material defeats him. The story opens with magnificent promise: Holmes's disquisition on the word "grotesque" and its proximity to the criminal is among the finest aesthetic pronouncements Watson has recorded, a moment of genuine critical intelligence that one wishes Doyle had applied more rigorously to the construction that follows. The introduction of Scott Eccles is equally accomplished — his portrait, from spats to gold-rimmed spectacles, compressed into a single paragraph of effortless social satire, the man's entire moral universe evoked through his outrage at being made to look improper.
The first chapter, "The Singular Experience of Mr. John Scott Eccles," sustains this quality through a sequence of genuinely eerie effects: the distracted host, the midnight voice at the door, the abandoned house at dawn. Doyle's atmospheric instincts are superb here, and the scene at Wisteria Lodge with Constable Walters — the terrified policeman, the face at the window, the voodoo fetish in the kitchen — achieves a pitch of Gothic dread that ranks among the most effective passages in the entire canon. One must also give full credit to Inspector Baynes, that rarest of figures in this series: a competent official detective. Baynes is a triumph of characterization, his small bright eyes gleaming behind their folds of flesh, his sly wink when Holmes condescends to warn him, and his masterstroke of deliberately arresting the wrong man to lull the true quarry. Holmes's praise of Baynes — that he possesses "instinct and intuition" — feels earned rather than formulaic, and the quiet professional rivalry between the two men provides a pleasure more subtle than the main plot deserves.
Yet the comical flaws multiply as the story expands. The entire scheme depends upon Garcia cultivating Scott Eccles as an alibi witness — a plan so preposterously elaborate that one marvels anyone thought it worth the trouble. Garcia spends weeks befriending this dull churchman, installs him for the night at Wisteria Lodge, manipulates the clocks, and then ventures out to be bludgeoned to death on a common, rendering the alibi perfectly useless. The note from Miss Burnet, with its directions to the seventh door on the right past the green baize, reads less like a secret communiqué than like instructions for finding the lavatory at a country house party. Meanwhile, Doyle's handling of Don Murillo, the Tiger of San Pedro, asks us to accept that a dictator notorious enough to make the European press has successfully hidden in the Home Counties by the expedient of calling himself "Henderson" — a disguise roughly as penetrating as a false moustache at a fancy-dress ball. And the resolution, in which Murillo simply escapes to be murdered six months later in Madrid, is not so much a conclusion as an admission that the author could find no way to conclude.
What one takes from "Wisteria Lodge," finally, is a story at war with itself — half atmospheric masterpiece, half geopolitical muddle — and one cannot help suspecting that the best tale Doyle had to tell was the smaller, stranger one buried within: the lonely policeman in the empty house, the face at the rain-streaked window, the torn white cock and the pail of blood. These images possess a power that no amount of plotting about Central American revolutions can match, and they suggest that Doyle's true gift was not for the elaborate architecture of crime but for the sudden, uncanny detail that makes the skin prickle. When he trusts that gift, as in the kitchen scene at Wisteria Lodge, he produces work that transcends the genre entirely. When he tries to build a geopolitical edifice around it, he produces something that even Holmes, in his closing remarks, can only call "chaotic" — a verdict the reader is unlikely to dispute.
