Watson's prefatory note is structurally fascinating — he breaks the fourth wall to warn us Holmes will fail, which should kill all suspense, yet somehow the domestic tension carries the story regardless. The pipe analysis that opens the tale is vintage Holmes bravura, yet it leads absolutely nowhere; the deductions about left-handedness and good teeth have zero bearing on anything that follows, as though Doyle included it purely because readers expected their parlour trick. Holmes mentions cocaine in the second paragraph with the magnificent euphemism "protest against the monotony of existence" — one wonders if Doyle's editor flinched. Grant Munro is a hop merchant, surely the least glamorous profession ever assigned to a Holmes client; Doyle seems almost to be testing how ordinary a man can be and still hold a narrative. The walk to Crystal Palace and back is roughly ten miles — Munro's response to marital crisis is essentially a half-marathon. Notice that Effie transferred all her money to her husband upon marriage, then must ask permission to access her own capital; Doyle records this without comment, but the modern reader hears the prison door click shut. The story's title refers to the mask but also, unavoidably, to skin colour — a double meaning Doyle likely intended but never acknowledged.
